<TEXT><FRONT><DIV1 TYPE="Note"><HEAD>Note</HEAD><P>For facility of reference this text quotes the Harleian MS. 268, and the Arundel MS. 378, of the British Museum, at all points where these Latin copies of Etienne de Besan&ccedil;on's collection of exempla throw any light on difficult or confused readings. A further clearing-up will be undertaken in the notes, which with an introduction and a glossary are to follow Part II.</P><P>Words and letters which have been obliterated or worn away from the MS. are restored conjecturally in brackets; words and letters inadvertently omitted by the writer of the MS. are also conjecturally supplied in brackets, but in italic, to distinguish them from those for which the MS. leaves a space. Capitals have been given to names of persons and places, and have been left in some common nouns as they stand in the MS.; modern punctuation has been adopted throughout.  Scribal errors are corrected by footnotes.  Signs standing in earlier MSS. for final -e are represented by a small stroke curved to the right or left, only the diminutive curl after short r has been left out.</P><P>A list of <HI
REND="i">errata</HI> will be printed with Part II, also an Index to the Tales.</P></DIV1><DIV1
TYPE="Note"><HEAD>Note</HEAD><P>Part II of the <HI REND="i">Alphabetum Narrationum</HI> brings the text to an end, and leaves introduction, glossary, index and general clearing-up for Part III.</P><P>The name of &Eacute;tienne de Besan&ccedil;on still stands on the title-page; this is the last time it may be associated with this collection of Tales.  The association is of so long and respectable a standing that it is worthy of an easy dissolution, though &Eacute;tienne himself might possibly have felt no regret to see it brought about, as it assuredly has been by Mr. J.A. Herbert's article in the <HI
REND="i">Library</HI> for January, 1905.  Mr. Herbert sums up the case as stated by Mons. Haur&eacute;au, and adds evidence of his own weighty enough to dispose finally of the claims made for &Eacute;tienne's authorship by Leandro Alberti, Qu&eacute;tif and &Eacute;chard, and later writers.</P><P>There is a case for Arnold of Li&egrave;ge, but the verdict is a little in suspense.  A definite attribution of authorship must wait for Part III, though it may be said forthwith that any testing of evidence hitherto undertaken serves only to strengthen Arnold's claims.  For the present, however, readers must look for these in the article quoted above.</P><SIGNED>M. M. BANKS.</SIGNED></DIV1></FRONT>
<BODY>

<PB N="1">
<HEAD>AN ALPHABET OF TALES.</HEAD>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>I.<LB><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Abbas non debet esse nimis rigidus.
Vnde Anselmus.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> SOM tyme &thorn;er was ane abbott &thorn;at asked cownce&llbar; of
Saynt Anselme, &amp; sayd vnto hym <NOTE ID="P1.N1">MS. hyr.</NOTE> , "what
sa&llbar; w[e] do with childer &thorn;at er nurysshid &amp; broght
vp&ptail; in our clostre? ffor," he sayde, "we sese nott day &amp;
nygh[t to] bete &thorn;aim, &amp; yitt &thorn;ai er ay &thorn;e langer
&thorn;e wers."  And &thorn;a&ntail; Saynt Anselme ansswerd hy&mtail;
agay&ntail; [&] say&dtail;, "ye spend fu&llbar; wele your nurysshyng
&amp; you&rtail; almos, &thorn;at of <NOTE ID="P1.N2"><HI REND="i">After</HI> of, bestis makis men, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> me&ntail;
makis b[estis], ffor, &amp; &thorn;ou sett in my garthy&ntail; a yong plante
of a tre, &amp; closyd it rownde aboute, strayte o&ntail; [evur]-ilk
side, &thorn;at it mot nott sprede furt&hbar; no bewis, whatky&ntail;
a tre wolde spryng &thorn;eroff?  ffor sut[h, an] vnprofitable tre.
O&ntail; &thorn;e same maner of wise," he sai&dtail;, "do ye; ye kepe
strayte in your clostre chi[lder] &amp; yong me&ntail;, with ferdnes
&amp; thretyngis, so at &thorn;ai may hafe no libertie;
wha&rtail;-oppo&ntail; it happe[ns], for als meki&llbar; as &thorn;ai
fele in you anence &thorn;aim selfe no maner of luff nor swettnes, nor
hafe no fai[th] <NOTE ID="P1.N3">Latin MSS. fidem boni.  (This reference and others following, are to the Latin MSS.  Harl. 268, and Arundel, 375, in the British Museum).</NOTE> of no gudenes afterwerd in you,
&thorn;erfo&rtail; it happyns of &thorn;aim be a mervolos maner, &amp;
a wrichid.  ffo[r] evur as &thorn;ai grow &amp; waxis in bodis, Right
so in &thorn;aim growis hateri&dtail; &amp; suspecio&ntail; of
a&llbar; <NOTE ID="P1.N4">Latin MSS. omnis mali.</NOTE> [y&llbar;]; and &thorn;erfo&rtail;, for
als meku&llbar; as &thorn;ai of no ma&ntail; war nurisshi&dtail; in
trew nor in perfite charite, &thorn;erfo[r &thorn;ai] may not luke of
no ma&ntail;, bod with a sow&rtail; cowntenance and a frowar&dtail;
luke."  et c&curl;.  </P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>II.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Abbas debet esse compaciens
peccatoribus.</FOREIGN>
</HEAD>
<P> We rede in a buke &thorn;at is callid 'Vitas Patrum,' how
so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a monke &thorn;at happen[yd] o&ntail; a
tyme to sy&ntail; flesshlie with

<PB N="2">

a woma&ntail;; &amp; he went &amp; schrafe hy&mtail; &thorn;erof vnto
ane of his brethyr, ane alde monke.  And &thorn;is monke tuke not his
confessio&ntail; tendirlie, bod chiddi&dtail; hy[m], &amp; flate with
hy&mtail;, &amp; sai&dtail; he was vnworthi to be a monke &amp; for to
bere &thorn;e name of &thorn;er ordur, becauce he fe&llbar; so
lightlie vnto flesshlie temptacio&ntail;; To so meku&llbar; att,
whe&ntail; &thorn;ai war partid, &thorn;is y[ong]er monke bega&ntail;
to fa&llbar; in a despare, So &thorn;at o&ntail; a nyght he gat
hy&mtail; se[cular] wede, &amp; stale away oute of his ce&llbar;, and
liffid as a secule&rtail; ma&ntail; in &thorn;e werl&dtail;.  So
o&ntail; a ty[me] as he went be &thorn;e way, it happen&dtail; be
&thorn;e dispensacio&ntail; of almi&yogh;ti Go&dtail;, hy&mtail;
happen&dtail; to mete with ane abbott &thorn;at hight Appollinius,
whilk &thorn;at knew &thorn;e cauce of his gate oute of his ordur,
whilk abbott comfurthid hy&mtail; with fayr wurdis, and said vnto
hy&mtail; &thorn;us: "tur&ntail; agay&ntail;, brother, vnto &thorn;i
se&llbar;, &amp; hafe no merve&llbar; at &thorn;ou, at is a yong
ma&ntail;, be tempi&dtail; with sy&ntail;, ffor I my selfe, now in
myne olde age, is hugelie tempid with &thorn;e same sy&ntail;."  So,
&thorn;urg&hbar; his comfurthable wurdis, &thorn;is monke turnyd
agay&ntail; vnto his ce&llbar;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is Abbott
Abbollinius o&ntail; a tyme come vnto &thorn;is olde monke ce&llbar;
dure, &thorn;at had made &thorn;is yong ma&ntail; to despayre, &amp;
&thorn;er he prayed <NOTE ID="P2.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">prayer</HI>.</NOTE> at &thorn;is olde monke myght
somwhatt fele of &thorn;e temptacio&ntail; of his oder bruder, &amp;
at his oder bruder myght be delyver&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; he had
done his prayer, he was war of a little blak felow like a ma&ntail; of
Ynde, shotand byrnand aro[ws] at &thorn;is olde ma&ntail;, vnto so
meku&llbar; at &thorn;is olde monke was so stirrid with sy&ntail;
&amp; temptacio&ntail; of his bodye, &thorn;at he stale oute of his
ordur in-to &thorn;e werl&dtail;.  So o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;is abbot
come vnto hy&mtail; &thorn;er he was, &amp; sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;:
"Tur&ntail; agay&ntail; in-to &thorn;i ce&llbar;, &amp; hafe
compassio&ntail; o&ntail; &thorn;i neghburs."  And &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;is abbott went vnto his prayers, &amp; praye&dtail; for
hy&mtail;; [&amp; he co]me home vnto his ce&llbar;, &amp; onone he was
delyver&dtail; of his temptacio&ntail;.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> III.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Abbas discretus peccatores a peccato
retrahit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' &thorn;at in &thorn;e tyme of
Valencia&ntail; &thorn;er was a passand [fayr maydyn] &thorn;at hight
Thaysis, whilk maydy&ntail;



<PB N="3">

hur modir in a&llbar; hur yong age lete [do accordand to] hur wi&llbar;

<NOTE ID="P3.N1">Latin MSS. quam mater eius a pueritia statuit in prostibulo.</NOTE> .  So whe&ntail; hur moder deye&dtail;, sho
become &thorn;e moste commo&ntail; strompy&dtail; in a&llbar; &thorn;e
lan&dtail;, vnto so [m]yki&llbar; &thorn;at me&ntail; come vnto hur
infenytelie.  So &thorn;er was ane Abbott &thorn;at hight Pasuncius
<NOTE ID="P3.N2">Harl. MS. prasencius, Arun. MS. pasuncius.</NOTE> , whilk [&thorn;]at, whe&ntail; he harde
te&llbar; o&ntail; hur, he tuke oppo&ntail; secula&rtail; wede, &amp;
tuke in his purs a shelyng, [and] went vnto hur and gaff hur &thorn;is
shelyng to lat hy&mtail; hafe his wi&llbar; of hur.  And sho
[grawn]tit, &amp; led hy&mtail; u&ptail; into a chambre, and
whe&ntail; sho was in &thorn;e chambre, hur bed was [ga]ylie dyght
&amp; clenlie, &amp; sho did of hur clothis &amp; went &thorn;erto,
&amp; bad hy&mtail; co&mtail; vnto hur.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he
spirry&dtail; hur iff &thorn;er wer no mo&rtail; privalie place
&thorn;at he &amp; sho mott lie samen in, and sho sai&dtail;, "yis."
And &thorn;a&ntail; he sai&dtail;, "Go we &thorn;erto."  And sho led
hy&mtail; &thorn;erto, &amp; say&dtail;: "Sir, &amp; &thorn;ou drede
any ma&ntail;, Be nott aferde, for here commys no ma&ntail;, nor no
ma&ntail; may nowder se the nor me.  And if &thorn;ou be ferde for
God&dtail;, or drede Hy&mtail;, dowte nott &thorn;att whar-euer we
[b]e,  Almyghtie God seis vs."  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is olde
Abbott askid hir &thorn;uff sho knew almighti [G]o&dtail;, And sho
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail; &thorn;at sho knew
almyghti Go&dtail; &amp; att his kyngdo&mtail; was for to co&mtail;; &amp;
also sho sai&dtail; &thorn;at turmettrie &amp; pay&ntail; sulde be for
sy&ntail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he ansswer&dtail; hur agay&ntail;
&amp; sai&dtail;: "Thow &thorn;att knowis almyghty [God], why hase &thorn;ou
loste and myschevid so many sawlis as &thorn;ou hase done? for
&thorn;ou mo&ntail; nott alonelie be dampnyd in &thorn;ine awne sawle,
bod also &thorn;ou <NOTE ID="P3.N3">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, bod also &thorn;ou.</NOTE> mo&ntail; giff acompte for
&thorn;er sawlys at &thorn;ou hase dampne&dtail;."  And whe&ntail;
sho har&dtail; &thorn;is, sho ffe&llbar; dow&ntail; on hur kneys att
his fette, &amp; wepid sore, and made meku&llbar; sorow; &amp;
evy&ntail; furthwit&hbar; a&llbar; &thorn;at evur sho had getty[n]
with hur sy&ntail; and hur wrichidnes, afor&ntail; a&llbar; &thorn;e
peple sho put it in a greate fy[re &] burnyd <NOTE ID="P3.N4"><HI REND="i">After</HI> burnyd, i&dtail;, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> itt;
and so, be cownce&llbar; of &thorn;is abbott, not alonelie for hur
sy&ntail;-doyng, bod s[o] sho tuke itt vppo&ntail; hur to name
a&llbar;-myghti Go&dtail;, sho was sparre&dtail; in a cloce ce&llbar;
iij yere, and grete penance was enioyny&dtail; hur for hur sy&ntail;;
and emang a&llbar; hur o&thorn;er penance, &thorn;is was hur

<NOTE ID="P3.N5">MS. his.</NOTE> prayer: " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Qui plasmasti me,
miserere mei!</FOREIGN> Thow Lor&dtail; at made me, hafe mercie
o&ntail; me!"  And whe&ntail; sho had bene &thorn;er iij yere,


<PB N="4">

&thorn;is Abbott had in a reuelacio&ntail; a knowlege &thorn;at
a&llbar; hur synys was forgiffy&ntail; hur <NOTE ID="P4.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, all hur synys.</NOTE> .
&thorn;an this abbott tuke hur furth of &thorn;is ce&llbar;, and sho
tolde hy&mtail; &thorn;at sho had made a grete pak&ktee; of a&llbar;
hur synys, and &thorn;at sho lay&dtail; euer-ilk day in hur eye-syght,
and euer &thorn;is pakk wex les &amp; les, vnto &thorn;er was noght
lefte in it; &amp; &thorn;erby sho wiste &thorn;at hur synys was
forgiffy&ntail; hur within &thorn;at iij yere penance doyng.  et
c&curl;.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> IV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Abbas debet esse elemosinarius.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Frendis, we rede how &thorn;at &thorn;er was ane Abbott &thorn;at
hight Petrus Damanus <NOTE ID="P4.N2"><HI REND="i">For</HI> Petrus Damianus.</NOTE> , and [on a tym]e he made a
grete feste; and vnto &thorn;is feste he garte by a grete fyss&hbar;
&thorn;at [coste] xx &dtail;; and onone it was sode&ntail; &amp; sett
befo&rtail; hy&mtail;.  And as he sett att [mea]te, &thorn;er come
vnto his yate a pure ma&ntail;; and with a greate noyse &amp; a cry
[he besogh]t &thorn;at &thorn;e Abbott wol&dtail; giff hy&mtail;
&thorn;e beste mete <NOTE ID="P4.N3">MS. mece.</NOTE> &thorn;at stude befo&rtail;
hy&mtail;; [&amp; &thorn;e] Abbott harde hy&mtail;, and with a gude
harte sent hy&mtail; itt, &thorn;e fyssch &thorn;at ha&dtail; coste
hy&mtail; xx &dtail;, evy&ntail; hale as it was; and a monke bare
hy&mtail; it.  And onone as he had it delyver&dtail;, &thorn;is
mon&ktee; lukid after &thorn;is pure ma&ntail;, &amp; he saw
hy&mtail; steg&hbar; vnto hevy&ntail; with &thorn;e dubler &amp;
&thorn;e ffiss&hbar; in his han&dtail;.  And he went in, an&dtail;
tolde &thorn;e abbott.  And &thorn;is abbott &thorn;ankid almyghti
Go&dtail;, &amp; trustid &thorn;at it was God Hy&mtail; selfe
&thorn;at come to feche his almos at his yate.  et c&curl;.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> V.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Abbas debet esse conformis subditis in vestibus et
victualibus.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how som tyme &thorn;er was ane Abbott, &thorn;at euer-ilk
day fure gaylie att his meate, &amp; w[ent] euer gaylie araye&dtail;,
&amp; lett for no coste, bod boght of &thorn;e beste mete &amp; drynk
&amp; clothis &thorn;at he cuthe gett for any sylver, after his
astate.  So it happend o&ntail; a day whe&ntail; he had gaylie
far&ntail; att his meate, and his brether in &thorn;e covent had
far&ntail; bod badlie, &amp; had little mete to ete, it happend


<PB N="5">

after meate &thorn;at he mett ane of his brethir, a monk, &amp; with a
grete haste &amp; a prowde cowntenance he bad hy&mtail; faste his
eran&dtail;.  And &thorn;is monke tarid, &amp; went nott furthwith as
&thorn;e Abbott bad hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;e Abbott saw &thorn;is,
&amp; sayd vnto hy&mtail; with a grete indignacio&ntail;: " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">ffrater! frater! non audisti que iussi?</FOREIGN> Brother,
brother," sai&dtail; he, "&thorn;ou harde nott whatt I commawndid
&thorn;e?"  Tha&ntail; &thorn;is monke ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;, "fforsuthe I know wele I a&mtail; your
bruther, bod trewlie nowder your kirty&llbar; nor your cowle, nor your
welefare at your meate is my sister; for fra ye fa&rtail; wele at your
meate, ye rakk nevur &amp; we &thorn;at sulde be your brethir fare
neuer so i&llbar;; &amp; if ye may gett gay clothyng &amp; gude, ye
rakk neuer how we fare." et c&curl;.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> VI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Abbas interdum debet gaudere cum subditis
suis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in &thorn;e life of Saynt Anto&ntail; how o&ntail; a tyme
ane archer, &thorn;at was a gude sh[oter], fand Saynt [Anton] syttand
emang his brethir makand merie with &thorn;aim.  And &thorn;is archer
was displesi&dtail; &thorn;erwith &amp; &thorn;oght &thorn;ai sulde
hafe bene in &thorn;er clostre, &amp; tente &thorn;er bukis &amp;
&thorn;er serues, &amp; nott hafe bene att no sporte nor no welefare.
And onone Saynt Anto&ntail; purseyvy&dtail; his menyng, and callid
hy&mtail; to hy&mtail;, &amp; bad hy&mtail; putt ane of his arows in
his bow, &amp; shote als fer as he myght, &amp; he di&dtail; so; and
&thorn;a&ntail; bad hy&mtail; take a noder, and do o&ntail; &thorn;e
same wyse, and he did as he bad hy&mtail;; &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; he
bad hy&mtail; take a thri&dtail;, &amp; draw hys bow als fer as he
myght, at it mott fle far fro hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;is archer <NOTE ID="P5.N1">MS. archer&dtail;.</NOTE> [ansswerd] hy&mtail; agay&ntail;
and sai&dtail;, "Sir, I dar nott, for I may happe&ntail; draw so fer
&thorn;at I may breke my bow, &amp; &thorn;at wol&dtail; I nott, for
&thorn;a&ntail; I monde make meku&llbar; sorow."  Tha&ntail; Saynt
Anto&ntail; say&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; agay&ntail;, "loo!  so&ntail;,
&thorn;us it is in &thorn;e werke of a&llbar;myghtie Go&dtail;; ffor
and we draw it oute of mesur, we may sone breke itt; &thorn;at <NOTE ID="P5.N2">MS. &thorn;an.</NOTE> is to say, and we halde ou&rtail; brethir so strayte
in aw &thorn;att &thorn;ai co&mtail; to no myrt&hbar; nor no sporte,
we may lightlie <NOTE ID="P5.N3">MS. lighlie.</NOTE> cauce &thorn;aim to breke
&thorn;er ordur.  And herefo&rtail; vs muste so&mtail; tyme lowse
ou&rtail; pithe, &amp; suffre &thorn;aim hafe so&mtail;

<PB N="6">

recreacio&ntail; &amp; disporte emang a&llbar; &thorn;er other chargis, as
Cato&ntail; says, <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Interpone tuis interdum gaudia
curis.</FOREIGN>" et c&curl;.</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Abbas malus eternaliter punitur.  Infra de
Ebrietate.  Abbas non mansuetem <NOTE ID="P6.N1">MS. mansuentem.</NOTE> debet corrigere.
Infra de correccione.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST></P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> VII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Abbas quantum potest debet peccatores
reuocare.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a thefe &thorn;at had
many other thevis at his reule a[nd] gouernance, &amp; he was prince
&amp; maister of &thorn;aim a&llbar;, vnto so meku&llbar; &thorn;at
with his robro[rie &] his thifte he distroyed nerehan&dtail; a&llbar;
&thorn;e regio&ntail; &thorn;at he dwelte in, in spolyng now of ane
&amp; now of a noder.  So &thorn;er was ane Abbott &thorn;at harde
te&llbar; of hy&mtail;, &amp; he tuke a gude hors, &amp; &thorn;e
beste clothis &thorn;at he had, &amp; rade into &thorn;e wud &thorn;er
&thorn;is thieff lay; and onone he was take&ntail; with &thorn;is
thieff &amp; his felows; and &thorn;is abbott askyd &thorn;aim what
&thorn;ai wolde with hy&mtail;; And &thorn;ai [an]sswer&dtail;
hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;, &thorn;ai wol&dtail; hafe his
hors &amp; his clothis.  And &thorn;is abbott [a]nsswer&dtail;
&thorn;aim agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;, "ye sa&llbar; hafe &thorn;aim
a&llbar; redie; for &thorn;e gudis of God, &thorn;ai e&rtail;
commo&ntail;, and I hafe wor&ntail; &amp; occupie&dtail; &thorn;ies
gudis &thorn;is many yeris, and &thorn;erfo&rtail; it is right at ye
hafe &thorn;aim now &amp; vse &thorn;aim als long as I hafe done."
And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is maister thefe sai&dtail; vnto &thorn;is
abbott, "Sur, &thorn;is day we wi&llbar; se&llbar; a&llbar; &thorn;is
gere, and bye vs suc&hbar; thyng as vs nedis vnto ou&rtail; fyndyng."
&amp; &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is Abbott sai&dtail; vnto &thorn;is
maister thieff, "Whi laburs &thorn;ou &thorn;us, &amp; puttis &thorn;i
selfe in so grete pere&llbar; as &thorn;ou dose, for &thorn;i
lifelo&dtail;?  Co&mtail; with me vnto ou&rtail; abbay, &amp; I
sa&llbar; so ordan&dtail; at &thorn;ou sa&llbar; nott myster to be a
thief no mo&rtail;."  Tha&ntail; &thorn;is thief sai&dtail;, "Sur
abbott, I may not eate your benys nor your cale, nor I may not drynk
your thy&ntail; ale."  Tha&ntail; &thorn;is abbott ansswer&dtail;
hy&mtail; &amp; sai&dtail;, "I sa&llbar; giff the gude fissc&hbar;
&amp; fless&hbar; to ete, &amp; gude wyne to dryn&ktee;."  So
vnnethis yit he wol&dtail; graunt &thorn;erto, bod yit att &thorn;e
laste he went home with &thorn;is abbot, &amp; &thorn;oght he
wol&dtail; prufe whethir he wol&dtail; holde his promys or noght.  So
&thorn;is Abbott garte orday&ntail; for hy&mtail; a fayr chawmer &amp;
a fayre be&dtail;, and assigned hy&mtail; a monk to seryff hy&mtail;,
&amp; for to gar hy&mtail; hafe a&llbar; &thorn;ing &thorn;at he



<PB N="7">

desiri&dtail;.  And euer-ilk day whe&ntail; &thorn;is thief had
ety&ntail; &amp; dronke&ntail; of &thorn;e beste meate &thorn;at cuthe
be gette&ntail;, &thorn;is monke, be commandment of his abbott,
befo&rtail; &thorn;is thieff ete no thyng bod brede &amp; watir.  And
whe&ntail; &thorn;is monk had done &thorn;us a long while, o&ntail; a
day &thorn;is thief sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;, "bruthir! whatt grete
sy&ntail; hase &thorn;ou done, &thorn;at &thorn;ou pynys &thorn;i
selfe so evur-ilk day with brede &amp; watir?  hase &thorn;ou
slay&ntail; any me&ntail;?"  And &thorn;is [monk] say&dtail;, "Nay,
sur, God forbede &thorn;at euer I ky&llbar; any ma&ntail;."
Tha&ntail; &thorn;is thief aski&dtail; hy&mtail; if he had done any
fornycacio&ntail; or avowtrie, or done any sacrelege; and
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is monke sayny&dtail; for merve&llbar; &amp;
sai&dtail;, "sur, whi say ye so?  I hafe bene broght vp in &thorn;is
abbay of bar&ntail; liti&llbar;, &amp; I tuchi&dtail; nevur no
womma&ntail; with sy&ntail;."  Tha&ntail; this thief was compuncte,
&amp; sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; selfe, "A! how wrichi&dtail; &amp;
vnhappie a&mtail; I, &thorn;at hase done so meku&llbar; i&llbar; as I
hafe done, as thifte, &amp; mansslaghter, fornycacio&ntail;, &amp;
avowtrie &amp; sacrelege; &amp; I neuer fasti&dtail; nor did no
penance."  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is thief garte ca&llbar;
&thorn;is abbott vnto hy&mtail;, &amp; fe&llbar; o&ntail; kneis
befo&rtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; besoght hy&mtail; &thorn;at he myght <NOTE ID="P7.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, &thorn;at he myght.</NOTE> be receyvi&dtail; into &thorn;e abbay to be a bruther;
&amp; he grawnti&dtail; hy&mtail;, and so he was made a monke in
&thorn;at abbay.  And afterwar&dtail; he become so gude a ma&ntail;
&amp; so halie, &thorn;at he passi&dtail; a&llbar; his other brethir
in gude lyfe &amp; abstinence, &amp; in gude reule of religio&ntail;
&amp; holynes.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> VIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Abbas non debet eligi per preces
carnales.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Hubertus, in a buke &thorn;at he makis `De Dono Timoris,' tellis
how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was ane abbott, and whe&ntail; he sulde
dye, he besoght his brethir &thorn;at whe&ntail; he was deade
[&thorn;ai] wolde chese his suster so&ntail;, &thorn;at <NOTE ID="P7.N2">MS. &thorn;as.</NOTE> was a monke of &thorn;e same place, to be Abbott; and
so &thorn;ai did.  So o&ntail; a tyme as &thorn;is new Abbott
walki&dtail; in his garthy&ntail; beside a we&llbar;, [he] harde a
huge voyse makand a grete mornyng &amp; a sorow, &amp; &thorn;at
mervaluslie, and onone &thorn;is abb[ott] coniurid it.  And whe&ntail;
he had so done, It tol&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;at it was &thorn;e
saule of the Abbott a[t] was his eame, whilk it sai&dtail; was in
grete pay&ntail;, &amp; byrny&dtail;, and a&llbar; becauce &thorn;at
he, er he dye&dtail;, desiri&dtail; his brethir to make hy&mtail;
&thorn;at was his sybma&ntail; Abbott.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e
new abbott, his suster so&ntail;,





<PB N="8">

sai&dtail;; "How may &thorn;ou byr&ntail; in so grete pay&ntail;,
&amp; be in so calde a we&llbar; [as] &thorn;ou ert in?"
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is spiritt bad &thorn;is abbott go into
&thorn;e kurk &amp; take &thorn;er a copir candilstik, [&] bryng it
with hy&mtail; &amp; caste it into &thorn;e we&llbar;, &amp; So he
di&dtail;.  And onone, as it was caste&ntail; into &thorn;e we&llbar;,
it was melti&dtail; as it had bene wax &thorn;at had bene putt in-to
&thorn;e fire.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;is new abbott saw &thorn;is,
onone he renownci&dtail; his abboshi&ptail;, &amp; garte chese a
noder.  And fro thens furt&hbar; he neuer hard &thorn;is voice
agay&ntail;.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> IX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Abbas bona monasterij non debet amicis
dare.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was ane abbott of Saynt
Pantaleus <NOTE ID="P8.N1">Harl. MS. Pentaleonis, Arun. MS. Panthaleonis.</NOTE> in Cola&ntail;, &thorn;at hight
Cesari[us], &amp; he had a bruther &thorn;at was a merchan&dtail;;
&amp; euer whe&ntail; &thorn;is merchan&dtail; come vnto hy&mtail;, he
wolde giff hy&mtail; a grete substance of money of his monasterie.
And many yeris &thorn;is money at [his] bruther gaff hy&mtail;, he
mengi&dtail; it with his aw&ntail; in his merchandice, &amp; euer his
gudis fa[ylid] hy&mtail;, &amp; he loste a&llbar; &thorn;at evu&rtail;
he di&dtail;.  Not-with-stondyng, afo&rtail; his bruther was abbott,
he [w]a[s] a wurthie merchan&dtail;, &amp; was a riche ma&ntail; &amp;
hedi&dtail; gretelie vnto his bying and his sellyng.  So o&ntail; a
tyme &thorn;is abbott his bruther sent after hy&mtail;, whe&ntail; he
harde of his rewle, and sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "Bruther, whi
wastis &thorn;ou &thorn;us vilauslie &thorn;i substance &amp; &thorn;i
gudis bothe vn[to &thorn;i] confusio&ntail; &amp; myne?"  Tha&ntail;
&thorn;is merchan&dtail; ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
sai&dtail;, "I liff als skantlie as I ca&ntail;, &amp; diligentlie I
kepe a&llbar; my merchandice, and I wote neuer how it behappens vn[to
me], ffor my felows profettis &amp; waxis riche me&ntail;, &amp; I
defayle &amp; waxis pure."  So he tuke his lefe att his bruther &amp;
wente home.  And so, as he went hamwer&dtail;, he fe&llbar; into a
grete compunccio&ntail;, &amp; trusti&dtail; he had done so&mtail;
grete sy&ntail;, &thorn;at causi&dtail; his gudis to fa&llbar; away
fro&mtail; hy&mtail; be grevans of a&llbar;-mighti God.  So he
avisi&dtail; hy&mtail;, and went to a preste and shrafe hy&mtail;,
&amp; tolde hy&mtail; a&llbar; his life.  And &thorn;is preste
ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "The money at &thorn;ou
hase take&ntail; of &thorn;i bruther, it is stoltherye, &amp; it
wastis &thorn;i money and &thorn;i gudis, and &thorn;erfo&rtail; fro
hens furt&hbar; take no mo&rtail; money of hy&mtail;, &amp; &thorn;ou
sa&llbar; do wele enog&hbar;.  And with &thorn;at litle &thorn;at is
lefte



<PB N="9">

the make &thorn;i merchandice, &amp; halfe of &thorn;i winnyng alway
restore agay&ntail; vnto &thorn;e abbay, ewhils &thorn;ou hafe payde
agay&ntail; a&llbar; att &thorn;i bruther lente the, &amp; liff of
&thorn;e toder halfe of &thorn;i wynnyng"; and so he di&dtail;.  And
with-in a while he waxi&dtail; so riche, at he restori&dtail; a&llbar;
agay&ntail; &thorn;at his bruther had giffe&ntail; hy&mtail;; and
&thorn;a&ntail; he was a passand riche ma&ntail;.  So o&ntail; a tyme
&thorn;is abbot had grete mervayle of hy&mtail; &amp; saide vn[to]
hy&mtail;; "how erte &thorn;ou waxe&ntail; riche so sodanlie, &amp;
within a while was bod a pure ma&ntail;?"  And he ansswer&dtail;
hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "Bruther abbott, als long as I
reseyvi&dtail; &thorn;[e] substance &amp; &thorn;e gudis of &thorn;i
brethers of the, I was euer pure &amp; bakstad; and &thorn;ou did
grete sy&ntail; att gaff me itt, for &thorn;ou did bod stale it fro
&thorn;i brether &amp; gaf me it.  And euer se&ntail; I forsuke to
take swilk stolethery, I hafe abundi&dtail; &amp; waxin ryche of
gudi[s]; and &thorn;erfo&rtail; I wi&llbar; no mo&rtail; of &thorn;i
money, for &thorn;uf a&llbar; &thorn;ou hase it in gouernance, yitt
itt is &thorn;i brethers als wele as thyne." et c&curl;.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> X.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Abbas in vestibus et in calciamentis humilem se
debet ostendere.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede of ane Abbott off Ceustus ordur, how he o&ntail; a tyme
come vnto Philip&ptail;, &thorn;at was kyng of Romayns, for dyvers
nedis of his howse, for to speke with hy&mtail;.  So &thorn;e kyng
behel&dtail; his hose &amp; his shone, &amp; &thorn;ai war passand
strayte &amp; clenlie done vppo&ntail;; and whe&ntail; he had
con[s]ydurd &thorn;is, he aski&dtail; &thorn;is abbott of whyne he
was; and &thorn;is abbott ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
sayd, "Sur, I a&mtail; abbott of a fu&llbar; pure howse."  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e kyng sai&dtail; agay&ntail; vnto hy&mtail;,
"Sur, &thorn;at semys wele be you&rtail; hose &amp; you&rtail; shone
&thorn;at your howse is made passand pure, for &thorn;ai er costios
&amp; dere."  And with &thorn;is wur&dtail; &thorn;is abbott was
confusi&dtail;, &amp; neuer after ware so costios hose nor shone, nor
so strayte as he did befo&rtail;.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Abbatis simplicitas plus prodest aliquando
Conuentui quam ipsius calliditas.  de bona vxore.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how &thorn;er was a monk of Clariua&llbar; &thorn;at was
Abbott &thorn;er, &amp; his name was Petur, &amp; he was a passan&dtail;
innocent ma&ntail;.  So

<PB N="10">

hy&mtail; happyn&dtail; o&ntail; a day he <NOTE ID="P10.N1">MS. &thorn;ai.</NOTE> was
[a]ssigny&dtail; for to go, &amp; a monke with hy&mtail;, to speke
with a knyght &thorn;at had tane myku&llbar; of &thorn;is abbott gudis
fro hy&mtail;, and sai&dtail; &thorn;ai war his aw&ntail;; and
&thorn;is knyght mett &thorn;is abbott at a place apoynti&dtail;, with
a grete menyay of his kyns-me&ntail; with hy&mtail;.  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;ai wer mett, The abbott said vnto &thorn;is knyght, "Thow ert a
criste&ntail; ma&ntail;; and &thorn;erfo&rtail; &amp; &thorn;ou
wi&llbar; say <NOTE ID="P10.N2">MS. said.</NOTE> of suthfastnes &amp; be &thorn;i
treuth at &thorn;ies gudis er &thorn;ine, I wu&llbar; trew the, &amp;
fro hens furthe speke no more &thorn;eroff."  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e
knyght har&dtail; &thorn;is he was passand fay&ntail;, &amp;
forsi&dtail; litle of suthefastnes, and sai&dtail; &thorn;at o&ntail;
suthfastenes &amp; be his treuthe, &thorn;ase gudis war his &amp; not
&thorn;e abbays.  Tha&ntail; &thorn;e abbott say&dtail;, "thyne be
thay"; and &thorn;us &thorn;ai parti&dtail;, &amp; &thorn;e abbott
lefte hy&mtail; &thorn;is gude.  Tha&ntail; &thorn;is knyght went home
&amp; tolde his wife, and sho as a gude woma&ntail; was fer&dtail;
&thorn;erof, &amp; sai&dtail; vnto hur husban&dtail;; "fforsuthe, Sur,
&thorn;ou hase done dissaytefullie agay&ntail; yone holie abbott.  Be
war, for bod if &thorn;ou resto&rtail; agay&ntail; vnto yone abbott
&thorn;e gudis at &thorn;ou hase taky&ntail; &thorn;erfra, &thorn;ou
sa&llbar; want my felowshu&ptail;"; and &thorn;urgh hur cownce&llbar;
&amp; hur saying he was agaste.  And o&ntail; &thorn;e mor&ntail; he
went vnto Clareva&llbar; abbay, &amp; come vnto &thorn;e abbott, &amp;
renowcid a&llbar; &thorn;ies gudis &amp; forsuke &thorn;aim, &amp;
restori&dtail; &thorn;e abbay agay&ntail;, and praye&dtail; &thorn;e
abbott for to forgyff hy&mtail; &thorn;at wrong at he had done vnto
hy&mtail;.</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Abbas durus ad simplicitatem et hospitalitatem
divisioni subiacet.  Infra de
histrionibus.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Abbas infirmis multum debet
condescendere.</FOREIGN></HEAD> 

<P> Som tyme &thorn;er was ane abbott of Cistus, &thorn;at hight
Cesarius, comandi&dtail; vnto a monk of his &thorn;at was seke,
&thorn;at he sulde eate fless&hbar;; and &thorn;is monke obeyi&dtail;
his commandment, &thorn;uff a&llbar; it was agay&ntail; his wi&llbar;,
and sai&dtail; vnto his abbott; "and I pray you for charitie &thorn;at
ye wu&llbar; vuchesafe to eate flessc&hbar; with me."  An&dtail; onone
&thorn;is abbott graunti&dtail; &amp; sett hy&mtail; dow&ntail; be
&thorn;e monke, &amp; tuke a morse&llbar; of [flessc]&hbar; oute of
&thorn;e seke ma&ntail; platir &amp; eate it.  So it happen&dtail;
&thorn;at





<PB N="11">

with-in ij dayes after, &thorn;is abbott went vnto a kur&ktee;
wha&rtail; &thorn;er was a ma&ntail; &thorn;at had a fen&dtail; in
hy&mtail;, and onone as &thorn;is abbott saw hy&mtail;, he spak vnto
&thorn;e fen&dtail; &amp; sai&dtail;.  "O! &thorn;ou i&llbar; spirit!
I coniure &thorn;e &amp; chargis the &thorn;urg&hbar; &thorn;at
charite be &thorn;e whilk laste day I ete fless&hbar; for my monke
sake, at &thorn;ou tarie here no langer, bod pas furt&hbar; of
&thorn;is ma&ntail;."  And onone &thorn;is fende fle&dtail; &amp; went
furt&hbar; of &thorn;is ma&ntail;, becauce &thorn;e fire of charite
was so hate &thorn;at he myght not suffer it.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Abbatissa semper subiectas sibi in dissiplina
debet regere, et ad beatam mariam virginem deuocionem
habere.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Som tyme &thorn;er was a no&ntail; &thorn;at was ane abbatiss of a
grete place, and sho was called gude of gouernans bothe in wurde &amp;
dede; &amp; with a spiritua&llbar; luf sho did &thorn;e cure &thorn;at
sho had take&ntail; of hir sisters. &amp; with grete aw &amp;
straytnes, &thorn;e congregacio&ntail; att sho had gouernan[s] of, sho
compelli&dtail; to kepe &thorn;er ordur.  Notwithstondyng,
&thorn;urg&hbar; entysing of &thorn;e devu&llbar;, sho lete hur
carvur, &thorn;at was hur aw&ntail; syb-ma&ntail;, hafe at do with
hur, so &thorn;at sho conseyvid and was with childe.  And for a&llbar;
&thorn;at, yit sho lett nott, bod kepyd diligentlie emang hur susters
&thorn;e rigur of disciplyne.  Tha&ntail; it happend &thorn;at sho wex
grete &amp; drew nere hur tyme, &amp; hur susters &thorn;e nonnys
purseyvi&dtail;, &amp; was passan&dtail; fay&ntail; &thorn;erof,
becauce sho wa[s] so strayte vnto &thorn;aim, at &thorn;ai myght have
a cauce to accuse hur in.  And hur accusers garte write vnto &thorn;e
bissho&ptail; &amp; lete hy&mtail; wete &thorn;erof, and desiri&dtail;
hy&mtail; to co&mtail; vnto &thorn;er place and see hur.  So he
grawnti&dtail;, and &thorn;e day of hy&mtail; commyng drew nere.  And
&thorn;is abbatis, &thorn;at was grete with childe, made meku&llbar;
sorow &amp; wiste neuer what sho might do.  And sho had a privay
chape&llbar; with-in hur chawmer, &thorn;er sho was wunt daylie als
devoutlie as sho cuthe to say our ladie matyns.  And sho went in
&thorn;er &amp; sparri&dtail; &thorn;e dure vnto hur, and fe&llbar;
devoutelie o&ntail; kneis befo&rtail; &thorn;e ymage of our ladi,
&amp; made hur prayer vnto hur, &amp; wepid sore for hur sy&ntail; and
besoght vr ladie for to helpe hur &amp; safe hur, &thorn;at sho war
not shamy&dtail; whe&ntail; &thorn;is bisshop&ptail; come.  So in hur
prayers sho happen&dtail; to fa&llbar;

<PB N="12">

o&ntail; slepe, and our ladie, as hur thoght, apperi&dtail; vnto hur
with ij angels, &amp; comfurthi&dtail; hur &amp; sai&dtail; vnto hur
in &thorn;is maner of wise; "I hafe har&dtail; &thorn;i prayer, and I
hafe gette&ntail; of my so&ntail; forgifnes of &thorn;i sy&ntail;,
&amp; delyverans of &thorn;i confusion."  And onone sho was delyvur of
hur childe, &amp; our ladie chargi&dtail; &thorn;ies ij angels to hafe
it vnto ane hermett, &amp; chargi&dtail; hy&mtail; to bryng it
v&ptail; vnto it was vij yere olde; and &thorn;ai did as sho
commaundi&dtail; &thorn;aim; &amp; onone ou&rtail; ladie
vanysshi&dtail; away.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is abbatiss
wakyn&dtail; &amp; grapi&dtail; hur selfe, &amp; fel&dtail; hur selfe
delyvurd of hur childe, &amp; hole &amp; sownde; &amp; sho thankid
almighti God &amp; ou&rtail; blissi&dtail; ladie &thorn;at &thorn;us
h[ad] delyvur&dtail; hur.  In &thorn;e mene while o&ntail; a day,
&thorn;is bissho&ptail; come &amp; went into &thorn;e chapit&rtail;
howse, &amp; calli&dtail; a&llbar; &thorn;e nonnys afor&ntail;
hy&mtail;; &amp; &thorn;is abbatis wol&dtail; hafe gone vp &amp; sett
hur in hur stede be &thorn;e bissho&ptail; as sho was wunte to do; and
&thorn;is bissho&ptail; reprovi&dtail; hur &amp; chargi&dtail; hur to
go furt&hbar; of &thorn;e chapit&rtail;, &amp; sai&dtail; sho was not
wur[thi] to be &thorn;er-in. &amp; whe&ntail; sho was gone he sent ij
clerkis after hur to examy&ntail; h[ur], &amp; to serche whethur sho
wer with childe or noght; &amp; &thorn;ai cuthe fynde no taky&ntail;
o&ntail; hur &thorn;at sho sulde be with childe.  And &thorn;ai come
vnto &thorn;e bissho&ptail; &amp; tolde hy&mtail; &thorn;at sho was
innocent of &thorn;at at sho was accusi&dtail; of.  Neuer-&thorn;e-les
&thorn;is bisshop mystristi&dtail; &thorn;aim, &amp; trowid &thorn;ai
had taky&ntail; so&mtail; money of hur, &amp; he sai&dtail; he wolde
serge hur hy&mtail; selfe; &amp; so he did, &amp; he cuthe not fynde
in hur no synge &thorn;at sho sulde be with childe.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is bissho&ptail; fe&llbar; downe befo&rtail;
hur o&ntail; his kneis, &amp; aski&dtail; hur forgifnes of &thorn;e
wrong at he had done vnto hur; and a&llbar; &thorn;aim &thorn;at had
accusi&dtail; hur, he chargi&dtail; at &thorn;ai sulde be putt oute of
&thorn;e place.  And &thorn;is abbatis besoght hy&mtail; nay, and
forgaff &thorn;aim at &thorn;ai had saide vppo&ntail; hur.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; sho tuke &thorn;is bissho&ptail; in confessio&ntail;
&amp; tolde hy&mtail; a&llbar; how it had happend hur, &amp; how
ow&rtail; ladie had delyver&dtail; hur; and &thorn;is bissho&ptail;
had grete mervayle &thorn;erof, &amp; sent &thorn;ies ij clerkis vnto
&thorn;is hermett to luke if it wer so or noght.  &amp; &thorn;ai
broght &thorn;e bisshop&ptail; wurd fro the hermett, &thorn;at ij yong
me&ntail; had broght hy&mtail; &thorn;is childe, &amp; sai&dtail;
&thorn;at our ladie commaundid hy&mtail; to kepe it vij yere.  And
whe&ntail; it was vij yere olde, &thorn;is bisshop tuke it &amp; garte
putt it vnto &thorn;e skule, &amp; it encreci&dtail; gretelie in
vertue &amp; connyng, vnto so meku&llbar; &thorn;att whe&ntail;
&thorn;is bissho&ptail; decesi&dtail;, he was made bissho&ptail; after
hy&mtail; nexte succedyng.

<PB N="13">
</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Abbatissa pura et munda debet esse corpore et
temptacionibus omnino resistere.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede be tellyng of olde fadurs, how &thorn;at &thorn;er was a
holie abbatis, and sho was gretelie vexi&dtail; xiij yere with
&thorn;e sy&ntail; of fornycacio&ntail;, &amp; euer whe&ntail; sho was
tempi&dtail; sho prayed a&llbar;-myghti Go&dtail; to send hur strenth
to withston&dtail; &thorn;is temptacio&ntail;, &amp; not for to mofe
it away.  So o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;e spiritt of fornycacio&ntail;
apperid vnto hur bodelie &amp; sai&dtail;; "&thorn;ou hase
ouer-comme&ntail; me."  &amp; sho ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
sai&dtail;, "I hafe not ouercomme&ntail; &thorn;e, bod my Lord Iesu
Criste hase ouercomme&ntail; &thorn;e." et c&curl;.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Abbatissa non debet esse in vestibus et lectis
nimis delicata.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in a fable how at &thorn;e lop&ptail; &amp; &thorn;e gutt
o&ntail; a tyme spak to-gedre, &amp; emang &thorn;er o&thorn;er
talkyng, athir of &thorn;aim aski&dtail; other of &thorn;er lugyng,
&amp; how &thorn;ai war herber&dtail; &amp; whare, &thorn;e night next
befo&rtail;.  And &thorn;e lop&ptail; made a grete playnte &amp;
sai&dtail;, "I was herber&dtail; in &thorn;e bed of ane abbatice,
betwix ij white shetis, opo&ntail; a softe matres, &amp; &thorn;er I
trowe&dtail; to hafe had gude herberie, for hur fless&hbar; was fatt
&amp; tendre, &amp; &thorn;erof I trowi&dtail; to hafe ha&dtail; my
fy&llbar;.  &amp; furste, whe&ntail; I bega&ntail; <NOTE ID="P13.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, furste.</NOTE> for to bite hur, sho bega&ntail; to cry &amp;
ca&llbar; o&ntail; hur maydyns, and whe&ntail; &thorn;ai come, onone
&thorn;ai lighti&dtail; candels &amp; soght me, bod I hi&dtail; me to
&thorn;ai war gone.  &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; I bate hur agay&ntail;,
&amp; sho come agay&ntail; &amp; soght me with a light, So &thorn;at I
was fay&ntail; to lepe oute of &thorn;e be&dtail;.  And so a&llbar;
&thorn;is nyght I had no reste, bod was chasi&dtail; &amp;
charri&dtail; &amp; vnnethis gatt away with my life."  Tha&ntail;
ansswer&dtail; &thorn;e gowte &amp; sai&dtail;, "I was herber&dtail;
in a pure wommans howse, &amp; onone as I prikki&dtail; hur in hur
thomble ta, sho rase &amp; uetti&dtail; a grete bo&llbar; fu&llbar; of
clothis, &amp; went with &thorn;aim vnto &thorn;e watir, &amp; stude
&thorn;er-in with me vp to hur kneis; so &thorn;at, what for calde
&amp; for holdyng in &thorn;e watir, I was nere-han&dtail;
slay&ntail;."  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e lop&ptail; sai&dtail;,



<PB N="14">

"This night wi&llbar; we [cha]nge ou&rtail; herbery"; &amp; so
&thorn;ai di&dtail;.  &amp; o&ntail; &thorn;e mor&ntail; &thorn;ai
mett agay&ntail;; &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e lop&ptail; sai&dtail;
vnto &thorn;e gowte, "&thorn;is night hafe I had gude herberie, for
&thorn;e womma&ntail; &thorn;at was &thorn;ine oste yisternyght was so
werie and so yrke, &thorn;at I was sekurlie herberd with hur, &amp;
eate of hur blude als meku&llbar; as I wol&dtail;."  And
&thorn;a&ntail; ansswer&dtail; &thorn;e gutt &amp; said vnto &thorn;e
lop&ptail;, "&thorn;ou gaff me gude cownce&llbar; yistreve&ntail;, for
&thorn;e abbatiss vnder-nethe a gay couerlade, &amp; a softe shete and
a delicate, couerde me &amp; nurisshi&dtail; me a&llbar; nyght.  &amp;
als sone as I prikkid in hur thomble ta, sho wappid me in furris,
&amp; if I hurte hir neuer so i&llbar;, so lete me alone, &amp; laide
me in the softests place of &thorn;e be&dtail;, &amp; tribulde me
nothyng.  And &thorn;erfo&rtail; als lang as sho liffis I wil[l] be
herber&dtail; with hur, for sho makis meki&llbar; of me."  And
&thorn;a&ntail; sai&dtail; &thorn;e lop&ptail;, "I wu&llbar; be
herber&dtail; with pure folke als lang as I liff, for &thorn;er may I
be in gude reste &amp; ete my fy&llbar;, &amp; no bod[ie] lett me."
And &thorn;us &thorn;e gowte abade with ric&hbar;e folk &amp; &thorn;e
lop&ptail; with pure folk. et c&curl;.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Abscondere.  Abscondere debet mulier pulcritudinem
suam ne aliquis in eam offendat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Eaclides <NOTE ID="P14.N1">Latin MSS. Heraclides.</NOTE> tellis how att &thorn;er was a
mayde&ntail; whase name was Alexandria, &thorn;at garte cloce hur
selfe in a grete grafe, &amp; tuke hur meat att a little hole, to so
meku&llbar; &thorn;at x yere to-gedyr sho saw neuer nowder ma&ntail;
nor womma&ntail;, nor shewi&dtail; nevur hur visage to no creatur.  So
o&ntail; a tyme, &thorn;er come a ma&ntail; vnto hur hole, &amp;
spirri&dtail; whi sho was closi&dtail; &thorn;er &amp; wolde not
co&mtail; oute.  And sho ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;,
"So&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a yong ma&ntail; &thorn;at luki&dtail;
o&ntail; my fayrehede, &amp; &thorn;urg&hbar; &thorn;at luke his saule
was hurte with sy&ntail;; &amp; &thorn;erfo&rtail; or I sulde be sene
for to hevie any ma&ntail;, me had leuer be closi&dtail; in &thorn;is
grafe als lang as I liff, &thorn;a&ntail; for to noy &thorn;e saule
&thorn;at is made vnto &thorn;e liknes of almighti God."  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is ma&ntail; askid hur how sho might liff so;
Sho ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;, "fro &thorn;e
begynyng of &thorn;e day I fa&llbar; in hand with my prayers, &amp;
forther-mo&rtail; of &thorn;e day I wurk lyne wer&ktee;, and
&thorn;a&ntail; I &thorn;ink of holie martyrs, confessurs, &amp;
virgynnys,



<PB N="15">

and &thorn;a&ntail; I take me meate &amp; dryn&ktee;; and
&thorn;a&ntail; agai&ntail; evy&ntail; I go to ryste, &amp; &thorn;er
I wurschu&ptail; allmyghti Go&dtail;.  And &thorn;us I abide &thorn;e
ende of my life with a gude hope, &amp; a belefe &thorn;at I sa&llbar;
be savi&dtail; o&ntail; &thorn;e day of dome." et c&curl;.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Absolucio.  Absolucio eciam valet post
mortem.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede of a monke &thorn;at hight Hubertus, whilk &thorn;at
whe&ntail; he sulde dy, he aski&dtail; straytlie &thorn;at &thorn;e
abbott myght co&mtail; vnto hy&mtail; &amp; assoyle hy&mtail;, as he
di&dtail; other of his brether &thorn;at dye&dtail;.  And &thorn;is
abbott was fro home, &amp; in &thorn;e mene while [&thorn;is] monke
deye&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e abbott come home &thorn;ai
telli&dtail; hy&mtail;, and &thorn;is abbo[tt] went vnto &thorn;e
alta&rtail; &thorn;er &thorn;is monk was beri&dtail;, &amp; sett
hy&mtail; dow&ntail; o&ntail; his kneis &amp; prayed for hy&mtail;.
And as he satt in his prayers, hy&mtail; &thorn;oght &thorn;is monke
rase oute of his grafe &amp; come vnto hy&mtail;, &amp; sai&dtail;,
"Benedicite!"  right as he had bene o life, and askid a due
absolucio&ntail;.  So &thorn;is abbott, gretlie astony&dtail;
&thorn;er-with, Sai&dtail;, " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">miseriatur tui et
c&curl;, et absolucionem.</FOREIGN>" And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is
mon&ktee; aski&dtail; hy&mtail; penans.  And &thorn;is abbott wiste
neuer whatky&ntail; penance sulde be giffe&ntail; vnto &thorn;aim at
wer deade; and he commandi&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;at he sulde be in
purgatorie vnto he had sai&dtail; a mes for hy&mtail;.  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;e mon&ktee; har&dtail; &thorn;is, he crye&dtail; so horrible,
&thorn;at a&llbar; &thorn;e abbay har&dtail;, o&ntail; &thorn;is maner
of wise; "O !  &thorn;ou ma&ntail; with-oute mercie! &thorn;at hase
commandi&dtail; me to be so long in &thorn;e grete pay&ntail; of
purga[to]rie <NOTE ID="P15.N1">MS. purgarie.</NOTE> ."  And with &thorn;at he
vanysshi&dtail; away.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Absolucio ad-huc valet post
mortem.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in &thorn;e life of Saynt Gregur how at &thorn;er was ane
abbott of a monasterie off Saynt Gregories, and he come vnto Saynt
Gregur &amp; tolde hy&mtail; how &thorn;at he had a monk in his place
&thorn;at vsi&dtail; for to cone mony vnder-nethe &thorn;e ert&hbar;,
&amp; wolde not lefe it for no commandmente.  And Saynt Gregur sent
for hy&mtail;, &amp; chargi&dtail; o pay&ntail; of cursyng to lefe it.
So with-in a while after, &thorn;is monke dye&dtail;, &amp; Saynt
Gregur wuste nott.  And whe&ntail; he was enforme&dtail; &thorn;erof,



<PB N="16">

he was wrothe &thorn;at &thorn;is monke die&dtail; vnasoyli&dtail;.
And he wrote his absolucio&ntail; in a scrow of papir to assoyle
hy&mtail; of &thorn;e sai&dtail; sentans of cursyng, and gaff it vnto
ane of his dekyns, &amp; commandi&dtail; him to go vnto &thorn;is
monke grafe &thorn;er he was beri&dtail;, &amp; rede it ouer
hy&mtail;.  And he did so, and vppo&ntail; &thorn;e nyght after,
&thorn;is monk &thorn;at was deade apperi&dtail; in a visio&ntail;
vnto his abbott, &amp; tolde hy&mtail; &thorn;at fro he was dede vnto
he was asoyli&dtail; he was in grete pay&ntail;, bod fro &thorn;e
how&rtail; &thorn;at he was asoyli&dtail; he went vnto blis, &amp; was
delyver&dtail; of a&llbar; his pay&ntail;.  et c&curl;.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Abstinencia.  Abstinencia debet esse
discreta.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Collacionibus Patrum,' how &thorn;at a gude halie
abbott, &thorn;at hight Moyses, o&ntail; a tyme sai&dtail; of
hy&mtail; selfe in &thorn;is maner of wise; "I remembre so for to hafe
dispysi&dtail; &thorn;e appetite of mete &amp; drynke, so at ij dayes
or iij, mete nor drynke was neuer in my mynde.  And I hafe so abstenyd
me fro slepe, not-with-stonding I was attempti&dtail; gretlie
&thorn;erto be &thorn;e devu&llbar;, &thorn;at many nyghtis &amp; many
[dayis] <NOTE ID="P16.N1">Latin MSS. ut per plures dies ac noctes.</NOTE>  I slepi&dtail; neuer a dele, bod bad
my prayers vnto almyghti Go&dtail;.  And yitt I feli&dtail; my selfe,
&thorn;at I had dyvers tymys mo&rtail; hurte with outrage takyng of
meate &amp; dryn&ktee; &amp; slepe &thorn;a&ntail; with abstinens
&thorn;eroff."  Bod monkis er not so now o dayis, for or a monk
wanti&dtail; now ane how&rtail; slepe, or a negg of his serves in his
diss&hbar;, hy&mtail; had levur &thorn;at his howse was in xx &lbar;i
dett.  And so war nott monkis in olde tyme <NOTE ID="P16.N2">This tale is very different from the Latin version.</NOTE>
.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Abstinencia singularis in commitate est
reprehensibilis.</FOREIGN></HEAD> 

<P> We rede in a buke &thorn;at is calli&dtail; 'Vit&aelig; <NOTE ID="P16.N3">MS. Vitas.</NOTE> Patrum,' how o&ntail; a tyme, a&llbar; &thorn;e
monkis &thorn;at was in ane abbay opo&ntail; a solempne fastyng-day
ete samen in &thorn;er fratur.  And emang &thorn;aim &thorn;er was one
&thorn;at bad bryn&gtee; hy&mtail; salte, for he ete no buli&dtail; meate.
And he &thorn;at he bad bryng hy&mtail; salte was occupie&dtail; with
o&thorn;er laburs, and forgatt to







<PB N="17">

bryng hy&mtail; itt; &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is monk calli&dtail;
&thorn;er-fo&rtail; agay&ntail;.  And &thorn;is servand cried vp
opo&ntail; hyght and bad so&mtail; ma&ntail; bryng salte vnto
&thorn;is monke, for he ete no buli&dtail; mete.  And &thorn;a&ntail;
rase vp one alde mon&ktee; &amp; sai&dtail; vnto &thorn;is monk
&thorn;at calli&dtail; for salte; "Bruther, it had bene mo&rtail;
expedient vnto &thorn;e &thorn;is day for to hafe ety&ntail;
fless&hbar; in &thorn;i ce&llbar;, &thorn;a&ntail; for to hafe made
&thorn;is voyce of &thorn;ine abstinence emange so many of &thorn;i
brethir."</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Abstinencia moderata pro loco et tempore displicet
diabolo.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Jacobus de Vetriaco <NOTE ID="P17.N1">MS. Vetriano.</NOTE> tellis how &thorn;at
&thorn;er was a holie Saynt &thorn;at hight Maria de Oginiez, whilk
&thorn;at oft sithes punysshi&dtail; hur selfe with grete abstinence.
So o&ntail; a tyme sho refresshi&dtail; hur with mete, &amp; as sho
satt etand sho was war <NOTE ID="P17.N2"><HI REND="i">After</HI> war, vi, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> of &thorn;e devu&llbar;;
&amp; with a grete [con]tenans &amp; ane angrie he sai&dtail; vnto
hur, "Beholde &thorn;is gluto&ntail;! how ferventlie sho etis!"  And
sho satt sti&llbar; &amp; vmbethoght hur, &amp; knew his falssett
we&llbar; enog&hbar;, &amp; ete o&ntail;.  &amp; euer &thorn;e
devu&llbar; wolde hafe lett hur for to hafe ety&ntail;, becauce he
wulde sho had dyed for defawte; and ay &thorn;e mo&rtail; he lett hur
to ete, &thorn;e mo&rtail; sho ete.  And he saw at sho wolde not lett
to ete for hy&mtail;, bo&dtail; at ay &thorn;e langer he laburd hur,
&thorn;e more sho ete.  [&] with a grete crying &amp; a noyse he
vanyshi&dtail; away fro hur, &amp; neuer after truble&dtail; hur nor
di&dtail; hur har&mtail;.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Admirabilis abstinencia.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis <NOTE ID="P17.N3">MS. Vitas.</NOTE> Patrum' how &thorn;at
&thorn;er was a gude holie alde ma&ntail;, &amp; xl yere he
dran&ktee; nevur; &amp; evur he wulde take a vesse&llbar; &amp;
fulfi&llbar; it with wyne &amp; hyng it in his chawm[re] &thorn;at he
mott daylie se it.  So o&ntail; a tyme his brethir asky&dtail;
hy&mtail; whi he did so, and he ansswerd agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;,
"I do it to &thorn;is entent, &thorn;at whe&ntail; I se &thorn;at
&thorn;ing at I desire, &thorn;at with abstinens &thorn;erof I may
suffre mo&rtail; pay&ntail;; and so of almyghti God I sa&llbar; have
more mede."







<PB N="18">
</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Abstinencia refrenat concupiscenciam in re habita
que fuerat concupita vel desiderata.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede ex 'Dictis Patrum' how &thorn;at &thorn;er was so&mtail;
tyme a ma&ntail; of religio&ntail;, &thorn;at be temptacio&ntail; of
&thorn;e devu&llbar; covett gretle to ete spyce.  So o&ntail; a tyme
he boght hy&mtail; spice, &amp; wulde not ete &thorn;erof, bod hang it
befo&rtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;at he mott se itt.  &amp; becauce he
wolde not be ouercomme&ntail; with covatice &thorn;erof, he wolde
neuer eate &thorn;ero&ntail; nor tuche itt, Bod euer whe&ntail; he saw
itt, punysshi&dtail; his body &thorn;erwith becauce &thorn;at it
desiri&dtail; it.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Abstinencia interdum vincit diabolum
inpugnantem.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis <NOTE ID="P18.N1">MS. Vitas.</NOTE> Patrum' how at &thorn;er
was a freer &thorn;at was so gretelie tempi&dtail; with &thorn;e
devu&llbar;, &thorn;at euer-ilk day, at iij of &thorn;e be&llbar;, he
fe&llbar; into so grete a honger, &thorn;at he myght not suffer it.
So o&ntail; a tyme he sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; selfe, "Benedicite!
how is it with me, &thorn;at I a&mtail; so turment with suche a honger
at iij of &thorn;e be&llbar; in &thorn;e mornyng, so &thorn;at I may
nott forbere meate no day vnto vj of &thorn;e clokk, or ix, or none?"
And euer-ilk day befo&rtail; none, not-with-stondyng a&llbar;
&thorn;is honger, he wul&dtail; say his matyns, his mes, &amp; his
o&thorn;er prayers <NOTE ID="P18.N2">MS. prayes.</NOTE> ilk day or he ete any meate,
as &thorn;e rewle of his religio&ntail; aski&dtail;, and
&thorn;a&ntail; he wulde sett hy&mtail; dow&ntail; &amp; take
hy&mtail; meate; and &thorn;us he di&dtail; many day.  So o&ntail; a
day whe&ntail; he had bene at his prayers, he walki&dtail; vp &amp;
dow&ntail; in a garthy&ntail;, &amp; hy&mtail; thoght &thorn;er come
so swete a savur oute of his parce&llbar; be&dtail; &amp; his erbis,
&thorn;at he was so replete &thorn;erwith &thorn;at ij or iij dayes
hy&mtail; liste nevur at e[ate].  And yit hy&mtail; thoght &thorn;at
he was als strong of hy&mtail; selfe as he had ety&ntail; sufficient
at evur-ilk mele tyme.  et c&curl;.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Abstinencia a nimis potu reddit hominem cautum in
consilijs et facundum in verbis.</FOREIGN></HEAD> <P> Helinandus, a
grete cler&ktee;, writan&dtail; of &thorn;e life &amp; maners of one
&thorn;at hight Romulus, &thorn;at was one of &thorn;e foundors of
Rome, wrate





<PB N="19">

o&ntail; hy&mtail; in &thorn;is maner of wise &amp; sai&dtail;,
&thorn;at agayns &thorn;is Romulus sul&dtail; go vnto &thorn;e
cownce&llbar; howse, he wold not drynke, &amp; in-esspecia&llbar;
wyne, bod in esy quantitie iij dayes befo&rtail;.  So o&ntail; a tyme
a gude ma&ntail; of Rome, &thorn;at purseyvid his condicio&ntail;,
sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;, "Thow Romullus! and a&llbar; me&ntail;
di&dtail; as &thorn;ou duse, wyne sulde not be in Rome in so grete
dayntie as it is.  For &amp; no ma&ntail; wolde dryn&ktee; no
mo&rtail; &thorn;erof &thorn;an &thorn;ou Duse, it sulde not be so
dere as it is."  et c&curl;.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Abstinencia indiscreta est nimis
periculosa.</FOREIGN></HEAD> <P> Cesarius tellis how a devu&llbar; in
liknes of ane aunge&llbar; apperi&dtail; evur-ilk day vnto a monke
whe&ntail; he was at his meate, &amp; shewi&dtail; hy&mtail; alway
halfe a lafe, &amp; bad hy&mtail; no mo&rtail; bod &thorn;at.  And
&thorn;e monke did evur as he bad hy&mtail;, &amp; with-in a shorte
while he wex passand wayke.  And &thorn;er fe&llbar; a swyngyllyng in
his hede &thorn;at he wex fonde with, &amp; mad as a guse; &amp; so he
contynued vnto he deyi&dtail;.  et c&curl;.</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Abstinencia a carnibus est necessaria.  Infra de
gula.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Abstinencia.  Abstinentibus deus providet de
necessarijs.</FOREIGN></HEAD> <P> Saynt Gregorie tellis how &thorn;at
ane abbott, &thorn;at hight Honoratus, &amp; his fadur &amp; his
moder, o&ntail; a tyme made a feste vnto his frendis.  And &thorn;er
was at &thorn;is feste a childe &thorn;at was ane of his kynsme&ntail;
&thorn;at satt att &thorn;e bur&dtail;, and whe&ntail; &thorn;ai bad
hy&mtail; eate fless&hbar;, he wolde eate none, for grete abstinens
&thorn;at he vssy&dtail;.  And &thorn;ai &thorn;at satt abowte
lowg&hbar; at hy&mtail;, &amp; aski&dtail; hy&mtail; in skor&ntail;,
se&ntail; he wolde nott ete fless&hbar;, if he wol&dtail; eate any
fyssc&hbar;.  &amp; he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;,
"Ya."  &amp; he had it.  And in &thorn;e mene while at &thorn;ai
talkid &thorn;us with hy&mtail;, happend &thorn;aim want watir; &amp;
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;er mawnciple went vnto &thorn;e we&llbar; &amp;
drew watir.  And as he was drawan&dtail;, &thorn;er happen&dtail; of
Sodentie a fyss&hbar; to co&mtail; in-to &thorn;e bukett, &amp;
&thorn;at a grete; &amp; he was fay&ntail; &thorn;erof, &amp; broght
it in &amp; lete &thorn;e abbott se itt.  &amp; &thorn;e abbott

<PB N="20">

garte sethe it, &amp; it was so foysonable &thorn;at it fande &thorn;e
childe and a&llbar; at was att meate fyss&hbar; enog&hbar; at a mele.
et c&curl;.</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Accepcio personarum.  Accepcione personarum multi
decipiuntur.  Infra de iudicio humano.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Accidia.  Accidia multos retrahit a bono
opere.</FOREIGN></HEAD> <P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;at a monk
o&ntail; a tyme was so tempyd with sleuthe &amp; slugisnes, &thorn;at
evur whe&ntail; he sulde rise vnto matyns, he was euer stryke&ntail;
into a grete ferdnes &amp; a fayntnes, to so meku&llbar; &thorn;at he
supposi&dtail; hy&mtail; selfe &thorn;at it was a sekenes.  &amp; ilk
nyght, whe&ntail; his brethir went to matyns, he happe&dtail; his hede
with clothis &amp; lay sti&llbar;.  So it happen&dtail; o&ntail; a
gude night, a&llbar; his brether, whe&ntail; &thorn;ai har&dtail;
&thorn;e be&llbar;, rase &amp; went to matyns.  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;ai wer gone, he thoght he wol&dtail; ryse &amp; go with
&thorn;aim, &amp; bukkled vpwar&dtail;.  And onone &thorn;is slugisnes
come o&ntail; hy&mtail;, &amp; causi&dtail; hy&mtail; lay hy&mtail;
dow&ntail; agay&ntail; &amp; hap&ptail; hys heade.  And sodanle he
hard a voyce &thorn;at was vnknowe&ntail; to hy&mtail;, as hy&mtail;
&thorn;oght, speke vnder his hede, &amp; sai&dtail;, " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Noli surgere; noli sudorem tuum interrumpere.</FOREIGN>
Rise nott, bod ly sti&llbar;, &amp; lett not &thorn;i selfe to swete;
for &amp; &thorn;ou do, it wi&llbar; hurte the."  &amp;
&thorn;a&ntail; he was halfe agaste, &amp; liftid up his han&dtail;
&amp; sayny&dtail; hy&mtail;.  And onone it smate in his myn&dtail;
&thorn;at it was bod ane illusio&ntail; of &thorn;e devu&llbar; &amp;
a fantasie, &amp; onone he rase v&ptail; &amp; went to matyns with hys
brether.  And fro thens furt&hbar;, he was neuer slugiss&hbar; to rise
&amp; go vnto Goddis serves, nor &thorn;at fayntnes nor &thorn;at
swete come neuer o&ntail; hy&mtail; aftre.</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Accidia in oratione est vitanda.  Infra de dormire
in oratione.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Accidia causatur frequenter ex eo quod homo
ociosus non cogitat circa vtilia aliqua.</FOREIGN></HEAD> <P> We rede
In 'Vitis <NOTE ID="P20.N1">MS. Vitas.</NOTE> Patrum' vnto &thorn;er was ane
ma&ntail; of religio&ntail; &thorn;at say&dtail; vnto his bruther
&thorn;at was ane olde ma&ntail;, "what sa&llbar; I do? for



<PB N="21">

I sit in my ce&llbar; &amp; duse noght, bod is made slugis with
slewt&hbar;."  Tha&ntail; &thorn;is olde ma&ntail; ansswer&dtail;
hy&mtail; &amp; sayde, "hase &thorn;ou not sene turment &thorn;at is
for to co&mtail;?  for &amp; &thorn;ou prynti&dtail; &thorn;aim in
&thorn;i harte, and &thorn;i Ce&llbar; war fu&llbar; of wormys
evy&ntail; vnto &thorn;i nek&ktee;, &thorn;ou sulde suffer it
pacientlie &amp; be nothyng slugyss&hbar; &thorn;erwith, bod take it
mekelie."</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XXX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Accusacio.  Accusat demon peccatores et scribit
peccata eorum.</FOREIGN></HEAD> 

<P> Saynt Bede tellis in 'Gestis Anglorum,' how at &thorn;er was a
knyght in Englon&dtail; &thorn;at was a dughti ma&ntail; in armys, bod
he was corrupte in maners.  And o&ntail; a tyme hy&mtail; happend to
fa&llbar; passand seke.  And &thorn;e kyng come vnto hy&mtail;, &amp;
comforthe&dtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; bad hy&mtail; be of gude chere.  And
[he] ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail; &thorn;at he myght
nott, ffor he was passand fer&dtail; &thorn;at hys seknes sul&dtail;
cover o&ntail; hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;e kyng come to hy&mtail; a noder
tyme &amp; comfurthe&dtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; bad hy&mtail; take gude
harte vnto hy&mtail; &amp; be of gude chere.  And he ansswer&dtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail; &thorn;at he myght not, for it was to
late, for he sai&dtail;; "I a&mtail; demy&dtail; &amp; dampny&dtail;;
ffor a litle while or ye come in, [&thorn;er] was here ij fay&rtail;
yong me&ntail;, and one sett hy&mtail; at my bed hede, &amp; a noder
at my fete.  And &thorn;ai sai&dtail;, 'This ma&ntail; mo&ntail; dye.
And &thorn;erfo&rtail; lat us se if we hafe any right in hy&mtail;.'
And &thorn;e tone of &thorn;aim tuke oute of his boso&mtail; a buke
writty&ntail; a&llbar; with gol&dtail; letters.  And he soght a&llbar;
&thorn;e buke &thorn;urg&hbar;, &amp; he cuthe fyn&dtail; nothyng of
me bod a few gude dedis &thorn;at I did in my yowthe&dtail;, or I
cuthe sy&ntail; deadlie; &amp; &thorn;at he shewi&dtail; me, &amp; I
was passyng glad &thorn;eroff.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;er come in
ij fowle fendis, &amp; &thorn;e tane of &thorn;aim broght with
hy&mtail; a grete blak buke, and &thorn;er-in was wrette&ntail;
a&llbar; &thorn;e evu&llbar; dedis &thorn;at evur I di&dtail;.  And
&thorn;ai said vnto &thorn;ies ij angels; 'wharto ston&dtail; ye here
al day with hy&mtail; &thorn;is?  ye hafe no right in hy&mtail;, for
&thorn;is many yeris was &thorn;er nothyng of hy&mtail; wretty&ntail;
in your buke.'  Tha&ntail; &thorn;e angels ansswer&dtail; &amp;
say&dtail;, 'Thai say suthe, &amp; &thorn;erfo&rtail; go we hyne.'
And &thorn;is done, &thorn;ies fendis cuttys me in sonder with ij
sharpe swerdis; and &thorn;e tone begynys at my fute, and &thorn;at
other at my heade, &amp; &thorn;ai smyte me now o&ntail; myne
ey&ntail;, &amp; I hafe loste my sight, and now fro my fute

<PB N="22">

&thorn;ai co&mtail; vnto my harte."  And whe&ntail; he had &thorn;us
sai&dtail; he swelte, et c&curl;.  This tale is gude to te&llbar; agayns
&thorn;aim &thorn;at er slaw in penance doyng, or at wi&llbar; not
lefe sy&ntail; or it lefe &thorn;aim. et c&curl;.</P>
<P>

<LIST><ITEM><FOREIGN>&para;. Accusat Angelus.  Infra ffideiussor.</FOREIGN></ITEM> <ITEM><FOREIGN>&para;. Accusat
demon.  Infra demon.</FOREIGN></ITEM> <ITEM><FOREIGN>&para;. Accusant Sancti.  Infra Episcopus.
ii.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XXXI.  <LB>&para;.<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Accusare fratrem non
expedit semper.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> As holie fadurs tels, we rede how &thorn;er was a holie religious
ma&ntail;, &thorn;at aski&dtail; his abbott, &thorn;at hyght
Josep&hbar;, &amp; sai&dtail;; "And I se my bruther do a tryspas, it
is gude vnto me to lay&ntail; itt?"  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is old
Abbott ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;,
"Whe&ntail; so&mtail; evur we hide &thorn;e sy&ntail; of ow&rtail;
bruther, almighti God hydis ow&rtail; sy&ntail;, &amp; whe&ntail;
so&mtail; evur we vtter &thorn;e synys of ow&rtail; brether,
&thorn;a&ntail; almightti God vtters ou&rtail; sy&ntail;."  This tale
is gude to te&llbar; vnto &thorn;aim &thorn;at luffis to sklander
&thorn;er evy&ntail; criste&ntail;.  et c&curl;.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XXXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Accusacio frequenter est falsa.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P> We rede de Sancta Marina, how at &thorn;er was a secule&rtail;
ma&ntail; &thorn;at had a doghter alone, &amp; no ma childer.  So
o&ntail; a tyme he betuke &thorn;is bar&ntail; vnto his fadur to kepe,
and went hy&mtail; [se]lfe vnto ane abbay &amp; made hy&mtail; a
monke.  And whe&ntail; he had bene &thorn;er a while, euer whe&ntail;
he thoght of his yong doghter he was passand hevie.  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;e abbott pursayvi&dtail; &thorn;is, he aski&dtail; hy&mtail;
whi he was so hevie &amp; so sa&dtail;.  And he fe&llbar; dow&ntail;
vnto hy&mtail; o&ntail; his kneys wepand, &amp; sai&dtail;, "ffadur
abbott!  I hafe a so&ntail; &thorn;at I hafe lefte in &thorn;e cytie,
&amp; evur whe&ntail; I thyn&ktee; opo&ntail; hy&mtail;, my harte is
sore &amp; passand hevie."  And yitt he wol&dtail; not te&llbar;
hy&mtail; &thorn;at it was a doghter, bod at hit was a so&ntail;.  And
&thorn;e Abbott bad hy&mtail; go &thorn;er fo&rtail;, &amp; bryng it
into &thorn;e place, &amp; kepe it with hy&mtail;, &amp; giff it meate
&amp; drynk, &amp; ler&ntail; itt.  And so he di&dtail;, and
cle&dtail; it in mans clothyng &amp; calli&dtail; it Marinus.  And he
warny&dtail; &thorn;at o&ntail; no wyse no ma&ntail; sulde know
&thorn;at it wer a womma&ntail;,

<PB N="23">

for drede &thorn;at it fe&llbar; in-to temptacio&ntail; of &thorn;e
devu&llbar;.  And whe&ntail; sho was xvii yere olde, &thorn;is
mon&ktee; hur fadur dye&dtail;, and sho was lefte alone.  &amp; no
ma&ntail; knew bod at sho was a ma&ntail;, &amp; euer-ilk bodie
luffi&dtail; hur.  So o&ntail; a tyme sho was made ane offisur in
&thorn;e abbay, for to folow &thorn;er car &amp; lede wud &amp;
fewe&llbar; vnto &thorn;er brewhowse, &amp; so sho di&dtail;; and ilka
nyght sho lay in &thorn;e brewhowse.  So o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;e
brewster doghter happen&dtail; to be with childe with a knyght at
servid &thorn;e abbott, and in &thorn;e mene while &thorn;is Marinus
was made a bruther of &thorn;e place, &amp; sho sai&dtail; &thorn;at
he was &thorn;e fadur &thorn;erof, &amp; had gette&ntail; it.  And
&thorn;e abbott garte ca&llbar; &thorn;is Marinus furt&hbar;, &amp;
examyn&dtail; hy&mtail; whethur &thorn;at he had done &thorn;is dede
or noght.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is Marinus ansswer&dtail; with a
grete sighyng &amp; sai&dtail;, "ffadur abbott!  I hafe synny&dtail;,
&amp; I ask penance for my sy&ntail;, &amp; I pray you &amp; a&llbar;
my brether to pray for me."  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e Abbott wex
wrothe with hy&mtail; &amp; putt hy&mtail; furt&hbar; of &thorn;e
abbay, and feste hy&mtail; be &thorn;e fute with a chyne with-oute
&thorn;e abbay yate, and a&llbar; me&ntail; mott wonder o&ntail;
hy&mtail;, &amp; wolde lat no ma&ntail; giff hy&mtail; meate bod att
he beggi&dtail; for Goddis sake of &thorn;aim &thorn;at come in &amp;
oute.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e childe was att spanyng, &thorn;is
brewster doghter broght it vnto hy&mtail; &amp; lefte it with
hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;is holie virgy&ntail; Marinus tuke it with gude
wi&llbar;, &amp; with meate &amp; drynk at &thorn;ai at come in &amp;
oute gaff hur, sho broght it vp&ptail;, &thorn;uf a&llbar; it war a
noder mans &amp; not hurs.  So at &thorn;e laste hur brethir had
compassio&ntail; of hur, &amp; besoght &thorn;er abbott, att he
wol&dtail; forgiff hur hur trespas, trustyng alway at sho was
ma&ntail; &amp; no womma&ntail;, ffor sho had &thorn;a&ntail; bene
feste at &thorn;e yate v yere.  And &thorn;is Abbott forgaff hur at
requeste of his brethir, &amp; tuke hur in &amp; garte putt hur vnto
al maner of vile occupasions with-in &thorn;e abbay, &amp; to be
servan&dtail; vnto evur ema&ntail;; &amp; sho was so, &amp; tuke it
plesandlie.  So with-in <NOTE ID="P23.N1"><HI REND="i">After</HI> with, <HI REND="i">some letter erased</HI>.</NOTE> a while sho dye&dtail;;
and whe&ntail; &thorn;is abbott saw at sho was deade, he sai&dtail;
vnto hys brethir, "Loo! now may ye se whatky&ntail; a sy&ntail; sho
di&dtail;, &amp; yitt sho shrafe hur neuer &thorn;erof, nor
aski&dtail; forgifnes."  An&dtail; &thorn;a&ntail; he commandi&dtail;
wass&hbar; hur bodie, &amp; berie hur far fro &thorn;e abbay.  And
whe&ntail; &thorn;ai wasshi&dtail; hur &amp; fan&dtail; &thorn;at sho
was a womma&ntail;, &thorn;ai weppi&dtail; &amp; made grete sorow
becauce &thorn;ai turment hur, &thorn;at was a womma&ntail; of so gude
conversacio&ntail; &


<PB N="24">

penance, so vnrightwuslie.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e abbot saw at sho
was a womma&ntail;, he fe&llbar; opo&ntail; his kneis &amp; bett
opo&ntail; his breste, and besoght hur of forgifnes, and commandi&dtail;
&thorn;at hur bodie sulde be beri&dtail; in &thorn;e kur&ktee;, in
ane oritorie.  And opo&ntail; &thorn;e same day &thorn;is
damyse&llbar; at bare &thorn;is childe was vexi&dtail; with a
fen&dtail;, &amp; come vnto &thorn;e abbay &amp; aski&dtail; mercy at
hur grafe; &amp; &thorn;er sho was delyverd, and grawnti&dtail; who
aght &thorn;e chil&dtail;.  &amp; &thorn;er sho abade in &thorn;e
oratorie vij dayes, &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; sho was delyver&dtail;.  And in
&thorn;at same oratorie vnto &thorn;is day, be merettis of &thorn;is
holie virgy&ntail;, is many wurthi meracle done, &thorn;urg&hbar;
vertue of Go&dtail; &amp; &thorn;is holie maydy&ntail;.</P> 
<P><LIST>

<ITEM><FOREIGN>Aduersitas.  Aduersitas presens est aliquando signum
boni.  Infra de prosperitate.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM> <FOREIGN>Adoracio.  Adorari debet corpus Christi in omni loco.
Infra de milite. v.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XXXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Adulator.  Adulator frequenter honoratur, et verax
homo contempnitur.</FOREIGN></HEAD> 

<P> Esopus tellis in his fables, how &thorn;er was ij me&ntail;, ane a
trew ma&ntail; &amp; a noder a lyer.  And &thorn;ai come to-gedur
in-to &thorn;e regio&ntail; of apis.  And emang &thorn;aim was a chefe
ape, &thorn;at satt in a hye sete &thorn;at was ordand for hy&mtail;
emang a&llbar; &thorn;e toder apis.  And he aski&dtail; &thorn;aim
many questions; emangis a&llbar; o&thorn;er he sai&dtail; vnto
&thorn;aim; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Quis sum ego?</FOREIGN> who am I?"
And &thorn;is lyer ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;, "Sur,
&thorn;ou erte ane Emperour, &amp; &thorn;ies abowte &thorn;e er
&thorn;i dukis &amp; &thorn;ine erlis &amp; &thorn;i barons&curl;."  And
onone as he had &thorn;us sai&dtail;, &thorn;is ape commandi&dtail;
hy&mtail; to hafe a grete reward.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is trew
ma&ntail; saw how &thorn;is lyer was rewardi&dtail;, and sai&dtail;
privalie vnto hy&mtail; selfe, "Now, se&ntail; he &thorn;is at did bod
make <NOTE ID="P24.N1">MS. made.</NOTE> a lye hase had suche a grete rewar&dtail;, I
mo&ntail; <NOTE ID="P24.N2">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, mo&ntail;.</NOTE> hafe a grete rewar&dtail; for my
sut&hbar; saying."  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is ape aski&dtail;
&thorn;is trew ma&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;, "who am I?"  And he
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;, "Thow ert bod ane ape,
and a&llbar; &thorn;ies o&thorn;er apis er like &thorn;e."  And onone
as he had &thorn;us sai&dtail;, he commandi&dtail; a&llbar; &thorn;e
toder apis for





<PB N="25">

to bite hy&mtail; &amp; skratt hy&mtail; with &thorn;er tethe &amp;
&thorn;er naylis; &amp; so &thorn;ai di&dtail;, to he vnnethis gatt
away with his life.  This tale is gude to te&llbar; agay&ntail;
flaterers, &amp; agayns &thorn;aim &thorn;at wu&llbar; here no thyng
bod at is to &thorn;er plesur.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XXXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Adulator non est audiendus.</FOREIGN></HEAD> 

<P>We rede how so&mtail; tyme a ma&ntail; &thorn;at hyght Seutonius,
&thorn;at was a grete lor&dtail;, o&ntail; a tyme was at a gamen in
&thorn;e Emperour presens, and &thorn;e Emperour common&dtail; &amp;
talky&dtail; with his meneyay; &amp; emang a&llbar; his o&thorn;er
saying, he say&dtail; &thorn;at &thorn;is Seutonius was a gude lorde,
and ane evy&ntail; &amp; a iuste.  And his meneya was glad &thorn;erof
&thorn;at <NOTE ID="P25.N1"><HI REND="i">After</HI> &thorn;at, his mene, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> &thorn;e Emperour commandi&dtail;
&thorn;er maister, &amp; calli&dtail; hy&mtail; lor&dtail;.  And
o&ntail; &thorn;e mor&ntail; whe&ntail; he was comme&ntail; home vnto
his place, &thorn;o &thorn;at calli&dtail; hy&mtail; lor&dtail;, he
was passand wrothe with &thorn;aim, &amp; made a decre &amp; bad
&thorn;aim neuer ca&llbar; hy&mtail; lor&dtail;, for, he sai&dtail;,
&thorn;er was no lor&dtail; bod one.</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Adulator hominem supra se <NOTE ID="P25.N2">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, supra se.</NOTE>
frequenter per mendacium extollit.  Infra de Augurrio.
ii<HI REND="sup">jo</HI>.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XXXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Adulterium.  Adultera vxor non est
tenenda.</FOREIGN></HEAD> 

<P> We rede how &thorn;at one &thorn;at hight Genulphus <!-- P25.N3 --> in Frawnce, boght a we&llbar;, &amp; he was a wed
ma&ntail; &amp; he was a holie man <NOTE ID="P25.N4">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, &amp; a wed man.</NOTE> ; &amp;
whe&ntail; he come home in-to Burgundie &thorn;er he dwelte, he
fan&dtail; same we&llbar; spronge&ntail; in his garthe&ntail;.  So
o&ntail; a day, &thorn;is Genulphus <NOTE ID="P25.N3">Lat. MSS., Gangulphus, Gengolphus.</NOTE> &amp; his
wife walki&dtail; samen in &thorn;er garthy&ntail; &amp; sett
&thorn;aim dow&ntail; be &thorn;e we&llbar;; &amp; he reprovi&dtail;
hur for avowtrie, &amp; sai&dtail; it was telli&dtail; hy&mtail; at a
noder ma&ntail; held hur beside hy&mtail;; &amp; sho denye&dtail; it
&amp; sai&dtail; nay.  Tha&ntail; he sai&dtail; vnto hur; "Bare
&thorn;ine ar&mtail; &amp; take vp a little stone in &thorn;e
botho&mtail; of &thorn;is we&llbar;, &amp; if &thorn;ine ar&mtail;
co&mtail; vp vnhurte I sa&llbar; trow at &thorn;ou ert innocent of
&thorn;is at is put o&ntail; <NOTE ID="P25.N5">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, on.</NOTE> the."  And sho
trowed at sho had bene sekur enog&hbar;, &amp; showi&dtail; in hur
ar&mtail; in-to &thorn;e we&llbar;.  And whe&ntail; sho drew it oute,
it was as it had bene scaldi&dtail; with &thorn;e fyre.  And

<PB N="26">

&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is holie ma&ntail; sai&dtail; vnto hur; "Lo!
now aperis &thorn;e treut&hbar; of &thorn;i falssett, and
&thorn;erfo&rtail; fro hens furt&hbar; &thorn;ou sa&llbar; neuer be my
felow."  &amp; he devidi&dtail; his gude in two &amp; gaff hur
&thorn;e to halfe, &amp; lete hur dwe&llbar; be hur one.  And with-in
a liti&llbar; whi&llbar; a clerk &thorn;at hel&dtail; &thorn;is
Genulphus <NOTE ID="P26.N1">Lat. MSS., a clerico adultero occisus est.</NOTE> come to hy&mtail; o&ntail; a nyght
whe&ntail; he lay slepand in his bed, &amp; slew hy&mtail;.  And
whe&ntail; he was beri&dtail; he did meracles.  And whe&ntail; his
wife har&dtail; te&llbar; at he did meracles, scho skornyd hy&mtail;
&amp; sai&dtail; o&ntail; &thorn;is maner of wise; "It is als trew at
Genulphus duse meracles, as it is at myne ars syngis."  And onone hur
ars made ane vglie noyse, and wolde not lefe for noght sho cut&hbar;
do.  And evur after, opo&ntail; &thorn;e fryday at hur husband suffred
martyrdo&mtail; o&ntail;, wekelie whe&ntail; sho spakk any wur&dtail;,
hur ars bega&ntail; to syng &amp; make ane vglie noyse, &amp;
wol&dtail; neuer lefe it o&ntail; &thorn;e fryday whils at sho
liffi&dtail;.  et c&curl;.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XXXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Adulterium punit deus in hac
vita.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Petrus Damanus <NOTE ID="P26.N2"><HI REND="i">For</HI> Damianus.</NOTE> .  O&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail;
he was at &thorn;e cetie of Pariss&hbar; <NOTE ID="P26.N3">Latin MSS. apud permensem vrbem.</NOTE> ,
opo&ntail; &thorn;e day befo&rtail; &thorn;e ffest of Gervasij &amp;
Prothasij, a ma&ntail; of &thorn;e cetie rase tymelie in &thorn;e
mornyng &amp; drafe his oxe&ntail; vnto a fer pastur; &amp; &thorn;is
ma&ntail; had &thorn;e axis i&llbar;.  And one of his neghburs
purseyvi&dtail; &thorn;at he was gone vnto &thorn;e fel&dtail;, &amp;
he feny&dtail; hy&mtail; as he had shaky&ntail; in &thorn;e axis,
&amp; come in-to &thorn;is mans howse shakan&dtail;, &amp; went into
&thorn;e bed to &thorn;e wife.  And &thorn;e wyfe trowed &thorn;at it
had bene hur husband &thorn;at had comme&ntail; fro &thorn;e felde
shakan&dtail; in &thorn;e axis, &amp; sho hawsi&dtail; hy&mtail;, and
onone he defowli&dtail; &amp; went his wais.  And with-in a while
after, hur husbon&dtail; come home passand seke, &amp; bad hur make
hy&mtail; a cuche &thorn;at he myght lig o&ntail;.  And &thorn;e wife
reprevi&dtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; sayd sho mott thole hy&mtail; "go vnto
&thorn;e kurk of &thorn;ase holie martyrs with othe[r] christen
me&ntail;, &amp; here dyvyne serves."  And hur husban&dtail; was
gretlie astonyd with hur language, &amp; askid hur what sho mente; and
sho telli&dtail; hy&mtail; a&llbar; &thorn;e matyr.  And onone as sho
had tol&dtail; hy&mtail;, he consayvi&dtail; &thorn;at bothe he &amp;
sho was desayvi&dtail;; and whe&ntail; &thorn;ai come vnto &thorn;er
selfe, &thorn;ai besoght God to venge &thorn;er harmys, and at it
myght be opynlie knowe&ntail;

<PB N="27">

who did &thorn;is avowtrie.  And onone &thorn;er neghbur &thorn;at did
&thorn;is avowtre was vexi&dtail; with a fen&dtail;, &amp; skratt
&amp; bete hy&mtail; selfe, &amp; went in-to &thorn;e kur&ktee;,
&amp; &thorn;er he was so ma&dtail; &thorn;at now he wol&dtail; clymbe
vp als hye as he myght, &amp; sodanlie fa&llbar; dow&ntail;
agay&ntail; vnto &thorn;e erthe; &amp; now he wol&dtail; ry&ntail;
agay&ntail; &thorn;e wa&llbar; with his hede, &amp; now he wolde
sodanly fa&llbar; dow&ntail; vnto &thorn;e ert&hbar;. &amp; &thorn;us
he di&dtail; ewhils he swelte afor&ntail; a&llbar; &thorn;e
pepu&llbar;.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XXXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Adulterium eciam aues abhorrent.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was in a knyghtis
gart&hbar; a [storkis] <NOTE ID="P27.N1">MS. has here a gap; the scribe could not read the Latin, "nidus erat ciconiarum maris," so left the space empty.</NOTE> neste; an&dtail;
&thorn;er was bathe &thorn;e male and &thorn;e fema&llbar;.  And
o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; &thorn;e male was away, sho lede a noder
fewle do avowtrie with hur; and euer whe&ntail; he had done, sho wolde
go vnto a dike at was beside &thorn;e place, &amp; &thorn;er sho
wol&dtail; wass&hbar; hur.  And &thorn;is knyght had grete
merve&llbar; here-of, &amp; garte make a hedgyng ou&rtail; &thorn;is
dyke, at sho mot nott wy&ntail; &thorn;erto.  So o&ntail; a tyme
whe&ntail; sho had truspasi&dtail;, sho come &amp; soght &thorn;e
watir to wass&hbar; hur in, &amp; sho myght noght wy&ntail;
&thorn;erto.  And in &thorn;e mene wile come hur male, and onone he
purseyvi&dtail; &thorn;at sho had fawti&dtail;, and with his by&llbar;
he strake a grete strake at sho lay sti&llbar; with.  And becauce he
was nott of myght and power to sla hur be his one, &thorn;erfo&rtail;
he gader&dtail; samen a grete company of [storks], &amp; with-in ane
how&rtail; &thorn;ai come o&ntail; hur with a grete wudnes, &amp; in
sight of &thorn;e knyght and a&llbar; me&ntail; in &thorn;e cowrte,
&thorn;ai flow opo&ntail; hur &amp; slew hur as a wric&hbar;e.  Loo!
surs, how burdis hatis avowtre; &thorn;erfo&rtail; me thynk &thorn;at
me&ntail; &amp; womme&ntail; sulde hate it meku&llbar;
more.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XXXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Aduocatus.  Aduocatorum cautele aliquando sunt
periculose.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a yong [man] &thorn;at
feste hy&mtail; at &thorn;e scule with Pictagoras, for to be a sophister
&amp; ler&ntail; eloquens, &amp; for to know &thorn;e crafte of
disputyng in a&llbar; maner of cawsis, and he agrei&dtail; with
hy&mtail; to giff hy&mtail; a grete dele of money.  So o&ntail;



<PB N="28">

a day he come in-to &thorn;e cowrte, &amp; pley&dtail; with &thorn;e
me&ntail; of courte &amp; &thorn;e iudgies, &amp; ouer-come
&thorn;aim.  And so &thorn;urg&hbar; techyng of &thorn;is Pictagoras
he habundi&dtail; euer mo&rtail; &amp; mo&rtail; in eloquens &amp; in
sutis in &thorn;e law, to so meku&llbar;, he was more desyri&dtail; to
pley in &thorn;e law &thorn;a&ntail; was his maister Pictagoras.  So
o&ntail; a day as &thorn;ai wer bothe in &thorn;e courte befo&rtail;
&thorn;e iudgies, &thorn;is Pictagoras said vnto hy&mtail;; " <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Redde mihi quod peto</FOREIGN>; Gyff me at I ask the;
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Siue pro te, Siue contra te</FOREIGN>; Owder for
&thorn;e or agayn; and here-in I wu&llbar; dispute.  And yf I dispute
for the, I wu&llbar; say &thorn;ou aw me my hyre be counan[d].  And if
I dispute agayns &thorn;e, my hyre is awyng me be &thorn;e law; &amp;
so &thorn;ou ert ouercomme&ntail;, &amp; I ouerco&mtail; the."  And
&thorn;a&ntail; he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;,
"Maister, &thorn;ou sa&llbar; vnderston&dtail; &thorn;at [&thorn;ou]
sal be ouercomme&ntail; bothe ways; for if &thorn;e law procede for
me, be &thorn;e sentance of &thorn;e law I sa&llbar; aw &thorn;e no
thyng, for I ouerco&mtail; &thorn;e.  And if &thorn;e procede be
agayns me, I sa&llbar; aw nothyng be counan&dtail;, for I a&mtail; not
ouercomme&ntail;."  And &thorn;e iudgis fe&llbar; in han&dtail; with
&thorn;is matir, and in a lang day &thorn;ai cut&hbar; not make ane
end &thorn;eroff.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XXXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Aduocati eciam silencium vendunt.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Helenandus.  Demostenes <NOTE ID="P28.N1">MS. Helenandus de Mostene.</NOTE> o&ntail; a tyme
askid Aristodemus <NOTE ID="P28.N2">MS. Aristodimus.</NOTE> , &thorn;at was a maker of
talis, what he tuke euer in &thorn;e cowrte whe&ntail; he spakk.  And
he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail;, &amp; sai&dtail; he tuke a besand of
golde.  And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;, "I take
more to hol&dtail; my tong agayns &thorn;aim &thorn;at pleyis in
&thorn;e law.  For my tong is boun, &amp; may not speke bod if it be
lowsi&dtail; with bandis of syluer."</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Aduocatorum cautele aliquando sunt necessarie.
Infra vbi agitur de cautela.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XL.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Aduocati quia in vita vendunt linguas suas, ipsis
in morte priuantur <NOTE ID="P28.N3">Heading supplied from Lat. MSS.</NOTE>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Aduocatis, becauce in &thorn;er lifis &thorn;ai se&llbar;
&thorn;er tonges, whe&ntail; &thorn;ai er dea&dtail; &thorn;er tongis
er taky&ntail; fro &thorn;aim; as we rede of one &thorn;at hight
<PB N="29">

Cesarius, &thorn;at was ane aduocatt in Saxonia.  So o&ntail; a tyme
Sekenes come o&ntail; hy&mtail; &amp; dy sul&dtail; he.  And
agay&ntail; he sul&dtail; dy, he bega&ntail; at yiske; &amp;
evy&ntail; sodanlie his tong was taky&ntail; away, so &thorn;at no
ma&ntail; cuthe fynde in his mouthe &thorn;at he had no tong
whe&ntail; he was dea&dtail;.  And rightwuslie he loste his ton[g]
whe&ntail; he was dead, becauce he solde it whe&ntail; he was o&ntail;
lyfe.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XLI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Aduocatus sicut consueuit viuens, ita moriens vult
[&thorn;er] iudicia procedere contra deum.</FOREIGN></HEAD> 

<P>Jacobus de Vetriaco tellis how Som tyme &thorn;er was a reprovable
aduocatt; &amp; o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; he was seke &amp; lay in
his bed, bow&ntail; to dey, &thorn;e preste broght hy&mtail; &thorn;e
holie Sa[cra]ment, &amp; desyrid hy&mtail; to resayve itt.  And he
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; as he was wu[nt to] do in cawsis of
&thorn;e law, &amp; say&dtail;; "I wi&llbar; nott resayve &thorn;e
sacrament bod if it be de[m]yd at I resayfe itt, and whethir I
sa&llbar; take it or noght."  And a&llbar; at stude about sai&dtail;
it was right at he tuke itt, &amp; &thorn;ai sai&dtail; &thorn;ai gaff
dome &thorn;erin.  And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;:
"ye hafe no power for to deme me, for ye [&thorn;at] er no better
&thorn;a&ntail; myselfe, is bod evynlyngis with me."  And
&thorn;erfo&rtail; he sai&dtail; he wol&dtail; appele fro &thorn;er
wykky&dtail; sentan[s].  And emang &thorn;is vnthrifti language he
gaff vp his gaste.  et c&curl;.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XLII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Aduocatus petens inducias mortis non optinet, qui
eciam in causis inducias non concessit.</FOREIGN></HEAD> 

<P> Jacobus de Vetriaco tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was ane
Aduocatt, whe&ntail; he lay seke &amp; was in passyng, he saw many
fendis.  And he was passand ferde, &amp; aski&dtail; a respett of
almi&yogh;tti Go&dtail;, &thorn;at he mot liff a litle while langer.
And becawse he wolde neuer giff a respett in no cawsis in &thorn;e
law, bod if it war to prolonge &thorn;e cauce &amp; hurte his
aduersarie, &thorn;erfor he myght not opteyne of almighti God
&thorn;at at he aski&dtail;, bod dyed furt&hbar;-with in myserie &amp;
in wrichidnes.

<PB N="30">
</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XLIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Aduocati puniuntur in inferno.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how &thorn;er was a holie ma&ntail; &thorn;at o&ntail; a
night was ravisshid in a visio&ntail;, &amp; hy&mtail; thoght he saw
he&llbar;; &amp; &thorn;er he saw Nero boyland hy&mtail; in hate
byrnand golde.  And onone he se aduocattis command vnto hy&mtail;, and
he said vnto &thorn;aim: "O!  ye aduocattis, my frendis, &thorn;at
whils ye liffid sellid mens trew cawsis, co&mtail; hedur vnto me!  for
&thorn;is place is kepi&dtail; to you &amp; me."  et c&curl;.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XLIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Affectus carnalis non debet esse in
religiosis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how at &thorn;er was a ma&ntail; of religio&ntail;
&thorn;at was a holie ma&ntail;, and a sustir of his, &thorn;at he
luffid passandlie wele, happen&dtail; to fa&llbar; seke.  And he wolde
not als meku&llbar; as co&mtail; furt&hbar; of his abbay to vysitt hur
&amp; se hur.  Tha&ntail; sho, becauce sho wolde giff hy&mtail; none
occasio&ntail; to sy&ntail;, sho sent a ma&ntail; vnto hur bruther,
&amp; bad hy&mtail; pray &thorn;at he wol&dtail; go in-to his
se&llbar; &amp; pray for hur, &thorn;at, with &thorn;e grace of God,
sho mott se hy&mtail; in hevy&ntail;.  And sho did so
afterwar&dtail;.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XLV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Affectus carnalis debet reprimi.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede, ex 'Dictis Patrum,' how abbott Joh&ntail; had a suster,
whilk &thorn;at fro hur yowthed forwar&dtail; conuersi&dtail;
a&llbar;-way in a gude purpos, to so meku&llbar; scho taght hur
bruther, &amp; made hy&mtail; for to lefe &thorn;e vanyties of
&thorn;is werl&dtail;, &amp; go vnto ane abbay &amp; make hy&mtail;
mon&ktee;.  And &thorn;er he abade xxiiij yere, &amp; neuer come
oute.  So o&ntail; a tyme his suster desyri&dtail; gretelie to speke
with hy&mtail;, and sent oft sithes vnto hy&mtail; lettres, and
desiri&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;at he wol&dtail; co&mtail; vnto hur as
in way of charitie, at sho mot se hy&mtail;, &amp; at &thorn;ai myght
be glad to-gedur of &thorn;er yowthid and or &thorn;ai deyid.  And he
excusi&dtail; hy&mtail; euer, &amp; wrote vnto hur agay&ntail; &amp;
said he wolde nott.  &thorn;a&ntail; sho wrote agay&ntail; vnto
hy&mtail;, &amp; sai&dtail; se&ntail; he wolde not co&mtail; unto hur,
itt was nedefu&llbar; att sho sulde co&mtail; vnto hy&mtail;.  And
&thorn;is abbot &thorn;a&ntail; tuke ij of his brethir with hy&mtail;;
&amp; whe&ntail; he come vnto his suster

<PB N="31">

yate, he crie&dtail; &amp; said, "Co&mtail; furthe &amp; se
pylgrames!"  And sho come furt&hbar; &amp; knew hy&mtail;, &amp; so
did he hur; &amp; yitt nowder of &thorn;aim spak ma wurdis to
o&thorn;er, &thorn;at now&thorn;er of &thorn;aim sulde ke&ntail;
o&thorn;er be voyce.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai had dronke&ntail; watir
togeder, &thorn;is abbott &amp; his monkis went home agay&ntail; vnto
&thorn;er abbay.  And with-in a litle while after, his suster wrote
vnto hy&mtail; agay&ntail;, &amp; desiri&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail;
to co&mtail; vnto hur; and he ansswerd agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;,
"I come vnto &thorn;e and &thorn;ou gaff me watir, &amp; I tuke it of
&thorn;i hand &amp; dranke itt; and &thorn;erfo&rtail; it suffisis
vnto the at &thorn;ou saw me.  And &thorn;erfo&rtail; pray for me,
&amp; I sa&llbar; pray for the; for I wu&llbar; co&mtail; no ner the."
et c&curl;.</P>
<P>
<LIST>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Affectus viri naturaliter inclinatur ad mulierem.  Infra de
Concupiscencia.</FOREIGN></ITEM> <ITEM><FOREIGN>Affectum eternalem <NOTE ID="P31.N1">Latin MSS. <HI REND="i">have</HI> carnalem.</NOTE> non
debent sequi Religiosi.  Infra de Sanguineis <NOTE ID="P31.N2">Latin MSS. <HI REND="i">have</HI> consanguineis.</NOTE>
.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XLVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ager.  Agrorum [terminos <NOTE ID="P31.N3">From the Latin MSS.</NOTE>]
transponentes et inuasores puniuntur in hac vita.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>Cesarius tellis how &thorn;at in Colay&ntail; &thorn;er was a
husband-ma&ntail; &thorn;at hyght Henrie; and sekenes tuke hy&mtail;,
&amp; he drew vnto his dedewar&dtail;.  And evur hy&mtail; thoght
&thorn;at &thorn;er was enence his mouthe a grete burnand stone
hyngan&dtail;, euer in like to hitt hy&mtail;.  And as hy&mtail;
thoght, &thorn;e hete &thorn;eroff burnyd hy&mtail; hugelie.  And he
crie&dtail; horrible &amp; sai&dtail;; "Behol&dtail; &thorn;is stane
&thorn;at hyngis befo&rtail; my face, how &thorn;at it burnys me!"
And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai garte ca&llbar; a preste, &amp; he was
shrevy&ntail;.  Neuer-&thorn;e-les, it profettid hy&mtail; noght, and
&thorn;e preste said vnto hy&mtail;; "So&ntail;, vmthynk &thorn;e if
&thorn;ou hafe dissayvi&dtail; any ma&ntail; be &thorn;is stane."  And
at &thorn;is wurde he vmthoght hy&mtail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "A!  Sur, I
hafe now gude mynde how I remevi&dtail; &thorn;is stone in &thorn;e
fel&dtail;, to &thorn;e entent &thorn;at I wolde enlarge myne
aw&ntail; grown&dtail; &amp; mynys o&thorn;er mens grown&dtail;."  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e preste tolde hy&mtail; at &thorn;at was
&thorn;e cauce; and he shrafe hy&mtail; &thorn;eroff, &amp;
promyssi&dtail; to make amendis &thorn;erfor.  And &thorn;us hitt
wanysshi&dtail; away, &amp; he was delyverd

<PB N="32">

of &thorn;at horrible visio&ntail;, &amp; liffid after many day, &amp;
made a restitucio&ntail; &amp; become a gude man[n].</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XLVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Agrorum <NOTE ID="P32.N1"><HI REND="i">After</HI> Agrorum, and, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE>.  Adhuc de
agris.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;att in &thorn;at same contret&hbar;
&thorn;er was a husbon&dtail;, &amp; whe&ntail; he sulde dye, &thorn;e
devu&llbar; come afor&ntail; hy&mtail; with a byrnan&dtail; stake, and
thretid hy&mtail; &thorn;at he sulde &thorn;ruste itt in at his
mouthe.  And he wiste neuer whi, bod whatt way as euer he turnyd
hy&mtail;, &thorn;e devu&llbar; was euer at &thorn;e mouthe o&ntail;
hy&mtail; with &thorn;is stake.  So he vmthoght hy&mtail; what it sulde mene;
and at &thorn;e laste, he remembrid hy&mtail; how, o&ntail; a tyme, he
had remou&dtail; a stake of &thorn;e same mesur &amp; lenthe oute of
his aw&ntail; feldis into a knyghtis felde &thorn;at was
nerehan&dtail; hy&mtail;, to enlarge his aw&ntail; gron&dtail; with.
And &thorn;a&ntail; whe&ntail; nede cachi&dtail; hy&mtail;, he garte his
meneya ga take it vp, &amp; sett agay&ntail; whare it stude, &amp;
sent vnto &thorn;e knyght &amp; praye&dtail; hy&mtail; to forgiff
hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;is ansswer&dtail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "I wote not
&thorn;eroff, bod se&ntail; he was fals to me, latt hy&mtail; alone to
he be wele punysshi&dtail;."  And euer &thorn;e devu&llbar; abade
sti&llbar; with [&thorn;e] stake, &amp; wol&dtail; euer hafe putt it
in his mouthe.  Tha&ntail; he sent agay&ntail; vnto &thorn;e knyght,
&amp; prayed hy&mtail; forgiff hy&mtail; for Goddis sake, &amp; he
wol&dtail; nott.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he sen&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; his
wyfe &amp; his childre wepan&dtail;, &thorn;at besoght hy&mtail; for
charitie to forgiff hy&mtail; &thorn;e trispas at he had done vnto
hy&mtail;; "for he liffis with meku&llbar; sorow, and he may not dye
or ye forgiff hy&mtail;."  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e knyght
sai&dtail;; "Now I wi&llbar; forgiff, for now I a&mtail; we&llbar;
vengi&dtail;."  And fro &thorn;at hou&rtail;, a&llbar; &thorn;e
ferdnes of &thorn;e devu&llbar; sesi&dtail; away fro hy&mtail;.  et
c&curl;.</P>
<P>
<LIST>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Allexij confessoris.  Infra de Paciencia.  iiiii.</FOREIGN></ITEM> <ITEM><FOREIGN>Alexandri
magni <NOTE ID="P32.N2">MS. magno.</NOTE> .  Infra de superbia. v. et de
morte. ix<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. et xv<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.  Et de Vindicta.
ij<HI REND="sup">o</HI></FOREIGN>.</ITEM></LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XLVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Agnetis Virginis et martiris.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in hur meracles how &thorn;at &thorn;er was a preste
&thorn;at servi&dtail; in a kur&ktee; of Saynt Agn[es], whilk
&thorn;at o&ntail; a tyme was hugelie vexid
<PB N="33">

with temptacio&ntail; of his fless&hbar;; bod becauce &thorn;at he
wol&dtail; nott offen&dtail; allmyghti Go&dtail;, he besoght &thorn;e
pope &thorn;at he wol&dtail; giff hy&mtail; lefe to be weddi&dtail;.
And &thorn;e pope, considuryng his gudenes &amp; his symplenes, gaff
hy&mtail; a ryng, &amp; bad hy&mtail; go home vnto a fay&rtail; ymage
of Saynt Agnes, &thorn;at was payntti&dtail; in his kurk, &amp;
o&ntail; his behalfe charge hur &thorn;at sho sulde suffre hy&mtail;
wed hur.  And &thorn;e preste come home &amp; chargi&dtail; &thorn;e
ymage as &thorn;e pope bad [hym].  And onone sho putt furt&hbar; hur
ryng-fynger &amp; profir&dtail; it to hy&mtail;, &amp; he putt
o&ntail; &thorn;e ryng.  And [sho] drew in hur fynger agay&ntail;, And
onone a&llbar; maner of temptacion <NOTE ID="P33.N1">MS. temptacid.</NOTE> passi&dtail;
away fro &thorn;is preste.  And in Rome in hur <NOTE ID="P33.N2"><HI REND="i">After</HI> hur, hu, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE>
kurk, at &thorn;is day, &thorn;e same ryng shewis yitt o&ntail; hur
fynger, &amp; is closi&dtail; into &thorn;e burde agay&ntail;.  et
c&curl;.

</P>
<P> 
<LIST>
<ITEM><FOREIGN> Amandi confessoris.  Infra de infante, i.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Ambicio.  Ambicioso totus mundus non sufficit.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>
</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XLIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ambiciosi reprimendi sunt a
sapientibus.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how &thorn;at o&ntail; a tyme, ane of &thorn;e prophettis
sayd vnto Alexander; "And so wer &thorn;at our goddis wolde &thorn;at
&thorn;e statur of &thorn;i bodie war like vnto &thorn;i covatusnes,
All &thorn;is werl&dtail; mott nott resayfe &thorn;e; for &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;ou might putt &thorn;ine one han&dtail; in-to &thorn;e far side
of &thorn;e este, &amp; &thorn;e toder vnto &thorn;e fer side of
&thorn;e weste.  Knowis &thorn;ou nott att grete treis, &thorn;ai er
lang in growyng?  &amp; yitt &thorn;ai may be cutt dow&ntail; in ane
how&rtail;.  And he is a fule &thorn;at pullis not dow&ntail; frute
whe&ntail; &thorn;ai er moste ripe.  Therfo&rtail; vuise the,
&thorn;atte&ntail; whe&ntail; &thorn;ou erte att hyeste of &thorn;i
brawnchis, at &thorn;ai be nott cutt in sonder &amp; &thorn;ou
fa&llbar; dow&ntail;, ffor, as &thorn;ou may see, a lio&ntail; is
so&mtail; tyme meate to smale burdis.  And &thorn;er is nothyng so
staby&llbar; <NOTE ID="P33.N3">Latin MS. cui periculum non sit ab inualido denique.</NOTE> , bod vmwhile &thorn;er is
parce&llbar; &thorn;erin.  And if &thorn;ou be a go&dtail;, &thorn;ou
aght to giff benefice vnto morta&llbar; fol&ktee;, &amp; nothyng take
fro &thorn;aim.  And if &thorn;ou be a ma&ntail;, vmthynk &thorn;e
alway what &thorn;ou erte, for it is grete folie vnto the to thynk so
lang of o&thorn;er folk at &thorn;ou forgett &thorn;i selfe."  et
c&curl;.

<PB N="34">
</P>
<P><LIST>

<ITEM><FOREIGN>Ambicio quandoque inducit hominem ad perpetrandum homicidium.
Infra vbi agitur de Archidiacono.</FOREIGN></ITEM>

<ITEM><FOREIGN>Ambiciosi frequenter cum confusione frustrantur.  Infra vbi agitur
de Simonia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>

</LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> L.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ambicio inducit hominem ad faciendum conuenciones
cum diabolo.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in &thorn;e 'Cronicles of Saynt Siluester' of a pope
&thorn;at hyght Secundus <NOTE ID="P34.N1">For Sylvester II.</NOTE> , how furste he was a
monke, and &thorn;a&ntail; afterwer&dtail; he made homage vnto
&thorn;e devu&llbar;, promysyng hy&mtail; to do what &thorn;ing so he
commanddid hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;e devu&llbar; hight hy&mtail; at he
sulde hafe evur what &thorn;ing so he desyrid; and he spak oft sithis
with &thorn;e devu&llbar;.  And evur he encresi&dtail; so in sciens
&amp; in connyng, at Ottonus, at was Emperour, and Robert, &thorn;at
was kyng of Frawnce, wer his scolers.  So be procuryng be &thorn;e
devu&llbar;, he was made archbisshopp&curl; of Bononience <NOTE ID="P34.N2">For Bononia, = Bologna. MS. Arund. Factus est Archiepiscopus Remensis.</NOTE> .  Syne he was made a cardina&llbar;, and at &thorn;e
laste he was made pope.  So o&ntail; a tyme as he was spekand with
&thorn;e devu&llbar;, he aski&dtail; hy&mtail; how long he sulde liff,
and he ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;, vnto he
sang mes in Jerusalem; and with &thorn;is wurde he was passand
gla&dtail;, &amp; &thorn;oght it sulde be long or he sang any mes
&thorn;er, or yit go thedur in pylgramage.  So it happen&dtail;
afterwar&dtail; in &thorn;e lentre&ntail;, &thorn;at he sai&dtail; mes
in Rome in a kurk &thorn;at hight Jerusalem; and whe&ntail; he was at
mes he har&dtail; a grete noyse of devuls, and he fe&llbar; so seke
&thorn;at he feli&dtail; hy&mtail; selfe &thorn;at hy&mtail; burd dye;
and &thorn;a&ntail;, &thorn;uf a&llbar; he war nevur so wykki&dtail;
in <NOTE ID="P34.N3"><HI REND="i">After</HI> in, liffi&dtail;, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> liffyng, ye[t] he had compunccio&ntail;,
&amp; made meku&llbar; sorow for his sy&ntail;.  And he besoght God of
mercye, &amp; wol&dtail; not dy in dispayr.  And &thorn;er he made ane
oppy&ntail; confessio&ntail; of a&llbar; his sy&ntail; befo&rtail;
&thorn;e peple, and he commandi&dtail; &thorn;at all &thorn;ase
membris &thorn;at he had servi&dtail; &thorn;e devu&llbar; with suld
be cutt off, &amp; at &thorn;e carcas of his bodie sulde be







<PB N="35">

put in a carte, &amp; whethir-so&mtail;-evur at &thorn;e cate&llbar;
led it, at &thorn;er it sulde be beri&dtail;; and so &thorn;e
pepu&llbar; di&dtail;.  And &thorn;ai led it in-to &thorn;e kurk of
[Sai]nt Joh&ntail; Lateranencis; &amp; &thorn;er it was beri&dtail;.
And in toky&ntail; &thorn;at almyghti God had mercie of hy&mtail;, hys
grafe spryngis als wele smale crusy&llbar; bonys as oyle yit vnto
&thorn;is day <NOTE ID="P35.N1">MS. Arund. Et in signum misericordie, sepulcrum ipsius, tam ex tumultu ossium quam ex sudore, presagium est Pape morituri, sicut in eodem sepulcro litteris est exaratum.</NOTE> .  et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ambicio inducit hominem ad negandum deum et
scripto suo firmare.  Infra de Theophilo, vbi agitur de Maria, dei
genitrice.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
</LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> LI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ambrosij Confessoris.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Historia Tripartita' how o&ntail; a tyme, at &thorn;e
cetie of Cessalonye, &thorn;er fe&llbar; a stryfe betwix &thorn;e
iudgies &amp; &thorn;e comons, to so meku&llbar; att &thorn;e
como&ntail; peple stanyd &thorn;e comons to dede.  And whe&ntail;
Theodosius, &thorn;at was Emperour, hard tell <NOTE ID="P35.N2">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, tell.</NOTE>
hereof, he garte ky&llbar; &thorn;aim &thorn;at did no truspas, with
&thorn;aim at did &thorn;e trispas.  So o&ntail; a tyme afterward,
whe&ntail; &thorn;is Emperour wolde hafe comme&ntail; in-to &thorn;e
kur&ktee;, &thorn;is holie ma&ntail;, Ambros, mete hy&mtail; att
&thorn;e dure &amp; forbad hy&mtail; &thorn;at he suld co&mtail; in,
sayand o&ntail; &thorn;is maner of wise; "O, &thorn;ou Emperour!  whi
knawis &thorn;ou nott &thorn;i presumpcio&ntail; after so grete a
hastenes?  O, &thorn;ou Emperour! att erte a prynce, &amp; hase
imperia&llbar; power, It semys &thorn;e at reso&ntail; sulde
ouer-co&mtail; &thorn;i power, &amp; nott &thorn;i power reso&ntail;:
how dar &thorn;ou &thorn;at with &thorn;ine ee&ntail; hase
beholde&ntail; &thorn;i servan&dtail; dye, trede with &thorn;i fete
opo&ntail; &thorn;is holie paymente?  And how dar &thorn;ou holde vp
&thorn;i handis vnto God, &thorn;at yitt droppis with blude &thorn;at
is innocent?  And how dar &thorn;ou resayfe &thorn;e holie sacrament
in bread or wyne, whe&ntail;, &thorn;urg&hbar; &thorn;e hastines of &thorn;i
wurde, innocent blude is wronguslie spylte?  And &thorn;erfo&rtail;, Go
&thorn;i ways, &thorn;ou &thorn;at ert boun with sy&ntail;, and amende
&thorn;i fawte, &amp; do away &thorn;e band att &thorn;ou ert bun
with, and &thorn;ou may hafe a medcy&ntail; to amen&dtail; &thorn;e
with, &amp; &thorn;ou wi&llbar;."  And with &thorn;ies wurdis
&thorn;is Emperour obeyi&dtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; made sorow and went
home agay&ntail; to his place; &amp; &thorn;er

<PB N="36">

he wepud, &amp; made meku&llbar; sorow, &amp; sayd vnto hy&mtail;
selfe o&ntail; &thorn;is maner of wyse; "The kurk is oppy&ntail; to
&thorn;aim &thorn;at er my servandis, &amp; it is sparrid vnto me
&thorn;at a&mtail; ane Emperour."  And &thorn;a&ntail; ane &thorn;at
was maister of a&llbar; his knyghtis, &thorn;at hight Ruffinus, come
vnto Saynt Ambroce and besoght hy&mtail; to assoyle &thorn;e Emperour.
And whe&ntail; Saynt Ambros saw hy&mtail;, he sayde; "O, &thorn;ou
Ruffinus!  at was doar &amp; cowncelur of suc&hbar; a dede,
&thorn;inkis now no shame to speke agayns &thorn;e magestie of
almighti God?  I lat &thorn;e witt, &amp; &thorn;e Emperour co&mtail;
here, I sa&llbar; forbid hy&mtail; to entyr into &thorn;is holie place
vnto he take his penans for his tyrandrie, and &thorn;at done I
wi&llbar; resayve hy&mtail; gladlie."  And &thorn;is Ruffinus went
&amp; tolde &thorn;is vnto &thorn;e Emperour.  And &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;is Emperour sai&dtail;; "I wi&llbar; go vnto hy&mtail; at I may
take rightwus penans for myne vnrigh[t]wusnes dedis."  So o&ntail; a
tyme he wente agay&ntail; vnto &thorn;e kur&ktee;, and Saynt Amb[ros]
come agay&ntail; &amp; forbad hy&mtail;, &amp; sai&dtail;; "whatt
penans hase &thorn;ou done for a&llbar; &thorn;i wykkednes?"  &amp;
&thorn;e Emperour ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sayde; "It longes
vnto &thorn;e to giff me penans, &amp; it is my parte to obey the,
&amp; do at &thorn;ou commandis me."  And &thorn;a&ntail; he shrafe
hy&mtail; vnto &thorn;is [Am]brosius, &amp; enionyd hy&mtail; penance.
And &thorn;is Emperour tuke it so thankfullie, &thorn;at for his
opy&ntail; sy&ntail; he did oppy&ntail; penans.  et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> LII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ambrosij Confessoris.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Historia Tripartita' how o&ntail; a tyme, whe&ntail;
&thorn;is Theodosius &thorn;e Emperour come in-to &thorn;e wher,
&thorn;is Ambros com&mtail; vnto hy&mtail; &amp; aski&dtail; hy&mtail;
what he behel&dtail; &thorn;er; and he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail;
&amp; said, "I come in to behol&dtail; how criste&ntail; me&ntail;
reseyvis &thorn;er sacrament."  The[n] Saynt Ambros say&dtail; vnto
hy&mtail;, "O &thorn;ou Emperour! &thorn;ies inward placis er
ordan&dtail; for prestis; And &thorn;erfo&rtail; go furt&hbar;, and
&thorn;er abyde with other vnto &thorn;ou be howsel&dtail;."  And
onone &thorn;e Emperour did as he bad hy&mtail;."  So o&ntail; a tyme
efterwar&dtail; &thorn;is Emperour went vnto Costantynople, &amp;
stude &thorn;er in &thorn;e kur&ktee; with-owte&ntail; &thorn;e
where.  And &thorn;e bisshop&ptail; &thorn;er went vnto hy&mtail; &amp;
commaundi&dtail; hy&mtail; to go into &thorn;e quere.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e Emperour sayde; "vnnethis yit I may knaw
whatt differens is betwix

<PB N="37">

ane Emperour &amp; a preste, ffor yitt vnnethis hafe I fo&ntail;
&thorn;e treut&hbar;.  Notwithstondying I ca&ntail; verelie fynde at
my maister Ambros is wurthi to be made a bisshop&ptail;."  et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> LIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Amicicia.  Amicus verus eciam morti se exponit pro
amico.</FOREIGN></HEAD> 

<P> We rede how &thorn;at Pictagoras had ij disciples, &amp; &thorn;ai
was passand gude frendis, &amp; ather luffi&dtail; wele other.  And
&thorn;at one hight Damo&ntail; &amp; &thorn;e toder Phicias.  So
o&ntail; a tyme Dionisius, &thorn;at was a tirand, wolde hafe
slay&ntail; &thorn;e tone of &thorn;aim, &amp; he &thorn;at sulde be
deade askid lefe &thorn;at he myght go home &amp; ordan&dtail; for his
wife &amp; his howshol&dtail;, &amp; he sulde co&mtail; agay&ntail;.
And &thorn;e toder become his borg&hbar;, &amp; bade behyn&dtail;
hy&mtail; in his stede.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e day come, &thorn;is
disciple come nott agay&ntail;, &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; euere ma&ntail;
demy&dtail; &thorn;e toder, &thorn;at was his suertie, to dye for
hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;is ma&ntail; at was suertie sayde he
dowti&dtail; nothyng &thorn;e constance of his fren&dtail;, and
present hy&mtail; befo&rtail; &thorn;is tyrand, &amp; bad hy&mtail; do
with hy&mtail; what he wolde &amp; asoyle hys fren&dtail;.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is tyran&dtail; had grete mervayle of his witt,
&amp; for his trew frenshi&ptail; he forgaff &thorn;aim bothe.  et
c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> LIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Amici necessitatibus eciam est
subueniendum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Senec tellis how a philosophur &thorn;at hight Archisilus <NOTE ID="P37.N1">MS. Harl. Archelisas philosophus. MS. Arund. Achesilas.</NOTE> had a fren&dtail; &thorn;at was bothe seke &amp;
pure.  And for shame he wol&dtail; latt no ma&ntail; witt at he was
so.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;is philisophur vnderstude &thorn;is, he
calli&dtail; &thorn;is fren&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;, &amp; lete
hy&mtail; witt in privatie betwix &thorn;aim two &thorn;at he wolde
helpe hy&mtail;, &amp; sulde make hy&mtail; hale of his sekenes; &amp;
he tuke a grete sache&llbar; &amp; fyllid it fu&llbar; of money
privalie, &amp; bande it vnto his side agayns his long in stede of a
playstre.  And &thorn;e toder man trowi&dtail; it had bene so.  And
&thorn;is he did to the entent at a <NOTE ID="P37.N2">Latin MSS. vt homo inutiliter verecundus.</NOTE> ma&ntail;
&thorn;at is shamefu&llbar; vnprofitable sulde titter fynde &thorn;at
he desyri&dtail;, &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;at &thorn;ing att he
aski&dtail;.

<PB N="38">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> LV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Amicicia vera multum est laudabilis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how &thorn;at in &thorn;e tyme of Pipinius &thorn;at was
kyng of France, &thorn;er was two childer, and &thorn;ai war passand
like.  And &thorn;e tone was ane Erle so&ntail; &thorn;at hight
Auernus, and &thorn;e toder was a knyght so&ntail; &thorn;at hight
Bericanus, whilk &thorn;at was bor&ntail; vnto Rome for to be baptisid
whe&ntail; &thorn;ai war big childre.  Not-withstondyng afo&rtail;
&thorn;at, in a cetie at was callid Luca &thorn;er &thorn;ai war
broght vp togedur, &thorn;ai wer grete felows, &amp; ather luffid
other passan&dtail; wele; and att Rome &thorn;ai wer bothe to-gedur
baptisid of &thorn;e pope.  And he namyd &thorn;e erle so&ntail;
Amelius, and &thorn;e knyght so&ntail; Amicus.  And he gaff ather of
&thorn;aim a cop&ptail; of wud &thorn;at was passand like.  And
&thorn;ai thanki&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; went &thorn;er wayes.  And
&thorn;er was betwix &thorn;aim so grete felaschu&ptail; &amp; so
grete evynhed of wi&llbar;, at &thorn;ai wolde neuer ete nor slepe bod
to-gedur.  So o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;is Amicus hard te&llbar;
&thorn;at his fadur was dead, &amp; att malicious me&ntail; wol&dtail;
take his heritage fro hy&mtail;.  And als hastelie als he cuthe, he
went vnto <NOTE ID="P38.N1"><HI REND="i">After</HI> vnto, hy&mtail;, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> his o&thorn;er frend at te&llbar; hym,
&amp; he cuthe not fynd hy&mtail;.  So als sone as &thorn;is Amelius
ha[rd] te&llbar; at his fren&dtail; Amicus fadur was dead, and he went
vnto hy&mtail; att comfurt&hbar; hy&mtail;, and he cuthe neuer fynde
hy&mtail;.  So &thorn;is Amicus happend to be lugid at a wurthi mans
place, &amp; happend to tarie &thorn;er, &amp; weddid &thorn;e gude
mans doghter.  And &thorn;is Amelius soght hy&mtail; to ij yere was
passi&dtail;, &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; a pilgre&mtail; tolde hy&mtail;
&thorn;er he was, &amp; how he was expulsi&dtail; oute of his
aw&ntail; contre.  And &thorn;is Amelius doffi&dtail; his cote &amp;
gaff &thorn;is pylgra&mtail;, &amp; ba&dtail; hy&mtail; pray vnto God
"&thorn;at I mot sone fynde hy&mtail;."  And &thorn;e same day att
evy&ntail;, Amicus mett &thorn;is pylgra&mtail; and haskid hy&mtail;
if he saw oght &thorn;is Amelius.  And &thorn;is pylgra&mtail;
ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;, "wharto spirris
&thorn;ou me?  Ert &thorn;ou nott Amelius att askid me if I saw oght
to day <NOTE ID="P38.N2"><HI REND="i">After</HI> day, Amelius, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> Amicus?  fforsuth I ca&ntail; nott wytt,
ffor &thorn;ou hase changid bothe [&thorn;i] hors &amp; &thorn;i
harnes &amp; also &thorn;i felashu&ptail;."  And he ansswer&dtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; say[d]; "Nay, I a&mtail; not Amelius, bod I am
Amicus &thorn;at sesis not for to seke hy&mtail;."  And &thorn;e
pylgra&mtail;

<PB N="39">

tolde hy&mtail; &thorn;at he sulde fynde hy&mtail; at Pariss&hbar;.
And he went vnto Pariss&hbar; &amp; fande hy&mtail; &thorn;er.  And
&thorn;ai kissi&dtail;, and wer athir fay&ntail; of other.  And
&thorn;ai went in-to cowrte to king Charlis, and onone &thorn;is
Amicus was made &thorn;e kyngis tresurer, and Amelius was made karvur.
And &thorn;ai war fayr yong me&ntail; &amp; wise and discrete, and
&thorn;ai war wurshuppid &amp; had in grete dayntie with evur
ema&ntail;.  So o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;is Amicus went &amp; vissytt
his wiffe, and tarid with hur, &amp; Amelius bade sti&llbar; in
&thorn;e courte.  So it happend hy&mtail; priualie to lie by &thorn;e
kyngis doghter, And whe&ntail; he had done he tolde it in privatie
vnto ane erle &thorn;at hight Ardericus, &thorn;att was swor&ntail; to
hy&mtail; to be hy&mtail; trew fren&dtail; many day befo&rtail;.  And
he went &amp; accusi&dtail; hy&mtail; vnto &thorn;e kyng.  And he
sai&dtail; nay to it, &amp; oblissi&dtail; hy&mtail; to feght with
hy&mtail; in &thorn;e quare&llbar;.  And &thorn;e day was
appoyntti&dtail; &thorn;aim be &thorn;e kyng at &thorn;ai sul&dtail;
feght vppo&ntail;.  And in &thorn;e mene while Amicus come home, &amp;
Amelius tel&dtail; hy&mtail; a&llbar;; and he blamyd hy&mtail; greteli
&thorn;erfo&rtail;.  And o&ntail; &thorn;e day att &thorn;ai sulde
feght, &thorn;is Amicus did o&ntail; Amelius armur &amp; went into
&thorn;e place for to feght for hy&mtail;, and our-come &thorn;is
Ardericus &amp; smate of his hea&dtail;; and &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e
kyng gaff hy&mtail; his doghter.  And &thorn;is done, &thorn;is
Amelius went vnto Amicus howse, and &thorn;e wife trowid &thorn;at it
had bene Amicus, and whe&ntail; she wol&dtail; owder kis hy&mtail; or
hals hy&mtail;, he putt hur away fro&mtail; hy&mtail;.  And herefor
sho was passan&dtail; hevie, and tolde hur neghburs &thorn;e cauce of
hur hevynes, &amp; how he wol&dtail; euer-ilk nyght, whe&ntail;
&thorn;ai lay to-gedur, lay a nakid swer&dtail; betwix &thorn;aim and
sai&dtail;, &amp; sho lay nere hy&mtail;, he sulde ki&llbar; hur.  And
&thorn;is done, &thorn;is Amicus &amp; Amelius changi&dtail; &thorn;er
clothyng agay&ntail;, and Amicus went home vnto his aw&ntail; howse,
and sent Amelius agay&ntail;; &amp; he wed &thorn;e kynges doghter.
And belife after &thorn;is, Amicus happend to wax lepre.  And he wex
so pure vnto so meku&llbar; he was so fowle, &thorn;at his wife and his
childre put hy&mtail; fro &thorn;aim.  So o&ntail; a tyme he was so
compulsi&dtail; with honger and with wrich[id]nes, &thorn;at he went
vnto &thorn;is Erle Amellius <NOTE ID="P39.N1"><HI REND="i">Under</HI> Amellius, Avellius, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> place, and
&thorn;er he layed hy&mtail; dow&ntail; befo&rtail; &thorn;e ya[tt],
&amp; knokkid with his tables as lepre me&ntail; duse.  And &thorn;e
Erle har&dtail;, &amp; sent hy&mtail; brede and fless&hbar; &amp; a
drynk in &thorn;e cop&ptail; &thorn;at &thorn;e pope gaff hy&mtail; at
Rome.  And &thorn;e ma&ntail; at broght itt putt it



<PB N="40">

oute of &thorn;e erle cop&ptail; into &thorn;e lepre mans cop&ptail;;
&amp; hy&mtail; thoght &thorn;at &thorn;ase coppis wer passand like,
and went in &amp; tolde &thorn;e Erle how at &thorn;is lepre ma&ntail;
had a cop&ptail; &thorn;at was passand like his cop&ptail;.  And he
garte feche hy&mtail; in to hy&mtail;; &amp; Amicus tolde hy&mtail;
a&llbar; &thorn;e <NOTE ID="P40.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, &thorn;e.</NOTE> proces how &thorn;at it had
happen&dtail; with hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;is Erle &amp; his wife wepud
&amp; made meky&llbar; sorow for hy&mtail;, &amp; hight hy&mtail;
&thorn;at he sulde hafe gude enog&hbar; whils &thorn;at he
lyffy&dtail;.  So o&ntail; &thorn;e night after, as &thorn;is Amicus
lay in his bed, &thorn;e aunge&llbar; Gabrie&llbar; apperid vnto
hy&mtail;, &amp; bad hy&mtail; by&dtail; Armelius sla his two sonnys
at he had, &amp; sprenkle hy&mtail; with &thorn;e blude of &thorn;aim,
&amp; he sulde be hale of a&llbar; his lepre: and he did so.  And
whe&ntail; he had tolde hy&mtail; he was passand hevye.
Neuer-&thorn;e-les he remembri&dtail; of &thorn;e fait&hbar; &amp;
gude treut&hbar; at he had done vnto hy&mtail;, and he come vnto
&thorn;e bed &thorn;er his childre lay, &amp; with grete wepyng &amp;
mornyng he drew his swer&dtail; &amp; tuke his childre and hedid
&thorn;aim.  And he put &thorn;er bodies &amp; &thorn;er hedis
to-gedur in myddest &thorn;e be&dtail;, &amp; cover&dtail; &thorn;aim
and gader&dtail; &thorn;er blude in a vesse&llbar;, &amp; come to
Amicus &thorn;er he lay &amp; al by-sprenkle&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;erwith,
an&dtail; said in &thorn;is maner of wise; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Diuine Iesu Christe, qui fidem hominibus servare
precepisti, et leprosum verbo sanasti,</FOREIGN> &thorn;is my trew
felow vuchesafe to hele of his lepre, for whose luff I was not
fer&dtail; to she&dtail; my childre blude."  And onone he was
clensi&dtail;, &amp; &thorn;is Amelius cled hy&mtail; in his beste
clothyng.  And a&llbar; &thorn;e bellis in &thorn;e place rang be
&thorn;er one.  And &thorn;is cowntes aski&dtail; whi &thorn;ai rang
&amp; &thorn;er cuthe no bodie te&llbar; hur.  So &thorn;is Erle with
grete murnyng &amp; sarow went into &thorn;e chawmre agay&ntail;,
&thorn;er he had slay&ntail; his childer, &amp; he fande &thorn;aim
ligan&dtail; in &thorn;e be&dtail;, laykan&dtail; samen in als gude
quarte as evur &thorn;ai wer.  And &thorn;er was abowte bathe
&thorn;er nekkis ij cerkles as &thorn;ai had bene ij rede thredis.
And &thorn;a&ntail; he was fay&ntail;, &amp; went vnto his wyfe &amp;
tolde hur a&llbar; &thorn;e proces, how at it had happen&dtail;
hy&mtail;.  And fro thens furt&hbar; bothe he &amp; sho liffid in
chastitie.  And a fen&dtail; vexi&dtail; so Amicus wife, &thorn;at
onone <NOTE ID="P40.N2">MS. ononone.</NOTE> he made ane ende of hur.  And be strenth
of &thorn;is Erle, &thorn;is Amicus went in-to &thorn;e contre
&thorn;er he dwelte, &amp; ouer-co&mtail; it &amp; made it to be
subgett vnto hy&mtail;; &amp; &thorn;er he liffi&dtail; many day in a
holie life, &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; afterwar&dtail; be proces of tyme,
Amelius &amp; Amicus dyed bothe, and wer beri&dtail;





<PB N="41">

in placis far in sondre.  So not-withstondyng, afterwar&dtail; be
grete miracle, &thorn;ai wer bothe fu&ntail; in <NOTE ID="P41.N1">MS. &amp;.</NOTE>
a grafe ligan&dtail; for &thorn;er trew luff.  et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> LVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Amici semper [mutuam] debent seruare
honestatem.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis how &thorn;at &thorn;er was ij frendis, and
&thorn;e tone desyri&dtail; &thorn;e toder to do for hy&mtail; ane
vnrightwus thyng.  And he wol&dtail; not do itt for hy&mtail;.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; he sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "what is &thorn;i
frenshi&ptail; wurth vnto me whe&ntail; &thorn;ou wi&llbar; not do for
me at I pray &thorn;e?"  And he ansswer&dtail; agayn &amp; said, "what
profettis &thorn;i frenshi&ptail; vnto me, whe&ntail; <NOTE ID="P41.N2">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, when.</NOTE> &thorn;u desyris me for to <NOTE ID="P41.N3">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, forto do.</NOTE> do
for &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ing &thorn;at is vnhoneste, and agayn my
treuthe?"  et c&curl;.

</P>
<P> <LIST><ITEM> <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Amicum mala de amico dixisse non est
de facili credendum.  Infra vbi agitur de credere.</FOREIGN></ITEM>


</LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> LVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Amicus Debet probari ante
necessitatem.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how som tyme &thorn;er was ij merchandis in Egipte,
&thorn;e tone of Egipte and &thorn;e toder of Baldac <NOTE ID="P41.N4">MS. Waldac; Harl. MS. Daldac; Arund. MS. Baldac.</NOTE> , &thorn;at &ktee;now wele athir other be &thorn;er
name, &amp; luffi&dtail; passandlie wele to-gedur.  &amp; &thorn;is
Marchan&dtail; of Baldac come into Egipte, &amp; &thorn;e
merchan&dtail; &thorn;er reseyvud hy&mtail; thankfullie, and a grete
while he festid hy&mtail; &amp; all his meneya.  So whe&ntail; a
sennett was passi&dtail;, &thorn;is merchan&dtail; of Baldac happend
to fa&llbar; passand seke, And &thorn;ai went &amp; gatt hy&mtail;
lechis; and a leche feli&dtail; his powce <NOTE ID="P41.N5">MS. pownce.</NOTE> &amp;
luki&dtail; his watir, bod he cuthe fynde no sekenes in hy&mtail;.  So
at &thorn;e laste he oppyn&dtail; his harte privalie vnto &thorn;e
gude ma&ntail; of &thorn;e howse, &amp; tolde hy&mtail; how &thorn;at
all his sekenes was for luff of a maydy&ntail; &thorn;at &thorn;is
merchan&dtail; of Egipte had in his howse, becauce he wol&dtail; wed
hu&rtail; vnto his wife.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;is merchan&dtail;
wuste at it was herefo&rtail;, he gaff hy&mtail; &thorn;is
mayde&ntail; vnto wife, and gaff hy&mtail; a grete dele of gude with
hur.  And whe&ntail; he had wed hur, he tuke hur &amp; a&llbar; his
meneya &amp; wente into his aw&ntail; contre.  So be

<PB N="42">

proces of tyme after, it happend &thorn;is merchan&dtail; of Egipte to
lose his gudis &amp; to wax passand pure, to so meku&llbar; &thorn;at
he come vnto &thorn;e contrey of Baldac bothe nakid &amp; hongrie
o&ntail; ane evyneng, and &thorn;er wol&dtail; no ma&ntail; luge
[hym]; &amp; he went &amp; layde hy&mtail; dow&ntail; in a kur&ktee;
porche.  So &thorn;er happen&dtail; &thorn;at evynyng in &thorn;e
tow&ntail; a ma&ntail; to be slay&ntail;, &amp; no ma&ntail; wiste who
did itt.  And &thorn;e me&ntail; of &thorn;e tow&ntail; rase up &amp;
soght &thorn;is mans queller, &amp; &thorn;aim happen&dtail; to
fyn&dtail; &thorn;is ma&ntail; likkan&dtail; in &thorn;e kurk porche.
And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai had fo&ntail; hy&mtail;, &thorn;ai said
a&llbar; &thorn;at it was he &thorn;at did &thorn;e dede; and he
grauntid at he did itt, &thorn;uff a&llbar; he did it nott, beyng in
wi&llbar; to end his pouertie with dead.  And &thorn;ai tuke hy&mtail;
&amp; putt hy&mtail; in priso&ntail; &thorn;at nyght, &amp; o&ntail;
&thorn;e mor&ntail; &thorn;ai had hy&mtail; vnto &thorn;e galos att
hang hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;is o&thorn;er merchan&dtail; &thorn;at was
his fren&dtail; come with many o&thorn;er to se hy&mtail; dede.  And
whe&ntail; he saw hy&mtail;, onone he knew what he was, and &thorn;a&ntail;
he sai&dtail;; "Leve, ye dampe ane Innocent, ffor I slew &thorn;e
ma&ntail; my selfe &amp; not he."  And &thorn;ai <NOTE ID="P42.N1">MS. &thorn;an.</NOTE>
take hy&mtail; &amp; lete &thorn;e toder go.  And a lurda&ntail;, at
did &thorn;e dede, stude emang o&thorn;er me&ntail; &amp; saw, &amp;
he remordi&dtail; in his conciens &amp; sai&dtail;; "Nowder of
&thorn;ies two did itt, I did it my selfe."  And &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;ai lete &thorn;e toder go &amp; tuke hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;e
iudgies had grete merve&llbar; here-off, And tuke &thorn;aim a&llbar;
iij, &amp; had &thorn;aim vnto &thorn;e kyng.  And onone &thorn;ai
tolde hy&mtail; a&llbar; &thorn;e proces; and becauce of &thorn;er
treuth he pardon&dtail; &thorn;aim ilkone.  And &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;is merchan&dtail; of Baldac parti&dtail; his gudis evy&ntail;
in two, and gaff it vnto &thorn;is pure merchan&dtail;, &amp; he tuke
it &amp; went agay&ntail; into his aw&ntail; contrey, and
afterwar&dtail; was als riche as euer he was.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> LVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Amicus in necessitate probatur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how &thorn;er was a ma&ntail; in a contrey &thorn;at was
taky&ntail; &amp; had to &thorn;e kyngis cowrte, &amp; sulde die.  And
he come vnto a ma&ntail; &thorn;at he luffi&dtail; passan&dtail; <NOTE ID="P42.N2">MS. passid.</NOTE> wele, &amp; prayed hy&mtail; to helpe hy&mtail; in
&thorn;at grete nede; [and he said vnto hym] <NOTE ID="P42.N3">Latin MSS. qui dixit.</NOTE> ,
"I hafe o&thorn;er frendis at I luff als wele as I do the, &amp;
&thorn;erfor wi&llbar; nott go with the, bod I sa&llbar; giff &thorn;e
a garment to hap&ptail; &thorn;e with."  And &thorn;a&ntail; he mett
[with] a secun&dtail; fren&dtail; &thorn;at he luffi&dtail; bettir,
&amp; he praye&dtail; hy&mtail; to go with hy&mtail; &amp; helpe







<PB N="43">

hy&mtail;; &amp; he sai&dtail; he wol&dtail; go with hy&mtail; a little
way, bod he myght not tarie, he wol&dtail; co[m] sone agay&ntail;.
And &thorn;an he mett with his thri&dtail; fren&dtail;, &thorn;at he
luffi&dtail; bod liti&llbar;, and with grete shame he prayed hy&mtail;
to helpe hy&mtail;.  And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
say&dtail;; "I hafe y[it] in my mynde a little gude tur&ntail; at
&thorn;ou did me with vsurie, and yitt I sa&llbar; reward t[he], ffor
I sa&llbar; putt my sawle for &thorn;i sawle."  Frendis! ye sa&llbar;
vnderston&dtail; &thorn;at &thorn;is ffurst fren&dtail; is we[r]ldly
possessions, whilk &thorn;at whe&ntail; we dye giffis vs bod a wyndyng
clothe to lap vs in.  And &thorn;e secon&dtail; fren&dtail; is
ow&rtail; kynsme&ntail; and our frendis, &thorn;at <NOTE ID="P43.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, &thorn;at.</NOTE> gase with vs vnto we co&mtail; att ow&rtail; grafe.
And &thorn;e iij fren&dtail; is almighti Go&dtail;, whilk &thorn;att
putt bothe His life &amp; His sawle for His frendis whe&ntail; He
suffre&dtail; His passio&ntail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> LIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Amicus eciam propter necessitatem debet
probari.</FOREIGN></HEAD> 

<P> We rede how &thorn;e fadir taght his so&ntail; for to prufe his
frende, &amp; saide; "Take &amp; sla a calfe &amp; lay it in salte.
And whe&ntail; &thorn;i frende commys vnto the, tell hy&mtail;
&thorn;at &thorn;ou haste slay&ntail; a ma&ntail;, &amp; pray
hy&mtail; for to go berie hy&mtail; privalie '&thorn;at &thorn;ou be
not suspecte, nor I nowder; And so &thorn;ou may safe my life.'"  And
his furste fren&dtail; at he come to &amp; tolde &thorn;is matier
ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "Nay, bere hame &thorn;e
deade ma&ntail; with &thorn;e, for he sa&llbar; not com in my howse;
ffor as &thorn;u hase done sa&llbar; &thorn;ou ansswer, for me."  And
so he went fro fren&dtail; to fren&dtail;, &amp; ilkone ansswerd
hy&mtail; in &thorn;is wise.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he come vnto a
fren&dtail; of his fadurs, telland hym; And he bad hy&mtail; go bere
hy&mtail; in-to his howse, and sai&dtail; he sulde do it &amp; kepe it
privay enog&hbar;.  And he sent oute his wife &amp; a&llbar; his howse
meneya, and wente &amp; grufe it hy&mtail; selfe.  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;at he had done, he tol&dtail; hy&mtail; a&llbar; how he had
done, &amp; &thorn;anki&dtail; hy&mtail; for his kyndnes.

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>LX.
<LB>

<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Amicis eciam delinquentibus est
parcendum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis how att &thorn;er was a tyrand in Athens, &amp; he
had a fayr doghter.  And &thorn;er was a yong felow &thorn;at
luffi&dtail; hur wele and wol&dtail; hafe had hur to his wife.  So
o&ntail; a tyme hy&mtail; happend



<PB N="44">

to mete hur in ane oppy&ntail; place, and befo&rtail; hur modir he
kissi&dtail; hur.  And &thorn;e wyfe went &amp; tolde &thorn;is tyrant
hur husban&dtail;, &amp; walde hafe garte smyte of his hede.  And
&thorn;is tyran&dtail; ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; said; "If we
sla &thorn;aim &thorn;at luffis vs, what sulde we do with &thorn;aim
att hatis vs?"  And &thorn;us he ansswer&dtail; manlie, &amp;
&thorn;oght for luf &thorn;at &thorn;is yong ma&ntail; had vnto
&thorn;is doghter of his, &thorn;at <NOTE ID="P44.N1">MS. yit.</NOTE> he
luffi&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; wolde not suffre hy&mtail;
hafe none i&llbar;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> LXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Amicis eciam Conuicia et obprobria interdum
sunt condonanda.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis how that &thorn;er was a tyran&dtail; &thorn;at
o&ntail; a nyght satt att supper with a ma&ntail; &thorn;at hyght
Crasippus.  And as &thorn;ai fe&llbar; at supper &thorn;ai fe&llbar;
att varyans.  And &thorn;is Crasippus was so angrie and flate so,
&thorn;at &thorn;e frothe sprang at &thorn;e mowthe of hy&mtail;,
becauce he mot not venge hy&mtail;.  Neuer-&thorn;e-les &thorn;is
tyran&dtail; suffre&dtail; hy&mtail; becauce he was in his howse.  And
on &thorn;e mor&ntail; whe&ntail; he was comme&ntail; vnto hy&mtail;
selfe, he com vnto &thorn;is Crasippus &amp; tolde hy&mtail; soberlie
of his anger, and forgaff hy&mtail; itt.

</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Amici mors debet pacienter tolerari 
<NOTE ID="P44.N2">So in the Latin MSS.  The English MS. has, to&llbar;ari.</NOTE> .  Infra de morte, xiiij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> LXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Amici falsi multa promittunt que non
implent.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Libro de dono Timoris' how &thorn;at &thorn;er was a
nygromansier, and he had a dissiple; And he feny&dtail; hy&mtail;
&thorn;at he luffid his maister passyng wele.  And he beheste his
master mekle &thorn;ing and he wolde helpe att he war riche.  And his
maister thoght to prufe hy&mtail;, whethir he sai&dtail; treut&hbar; or
noght.  And be his enchawntmentis he garte hy&mtail; thynk at he was
ane Emperour.  And whe&ntail; it was latty&ntail; hy&mtail; witt
&thorn;at &thorn;er was meku&llbar; lande voy&dtail;, hy&mtail;
&thorn;oght his maister come vnto hy&mtail; and prayed hy&mtail; to be
myndefu&llbar; of his





<PB N="45">

promys, and at he wolde giff hy&mtail; so&mtail; lande.  And he
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; aski&dtail; hy&mtail; what he was,
&amp; sai&dtail; he knew hy&mtail; noght.  And his maister sai&dtail;;
"I a&mtail; he &thorn;at gaff vnto you a&llbar; &thorn;ies gud[is];
and becauce now ye ke&ntail; me noght, Now I sa&llbar; take a&llbar;
away fro you."  And with &thorn;at he v[a]nysshi&dtail; his
enchawntement, &amp; &thorn;er was oght nott lefte of a&llbar;
&thorn;at hy&mtail; &thorn;oght he saw.  In like wise wi&llbar; God do
vnto riche me&ntail; &thorn;at whils &thorn;ai er pure promyssis
enog&hbar; vnto Almighti Go&dtail;, and whe&ntail; &thorn;ai er riche,
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai wi&llbar; not ke&ntail; nor giff Hy&mtail;
noght, &thorn;at is to say, giff noght for His sake. et c&curl; ad
libitum.

</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Amici sunt multi ficti <NOTE ID="P45.N1">MS. facti, but Latin MSS. ficti.</NOTE>.
Infra vbi agitur de fidelitate.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> LXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Amor Castus in omnibus est
laudandus.</FOREIGN></HEAD> 

<P> We rede in 'Vita Beati Lupi' how he had in his howse a holie
virgy&ntail; &thorn;at was his predecessur doghter, &amp; he
luffi&dtail; hur passandli wele, and his howsol&dtail; bakbate
hy&mtail; &thorn;erfo&rtail;.  So o&ntail; a tyme, befo&rtail;
&thorn;aim a&llbar;, he tuke hur abowte &thorn;e nek&ktee; &amp;
kyssi&dtail; hur, &amp; sai&dtail; vnto &thorn;aim o&ntail; &thorn;is
maner of wise; "Other mens wurdis sa&llbar; neuer noy a ma&ntail;, how
&thorn;at evur &thorn;ai say, whome &thorn;at his consciens fylis
noght."  For he luffid God aboue al thyng, and so wiste he wele
&thorn;at sho di&dtail;; and &thorn;erfo&rtail; he luffi&dtail; hur
with a meke mynde.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> LXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Amor carnalis peruertit in homine fidem.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vita Sancti Basilij,' how &thorn;er was a wurthi
ma&ntail; &thorn;at had a fayr doghter; and he had a yong boy vnto his
servan&dtail;.  And he luffi&dtail; &thorn;is damyse&llbar; so hartlie
wele &thorn;at he was in poynt to dye for hur.  So he went vnto a
nygromansier and agrei&dtail; with hy&mtail; &thorn;at he sulde gett
hy&mtail; &thorn;e luff hur.  And he, evy&ntail; befo&rtail; &thorn;is
yong felow, raysi&dtail; a grete meneya of fendis, and &thorn;e grete
fende sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "And &thorn;ou wi&llbar; at I
fulfi&llbar; &thorn;i wi&llbar;, make me



<PB N="46">

a wrytyng with &thorn;i han&dtail; <NOTE ID="P46.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, writing, <HI REND="i">here</HI>.</NOTE> &thorn;at
&thorn;ou forsakis God &amp; &thorn;i cristendo&mtail;, &amp; at
&thorn;ou sal be my servan&dtail;, and for to dwe&llbar; with me for
evur."  And he grawnti&dtail; &thorn;erto, and wrote it &amp;
delyver&dtail; it vnto hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;is done, &thorn;ir
fendis made &thorn;e harte of &thorn;is maydy&ntail; so for to
kynde&llbar; in &thorn;e luff of &thorn;is [boy] <NOTE ID="P46.N2">MS. maydyn.</NOTE>
, to so meku&llbar; sho fe&llbar; o&ntail; hur kneis befor hur fadur
&amp; crie&dtail; o&ntail; hy&mtail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "Hafe mercie
o&ntail; me, fadur! for I a&mtail; hugelie truble&dtail; for &thorn;e
luff of suche a yong man, and &thorn;erfor I pray you latt me hafe
hy&mtail; to husban&dtail;, or els I mo&ntail; dye."  And whe&ntail;
hur fadur har&dtail; &thorn;is, he sai&dtail;: "Alas! what is
happen&dtail; vnto my doghter?  I purposid to hafe mari&dtail;
&thorn;e with a wurshupfu&llbar; ma&ntail;, and &thorn;ou erte
streke&ntail; in &thorn;e luste of a yong lad."  Neuer-&thorn;e-les be
cownce&llbar; of his frendis, he lete hy&mtail; hafe hur, &amp; gaff
hy&mtail; a porcio&ntail; of his gudis with hur.  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;ai had bene wed a while, sho pursayvi&dtail; &thorn;at he
wol&dtail; nowder say&ntail; hy&mtail; nor co&mtail; into &thorn;e
kur&ktee; to here no dyvyne serves.  And &thorn;e neghburs
trowi&dtail; at he was not cristen&dtail;; and sho went &amp; tolde
hy&mtail;.  And he sai&dtail; &thorn;ai lye&dtail;, and sho sai&dtail;
&thorn;at sho wol&dtail; not trow hy&mtail; bod if he wolde go with
hur vnto &thorn;e kur&ktee; on &thorn;e mor&ntail;.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; he saw &thorn;at he myght no langer kepe it
cownce&llbar;, and tol&dtail; hur a&llbar; how &thorn;at it had
happend hy&mtail;.  And sho made meku&llbar; sorow, and went vnto
Saynt Basy&llbar; &amp; tolde hy&mtail;.  And he aski&dtail; hur
husbon&dtail; if he wol&dtail; reverte agay&ntail; to Criste; and he
sayde &thorn;at he wol&dtail; fu&llbar; fay&ntail;, bot he myght nott;
"for I a&mtail; swor&ntail; vnto &thorn;e devu&llbar; and hafe denyed
Criste, &amp; hafe writte&ntail; my dede &thorn;eroff &amp;
delyver&dtail; it vnto &thorn;e devu&llbar;."  And &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;is Basilius told hy&mtail; &thorn;at God was mercifu&llbar;,
&amp; if he wol&dtail; shrife hy&mtail; of his sy&ntail; &amp; do his
penans &thorn;erfor, &thorn;at God wol&dtail; forgiff hy&mtail;.  And
he tuke hy&mtail; and blissi&dtail; hy&mtail; with &thorn;e cros,
&amp; put hy&mtail; in a howse be his one in grete penance xlti dayes.
And in &thorn;e mene while &thorn;er was harde grete crying of fendis
&thorn;at apperi&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;, bod ilk day &thorn;is Basilius
come vnto hy&mtail; and comfurthed hy&mtail;.  And efter &thorn;is he
tuke hy&mtail; befo&rtail; a&llbar; his clergie &amp; &thorn;e
pepu&llbar;, &amp; had hy&mtail; vnto &thorn;e kur&ktee;.  And
&thorn;e devu&llbar; come &thorn;at a&llbar; me&ntail; might se, &amp;
wol&dtail; hafe take&ntail; hy&mtail; fro hy&mtail;, and &thorn;is
yong ma&ntail; crie&dtail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "holie fadur! helpe me!"
An&dtail; &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e devu&llbar; sai&dtail; at a&llbar;
myght here; "Basy&llbar;, &thorn;ou duse me wrong; for I come





<PB N="47">

not to hy&mtail;, bod he come to me, &amp; forsuke Criste, &amp; was
swor&ntail; vnto me.  And &thorn;er-of I hafe his writyng in my
han&dtail; <NOTE ID="P47.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, &thorn;erof.</NOTE> .  And Saynt Basi&llbar; &amp; his
<NOTE ID="P47.N2"><HI REND="i">After</HI> his, maydyn, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> clergie sett &thorn;aim dow&ntail; &amp; made
&thorn;er prayer for hy&mtail;, &amp; sodanlie &thorn;is chartyr fell
dow&ntail;, &amp; &thorn;is holie ma&ntail; tuke it v&ptail; in his
hand &amp; opyn&dtail; it &amp; shewi&dtail; it vnto &thorn;is yong
ma&ntail;, &amp; askid hy&mtail; if he kend itt.  And he said; "ya,
sur, for I wrote it my selfe."  And he burny&dtail; it &amp; had
hy&mtail; vnto &thorn;e kur&ktee;, &amp; delyvur&dtail; hy&mtail;
vnto his wife, &amp; bad hy&mtail; be a gude ma&ntail;; &amp; so he
was evur after.

</P>
<P>
<LIST>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Amantem carnaliter expedit elongare.  Infra, Clementis in
principio.</FOREIGN></ITEM> <ITEM><FOREIGN>Amor carnalis eciam magnorum adiutorium
requirit.  Infra vbi Agitur de arte magica, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM> <ITEM><FOREIGN>Amor carnalis
eciam propinquis non parcit.  Infra de contricione, iij et vj.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Amor carnalis Cristianos Iudeis coniungi facit.  Infra de
contricione, iiij.</FOREIGN></ITEM> <ITEM><FOREIGN>Amor carnalis hominem quandoque periculo
exponit.  Supra de Amicicia, viij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> LXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Andree Apostoli.</FOREIGN></HEAD> <P> We rede in
<NOTE ID="P47.N3">Harl. MS. ex lege Lombardicis. <HI REND="i">For</HI> 'Legenda Lombardica.'</NOTE> 'Libris Lombardorum,' how som tyme &thorn;er was
ane olde ma&ntail; of lxxx <NOTE ID="P47.N4"><HI REND="i">After</HI> of, xl, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> yere olde.  Ande
o&ntail; a tyme he sayde vnto Saynt Andrew &thorn;e aposti&llbar;,
&thorn;at a&llbar; &thorn;e tyme of his life he had vsi&dtail; evur
lichorie.  And Saynt Andrew praye&dtail; vnto God for hy&mtail;
&thorn;at he myght be delyver&dtail; &thorn;eroff; &amp; so he was a while
<NOTE ID="P47.N5">MS. has also, onone he fell &thorn;erto, at the foot of the page.</NOTE> , bod onone he turnyd agay&ntail; vnto &thorn;e
sy&ntail; as he was wunte to do.  Not-withstondyng he bare opo&ntail;
hy&mtail; a euange[ll] wrette&ntail;.  So o&ntail; a tyme he come vnto
&thorn;e bordelhouse to fulfi&llbar; his luste, and onone a
commo&ntail; womma&ntail; mett with hy&mtail;, &amp; sai&dtail; vnto
hy&mtail; in &thorn;is maner of wise; "O! &thorn;ou olde man! go
&thorn;i ways! go &thorn;i ways! for &thorn;ou

<PB N="48">

arte &thorn;e Ange&llbar; of Go&dtail;.  And &thorn;erfo&rtail; tuche
me noght, ffor I se vppo&ntail; &thorn;e many mervaylis."  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is olde ma&ntail;, beyng astony&dtail; gretelie
with &thorn;is como&ntail; womma&ntail; language, remembre&dtail; how
&thorn;at he had vppo&ntail; hy&mtail; &thorn;e evange&llbar;.  &amp;
&thorn;a&ntail; he went agay&ntail; vnto Saynt And[r]ew &amp; tolde
hy&mtail; a&llbar;, &amp; praye&dtail; hy&mtail; to pray for
hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; Saynt Andrew wepid for hy&mtail; &amp;
say&dtail;; "I sa&llbar; [no] meate eate vnto tyme I know if ou&rtail;
Lor&dtail; wi&llbar; hafe mercie of &thorn;e or noght."  And so he lay
in [h]i[s] prayers &amp; fastid v dayes.  &amp; &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;er come vnto Saynt And[r]ew a voyce &thorn;at say&dtail;; O!
&thorn;ou Andr[ew]! our Lor&dtail; hase graunti&dtail; &thorn;e att
&thorn;is alde ma&ntail; sal be savi&dtail;.  Bod as &thorn;ou with
fastyng hase made &thorn;e lene, Right so muste hy&mtail; chastes his
fless&hbar; with fastyng if he sal be savi&dtail;."  And so he did,
&amp; fastid sex dayes brede &amp; watir, &amp; efterwar&dtail; sex
monethis; &amp; afterwar&dtail; he was a gude ma&ntail;, &amp;
decesi&dtail; in gude life.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;er come a
voyse vnto Saynt Andrew &amp; sai&dtail;; "Be &thorn;i holie prayer
<NOTE ID="P48.N1">MS. pray.</NOTE> , Nicholas &thorn;at I had loste hafe I
gette&ntail; agay&ntail;."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> LXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Andree Apostoli.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede o&ntail; [a] tyme how a yong ma&ntail; sai&dtail; vnto
Saynt Andrew in privatie; "My moder o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;oght me
passand fayr, &amp; desyri&dtail; me to hafe att do with hur.  And
whe&ntail; sho saw &thorn;at o&ntail; no wise I wolde consent vnto
hur, sho went vnto &thorn;e iudgies of &thorn;e law &amp;
accusi&dtail; me to &thorn;aim &thorn;at I had done it with hur.  And
&thorn;erfor I <NOTE ID="P48.N2">MS. he.</NOTE> pray &thorn;e" he sai&dtail;, "to
pray for me, at I be nott wrongoslie putt to dea&dtail; <NOTE ID="P48.N3">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, wrongoslie.</NOTE> .  Not-withstondyng me had levur suffer to take my
deade wronguslie, &thorn;a&ntail; <NOTE ID="P48.N4">MS. &thorn;at.</NOTE> for to hafe
corrupte my <NOTE ID="P48.N5"><HI REND="i">After</HI> my, br, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> moder."  So o&ntail; a day &thorn;is
yong ma&ntail; was broght vnto &thorn;e bar befo&rtail; a iudge, and
Saynt Andrew felowi&dtail; hy&mtail; thedir; and &thorn;e moder stude
furthe &amp; accusi&dtail; hur so&ntail; fellie, saying &thorn;at he
wol&dtail; hafe lye&ntail; by hur.  And &thorn;is yong [man] stude
sti&llbar; &amp; spak no wurde.  Tha&ntail; Saynt Andrew spak vnto
&thorn;e moder &amp; sayde; "O! &thorn;ou crowelleste of womme&ntail;!
be &thorn;i fals <NOTE ID="P48.N6"><HI REND="i">After</HI> fals, &thorn;, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> luste, &thorn;ow wolde distroy
&thorn;ine aw&ntail; so&ntail;."  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is moder
say&dtail; vnto

<PB N="49">

&thorn;e iudge; "Sur, whe&ntail; my so&ntail; wol&dtail; hafe done
&thorn;is dede with me, &amp; I had avoydi&dtail; hy&mtail;,
&thorn;a&ntail; he went vnto &thorn;is ma&ntail;."  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e iudge wex wrothe, &amp; commandi&dtail;
&thorn;is yong ma&ntail; to be put in a ly&ntail; sekk, enoynty&dtail;
with pykk &amp; tar, &amp; so to be caste&ntail; in a depe watir; and
he commawndi&dtail; att Saynt Andrew sulde be put in priso&ntail;.
And &thorn;is done, Saynt Andrew kneli&dtail; dow&ntail; &amp; made
his prayers, &amp; sodanlie &thorn;er fe&llbar; a grete thondre &amp;
ane erd-quake, &amp; smate dow&ntail; euerilk a ma&ntail; vnto
&thorn;e ert&hbar;.  And &thorn;is womma&ntail; was burny&dtail; to
dede with a thondre-bolte, &amp; fe&llbar; dow&ntail; to ass&hbar;.
And &thorn;a&ntail; Saynt Andrew made his prayer agay&ntail;, &amp;
a&llbar; sesi&dtail;; and &thorn;us &thorn;e iudge &amp; a&llbar;
&thorn;at wer aboute wer torny&dtail; vnto &thorn;e f[aith].


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> LXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Andree Apostoli.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;e devu&llbar; apperi&dtail;
vnto a certay&ntail; bisshop&ptail; <NOTE ID="P49.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, vnto a bisshop&ptail;.</NOTE> &thorn;at
had grete devocio&ntail; vnto Saynt Andrew, in for&mtail; &amp; lyknes
of a fayr mayde&ntail;, &amp; sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; o&ntail;
&thorn;is maner of wise; "Sur, I wulde be shreve&ntail; at you &amp;
at no noder."  &amp; &thorn;is bissho&ptail; graunti&dtail;,
not-withstondyng it was agayns his wi&llbar;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; sho
sett hur dow&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "Sur, I a&mtail; yong &amp;
passan&dtail; fayr, as ye may se; and I a&mtail; a kyngis doghter, and
my fader wolde hafe marid me vnto a wurthi prince, and I a&mtail; fled
away &amp; wol&dtail; not hafe hy&mtail;, becauce I had avowe&dtail;
my virginitie vnto almighti Go&dtail;.  And becauce I harde te&llbar;
of your halines, &thorn;erfor I a&mtail; comme&ntail; vnto you for
refute."  Tha&ntail; &thorn;is bisshop&ptail; had grete mervayle of
hur fayrnes &amp; hur gudelie language, &amp; sayd vnto hur;
"Doghter, I latt &thorn;e witt for &thorn;i gude entent, &thorn;at
what at evur I hafe sa&llbar; be &thorn;ine; and I pray &thorn;e
&thorn;is day for to dyne with me."  And &thorn;a&ntail; sho
ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "Nay, holie
fadur, desire it nott, nor pray me not &thorn;erto, &thorn;at no
suspecte rise betwix vs &thorn;at myght hurte &thorn;i gude name and
&thorn;i fame."  And &thorn;is bisshop&ptail; ansswerd hur agay&ntail;
&amp; sayd; "We sa&llbar; not be be our one, &amp; &thorn;erfo&rtail;
&thorn;er sa&llbar; no suspecio&ntail; ryse of vs."  So &thorn;is
bisshop&ptail; went to meate, and &thorn;is womma&ntail; was sett
enence hy&mtail; in a chayre.  And a&llbar; &thorn;e meat-while
&thorn;is bisshop&ptail; behel&dtail; hur, &amp; had grete
mervay&llbar; of



<PB N="50">

hur fayrnes; &amp; sho purceyvi&dtail; &thorn;is, &amp; encresi&dtail;
hur fayrenes ay more &amp; more, vnto so mekle at &thorn;is
bisshop&ptail; was wowndi&dtail; gretlie in his harte with flesshlie
luste, vnto so mekle &thorn;at he thoght to aske hur if sho wulde latt
hy&mtail; ly by hur.  And &thorn;a&ntail; sodanlie &thorn;er come vnto
&thorn;e yate a pylgra&mtail;, &amp; knokki&dtail; &amp; askid meate
for Goddis sake.  Tha&ntail; &thorn;is womma&ntail; desyre&dtail;
&thorn;e bysshop&ptail; &thorn;at he sulde hafe no meate vnto at he
ha&dtail; essoyny&dtail; iij questions &thorn;at sho sul&dtail;
as&ktee; hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;e furste questio&ntail; was
&thorn;is, What was &thorn;e grettest mervayle &amp; fayrest
&thorn;ing &thorn;at evur God made in leste rowme?  And a messanger
come vnto &thorn;e pylgra&mtail; &amp; askid hy&mtail; it; and
&thorn;e pylgra&mtail; ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;,
&thorn;at it was &thorn;e dyuersitye &amp; fayrnes to a mans vysage;
"ffor &amp; a&llbar; me&ntail;," he sai&dtail;, "war samen, &thorn;at
was fro &thorn;e byggyny&ntail;g of &thorn;e werl&dtail; vnto &thorn;e
endyng, yit ij sulde nott be fo&ntail; to-gedur &thorn;at war lyke in
visage in a&llbar; maner of thyng; &amp; a&llbar; &thorn;e wittes of a
ma&ntail; is sett in &thorn;at litle row&mtail;."  So &thorn;is
messanger come in &amp; tol&dtail; &thorn;e bissho&ptail;, &amp; he
&amp; a&llbar; me&ntail; say&dtail; &thorn;e pylgram had
ansswer&dtail; we&llbar;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; sho sent hy&mtail; a
noder questio&ntail;, and &thorn;at was &thorn;is; <NOTE ID="P50.N1">Lat. MSS. vbi terra est altior celo?  Ille autem respondit; "In celo empireo, vbi corpus Christi."</NOTE> Whether was hyer heve&ntail; or ert&hbar;e?  And he
ansswerd agay&ntail; &amp; sayde <NOTE ID="P50.N2"><HI REND="i">After</HI> sayde, &amp; he sai&dtail;, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> &thorn;at
ert&hbar; was hyer &thorn;a&ntail; hevy&ntail;, " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">quia in celo empirio ibi est corpus Christi, quod est super
omnes celos.</FOREIGN>" And whe&ntail; &thorn;e messanger come with
&thorn;is, sho sai&dtail; &thorn;att sho sulde sende hy&mtail; a war
questio&ntail; &thorn;a&ntail; owther off &thorn;e tother was, and
&thorn;at was &thorn;is; How far space it was betwix hevy&ntail; &amp;
ert&hbar;?  And &thorn;a&ntail; he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
sai&dtail;; "He &thorn;at sent &thorn;e vnto me knowis &thorn;at
bettyr &thorn;an I doo, ffor I fe&llbar; neuer fro hevy&ntail; to
erthe, &amp; he fe&llbar; fro hevy&ntail; vnto he&llbar; &thorn;at is
vnder &thorn;e ert&hbar;, &amp; &thorn;erfor he mett itt; ffor
&thorn;at womma&ntail; at bad &thorn;e spy&rtail; me &thorn;ies
questions is &thorn;e devu&llbar;, &thorn;at putt hy&mtail; in lyknes
of a womma&ntail;."  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e messange&rtail; harde
&thorn;is, he had grete wunder, and went in &amp; befo&rtail; a&llbar;
me&ntail;, &amp; told a&llbar; as he bad hy&mtail;.  And a&llbar; att
was aboute had grete mervayle, and sodanlie &thorn;e devu&llbar;
vanysshi&dtail; away with a grete thonder &amp; a levenyng; and
&thorn;e bissho&ptail; &amp; a&llbar; &thorn;e felowschi&ptail;
sayny&dtail; &thorn;aim, &amp; onone it cesi&dtail;.  Tha&ntail; he
garte send furt&hbar; <NOTE ID="P50.N3"><HI REND="i">After</HI> furt&hbar;, &thorn;is, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> to seke &thorn;is
pylgra&mtail;, &amp; &thorn;er cuthe no ma&ntail; fyn&dtail;
hy&mtail;.

<PB N="51">

Than &thorn;is bisshop&ptail; come vnto hy&mtail; selfe, &amp; had
grete sorow for &thorn;e temptacio&ntail; &thorn;at he was
falle&ntail; in, &amp; shrafe hy&mtail; &thorn;eroff &amp; tuke his
penans &thorn;erfo&rtail;.  And afterwar&dtail; he had knowlege be
revelacio&ntail;, &thorn;at &thorn;is pylgra&mtail; was Saynt Andrew.
And fro thyne furt&hbar;, evur after whils he liffi&dtail;, he had
more devocio&ntail; vnto Saynt Andrew &thorn;a&ntail; he had
befo&rtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> LXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Angelus.  Angelis fetent peccata
hominum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' how, o&ntail; a tyme, ane ange&llbar;
in a mans lyknes come &amp; went with ane hermett a grete way.  So
&thorn;aim happen&dtail; co&mtail; be a caryo&ntail; &thorn;at had
ligge&ntail; dea&dtail; many day, &amp; it stynki&dtail; i&llbar;; and
&thorn;is hermett helde his nece, at he sulde nott fele savur
&thorn;erof.  And &thorn;is aunge&llbar; aski&dtail; hy&mtail; whi he
helde his nece, and he ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
sai&dtail;; "Becauce I may not fele &thorn;is savur."  And &thorn;ai
went o&ntail; furt&hbar;, &amp; onone &thorn;ai mett a fay&rtail; yong
ma&ntail; cled in gay clothyng, &thorn;at had a fayr garlan&dtail;
o&ntail; his head, &thorn;at rade opo&ntail; a gay hors in a sadle
a&llbar; of gol&dtail; &amp; sylver.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai wer a
gude way fro hy&mtail;, &thorn;is ange&llbar; in a mans liknes stoppyd
his nease-thrillis.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;is hermett saw, he had
grete merva&llbar; &thorn;erof, &amp; sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "whi
stoppis &thorn;ou &thorn;i nece so, &amp; stoppi&dtail; &thorn;aim
no&yogh;t right now?"  And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
sai&dtail;; "yone yong ma&ntail; &thorn;at is so prowde &amp;
fu&llbar; of sy&ntail;, stynkis mo&rtail; vglie in &thorn;e sight of
God &amp; a&llbar; his aunge&llbar;, &thorn;a&ntail; done a&llbar;
&thorn;e cario&ntail; of &thorn;is werl&dtail; in syght or felyng of
cryste&ntail; me&ntail;." et c&curl;.

</P>
<P><LIST><ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Angelus accusat peccatores.  Infra de
fideiussor[e]. ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>

</LIST>
</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>LXVIIIa.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Angelus actus nostros dinumerat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> As we rede of ane hermett &thorn;at had a ce&llbar; far fro
&thorn;e watir. et c&curl;.</P><P><LIST><ITEM><FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Vt infra de laborare,
ij.</FOREIGN>
</ITEM></LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> LXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Angelus a morte corporali liberat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;er was a damyse&llbar; in a chylde
liknes &thorn;at went in felowshu&ptail; w[ith] a thefe be &thorn;e
way, &amp; wiste no&yogh;t what he

<PB N="52">

was.  &amp; &thorn;is thefe gaff hur to bere a paghal&dtail; of gere
&thorn;at he had stol&ntail;.  So it happen&dtail; at &thorn;e
me&ntail; att aght &thorn;is gude folowi&dtail; after &thorn;is thefe,
&amp; onone as he har&dtail; noyse of rynyng of &thorn;aim, &amp; he
gatt away, &amp; lete &thorn;is damyse&llbar; alone with &thorn;is
stol&ntail; gude.  And &thorn;is childe was taky&ntail; with &thorn;is
thifte &amp; demyd to be hanged; &amp; whe&ntail; sho cuthe gett no
skosacio&ntail; to helpe hur with, bod at sho trewi&dtail; vereli[e]
to dye, sho shrafe hur vnto &thorn;e preste &amp; tolde hy&mtail;
a&llbar; &thorn;e proces.  So &thorn;ai went &amp; soght &thorn;is
thefe in &thorn;e wud &amp; fande hy&mtail;, &amp; tuke hy&mtail;; and
whe&ntail; he was take&ntail; he <NOTE ID="P52.N1">MS. le.</NOTE> alegid for
hy&mtail; selfe, &amp; sai&dtail; &thorn;at &thorn;is paghal&dtail;
was not of his, &amp; &thorn;erfo&rtail; he sai&dtail; &thorn;at
&thorn;ai at &thorn;e stol&ntail; gude was fun with sulde suffre
&thorn;e penance.  And &thorn;us he alegi&dtail; &thorn;at &thorn;e
childe sulde be dede &amp; not he.  So be cownce&llbar; of &thorn;e
preste, &thorn;er was broght furt&hbar; a hote yr&ntail; to prufe
&thorn;e treut&hbar; with; and &thorn;is damyse&llbar; tuchi&dtail;
&thorn;is hote yr&ntail; &amp; hur han&dtail; was nothyng
byrny&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e thefe tuchid itt, his hand was
grevuslie burny&dtail;, and so &thorn;e thiefe was hange&dtail; &amp;
&thorn;e mayde&ntail; delyver&dtail;.  So &thorn;e kynsme&ntail; of
&thorn;is thieff wex wrothe with &thorn;is, and tuke dow&ntail;
&thorn;is thieff, &amp; hanged v&ptail; &thorn;is damyse&llbar;.  And
onone &thorn;er come ane aunge&llbar; &amp; helde hur v&ptail;, so at
sho felid no grevans bod a grete swettnes, &amp; hard a passand swete
melodie, in &thorn;e whilk it was tolde hur &thorn;at a sister saule
of hurs, &thorn;at hight Agnes, who had vnto hevy&ntail;, and at sho
suld at ij [yere] ende after folow hur.  And &thorn;er sho hang ij
dayes; &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; hirdme&ntail; trowid at sho ha&dtail;
bene dea&dtail;, &amp; cut dow&ntail; &thorn;e rape &amp; went sho
sulde hafe falle&ntail; dow&ntail;; bod scho was susteny&dtail; with
ane ange&llbar; &amp; latty&ntail; dow&ntail; be little &amp; litle,
vnto sho stude evy&ntail; opo&ntail; &thorn;e ert&hbar;.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e aunge&llbar; sayd vnto hur; "Now erte
&thorn;ou fre; Go whethur &thorn;ou wi&llbar;."  And sho sai&dtail;
sho purposi&dtail; go vnto &thorn;e cetie of Vero&ntail; <!-- P52.N2 --> ; &amp; onone with-in a stownde sho was sett nere
&thorn;e cetie of Vero&ntail; <!-- P52.N2 --> , &amp;
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e aunge&llbar; tol&dtail; hur &thorn;at sho was
with-in iij myle of &thorn;is cetie.  And &thorn;is happen&dtail; att
&thorn;e cetie of Auguste, &amp; &thorn;at is vij day iorney fro
Vero&ntail; <NOTE ID="P52.N2"><HI REND="i">For</HI> Verona.</NOTE> .

</P>
<P>

<LIST><ITEM><FOREIGN>Anima purgatur in loco quo peccauit.  Infra de pena.</FOREIGN></ITEM>

<ITEM><FOREIGN>Anima punitur cum persona cum qua peccauit.  Infra de penitentia et
Purgatorio.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<PB N="53">
 
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Anime aliquando ab amicis iuvantur.  Infra de apostata, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>

<ITEM><FOREIGN>Anima punitur secundum qualitatem peccati.  Infra de
purgatorio.</FOREIGN></ITEM>

<ITEM><FOREIGN>Animosus debet esse miles in bello.  Infra de milite,
vj.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST> </P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> LXX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Annunciacio Dominica.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> The feste of &thorn;e annunciacio&ntail; of our ladie aght to be
had in grete reuerens, &amp; to be wurshuppid with grete
devocio&ntail;; and opo&ntail; &thorn;at day aght &thorn;e Ave Maria
ofte to be sai&dtail;, as we rede of a knyght &thorn;at was a
passan&dtail; ryche ma&ntail;, notwithstondyng he went &amp; made
hy&mtail; a monke in &thorn;e Ceustos ordur.  And &thorn;uf a&llbar;
he cuthe no lettre o&ntail; &thorn;e buke, yit for his hy burthe <NOTE ID="P53.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">here repeats</HI>, yit.</NOTE> he was take&ntail; in &amp; putt emang monkis.  And a
maister was delyver&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; to ler&ntail; hy&mtail;
o&ntail; &thorn;e buke; and he cuthe ler&ntail; hy&mtail; no thyng bod
&thorn;ies ij wordys, <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ave Maria.</FOREIGN> And
&thorn;at he was evur harpand o&ntail;, to so meki&llbar; &thorn;at
whider as euer he went, or what thyng so&mtail; evur he di&dtail;, he
was evur sayand <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ave Maria.</FOREIGN> So at
&thorn;e laste hy&mtail; happyn&dtail; to dye, &amp; was beri&dtail;
with other monkis; and &thorn;er sprang oute of his grafe a fayr
lelie, and o&ntail; evur-ilk a lefe &thorn;eroff was wrete&ntail;,
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ave Maria,</FOREIGN> with golde lettres.  And
&thorn;e monkis ra&ntail; &thorn;erto &amp; grufe dow&ntail; in his
grafe to &thorn;ai <NOTE ID="P53.N2">MS. &thorn;e.</NOTE> fande &thorn;e rute of
&thorn;e lelie, &amp; &thorn;ai fan&dtail; how it sprang furt&hbar; of
his mouthe.  And be &thorn;at &thorn;ai vnderstude &thorn;at he
sai&dtail; &thorn;ase ij wurdis, <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ave
Maria,</FOREIGN> with grete deuocio&ntail;.  And perfo&rtail; our
ladie wol&dtail; lat &thorn;aim hafe knowlege.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> LXXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ave Maria dictum deuote liberat hominem de
potestate diaboli.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a knyght &thorn;at was a
thieff, and vsi&dtail; forto rob me&ntail; be &thorn;e way.  So
o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;er come be &thorn;e way a ma&ntail; of
religio&ntail;, and onone he was take&ntail; with &thorn;is knyghtis
me&ntail;,

<PB N="54">

&thorn;at was thevis.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai had take&ntail;
hy&mtail; he praye&dtail; &thorn;aim speciallie to hafe hy&mtail; to
&thorn;er maister; and whe&ntail; he come afo&rtail; &thorn;e knyght
he prayed &thorn;e knyght &thorn;at he wol&dtail; latt hy&mtail; se
a&llbar; his me&ntail;; and he graunti&dtail;, &amp; garte feche
a&llbar; his me&ntail;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;at a&llbar; was
befo&rtail; hy&mtail;, &thorn;is holie ma&ntail; of religio&ntail;
aski&dtail; &thorn;is knyght if &thorn;er was a&llbar;, and &thorn;ai
sai&dtail;, "ya"; and he say&dtail; it was not sa.  So &thorn;ai
luki&dtail; aboute &thorn;aim, &amp; one of &thorn;aim say&dtail;
&thorn;at &thorn;e chamberlay&ntail; was wantand.  And &thorn;e knyght
sent fo&rtail; hy&mtail; &amp; he come, bod yit it was with i&llbar;
wi&llbar;.  And whe&ntail; he saw &thorn;is holie ma&ntail; of
religio&ntail;, he starte bakk &amp; glori&dtail; with his ee&ntail;
as he had bene wude, &amp; wulde co&mtail; no ner for noght at no
ma&ntail; cuthe do.  Tha&ntail; &thorn;is holie ma&ntail; said vnto
hy&mtail;; "I adiure &thorn;e in &thorn;e name of Go&dtail; at
&thorn;ou te&llbar; me what &thorn;ou erte, and wharefor &thorn;ou
come hedur."  And &thorn;a&ntail; he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
say&dtail;; "Allas! now moste me nedis te&llbar; what I a&mtail;! I
a&mtail;," he sai&dtail;, "a fen&dtail;, &amp; I made me like a
ma&ntail;, &amp; I hafe wunte with &thorn;is knyght &thorn;is xiiij
yere, &amp; alway lige&ntail; in wayte if I cuthe wache what day he
say&dtail; not, 'Aue Maria'; ffor what day he had fayli&dtail;
&thorn;eroff, I sulde hafe strangled hy&mtail;; and what day as he
sai&dtail; &thorn;at Ave, I had nevur power o&ntail; hy&mtail;, nor
not mot hafe.  And a&llbar; &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at I hafe bene with
hy&mtail; he fayli&dtail; nevur a day, bod he sai&dtail; it a tyme of
&thorn;e day."  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e knyght hard &thorn;is, he was
hugelie astony&dtail; &amp; had grete mervayle, &amp; fe&llbar;
dow&ntail; o&ntail; his kneis befo&rtail; &thorn;is holie ma&ntail;,
&amp; aski&dtail; hy&mtail; forgifnes, &amp; was shrevy&ntail;, &amp;
tuke penance and amendi&dtail; his life.  And &thorn;is holie
ma&ntail; commandi&dtail; &thorn;is fen&dtail; at he sulde go his
ways, and nevur aftur presume to dissese any creatu&rtail; &thorn;at
had deuocio&ntail; vnto ou&rtail; ladie, Saynt Marie. et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Antiphonam Regina celi Angeli cantauerunt. Infra
de Maria. x.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> LXXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Antonij Abbatis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum,' how o&ntail; a tyme as Saynt
Anto&ntail; lay in a den in wildernes, a grete multitude of fendis
come vnto hy&mtail; and rafe hy&mtail;, &amp; toyli&dtail; hy&mtail;,
to so mekle he was nerehan&dtail; dea&dtail;.

<PB N="55">

And his brether went &amp; soght hy&mtail;, &amp; fan&dtail; hy&mtail;
nere dede; &amp; &thorn;ai wepud &amp; made grete sorow, and
fechi&dtail; hy&mtail; home.  So o&ntail; a nyght whe&ntail; he was
amendi&dtail;, &amp; a&llbar; his brethir was oslepe, he garte bere
hy&mtail; agay&ntail; vnto &thorn;e sayd de&ntail;: and as he lay
&thorn;er, &amp; many wowndis vppo&ntail; hy&mtail;, he lukid evur
whe&ntail; &thorn;ir fendis sul&dtail; co&mtail; agay&ntail;.
Tha&ntail; &thorn;ai come in liknes of wilde bestis, &amp; with
&thorn;er hornys &amp; &thorn;er tethe &thorn;ai rafe his fless&hbar;,
&amp; wowndi&dtail; hy&mtail; hugelie.  Tha&ntail; sodanlie &thorn;er
apperi&dtail; a mervaylus light, &amp; &thorn;ies fendis fle&dtail;;
&amp; sodanlie Saynt Anto&ntail; was hele of a&llbar; his wowndis.  So
att &thorn;e laste he vnderstude &thorn;at &thorn;er was almighti God
Hy&mtail; selfe; &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; he sai&dtail;; "A! gude Jesu!
whar was &thorn;ou? whar was &thorn;ou? whi was &thorn;ou not with me
in &thorn;e begynyng, at &thorn;ou mot hafe helpi&dtail; me, and helid
my wowndis?"  And our Lord ansswerrid hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
sai&dtail;; "Anto&ntail;, I was here, bod I abade to se &thorn;i
bate&llbar;; and becauce now at &thorn;ou has manlelie
ouercomme&ntail; &thorn;ine enmys, I sa&llbar; make &thorn;i name to
be knowe&ntail; &thorn;urg&hbar; a&llbar; &thorn;is werl&dtail;, and
&thorn;e for to be wurshuppi&dtail;."

</P>
<P>
