</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> LXXXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Auditus.  Audire sermonem impedit demon.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Jacobus de Vetriaco tellis, how som tyme &thorn;er was a religious
ma&ntail;, and as he was sayan&dtail; a sermo&ntail; in a kurk
o&ntail; a tyme, he saw &thorn;e devu&llbar; in &thorn;e kurk.  &amp;
&thorn;er he adiuri&dtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; chargi&dtail; hy&mtail;
o&ntail; Goddis behalfe, &thorn;at he sulde te&llbar; hy&mtail; his
name, &amp; what he was.  And &thorn;is Deuy&llbar; ansswer&dtail;
&amp; sai&dtail;; "I a&mtail; a fen&dtail;, &amp; I a&mtail;
calli&dtail;



<PB N="67">


<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Claudens Aurem, Ere sparrer</FOREIGN>.  And I hafe
other iij felows, and ane is calli&dtail; <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Claudens
Cor</FOREIGN>, a noder, <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Claudens Os</FOREIGN>,
&amp; &thorn;e thri&dtail;,

<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Claudens Bursam</FOREIGN>.  The furst sparis a
mans harte, &thorn;at he may not hafe contricio&ntail; for his
sy&ntail;.  The second sparis his mouthe, &thorn;at he sa&llbar; not
shryfe hy&mtail;, &amp; &thorn;e thri&dtail; sparis his purs,
&thorn;at he sa&llbar; make no satisfaccio&ntail; nor dele none
almos-dede, at his sy&ntail; may be forgyffy&ntail; hy&mtail;.  And I
my selfe sparis a mans eris, &thorn;at he sa&llbar; nott here noo gude
prechyng, &thorn;at sulde cauce hy&mtail; to forsake his sy&ntail;."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> LXXXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Audientes verbum dei deus audiet, Et nolentes
audire non audiet.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Jacobus de Vetriaco tellis, how som tyme &thorn;er was a
husband-ma&ntail; &thorn;at wald nott here of almyghti God.  So
o&ntail; a tyme hy&mtail; happen&dtail; to dye, and whe&ntail; he was
bor&ntail; vnto &thorn;e kurk, &amp; &thorn;e prestis &amp; &thorn;e
clerkis was besy aboute hys dirige-doyng, in syngyng &amp; redyng
aboute his bodie, &thorn;e crucifix, at stude vp in &thorn;e
rude-lofte, lowsyd his handis fra &thorn;e rude, &amp; stoppi&dtail;
his eris &thorn;at he sulde nott here &thorn;aim.  And a&llbar;
&thorn;at was in &thorn;e kur&ktee;, whe&ntail; &thorn;ai saw
&thorn;is, had grete mervayle &thorn;eroff.  And &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;e preste said vnto &thorn;e pepu&llbar;; "Know ye whatky&ntail;
a toky&ntail; &thorn;is is? ye know verelie, &thorn;at he this at lies
here had neuer wi&llbar; in a&llbar; his life to here &thorn;e
wur&dtail; of God&dtail;, nor at no ma&ntail; sulde speke off
Hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;erfo&rtail; he is now in &thorn;e power of
&thorn;e devu&llbar;; and &thorn;erfor &thorn;e crucifix now stoppis
his eris, &thorn;at he here nott &thorn;e prayers &thorn;at we syng
&amp; say for hy&mtail;."  And so &thorn;ai a&llbar; lefte &thorn;er prayers
&amp; wolde pray no more for hy&mtail;; &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; the
crucifix putt vp his armys as &thorn;ai war befor. et c&curl;.

</P>
<P><LIST>
<ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Audire missam est multum vtile.  Infra de
Incepcione.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> LXXXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Augurium aliquando est verum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Historia Ecclesiastica' how o&ntail; a tyme Herodes
Agrippa come vnto Rome, &amp; &thorn;er he was passand famyliari with

<PB N="68">

one &thorn;at hight Gayus, &thorn;at was &thorn;e Emperou&rtail;
cussy&ntail;.  So o&ntail; a day, as Herod was in a chariott with
&thorn;is Gayus, Herod lifte vp his handis vnto hevy&ntail; &amp;
sai&dtail;; "Wol&dtail; God at I mott se yone alde ma&ntail; deade,
&thorn;at is Emperour, &amp; at &thorn;ou war lorde of a&llbar;
&thorn;is werl&dtail;."  And whe&ntail; he had har&dtail; &thorn;is
Hero&dtail; say so, he went vnto Tyberius, &thorn;at was Emperour,
&amp; tolde hy&mtail;.  And he wex passand wrothe &thorn;erwith, &amp;
garte putt Herod in priso&ntail; &thorn;erfo&rtail;.  So o&ntail; a
day as &thorn;ai satt in priso&ntail;, he &amp; his felous, &thorn;ai
war war of ane owle sytt in &thorn;e bewis of a tre.  &amp;
&thorn;a&ntail; one of &thorn;aim, &thorn;at was wiseste of &thorn;aim
a&llbar;, sai&dtail; vnto Hero&dtail;; "dowte &thorn;e no&yogh;t, for
&thorn;ou mo&ntail; sone be delyver&dtail;, &amp; be so gretelie
enhawnsi&dtail; &amp; &thorn;ai &thorn;at er &thorn;i frendis sal be
&thorn;ine enmys; &amp; in &thorn;is prosperitie &thorn;ou sa&llbar;
dye."  So with-in a little while after, &thorn;is Tyberius dye&dtail;,
and &thorn;is Gayus was chosy&ntail; Emperour.  And he tuke vp
&thorn;is Herod oute of priso&ntail; &amp; gretelie enhawnecid
hy&mtail;, &amp; made hy&mtail; &thorn;e chefe kyng in a&llbar; Iurie.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> LXXXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Augurrium.  Sicut supra.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>Josephus tellis &thorn;at whe&ntail; Hero&dtail; come vnto Cesarie
&amp; a&llbar; &thorn;e me&ntail; of &thorn;e contre come vnto
hy&mtail;, he had o&ntail; clothyng of clothe of golde &amp; syluer.
So o&ntail; a day he satt in &thorn;er mote-ha&llbar;, &amp; &thorn;e
so&ntail; bemys shane opo&ntail; his clothyng.  &amp; &thorn;ai
&thorn;at saw hy&mtail; thought at &thorn;er was ij sonnys, one at
schane o&ntail; hy&mtail;, &amp; a noder at shane oute of hy&mtail;;
&amp; so &thorn;ai tuke a grete ferdness for hy&mtail;, to so
meku&llbar; at &thorn;ai sai&dtail; o&ntail; &thorn;is maner of wise;
"hedertowar&dtail; we dred yone ma&ntail; bod as a ma&ntail;, bod fro
hyne-furt&hbar; we sa&llbar; wurshup&ptail; hy&mtail; abow&ntail;
&thorn;e natur of ma&ntail;"; vnto so meku&llbar; &thorn;at,
&thorn;urg&hbar; &thorn;e adulacio&ntail; of &thorn;e pepy&llbar;, he
supposi&dtail; hy&mtail; selfe more for to be a god &thorn;a&ntail; a
ma&ntail;.  So o&ntail; a day as he satt vnder-nethe a tre, he was war
of ane owle syttand in &thorn;e tre abow&ntail; his hea&dtail;; and
&thorn;erby he wiste &thorn;at he sulde sone dy, &amp; sai&dtail;;
"Lo! surs, I, &thorn;at a&mtail; your lor&dtail;, mo&ntail; now dy."
For he knew be &thorn;e sight of &thorn;is owle, &thorn;at he sulde dy
with-in v dayes after.  And onone he was smyty&ntail; with seknes, and
v dayes wormes knew hy&mtail; so in his bowels &thorn;at at &thorn;e
laste he <NOTE ID="P68.N1">MS. de.</NOTE> expire&dtail; &amp; dye&dtail;.



<PB N="69">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> LXXXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Augustinus.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;er was a ma&ntail; &thorn;at
had a grete deuocio&ntail; vnto Saynt Austi&ntail;.  &amp; o&ntail; a
tyme he come vnto a monk &thorn;at kepi&dtail; Saynt Austy&ntail;
shry&ntail;, &amp; gaff hy&mtail; a grete dele of money, &amp; besoght
hy&mtail; to giff hy&mtail; a fyngre of Saynt Augusty&ntail;.  And
&thorn;is monke [tuke] a noder dead mans fynger &amp; wappi&dtail; it
in a sylke&ntail; clothe, &amp; gaff hy&mtail; it &amp; tolde
hy&mtail; &thorn;at it was Saynt Austy&ntail; fynger.  And he tuke it
with grete reuerens, &amp; alway wurschippi&dtail; it als deuotelie as
he cuthe, &amp; wolde putt it to his mouthe, his ey&ntail; &amp; vnto
his breste.  So almighti God, seyng &thorn;e fait&hbar; of &thorn;is
ma&ntail;, als wele mercifullie as mervaluslie, gaff vnto &thorn;is
ma&ntail; a fynger of Saynt Austy&ntail;.  And he went home
&thorn;erwith in-to his contret&hbar;; &amp; &thorn;er it di&dtail;
grete meracles, vnto so meku&llbar; at &thorn;e fame &thorn;erof come
vnto &thorn;e monasterie &thorn;er Saynt Austy&ntail; was
shryny&dtail;.  And &thorn;e Abbott examyn&dtail; &thorn;is monke
&thorn;erof, &amp; he sai&dtail; at it was bod a dede mans fynger at
he gaff hy&mtail;, &amp; not Saynt Austyns.  And &thorn;e Abbott &amp;
his brethir oppyn&dtail; his fertir &amp; luki&dtail;, &amp;
fan&dtail; &thorn;at a fynger of his was away.  &amp; whe&ntail;
&thorn;e abbott knew &thorn;e treut&hbar;, he putt &thorn;is monke
oute of his offes, &amp; punysshi&dtail; hy&mtail; grevuslie for
&thorn;at at he had done.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XC.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Augustinus.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Whe&ntail; Saynt Austy&ntail; liffi&dtail;, vppo&ntail; a tyme as
he satt redan&dtail; o&ntail; a buke, he was war of a fen&dtail;
beran&dtail; a grete buke in hys armys.  And Saynt Austy&ntail; <NOTE ID="P69.N1">Austy&ntail;, <HI REND="i">omitted and added above the line</HI>.</NOTE> adiuri&dtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; chargi&dtail;
hy&mtail; o&ntail; Goddis behalfe at he sulde te&llbar; hy&mtail;
whatt was wretty&ntail; in &thorn;at buke. &amp; he sai&dtail;
&thorn;er was wretty&ntail; mens syns. &amp; Saynt Austy&ntail;
chargi&dtail; &thorn;at [fend], &amp; &thorn;er war wrette&ntail; any
of his syns, &thorn;at he sulde latt hy&mtail; se &thorn;aim, at he
myght rede &thorn;aim. &amp; he shewi&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;e buke,
&amp; he cuthe fyn&dtail; nothyng &thorn;er wrette&ntail; of hy&mtail;
selfe, bod at a tyme he had forgette&ntail; to say his evynsong. &amp;
he commaundi&dtail; &thorn;is fen&dtail; &thorn;at he sul&dtail; abide
&thorn;er sti&llbar; vnto he come agay&ntail;. &amp; he went into
&thorn;e kur&ktee;, &amp; devoutelie say&dtail; his comply&ntail;
&amp; divers other gude orysons &


<PB N="70">

prayers, &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; he come agay&ntail; &amp; chargi&dtail;
&thorn;is fende to latt hy&mtail; se &thorn;at place agay&ntail; in
&thorn;e buke.  And &thorn;is fen&dtail; turny&dtail; &thorn;is buke
ouer &amp; ouer &amp; soght it, bod he cut&hbar; not fynde nothyng bod
a voyde place.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he was wrothe, &amp; sai&dtail;
vnto Saynt Austy&ntail;; "&thorn;ou hase fowlie deseyvi&dtail; me.  Me
forthynkis now at evur I shewi&dtail; the my buke, for be &thorn;e
vertue of &thorn;i prayer &thorn;ou hase done away &thorn;i
sy&ntail;."  And with &thorn;is he wanysschi&dtail; away &amp; was
confusi&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XCI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ad-huc de Sancto Augustino.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;er was a womma&ntail; &thorn;at
myster&dtail; cownce&llbar;, &amp; sho come vnto Saynt Austy&ntail;
&amp; fande hy&mtail; at his studie.  And sho come vnto hy&mtail;
&amp; salusi&dtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; he wol&dtail; nowder luke
o&ntail; hir nor ansswer hur.  And sho stude sti&llbar; &amp; vmthoght
hur, &amp; trowi&dtail; &thorn;at for his halynes he wol&dtail; not
behol&dtail; a wommans face.  And sho come ner hy&mtail; an&dtail;
tol&dtail; hy&mtail; hur eran&dtail;, and he wolde not ansswe&rtail;
hur nor als mekle as ans move hy&mtail;.  And whe&ntail; sho saw
&thorn;is, sho went away fro hy&mtail; with grete sorow &amp; hevynes.
And o&ntail; &thorn;e mor&ntail; after, whe&ntail; he had sai&dtail;
his mes &amp; &thorn;e same womma&ntail; was &thorn;er-att, after
&thorn;e sacryng-tyme sho was ravisshi&dtail; in hur spyritt, and sho
thoght &thorn;at sho was afo&rtail; &thorn;e iugement of almighti
Go&dtail;; and &thorn;er, as sho thoght, sho saw Saynt Austy&ntail;,
faste disputan&dtail; of &thorn;e ioy of &thorn;e holie
Trinytie. &amp; as hur thoght, &thorn;er was a voyse at sai&dtail;
vnto hur; "whe&ntail; at &thorn;ou come vnto Saynt Austy&ntail;,
o&ntail; &thorn;is maner of wyse he was disputan&dtail; of &thorn;e
ioy of &thorn;e holie Trynytie; and &thorn;at he thynkys o&ntail; wele
enog&hbar;.  Bod go now vnto hy&mtail; boldlie, &amp; &thorn;ou
sha&llbar; fyn&dtail; hy&mtail; meke enog&hbar;, and he sa&llbar; giff
&thorn;e gude cownce&llbar;." &amp; sho did so; &amp; he harde hur
with gude wi&llbar; &amp; gaff hur his beste cownce&llbar;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XCII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ad-huc de Sancto Augustino.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Som tyme &thorn;er was a ma&ntail; &thorn;at was ravisshi&dtail;
in his spiritt, &amp; he saw many Saynttis in grete ioy; &amp; emangis
a&llbar; o&thorn;er hy&mtail; thoght &thorn;at he cuthe not se Saynt
Austy&ntail;.  And he spyrri&dtail; one of &thorn;e

<PB N="71">

Saynttis whar Saynt Austy&ntail; was, and he ansswer&dtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Saynt Austy&ntail; is in a hy place;
&thorn;er he is disputan&dtail; of &thorn;e ioy of &thorn;e holie
Trinytie.  Thus me&ntail; may Se &thorn;at he is a holie Saynt."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XCIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Avis.  Avium Vanitas siue ludus grauiter punitur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Petrus Clunacensis <NOTE ID="P71.N1">MS. Climacensis.</NOTE> tellis how som tyme
&thorn;er was a knyght &thorn;at was in purgatorie, whilk &thorn;at
was a gude ma&ntail; &amp; luffid wele for to herber pure fol&ktee;;
bod whils he liffi&dtail; he had a grete delectacio&ntail; to layke
with fewlis; and whe&ntail; he was purgi&dtail; in purgatorie of
a&llbar; his o&thorn;er synnys, &thorn;at for &thorn;is sy&ntail;
&thorn;er come evur vnto hy&mtail; a thyng like a burde, &amp;
gretelie turment hy&mtail;. et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XCIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Avis oratio est exaudita aliquando.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a bur&dtail; &thorn;at
was lerny&dtail; to speke.  So o&ntail; a tyme sho flow away in
&thorn;e feldis, &amp; &thorn;e Goshalk sewi&dtail; after hur &amp;
wol&dtail; hafe kylli&dtail; hur.  And whe&ntail; sho saw hy&mtail;
co&mtail;, as sho was lerny&dtail; at home, sho bega&ntail; to cry,
&amp; say&dtail;; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sancte Thoma ! adiuua me
!</FOREIGN> A ! Saynt Thomas, helpe me!"  And onone &thorn;is goshalk
fe&llbar; dow&ntail; dea&dtail;, and &thorn;is bur&dtail;
esskapi&dtail; &amp; had none har&mtail;.  Lo ! surs, what vertue it
is to ca&llbar; o&ntail; Saynt Thomas, martir of Cantyrbery, in any
tribulacio&ntail; !


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XCV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Baptismus in forma debita debet celebrari.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> The Cronycles tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a bisshop&ptail;
of Arryans <NOTE ID="P71.N2">Harl. MS. episcopus arrianus.</NOTE> , and o&ntail; a tyme he
baptisi&dtail; a ma&ntail; &thorn;at hight Barba.  And he sai&dtail;
in &thorn;is maner of wise; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Baptizo te, Barba,
in nomine patris per filium, in spiritu sancto per filium et spiritum
sanctum,</FOREIGN>" to &thorn;e purpos &thorn;at he wol&dtail; shew
whilk of &thorn;aim was leste.  And sodanlie &thorn;e watir was away,
and he &thorn;at sulde hafe bene crysten&dtail; ra&ntail; vnto
&thorn;e kir&ktee;, &amp; was cristen&dtail; &thorn;er.





<PB N="72">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XCVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Balliuus non debet poni in officio pauper vel
auarus.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius <NOTE ID="P72.N1">MS. We rede how &thorn;at Valerius, whe&ntail;, &amp;c.</NOTE> .  We rede how &thorn;at whe&ntail;
&thorn;er was a varyans emang &thorn;e senaturs of Rome, whethir of ij
me&ntail; at was ordand &thorn;erto sulde be sent for a specia&llbar;
eran&dtail; vnto &thorn;er capta&ntail;, So &thorn;ai vmthoght
&thorn;aim at &thorn;ai wol&dtail; aske cownce&llbar; att Supercipius
<NOTE ID="P72.N2"><HI REND="i">For</HI> Scipio.</NOTE> Affricanus, at was a lernyd ma&ntail; &amp;
dwelte emang &thorn;aim.  And so &thorn;ai dy&dtail;, &amp; &thorn;ai
a&llbar; abade of his ansswer.  And whe&ntail; he saw &thorn;ies ij
me&ntail;, of whilk &thorn;e tone sulde be sent furt&hbar; &thorn;is
message, he consydur&dtail; at &thorn;e tone of &thorn;aim was pure
&amp; covatus, &amp; &thorn;e toder ryche &amp; sparan&dtail; &amp;
bod a chynche, [&] he sayd vnto &thorn;e senaturs in &thorn;is maner
of wyse; "Me plesis not at nowder of &thorn;ies sulde be sent
&thorn;is message; ffor &thorn;e tane of &thorn;aim hase noght, and no
maner of &thorn;ing is enog&hbar; vnto &thorn;e toder; &amp;
&thorn;erfo&rtail; suc&hbar; me&ntail; sulde be no baillays, nor go no
messagies."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XCVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Balliuorum frequens mutacio non est vtilis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how o&ntail; a tyme Tyberius Cesar aski&dtail; Josephus
whi he wol&dtail; not change ofte his Baillays &amp; his servandis,
[&] he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail; &thorn;at he
wol&dtail; spare &thorn;e peple; ffor baillays &amp; servandis
&thorn;at er long in offes hase ans enog&hbar;, &amp; wi&llbar; not
a&llbar;-way be gaderhan&dtail; vnto &thorn;er selfe; &amp; euer
&thorn;ai &thorn;at er putt in of new er gredye, &amp; gaders samen
vnto &thorn;erselfe a&llbar; &thorn;at evur &thorn;ai may.  "And
&thorn;is," he sai&dtail;, "I ca&ntail; shew you be exsample of a
ma&ntail; &thorn;at was wowndi&dtail; &amp; lay in &thorn;e way.  And
a grete multitude of fleis come vnto his wown&dtail; &amp; satt
&thorn;er-o&ntail; &amp; bate hy&mtail;; &amp; he was so sore
&thorn;at he myght nott remew &thorn;aim away.  So &thorn;er come a
ma&ntail; &amp; fan&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; had compassio&ntail;
o&ntail; hy&mtail;, and onone he drafe away &thorn;ies fleis &amp;
killi&dtail; &thorn;aim at satt vppo&ntail; his wown&dtail;.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e wowndi&dtail; ma&ntail; sai&dtail; vnto
hy&mtail; o&ntail; &thorn;is maner of wise; 'Thow hase done me ane
i&llbar; tur&ntail;, ffor &thorn;e fleis at &thorn;ou hase slay&ntail;
&amp; donge&ntail; away war now filli&dtail; with my blude, &amp;
&thorn;erfo&rtail; evur &thorn;e langer &thorn;ai wold hafe
bytte&ntail; me &thorn;e les.  Bod &thorn;e fleis &thorn;at wi&llbar;
co&mtail; vnto my wown&dtail; of new, wi&llbar; bite me war





<PB N="73">

&amp; &thorn;ai wol&dtail; hafe done; &amp; &thorn;erfo&rtail; me had
levur at &thorn;ai had byddin sty&llbar;, [&thorn;an] &thorn;att
othe&rtail; &thorn;at er hongry sul&dtail; co&mtail; &amp; pryk me war
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai di&dtail;.'"  et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XCVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Balliuus hic iniuste iudicans alibi
iudicabitur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Libro de Dono Timoris,' how &thorn;at <NOTE ID="P73.N1">MS. &thorn;an.</NOTE> o&ntail; a tyme a philosophur, whe&ntail; he saw a
thief led to be hange&dtail; with a baillay, this philosophur
sai&dtail;; "Lo! &thorn;e gretter thieff ledis &thorn;e les thieff to
hangyng."  And so it happens oft sithes now-of-dayes; ffor commonlie
&thorn;e lytle &thorn;ieff is hanged, Bod his resettyr &amp; his
mayntynnuer is savi&dtail;.  et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> XCIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Balliui frequenter munera recipiunt sed non
faciunt quod promittunt.</FOREIGN></HEAD> <P> Som tyme &thorn;er was a
ballay of a grete lordshu&ptail;, &thorn;at made a feste grete
an&dtail; costios vnto &thorn;e weddyng of a so&ntail; of his.  So
&thorn;er was a tenan&dtail; in &thorn;e lordshup, &thorn;at had a
grete cauce &thorn;er in &thorn;e cowrte to be determyn&dtail;
befo&rtail; &thorn;e Stewer&dtail;.  And agay&ntail; &thorn;is baillay
so&ntail; sulde be wed, he come vnto &thorn;e baillay &amp;
sai&dtail;; "Sur, I pray you stand for me befo&rtail; &thorn;e
stewer&dtail; in &thorn;e courte, at I may hafe ryght, &amp; I
sa&llbar; giff you a fatt cow to your so&ntail; weddyng." &amp; he
tuke &thorn;e cow &amp; say&dtail; &thorn;at he sul&dtail;.  So
&thorn;is mans aduersarie harde te&llbar; here-off, and he come vnto
&thorn;is baillay wyfe &amp; gaff hur a fatt ox, &amp; besoght hur at
sho wol&dtail; labur vnto hur husband &thorn;at he wol&dtail; ansswer
for hy&mtail; agayns&curl; his aduersarie in &thorn;e courte.  And sho
tuke &thorn;e cow &amp; labur&dtail; vnto hur husban&dtail;, &amp; he
promysi&dtail; hur at he sul&dtail; fulfi&llbar; hur entent.  So bothe
&thorn;e parties come into &thorn;e courte afo&rtail; &thorn;e
Stewer&dtail;, &amp; put furt&hbar; per cawsis, &amp; &thorn;e baillay
stude sti&llbar; &amp; spak not a wurd for nowdur of &thorn;aim, vnto
so meky&llbar; at he &thorn;at gaff &thorn;e ox was like to be
casty&ntail;.  And &thorn;e ma&ntail; &thorn;at gaff hy&mtail; &thorn;e ox
sai&dtail; vnto &thorn;e baillay; "Sur, whi spekis nott &thorn;e ox?"
and &thorn;e baillay



<PB N="74">

ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "ffor suthe!
&thorn;e ox may nott speke, ffor &thorn;e cow is so fayr &amp; so gude
&thorn;at sho wi&llbar; nott latt hy&mtail; speke."

</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Hec fabula valet ad quoscumque iudices, et quo&dtail;

munera peruertunt iudicium, et quo&dtail; mulieres

sepius optinent magis quam viri.</FOREIGN></ITEM>


</LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> C.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Basilius.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how som tyme &thorn;er was a holie hermett, &thorn;at saw
&thorn;is Basilius o&ntail; a tyme walk in his pontifica&llbar;
abbett; &amp; he &thorn;oght dedey&ntail;, &amp; had a dispyte
&thorn;eratt, &amp; demyd in hy&mtail; &thorn;at he had a
delectacio&ntail; &amp; a pride in &thorn;is clothyng.  So sodanly
&thorn;er come a voyce vnto &thorn;is hermett, &amp; sayd o&ntail;
&thorn;is wise; "Thow hase more delectacio&ntail; in grapyng of
&thorn;i catt tayle, &thorn;a&ntail; Basilius hase in his gay
pontifica&llbar; clothyng."  et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Basilius Iuuenem a diabolo eripuit.  Supra de amore.</FOREIGN></ITEM>

<ITEM><FOREIGN>Basilius mortem Iuliani apostate procurauit.  Infra

de vindicta.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Basilius oracione sua mortem suam prolongari fecit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede &thorn;at whe&ntail; Saynt Basy&llbar; was seke &amp; drew
nere vnto his deadwar&dtail;, he commandi&dtail; to gar feche vnto
hy&mtail; o&ntail; &thorn;at hight Josep&hbar;, &thorn;at was a Iew,
whome &thorn;at he had sene be reuelacio&ntail; at sulde be a crysten
ma&ntail;.  And &thorn;is Josep&hbar; was passan&dtail; connyng in
grapyng of &thorn;er vaynys at war seke, and he come vnto hy&mtail;
&amp; feli&dtail; his <NOTE ID="P74.N1"><HI REND="i">After</HI> his, fel, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> vaynys.  And Saynt
Basi&llbar; aski&dtail; hy&mtail; how hy&mtail; thoght of hy&mtail;
<!-- P74.N2 --> , &amp; he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
say&dtail; <NOTE ID="P74.N2">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats, from</HI> &, <HI REND="i">to</HI> sayd.</NOTE> ; "Sur, &thorn;ou sa&llbar; dye or
&thorn;e so&ntail; sett."  And &thorn;a&ntail; Saynt Bas&llbar; say&dtail;;
"what &amp; I dye nott or to-mor&ntail;?"  And &thorn;is Jew
sai&dtail;; "Sur, &thorn;at may not be; for &thorn;ou erte bod a dede
ma&ntail;; for vnnethis wi&llbar; &thorn;i life &amp; &thorn;i saule
byde samen ane how&rtail;."  Tha&ntail; Saynt Basi&llbar; sayd vnto
hy&mtail;; "what wi&llbar; &thorn;ou





<PB N="75">

say &amp; I liff vnto to-mor&ntail; at vj of &thorn;e clo&ktee;?"
And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is Jew ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
sai&dtail;; "and &thorn;ou liff, I wote wele &thorn;at I mo&ntail;
dye."  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e Saynt ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "fforsuth &thorn;ou sais suthe, for
&thorn;ou sa&llbar; dye fro sy&ntail; and liff vnto Cryste."  And
&thorn;e Jew ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "I
wote what &thorn;ou says, and if &thorn;ou liff so sa&llbar; I do."
Tha&ntail; &thorn;is holie ma&ntail; made his prayer vnto almyghtti
Go&dtail; at his life mott be eky&dtail;, at &thorn;at ma&ntail; mott
be savi&dtail;.  So &thorn;is Jew went his wayes &amp; come
agay&ntail; o&ntail; &thorn;e mor&ntail;, and fan&dtail; &thorn;is
holie ma&ntail; liffan&dtail;.  And he fe&llbar; dow&ntail; o&ntail;
his kneis and wurshuppi&dtail; crystemmens God&dtail;.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is holie ma&ntail;, yitt als i&llbar; as he
myght, rase u&ptail; &amp; went vnto &thorn;e kur&ktee;, &amp;
baptisi&dtail; hy&mtail; his aw&ntail; handis.  And whe&ntail; he had
done, he went home agay&ntail; &amp; laye&dtail; hy&mtail; dow&ntail;;
and abowte none of &thorn;e same day he passy&dtail; vnto almighti
Go&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Basilius veniam pro peccatis mulieri impetrauit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how &thorn;er was a womma&ntail; &thorn;at wrate a&llbar;
hur synnys in a by&llbar;; and emangis a&llbar; o&thorn;er sho wrate a
grete sy&ntail; at sho had done, &amp; &thorn;is by&llbar; sho
delyver&dtail; vnto Saynt Basy&llbar; &amp; prayed hy&mtail; to pray
for hur &thorn;at hur synnys myght be forgiffe&ntail; hur.  And he
sett hy&mtail; dow&ntail; o&ntail; his kneis &amp; made his prayers
for hur.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he oppyn&dtail; &thorn;is by&llbar;, &amp;
&thorn;is womma&ntail; with hy&mtail;, and a&llbar; hur synys war
away, out-take &thorn;is grete sy&ntail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; sho
praye&dtail; hy&mtail;, &thorn;at as he with his prayers had
gette&ntail; hur forgifnes of a&llbar; hur oder synys, at he
wol&dtail; so pray for hur att sho mott be forgiffe&ntail; of
&thorn;at sy&ntail;.  And he bad hur go away fro&mtail; hy&mtail;,
&amp; sayde he was a synner &amp; myster&dtail; forgyfnes of his
sy&ntail; als wele as sho di&dtail;.  And sho wolde nott away, bod
abade sti&llbar; crian&dtail; o&ntail; hy&mtail; to pray for hyr <NOTE ID="P75.N1">MS. hy&mtail;.</NOTE> .  And he bad hur go vnto Saynt Effre&mtail;, &amp;
he myght grawnt hur at sho aski&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; sho come att
Saynt Effre&mtail; &amp; tol&dtail; hy&mtail;, he sent hur agay&ntail;
vnto Saynt Basy&llbar; &amp; bad hur go fast, at he wer nott dead or
sho come.  And whe&ntail; sho come, me&ntail; was beran&dtail;
hy&mtail; vnto his grafe.  And &thorn;a&ntail; sho bega&ntail; to cry
&amp; sai&dtail;; "a&llbar;-myghti God deme betwix &thorn;e &amp; me;
for whe&ntail; &thorn;ou might hafe prayed for me, &thorn;ou sent me



<PB N="76">

vnto a noder."  And sho keste &thorn;is bi&llbar; vpp[on] his bere,
&amp; with-in a while sho tuke it agay&ntail; &amp; opyn&dtail; it,
and fande a&llbar; hir sy&ntail; clene done away oute &thorn;eroff.

</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Bede presbiteri.  Infra de predicacione.
I.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Bellum.  Bellare non expedit sine magna
causa.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how &thorn;at Cesar Augustus, &thorn;at was moste noble in
batayle, euer denyed to take bate&llbar; o&ntail; han&dtail; bod if it
war mo&rtail; for hope of avayntage &thorn;an <NOTE ID="P76.N1">MS. &thorn;at.</NOTE>
drede of har&mtail;.  For he saide &thorn;at in were a little profett
myght nott make amendis vnto &thorn;e grete har&mtail; &thorn;at
commys of feghtyng; "ffor," as he sai&dtail;, "&amp; a ma&ntail;
fysshid with a huke a&llbar; of gol&dtail; &amp; gatt a little
fyss&hbar;, &amp; at &thorn;e laste his huke war broke&ntail; away,
&thorn;e takyng of &thorn;at fyssc&hbar; myght not make amendis vnto
&thorn;e los &thorn;at he had of his golde&ntail; huke."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Bellantes debent esse cauti et experti.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Justinus tellis how &thorn;at kyng Alexander chose not to go with
hy&mtail; in his weris yong me&ntail;, nor &thorn;aim &thorn;at was in
&thorn;e <NOTE ID="P76.N2">MS. &thorn;er.</NOTE> flow&rtail; of &thorn;er youthe[d] <NOTE ID="P76.N3">MS. youther.</NOTE> , bode alde knyght[is] &thorn;at war wise, &amp; had
vsyd batels &amp; cuthe gyff gude cownce&llbar;, at had bene in weris
with his fadur.  And suche me&ntail; he trusti&dtail; for gude
knyghtis &amp; made &thorn;aim maisters of his chyvalrie.  And he
sayde &thorn;at in batay&llbar; a ma&ntail; sulde nott &thorn;ink of
cowardness nor of fleyng away, bod rather of havyng victorye, and at a
ma&ntail; sul&dtail; giff no truste vnto his fete, bod vnto his
wapy&ntail; &thorn;at was in his han&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Bella procurat Diabolus frequenter.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; &thorn;e grete Emperour
Henrie at a grete cetie hel&dtail; his whisson-tyde, a little
befo&rtail; mes, whe&ntail; &thorn;ai sett burdis in &thorn;e
ha&llbar;, &thorn;er bega&ntail; a grete fray, so &thorn;at grete
blude was shed betwix &thorn;e chamberlayns of &thorn;e
archbysshop&ptail; &amp; &thorn;e Abbott







<PB N="77">

of Sulde&ntail;; and a&llbar; for ather of &thorn;aim wol&dtail; hafe
sett &thorn;er lordis sete next &thorn;e Emperour sete.  For &thorn;e
Abbott of Sulda&ntail; fyndy&ntail; vnto &thorn;e emperour whe&ntail;
hy&mtail; mysters, LX Ml of harnessi&dtail; me&ntail;.  And
he&rtail;for he had a privalege of old tyme grawnti&dtail;, &thorn;at
he sulde att grete festys sytt nexte &thorn;e Emperour o&ntail; his
right hand.  So &thorn;e partis onone war stilli&dtail; &amp; &thorn;e
mes bego&ntail;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai war att &thorn;e laste end
of &thorn;e sequens, &amp; had songe&ntail; &thorn;is vers; " <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">hunc diem gloriosum fecisti</FOREIGN>"; onone a&llbar;
&thorn;at was in &thorn;e kurk har&dtail; a voyce say &thorn;us; "
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">hunc diem bellicosum Ego ffeci.</FOREIGN>" And in
confusio&ntail; of &thorn;e fen&dtail;, &thorn;e Emperour garte
begy&ntail; &thorn;e sequens agay&ntail; with grete deuocio&ntail;;
&amp; a&llbar; &thorn;e meate at was ordan&dtail; for hy&mtail; &amp;
his meneya, he garte dele it furth-with vnto pure me&ntail; for Goddis
sake.  et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Bellare possunt religiosi cum armis 
<NOTE ID="P77.N1">Latin MSS., sine armis.</NOTE>  in spe diuini

auxilij, defendendo ius summum.  Infra de

Religioso.</FOREIGN></ITEM>

<ITEM><FOREIGN>Bellare nesciunt homines concordes.  Infra de

Concordia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>

<ITEM><FOREIGN>Bellant eciam aliquando post mortem inimici. [ 
<NOTE ID="P77.N2">Reference from Lat. MSS.</NOTE> Infra

de Odio.]</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Beneficia impensa eciam bruta animalia
recognoscunt.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Damianus tellis how so&mtail; tyme merchandis of Venys wer
opo&ntail; &thorn;e se, &amp; gretlie vexi&dtail; with stormys, so at
&thorn;ai wyste neuer whar &thorn;ai war.  So att &thorn;e laste
&thorn;ai fan&dtail; ane Ile in &thorn;e see, &amp; &thorn;er
&thorn;ai landi&dtail; &amp; tuke &thorn;aim ffressch water &amp; wud,
&amp; suc&hbar; as &thorn;aim nedi&dtail;.  And &thorn;ai cuthe fynd
no creatur &thorn;er bod wilde bestis.  So at &thorn;e laste, as a
meneya of &thorn;aim went vp in a cragg to gett &thorn;aim wu&dtail;,
&thorn;ai fande how &thorn;at a drago&ntail; had take&ntail; a
lyo&ntail; &amp; wol&dtail; hafe devowri&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp;
drawe&ntail; hy&mtail; into his de&ntail;; and &thorn;ai fe&llbar;
o&ntail; &thorn;is drago&ntail; with &thorn;er wapens &amp; kyl&dtail;
hy&mtail;, &amp; delyver&dtail; &thorn;e lyo&ntail; &amp; lete
hy&mtail; go.  And evur-ilk day als lang as &thorn;ai lay &thorn;er,
&thorn;is lyo&ntail; was nott vnkyn&dtail;, &amp; he broght &thorn;aim
owder a swyne or a schepe new slay&ntail;, a little





<PB N="78">

befor none of &thorn;e day, evy&ntail; in &thorn;e sky&ntail; as he
had take&ntail; itt.  Lo!  how frendlie ane vnresonable beste
rewardi&dtail; &thorn;aim &thorn;at di&dtail; hy&mtail; gude &amp;
savy&dtail; his lyfe.  et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Beneficia conferenda sunt Dignis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Seneca tellis &thorn;at he &thorn;at hase benefice in giffyng
sulde do as &thorn;ai do at playes at &thorn;e ba&llbar;; for &amp; a
ma&ntail; caste a ba&llbar; fro hy&mtail; to a noder, &amp; he to
hy&mtail; agay&ntail;, No doute, of patte&ntail; fro&mtail; &thorn;e
tone of &thorn;aim it wi&llbar; fa&llbar; vnto &thorn;e ert&hbar;.
Bod a gude player wi&llbar; vmwhile caste &thorn;e ba&llbar; ferrer
&amp; vmwhile nerrer, at he at is a gude player may play with
hy&mtail;.  Right so sulde it be betwix hy&mtail; &thorn;at giffis
&thorn;e benefis &amp; hy&mtail; &thorn;at takis it, for he &thorn;at
giffis it sul&dtail; se &thorn;at he &thorn;att he gaff it to war able
for to take it, &amp; kepe it fro &thorn;e erthe; &thorn;at is to
mene, &thorn;at he cuthe reule it to &thorn;e plesur of Go&dtail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Beneficia acquisita male malum exitum habent.  Infra

De Blasfemia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>

<ITEM><FOREIGN>Beneficia multa eciam prestat deus 
<NOTE ID="P78.N1">MS.<HI REND="i"> here repeats</HI>, eciam.</NOTE>  inuitis.  Infra

Inuitus.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Benedictio.  Benedicendus est cibus et potus
antequam sumatur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how &thorn;at &thorn;er was so&mtail; tyme a holie
mayde&ntail; in a monasterie of virgyns.  And o&ntail; a day as sho
went into hur garthy&ntail;, sho saw ane herbe &thorn;at is
calli&dtail; letes, and sho desyri&dtail; to eate &thorn;ero&ntail;
gretelie; &amp; sho tuke &thorn;erof &amp; blissi&dtail; it nott &amp;
ete &thorn;er-o&ntail;, for sho forgatt at bliss it.  And onone sho
was take&ntail; with a fen&dtail; &amp; fe&llbar; dow&ntail;; and
&thorn;er come vnto hur a holie ma&ntail; &thorn;at hyght Equirius,
&amp; purseyvi&dtail; &thorn;at a fen&dtail; was in hur, &amp;
commandi&dtail; hy&mtail; to go oute of hur.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is
fen&dtail; crye&dtail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "Allas! whatt hafe I done?  I
satt opo&ntail; &thorn;e letes, &amp; sho come &amp; tuke me v&ptail;
&amp; bate me."  &amp; vnnethis for a&llbar; &thorn;is holie mans
commandment, wal&dtail; he go oute of hur.  et c&curl;.



<PB N="79">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Benedicti Abbatis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Gregur tellis how o&ntail; a tyme opo&ntail; pass&hbar; day
&thorn;er was a gude holie preste, &amp; ordan&dtail; hy&mtail; bettyr
meate in wurshu&ptail; of &thorn;e day.  And our Lorde apperi&dtail;
vnto hy&mtail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Thow ordans delicious meattis for
&thorn;i selfe, &amp; my servand Benett, in such a place, suffres
grete honger."  And onone &thorn;is preste rase &amp; tuke meatt with
hy&mtail; &amp; soght hy&mtail;.  And at &thorn;e laste with grete
labur &amp; sekyng he fand hy&mtail;, &amp; sayd vnto hy&mtail;;
"Ryse, &amp; lat vs take vs meate &amp; drynke to-gedur, ffor
&thorn;is day hafe I broght &thorn;e meatt, and it is passc&hbar;
day."  And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;, "I knaw
wele &thorn;at &thorn;is day is passc&hbar; day, ffor cauce att
&thorn;ou erte comme&ntail;."  And he had bene so lang oute of mans
felaschu&ptail; &thorn;at he ha&dtail; clene forgette&ntail; what day
att pass&hbar; day was.  Tha&ntail; &thorn;is preste said vnto
hy&mtail;; "fforsuthe &thorn;is day is &thorn;e solempnitie of
&thorn;e resurreccio&ntail; of our Lor&dtail;, and &thorn;erfo&rtail;
as &thorn;is day it acordis nott for &thorn;e to lyff in abstinens;
ffor I was sent vnto the and bedy&ntail; bryng &thorn;e meatt."  And
&thorn;an &thorn;ai bothe thanki&dtail; almyghti God &amp; say&dtail;
&thorn;er prayers, &amp; tuke &thorn;aim meat to-gedur in
wurshu&ptail; of &thorn;e resurrecio&ntail; of our Lor&dtail;.  et
c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Benedictus Diabolum expulit a iuuene.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a monk &thorn;at hight
Gregorie, and in no wise he myght nott lang abyde att dyvyne serves,
nor at his prayers, bod evur whe&ntail; his other brether say&dtail;
&thorn;er prayers or &thorn;er serves, onone he went furt&hbar; and
made hy&mtail; to do so&mtail; other labur.  So o&ntail; a tyme his
Abbott, Saynt Benett, was war of a lytle blak boy led hy&mtail; oute
be &thorn;e shurte of his clothis.  So o&ntail; a day whe&ntail; he
went furt&hbar;, &amp; &thorn;is lurda&ntail; led hy&mtail; oute,
&thorn;a&ntail; Saynt Benett strake &thorn;is yong monk with a wan&dtail;
&amp; bad hy&mtail; go in agay&ntail;, &amp; abide in his prayers as
his other brethir di&dtail;.  &amp; so for fer&dtail; of &thorn;is
strake of Saynt Benett, &thorn;is fende at was in a blak boy lyknes
durst nevur after co&mtail; &amp; feche hy&mtail; furthe.  et c&curl;.

<PB N="80">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Benedictus spiritum elacionis a iuuene expulit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Gregur tellis &thorn;at o&ntail; ane evynyng whe&ntail;
&thorn;is holie ma&ntail; was at his supper, &thorn;er stude
befo&rtail; hy&mtail; a yong gentylma&ntail; &thorn;at come of a hy
kynri&dtail;, &amp; helde &thorn;e candy&llbar;.  So &thorn;is yong
ma&ntail; was prowde, &amp; &thorn;oght scor&ntail; &thorn;at he sulde
hol&dtail; &thorn;e candy&llbar;, &amp; say&dtail; with-in hy&mtail;
selfe o&ntail; &thorn;is maner of wyse; "what is he &thorn;is at
syttis att supper &amp; I holde cande&llbar; vnto and duse suc&hbar;
serves?  what a&mtail; I &thorn;at I sulde seryff hy&mtail;
&thorn;is?" and &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is holie ma&ntail; say&dtail;
vnto hy&mtail;; "Bruther, Cros &amp; mark &thorn;i harte! what is
&thorn;at att &thorn;ou spekis vnto &thorn;i selfe?" and he
calli&dtail; one of his brethir &amp; commanddi&dtail; hy&mtail; to
take &thorn;e candi&llbar; fro hy&mtail; &amp; halde it, &amp;
commawndi&dtail; hy&mtail; to go vnto hys chambre &amp; take his
reste.  &amp; &thorn;is yong ma&ntail; was so asshamy&dtail; &thorn;at
he knew his thoght, &thorn;at neuer after he was prowde nor thoght
disdeingne to done hy&mtail; serves.  et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Barnardus.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how o&ntail; a tyme as Saynt Barnard was prechan&dtail;,
and a&llbar; &thorn;at was aboute hy&mtail; lythed hy&mtail; with gude
deuocio&ntail;, &thorn;er entred into his harte suche a
temptacio&ntail; &thorn;at, as hy&mtail; thoght, rownyd vnto hy&mtail;
&amp; sayde; "Behalde, &amp; se now how wele &thorn;ou prechis, &amp;
how gladlie &thorn;att &thorn;e pepu&llbar; heris &thorn;e, &amp; how
wyse and wyttie &thorn;ou erte calli&dtail; in &thorn;i prechyng!"
And &thorn;is holie ma&ntail;, felyng hy&mtail; selfe styrri&dtail;
with &thorn;is temptacio&ntail;, tarid a while in his sermo&ntail;,
and or he passyd any forther or made ane ende, he bega&ntail; to wax
hevy &amp; pensie for &thorn;is thoght.  And onone he was
comfurthi&dtail; &thorn;urg&hbar; &thorn;e helpe of a&llbar;myghti
Go&dtail;.  And privalie he ansswerd vnto &thorn;is temptacio&ntail;
in &thorn;is maner of wise; "&thorn;ou fals temptacio&ntail;! be the I
bega&ntail; nott, nor be the I sa&llbar; nott en&dtail;."  And
&thorn;a&ntail; he procedi&dtail; in his sermo&ntail; &amp; made a
gude ende.  And onone &thorn;is temptacio&ntail; recedid away, and he
had it nevur after.

<PB N="81">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ad-huc de Sancto Barnardo.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;at as Saynt Barnar&dtail; rade in
&thorn;e contrey, hy&mtail; happend to be harbard at a gude
husban&dtail; howse.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai had suppid, &thorn;is
husband sayd vnto hy&mtail;; "Sur, what aylis you at ye forsake
&thorn;e labur &thorn;at is in &thorn;is werl&dtail; &amp; gase vnto
religio&ntail;? for in your prayers ye may hafe als gude a thoght here
as &thorn;er."  So Saynt Barnard telli&dtail; hy&mtail; many cawsis,
&amp; at &thorn;e laste he thoght he wol&dtail; ouerco&mtail;
hy&mtail;, &amp; say&dtail;; "Go a little fro&mtail; vs, &amp; say
&thorn;i pater noster with a&llbar; &thorn;e entente &amp; gude
deuocio&ntail; at &thorn;ou ca&ntail;, &amp; if &thorn;ow end it &amp;
&thorn;inke of no noder &thorn;ing or &thorn;ou hase done, I sa&llbar;
giff &thorn;e my hors; &amp; beheste me be &thorn;e faythe of &thorn;i
bodie, &thorn;at &amp; &thorn;ou thyn&ktee; of any other &thorn;ing,
at &thorn;ou sa&llbar; te&llbar; me."  And &thorn;is husband was glad
&amp; grawnti&dtail; here-to, trowyng to wy&ntail; &thorn;is hors,
&amp; went a litle asyde, &amp; baldlie went in han&dtail; with his
pater noster &amp; sayde it.  &amp; whe&ntail; he wa[s] skantlie at
&thorn;e myddest &thorn;erof, a besy thoght smate in his harte, &amp;
&thorn;at was &thorn;is; &thorn;at &amp; he wa&ntail; &thorn;e hors,
whethur he sulde hafe &thorn;e sadle &amp; &thorn;e brydi&llbar; with
hy&mtail; or noght.  And &thorn;is done, with grete contricio&ntail;
he went vnto Saynt Barnard agay&ntail;, and tol&dtail; hy&mtail; what
&thorn;oght come in his mynde in &thorn;is prayer-saying: and
&thorn;us he had not &thorn;e hors.  &amp; fro thens furthe, he had
nevur presumpcio&ntail; in his mynde of his prayers-saying with-oute
temptacio&ntail; neuer afte&rtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ad-huc de Sancto Barnardo.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> On a tyme as Saynt Barnard come into Normundie, a womma&ntail;
come vnto hy&mtail; &amp; tolde hy&mtail; &thorn;at &thorn;e space of
vj yere sho was gretlie tempi&dtail; with a fen&dtail; to fa&llbar;
vnto lichorie, euer whe&ntail; sho was in hur be&dtail;.  And ay it
bad hur at sho sulde nott te&llbar; Saynt Barnard &thorn;eroff.  And
Saynt Barnar&dtail; gaff hur his staff, &amp; bad hur &thorn;at,
whe&ntail; sho went to bed, sho sulde lay itt in hur bedd by hur; and
sho did so.  &amp; onone he come, bod he myght not co&mtail; nere
&thorn;e bed&dtail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he thred hur, &amp; sai&dtail;
&thorn;at when Saynt Barnard was gone he

<PB N="82">

sulde venge hy&mtail; opo&ntail; hur.  &amp; o&ntail; &thorn;e
mor&ntail; sho went vnto Saynt Barnar&dtail; &amp; tol&dtail;
hy&mtail;; &amp; he garte ca&llbar; samen a&llbar; &thorn;e peple vnto
&thorn;e kur&ktee;, and commawndid &thorn;at ilk ma&ntail; sulde hafe
a candy&llbar; byrnand in his han&dtail;.  And with a&llbar;
&thorn;ase candels he cursi&dtail; &thorn;is fend &amp;
entirditi&dtail; hy&mtail;, & <NOTE ID="P82.N1">MS. gaff a commawndi&dtail;.</NOTE> commawndi&dtail;
&thorn;at he sulde neuer fro thens furt&hbar; co&mtail; att &thorn;is
womma&ntail; agay&ntail;.  And &thorn;us sho was delyver&dtail; fro
a&llbar; &thorn;is illusio&ntail; of &thorn;e fende.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Blasfemia in deum grauiter
punitur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Som tyme &thorn;er was a ma&ntail; &thorn;at had a so&ntail; of xv
yere age, whilk &thorn;at he luffyd passandlie wele, &amp; broght
hy&mtail; vp tenderlie.  And &thorn;is childe had in condicio&ntail;
&thorn;at whe&ntail; any thyng displesid hy&mtail;, onone he wolde
blasfeme &thorn;e name of Go&dtail;.  So &thorn;e pestelence come
&amp; tuke it, so &thorn;at it burd dye.  &amp; whe&ntail; he had
&thorn;e spottys &thorn;e fadur hel&dtail; hy&mtail; vp in his armys;
and &thorn;is childe saw wykkid spirittis co&mtail; vnto
hy&mtail;-war&dtail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "helpe fadur!"  And whe&ntail;
his fadur saw hy&mtail; quake for drede, he aski&dtail; hy&mtail; what
at he saw; &amp; he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;,
&thorn;at i&llbar; me&ntail; come vnto hy&mtail; &amp; wolde take
hy&mtail;; &amp; he bega&ntail; to blasfeme almyghti Go&dtail;, &amp;
with &thorn;att he swelte.
</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Blasfemus per oracionem eciam post mortem ad
penitenciam reuocatur.  Infra de Oracione.
ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Blasfemus visibiliter a deo punitur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Damianus tellis how &thorn;at in Burgundie &thorn;er was a proude
clerk &amp; a covatus.  So hy&mtail; happend, be power at was
gyffe&ntail; vnto hy&mtail;, to take wranguslie vnto hy&mtail; selfe
&thorn;e kurk of Saynt Maurys.  So o&ntail; a tyme as he har&dtail;
mes, in &thorn;e end of &thorn;e gospe&llbar; he har&dtail; &thorn;is
clauce re&dtail;; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Qui se humiliat exaltabitur,
et qui se exaltat humiliabitur,</FOREIGN>" [&] &thorn;is wrichid clerk
made a skor&ntail; &thorn;erat &amp; say&dtail; &thorn;at it was fals.
For he sai&dtail;, &amp; he had meki&dtail; hy&mtail; unto hys enmys,
he had not



<PB N="83">

had &thorn;e riches &amp; &thorn;e prophett of &thorn;at kur&ktee;.
And furt&hbar;-with a levynnyng like a swer&dtail; went in at &thorn;e
mouthe of hy&mtail; &thorn;at spak, as he was spekand, &amp; onone it
killy&dtail; hy&mtail;.  et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Aliquando blasfemus corporaliter punitur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Damianus tellis &thorn;at at Bolay&ntail; ij frendis at wer
gossops satt to-gedur samen at meate at a feste; and &thorn;ai war
servi&dtail; of a boyli&dtail; cok&ktee;.  &amp; &thorn;e tone tuke
his knyfe &amp; kutt it in sonder in pecis; &amp; he putt &thorn;eron
peper &amp; muster&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; he had done, &thorn;e toder
sayd vnto hy&mtail;; "Gosso&ptail;, &thorn;ou hase broke&ntail;
&thorn;is cok&ktee; so &thorn;at, &amp; Saynt Petur wolde nevur so,
it myght nevur co&mtail; samen agay&ntail;."  And the toder
ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Not now, &amp;
Saynt Petir, bod also &amp; Criste hy&mtail; selfe wol&dtail;
commawn&dtail;, &thorn;is Cok&ktee; sulde nevur ryse."  And onone as
he had say&dtail;, &thorn;is cok&ktee; starte vp&ptail; with his
fedurs o&ntail;, &amp; clappi&dtail; samen hys wengis &amp; krew;
&amp; &thorn;ai mot se clefe in his fedurs a&llbar; &thorn;e
liquo&rtail; at was putt o&ntail; hy&mtail;.  &amp; with &thorn;e
sprenclyng of his wengis, &thorn;e peper &amp; &thorn;e sauce light
vppo&ntail; bathe thies gosseps, &amp; with &thorn;at &thorn;ai wer
streke&ntail; with a lepre whilk hel&dtail; &thorn;aim vnto &thorn;er
lyvis en&dtail;, &amp; made ane en&dtail; of &thorn;aim.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Blasfemus aliquando statim vita
privatur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how o&ntail; a tyme ij me&ntail; playe&dtail; at
&thorn;e dyce, and whe&ntail; &thorn;e tane of &thorn;aim bega&ntail;
to lose, he bega&ntail; to wax wrathe with &thorn;e toder &amp; speke
grete wurdis, &amp; rauie &amp; flite with Go&dtail; for &thorn;at he
wa&ntail; nott.  And &thorn;e toder, whe&ntail; he har&dtail;
hy&mtail; flite with Go&dtail; &amp; speke grete wurdis, flate with
hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; bad hy&mtail; hol&dtail; his tong; &amp;
he wol&dtail; not, bod evur whe&ntail; he loste, blasfemy&dtail; owder
God or ou&rtail; Ladie.  So as &thorn;ai satt threpand &thorn;us,
&thorn;aim &thorn;oght &thorn;ai har&dtail; a voyce aboue &thorn;aim
&thorn;at say&dtail;; "I hafe suffre&dtail; hedur-towar&dtail; iniurie
&amp; wrong to be done vnto my selfe, bod I wi&llbar; nor may not
suffre no langer &thorn;e iniurie &amp; wrong done vnto my moder."
And onone he &thorn;is att laste, as he leny&dtail; opo&ntail;
&thorn;e tabels, was sodanlie

<PB N="84">

streky&ntail; with a wow&ntail; &thorn;at a&llbar; me&ntail; myght se,
&amp; bafi&dtail; att his mouthe &amp; swelte.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Bos totus vno die ab uno commestus est.  Infra de

commestione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>

<ITEM><FOREIGN>Bubo aliquando est signum eventuum futurorum.

Supra de augurrio.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Bupho.  Mirabilis fabula de
Buphone.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how som tyme in &thorn;e Dioces of Colay&ntail;, a
ma&ntail; &thorn;at hyght Theodoricus hurte a tade, &amp; whe&ntail;
he had hurte hur sho stude vp ayeyns hy&mtail; o&ntail; hur
hynderfete; &amp; he waxe&dtail; wrate &thorn;erwith, &amp; tuke ane
yr&ntail; &amp; slew hur.  Bod, att is mervalus to te&llbar;, sho gatt
life agay&ntail;, &amp; in a purpos to venge hur, sho persewi&dtail;
after hy&mtail;; &amp; ans or twyce euer with a spade he smate hur in
sonder.  At &thorn;e laste he burnyd hur, &amp; it profetti&dtail; hym
no thyng; to so meku&llbar; &thorn;at, for ferde of hur, he durste not
slepe in no place apo&ntail; &thorn;e erthe, vnto so meku&llbar;
&thorn;at o&ntail; nyghtis he garte hyng his bed att a hy balke.  So
o&ntail; a day hy&mtail; happen&dtail; ryde o&ntail; huntyng &amp; a
felow with hy&mtail;, &amp; he sett spe&llbar; o&ntail; ende &amp;
tolde hy&mtail; a&llbar; &thorn;e cace.  Sodanlie he luki&dtail;
behyn&dtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; &thorn;is tade was clymman&dtail; in his
hors tayle &amp; walde fay&ntail; hafe bene att hy&mtail;, and he
bega&ntail; to cry.  And his felow sayde; "Be war! for &thorn;e
devu&llbar; is in &thorn;i hors tayle, &amp; wol&dtail; be u&ptail;
att &thorn;e."  &amp; he lighty&dtail; &amp; slew itt.  A noder tyme
as he satt at ale emang felowshu&ptail;, he was war of &thorn;is tade
syttand o&ntail; a poste in &thorn;e syde of a wa&llbar;, and onone as
he saw hur he crye&dtail; &amp; sayde; "lo!  surs! yonder is a
fen&dtail; &thorn;at I mo&ntail; nevur be delyvur&dtail; of or he
venge hy&mtail; o&ntail; me."  And onone be cownce&llbar;, he
naken&dtail; &thorn;e tane of his legis &amp; lete &thorn;e tade
co&mtail; vnto it, &amp; sho gatt hy&mtail; be &thorn;e leg &amp; bate
hy&mtail;; &amp; whe&ntail; sho had done, he putt hur of with hys
han&dtail;.  And he tuke a rasur, &amp; a&llbar; &thorn;e bitt at sho
had bytty&ntail;, he cutt it oute &amp; keste it fro&mtail; hy&mtail;;
&amp; onone &thorn;is pece bolny&dtail; mervaloslie als grete as a
fute-ba&llbar; &amp; breste; &amp; &thorn;us he was delyver&dtail;.
et c&curl;.

<PB N="85">
</P>
<P>
