<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cantus proprius multos decipit qui credunt bene
cantare et pessime ac vilissime cantant.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Jacobus de Vetriaco tellis how &thorn;at &thorn;er was a preste
&thorn;at trowi&dtail; he was a passan&dtail; gude synger,
not-with-stondyng he was not so.  So o&ntail; a day &thorn;er was a
gentyl-womma&ntail; &thorn;at satt behyn&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp;
har&dtail; hy&mtail; syng, &amp; sho bega&ntail; to wepe; and he,
trowyng &thorn;at sho wepi&dtail; for swettnes of his voyse,
bega&ntail; to syng lowder &thorn;a&ntail; he di&dtail; tofo&rtail;;
&amp; ay &thorn;e hyer sho hard hy&mtail; syng, &thorn;e faster wepud
sho.  Tha&ntail; &thorn;is preste aski&dtail; hur whi sho wepu&dtail;
so as sho di&dtail;, and sho ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail;
&amp; say&dtail;; "Sur, I a&mtail; a pure genti&llbar;womma&ntail;,
&amp; &thorn;e laste day I had no calfe bod one; &amp; &thorn;e wulfe
come &amp; had it away fro me; and evur whe&ntail; &thorn;at I here
you syng, onone I remembre me how &thorn;at my calfe &amp; ye cried
like."  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e preste har&dtail; &thorn;is, onone he
thoght shame, &amp; remembred hy&mtail; &thorn;at &thorn;at &thorn;ing
at he thoght was grete lovyng vnto Go&dtail;, was vnto Hy&mtail; grete
shame and velany; &amp; fro thens furt&hbar; he sang nevur so lowde.
et c&curl;



<PB N="86">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cantando multi vanam gloriam appetunt et ideo
aliquando a deo puniuntur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a mon&ktee; at
&thorn;e Mownte of Cassia&ntail;, &thorn;at had a passand swete voyce.
So o&ntail; &thorn;e pasc&hbar; evy&ntail;, whe&ntail; he sul&dtail;
blis &thorn;e candy&llbar; of &thorn;e pasca&llbar;, he sang it
i&ntail; a moste swete voyce, to so meku&llbar; &thorn;at ilk bodie
&thorn;at har&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;oght his voyce was a dulcett
melodye.  &amp; onone as &thorn;e pasca&llbar; was blissi&dtail;,
sodanlie it was away, an&dtail; his prior and his brethir trowi&dtail;
&thorn;at it was so take&ntail; away sodanlie becauce of his pride
&amp; his elacio&ntail; et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cantus clamosos
<NOTE ID="P86.N1">MS. clamosus.</NOTE> Deus paru&mtail; reputat et demon
approbat
<NOTE ID="P86.N2">MS. approbatt.</NOTE>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how o&ntail; a tyme, whe&ntail; clerkis wer
syngan&dtail; &amp; makand a grete noyse, a religious ma&ntail; was
war of a fen&dtail; syttan&dtail; in a hy place in &thorn;e kurk,
holdan&dtail; opy&ntail; a grete sek&ktee; in his left han&dtail;.
And wit&hbar; his right han&dtail; he putt &thorn;e voyces of
&thorn;aim at sang into his sek&ktee;.  So whe&ntail; &thorn;ai had
done &thorn;er sang, &thorn;ai made a grete lawde &thorn;erof &amp; a
grete commendacio&ntail;.  &amp; he &thorn;at saw &thorn;e
vysio&ntail; ansswer&dtail; &amp; say&dtail;; "fforsuthe ye sang wele,
bod ye filli&dtail; a tome sekk evy&ntail; fu&llbar; with your sang."
And &thorn;ai had grete merve&llbar; &thorn;er-off, and spyrri&dtail;
hy&mtail; what he ment, &amp; he tol&dtail; &thorn;aim a&llbar; what
at he saw, &amp; how.  et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cantoris speciem
<NOTE ID="P86.N3"><HI REND="i">After</HI> speciem, dui, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> diabolus aliquando sumit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis of a clar&ktee; &thorn;at som tyme had a swete
voyce, to so meku&llbar; &thorn;at me&ntail; at har&dtail; hy&mtail;
syng &thorn;oght &thorn;at it was a grete delite to here hy&mtail;.
So o&ntail; a day a religious ma&ntail; happen&dtail; to here
hy&mtail; harpe, and onone as he harde hy&mtail; he say&dtail; in
&thorn;is maner of wyse; "This voyce &amp; &thorn;is melodie is not of
a ma&ntail; bod, rather of &thorn;e devu&llbar;."







<PB N="87">

And a&llbar; me&ntail; mervayl&dtail; of &thorn;is at he sai&dtail;,
&amp; evy&ntail; furthwith he co[n]iury&dtail; hy&mtail;; &amp;
&thorn;e fen&dtail; onone went his way, &amp; lefte &thorn;e bodie as
a dea&dtail;, dry caryo&ntail;; &amp; so &thorn;ai mott wit at it was
a dry caryo&ntail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXXIV.  
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cantare vel eciam scribere, vel eciam referre aliqua
crimina scurilia, uel inhonesta carmina, non
expedit.  et c&curl;.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis of one &thorn;at was a passan&dtail; famos poett,
&thorn;at hight Aurilegus <NOTE ID="P87.N1">Lat. MSS. Archilegus.</NOTE> ; and for cauce of his
oppynyons, &thorn;e contre at he dwelte in damny&dtail; his bukys
&amp; exilde hy&mtail; selfe, and a&llbar; be-cauce at his bukys spakk
of vnclennes of liffyng &amp; of gestis &amp; enchawntementis.
&thorn;erfor &thorn;ai wol&dtail; nott suffer hy&mtail; abide emangis
&thorn;aim, at his bukis sul&dtail; not be ensample to i&llbar; vnto
&thorn;er contre afterwar&dtail; whe&ntail; he was dea&dtail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cantare aliquando expedit nouas historias sanctorum.

Infra de deuocione.  vj.</FOREIGN></ITEM>


</LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cantanda est letania contra
tribulaciones.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Johannes Damacenus tellis how o&ntail; a tyme, att &thorn;e cetie
of Constantynople, &thorn;er was tribulacio&ntail;, &amp; peple went
aboute &thorn;e kur&ktee; in &thorn;er prayers to pray Go&dtail; to
sese itt; [&] a childe sodanlie emang &thorn;e peple was take&ntail;
v&ptail; vnto hevy&ntail;, &amp; &thorn;er he was taght &thorn;e sang
of &thorn;e latenye.  And sodanlie he was sett agay&ntail; emang
&thorn;e peple &amp; bega&ntail; &thorn;e letany hy&mtail; selfe,
&amp; tol&dtail; &thorn;e clerkis how &thorn;ai sulde syng after
hy&mtail;.  &amp; So &thorn;ai di&dtail;; and &thorn;is done onone
&thorn;e tribulacio&ntail; cesy&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cantus humilis cum cordis deuocione plus placet
deo quam voces in celum arroganter eleuare.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how o&ntail; a tyme in &thorn;e Ceustus ordur,
whe&ntail; &thorn;e psal&mtail; was bego&ntail; in a medu&llbar;
voyce, &amp; a&llbar; &thorn;e monkis felow&dtail; after



<PB N="88">

in &thorn;e same voyce, a prowde yong monke bega&ntail; at sett it
v&ptail; abow&ntail; &thorn;aim iij notis; and &thorn;uf a&llbar;
&thorn;e ol&dtail; monkis resisti&dtail; hy&mtail;, yit so&mtail;
&thorn;at was o&ntail; his syde fe&llbar; in tone vnto hy&mtail;
an&dtail; helpy&dtail; hy&mtail;, and so he requori&dtail;.  &amp;
&thorn;e ol&dtail; monkis, for disclander of Goddis serves, lete
hy&mtail; alone; and onone &thorn;er was sene co&mtail; oute att his
mouthe a fen&dtail; in lykkenes of a byrnyng yr&ntail;, &amp; went
evur fro ma&ntail; to ma&ntail; &thorn;at helpy&dtail; hy&mtail;,
&amp; burny&dtail; &thorn;aim.

</P>
<P>
