<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Caro.  Carnis eciam temptacione Sancti quandoque
vexantur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Heraclides tellis, in 'Libro Paradisi,' how o&ntail; a tyme a
holie mon&ktee; &thorn;at hight Helyas, &thorn;at was a virtuos
ma&ntail; &amp; had grete petie &amp; mercye of womme&ntail;, had
vndernethe his gouernance in a monasterie CCC womme&ntail;.  And
whe&ntail; he had contynued in &thorn;is occupacio&ntail; ij yere, and
was bod of xxx<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> or xl<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> yere age, sodanlie he was attempy&dtail; with
his fless&hbar;, and onone as he feli&dtail; &thorn;is, he went oute
of his monasterie ij dayes in-to wyldernes, &amp; made hys prayer in
&thorn;is maner of wyse; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Diuine deus meus, et
c&curl;.</FOREIGN> Lor&dtail;, I beseke &thorn;e owder to remefe
&thorn;is temptacio&ntail; fro&mtail; me, or els sla me!"  So at
evy&ntail; sodanlie he fe&llbar; opo&ntail; a slepe, &amp; hy&mtail;
thoght &thorn;er come vnto hy&mtail; iij angels &thorn;at say&dtail;;
"Why went &thorn;ou furt&hbar; oute of &thorn;e

<PB N="89">

monasterie of &thorn;ies womme&ntail;?"  And he ansswer&dtail; &amp;
sai&dtail;, for he was fer&dtail; &thorn;at owder he sulde noy
&thorn;aim, or &thorn;ai hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;ai say&dtail;
&thorn;ai sul&dtail; delyver hy&mtail; of &thorn;is drede, and bad
hy&mtail; go home &amp; take charge of &thorn;aim agay&ntail;.  And he
grawnty&dtail; &thorn;erto &amp; made &thorn;aim ane athe at he sulde
do so.  And &thorn;ai lay&dtail; hy&mtail; dow&ntail;, &amp; one of
&thorn;aim hel&dtail; his handis &amp; a-noder his fete, &amp;
&thorn;e thri&dtail; with a rasur cutt away bothe his balok-stonys,
not at it was done, bod as hy&mtail; thoght it was done; and
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai asky&dtail; hy&mtail; if he was any better,
&amp; if he was any bettyr &thorn;a&ntail; he was befo&rtail;.  And he
ansswerd agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "I vnderstan&dtail; &thorn;at a
hevie burdy&ntail; is take&ntail; fro me, and &thorn;erfo&rtail; I
trow &thorn;at I a&mtail; delyver&dtail; of &thorn;at at I was
fu&llbar; fer&dtail; for."  And with-in v dayes he went agay&ntail;
in-to his monasterie, &amp; liffi&dtail; &thorn;erin afterwar&dtail;
xl<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> yere.  And as holie fadurs says, fro thens forward suc&hbar; a
thoght come nevur after in his mynde.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Carnales cogitaciones a sanctis beneficia dei auferunt.

infra de predicacione.  iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>

<ITEM><FOREIGN>Carnalis cogitacio accepta a sanctis demones letificat.

Infra de cruce.  ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>

<ITEM><FOREIGN>Carnalem temptacionem demon frequenter procurat.

Supra de Sancto Andrea et eciam vbi agitur de

Sancta cruce.  ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>

<ITEM><FOREIGN>Caro mouetur ad modicum tactum mulieris quemque.

Infra de Sancto leone.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Carnale peccatum committere sanctos
procurat demo&ntail;
<NOTE ID="P89.N1">Lat. MSS. Carnale peccatum committere sanctos prius curat demon. Eng. MS. committere plus sanctos, etc.</NOTE>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede of olde Thebens <NOTE ID="P89.N2">Latin MSS. Senex Thebensis.</NOTE> &thorn;at was a
preste so&ntail; of &thorn;e ol&dtail; law, &amp; o&ntail; a day as he
saw his fadur sacrefie vnto &thorn;e ydolsis &amp; fals goddis, he was
war of &thorn;e devu&llbar; &amp; a&llbar; his chyvalrie
standan&dtail; by; and hy&mtail; &thorn;oght at &thorn;e devu&llbar;
was sett in chayre, and a&llbar; &thorn;is felaschu&ptail;





<PB N="90">

come afor hy&mtail; &amp; made &thorn;er acommptis of &thorn;er
wykke&dtail; temptacions.  And one come &amp; say&dtail;, &thorn;at
with-in &thorn;at xxx<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> dayes he had made many me&ntail; ilk one to
sla o&thorn;er; and a noder say&dtail; &thorn;at with-in xx<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> dayes he
had drowny&dtail; many me&ntail; in &thorn;e see; and &thorn;e
thri&dtail; sai&dtail; &thorn;at he had bene at a weddyng, &amp;
&thorn;er he had made ilk one to sla other.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai
had sai&dtail;, he commanddi&dtail; ilk one of &thorn;aim to be
bety&ntail;, fore becauce &thorn;ai had occupy&dtail; so lang tyme
&amp; done so litle labur.  So at &thorn;e laste &thorn;er come one
&amp; say&dtail; &thorn;at he had bene besye xl<HI REND="sup">ty</HI> [yere] <NOTE ID="P90.N1">Latin MSS. per xl annos.</NOTE> to stir a monke &thorn;at was in wyldernes vnto
sy&ntail;, &amp; vnnethis &thorn;at same nyght he had stird hy&mtail;
to do fornycacio&ntail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e grete
devu&llbar; rase oute of &thorn;e chayre &amp; kissyd hy&mtail; &amp;
sett his crow&ntail; o&ntail; his heade, &amp; sayde &thorn;at he was
wurthi lovyng, &amp; to be sett in &thorn;e chayr, for he had done a
grete cure.

</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Carnali temptacione mediante diabolus virum vel

mulierem inducit ad negandum deum.  Supra

de amicicia.  ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>


</LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Carnem commouens diabolus eciam in sanctis per
formam mulieris, inducit eos in desperacionem.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how som tyme &thorn;er was a monke &thorn;at was of a
grete abstinence &amp; lay in a de&ntail;, &amp; fu&llbar; of vertues
&amp; gude liffyng.  So o&ntail; a tyme, be temptacio&ntail;, he tuke
a presumpcio&ntail; &amp; &thorn;oght his <NOTE ID="P90.N2">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI> his.</NOTE>
holines come more of hy&mtail; selfe &thorn;a&ntail; of Go&dtail;;
[and] &thorn;e devu&llbar; o&ntail; ane evynyng fenyd hy&mtail; selfe
in lyknes of a womma&ntail; goand wy&llbar; in &thorn;e wyldernes, and
come vnto his de&ntail; dure, &amp; calli&dtail; &amp; sai&dtail; sho
was a wery womma&ntail; &amp; had gane wi&llbar;, &amp; sett hur
dow&ntail; o&ntail; hur kneis &amp; besoght hy&mtail; to hafe mercie
o&ntail; hur.  And, "Sur," scho sai&dtail;, "it is now nere nyght,
&amp; I beseke &thorn;e lat me lig to to-mor&ntail; in a hyr&ntail; of
&thorn;i de&ntail;, att wylde bestis sla me not and eate me."  And he
had compassio&ntail; o&ntail; hur &amp; graw[n]ti&dtail; hur.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; sho went in &amp; tolde hy&mtail; &thorn;e cauce of
hur gate wi&llbar;.  And with hur fayr speche





<PB N="91">

&amp; hur swete wurdis, sho smate his harte in-to a luste &amp; a
lykyng, &amp; sho made hy&mtail; such cownttenans &amp; flaghter,
&thorn;at it luste lenyd vnto hur ay mar &amp; mare.  So &thorn;is
monke was so attempyd with hur, &thorn;at he rase &amp; tuke hur in
his armys &amp; hawsi&dtail; hur, &amp; &thorn;oght to hafe done his
luste &amp; his lykyng with hur; &amp; sho bega&ntail; to giff a huge
cry &amp; ane vglie, &amp; slippid oute of his handis.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; he har&dtail; a grete multitude of fendis in &thorn;e
ayr, &thorn;at sayde; "O! &thorn;ou monk, at was so extolli&dtail; in
hevy&ntail;, how depe now &thorn;ou erte drowny&dtail; in he&llbar;!
Vmthynke &thorn;e how he &thorn;att heightens hy&mtail; selfe
mo&ntail; be lawuy&dtail;."  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is monk
fe&llbar; into a despayr, &amp; was nere-hand evy&ntail; wude, &amp;
gaff hy&mtail; selfe vnto a&llbar; vnclennes &amp; sy&ntail;, &amp;
efterwar&dtail; dyed in wykkid lyffyng. et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXXX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Carnales motus sunt per affliccionem corporis
reprimendi.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' how &thorn;er was a certay&ntail;
womma&ntail; &thorn;at made beheste vnto yong me&ntail; &thorn;at sho
was felowshuppi&dtail; with, &thorn;at sho sulde gett oute ane
ol&dtail; holie ma&ntail; oute of his ce&llbar;.  And sho come vnto
his ce&llbar; &amp; feny&dtail; hur ane eran&dtail;, &amp; he lete hur
in; &amp; onone he was streky&ntail; with a concupiscens to sy&ntail;
with hur; and onone as he feli&dtail; &thorn;is, he made a fyre &amp;
burny&dtail; &thorn;e fyngers of bothe his handys, at &thorn;ai
smerti&dtail; so at it putt away a&llbar; his temptacio&ntail;.  And
&thorn;is womma&ntail; layde hur dow&ntail; in a noke of his ce&llbar;
&amp; slepy&dtail;, &amp; in hur slepyng sho dye&dtail;.  And o&ntail;
&thorn;e mor&ntail; &thorn;ies yong me&ntail; come vnto hy&mtail;, and
&thorn;is olde ma&ntail; sayd vnto &thorn;ai&mtail;; "wi&llbar; ye se
how &thorn;is childe &amp; doghter of &thorn;e devu&llbar; hase
burny&dtail; my fyngers? and lo!  whar sho lyes slepan&dtail;!"  And
&thorn;ai went vnto hur &amp; wol&dtail; hafe waken&dtail; hur, &amp;
&thorn;ai fande hur dead.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is old ma&ntail;
made his prayers vnto almi&yogh;ttie God, &amp; raysyd hur fro deade
vnto life, &amp; bad hur be a <NOTE ID="P91.N1">MS. as.</NOTE> gude womma&ntail;,
&amp; tem&ptail; no mo&rtail; no me&ntail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Carnales motus dominandi sunt disciplinis et ieiunijs.

Infra de temptacione.</FOREIGN></ITEM> 
<PB N="92">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Carnalis temptacio aliquando extinguitur orationibus

sanctorum.  Supra de Agnete.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXXXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Carnis temptacio reprimenda est eciam in
senibus.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Heraclides tellis of hy&mtail; selfe &amp; sais &thorn;us;
"whe&ntail; o&ntail; a tyme I was gretelie tempy&dtail; with
temptacio&ntail; of my fless&hbar;, I went vnto a ma&ntail; &thorn;at
hight Pachonius, &thorn;at dwelte in wyldernes a solitarie, and tolde
hy&mtail; my dissese, whilk at I durste not for shame te&llbar; att
hame vnto Euagerus, &thorn;at was my maister.  And he ansswer&dtail;
me in &thorn;is maner of wyse, &amp; say&dtail;; 'Be it not vnto
&thorn;e a new thyng at &thorn;ou suffers, ffor I hafe bene &thorn;is
xl<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> yere in my prayers, &amp; liffi&dtail; in my ce&llbar; ane
ol&dtail; ma&ntail; as &thorn;ou may see, &amp; evur restreyny&dtail;
me fro&mtail; &thorn;at temptacio&ntail;; and now &thorn;is laste xij
yere, &thorn;at temptacio&ntail; fe&llbar; opo&ntail; me &amp; wolde
neuer away fro mee; and &thorn;a&ntail; I thoght att I was destitute
of &thorn;e helpe of a&llbar;myghti God&dtail;, &amp; &thorn;oght
&thorn;at me had levur dy &thorn;a&ntail; for to concent vnto
sy&ntail;.  And I nakyn&dtail; me &amp; went furt&hbar; of my
ce&llbar; &amp; layi&dtail; me befo&rtail; a wylde beste, &amp;
wol&dtail; hafe bene devowri&dtail; &amp; slay&ntail;; &amp; sho come
&amp; lykkid me from my hede vnto my fete, &amp; went hur way.
&thorn;a&ntail; I vmthoght mee &thorn;at God wol&dtail; spare mee,
&amp; I turnyd agay&ntail; vnto my ce&llbar;; and &thorn;a&ntail;
with-in a while after, &thorn;e devu&llbar; transfygur&dtail; into
liknes of a fayre damyse&llbar; &thorn;at I ha&dtail; sene
befo&rtail;, &amp; co&mtail; vnto me &amp; sat dow&ntail; o&ntail; hur
kneis afo&rtail; me, &amp; stirri&dtail; an&dtail; movid me so, at I
had nere-han&dtail; desyri&dtail; to hafe had at do with hur.  So at
&thorn;e laste I vmthoght me &amp; I wex wrathe with hur, &amp; gaff
hur a grete strake with my right hande; &amp; onone sho
vanysshi&dtail; away.  And &thorn;a&ntail; I went vnto wyldernes,
&amp; &thorn;er I fande a serpent, &amp; I tuke it v&ptail; in my
han&dtail; &amp; fretid itt, &amp; put it vnto my membres, to
th'entente &thorn;at I mot be peryssche&dtail; with &thorn;e bytyng
&thorn;eroff.  And sho wolde nothyng bite me.  And &thorn;a&ntail; I
har&dtail; a voyce at say&dtail; vnto me; 'Go hame &amp;
withstan&dtail; &thorn;i temptacio&ntail;, ffor almi&yogh;ti God hase
suffer&dtail; &thorn;e to be tempi&dtail; becauce at &thorn;ou sulde
know &thorn;ine infirmyte &amp; &thorn;i frelenes, and at &thorn;ou
sulde beseke God for to helpe &thorn;e.'  And &thorn;a&ntail; I went
home vnto my ce&llbar;, &amp; contynowi&dtail; in <NOTE ID="P92.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, in.</NOTE>



<PB N="93">

my prayers, &amp; bade in a faste belefe &thorn;at &thorn;urg&hbar;
&thorn;e helpe of a&llbar;myghtie Go&dtail; I mott with-ston&dtail;
temptacio&ntail;; &amp; so I thank God I hafe done
hedur-towar&dtail;.'"


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXXXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Carnis temptacionem
<NOTE ID="P93.N1">MS. tempacioni.</NOTE> reprimunt fetor et horror
mulieris mortue.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' how &thorn;er was a bruther &thorn;at
gretelie was turment with myn&dtail; of a womma&ntail; &thorn;at he
saw som tyme.  So o&ntail; a tyme a noder bruther of his come &amp;
tolde hy&mtail; at sho was dea&dtail;; and o&ntail; &thorn;e nyght
after he come &thorn;er, he har&dtail; te&llbar; sho was beri&dtail;,
&amp; he grufe dow&ntail; vnto hur &amp; behel&dtail; &thorn;e fayr
clothe at sho was wappi&dtail; in, and he tuke hur v&ptail; &amp; had
hur vnto his ce&llbar;.  And a litle while after sho bega&ntail; to
stynke, and he tuke hur oute &amp; say&dtail;, whe&ntail; he
luki&dtail; o&ntail; hur; "Lo, fless&hbar;! now &thorn;ou hase desyre,
ffy&llbar; now &thorn;i luste o&ntail; hur!"  And o&ntail; &thorn;is
maner of wise he chasti&dtail; hy&mtail; selfe many day, vnto
hy&mtail; i&llbar; temptacio&ntail; went away fro&mtail; hy&mtail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Carnales motus per lesionem corporis quandoque

sunt reprimendi.  Infra de castitate.  v.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXXXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Carnales motus in se corporaliter extinxisse nemo
debet gloriari.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede of a ma&ntail; &thorn;at hight Paphencius, how o&ntail; a
tyme he liffi&dtail; so straytlie many yeris, so &thorn;at he
trowi&dtail; he was delyver&dtail; fro flesshlie concupiscens, &amp;
vnto so meku&llbar; &thorn;at he was so strang in his selfe, &thorn;at
he mott withston&dtail; any temptacio&ntail; of &thorn;e devu&llbar;.
So o&ntail; a tyme he had burny&dtail; his han&dtail; i&llbar;, &amp;
his brethir come &amp; made a medcy&ntail; &amp; lay&dtail;
&thorn;er-vnto; and he made grete sorow &amp; was passan&dtail; hevie
&thorn;at be instigacio&ntail; of &thorn;e devu&llbar; his han&dtail;
was burny&dtail;; and after &thorn;is hevynes he fe&llbar; o&ntail;
slepe, and ane ange&llbar; aperi&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;



<PB N="94">

&amp; say&dtail;; "Whi erte &thorn;ou hevie, se&ntail; &thorn;ou may
not suffer a little burnyng of erdlie fyre, &amp; kepis in &thorn;i
selfe a movyng of a flesslie luste?  Go &amp; take a naked fayr
mayde&ntail; &amp; se hur ons, &amp; if &thorn;ou fele &thorn;i harte
for to be in tranquillite &amp; reste, Tha&ntail; &thorn;ou may wele
wete &thorn;at &thorn;ou may, with-oute grete hurte, suffre a little
burnyng of fyre."  et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXXXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Castitas.  Castitatem mittit deus illam indigentibus
<NOTE ID="P94.N1">Latin MSS. <HI REND="i">have</HI> diligentibus.</NOTE>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Gregorius Nazarenus tellis, whe&ntail; he duelie kepi&dtail;
hy&mtail; in chastitie &amp; was bo&dtail; a yong ma&ntail;, &amp;
lerny&dtail; philosophi att Athenys, he saw in a dreme, as hy&mtail;
thoght he saw syttan&dtail; by hy&mtail; redan&dtail; ij fayr
womme&ntail;, one o&ntail; his right side &amp; a noder o&ntail; his
lefte syde.  And hy&mtail; <NOTE ID="P94.N2">MS. me.</NOTE> &thorn;oght he <NOTE ID="P94.N3"><HI REND="i">Under</HI> he, I, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> durst not for brekyng of his chastite behol&dtail;
&thorn;aim, nor he durst not aske &thorn;aim whyne &thorn;ai come nor
what &thorn;ai wol&dtail;.  And &thorn;ai behel&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp;
say&dtail;; "yong ma&ntail;! be not hevie, for &thorn;ou knowis vs
wele enog&hbar;; ffor &thorn;e tone of vs is wisdo&mtail; &amp;
&thorn;e toder is chastite, and we erte sent hedur to dwe&llbar; with
&thorn;e; ffor &thorn;ou hase ordan&dtail; for vs in &thorn;i
har&dtail; harte a ioyfu&llbar; habitacle &amp; a merie."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXXXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Castitas in vxore est multum
laudabilis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Jeronimus tellis how &thorn;er was som tyme <NOTE ID="P94.N4">MS. <HI REND="i">inserts</HI>, man, <HI REND="i">here</HI>.</NOTE>
a noble ma&ntail; &thorn;at hight Duellus, &amp; he was ane alde
ma&ntail; &amp; a wayke of bodie, &amp; he wed a maydy&ntail;
&thorn;at hight Yliana.  So o&ntail; a tyme his neghburs &amp; he
fe&llbar; at debate, &amp; ane of &thorn;aim vpbraye&dtail; hy&mtail;
&amp; say&dtail; his ande stynky&dtail;, &amp; his mouthe, &amp;
sai&dtail; his yong wife was i&llbar; wari&dtail; o&ntail; hy&mtail;.
And he was displesi&dtail; &thorn;er-with &amp; went hame.  And onone
as his wife saw his cowtenans, sho aski&dtail; hy&mtail; whi he was so
hevie; and he blamy&dtail; hur &amp; sai&dtail; he was wrothe with hur
becauce sho wol&dtail; neuer se&ntail; &thorn;ai wer we&dtail;
te&llbar; hy&mtail; at his ande stynki&dtail;; for, he sai&dtail;,
&amp; sho had telli&dtail; hy&mtail; he sul&dtail; hafe done so&mtail;
medcy&ntail; &thorn;erfor









<PB N="95">

to distroy itt.  And sho sai&dtail;; "Sur, I sulde hafe done so, bod
a&llbar; oder mens an&dtail; duse so as yours duse." et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Castitatis violatores eciam aves puniunt.  Supra de

adulterio.</FOREIGN></ITEM>

<ITEM><FOREIGN>Castitatis amore vita corporalis contempnitur.  Infra

de virginitate.  I.</FOREIGN></ITEM>

<ITEM><FOREIGN>Castitatis amore propria patria relinquenda est.

Infra de Clemente.  iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXXXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Castitatis amore eciam membra corporis
contempnuntur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Jacobus de Vetriaco tellis <NOTE ID="P95.N1">Tellis, <HI REND="i">repeated and erased.</HI></NOTE> how som tyme
&thorn;er was a myghti prince &thorn;at was fowndur of a nonrie
&thorn;at stude nere-han&dtail; hy&mtail;; &amp; he covett gretelie a
fayr no&ntail; of &thorn;e place, to hafe hur vnto his lemma&ntail;.
&amp; notwithstondyng, nowder be prayer nor be gyfte he cuthe
ouerco&mtail; hur; &amp; at &thorn;e laste he tuke hur away be strang
han&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; me&ntail; come to take hur away, sho was
passan&dtail; fer&dtail;, &amp; aski&dtail; &thorn;aim whi &thorn;ai
tuke hur oute of hur abbay more &thorn;a&ntail; hur other sisters.
And &thorn;ai ansswer&dtail; hur agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;, becauce
sho had so fayr ee&ntail;.  And onone as sho har&dtail; &thorn;is sho
was fay&ntail;, &amp; sho garte putt oute hur ee&ntail; onone, &amp;
lay&dtail; &thorn;aim in a diss&hbar;, &amp; broght &thorn;aim vnto
&thorn;aim &amp; say&dtail;; "Lo! here is &thorn;e ene at your maister
desiris, &amp; bid hy&mtail; lat me alone, &amp; lose nowder his sawle
nor myne."  And &thorn;ai went vnto hy&mtail; &thorn;erwith &amp;
tol&dtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; he lete hur alone; &amp; be &thorn;is mene
sho kepi&dtail; hur chastite.  &amp; with-in iij yere after sho had
hur ee&ntail; agay&ntail; als wele as evur had scho, &thorn;urg&hbar;
grace of Go&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXXXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Castitatis exemplo et amore totum corpus aliquando
exponitur in periculo.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how o&ntail; a tyme, whe&ntail; &thorn;e cetie of
Leodonens <NOTE ID="P95.N2">Latin MSS. Leodiensis ciuitas.</NOTE> was wasti&dtail; be &thorn;e Brabans,
many womme&ntail; &amp; maydens &amp; oder, for luff of





<PB N="96">

chastite put &thorn;aim in grete pere&llbar; of &thorn;er bodis.  So
as one of &thorn;aim, to safe hur chastite, putt hur in grete
pere&llbar; of &thorn;e watir, ij of hur enmys come vnto hur in a
bote, &amp; drew hur into &thorn;er shi&ptail;, to &thorn;e entent at
&thorn;ai wol&dtail; devowre hur maydenhede.  And sho had levur hafe
gane agay&ntail; into &thorn;e watir &amp; hafe bene drowny&dtail;,
&thorn;a&ntail; at &thorn;ai had defowli&dtail; hur.  And sho lepe
oute of &thorn;e shi&ptail; into &thorn;e watir, and with strenthe of
hur lowpyng &thorn;e bote drowny&dtail;, &amp; &thorn;ase ij me&ntail;
war bathe drowny&dtail;; and sho be &thorn;e grace of allmyghti God
was savi&dtail;, &amp; come hole &amp; sownde vnto &thorn;e
lan&dtail;. et c&curl;.

</P>
