</LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXLI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Celandum est secretum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>Macrobius <NOTE ID="P98.N1">MS. Mocrobius.</NOTE> tellis how &thorn;er was a
noby&llbar; captay&ntail; in Rome &thorn;at hight Papirius; &amp;
whe&ntail; he was a childe with his fadur, o&ntail; a day he went with
hy&mtail; vnto the cowrte, and whe&ntail; he come home his moder
aski&dtail; hy&mtail; what at &thorn;e senaturs &amp; &thorn;e wyse
me&ntail; of Rome sai&dtail; at &thorn;er cowrte &amp; &thorn;er
parlement.  And he ansswer&dtail; hur &amp; say&dtail; &thorn;at it
was not lawfu&llbar; to te&llbar;, for he &thorn;at telli&dtail; it
mon&dtail; be dea&dtail; &thorn;erfo&rtail;.  And sho tuke a
wan&dtail; &amp; bett hy&mtail;, and he saw &thorn;at hy&mtail;
bur&dtail; nedes te&llbar; hur somwhat, &amp; he fenyd in &thorn;is
maner of wyse &amp; say&dtail;, &thorn;er a&llbar; &thorn;e
cownce&llbar; att &thorn;e senaturs had at do at &thorn;er parlement
was for to witt whedur it was more necessarie &thorn;at a ma&ntail;
sulde hafe ij wyvis, or a womma&ntail; ij husbandis.  An&dtail; sho
went &amp; tol&dtail; it vnto hur commedurs, &amp; telli&dtail;
&thorn;aim a&llbar; &thorn;e tow&ntail; our, so &thorn;at o&ntail;
&thorn;e mor&ntail; after, wur&dtail; come &thorn;er-of vnto &thorn;e
senaturs &thorn;at &thorn;e cownce&llbar; of &thorn;er parlement
shulde be dis-curi&dtail; be &thorn;is little childe; &amp; &thorn;ai
garte feche hy&mtail; afor&ntail; &thorn;aim, &amp; spyrri&dtail;
hy&mtail; what &thorn;at was at he had telli&dtail; his moder, &amp;
he tolde &thorn;aim <NOTE ID="P98.N2">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, &thorn;aim.</NOTE> a&llbar; &thorn;e proces.
And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e senaturs ordan&dtail; &thorn;at fro thens
furt&hbar; no childe, bod alonelie he, sulde co&mtail; into &thorn;er
parlement with his fadur, for pere&llbar; of tellyng of &thorn;er
cownce&llbar;; &amp; afterwar&dtail; hy&mtail; happen&dtail; be
&thorn;e wyseste ma&ntail; in a&llbar; Rome.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXLII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Celari debent defectus amicorum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>Ruffinus tellis &thorn;at o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; &thorn;e
Emperour Constantyne went into a place whar &thorn;er was gader&dtail;
many brethyr samen at





<PB N="99">

a cownce&llbar;, he fan&dtail; at &thorn;ai had emang &thorn;aim many
debatis &amp; stryvis; and he tuke of &thorn;aim a by&llbar; of
a&llbar; &thorn;er debatis &amp; &thorn;er stryvis, &amp; putt it in
his boso&mtail;, &amp; whe&ntail; he come home he burnyd it, at neuer
ma&ntail; sul&dtail; se it after, as prestis sulde do with
confessio&ntail;.  An&dtail; afterwer&dtail; he say&dtail;, whe&ntail;
&thorn;ai aski&dtail; hy&mtail; whi he had done so, in &thorn;is
mane&rtail; of wise; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Si vidissem sacerdotem vel
aliquem eorum qui monachali habitu sunt amicti, et c&curl;.</FOREIGN>
And I saw a preste or a monke doyng sy&ntail;, rather I sul&dtail;
hide hy&mtail; with my manty&llbar;, &thorn;a&ntail; disclander
hy&mtail;." et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXLIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cibus.  Cibariorum superfluitas semper est ab
omnibus vitanda.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>Saynt Jero&mtail; tellis of a philosophur &thorn;at hight Epicurus,
&thorn;at, if a&llbar; he was a sewer of voluptuosite, at he mott sett
his felicite &thorn;erin, neuer-&thorn;e-les he filli&dtail; his bukis
&amp; sai&dtail;, &thorn;at appyls &amp; o&thorn;er vile meatis sulde
be vsi&dtail;; &thorn;at <NOTE ID="P99.N1">Latin MSS. eo quod exquisite epule maiorem penam habeant inquirendo, quam voluptatem in abutendo.</NOTE> other metis sulde not
hafe mo&rtail; pay&ntail; in inquiryng &thorn;an luste in abusyng.
For he say&dtail; we mott nott a&llbar;-way giff hede vnto
wisdo&mtail;, if we thoght a&llbar;-way of habundans of our meate.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXLIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cibus moderatus et vniformis causat sanitatem
et pulcritudinem corporalem.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>Helynandus tellis how o&ntail; a tyme a bisshop&ptail; aski&dtail;
a yong ma&ntail; of Religio&ntail;, how it happen&dtail; &thorn;at he
was haler &amp; fayrer in his closter &thorn;a&ntail; he was
whe&ntail; he was i&ntail; &thorn;e werl&dtail;.  And he answer&dtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "For here I liff we&llbar; &amp;
clenlie; ffor as for &thorn;e furste, here I hafe my hea&llbar;, and
as for &thorn;e secun&dtail;, I a&mtail; here fayr, &amp; so I mott
not do in &thorn;e werl&dtail;; for &thorn;er I liffi&dtail; in
fylthe, &amp; so I did not here."  &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e
besshop&ptail; aski&dtail; hy&mtail; whatt at he had ety&ntail;
&thorn;at day, and he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;,
"enog&hbar;."  And &thorn;e bisshop&ptail; say&dtail; he aski&dtail;




<PB N="100">

hy&mtail; not of quantite, bod of qualitie; "bod what ete &thorn;ou
yisterday, &amp; what to <NOTE ID="P100.N1">MS. do.</NOTE> -day?"  And he
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "yisterday I ete cale
an&dtail; pes, &amp; to-day I eete pes &amp; cale, &amp; to-mor&ntail;
I mo&ntail; eate pess with cale, &amp; after to-mor&ntail; I mo&ntail;
eate cale with pease."  &amp; &thorn;us be a fayr circumstans he
broght aboute his sentans, so &thorn;at he mot shew at acordyng diett
makis a ma&ntail; bot&hbar; fayr &amp; hale of his bodie. et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
