<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXLV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cibo spirituali sustentatur corpus aliquando sine
corporali.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Jacobus de Vetriaco tellis, &thorn;at &thorn;e appetite of meate
was so wasti&dtail; in Saynt Marie of Oginiez <NOTE ID="P100.N2">MS. Ogimiem.</NOTE> ,
&thorn;at a grete while scho mott vnnethis take any meatte; so
&thorn;at som tyme be viij dayes, &amp; som tyme be x dayes, sho ete
neuer meate.  &amp; yit it was a grete mervayle, for, for a&llbar;
&thorn;is, nowder warki&dtail; hur hevu&dtail;, nor sho lefte not
&thorn;e labur of hur handis, &amp; sho was als strang to labur
o&ntail; &thorn;e laste day as sho was o&ntail; &thorn;e furste; and
if sho wol&dtail; hafe ety&ntail; &thorn;ase dayes, sho myght nott,
vnto <NOTE ID="P100.N3">Harl. MS. donec sensualitas que a spiritu quasi absorta fuerat ad se ipsam rediret.</NOTE> &thorn;e sensualitie &thorn;at come of hur
spiritt com vnto &thorn;e selfe agay&ntail;.  And som tyme whe&ntail;
sho was be hur selfe, so&mtail; tyme be xxx<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> dayes, sho wolde neuer
ete meate.  And many dayes sho wol&dtail; neuer speke wur&dtail; bod
&thorn;is alone; "I wu&llbar; resayfe my sacrament."  &amp; daylie sho
reseyvi&dtail; it in privatie.  And whe&ntail; v wowkis was done,
&thorn;a&ntail; scho oppyn&dtail; hur muthe &amp; spakk &amp;
reseyvi&dtail; bodelie meatt. et c&curl;.</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ciconia adulterium abhominatur et punit illud.

Supra de adulterio.  iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST></P>
<PB N="101"></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXLVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cineres.  Cineres sacri deuote sunt recipiendi.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>Cesarius tellis how &thorn;er was in a cetie ij me&ntail;, &amp;
&thorn;ai satt at myrth &amp; at ale o&ntail; fastyngan&gtee; evy&ntail;
vnto mydnyght in a taver&ntail;; &amp; in &thorn;e mornyng &thorn;ai
war so <NOTE ID="P101.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, so.</NOTE> thristie at &thorn;ai went thedur
agay&ntail;, &amp; sett &thorn;aim at &thorn;e ale vnto &thorn;ai rang
to mes.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai saw gude me&ntail; wen&dtail; vnto
&thorn;e kurk, one of &thorn;aim say&dtail; vnto &thorn;e toder; "Now
hafe we abydy&ntail; our lang.  Go we vnto &thorn;e kurk &amp; take
ou&rtail; ass."  And &thorn;e toder ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail;
agay&ntail; in skor&ntail;, &amp; sayde; "Sitt sti&llbar;, &amp; I
sa&llbar; giff &thorn;e ass."  And he tuke vp ass &amp; kest
opo&ntail; his hede, &amp; he o&ntail; his.  And furth-with &thorn;ai
war punyshid for &thorn;er scor&ntail;, ffor &thorn;ai feli&dtail; so
meku&llbar; duste, bathe aboute &thorn;er hedis &amp; &thorn;er facis,
as it had bene blaw&ntail; opo&ntail; &thorn;aim with a payr of
belows.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai feli&dtail; &thorn;is, &thorn;ai
bega&ntail; to cry; and whe&ntail; &thorn;ai oppyn&dtail; &thorn;er
mouthe, so meki&llbar; ass went in-to &thorn;er throtis, at &thorn;ai
war nerehan&dtail; weri&dtail;.  And &thorn;ai wer led&dtail; into
dyvers placis wha&rtail; &thorn;er was no duste, as in-to medows &amp;
in garthyns &amp; in selers, bod it profetti&dtail; nothyng at
&thorn;ai myght defen&dtail; &thorn;aim fro &thorn;is duste of ass at
was abowte &thorn;er hedis, to, att &thorn;e laste, &thorn;ai war
bothe whirkenid &thorn;er-with &amp; deyi&dtail;: &amp; &thorn;at had
&thorn;ai for &thorn;er skornyng.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXLVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Clementis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how &thorn;at Matidiana, &thorn;at was moder of Saynt
Clemett, was a <NOTE ID="P101.N2">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, a.</NOTE> passand fayr womma&ntail;, &amp;
hur husban&dtail; bro&thorn;er fe&llbar; amoros of hur, &amp; laburd
hur hugelie; &amp; sho wulde neuer consent vnto hy&mtail; for to cauce
hy&mtail; &amp; his bruther, hur husbond, to be at debate.  And sho vmthoght hur &thorn;at sho wolde go oute of &thorn;e
contre a while, and sho
fenyd a dreme &amp; tol&dtail; hur husban&dtail; at &thorn;er was a
voyce at come vnto hur in hur slepe, &amp; bad hur go furt&hbar;
of &thorn;e cetie with hur ij sonnys, Faustus &amp; Faustinus, vnto
tyme itt calli&dtail; hur agay&ntail;, and els sho &amp; bothe hur
sonnys mond be perysshi&dtail; &amp; distroye&dtail;.  And whe&ntail;
hur husban&dtail; har&dtail; &thorn;is, he had grete mervayle
&thorn;eroff,





<PB N="102">

&amp; he sent his wyfe &amp; hir ij sons, &amp; a parte of his meneya
with &thorn;aim, vnto Athenys, and hel&dtail; Clemett at home with
hy&mtail;, &thorn;at was bod v yere olde.  And as &thorn;ai war
sayland be &thorn;e se, &thorn;er shup brakk, and &thorn;is moder
loste hur sonnys &amp; went &thorn;ai had bene drow&ntail;; &amp; yit
sho gatt to lan&dtail; &amp; cla&mtail; vp o&ntail; a cragg.  And
&thorn;er scho dwelt a grete while with a womma&ntail; &thorn;at had
&thorn;e parlesie.  So &thorn;is Matidiana handis fe&llbar; benombe
for sorow of hur husban&dtail; &amp; hur chuldre, so &thorn;at sho mot
nothyng welde hur handis; so &thorn;at &thorn;ai wer evy&ntail; as
deade &amp; at sho had no felyng of &thorn;ai&mtail;.  And
afterwar&dtail; hur husban&dtail; sent vnto Athenas, &amp; hard no
tithandis nor wurd of his wyfe nor of his childer.  &amp; he putt
Clemett in a gude mans gouernans, &amp; gatt hy&mtail; a shi&ptail;
&amp; went to seke his wyfe an&dtail; his childre, &amp; so he
conteny&dtail; xx yere.  And in &thorn;e mene while, &thorn;is Clemett
drew vnto Saynt Petur, and tol&dtail; hy&mtail; what was happen&dtail;
vnto his fadur &amp; his moder.  So o&ntail; a tyme Petur &amp;
Clemett vnto-come &thorn;er &thorn;is Matidiana begi&dtail; hur meatt.
And Saynt Petur askid hur whi sho beggi&dtail; &amp; wolde nat wyrk
for hur meate, &amp; sho ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;,
&thorn;at hur handis was <NOTE ID="P102.N1"><HI REND="i">After</HI> was, v, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> benombe &amp; scho
mott not welde &thorn;aim, &amp; tel&dtail; hy&mtail; a&llbar;
&thorn;e proces how it had happen&dtail; with hur husban&dtail; &amp;
hur &amp; hur childre.  And &thorn;a&ntail; Petur sai&dtail; vnto hur;
"as for Clemett &thorn;i so&ntail;, I ca&ntail; shew &thorn;e
hy&mtail;."  And whe&ntail; sho har&dtail; &thorn;at sho swony&dtail;
&amp; fe&llbar; dow&ntail; vnto &thorn;e grown&dtail;; &amp; Petur
tuke hur v&ptail; be &thorn;e han&dtail; &amp; le&dtail; hur vnto
Clemett.  And whe&ntail; Clemett saw his maister Petir ledan&dtail; a
womma&ntail; be &thorn;e han&dtail;, he bega&ntail; to smyle; and
onone as &thorn;is womma&ntail; come vnto Clemett, sho hawsi&dtail;
hy&mtail; in hur armys, &amp; kissi&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; fe&llbar;
dow&ntail; in swone; &amp; he putt hur fro&mtail; hy&mtail; &amp;
trowe&dtail; sho had bene wude, and made hy&mtail; passand wrathe with
Petur.  And &thorn;a&ntail; Saynt Petur sai&dtail;; "what duse
&thorn;ou, so&ntail; Clemett?  Putt not &thorn;i moder away fro the."
And whe&ntail; Clemett har&dtail; &thorn;is, he wepud, &amp; tuke
v&ptail; his moder, &amp; fe&llbar; evy&ntail; dow&ntail; vnto
&thorn;e ert&hbar; hy&mtail; selfe for fay&ntail;; &amp; att &thorn;e laste
he tuke knowlege vnto his moder.  And in &thorn;e mene whlie Aquila
&amp; Niceta, &thorn;at war becomme&ntail; &thorn;e discipuls of
Petur, wer not &thorn;er present, and whe&ntail; &thorn;ai saw hur
&thorn;ai spurri&dtail; faste what sho was, and Clemett tol&dtail;
&thorn;aim how at sho was his moder; and Saynt



<PB N="103">

Petur telli&dtail; &thorn;aim a&llbar; &thorn;e proces.  &amp;
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai tuke a knowlege vnto hur &amp; say&dtail;,
"fforsuth we ij <NOTE ID="P103.N1"><HI REND="i">After</HI> ij, fa, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> er Faustus &amp; Fastinianus,
&amp; &thorn;is is our muder, &amp; Clemet is our brother."  &amp;
&thorn;ai kyssi&dtail; samen with grete wepyng &amp; Ioy.  And with-in
a while after &thorn;aim happen&dtail; be grace of Go&dtail; to
fyn&dtail; &thorn;er fadur; and &thorn;us a&llbar; &thorn;er sorow
tur&ntail; in-to myrthe &amp; Ioy.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXLVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Clericus ratione status sui habuit plura privilegia
<NOTE ID="P103.N2">MS. privalegia.</NOTE>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how &thorn;at a poett, &thorn;at hight Valerius, wulde
neuer ryse vnto Iulius Cesar whe&ntail; he come in-to &thorn;e company
of poettis, as it had bene a ma&ntail; &thorn;at ha&dtail; nott
ken&dtail; his magestie; and he di&dtail; it a&llbar; becauce he
trusti&dtail; hy&mtail; selfe was moste hye in comparyso&ntail; of
studie &amp; lernyng.  And he aski&dtail; hy&mtail; whi he wul&dtail;
not ryse vnto hy&mtail;, &amp; he sai&dtail; he wol&dtail; nott for
&thorn;er was no place of temporaltie nor of feghtyng in armur, bod
a&llbar; of turnyng of bukys &amp; volums.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXLIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Clerici non debent terrena appetere, sed virtutem
et honestatem.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede of Pyocinus <NOTE ID="P103.N3">MS. Arundel, Protinus.</NOTE> &thorn;e filosophur,
whe&ntail; he was ordand to make enornementis of vertues, (so
&thorn;at at he taght, he sul&dtail; not shew be <NOTE ID="P103.N4">MS. he.</NOTE> exsample of o&thorn;er me&ntail; bod rather be
exsample of hy&mtail; selfe), becauce he mot sitt sti&llbar; in ryst
&amp; pease, he chose hy&mtail; vnto a quiete place, wha&rtail; he sulde
here no noyse of no creatur; &amp; &thorn;er he hedi&dtail; a&llbar;
maner of &thorn;ing how God ordan&dtail; &thorn;aim.  And with-in a
while fro he had bene &thorn;er, he had in contempte a&llbar; maner of
wurshu&ptail; &amp; sai&dtail; &thorn;er was no trew wurshu&ptail; bod
connyng; ffor &thorn;at, he sai&dtail;, was most delicious, &thorn;e
whilk att mans witt cuthe ymagy&ntail; off trewthe in a mans saule. et
c&curl;.

</P>
