<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CL.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Clerici in ecclesia deuote debent dicere officium
diuinum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Jacobus de Vetriaco tellis how o&ntail; a tyme a holie ma&ntail;,
as he was in the quere, he was war of &thorn;e devu&llbar; &amp; a
hevie sakk <NOTE ID="P104.N1">MS. sa&llbar;.</NOTE> evy&ntail; fu&llbar; o&ntail; his
bak&ktee;.  &amp; &thorn;is holie ma&ntail; chargi&dtail; hy&mtail;
to charge hy&mtail; att te&llbar; hy&mtail; whatt he bare in &thorn;at
sek&ktee; at was so hevy.  &amp; he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
say&dtail;; "here in &thorn;is sak&ktee; er silappis &amp; wurdis
&thorn;at er ouerhippi&dtail;, &amp; also versis of &thorn;e salter
&amp; wurdis er momble&dtail; &thorn;at &thorn;ir prestis &amp;
&thorn;ies clerkis hase stolne in &thorn;is maty&ntail;-while."  &amp;
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is holie ma&ntail; aski&dtail; hy&mtail; what
he hight, and he sai&dtail; &thorn;at he hight Titiuillus.  And hereof
&thorn;is holie ma&ntail; made ij vers &amp; say&dtail;; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Fragmina verborum Titiuillus colligit horum, Et fert <NOTE ID="P104.N2">MS. ferte.</NOTE> ad forum quo premia reddat <NOTE ID="P104.N3">MS. reddit.</NOTE>
eorum.</FOREIGN>" et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CLI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Clerici non debent studere in uanis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Jacobus de Vetriaco tellis how o&ntail; a tyme at Pariss&hbar;, it
happen&dtail; &thorn;at a scoler, whe&ntail; he was dea&dtail;,
apperi&dtail; vnto his maister cled a&llbar; in parchemy&ntail;
writy&ntail;, with smale letters wrette&ntail; &thorn;ero&ntail;.  And







<PB N="105">

emang a&llbar; o&thorn;er questions his maister aski&dtail; hy&mtail;
what bement &thorn;at garment att was so light, &amp; &thorn;e letters
att was wrety&ntail; &thorn;ervppo&ntail;.  And he ansswer&dtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "ilkone of &thorn;ies letters er hevyer
vnto me &thorn;a&ntail; war &thorn;e weght of &thorn;is grete
kur&ktee; &amp; I bare it o&ntail; my ne&ktee;"; and shewi&dtail;
hy&mtail; &thorn;e kur&ktee; of Saynt Germa&ntail; at was &thorn;er,
&amp; sayd; "&thorn;ies er sophyms &amp; subtelties, whare-in I wastis
a&llbar; my dayes, &amp; I may not te&llbar; what hete at I a&mtail;
turment with a&llbar; my dayes vnder-nethe &thorn;is cape.  Bod &amp;
&thorn;ou wi&llbar; hol&dtail; furt&hbar; &thorn;i han&dtail;, I
sa&llbar; shew &thorn;e be a drop&ptail;."  And he putt furt&hbar; his
han&dtail;, and &thorn;er fe&llbar; &thorn;er-opo&ntail; as it had
bene bod a dropp of swete.  And it was so hate at it thirli&dtail; his
han&dtail; &thorn;u[r]g&hbar; as it had bene &thorn;e sharpe schote of
ane arow.  And onone &thorn;is maister as he saw &thorn;is, he lefte
&thorn;e logyk&ktee; skule, &amp; made hy&mtail; a mon&ktee; of
Ceustus ordur.  And he made &thorn;ies ij versis &amp; say&dtail;; "
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">linquo coax ranis, cra corvis, vanaque vanis; Ad
logicam pergo que mortis non timet ergo.</FOREIGN>" And he become a
gude ma&ntail;; &amp; als long as he liffi&dtail; &thorn;er was a hole
&thorn;urg&hbar; his han&dtail;. et c&curl;.

</P>
