<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CLII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cogitacionibus malis impeditur aliquis ne orationes
facte pro se ab aliquo exaudiantur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum,' how &thorn;er was a ma&ntail; &thorn;at
was gretlie tempi&dtail; with temptacio&ntail; of his fless&hbar;: and
he luke&dtail; vnto a gude

<PB N="106">

al&dtail; ma&ntail; &amp; lete hy&mtail; wete &thorn;erof, &amp;
praye&dtail; hy&mtail; to pray for hy&mtail;; and so he di&dtail;.
&amp; whe&ntail; he had long praye&dtail; for hy&mtail; he
mendi&dtail; no &thorn;ing, &amp; &thorn;is olde ma&ntail;
mervel&dtail; gretlie at his prayer was not har&dtail;.  So o&ntail; a
nyght as he lay in his prayers, he saw in a visio&ntail; &thorn;is
yong ma&ntail; sittant, &amp; evu&llbar; spyrittis in lyknes of
womme&ntail; playan&dtail; befo&rtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; makan&dtail;
hy&mtail; grete myrt&hbar;; and he saw &thorn;is yong mans gude
ange&llbar; <NOTE ID="P106.N1">MS. ans, <HI REND="i">with</HI> g <HI REND="i">written over the</HI> s, <HI REND="i">to make</HI> ange&llbar;.</NOTE> grete wrot&hbar; becauce he
wol&dtail; nott ryse &amp; make his prayer vnto almighti Go&dtail;.
And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is olde ma&ntail; sayd vnto &thorn;is yong
ma&ntail;; "Bruther! &thorn;e fawte is &thorn;ine &thorn;at &thorn;e
prayers &thorn;at er prayed for &thorn;e er nott harde.  For &thorn;ou
hase a delectacio&ntail; in evu&llbar; thoghtis, and it is impossible
to remofe i&llbar; thoghts fro the with other mens prayers, bod if
&thorn;ou doo so&mtail; labur &thorn;erin &thorn;i selfe.  For it is
with the as it is with a ma&ntail; &thorn;at is seke; ffor &amp; a
ma&ntail; &thorn;at is seke wi&llbar; nott abstene hy&mtail; fro
guttus meatis, what profettis it to do vnto hy&mtail; any cure of
lechecrafte?"


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CLIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cogitaciones ex toto nemo fugere possit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how o&ntail; a tyme a certay&ntail; ma&ntail; of
religio&ntail; made playnt vnto a holie abbott &thorn;att hight
Pastor, &thorn;at he had so many thoghtis of sy&ntail; in his mynde
&thorn;at he was like to be perisshi&dtail; &thorn;erwith.  And he had
&thorn;is monke in-to a play&ntail; felde vppo&ntail; a fayr day, whar
&thorn;e wynde blew, &amp; he ba&dtail; hy&mtail; hal&dtail; obrade
his skyrte &amp; take &thorn;e wynde &amp; bere it hame.  An&dtail; he
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail; he myght nott.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e abbott sai&dtail;; "No more may &thorn;ou
lett &thorn;oghtis to co&mtail; in &thorn;i harte &amp; &thorn;i
mynde, bod itt is &thorn;y parte to with-ston&dtail; &thorn;aim." et
c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM>
