<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CLV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cogitacio perpetuitatis penarum inferni aliquando
conuertit hominem.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Jacobus de Vetriaco tellis how &thorn;er was so&mtail; tyme a
seculer ma&ntail; &thorn;at was passand delicate.  So o&ntail; a tyme
he vmthoght hy&mtail; in his mynde, ffurst, if a thowsan&dtail; of
dampny&dtail; sawlis myght be delyver&dtail; fro pay&ntail;, and his
thoght ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; sayd, "nay."  &thorn;a&ntail; if
a hondreth M&lbar; mott be delyuer&dtail;, &amp; his thoght said,
"nay."  &thorn;an if a thowsan&dtail; thowsan&dtail; myght be
delyver&dtail;, &amp; his thoght said, "nay"; and &thorn;a&ntail; if
als many thowsan&dtail; mot be delyver&dtail; as &thorn;er was droppis
of watir in &thorn;e see, &amp; euer it sai&dtail;, "nay."  And as he
was in &thorn;ies thoghtis he was gretlie truble&dtail; &amp;
waxi&dtail; fer&dtail;.  So sodanlie he vmthoght hy&mtail; &amp;
sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; self &thorn;at &thorn;ai &thorn;at giffes
&thorn;er luff vnto &thorn;is werl&dtail; war passan&dtail;
blyn&dtail; &amp; fonde, &thorn;at for a

<PB N="108">

little tyme att &thorn;ai mo&ntail; liff &thorn;erin, for &thorn;e
transitorie delites and vanyties &thorn;eroff, fallis in-to
euerlastan&dtail; dampnacio&ntail; &amp; pay&ntail; of he&llbar;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CLVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cogitacio finis in omnibus operibus est multum
necessaria.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Libro de Dono Timoris,' how o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;er
was a yong ma&ntail; &thorn;att went vnto a fayre; and whe&ntail; he
had walki&dtail; abowte, &amp; sene many shappis &amp; meku&llbar;
chafir to se&llbar;, at &thorn;e laste he come vnto a sho&ptail;
&thorn;er ane ol&dtail; ma&ntail; [st]ude; &amp; he had as who say no
thyng to se&llbar;.  And &thorn;is yong ma&ntail; aski&dtail;
hy&mtail; what at he had <NOTE ID="P108.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, hym what he had.</NOTE> to se&llbar;.  And
&thorn;is alde ma&ntail; answer&dtail; &amp; sayd he had to se&llbar;
wisdo&mtail;; and &thorn;is yong ma&ntail; say&dtail; &thorn;at he
wolde by itt, and aski&dtail; hy&mtail; whatt he sulde pay
&thorn;erfo&rtail;.  And he sai&dtail;, "a hondret&hbar; mar&ktee;."
And &thorn;e toder &thorn;oght itt meku&llbar;, nott-withstondyng he
paye&dtail; hy&mtail; itt.  And whe&ntail; it was paye&dtail;,
&thorn;is olde ma&ntail; taght hy&mtail; &thorn;is wysdo&mtail; &amp;
sai&dtail;; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">In omni opere cogita primo ad quem
finem venire potes, vnde versus; 'Quicquid agas operis finem primo
mediteris.'</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is to say, in a&llbar; &thorn;i
werkis, evur at &thorn;e begynyng vmthynk &thorn;e whatt wi&llbar;
co&mtail; of &thorn;e endyng."  And whe&ntail; &thorn;is yong
ma&ntail; har&dtail; &thorn;is, hy&mtail; forthoght hys barga&ntail;
&amp; traysti&dtail; &thorn;at he had bene deseyvi&dtail;.  Tha&ntail;
&thorn;is olde ma&ntail; sai&dtail;; "Go &thorn;i wais home! and
forgett nott &thorn;is at I tolde &thorn;e, bod write itt in &thorn;i
howse ouer &thorn;i hallyng, &amp; in &thorn;i wyndows, &amp; o&ntail;
&thorn;i duris, &amp; o&ntail; &thorn;i vesse&llbar;, &amp; in
o&thorn;er dyvers places in &thorn;i howse; &amp; &thorn;ou sha&llbar;
fyn&dtail; att it sa&llbar; be &thorn;e best chafir at evur &thorn;ou
boght."  And he wente home &amp; did so.  And emang a&llbar;
o&thorn;er he garte browde &thorn;is reso&ntail; opo&ntail; a clothe
&thorn;at he was vsi&dtail; to be shavy&ntail; with.  So o&ntail; a
tyme &thorn;is yong ma&ntail; had enmys &thorn;at come vnto a barbur
att vsi&dtail; to shafe hy&mtail;, &amp; hyrid hy&mtail; for a grete
so&mtail; of money to sla hy&mtail; whe&ntail; he shufe hy&mtail;;
&amp; he tuke &thorn;er money &amp; grawnti&dtail; &thorn;at he sulde
do so.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;is barbur come to shafe &thorn;is gude
ma&ntail;, as he was in wetyng of hy&mtail; he luki&dtail; vpo&ntail;
&thorn;e raster clathe; &amp; he was somwhatt letter&dtail; &amp; red
&thorn;is reso&ntail;.  And onone as he had red it, he vmbythoght
hy&mtail; what ende wal&dtail; co&mtail; of &thorn;is



<PB N="109">

treso&ntail; &amp; he did itt.  &amp; he said vnto hy&mtail; selfe
&thorn;us; "and I sla &thorn;is ma&ntail; I mo&ntail; be slay&ntail;
&thorn;erfo&rtail;."  And he bega&ntail; to wax faynt &amp; hevie
&amp; swowny&dtail;.  And onone as &thorn;is gude ma&ntail; saw
hy&mtail; fare so, he steppi&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; &amp; lifte&dtail;
hy&mtail; vp o&ntail; his fete, and comfurthe&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp;
aski&dtail; hy&mtail; whatt hy&mtail; ayli&dtail;.  And he
praye&dtail; hy&mtail; to hol&dtail; hy&mtail; excusi&dtail; &amp; be
not wrothe &amp; he sulde te&llbar; hy&mtail;, &amp; he essuri&dtail;
vnto hy&mtail; &thorn;at he sul&dtail; not be wrothe.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is barbur sett &thorn;e spe&llbar; o&ntail;
en&dtail; &amp; tolde hy&mtail; a&llbar; &thorn;e dede.  &amp; he
forgaff hy&mtail; &amp; bad a noder ma&ntail; shafe hy&mtail;.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; he thanki&dtail; God &amp; &thorn;e wisdo&mtail;
&thorn;at he boght, for &thorn;us he fan&dtail; &thorn;at it
savi&dtail; &thorn;er lifes bothe. et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CLVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Columba.  Columbarum nutricio non placet
Deo.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a knight &thorn;at
luffi&dtail; wele to bryng vp &amp; brede dowvis in his place in his
chaw[m]ber-endis, &amp; in dyvers o&thorn;er places.  And his curatt
tolde hy&mtail; &thorn;at it was grete sy&ntail; vnto hy&mtail; for to
kepe so many of &thorn;aim to-gedur, for als meku&llbar; as &thorn;ai
hurte &amp; wasti&dtail; his neghburs cornys.  So o&ntail; a day he
tuke a skuttylfu&llbar; of cor&ntail; &amp; calli&dtail; &thorn;aim
to-gedur &amp; gaff &thorn;aim meate.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai wer
a&llbar; to-gedur befo&rtail; hy&mtail;, he spak vnto &thorn;aim with
a clere voyce &thorn;at a&llbar; me&ntail; myght here, an&dtail; sayde
o&ntail; &thorn;is maner of wyse; "Ye dowvis!  If it be Goddis
wi&llbar; att ye bide with me, dwe&llbar; sti&llbar;, or els I
commawn&dtail; you in Goddis name at ye rise vp, &amp; flee away
faste."  And att &thorn;is wurde, onone a&llbar; &thorn;ies dowvis
rase vpp, &amp; flow clene away in a grete flok&ktee;.  And neuer
after fro thens furt&hbar; &thorn;ai come agay&ntail; vnto his
place. et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
