<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CLVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Commendacio vel commessio.  Commendare vel
committere se diabulo nimis periculosum est.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Helinandus <NOTE ID="P110.N1">MS. Belmandus.</NOTE> tellis how o&ntail; a tyme
&thorn;e archedeky&ntail; of Aurilianens sul&dtail; go vnto Rome.  And
he praye&dtail; a chano&ntail; of his to graunt hy&mtail; a clerk of
his to go with hy&mtail;, &thorn;at hight Nathanael, &thorn;at was a
trew servan&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; for hy&mtail; &thorn;oght at he was
necessarie vnto hy&mtail; in his iorney.  And &thorn;is cler&ktee;,
&thorn;uf a&llbar; it was agayns his wi&llbar;, went with hy&mtail;,
&amp; he made hy&mtail; his purs-maister.  Soo whe&ntail; &thorn;ai
come nere Rome, &thorn;is Archdeky&ntail; was bod a chynche, &amp; he
aski&dtail; &thorn;is clerk a rekkeny&ntail; &amp; a compte of
&thorn;er expensis straytlie vnto &thorn;e leste halpeny.  And
&thorn;er &thorn;ai fe&llbar; vnto rekenyng &amp; vari&dtail;; &amp;
&thorn;is clerk betuke hy&mtail; <NOTE ID="P110.N2">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, hy&mtail;.</NOTE> selfe vnto
&thorn;e devu&llbar;, als witterlie as evur he was in fonte-stone, bod
it was as he sayde.  So &thorn;ai went o&ntail; flytan&dtail;.  And as
&thorn;ai went ow&rtail; at a brygg ou&rtail; a grete watir, &thorn;is
clerk happen&dtail; to fa&llbar; by &thorn;e brygg &amp; was
drowny&dtail;.  And he had made a counan&dtail; befo&rtail; with
&thorn;is Chano&ntail; &thorn;at was his maister, &thorn;at whethur of
&thorn;aim dye&dtail; furste, with-in xxx<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> dayes, &amp; he myght,
sul&dtail; co&mtail; vnto his felow, &amp; hide no thyng bod te&llbar;
hy&mtail; clerelie how it stude with hy&mtail;.  So o&ntail; &thorn;e
nyght afterwar&dtail;, as &thorn;is chano&ntail; lay in his bed
wakan&dtail;, &amp; a byrnan&dtail; lampe befo&rtail; hy&mtail;,
&thorn;is Nathanae&llbar; clerk stude befo&rtail; hy&mtail;, cled as
hy&mtail; thoght a&llbar; in a fayre cape made of feddurs.  And
&thorn;is chano&ntail; was nothyng afer&dtail; of hy&mtail;, bod was
we&llbar; apaye&dtail; of his commyng, and said vnto hy&mtail;;
"Nathanael! welco&mtail; home!  Is nott &thorn;e archedeky&ntail;
comme&ntail;?" and he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;;
"Nay, sur, bod I a&mtail; comme&ntail; as I made counan&dtail; with
you &thorn;at I sul&dtail; do; and I a&mtail; now dea&dtail; &amp; I
pray you to helpe me, for I a&mtail; in grete turmenttis."  And he
aski&dtail; hy&mtail; whi, se&ntail; he liffi&dtail; so honestlie
&amp; so trewlie as he di&dtail;.  And he say&dtail; agay&ntail;;
"Sur, forsuthe it sulde hafe bene wele with me, bod &thorn;is day I
was sodanlie grevi&dtail;, &amp; betaght my selfe vnto &thorn;e
devu&llbar;: and I pray you war&ntail; als many as ye may, at
&thorn;ai do neuer so as I di&dtail;, ffor &thorn;ai &thorn;at
wi&llbar; commen&dtail; &thorn;er selfe vnto &thorn;e devu&llbar;,
&thorn;ai giff hy&mtail; power of &thorn;aim; &amp; so di&dtail; I





<PB N="111">

&thorn;is day, &amp; &thorn;erfor I was drowny&dtail;, &amp; for no
no&thorn;er &thorn;ing a&mtail; I in pay&ntail;."  And &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;is chano&ntail; asky&dtail; hy&mtail;, se&ntail; &thorn;at he
was in pay&ntail;, how it was &thorn;at he ha&dtail; o&ntail; so fayr
a cape.  And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Sur,
&thorn;is cape is hevyer vnto me &thorn;a&ntail; war &thorn;e
gretteste towr in a&llbar; &thorn;is werl&dtail; &amp; it wer o&ntail;
my bak&ktee;.  And &thorn;e fayrnes &thorn;erof is a belefe of
forgifnes &thorn;at I hafe, if at I be trewlie praye&dtail;
fo&rtail;."  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is chano&ntail; hyght
hy&mtail; &thorn;at at hys power he sulde pray for hy&mtail;.  And
with &thorn;at he vanysshi&dtail; away; &amp; he har&dtail; neuer more
o&ntail; hy&mtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CLIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Commestio.  Comedit aliquando vnus plus
quam plures.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Solinus tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a strang knyght, a
ma&ntail; like a grete gian&dtail;, and he was a grete weryor &amp;
alway had &thorn;e victorie whar-evur he faght.  So o&ntail; a tyme as
he was in bata&llbar;, he was passan&dtail; hongrie, &amp; he gatt in
hys armys ane ox, and bare it a-way ane acre lenthe; &amp; with his
neve he slew it &amp; made meatt &thorn;erof, and ete it v&ptail; att
ons a&llbar; be his one.  And it grevi&dtail; hy&mtail; at &thorn;at
tyme no &thorn;ing; bod with-in a little while aftre, he &thorn;at had
victory of a&llbar; o&thorn;er me&ntail; in bate&llbar;, &thorn;urght
his aw&ntail; folie deyed away.

</P>
<P>
