<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CLX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Communio.  Communicare
<NOTE ID="P111.N1">MS. comminicare.</NOTE> frequenter volentes non
sunt prohibendi.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;at in &thorn;e dioces of Leodonens <NOTE ID="P111.N2">Latin MSS. Leodiensis.</NOTE> , in a tow&ntail; &thorn;at hight Chorenbar <NOTE ID="P111.N3">Harl. MS. Corebam.  Arund. MS. Chorenbar.</NOTE> , was &thorn;er a womme&ntail; &thorn;at
desiri&dtail; greatlie oft sithis








<PB N="112">

to be howsel&dtail;.  So o&ntail; a night, as sho lay o&ntail; a
cowche sayan&dtail; hur prayers, almi&yogh;ti Go&dtail; come in-to hur
chawmer, &amp; bare in his handis &thorn;e box at &thorn;e sacrament
was in in &thorn;e kir&ktee;, and &thorn;er come aungels with
hy&mtail;, syngan&dtail; &thorn;is sang; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">speciosus forma pro filijs hominum et c&curl;.</FOREIGN>"
And he stude befo&rtail; hur &amp; sai&dtail;; "Becauce &thorn;e
preste denye&dtail; to giff &thorn;e my bodie, I sa&llbar;
howse&llbar; &thorn;e myne aw&ntail; handis."  &amp; he did so, &amp;
tuke ane hoste oute of &thorn;e box &amp; gaff hur, &amp; went his
wayis.  And &thorn;er was in &thorn;e same chawmber a noder religious
womma&ntail; &thorn;at saw a&llbar; &thorn;is, and o&ntail; &thorn;e
mor&ntail; sho went vnto &thorn;e preste, and aski&dtail; of hy&mtail;
how many hostis war in &thorn;e sacrament-box in &thorn;e kur&ktee;;
and he saide &thorn;at wiste he wele enog&hbar;.  &amp; he
oppyn&dtail; &thorn;e <NOTE ID="P112.N1"><HI REND="i">After</HI> &thorn;e, buke, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> box &amp; luked &amp;
fan&dtail; &thorn;at one was away; &amp; yit a&llbar; was lokki&dtail;
as &thorn;ai war wunte to be; &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; he had grete
mervayle, &amp; wepu&dtail; &amp; made meki&llbar; sorow, and had
grete mer[v]e&llbar; how &thorn;is mott happe&ntail;.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is womma&ntail; comfurthi&dtail; hy&mtail;
&amp; tol&dtail; hy&mtail; a&llbar; &thorn;at evur sho saw, &amp;
wha&rtail; &thorn;e hoste was becomme&ntail;, &amp; cowncel&dtail;
hy&mtail; &thorn;at fro thens furt&hbar; he sulde nevur gruche to giff
&thorn;aim &thorn;e howsy&llbar; &thorn;at asky&dtail; itt, &amp; it
war nevur so ofte. et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Communione nemo debet privari qui secundum

conscienciam suam est sufficienter confessus, et

ad satisfaciendum paratus.  Infra de Iusticia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>


</LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CLXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Communicanti
<NOTE ID="P112.N2">MS. Comminicanti.</NOTE> non est administranda hostia non
consecrata.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;at Maister Maurice, &thorn;at was
bisshop&ptail; of Pariss&hbar;, o&ntail; a tyme was vexi&dtail; with
so grete a seknes in his hea&dtail;, &thorn;at it strake in-to his
bray&ntail;, &amp; tuke away his witt &amp; his mynde fro&mtail;
hy&mtail;.  So at &thorn;e laste he come vnto hy&mtail; selfe, &amp;
axky&dtail; to be howsel&dtail;; &amp; &thorn;ai &thorn;at wer abowte
was fer&dtail; at he had bene falle&ntail; in-to a wudenes; &amp;
&thorn;ai cowncel&dtail; &thorn;e preste to feche ane hoste &thorn;at
was vnsacre&dtail; &amp; giff hy&mtail;; and so he di&dtail;.  And
onone as he come with-in &thorn;e thress&hbar;wol&dtail; of &thorn;e
dure, &thorn;is bisshop&ptail; crye&dtail;





<PB N="113">

with a clere voyce &amp; sayde; "hafe it away! hafe it away! for
&thorn;at is not <NOTE ID="P113.N1">Not, <HI REND="i">omitted and added above the line</HI>.</NOTE> my Lorde."  And a&llbar;
&thorn;at was abowte hy&mtail; had grete wonder here-off; and
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e preste wente agay&ntail; &amp; broght with
hy&mtail; &thorn;e verray sacrament.  And &thorn;is bisshopp with
grete devocio&ntail; reseyvi&dtail; it, &thorn;urg&hbar; vertue of
&thorn;e whilk he come agay&ntail; vnto his right mynde.  And so he in
fu&llbar; faythe &amp; charitie passi&dtail; vnto God&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CLXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Communio
<NOTE ID="P113.N2">MS. Comminio.</NOTE> famem corporalem repellit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Som tyme &thorn;er was a womman &thorn;at be lefe of hur curatt
was euerilk Sonday <NOTE ID="P113.N3"><HI REND="i">Under</HI> Sonday, day, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> howsel&dtail;, an&dtail;
&thorn;at day after sho tuke no bodelie meatt; and yitt sho was
nothyng hongrie.  And onone as hur curatt purseyvi&dtail; &thorn;is,
he went vnto &thorn;e bissho&ptail; &amp; tol&dtail; hy&mtail;; &amp;
he bad hy&mtail; take ane hoste &thorn;at was vnsacre&dtail; &amp;
gyff hur; and so he dy&dtail;.  &amp; &thorn;is womma&ntail;
purseyvi&dtail; it noght, bod tuke it with gude deuocio&ntail; &amp;
went home; &amp; onone as sho come home, sho was so hungre&dtail;,
&thorn;at, as sho thoght, had sho nott titter gette&ntail; hur meatt
sho sulde hafe dye&dtail; furt&hbar;-wit&hbar;.  Yit notwithstondyng
sho ra&ntail; agay&ntail; vnto &thorn;e preste, &amp; trowe&dtail;
&thorn;is honger ha&dtail; bene comme&ntail; o&ntail; hur for hur
synnys, and with grete wepyng how &thorn;at was take&ntail; fro hur
&thorn;at Go&dtail; had giffe&ntail; sho tol&dtail; hy&mtail;.  And
whe&ntail; he har&dtail; &thorn;is he was greatlie reioysy&dtail;
&thorn;eroff, &amp; &thorn;anky&dtail; Go&dtail;, &amp; went with hur
vnto &thorn;e kur&ktee; &amp; gaff hyr &thorn;e verray sacrament.
And &thorn;urg&hbar; &thorn;e vertue hereoff a&llbar; hur hungre was
swagi&dtail;, &amp; &thorn;is grace &thorn;at was withdrawe&ntail;
fro&mtail; hur was giffe&ntail; hur agay&ntail;: and onone as &thorn;e
bisshop&ptail; har&dtail; &thorn;is he &thorn;anki&dtail; almighti
Go&dtail; &thorn;eroff.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CLXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Communio eciam fortitudinem corporalem
confert.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Som tyme &thorn;er was a wurthi knyght whilk &thorn;at did many
eniuries vnto Lowis &thorn;at was Erle of Losens, &amp; to his men.
So o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;is erle compleny&dtail; hy&mtail; of
&thorn;is knyght vnto his frendis.  So o&ntail; of &thorn;aim was a
wurthi ma&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "I dar vndertake &thorn;at I
sa&llbar; take hy&mtail;, &amp; I may be sekur &thorn;at none of you
sa&llbar; do hy&mtail; no bodely








<PB N="114">

har&mtail;."  And &thorn;e erle &amp; a&llbar; made hy&mtail; surans;
and &thorn;is worthi ma&ntail; gatt &thorn;is knyght and
delyver&dtail; hy&mtail; vnto &thorn;e erle.  And &thorn;e erle, in
savyng of his athe, garte make a depe graffe; &amp; he tuke &thorn;is
knyght &amp; wappi&dtail; hy&mtail; in softe clothis &amp; lay&dtail;
hy&mtail; &thorn;erin, &amp; garte caste erthe o&ntail; hy&mtail;,
&amp; so smori&dtail; hy&mtail; to dea&dtail;.  And &thorn;e frendis
of &thorn;is knyght compleny&dtail; of &thorn;is wurthi ma&ntail; vnto
&thorn;e Emperou&rtail; Frederike, &amp; sai&dtail; &thorn;at he for a
grete so&mtail; of money had take&ntail; &thorn;is knyght &amp; solde
hy&mtail; vnto &thorn;e Erle.  And &thorn;e Emperour garte ca&llbar;
hy&mtail; before hy&mtail;, &amp; wolde hafe garte putt hy&mtail; to
deade herefo&rtail;, and he cuthe not be excusy&dtail; for nothyng att
he cuthe say.  And &thorn;a&ntail; at &thorn;e laste he knew &thorn;at
hy&mtail; selfe was nott giltie as &thorn;ai say&dtail;, and
oblissi&dtail; hy&mtail; to profe &thorn;att as right &amp; law wolde;
&amp; &thorn;er he was demy&dtail; to feght &thorn;erfo&rtail;.  And
so a day was sett, &amp; his enmys gatt a strang knyght to feght with
hy&mtail;.  And o&ntail; &thorn;e day att &thorn;ai sulde feght
vppo&ntail;, &thorn;is wurshupfu&llbar; ma&ntail; shrafe hy&mtail;,
&amp; with gude deuocion reseyvi&dtail; hys sacrament &amp; went
boldlie into &thorn;e place &thorn;er &thorn;ai sulde feght; &amp; his
enmy come in manlelie agayns hy&mtail;.  And onone as &thorn;ai mett,
&thorn;is ma&ntail; att was hyri&dtail;, &thorn;at a&llbar; men
har&dtail;, aske&dtail; hy&mtail; if he had ety&ntail; oght &thorn;at
day.  And &thorn;is wurthi ma&ntail; ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
say&dtail;; "ya, I hafe reseyvi&dtail; &amp; ete &thorn;is day
&thorn;e bodie of almighti Go&dtail;."  And &thorn;is other
lurda&ntail; ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;;
"fforsuthe, &amp; &thorn;ou ha&dtail; eaty&ntail; &thorn;e devu&llbar;
&thorn;is day, I sa&llbar; feght with &thorn;e &amp; ouerthraw
&thorn;e."  And evy&ntail; furthwith after &thorn;is wurde of
blasfemyng, almi&yogh;ti God tuke his strent&hbar; fro&mtail;
hy&mtail; &amp; strenthi&dtail; &thorn;is other wurthi ma&ntail; so,
&thorn;at his enmy &thorn;at was hyri&dtail; agayns hy&mtail; had no
more strent&hbar;, nor myght no more stan&dtail; to feght with
hy&mtail; &thorn;a&ntail; he had bene a childe, vnto so meku&llbar; he
gaff ou&rtail; &thorn;e bate&llbar; &amp; hel&dtail; hy&mtail; selfe
as owrecomme&ntail;.  And &thorn;us &thorn;is trew knyght, be etyng of
&thorn;e bodie of almighti Go&dtail;, had a glorious victorie.

</P>
