<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CLXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Compaciendum est leprosis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Jacobus de Vetriaco tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a
worthi ladie, &amp; sho had grete petie of seke folk, &amp; speciallie
of lepre me&ntail;.  And hur husban&dtail; was a myghti ma&ntail;,
&amp; he had lepre folk in so grete vgsomnes &thorn;at he myght not
suffer to se &thorn;aim, nor lat &thorn;aim co&mtail; with-in his
howse.  So o&ntail; a day as a lepre ma&ntail; was cryan&dtail; at his
yate, &thorn;e ladie come to hy&mtail; &amp; aski&dtail; hy&mtail; if
he wol&dtail; owder eate or dryn&ktee;, and he ansswer&dtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "I a&mtail; here hugelie turment with
hete of &thorn;e so&ntail;, &amp; I wi&llbar; nowder eate nor drynk
bod if &thorn;ou take me into &thorn;i place."  And sho ansswer&dtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "knowis &thorn;ou not how my
husban&dtail; vgis to see lepros men?  &amp; he wi&llbar; onone
co&mtail; home fro huntyng, &amp; if he fynde &thorn;e with-in his
place, happelie he wi&llbar; sla bothe &thorn;e and me."  And he
wepi&dtail; &amp; made sorow.  So at &thorn;e laste &thorn;is ladie
might no langer se hy&mtail; wepe, &amp; sho tuke hy&mtail; v&ptail;
in hur armys &amp; bare hy&mtail; into hur place, and &thorn;a&ntail;
sho praye&dtail; hy&mtail; to eate.  He sai&dtail; agay&ntail; he
wal&dtail; nowder eat nor drynk bod if sho bare hy&mtail; vnto hur
chamber &amp; layde hy&mtail; in hur aw&ntail; be&dtail;, &amp;
&thorn;er he wolde riste hy&mtail; awhile &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; he
wol&dtail; eate.  And he made so meku&llbar; sorow &thorn;at sho mot
not suffre itt, &thorn;at sho had hy&mtail; vnto hur chawmer &amp;
lai&dtail; hy&mtail; in hur be&dtail;, &amp; sho lai&dtail; a softe
cod vndernethe his hea&dtail; &amp; happed hy&mtail; with a gay
couerla&dtail;.  And &thorn;is done, onone hur husban&dtail; come home
fro huntyng &amp; bad hur oppy&ntail; hy&mtail; &thorn;e chamber dure,
&amp; he wol&dtail; lay hy&mtail; dow&ntail; &amp; slepe a while;
&amp; sho was fer&dtail; at he sul&dtail; sla bothe &thorn;e lepre
ma&ntail; &amp; hur, &amp; made hur to tarie a while, &amp;
wol&dtail;e not co&mtail; &amp; oppy&ntail; &thorn;e dure redelie.
&amp; he seyng at sho tari&dtail; &amp; wol&dtail; nott co&mtail;,
brest oppy&ntail; &thorn;e dure in a grete anger and went in-to
&thorn;e chamb&rtail;.  An&dtail; onone he come bakk agay&ntail; &amp;
mett his wyfe &amp; sayde vnto hur; "Now &thorn;ou hase done wele; for
&thorn;ou hase araye&dtail; our be&dtail; o&ntail; &thorn;e beste
wise, bod I mervay&llbar; whare &thorn;ou gat so gude spicis
&thorn;urg&hbar; whilk a&llbar; our chawmer is fylli&dtail; so
fu&llbar; of gude savir with, for onone as I come into &thorn;e
chaw[m]ber, &thorn;er was &thorn;erin so swete a savur at me thoght I
was in paradice."  And whe&ntail; sho &thorn;at befo&rtail; was
fer&dtail; for hur dea&dtail; har&dtail; &thorn;is, sho went in-to
&thorn;e

<PB N="118">

chamber with hy&mtail; &amp; fand it as he sayde; &amp;
&thorn;a&ntail; sho tol&dtail; hy&mtail; a&llbar; how scho had done;
&amp; &thorn;ai luki&dtail; in &thorn;e be&dtail; and &thorn;is lepre
ma&ntail; was away.  And &thorn;a&ntail; hur husbon&dtail; &thorn;at
befo&rtail; was als wude as a lyo&ntail;, wex als meke as a lambe,
&amp; evur afterwar&dtail; luffi&dtail; God &amp; leplere me&ntail;
better.

</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Compati debet prelatus subditis temptatis.  Supra

