</LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXCV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Consolacio diuina allicit hominem ad manendum
in ecclesia.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis of a mon&ktee; of Ceustus ordur, &thorn;at had a
grace and a lefe, for feblenes att his body was in, for to ly in his
be&dtail; &amp; not co&mtail; att matyns at mydnyght; &amp; yitt for
a&llbar; &thorn;at he myght not reste in his bed in maty&ntail; tyme,
bod &thorn;at reste at he had, hy&mtail; bur&dtail; hafe it in
&thorn;e kur&ktee;.  So o&ntail; a day his brether chalangi&dtail;
hy&mtail; &thorn;erfo&rtail;, &amp; sai&dtail; se&ntail; he was so
wayke  of hy&mtail; selfe, at hy&mtail; wer bettir for to reste hy&mtail; in his
be&dtail; &thorn;a&ntail; for to co&mtail; vnto &thorn;e kur&ktee;,
&amp; specialli becauce he had lefe.  He ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail;
&amp; sai&dtail;; "Whe&ntail; I here my brethir syng, &amp; I be not with
&thorn;aim, &thorn;a&ntail; I a&mtail; mervoloslie truble&dtail; and
turment in my harte; &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; I wax hevy whe&ntail; I
vmthynk me &thorn;at &thorn;e comfurt&hbar; at God duse vnto
&thorn;aim &thorn;er did it so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er vnto me.
&amp; &thorn;uf a&llbar; I may nott helpe &thorn;aim, yit it comfurthis me
gretelie to here &thorn;aim."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXCVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Consolacio diuina non conceditur admittentibus
alienam.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a monke in Ceustus
ordur, and he was <NOTE ID="P135.N2">MS <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, was.</NOTE> a leche &amp; ra&ntail;
&thorn;urg&hbar; &thorn;e cuntre ilk day, &thorn;at vnnethis he wolde
be att hame at his abbay o&ntail; hy dayes.  So it happen&dtail;
opo&ntail; a night, in &thorn;e solempnyte of ou&rtail; Ladie, as he
stude at matyns




<PB N="136">

syngan&dtail; emangis his felos, he saw our Ladie Saynt [Marie]
co&mtail; in-to &thorn;e where, &amp; broght a boyste fu&llbar; of
lectuarie; &amp; sho putt &thorn;erof in-to evur-ilk monk mouthe with
a spone.  And whe&ntail; sho come att hy&mtail; sho sai&dtail;;
"&thorn;ou mysters not of my lectuarie, for &thorn;ou erte a leche
&amp; takis &thorn;ine aw&ntail; comfurt&hbar; at &thorn;e fu&llbar;":
&amp; so he ha&dtail; none.  And fro &thorn;ine furt&hbar;, bod if he
had bene compelli&dtail;, he wol&dtail; neuer oute of his abbay, nor
he had neuer after dayntie of bodelie medcy&ntail;.  So &thorn;e next
ffeste of our Ladie sho come agay&ntail;, &amp; did vnto &thorn;e
monkis as sho di&dtail; before; and whe&ntail; sho come att &thorn;is
mon&ktee;, sho sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "Becauce &thorn;ou hase had
mo&rtail; comfurt&hbar; of me &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ou had of
&thorn;i lechecrafte or <NOTE ID="P136.N1">MS. of of.</NOTE> of &thorn;i medcyns,
&thorn;erfo&rtail; I sa&llbar; giff &thorn;e of my medcyns."  And
whe&ntail; he had tasti&dtail; &thorn;eroff, onone he fel&dtail; suche
a swetnes, &thorn;at euer fro thens furt&hbar; he was so stable in his
ordur &thorn;at he refusi&dtail; a&llbar; maner of o&thorn;er
&thorn;ing.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXCVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Constans debet esse religiosus in omnibus, tam
prosperis quam aduersis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis of a monk of &thorn;e same ordur, &thorn;at
di&dtail; many grete meracles.  So his abbott aski&dtail; hy&mtail;
o&ntail; a tyme, how he had &thorn;at grace befo&rtail; a&llbar; his
brethir to do so many meracles.  And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail;
&amp; sai&dtail;; "I wote nevur, for I pray no more, nor fastis no
more, nor wakis no more, &thorn;a&ntail; duse myne other brether, nor
laburs no more; bod I know <NOTE ID="P136.N2"><HI REND="i">After</HI> know, n and some other letter, <HI REND="i">blotted</HI>.</NOTE> a thyng.  Ther may
no prosperite make me prow&dtail;, nor none aduersitie make me
displesi&dtail; nowder of my selfe nor of o&thorn;er."  And &thorn;e
abbo&dtail; askid hy&mtail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "Was &thorn;ou not
trubble&dtail; whe&ntail; suche a knyght byrny&dtail; our grange?"
And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Nay! for I
betaght &thorn;e rewar&dtail; &thorn;erof vnto almighti Go&dtail;; and
whe&thorn;er I hafe meku&llbar; or little, euer I than&ktee;
allmighti God &thorn;erof, &amp; takis it with gude wi&llbar;, ffor I
hafe dispyse&dtail; &amp; forsake&ntail; a&llbar; &thorn;e riches of
&thorn;is werl&dtail;." et c&curl;.

</P>
