<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CXCIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Contemplacioni modus apponendus est.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Heraclius <NOTE ID="P138.N1">Latin MSS.  Heraclides.</NOTE> tellis how &thorn;at Alexandrus
<NOTE ID="P138.N2">Latin MSS.  Alexandrinus Macharius.</NOTE> Macharius tol&dtail; hy&mtail; o&ntail; a tyme
&amp; say&dtail;, &thorn;at som tyme a vayne covatice of thoghtis of
vanytie occupye&dtail; his mynde, at he wal&dtail; certay&ntail; dayes
contynuallie bere hys myn&dtail; vnseuerable, to so meku&llbar;
&thorn;at he wal&dtail; spar his duris at no ma&ntail; sulde speke
with hy&mtail;, nor hafe ane ansswer of hy&mtail;.  And he wol&dtail;
flite with his aw&ntail; myn&dtail; &amp; say vnto hit; "vmbe-se
&thorn;e att &thorn;ou fa&llbar; not fro hevy&ntail; vnto ert&hbar;;
ffor &thorn;er &thorn;ou hase &thorn;i creatur &amp; a&llbar; angels
&amp; saynttis.  Thin&ktee; of a&llbar; &thorn;ies."  And &thorn;us
he contynue&dtail; ij dayes &amp; ij nyghtis; and &thorn;a&ntail; he
feli&dtail; &thorn;e devu&llbar; prikki&dtail; hy&mtail; so, att
hy&mtail; &thorn;oght att a&llbar; his ce&llbar; fe&llbar; opo&ntail;
hy&mtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CC.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Contemplacioni sic est insistendum, vt accio non
necligatur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' how a bruther o&ntail; a tyme come in
pylgramege vnto a place of monkis &thorn;at was at &thorn;e
mownt&curl; of Synay, &amp; &thorn;er he say &thorn;e monkis labur
&amp; grafe &thorn;at &thorn;ai sul&dtail; saw cor&ntail;.  And he
sai&dtail; vnto &thorn;aim in &thorn;is maner of wise; "Whie wurke ye
for meatt &thorn;at wi&llbar; do bo&dtail; waste &amp; periss&hbar;
away?  Remembre you of Marie Magdaly&ntail;, how sho did no bodelie
labur, &amp; yitt our Lor&dtail; sayde &thorn;at sho had chosy&ntail;
&thorn;e bettir parte."  And whe&ntail; &thorn;er abbott harde
te&llbar; of &thorn;is, he bad a disciple of his giff &thorn;is
ma&ntail; a buke, &amp; putt hy&mtail; in a ce&llbar; &thorn;at nothyng was
in.  And at how&rtail; of none &thorn;is ma&ntail; luki&dtail;
furt&hbar; if any ma&ntail; calli&dtail; hy&mtail; to mete; &amp;
&thorn;er was none att calli&dtail; hy&mtail;.  And after none
&thorn;e abbott come vnto hy&mtail; &amp; sayde; "how duse &thorn;ou?"
And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Sir Abbott!  Ete
none of your brethir no meate to-day?"  and &thorn;e abbott
say&dtail;; "yis."  And &thorn;a&ntail; he askid whi &thorn;ai
calli&dtail; not hy&mtail; to dener; &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is abbott
ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; sayde: "Thow





<PB N="139">

erte a spiritua&llbar; ma&ntail; &amp; mysters no meatt; and we er
flesshlie me&ntail; &amp; bus nedelyngis eatt; &amp;
&thorn;erfo&rtail; we wur&ktee; with oure handis."  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;is <NOTE ID="P139.N1">MS. his.</NOTE> bruther har&dtail; &thorn;is, he
bega&ntail; to forthynk at he had sai&dtail;, &amp; say&dtail; vnto
hy&mtail; selfe; "Now I know wele att it is necessarie to ioy&ntail;
&thorn;e life of Martha with &thorn;e life of Magdale&ntail;:
&thorn;at is to say, vmwhile to vse spiritua&llbar; life &amp; vmwhile
to vse contemplatyfe life," &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; he fe&llbar; to werk
and di&dtail; as &thorn;ai di&dtail;.

</P>
<P>
