<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Contemptus mundi.  Contempni debent omnia
exemplo philosophorum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Jero&mtail; tellis of a ma&ntail; &thorn;at hight
Socraticus, and o&ntail; a tyme his gudis wer a&llbar; tane fro
hy&mtail; safeyng a manti&llbar;.  And he had a disciple &thorn;at
hight Diogenes, &amp; he had no gude lefte bo&dtail; a skri&ptail;
an&dtail; taber&dtail; &amp; his vvermest clothe to hy&llbar;
hy&mtail; wit&hbar;; &amp; in his scri&ptail; he bare his meatt.  And
he had no howse bod a tome to&ntail;, &amp; hy&mtail; &thorn;oght
&thorn;att was a noble howse; &amp; in wynter whe&ntail; it was
cal&dtail;, he wal&dtail; evur tur&ntail; &thorn;is to&ntail; mouthe
vnto &thorn;e sowthe, &amp; in sommer he wal&dtail; tur&ntail; it into
&thorn;e northe, &amp; evur as &thorn;e so&ntail; turny&dtail;
wol&dtail; he tur&ntail; his to&ntail;.  And he had kepi&dtail; hy&mtail;
no gude bod alonelie a copp of tre to drynk opo&ntail;.  So o&ntail; a
tyme he saw a childe take vp&ptail; watir in &thorn;e luff of his
han&dtail; &amp; drynk &thorn;erof; and whe&ntail; he saw &thorn;at he
caste away his cop&ptail; &amp; say&dtail; &thorn;at he wiste neuer
&thorn;at natur had giffe&ntail; a ma&ntail; a vesse&llbar; to
dryn&ktee; off. et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Contempni[et] elongari debet turba hominum.  Infra
