<PB N="140">

</LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Contempni debent dignitates.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Heraclides tellis how &thorn;at a gude holie ma&ntail; &thorn;at
hight Animonus <NOTE ID="P140.N1">Latin MSS. Animosus.</NOTE> opo&ntail; a tyme was gretlie
desiri&dtail; to be a bisshop&ptail; with &thorn;e commo&ntail; peple,
to so meku&llbar; &thorn;e cetisens tuke hy&mtail; &amp; say&dtail; he
sul&dtail; be &thorn;er bisshop&ptail; magre his tethe.  An&dtail; he
saw &thorn;at he myght not esskape &thorn;aim, and he tuke ane
yr&ntail; &amp; pulli&dtail; of his lefte ere of his heade har&dtail;
be &thorn;e rutis, at a&llbar; me&ntail; mot se.  And &thorn;a&ntail;
he sai&dtail;; "Now may ye see at I may nott be a bisshop&ptail;, for
&thorn;e law wi&llbar; not at a ma&ntail; be made a bisshop&ptail;
&amp; owder of his eris be off."  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;er was a
bisshop&ptail; &thorn;at hight Dorotheus, &amp; he sai&dtail; vnto
[&thorn;e] peple &thorn;at &thorn;e Iewis kepi&dtail; &thorn;at law;
"Bod emang vs Criste&ntail; me&ntail; I doute not &thorn;at &amp; a
ma&ntail; bothe eris war cutt off, &amp; his maners wer gude &amp; honest,
bod he wer wurthie to be a bisshop&ptail; &amp; myght be made ane."
And whe&ntail; &thorn;e peple har&dtail; &thorn;is &thorn;ai
sai&dtail; he sulde be &thorn;er bisshop&ptail; magre his tethe.  And
whe&ntail; he saw &thorn;at, he was wrothe, &amp; sai&dtail;;
"fforsut&hbar;! and ye make me bisshop&ptail;, I sa&llbar; cutt oute
my tong at ye sa&llbar; nott witt what I say."  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai
har&dtail; &thorn;is, &thorn;ai lete hy&mtail; go.

</P>
