</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Contricio perfecta nullam penam corporalem
formidat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; a preste was
prechand &amp; tellan&dtail; of synnys &amp; &thorn;e paynys of
he&llbar;, a womma&ntail; cried vnto hy&mtail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Sur,
whatt sa&llbar; wurt&hbar; of prestes lemmans?"  And he knew sho was
bod a symple thyng &amp; ansswer&dtail; halfe in sporte &amp;
sai&dtail;; "Thai sa&llbar; nevur be savi&dtail; bod if &thorn;ai
crepe into a hate ove&ntail;."  And sho was a prestis lemma&ntail;,
&amp; sho tuke not &thorn;is wurde in bowrte, bod o&ntail; a day sho
hate a grete ove&ntail;, and no-bodie with hur; &amp; whe&ntail; it
was rede hate sho sparri&dtail; &thorn;e duris to hur &amp; crape into
it.  An&dtail; onone sho was burnyd to dea&dtail;.  And &thorn;er was
a grete felashup&ptail; of me&ntail; &amp; womme&ntail; standan&dtail;
samen with-oute, nerehan&dtail; hur place, and &thorn;aim &thorn;oght
&thorn;ai saw a white dowfe fle fro hur howse vnto heve&ntail;.  And
&thorn;ai had grete wonder &thorn;eroff, and brak up&ptail; hur duris;
&amp; &thorn;ai fande hur burny&dtail; of dea&dtail; in &thorn;e
ove&ntail;, &amp; &thorn;ai drew hur oute &amp; beri&dtail; hur in
&thorn;e felde as me&ntail; duse with &thorn;aim att kyllis &thorn;er



<PB N="142">

selfe.  So afterwar&dtail; a&llbar;mighti God wol&dtail; latt it be
knawe&ntail; &thorn;at sho slew not hur selfe of malece nor of
i&llbar; wi&llbar;, bod for penans &amp; obediens; opo&ntail; nightis
&thorn;er was sene a huge light abowte hur grafe.  &amp;
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai tuke hur vp&ptail; &amp; lay&dtail; hur in
Crystens mans beria&llbar;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Contricio perfecta eciam sine confessione delet
peccata.</FOREIGN></HEAD> 


<P> Cesarius tellis how o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;er was a scoler at
Pariss&hbar;, &thorn;at had done many vglie sy&ntail;, &amp; he
wol&dtail; not shrife hy&mtail; of &thorn;aim for shame;
notwithstondyng hertelie contricio&ntail; oue&rtail;-come his shame,
&amp; o&ntail; a tyme he come vnto &thorn;e priour of Saynt&curl;
Victors, &amp; wol&dtail; hafe bene shrevy&ntail;.  &amp; &thorn;er
was so meku&llbar; contricio&ntail; in his harte, &amp; so many sobbis
in his breste, &amp; so many syghyngis in his throte, &amp; so many
teris in his ee&ntail;, &thorn;at he mot not speke nor say a
wur&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e priour saw &thorn;is, he bad
hy&mtail; go &amp; write his sy&ntail;; and so he di&dtail;; and come
agay&ntail;, &amp; yitt for sorow he myght not speke a wur&dtail;, bod
gaff &thorn;is by&llbar; vnto &thorn;e priour.  And he red it, &amp;
hy&mtail; thoght &thorn;e synnys wer so grete at he desyri&dtail;
&thorn;e scolar &thorn;at he mott latt his abbott se itt, at he myght
aske hy&mtail; cownce&llbar; &thorn;erin.  And he lete &thorn;e abbott
se it; and whe&ntail; &thorn;e abbott luki&dtail;
&thorn;er-vppo&ntail;, he cuthe se nothyng wrette&ntail; &thorn;erin;
&amp; &thorn;a&ntail; he sai&dtail; vnto &thorn;e priour; "What may I
rede here, wha&rtail; right noght is wrette&ntail;?"  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;e priour saw &thorn;att, he had grete wondre &thorn;erof &amp;
sai&dtail;; "Sur, forsuthe a yong ma&ntail; wrate his confessio&ntail;
here-vppo&ntail;, and I red&dtail; it my selfe; bot now I se &thorn;at
God is mercifu&llbar;, &thorn;at graciouslie hase behalde&ntail; his
contricio&ntail; and forgiffe&ntail; hy&mtail; his sy&ntail;."  And
&thorn;us bothe &thorn;e abbott &amp; &thorn;e priour tol&dtail;
&thorn;is scolar &amp; assoyli&dtail; hy&mtail;; and &thorn;us with
grete ioy &amp; myrt&hbar; he went fro &thorn;aim home vnto his
lugyng.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Contricio perfecta peccata remittit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a womma&ntail;
&thorn;at lete hur aw&ntail; so&ntail; gett hur a bar&ntail;; and
whe&ntail; &thorn;is bar&ntail; was bor&ntail;, sho bare

<PB N="143">

it in hur armys vnto Rome, &amp; &thorn;er with grete wepyng &amp;
sorow, sho shrafe hur vnto Pope Innocent afo&rtail; a&llbar; his
cardinallis.  And &thorn;e pope enioyny&dtail; hur vnto penance at sho
sul&dtail; co&mtail; befo&rtail; hy&mtail; o&ntail; &thorn;e
mor&ntail; in &thorn;e same clothyng at sho had o&ntail; whe&ntail;
sho went to sy&ntail; with hur so&ntail;.  And o&ntail; &thorn;e
mor&ntail; sho di&dtail; of a&llbar; hur clothyng, and in hur sarke
alone sho come afo&rtail; &thorn;e pope, and sai&dtail; sho was redi
to fulfi&llbar; whatt penance so&mtail;-euer he wol&dtail;
enioy&ntail; hur.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e pope saw &thorn;att, he
sai&dtail; vnto hur; "&thorn;i sy&ntail; is forgyffe&ntail; the."  And
one of &thorn;e cardynals whe&ntail; he har&dtail; &thorn;is,
bega&ntail; to gruche agay&ntail; &thorn;e pope, &amp; sai&dtail; he
demy&dtail; vnsufficientlie.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e pope
sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "and I hafe demy&dtail; i&llbar;, &thorn;e
devu&llbar; entre into me; and if I hafe wele demy&dtail;, &thorn;e
same happe&ntail; &thorn;e, becauce at &thorn;ou gruchi&dtail;
here-in."  And onone att a&llbar; saw at wer aboute, &thorn;e
devu&llbar; bega&ntail; to vex &thorn;is cardina&llbar;, becauce att
he gruchi&dtail; &thorn;at &thorn;e pope declari&dtail; vnto &thorn;is
womma&ntail; &thorn;at hur sy&ntail; was forgyffy&ntail; hur.

</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Contricio perfecta per opera manifestatur.  Infra de

