</LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Contricio perfecta liberat a confusione
temporali.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was in Englan&dtail; a
clark &thorn;at was a chano&ntail; in Lincol&ntail; Mynster, and he
was nere sybb cussy&ntail; vnto &thorn;e bisshop&ptail;.  &amp;
&thorn;er was a Iew wonny&dtail; in &thorn;e tow&ntail;, &amp; he had
a fayr doghter: and &thorn;is cler&ktee; labur&dtail; hur so att sho
promysi&dtail; hy&mtail; att he sul&dtail; lyg by hyr, bod sho
sai&dtail; hur fadur luffi&dtail; hur so wele &amp; kepid hur so
&thorn;at &thorn;ai myght nott co&mtail; samen bod on Gude Fryday
nyght; ffor &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e Iewis hase bludie flux, &amp;
&thorn;ai vse little to be occupye&dtail; or co&mtail; forwar&dtail;.
And whe&ntail; &thorn;at night come, &thorn;is chano&ntail; hafeyng no
myn&dtail; of &thorn;e Passio&ntail; of Criste &thorn;at he
suffre&dtail; as &thorn;at day, come vnto hur &amp; lay with hur vnto
o&ntail; &thorn;e mor&ntail;.  And hur fadur rase &amp; come in-to
&thorn;e chamb&rtail; &thorn;er sho lay, &amp; saw a ma&ntail; in
bed&dtail; with his doghter, &amp; he thoght for to hafe slay&ntail;
hy&mtail;.  And whe&ntail; he luki&dtail;

<PB N="144">

o&ntail; hy&mtail;, he knew wele enog&hbar; at he was &thorn;e
bisschoppis cussy&ntail;, and &thorn;erfo&rtail; he was afer&dtail; to
sla hy&mtail;; &amp; he crye&dtail; with a hedus voyce &amp;
say&dtail;; "O! &thorn;ou fals Christe&ntail; ma&ntail;! what duse
&thorn;ou here in sy&ntail; &thorn;is day?  Wha&rtail; is &thorn;i
fait&hbar;?  Be &thorn;e dome of God rightwuslie &thorn;ou ert
giffe&ntail; in-to ow&rtail; handis; and war&ntail; it wer for drede
of &thorn;e bissho&ptail; at &thorn;ou ert cussy&ntail; vnto, onone I
sulde sla the."  And &thorn;us with grete confusio&ntail; he
showe&dtail; hy&mtail; oute att &thorn;e dure; and he went home, &amp;
happen&dtail; &thorn;at day, &thorn;at is to say
Pasc&hbar;-eve&ntail;, to be assigne&dtail; be &thorn;e bisshop&ptail;
to be his deky&ntail; in serves tyme &amp; rede &thorn;e pistle; &amp;
he was fer&dtail; as o&ntail; suc&hbar; a day to commytt his offes
vnto ane other ma&ntail;, for drede of suspecte; &amp; he was also
fer&dtail; to co&mtail; nere &thorn;e alta&rtail; &amp; &thorn;e halie
sacrament with so grete sy&ntail; as he was in.  And yitt for shame he
myght nott fyn&dtail; in his harte to shryfe hy&mtail;, so he was
&thorn;us ouercomme&ntail; with shame, &amp; di&dtail; o&ntail; his
mes clothis, &amp; stude att &thorn;e alta&rtail; befo&rtail; &thorn;e
bisshop&ptail;.  And sodanlie &thorn;is Iew and a grete meneya of
o&thorn;er Iewis with hy&mtail; come in att &thorn;e mynster dure with
a huge durdo&mtail; &amp; a noyse, ffor to make complaynt vnto
&thorn;e bysshop&ptail; of his cussy&ntail;.  And als tyte as
&thorn;is yong chano&ntail; saw &thorn;aim, he wex pale &amp; was
passan&dtail; fer&dtail;, and made his prayer vnto God in his harte,
&amp; sayd &thorn;us; "Lorde Iesu! delyuer me &amp; safe me shameles
of &thorn;is Iewis at &thorn;is tyme, and I beheste &thorn;e hertelie
&thorn;at I sa&llbar; shryfe me of &thorn;is sy&ntail; &amp; make a
sethe &thorn;erfo&rtail;; &amp; fro hens furth I sa&llbar; no more
offen&dtail; &thorn;e."  So &thorn;is bisshop&ptail; saw &thorn;ies
Iewis &amp; had grete mervayle whatt &thorn;ai did in &thorn;e
kur&ktee;, &amp; speciallie suche a day; and he commaundi&dtail;
&thorn;aim to stan&dtail;, &amp; aski&dtail; &thorn;aim what &thorn;ai
mente.  And onone as &thorn;ai wol&dtail; hafe accusi&dtail; &thorn;is
cler&ktee;, be &thorn;e vertue of God, &thorn;ai wer a&llbar; dombe,
&amp; myght nott speke. &amp; whe&ntail; &thorn;e bisshop&ptail; saw
&thorn;aim gaspe with &thorn;er mowthis agayns hy&mtail; &amp; mott
speke no wurde, he trowi&dtail; att &thorn;ai come for illusio&ntail;
of &thorn;e sacrament, &amp; with indignacio&ntail; <NOTE ID="P144.N1">MS. with indignacio&ntail; &amp;.</NOTE> he commanddi&dtail; &thorn;aim to be put oute of
&thorn;e mynster.  An&dtail; &thorn;is cler&ktee; feli&dtail; att God
had had mercie o&ntail; hy&mtail;; &amp; whe&ntail; serves was done,
he went vnto &thorn;e bysshop&ptail; &amp; shrafe hy&mtail;, and
afterwer&dtail; made hy&mtail; a mon&ktee; in Ceustus ordur.  And
&thorn;ai garte criste&ntail; &thorn;is damyse&llbar;, &amp; made hur
a no&ntail; of &thorn;e same ordur; and afterwar&dtail; &thorn;ai
bothe wer gude halie liffers.



<PB N="145">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Contricione sola deficiente, confessio nec aliqua
bona sufficiunt ad peccati dimissionem.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Som tyme &thorn;er was a yong ma&ntail; &thorn;at was a
chano&ntail; in Pariss&hbar;, &thorn;at liffid incontinent and
delicatelie, &amp; did many grevos sy&ntail;.  So o&ntail; a tyme he
was passan&dtail; seke, &amp; shrafe hy&mtail; &amp; made sorow for
his sy&ntail; &amp; hight to amend hy&mtail;, and reseyvi&dtail; his
sacrament, &amp; was enoynti&dtail;; and so he dye&dtail; &amp; was
wurthelie beri&dtail;.  So with-in a few dayes after he was deade, he
apperi&dtail; vnto ane &thorn;at he was familiarie with, &amp;
tol&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;at he was dampny&dtail;, &amp; sai&dtail;
&thorn;uff a&llbar; he war shreve&ntail; &amp; howsel&dtail; &amp;
enoynti&dtail;, &amp; beheste to do penance, yit he said he forgatt a
thyng, withoute &thorn;e whilk a&llbar; o&thorn;er &thorn;inges may
nott profett.  And he aski&dtail; hy&mtail; what was &thorn;att, &amp;
he sai&dtail;; "Contricio&ntail;; ffor &thorn;uf a&llbar;," he said,
"I promytt to lefe my sy&ntail;, yit my consciens sai&dtail; vnto me:
`what &amp; I men&dtail;, I sa&llbar; fa&llbar; vnto sy&ntail;
agay&ntail;'; ffor my harte more declynyd vnto &thorn;at
&thorn;a&ntail; not for to sy&ntail;.  &amp; &thorn;erfor I had no
faste purpos in gudnes, &amp; so be &thorn;e consequent, I had no
perfite contricio&ntail;, &amp; &thorn;erfo&rtail; I a&mtail;
dampned."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Contricio perfecta eciam in iudicio dei peccata
remittit quo ad culpam, et quo ad penam.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Jacobus de Vetriaco tellis how &thorn;er was a damyse&llbar;
&thorn;at synny&dtail; with hur <NOTE ID="P145.N1">MS. &thorn;er.</NOTE> fadur in
sy&ntail; of lichorie, &amp; hur moder o&ntail; a tyme purseyvi&dtail;
itt &amp; blamy&dtail; hur &amp; reprovi&dtail; hur
&thorn;erfo&rtail;, vnto so mekle, sho slew hur moder.  And whe&ntail;
hur fadur wiste &thorn;is, he had hur in hatere&dtail;; and whe&ntail;
sho pursayvi&dtail; &thorn;is, as hur fadur was slepan&dtail;
vndernethe a matres, sho smory&dtail; hy&mtail; odea&dtail;, &amp;
&thorn;a&ntail; sho become a commo&ntail; womma&ntail;.  And o&ntail;
a tyme a gude holie ma&ntail; prechi&dtail;, and hur happend to be at
his sermo&ntail;; and he tolde meku&llbar; of &thorn;e mercye of
a&llbar;-myghti Go&dtail;, vnto so meku&llbar; &thorn;at whe&ntail;
his sermo&ntail; was done, sho come vnto hy&mtail; with grete
contricio&ntail;, &amp; shrafe hur



<PB N="146">

of a&llbar; hur synys, &amp; aske&dtail; hy&mtail; if &thorn;e mercie
of Go&dtail; was so grete as he preche&dtail; att it was.  And he
ansswer&dtail; &amp; sai&dtail; &thorn;at it was meku&llbar; more;
an&dtail; &thorn;a&ntail; sho bad hy&mtail; enioyne hur penans, for
sho trusti&dtail; meki&llbar; in his mercie.  And he vmthoght
hy&mtail; &thorn;at he cuthe not so sodanlie enioy&ntail; hur
helefu&llbar; penance for hur sy&ntail; &thorn;at was so grete.  And
he bad hir abide vnto after meate, &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; he wol&dtail;
preche agay&ntail;; "&amp; &thorn;a&ntail;," he sai&dtail;, "I
sa&llbar; giff &thorn;e penans."  And sho ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Sur, I trow ye be in dispayr of my
sawle heale."  &amp; he say&dtail;; "Nay! bod in stede of penance, I
enioy&ntail; &thorn;e to abyde here in &thorn;i prayers so lang."  And
so sho di&dtail;.  And in &thorn;e mene-while sho had so meku&llbar;
sorow &amp; contricio&ntail; for hur sy&ntail;, &thorn;at hur harte
breste in two, &amp; sho dye&dtail;.  And &thorn;is was onone
tol&dtail; &thorn;is prechur how it was, &amp; he commawndi&dtail;
&thorn;e pepu&llbar; hertely to pray for hur; and as &thorn;ai wer in
&thorn;er prayers, &thorn;a&rtail; come a voyce vnto &thorn;aim fro
hevy&ntail;, &thorn;at say&dtail;; "Pray not for hur, for sho is in
hevy&ntail;.  Bod pray vnto hir &thorn;er, for to pray for you."

</P>
