<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Corporale Altaris sanguinem emisit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in `Gestis Beati Gregorij,' how &thorn;er was a wurthi
ma&ntail; &thorn;at was knowe&ntail; with Saynt Gregur; and he sent
vnto hy&mtail; messangers an&dtail; prayed hy&mtail; to send hy&mtail;
so&mtail; relikkis owder of appostels or martyrs.  And he
reseyvi&dtail; &thorn;aim honestlie &amp; helde



<PB N="150">

&thorn;aim with hy&mtail; a gude while, and went with &thorn;aim vnto
dyvers placis of Saynttis &thorn;at &thorn;ai aski&dtail; relikkis of,
&amp; sang mes &thorn;er. So att &thorn;e laste he tuke smale pecis of
ilk corprax whar &thorn;at he sang, and putt &thorn;aim in sma&llbar;
boystis, &amp; seli&dtail; &thorn;aim privalie &amp; gaff &thorn;aim;
and &thorn;ai tuke &thorn;aim.  And as &thorn;ai went hamwer&dtail;
&thorn;ai sai&dtail; ilkone to o&thorn;er; "we have ha&dtail; a fonde
iorney and wate neuer what precious &thorn;ing we hafe broght hame
vnto our lor&dtail;."  And &thorn;ai brak &thorn;e pope seale &amp;
oppyn&dtail; &thorn;ies boystis, &amp; &thorn;ai fande no &thorn;ing
bod smale pecis of lyn clothe.  An&dtail; with indignacio&ntail;
&thorn;ai come agay&ntail; vnto Rome &amp; tol&dtail; ane
archedeky&ntail; how &thorn;ai had done.  And at &thorn;e laste
&thorn;ai wer broght afo&rtail; Saynt Gregur; and he sai&dtail; his
prayers &amp; did mes.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he tuke one of &thorn;ies
little pecis of clothe, &amp; cutt it in sonder in &thorn;e myddest
with a knyfe; &amp; onone blude come oute &thorn;erof, &amp; made
a&llbar; &thorn;e clothe blodye.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ies messangers
saw &thorn;is, &thorn;ai had grete wonder &thorn;eroff, &amp;
&thorn;ai fe&llbar; o&ntail; &thorn;er kneis and &thorn;anki&dtail;
almi&yogh;tti Go&dtail;; an&dtail; &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e pope putt
&thorn;aim in &thorn;e boystis agay&ntail; &amp; seli&dtail;
&thorn;aim &amp; gaff &thorn;aim &thorn;aim agay&ntail;, &amp; bad
&thorn;aim be stedfaste in belefe.  &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ai went
home vnto &thorn;er lorde with grete myrt&hbar; &amp; ioy, and
delyver&dtail; &thorn;ies relikkis vnto hy&mtail;. et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Corporale immundiciam spiritualem non
sustinet.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a no&ntail; att was
sacrista&ntail;.  So o&ntail; a day sho wasshi&dtail; &thorn;e corprax
&amp; gaff it vnto a damyse&llbar; to dry; and onone as sho
tuchi&dtail; it &thorn;er apperi&dtail; a drop&ptail; &amp; a spott of
blude.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e Sacrista&ntail; saw it, onone sho
wasshi&dtail; it agay&ntail;; &amp; als sone as &thorn;e damyse&llbar;
tuchi&dtail; it, &thorn;er apperi&dtail; a noder spott of blude.
&amp; &thorn;a&ntail; sho lete &thorn;e priores &amp; a&llbar; hur
susters se it; and &thorn;ai had grete mervaile &thorn;eroff, &amp;
went vnto &thorn;er prayers, &amp; besoght Go&dtail; att &thorn;ai
myght hafe a knowlege what it ment.  And &thorn;ai serchi&dtail;
&thorn;is damyse&llbar;, &amp; fand &thorn;at a ma&ntail; had
liggy&ntail; by hur &amp; getty&ntail; hur with childe.

<PB N="151">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Chorizare.  Chorizantes aliquando visibiliter
puniuntur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how &thorn;at a preste &thorn;at hight Tullius on a tyme
opo&ntail; &thorn;e Yole-evy&ntail; sai&dtail; mes in a kur&ktee; of
Saynt Magnus.  And &thorn;er was in &thorn;e kurk-garthe a grete
meneya of me&ntail; &amp; wome&ntail; dawnssan&dtail; in a cercle and
syngand carals, &amp; letti&dtail; dyvyne serves with &thorn;er noyse
&amp; &thorn;er cry.  And &thorn;is preste commawndi&dtail; &thorn;aim
to lefe &amp; &thorn;ai wol&dtail; not for hy&mtail;.  And whe&ntail;
he saw &thorn;ai wol&dtail; not lefe, in his mes he prayed vnto God
&amp; Saynt Magnus &thorn;at it mot please &thorn;aim at &thorn;ai
sulde abide so sti&llbar; vnto &thorn;e yere en&dtail;; and so
&thorn;ai di&dtail;.  And a&llbar; &thorn;at yere nowder ray&ntail;
nor snaw fe&llbar; opo&ntail; &thorn;aim, nor &thorn;ai wer neuer
hongrie nor thrustie, nor &thorn;er clothes ware nott; bod euer
&thorn;ai went aboute syngan&dtail; carals as &thorn;ai had be mad
fol&ktee;.  And &thorn;er was a yong ma&ntail; &thorn;at had his
sister emang &thorn;aim, &amp; he tuke hur be &thorn;e ar&mtail; &amp;
wol&dtail; hafe drowe&ntail; hur fro &thorn;aim, &amp; he pulli&dtail;
of hur ar&mtail;; &amp; &thorn;er come no blude furthe, bod sho
dawnsi&dtail; o&ntail; sti&llbar;: &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ai di&dtail;
a&llbar; &thorn;e yere to it was passi&dtail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail;
Hubertus at was bysshop&ptail; of Colay&ntail; [com] &amp;
assoyli&dtail; &thorn;aim &amp; lowsi&dtail; &thorn;aim oute of
&thorn;is ban&dtail;, and recowncel&dtail; &thorn;er befo&rtail;
&thorn;e alta&rtail;.  And &thorn;er dye&dtail; of &thorn;aim
&thorn;er a ma&ntail; &amp; ij womme&ntail;; and a&llbar; &thorn;e
toder slepi&dtail; iij dayes &amp; iij nyghtis to-geder; and so&mtail;
of &thorn;aim had a tremblyng of a&llbar; &thorn;er bodie evur after
ewhils &thorn;ai liffi&dtail;.  And &thorn;is happend in a tow&ntail;
of Duche-lan&dtail;, in &thorn;e yere of ow&rtail; Lor&dtail;
m.&lbar;.x.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Correpcio.  Corriguntur aliqui per moniciones
sibi factas a bonis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Libro de Dono Timoris,' how &thorn;er was a religious
ma&ntail; &thorn;at was passand contemplatyfe; and o&ntail; a tyme he
was sodanlie ravisshi&dtail; vnto his dome.  And &thorn;er he saw ij
grete me&ntail;, of &thorn;e whilk &thorn;e tane was ane Erle, and
&thorn;e toder a grete prelatt; and &thorn;ai wer hugelie accusi&dtail;
befo&rtail; our Lor&dtail;.  Agayns &thorn;e whilk, &thorn;uf a&llbar;

<PB N="152">

hy&mtail; semy&dtail; passand grevi&dtail;, neuer-&thorn;e-les, be
prayers of so&mtail; of &thorn;aim att wer of &thorn;at cowrte, he
putt our his sentans and sai&dtail; vnto &thorn;is religious ma&ntail;
at he sul&dtail; make &thorn;aim hafe knowlege hereoff be his Abbott;
&amp; so he di&dtail;.  And &thorn;is Erle, for drede of &thorn;is
vysio&ntail; at was tol&dtail; hy&mtail;, forthoght his sy&ntail;
&amp; did penans &thorn;erfo&rtail;, and dyed a gude ma&ntail;.
An&dtail; &thorn;is prelatt sett lightly be &thorn;is visyo&ntail;
&amp; &thorn;is warnyng, and wol&dtail; nott amend his life.  And
afterwar&dtail; hy&mtail; happen&dtail; to be fo&ntail; sodanlie
dea&dtail; in his bed o&ntail; a nyght. et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Corripere debet pater filium, et prelatus
subditum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in &thorn;e same buke how &thorn;er was a yong ma&ntail;,
&amp; he was tenderlie broght vp &amp; no&thorn;ing correcte nowder of
fadur nor moder whe&ntail; he di&dtail; wrong; so he become a thefe,
&amp; stale grete gudis.  And o&ntail; a tyme he was take&ntail; &amp;
demy&dtail; to be hange&dtail;: and as he was led vnto &thorn;e galos
he desyri&dtail; at he mott se his fadur or he dye&dtail;; and he was
broght.  And he besoght hy&mtail; to forgiff hy&mtail; a&llbar;
offensis at he had made vnto hy&mtail;, &amp; so he di&dtail;; &amp;
&thorn;a&ntail; he prayed hy&mtail; to kis hy&mtail;.  And as he
kissi&dtail; hy&mtail;, he bate of his fadur nece; and &thorn;ai
&thorn;at wer abowte hy&mtail; had grete mervayle &thorn;eroff, and
sai&dtail; ffellie vnto hy&mtail; &thorn;erfor.  And he ansswer&dtail;
&thorn;aim agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "I sulde hafe done hy&mtail;
more skathe an&dtail; I had myght, ffor he is cauce of my dea&dtail;;
for he chasti&dtail; not me whe&ntail; I was yong, bod let me
fa&llbar; to gouernans &amp; to mysreule at I am now dampne&dtail; to
my dea&dtail; fo&rtail;, &amp; mon be hange&dtail;."

</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Corripiendi sunt paruuli.  Supra de
blasfemia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>


</LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Corripiendi sunt rebelles eciam si impacienter
ferant.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Helynandus tellis of a philosophur &thorn;at hight Policartus <NOTE ID="P152.N1">Harleian MS. Policarpus.</NOTE> &thorn;at was a techur of &thorn;e Emperour
Troia&ntail;, &thorn;at had ane vnthrifti servan&dtail; &amp; ane
i&llbar;; &amp; o&ntail; a tyme he had done a grete faute.  And
&thorn;is



<PB N="153">

philosophur his maister gart in his aw&ntail; presens take off his
clothis &amp; bete hy&mtail; wele naki&dtail;; and <NOTE ID="P153.N1">MS. as.</NOTE> as &thorn;ai bett hy&mtail; he crye&dtail; &amp;
say&dtail; &thorn;at his maister was no trew philosophur, &thorn;at
had writte&ntail; so fayr a buke of mekenes as he di&dtail;, &amp; for
a&llbar; &thorn;at was turny&dtail; in-to wrat&hbar; agayns hy&mtail;.
And be &thorn;is mene, he sai&dtail;, his techyng was contrari vnto
his warkis.  And his maister ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail;
&amp; say&dtail;; "Semys it to &thorn;e &thorn;at I a&mtail; angri
becauce &thorn;ou erte bett?  And &thorn;inkis &thorn;ou at it is yre,
at I pay &thorn;e at I aw? &thorn;ou seis I hafe no burnyng een, nor
no spome at my mouthe, nor I cry not lowde, nor I wax not rede, nor
trembles nott, nor hase no synge o&ntail; me &thorn;at sulde be
yrefu&llbar;."  And in &thorn;e mene-while he bad hy&mtail; &thorn;at
bett hy&mtail; &thorn;at he sul&dtail; contynue as he bega&ntail;
ewhi&llbar; &thorn;ai ij disputi&dtail;; "And with-oute&ntail; any yre
&thorn;ou sa&llbar; se me correcte &thorn;is i&llbar; servan&dtail;,
&amp; teche hy&mtail; rather to be meke &amp; speke fayr,
&thorn;a&ntail; for to flite or strife with his maister."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cosme &amp; Damyani.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> The&rtail; was so&mtail; tyme a ma&ntail; &thorn;at had a
specia&llbar; deuocio&ntail; vnto Saynt Cosme &amp; Damya&ntail;,
&amp; &thorn;e canker happen&dtail; into &thorn;e the of hy&mtail;
&amp; ha&dtail; wasti&dtail; it nerehan&dtail; away.  And o&ntail; a
tyme as he was slepan&dtail;, hy&mtail; thoght &thorn;ies ij saynttis
come vnto hy&mtail;, &amp; &thorn;ai broght with &thorn;aim
oyntementtis &amp; playsters.  And &thorn;e tone of &thorn;aim
sai&dtail; vnto &thorn;e toder; "Whar sa&llbar; we take vs
fless&hbar;, &thorn;at we may fi&llbar; &thorn;e hole with agay&ntail;
whe&ntail; we hafe cut oute &thorn;e roty&ntail; fless&hbar;?"  And
&thorn;e toder ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "In
&thorn;e kurk gart&hbar; of Saynt Petur ad Vincula <NOTE ID="P153.N2">MS. Saynt Petur Aduincula.</NOTE> , ffor &thorn;is day was &thorn;er a ma&ntail; of
Ynde <NOTE ID="P153.N3">Latin MSS. Ethiops.</NOTE> new beri&dtail;; and &thorn;erfo&rtail; go
feche vs of &thorn;at, at we may fi&llbar; &thorn;e hole with."  &amp;
&thorn;is man of Yn&dtail; hight Maurus; &amp; &thorn;ai went &amp;
fechi&dtail; his bodi, and &thorn;ai cut of &thorn;e &thorn;e of
&thorn;e whik ma&ntail; &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; of &thorn;e dede
ma&ntail; &amp; putt &thorn;e dea&dtail; mans the vnto &thorn;e whik
mans, &amp; anoynti&dtail; &thorn;e wown&dtail; diligentlie; &amp;
&thorn;ai tuke &thorn;e seke ma&ntail; the &amp; put it with &thorn;e
bodie of &thorn;is Maurus, and lay&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail;
&thorn;er he was.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is seke ma&ntail;
wakken&dtail;, and feli&dtail; at hy&mtail; ayli&dtail; no sore, &amp;
putt dow&ntail; his







<PB N="154">

hand vnto his hambe, &amp; he feli&dtail; no hurte; &amp; he garte
light a candy&llbar;, &amp; luki&dtail;, and his the ayli&dtail;
nothyng.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he was fay&ntail; &amp; rase oute of his
be&dtail;; and he tol&dtail; vnto euer-ilk ma&ntail; what he had sene
in his slepe, &amp; how he was heli&dtail;.  And &thorn;ai at he
tol&dtail; it vnto, went vnto &thorn;is Maurus grafe, &amp;
luki&dtail;; &amp; &thorn;ai fan&dtail; his legg away, &amp; &thorn;e
whik mans leg lay&dtail; &thorn;er in-stede &thorn;eroff in &thorn;e
grafe with &thorn;e dea&dtail; mans bodie.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Credere.  Credendum est non cito contra
amicum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis how o&ntail; a tyme it was tol&dtail; vnto Plato
&thorn;at Democrates <NOTE ID="P154.N1">Latin MSS. Zenocrates.</NOTE> his disciple had
sai&dtail; meku&llbar; i&llbar; agayns hy&mtail;; &amp; he wol&dtail;
giff no fayt&hbar; &thorn;erto.  So he att tol&dtail; itt, aski&dtail;
hy&mtail; whi &thorn;at he wol&dtail; not truste hy&mtail;, &amp; he
sai&dtail; he was redie to profe it at he had tol&dtail; hy&mtail;.
[Than] this Plato ansswer&dtail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "It is not trowable
at he &thorn;at I hafe luffid so lang, att I sulde not be luffi&dtail;
of hy&mtail; agay&ntail;."  And so he wol&dtail; gif no truste vnto
&thorn;e complaynt vnto he spak with hy&mtail; hy&mtail; selfe.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Credere cito periculosum est
iudici.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in Cronicles, how o&ntail; a ty&mtail;e &thorn;e Emperour
<NOTE ID="P154.N2">Latin MSS. Otto tertius imperaor.</NOTE> had a wyfe, &thorn;at wol&dtail; at ane Erle of
his o&ntail; a tyme had ligge&ntail; by hur.  And whe&ntail; sho
desiri&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;ervnto, he excusi&dtail; hy&mtail;
&amp; sai&dtail; he wol&dtail; not do suc&hbar; a truspas vnto his
lor&dtail;.  And sho saw &thorn;at, &amp; went &amp; accusi&dtail;
hy&mtail; vnto &thorn;e Emperou&rtail;, an&dtail; sai&dtail; he
wol&dtail; hafe defowli&dtail; hur.  And &thorn;e Emperour tuke it
vnto so grete wrat&hbar;, &thorn;at he garte smyte of his hea&dtail;
with-owte&ntail; Iugement; and he was neuer <NOTE ID="P154.N3">Neuer <HI REND="i">omitted, and added above the line</HI>.</NOTE>
olife agay&ntail;.  &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e emperour
desyri&dtail; his wyfe at &thorn;is erle mot be knowe&ntail; after he
was dea&dtail; be beryng of a hate yr&ntail;, at luke whe&thorn;er he
war innocent or noght; &amp; sho grawnti&dtail;.  And &thorn;e day of
Iugement was assigne&dtail;, and many wedos &amp; maydens calli&dtail;
vnto &thorn;e









<PB N="155">

dome; and &thorn;is Erlis wife come with hur husban&dtail; heade in
hur ar&mtail;.  And sho aske&dtail; of &thorn;e Emperour what deade he
war wurthi to hafe, &thorn;at slew a ma&ntail; wronguslie.  And he
sai&dtail; his hea&dtail; war wurthi to be smety&ntail; off.  And sho
ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;: "Thou ert
&thorn;at ma&ntail;, &thorn;at at fals suggestio&ntail; off &thorn;i
wife slew my husban&dtail;.  And for to make prefe here-of, I
obliss&hbar; me to bere &thorn;e hate yr&ntail;."  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;e Emperour saw &thorn;is, he had grete merve&llbar;, &amp;
commytt hy&mtail; selfe to abide what punyssment at sho wolde deme
hy&mtail; vnto.  So be prayer of bisshoppis &amp; o&thorn;er worthi
me&ntail; he tuke respecte with hur furst for x, ten dayes, &amp;
&thorn;a&ntail; for viij, &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; for vij, &amp;
&thorn;a&ntail; for vi.  And in the mene while he garte examy&ntail;
&thorn;e cauce.  And whe&ntail; he knew &thorn;e trewt&hbar;, he gaff
hur for his rawso&ntail; iiij castels &thorn;at er in &thorn;e
bisshop[ryk] of Lunens.  And be respecte at he had of &thorn;e dayes,
&thorn;ai er calli&dtail;, Decimum, Octauum,
Septimum, &amp; Sextum, yitt vnto &thorn;is day.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Credendum non est de facili referentibus aliorum
defectus.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede ex 'Dictis Patrum,' &thorn;at a certa&ntail; religious
ma&ntail; o&ntail; a tyme sai&dtail; vnto &thorn;e abbott Pastor,
&thorn;at he was so trubble&dtail; att hy&mtail; bur&dtail; lefe his
place, becauce at he har&dtail; certa&ntail; wurdis of a bruther of
his &thorn;at hy&mtail; thoght plesyd hy&mtail; noght.  And &thorn;is
Abbott bad hy&mtail; at he sul&dtail; nott trow &thorn;ies wurdis, for
&thorn;ai wer not trew.  And &thorn;e toder sai&dtail; &thorn;ai wer
trew, for a trew broder of his tolde hy&mtail; &thorn;aim; and
&thorn;e abbott sayd he was not trew at tol&dtail; hy&mtail;, ffor he
say&dtail;, &amp; he had bene a trew bruther he sulde noght hafe
sai&dtail; so.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he aski&dtail; hy&mtail; of
&thorn;e balke &amp; &thorn;e mote, what &thorn;ai wer; and he
tol&dtail; hy&mtail; whatt &thorn;ai war.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he bad
hy&mtail; vmthynk hy&mtail; in his aw&ntail; harte &thorn;at &thorn;is
balk was his aw&ntail; synys, and &thorn;is litle mote was &thorn;e
synnys of &thorn;e toder ma&ntail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Credere cito contra vxorem non debet vir.  Infra

de regina vel imperatrice.</FOREIGN></ITEM>


<PB N="156">


<ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Credendum non est omni verbo.  Supra de consilio

et infra de paciencia, iij.  Et supra de

accusacione. iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>


</LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Credendum non est omni spiritui antequam probandi
sint vtrum sunt ex deo vel non.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum,' how &thorn;e devu&llbar;, made
hy&mtail; in liknes of a gude ange&llbar;, come vnto a solitarie at
his fadir vesett euer-ilk day, and bad hy&mtail; be war of &thorn;e
devu&llbar;, for he was besy euere day to begyle hy&mtail;; "and
tomor&ntail;," he sai&dtail;, "he wi&llbar; come to &thorn;e in liknes
of &thorn;i fadur; and &thorn;erfo&rtail; now venge &thorn;e o&ntail;
hy&mtail;, &amp; luke at &thorn;ou hase a sharpe ax redie, at
whe&ntail; he commys nere the, gif hy&mtail; so grete a strake
o&ntail; &thorn;e hede att he presume no mo&rtail; to co&mtail; vnto
the."  And &thorn;is ankir trowi&dtail; &thorn;at he had bene ane
ange&llbar; at had bene sent vnto hy&mtail; fro God Hy&mtail; selfe to
giff hy&mtail; &thorn;is cownce&llbar;; &amp; o&ntail; &thorn;e day
after his aw&ntail; fadur come vnto hy&mtail; at vissit hy&mtail;, and
he with ane ax killi&dtail; hy&mtail;, and was taky&ntail;
&thorn;erfor &amp; hanged evy&ntail; furt&hbar;-with.

</P>
<P>   
<LIST><ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Crimen falso imponitur.  Infra de infamia.
</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cristus.  Cristianus, vbi agitur de Cristo
infra.</FOREIGN></ITEM>


</LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Crudelitas.  Crudele est malum pro bono <NOTE ID="P156.N1">MS. malo.</NOTE> reddere.</FOREIGN></HEAD> 


<P> We rede in &thorn;e storie of Nero, whe&ntail; Senec at was his
maister aski&dtail; hy&mtail; his ffe for his labur, he ansswer&dtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "Maister <NOTE ID="P156.N2">MS. Maistes.</NOTE> ,
&thorn;ou must dye; for als lang as &thorn;ou liffis I may hafe no
reste; ffor I hafe bene als fer&dtail; for &thorn;e as a bar&ntail;
wol&dtail; hafe bene, &amp; yitt is."  And &thorn;a&ntail; Seneca
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "Sur, se&ntail; me bus
nedis dy, I pray &thorn;e grawnt&curl; me att I may dy what maner of
dea&dtail; at me likis to chese my selfe."  And Nero grawnti&dtail;
hy&mtail;, &amp; bad hy&mtail; chese it hastelie, ffor hy&mtail;
bur&dtail; nedis dye.  And &thorn;a&ntail;





<PB N="157">

Senec garte make a grete batt&hbar; of war&mtail; watir &amp; garte
putt hy&mtail; selfe &thorn;erin, and garte latt hy&mtail; blude of
bothe his armys.  And so he ble&dtail; odeade.  And be &thorn;is
mea&ntail; he was calli&dtail; Seneca, <FOREIGN>quasi se necans;</FOREIGN> and be
&thorn;is mea&ntail; he was dea&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Crudelitas contra naturam detestanda
est.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Historia Neronis,' how at &thorn;is Nero garte sla his
moder &amp; cutt hur in sonder, at he might se how he lay in hur
wombe, &amp; wha&rtail;-with he was nurrisshi&dtail;.  And &thorn;e
philosophirs reprovi&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;erfo&rtail; &amp;
sai&dtail;, "&thorn;e law denyes, &amp; rightwusnes forbiddis <NOTE ID="P157.N1">MS. forbiddid.</NOTE> , att &thorn;e so&ntail; sulde sla his moder
&thorn;at suffer&dtail; so grete pay&ntail; for hy&mtail; in hur
burt&hbar; as sho di&dtail;, &amp; broght hy&mtail; v&ptail; with so
grete labur."  And &thorn;a&ntail; Nero sai&dtail; vnto &thorn;aim;
"Make ye me to be with childe, and afterwar&dtail; to be delyver
&thorn;eroff, at I may hafe verray knawlege whatt sorow my moder
ha&dtail; with birt&hbar; of me whe&ntail; I was bor&ntail;."  And
&thorn;ai ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail; &thorn;at it was
not possible, &thorn;at was contrarie vnto natur.  And he sai&dtail;
bod if &thorn;ai di&dtail; itt, &thorn;ai sulde dye ilkone.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai made hy&mtail; drynkis, and privalie
&thorn;ai made hy&mtail; to dryn&ktee; a froske; and be &thorn;er
crafte &thorn;ai made it to grow in his body &amp; to wax.  And so his
bely bega&ntail; agayns natur to bolne, to so meku&llbar; att he
trowi&dtail; he was with childe; and &thorn;ai made hy&mtail; daylie
to be dyett with suc&hbar; meatt as &thorn;ai knew wolde nuriss&hbar;
a fros&ktee;.  So o&ntail; a tyme his belie warki&dtail; hugelie,
&amp; he sai&dtail; vnto &thorn;ies lechis; "Take hede o&ntail; me,
ffor &thorn;e tyme of my birt&hbar; is nere; ffor my belie warkis so,
&thorn;at I may vnnethis draw myne an&dtail;."  And &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;ai gaff hy&mtail; a purgacio&ntail;, and he spewi&dtail; oute a
grete froske and ane vglie to luke o&ntail;, bludie &amp; infecte with
humers.  And whe&ntail; Nero luki&dtail; &thorn;ervppo&ntail;,
hy&mtail; vggi&dtail; &thorn;erwith, &amp; he aski&dtail;; "Had my
moder als meku&llbar; sorow for beryng of me, as I ha&dtail; for
beryng of &thorn;is?"  And &thorn;ai sai&dtail;, ya.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; he commandi&dtail; &thorn;at &thorn;is vglie
burt&hbar; of his sulde be norisshi&dtail; &amp; kepy&dtail;, and at
it sulde be closi&dtail; in a stone, as a snyle is in hur she&llbar;.



<PB N="158">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Crudelitas dampnum inferens rei publice non est
toleranda
<NOTE ID="P158.N1">MS. tolleranda.</NOTE>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in &thorn;e same storie, how o&ntail; a tyme Nero had
grete merva&llbar; whatky&ntail; a thyng burnyng was; and he garte
sett fyre in ane en&dtail; of Rome, &amp; it burny&dtail; vij dayes
&amp; vij nyghtis.  And evur he lay in a hy towre &amp; behel&dtail;
it; &amp; whe&ntail; he saw &thorn;e low rise v&ptail; into &thorn;e
ayr, hy&mtail; thoght it was a fayr syght.  And &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;e Romans wex grevi&dtail; &amp; wol&dtail; suffre it no langer,
&amp; rase &amp; pursewi&dtail; opo&ntail; hy&mtail;, &amp; drafe
hy&mtail; oute of &thorn;e cetie, &amp; wol&dtail; hafe slane
hy&mtail; &amp; &thorn;ai myght hafe gette&ntail; hy&mtail;.  And
whe&ntail; he saw &thorn;at he mot not esskape, he gatt hy&mtail; a
stowre, &amp; gnew vppo&ntail; &thorn;e tone en&dtail; &amp; made it
sharpe with his tethe, &amp; &thorn;rusti&dtail; hy&mtail; selfe
evy&ntail; thrug&hbar; &thorn;erwith.  And &thorn;us he made his
en&dtail;.  Neuer-&thorn;e-les we rede in a noder place &thorn;at he was
devowri&dtail; with wulfis <NOTE ID="P158.N2">MS. wulfi&dtail;.</NOTE> .

</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Crudelis non debet esse iudex.  Infra de
iudice.</FOREIGN></ITEM>

<ITEM>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Crudelis non debet esse prelatus.  Infra de
prelato.</FOREIGN></ITEM>


</LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Crux Cristi vel crucifixus.  Crucifixi ymago a Iudeis
in despectu vulneratur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how &thorn;at in &thorn;e tyme of Constantyne &thorn;e
iiij <NOTE ID="P158.N3">Lat. MSS.  In Siria, Ciuitate Bericho, Iudei ymaginem crucifixi inuenientes in domo cuiusdam Iudei, relictam ibi a quodam Cristiano qui ibi manserat, eam iniuriose doposuerunt. et cet.</NOTE> , &thorn;e Iewis fan&dtail; in a cetie ane
ymage of &thorn;e crucifix; &amp; &thorn;ai broght it into a Iewis
hows, & <NOTE ID="P158.N4">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, &amp;.</NOTE> &thorn;er &thorn;ai spitt
&thorn;ero&ntail; &amp; strake it with &thorn;er handis, &amp;
nayli&dtail; &thorn;e fete &thorn;erof vnto &thorn;e cros with naylis,
&amp; &thorn;ai put vnto &thorn;e mouthe &thorn;erof ayse&llbar; &amp;
ga&llbar;.  And at &thorn;e laste &thorn;ai oppen&dtail; &thorn;e syde
&thorn;erof, &amp; &thorn;er come blude &amp; watir; and &thorn;ai
sett ane ampu&llbar; vndernethe it &amp; kepyd it in.  And ilkone of
&thorn;aim att was seke, &thorn;ai wol&dtail; sprencle of &thorn;is
blude o&ntail; &thorn;aim, &amp; onone &thorn;ai war hale.  So at
&thorn;e laste &thorn;ies Iewis forthoght att &thorn;ai had done, and
tuke &thorn;is ymage










<PB N="159">

&amp; &thorn;e blude, &amp; had it vnto &thorn;e bisshop&ptail; of
&thorn;e cetie; and so &thorn;ai wer cristen&dtail; &amp; turny&dtail;
vnto &thorn;e fayt&hbar;.  And of &thorn;is blude was sent to many
cetis &amp; kyngdoms; &amp; yit to &thorn;is day it duse many
meracles.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Crucis signum magnam habet virtutem, eciam
infidelibus.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Grego&rtail; tellis how &thorn;at a bisshop&ptail; of
&thorn;e cetie of Funda&ntail; <NOTE ID="P159.N1">Latin MSS. Andreas, Fundare civitatis episcopus.</NOTE> had som tyme in
his howse soiornan&dtail; a no&ntail;; &amp; be fals temptacio&ntail;
of &thorn;e devu&llbar;, o&ntail; a tyme he was so tempi&dtail; at he
thoght he wol&dtail; hafe at do with hur.  So it happen&dtail; a Iew
to go wi&llbar; o&ntail; a nyght, &amp; cuthe fyn&dtail; no place to
reste hy&mtail; in.  And he went into a temple of Appollo, &amp;
&thorn;er he lay&dtail; hy&mtail; dow&ntail; &amp; slepi&dtail;.  And
abowte mydnyght, &thorn;er come a company of fendis, &amp; &thorn;er
chifta&ntail; was sett in a chayr emangis &thorn;aim, &amp; garte
&thorn;aim co&mtail; befo&rtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; examyn&dtail;
&thorn;aim of &thorn;er craftis.  And whe&ntail; ilk one of &thorn;aim
had tal&dtail; hy&mtail; a&llbar;, ane of &thorn;aim steppy&dtail;
befo&rtail; hy&mtail; at satt, &amp; sai&dtail; how he had
tempy&dtail; &thorn;is bisshop&ptail; with &thorn;is womma&ntail;,
&amp; in a burte to giff hur a knok&ktee; on &thorn;e bak&ktee;.
And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;er chifta&ntail; commendi&dtail; hy&mtail;,
&amp; chargi&dtail; hy&mtail; to perfor&mtail; at he had bego&ntail;.
And he commandi&dtail; &thorn;aim to seke aboute in &thorn;e temple,
&amp; luke who was &thorn;erin mo &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai.  And
&thorn;is Iew har&dtail; &thorn;at &amp; made a cros o&ntail;
hy&mtail;; and &thorn;ai soght aboute &amp; fan&dtail; hy&mtail;.  And
onone as &thorn;ai saw hy&mtail;, one of &thorn;aim saw, &amp;
sai&dtail;; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">ve! ve! vas vacuum sed bene
signatum;</FOREIGN> wo! wo! here is a voyde vessa&llbar;, bod it is
wele merki&dtail;."  And with &thorn;is voyce, a&llbar; &thorn;e
fendis vanysshi&dtail; away; and &thorn;e Iew rase vpp &amp; went vnto
&thorn;e bisshop of &thorn;e cetie &amp; tol&dtail; hy&mtail;.  And he
made meku&llbar; sorow for his sy&ntail;, &amp; put away &thorn;is
womma&ntail; &amp; cristen&dtail; &thorn;is Iew. et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cruce signari debent omnes propter
indulgencias.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Jacobus de Vetriaco tellis of hy&mtail; selfe &amp; says; "On a tyme
as I was in a tow&ntail; prechan&dtail;, &thorn;er was a ma&ntail;
&thorn;at durste not co&mtail; vnto &thorn;e sermo&ntail; for his
wyfe, not in-to &thorn;e kur&ktee;.  And he come to a



<PB N="160">

wyndow &amp; harde &thorn;e sermo&ntail;; and whe&ntail; he had
har&dtail; of &thorn;e ind[ulg]ence at longis vnto &thorn;aim at er
merki&dtail; with &thorn;e cros, for als meku&llbar; as he durste not
co&mtail; in att &thorn;e dure for his wyfe, he crope in att &thorn;e
wyndow in myddeste the peple, &amp; tuke &thorn;e cros as &thorn;ai
di&dtail;."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXXX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cruce signatis datur filius beate
virginis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Jacobus de Vetriaco tellis of hy&mtail; selfe and says: "ans in my
childe&dtail;, whe&ntail; I was in a howse of Ceustus ordur, &thorn;er
I har&dtail; a sermo&ntail; of &thorn;e cros.  And meki&llbar;
pepu&llbar; lefte a&llbar; <NOTE ID="P160.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, all.</NOTE> &thorn;e gudis att
&thorn;ai ha&dtail;, and come and wurshuppy&dtail; &thorn;e cros.  So
emang &thorn;aim was a bruther &thorn;at hight Symon&dtail;, and he
besoght God att he mott hafe so&mtail; knowlege whatt mede &thorn;ai
sulde hafe att wurshuppy&dtail; &thorn;e cros; and o&ntail; &thorn;e
nyght after he was ravisshi&dtail; in his spiritt, and &thorn;er he
saw our Ladie Saynt Marie holdand hur dere so&ntail;.  And aftre
&thorn;at euerilk a ma&ntail; with a contrite harte had take&ntail;
&thorn;e cros, sho gaff vnto hy&mtail; hur so&ntail;." et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXXXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cruce signati dolose puniuntur eciam
corporaliter.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;at in &thorn;e bisshoppry&ktee; of
Traiectens, ane vsurer tuke &thorn;e cros &amp; lete as he wal&dtail;
go vnto &thorn;e Holie Land.  And whe&ntail; he sulde go furt&hbar;,
he feny&dtail; hy&mtail; selfe seke &amp; wayke, &amp; say&dtail; he
myght not go, and hyri&dtail; a-noder to go for hy&mtail;, &amp; gaff
hy&mtail; bo&dtail; v marcis, &thorn;uf a&llbar; he myght have
giffe&ntail; hy&mtail; xl<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> marcis.  So afterwar&dtail; whe&ntail;
&thorn;ai at wer burnyd wer bow&ntail; furt&hbar;, he satt with
&thorn;aim in &thorn;e taver&ntail; &amp; sayde vnto &thorn;aim; "ye
wrichis, now ye forsake you&rtail; wyvis and your childer, &amp; your
frendis, and a&llbar; your other gudis, &amp; puttis your bodis in
perels be-yond &thorn;e see; and I sitt att home with my wyfe and my
childer, &amp; with a&llbar; <NOTE ID="P160.N2">MS. <HI REND="i">after</HI> a&llbar; al, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> my gudis, and for
v marke hase als meku&llbar; perdo&ntail; as ye hafe."  Bo&dtail;
almyghti God, att is rightwus, shewyng how meku&llbar; &thorn;e labur
&amp; expensis of pylgramys plesis hy&mtail;, &amp; how meku&llbar;
desayte &




<PB N="161">

blasfeme of bakbyters displesis hy&mtail;, suffer&dtail; &thorn;att
o&ntail; &thorn;e night after &thorn;e devu&llbar; come vnto hy&mtail;
in liknes of a servan&dtail; of his aw&ntail;, and broght with
hy&mtail; ij grete blak hors, and bad hy&mtail; faste caste of his
vppermest clothe, &amp; go with hy&mtail; &amp; lope o&ntail; one of
&thorn;ies hors.  And &thorn;e cross at he had taky&ntail; was
sewi&dtail; opo&ntail; his ouermeste clothe, and so he vmthoght
hy&mtail; &thorn;at he mott not esskape, &amp; keste away his
ouermeste clothe &amp; onone lepi&dtail; o&ntail; &thorn;e to hors,
&amp; &thorn;e devu&llbar; lepi&dtail; o&ntail; &thorn;e tother; &amp;
with-in a while &thorn;ai war led &thorn;er dyvers paynys wer.  And
&thorn;e devu&llbar; shewi&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;e seatt &thorn;er
he sulde sytt in paynys, and &thorn;e devu&llbar; say&dtail; vnto
hy&mtail;; "Now &thorn;ou sa&llbar; tur&ntail; agay&ntail; into
&thorn;i howse, bod with-in iij days &thorn;ou sa&llbar; dy, &amp;
tur&ntail; agay&ntail;."  And &thorn;a&ntail; he was broght
agay&ntail;, and me&ntail; aski&dtail; hy&mtail; whar he had bene; and
he tolde &thorn;aim a&llbar; as is afor say&dtail;.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; a preste was broght vnto hy&mtail;, &thorn;at
councel&dtail; hy&mtail; to shryfe hy&mtail; &amp; do penance for his
sy&ntail;.  And he wol&dtail; nott, bod fe&llbar; in despar &amp; dyed
withoute&ntail; owder shrift or howsi&llbar; or contricio&ntail;,
&amp; was beri&dtail; in he&llbar;. et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
