solitudine 
<NOTE ID="P167.N1">MS. solicitudine.</NOTE> .



<PB N="168">
</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Decipiuntur aliqui verbis multorum.  Infra de verbo
et de promisso.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXXXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Decipiuntur aliqui quia aliquando non inueniunt
quod querunt.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Libro de Dono Timoris,' how &thorn;er was a lor&dtail;
&thorn;at had a fule, &amp; &thorn;is lorde had also a gay
falco&ntail; &amp; a swyfte, &thorn;er was [bod] suc&hbar; one in
a&llbar; &thorn;at lan&dtail;.  And ilk ma&ntail; at saw it fle
commendid it &amp; praysid it.  So &thorn;is fole har&dtail; at ilk
ma&ntail; commendi&dtail; &thorn;is falco&ntail; so, and privalie
o&ntail; a nyght he gat &thorn;is falco&ntail; of his lordis &amp;
slew itt, and sothe itt, &amp; ete itt.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e
lor&dtail; myssi&dtail; &thorn;is hawke, he made grete sorow
&thorn;erfor, becauce he wiste nott how it was loste.  And he
commendid it gretelie in presens of &thorn;is fule; and whe&ntail;
&thorn;e fule har&dtail; hy&mtail; commend it so, he ansswer&dtail;
&amp; say&dtail;; "Forsuthe lor&dtail;, it dught nott; ffor I ete
neuer bitterer fless&hbar; &thorn;a&ntail; it was."  And so &thorn;is
fule fan&dtail; a noder &thorn;ing &thorn;a&ntail; he trowi&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXL.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Decima.  Decimas bene soluere est vtile.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;er was a knyght &thorn;at had so grete
deuocio&ntail; about payment of his tendis, &amp; &thorn;at he
wol&dtail; euer of rightwusnes pay &thorn;aim with-owte&ntail; any
tarying or with-oute dissayte or vexacio&ntail;.  And he had a
certa&ntail; vyneyar&dtail; of &thorn;e whilk he had yerelie x
to&ntail; of wyne.  So it happen&dtail; o&ntail; a yere whe&ntail; he
had gader&dtail; a&llbar; his vynys &amp; braye&dtail; &thorn;aim, he
had bod a to&ntail; of wyne.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;is knyght saw
&thorn;at, he sayd vnto his servan&dtail;; "That at was myne, God hase
take&ntail; it fro me; and yitt I wi&llbar; not take His parte fro
Hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;erfo&rtail; go byd &thorn;e preste feche
&thorn;is to&ntail; of wyne for his ten&dtail;."  And &thorn;e prest
did so.  And &thorn;e same yere o&ntail; a tyme, a bruther of &thorn;e
same knyghtis, at was a preste, went dow&ntail; be &thorn;e
garthy&ntail; abowte &thorn;e Martynmes; and he saw a&llbar; &thorn;e
vynys hang fu&llbar; of grapis.  And he went in-to his bruther &amp;
flate with hy&mtail; for

<PB N="169">

his neclegens, &amp; say&dtail;; "Whi hafe ye noght yitt garder&dtail;
your vynys, &amp; &thorn;e yere is so-fortherlie paste?"  And &thorn;e
knyght say&dtail; &thorn;at &thorn;ai war gader&dtail; lang
befo&rtail;.  And &thorn;e preste say&dtail; nay it was not so;
"ffor," he say&dtail;, "I was &thorn;eratt &thorn;is day, &amp; I saw
it grow fu&llbar; of vynys."  And &thorn;e knyght &amp; his meneya
went &amp; luki&dtail;, &amp; &thorn;ai fan&dtail; it was so.  And
&thorn;ai gader&dtail; &thorn;aim &amp; made wyne &thorn;eroff; &amp;
&thorn;er grew neuer ryper nor mo&rtail; plentefu&llbar; vynys in
&thorn;at gart&hbar; &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ase wer. et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXLI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Decanus ad inferni curiam inuitatur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;at in tyme of Hereticus <NOTE ID="P169.N1">Latin MSS. Tempore Henrici imperatoris.</NOTE> &thorn;e Emperour, in &thorn;e kurk of Palernens was
&thorn;er a certa&ntail; dea&ntail; &thorn;at sent a servan&dtail; of
his to seke a palfray of his &thorn;at hy&mtail; wanti&dtail;; &amp;
&thorn;er mett ane al&dtail; ma&ntail; &thorn;is servan&dtail; &amp;
aski&dtail; hy&mtail; whedir he went &amp; whatt he soght.  And he
sai&dtail; he soght his maister hors.  And &thorn;is ald ma&ntail;
tel&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;at &thorn;is hors was att &thorn;e Mownte
of Gybber; "and &thorn;er," he say&dtail;, "hase my lor&dtail; kyng
Arthur hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;at mownte byrnys evur o&ntail; a grete
low as it war fu&llbar; of burned-stone."  And &thorn;is servan&dtail;
had grete mervayle of his wurdis, and &thorn;e alde ma&ntail; said
vnto hy&mtail;; "Saw vnto &thorn;i maister &amp; charge hy&mtail; at
&thorn;is day xiiij dayes he co&mtail; thedur vnto Kyng Arthur
solempne courte.  And if &thorn;ou forgett &amp; te&llbar; hy&mtail;
nott, &thorn;ou sa&llbar; be grevuslie punysshi&dtail;
&thorn;erfo&rtail;."  And &thorn;is servan&dtail; went home &amp;
tol&dtail; his maister a&llbar; at he say&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; with
grete ferdnes.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e dea&ntail; har&dtail; att he
was sommon&dtail; vnto &thorn;e courte of Arthur, he log&hbar;
&thorn;erat &amp; made a skor&ntail; &thorn;erof.  And onone he
fe&llbar; seke, &amp; &thorn;e same day att he was somon&dtail; he
dye&dtail;. et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXLII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Dedicacio.  Dedicacione ecclesie expellitur ab
ea demo&ntail;.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Gregur tellis in his Dyaloggis, how o&ntail; a tyme a kurk
of &thorn;e Arryans was gyffe&ntail; vnto Criste&ntail; me&ntail;; and
&thorn;ai garte halow



<PB N="170">

itt.  And &thorn;e relikkis of Saynt Sebastia&ntail;, &amp; Saynt
Agnes &amp; Saynt Agas <NOTE ID="P170.N1">Latin MSS. relique ... sancte Agathe.</NOTE> war broght thedur,
a&llbar; &thorn;e peple at was gadder&dtail; thedur feli&dtail;
&thorn;e gron&dtail; in the kurk-dure quake, &amp; mofe
heder-war&dtail; &amp; &thorn;edurwar&dtail;.  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;ai wer with-in &thorn;e kirk, &thorn;ai feli&dtail; nothyng
&thorn;eroff.  And &thorn;ai had grete merve&llbar; here-off, and
a&llbar;-myghti God lete &thorn;aim a&llbar; hafe a knowlege &thorn;at
it was &thorn;e fen&dtail; &thorn;at garte &thorn;e ert&hbar; stir
whe&ntail; he went furthe of &thorn;at place &amp; it was
halow&dtail;. et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
