</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXLIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Delicie.  Delicias corporales secuntur frequenter
miserie et calamitates. et c&curl;.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Petrus Damyanus tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a duke at had a
wyfe &thorn;at liffe&dtail; so delicatlie &amp; so tenderly &thorn;at
sho wolde nott wass&hbar; hur with commo&ntail; watirs as we do, bod
sho wolde gar hur maydyns gader &thorn;e dew o&ntail; sommer mornyngis
at sho mot wass&hbar; hur with.  And sho wol&dtail; not tuc&hbar;e hur
meate with hur








<PB N="171">

handis hur selfe, bod after hur carvur had cutt itt in morcels sho
wol&dtail; take it vp&ptail; with poyntels &amp; crukis of gol&dtail;
&amp; putt itt in hur mowthe.  And sho wolde make hur bed so redolent
savurand with spice &thorn;at it was a mervayle to te&llbar; off.  And
as sho liffi&dtail; &thorn;us, be &thorn;e rightwusnes of Go&dtail;,
sho was so smyty&ntail; with canker and seknes &thorn;at sho
roti&dtail; so, &amp; sho o&ntail; life, &thorn;at no creatur mot fele
&thorn;e styn&ktee; of hur; to so meku&llbar; at a&llbar; folke lefte
hur &amp; a&llbar; hur servandis, bod onelie a damyse&llbar; &thorn;at
was left to kepe hur; &amp; yitt sho mott not co&mtail; att hur for
styn&ktee; with-oute sho had at hur nece many wele-saueryng spycis;
&amp; yitt sho mott not tarie with hur no tyme for horrible
styn&ktee;.  And whe&ntail; sho had lige&ntail; &thorn;us many day
sho dye&dtail;, &amp; no body with hur. et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXLIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Delicate viuentes in hoc seculo cogitare debent de
penis inferni.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Libro de Dono Timoris' how &thorn;er was a delicatt
scoler of Bola&nmacr;, and he fle&dtail; &thorn;e state of penance and
he wol&dtail; nowder here sermo&ntail; nor no wur&dtail; of Go&dtail;,
&thorn;at he sul&dtail; not be movi&dtail; to be a religious
ma&ntail;.  So it happen&dtail; at a freer-prechur, &thorn;at was his
contrey-ma&ntail; &amp; kend with hy&mtail;, come &amp; visett
hy&mtail; &amp; luke&dtail; how he di&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e
scolar saw hy&mtail; he say&dtail; unto hy&mtail;; "Freer, &amp;
&thorn;ou wi&llbar; speke with me of God I charge nott, and if
&thorn;ou speke with me of o&thorn;er thyngis &thorn;ou erte
welco&mtail;."  And &thorn;e ffreer ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp;
say&dtail;; "I sa&llbar; speke furste of o&thorn;er erandis, and att
&thorn;e end I sa&llbar; speke of God bod a wur&dtail;."  And
whe&ntail; he had sai&dtail; a&llbar; his erandis, be lefe of
&thorn;is scolar vnnethis graunty&dtail;, &thorn;e freer say&dtail;;
"Maister, I pray you for Goddis sake &thorn;at &thorn;is nyght
whe&ntail; ye lye in your bed war&mtail; happe&dtail;, &thorn;at ye
wol&dtail; vmthynk you of &thorn;e be&dtail; &thorn;at is ordan&dtail;
in he&llbar; to &thorn;aim &thorn;at mo&ntail; be dampny&dtail;,
&thorn;at liffis here in a&llbar; &thorn;e delicatis att &thorn;aim
liste hafe."  And &thorn;a&ntail; he aski&dtail; whatky&ntail; a
be&dtail; &thorn;at was; &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e freer
sai&dtail; &thorn;e saying of &thorn;e prophett Ysai; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Subter te sternentur, et c&curl;.</FOREIGN>" And whe&ntail;
&thorn;e freer had &thorn;us sai&dtail;, he went his ways, and
&thorn;is scoler o&ntail; &thorn;e nyght

<PB N="172">

after as he lay in his bed&dtail;, he vmthoght hy&mtail; o&ntail;
&thorn;ies wurdis, &amp; he mott not slepe a dele for thoght of
&thorn;is bed in he&llbar;, unto so meku&llbar; &thorn;is &thorn;oght
prevayli&dtail; so o&ntail; hy&mtail; &thorn;at with-in a litle while
after he made hy&mtail; a freer of &thorn;e same ordur. et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXLV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Delicie corporales et presentes impediunt spirituales
et futuras.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Libro de Dono Timoris' how so&mtail; tyme a
husband-ma&ntail; was biddy&ntail; vnto a kyngis bryda&llbar;, and as
he went thedurwar&dtail; he wex passand thrustie, &amp; he fan&dtail;
drovy watyr &amp; stynkan&dtail;, &amp; drank &thorn;eroff.  And his
felows cowncel&dtail; hy&mtail; not to drynk &thorn;erof, bod to byde
to he come att &thorn;e bryda&llbar;, &amp; &thorn;er he sulde hafe
gude wyne enog&hbar;, &amp; clarett; &amp; he wol&dtail; not, bod
filli&dtail; his body of &thorn;is stynkan&dtail; watir, into so
meku&llbar; at he bega&ntail; to bolk, &amp; his brethe for to stynke.
And whe&ntail; he come vnto &thorn;e kyngis yate with his felows,
&thorn;ai went in &amp; he was holde&ntail; oute for his bolkyng &amp;
his stynkan&dtail; brethe.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Qui delicantur corpore frequencius infirmantur.

Supra de abbatissa.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Demon impedit orationes quantum potest.  Infra de

