</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXLVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Demones insistunt morientibus.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Jacobus de Vetriaco tellis how o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; a sister
of &thorn;e fraternitie of Oegniez <!-- P174.N1 --> was seke
&amp; bow&ntail; to dye, Saynt Marie of Oegniez <NOTE ID="P174.N1">MS. Oegimez.</NOTE>
, as sho was in hur ce&llbar;, sho purseyvi&dtail; &amp; saw a
multitude of fendis rumyan&dtail; abowte hur <NOTE ID="P174.N2">MS. his.</NOTE>
sister be&dtail;, &amp; sho bow&ntail; to dye.  And as hur sisters war
sayan&dtail; &thorn;er prayers for hur, &amp; trowi&dtail; &thorn;at
sho sul&dtail; dye, sho ra&ntail; vnto &thorn;e be&dtail; of hur seke
sister &amp; weri&dtail; away with hur shirte &thorn;ir evu&llbar;
spyrittis as &thorn;ai had bene fleis, &amp; sai&dtail; hur prayers
alsso.  And &thorn;ai wythstude hur &amp; chalangi&dtail; hur sister
sawle as &thorn;er aw&ntail;. &thorn;a&ntail; sho mot suffer
&thorn;aim no langer, &amp; crye&dtail; o&ntail; Criste for His bittyr
passyo&ntail; &amp; His blude to helpe hur.  And &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;ies evu&llbar; spirittis labur&dtail; gretelie to hafe
gette&ntail; &thorn;is saule, and sho saw &thorn;at &amp; say&dtail;;
"Lor&dtail;, I beco&mtail; borg&hbar; for &thorn;is sawle; for
&thorn;uff a&llbar; sho hafe synny&dtail;, yit sho is confessi&dtail;
&thorn;erof.  And if oght be ignorans or neclegens be left
behyn&dtail; with hur, Lor&dtail;, latt hur lyff, &amp; I vndertake
sho sa&llbar; amen&dtail; hur."  &amp; so sho di&dtail;; &amp;
&thorn;e fendis vanysshi&dtail; away.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Demoni se commendare periculosum est.  Supra de

Commendacione.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXLIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Demones presciunt mortem malorum
aliquando.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Jacobus de Vetriaco <NOTE ID="P174.N3">The Latin MSS. attribute this tale to Helinandus.</NOTE> tellis of Elebrandus
&thorn;at was archebisshop&ptail; of Beme <NOTE ID="P174.N4">Latin MSS. Remensis.</NOTE> , how
o&ntail; a tyme his bed-felow tolde o&ntail; hy&mtail; &amp;
say&dtail;;










<PB N="175">

"My lor&dtail; o&ntail; a tyme sent me ane eran&dtail; vnto Attrebatt
<NOTE ID="P175.N1">Latin MSS. Attrebater, Atrebater.</NOTE> ; and whe&ntail; I and my servan&dtail; wer in
a wud, we har&dtail; a grete noyse of army&dtail; me&ntail;, &amp; as
vs thoght, of harnessi&dtail; hors, and fendis cryan&dtail;, &amp;
say&dtail;; 'Now we hafe our purpas <!-- P175.N2 --> of Arta
<!-- P175.N3 --> , and onone we sa&llbar; hafe our purpos <NOTE ID="P175.N2">Latin 'prepositum' <HI REND="i">misread as</HI> 'purpos'='propositum,' <HI REND="i">and repeated before</HI> 'bisshopp of Beam.' Latin: Iam habemus prepositum de Isrea, in proximo habebimus archiepiscopum Remensis.</NOTE> of &thorn;e bisshop&ptail; of Bea&mtail;'; bod we
may nott gett furt&hbar; our hors, nowder with staffis nor spurris.
And &thorn;a&ntail; I say&dtail; vnto my servan&dtail;; 'Latt vs make
crossis in our forhedis, &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; sa&llbar; we go
sekurlie.'  And so we di&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; we come home, we
fan&dtail; &thorn;e prefecte <NOTE ID="P175.N4">MS. prefeste; Latin MSS. prepositum.</NOTE> of Arta <NOTE ID="P175.N3">Arund. MS. de Arta; Harl. MS. de Isrea.</NOTE> dea&dtail;, and &thorn;e archbissho&ptail; of
Bea&mtail; bow&ntail; to dye."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCL.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Demon eciam viuos in equo portat in
infernum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Helynandus tellis how o&ntail; a tyme, opo&ntail; a solempne day,
as &thorn;e erle of Macisco&ntail; <NOTE ID="P175.N5">Harl. MS. Comes Matistonensis; Arund. MS. comes Mastisconensis.</NOTE> satt in his
aw&ntail; palas &amp; many knyghtis abowte hy&mtail;, sodanlie ane
vnknowe&ntail; ma&ntail; sittan&dtail; o&ntail; a hors come in at <NOTE ID="P175.N6">At <HI REND="i">omitted and added above the line</HI>.</NOTE> &thorn;e pales yate, and, att &thorn;ai a&llbar;
saw, rade evy&ntail; vp to hy&mtail; &thorn;er he satt, &amp;
sai&dtail; he come to speke with hy&mtail;, &amp; bad hy&mtail; ryse
&amp; go with hy&mtail;.  And he myght not agaynstand hy&mtail;, &amp;
rase &amp; went vnto &thorn;e dure; &amp; &thorn;er he fan&dtail; a
hors redie.  And he bad hy&mtail; lepe o&ntail;, &amp; so he
di&dtail;; and &thorn;e toder tuke his bridy&llbar;-rene at come for
hy&mtail;, &amp; at &thorn;ai a&llbar; saw, &thorn;ai rade vp in-to
&thorn;e ayre.  And &thorn;e erle crye&dtail; as he war wude; "Helpe
me my cetysyns!  Helpe me my cetisyns!"  And euer-ilk ma&ntail; in
&thorn;e cetie har&dtail; &thorn;is voyce, &amp; ra&ntail; oute; &amp;
&thorn;ai mot a grete while se hy&mtail; rydand in &thorn;e ayre.  And
at &thorn;e laste he was with-drawe&ntail; fro &thorn;er syght, &amp;
had vnto he&llbar;. et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Demon bonos bellare facit.  Supra de bello.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
