</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Demon sub specie boni aliquos ad mortem temporalem
et eternam ducit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;er was a Iew conuerti&dtail; in
&thorn;e bisshopprik of Cola&ntail;; and he was emang monkis, &amp;
&thorn;ai lerny&dtail; hy&mtail; o&ntail; &thorn;e buke to he cuthe
rede wele.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he garte write bukis, &amp; &thorn;e
monkis letti&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; wol&dtail; not ler&ntail;
hy&mtail; no more; &amp; onone as he saw &thorn;at, he stale away from
emang &thorn;aim and went his ways, to &thorn;e entent at he
wol&dtail; ler&ntail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e devi&llbar;
appered vnto hy&mtail; in liknes of ane aunge&llbar;, and bad
hy&mtail; ler&ntail; faste, ffor he sulde be a bissho&ptail;.  And a
little while afterwar&dtail; he apperi&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;

<PB N="177">

agay&ntail; o&ntail; &thorn;e same wise, and sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;;
"To-mor&ntail; mo&ntail; &thorn;ou be a bissho&ptail;, ffor &thorn;e
bisshop&ptail; is dea&dtail; &amp; &thorn;erfor haste &thorn;e to go
vnto &thorn;e cetie, ffor God wi&llbar; at &thorn;ou be made
bisshop&ptail; &thorn;er-of."  And onone &thorn;is wriche privalie
went his way; &amp; &thorn;at night he was hosti&dtail; with a preste
nerehan&dtail; &thorn;e cetie; and becauce &thorn;at he wol&dtail;
co&mtail; wurthelie vnto &thorn;e cetie, he rase vp &thorn;at same
nyght befo&rtail; day, &amp; stale &thorn;e prestis hors &amp; his
cloke, &amp; went his way.  Me&ntail; o&ntail; &thorn;e mor&ntail;
missi&dtail; &thorn;e hors, &amp; sewi&dtail; after hy&mtail; &amp;
tuke hy&mtail;, &amp; broght hy&mtail; vnto a seculer iugement, &amp;
&thorn;er he was dampny&dtail;.  And &thorn;us he ascendi&dtail;, nott
as a bisshop&ptail; vnto &thorn;e chayr, bod as a thefe vnto &thorn;e
galows.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Demon obstinatus est in malo.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; a devu&llbar; had
turment horrebly a ma&ntail; &thorn;at he was in, it was say&dtail;
vnto hy&mtail; of a certa&ntail; ma&ntail;; "Te&llbar; me, &thorn;ou
fen&dtail;, if &thorn;ou may co&mtail; agay&ntail; vnto &thorn;e blis
at &thorn;ou hase loste; and if &thorn;ou might, what wol&dtail;
&thorn;ou do &thorn;erfo&rtail;?"  And &thorn;e fen&dtail;
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "And it war in my chose,
I had leuer go vnto he&llbar; with a sawle &thorn;at I had
desayvi&dtail;, &thorn;a&ntail; for to tur&ntail; agay&ntail; vnto
hevy&ntail;."  &amp; &thorn;ai &thorn;at har&dtail; hy&mtail; say so,
had grete mervayle &thorn;erof, &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; he say&dtail;
agay&ntail; vnto &thorn;aim; "wharto merve&llbar; ye here-of?  My
malice is so meku&llbar; an&dtail; I a&mtail; so obstinatt &amp; so
frawar&dtail;, &thorn;at I may not wi&llbar; nor desire nothyng att is
gude nor profetable vnto my selfe." et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Demonis Penitencia.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;at in Cola&ntail; &thorn;er was a
womma&ntail; vexi&dtail; with a fen&dtail;, &amp; be grace of
Go&dtail;, a holie ma&ntail; drafe hy&mtail; oute of hur.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is holie ma&ntail; har&dtail; a noder
fen&dtail; &amp; hy&mtail; to-gedur, &amp; saw &thorn;aim bathe.
An&dtail; &thorn;e tane sai&dtail; vnto &thorn;e toder; "O! &thorn;ou
wriche!  why consenti&dtail; &thorn;ou to Lucifer?  For
&thorn;erfo&rtail; we fe&llbar; fro euerlastan&dtail; ioy."  And
&thorn;e toder ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;;
"Whi di&dtail; &thorn;ou

<PB N="178">

so?"  And &thorn;ai bothe forthoght it, &amp; sai&dtail; &thorn;e tane
vnto &thorn;e toder; "Halde &thorn;i tong! &thorn;is penans is our
late; ffor &amp; &thorn;er was a pyler of yr&ntail; byrnan&dtail;,
sett fu&llbar; of sharpe rasurs, sett evy&ntail; vp fro ert&hbar; to
hevy&ntail;, me had levir, &amp; I mot suffer it &amp; I had
fless&hbar;, be drawe&ntail; &thorn;ero&ntail; vp &amp; dow&ntail; to
&thorn;e day of dome, with counan&dtail; at I mot co&mtail;
agay&ntail; vnto &thorn;at ioy &thorn;at I was in." et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Demon in ornatu vestium delectatur 
<NOTE ID="P178.N1">MS. dilectatur.</NOTE> .  Infra de ornatu.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Demon psallentes in choro impedit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how o&ntail; a grete solempne nyght at matyns,
&thorn;e Covent of Hemmerode, as &thorn;ai war sayan&dtail; &thorn;is
psal&mtail;; ' <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Domine, quid multiplicati, et
c&curl;,</FOREIGN>' &thorn;er was so many fendis in &thorn;er quere,
&thorn;at with sight of &thorn;aim goyng vp &amp; dow&ntail;, &thorn;e
ta side fali&dtail; in &thorn;e psal&mtail;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e
toder syde labur&dtail; to gar &thorn;aim say right agay&ntail;,
&thorn;ai whetti&dtail; &thorn;er tethe agayns &thorn;aim &amp;
flaye&dtail; &thorn;aim so at &thorn;ai wiste neuer what &thorn;ai
sul&dtail; say; bod &thorn;e ta syde crie&dtail; agay&ntail; &thorn;e
toder, &thorn;ai wiste neuer whatt.  And nowder &thorn;e abbott nor
&thorn;e priour cuthe bryng &thorn;aim vnto &thorn;e psalmodie
agay&ntail;, nor none acordans.  And at laste, ilfarandlie, &thorn;ai
made ane en&dtail; of &thorn;is little psalme, with grete labur
an&dtail; confusio&ntail;; &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e devu&llbar;
&amp; a&llbar; his felashu&ptail; went away, &amp; &thorn;e prior saw
&thorn;aim fle a-way in liknes of dragons.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Demon nigromancia compellitur apparere.  Infra de

Nigromancia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>

<ITEM><FOREIGN>Demon ludit ad taxillos.  Infra de ludo taxillorum.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Demon confessionem in quantum potest
impedit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;at in &thorn;e tow&ntail; of Bo&ntail;,
in &thorn;e dioces of Colay&ntail;, &thorn;er was a prestis
lemma&ntail;; &amp; hur irki&dtail; so with hur sy&ntail; at sho
hangi&dtail; hur selfe.  And as sho did it &thorn;e rape braste, &amp;
sho was sti&llbar; o&ntail; life; and whe&ntail; sho saw sho was
delyver&dtail; of &thorn;at deade,



<PB N="179">

sho went &amp; made hur a no&ntail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; be
temptacio&ntail; of &thorn;e devu&llbar;, hur luffer come agay&ntail;
&amp; labur&dtail; to hafe hur as he was wunte; and sho wol&dtail;
no&yogh;t grawnt vnto hy&mtail; be no mene.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he
hyght hur &thorn;at, &amp; sho wol&dtail; consent vnto hy&mtail;, he
sulde make hur a ladie.  And &thorn;us he labur&dtail; hur nyght &amp;
day, &amp; sho cuthe not avoy&dtail; hy&mtail;; so sho kest o&ntail;
hur hali watir, &amp; made a cros o&ntail; hur, &amp; he
vanysshi&dtail; away for a while.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e
devu&llbar; come in his lyknes vnto hur agay&ntail;, &amp;
labur&dtail; hyr.  And &thorn;a&ntail; be cownce&llbar; of a gude
ma&ntail; sho say&dtail; hur Ave Maria; and onone as sho had
say&dtail; it, he fle&dtail; away as he had bene stryke&ntail; with
ane arow, and durste not co&mtail; nere hur; not-withstondyng he lefte
hur not a&llbar;.  And a ma&ntail; cowncel&dtail; hur to go shryfe
hur; and as sho went, he come vnto hur &amp; aski&dtail; hur whyder
sho was bow&ntail;, &amp; sho sai&dtail;; "I a&mtail; bow&ntail; to
distroy bothe &thorn;e &amp; me."  And he say&dtail;; "Nay, nay, do
not so!  Tur&ntail; agay&ntail;!"  And sho ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail;
&amp; say&dtail;; "&thorn;ou hase oftsithis confowndi&dtail; me, &amp;
&thorn;erfo&rtail; I wi&llbar; now go shryfe me."  And evur as sho
went he flow abow&ntail; hur in &thorn;e ayr, as it had bene a <NOTE ID="P179.N1"><HI REND="i">After</HI> a, g &amp; half 1, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> glede.  And als sone as sho oppyn&dtail; hur mouthe
to shryfe hur, he vanysshi&dtail; away with grete crying &amp;
yowlyng; and he appere&dtail; nevur vnto hur afterwer&dtail;, nor sho
har&dtail; hy&mtail; neuer efter.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Demon eciam virginem corrumpit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;at in &thorn;e same tow&ntail; of
Bo&ntail;, how &thorn;er was a preste &thorn;at had a doghter at was
wed&dtail;, &amp; hur husban&dtail; was dea&dtail;; &amp; sho was so
fayr &thorn;at he was fer&dtail; for hur, to so meku&llbar; &thorn;at
evur whe&ntail; he went furt&hbar; he wol&dtail; spar hur in a lofte.
So o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;e devu&llbar; apperi&dtail; vnto hur in
lyknes of a ma&ntail;, &amp; spak vnto hur wurdis of luff to gar hyr
inclyne to hy&mtail;, to so meku&llbar; at he lay by hur &amp; had at
do with hur.  And sho purseyvi&dtail; at sho was desseyvi&dtail; be a
fen&dtail;, &amp; tol&dtail; hur fadur.  And he was passan&dtail;
hevye an&dtail; made meku&llbar; sorow &thorn;erfo&rtail;, &amp; had
hur thyne ow&rtail; a grete watir in-to a noder contret&hbar;, at sho
sul&dtail; be ferrer fro &thorn;is fen&dtail;, &amp; <NOTE ID="P179.N2">&amp; <HI REND="i">omitted and added above the line</HI>.</NOTE>
at sho





<PB N="180">

sulde be bettur be changyng of &thorn;e ayr.  And &thorn;is
Devu&llbar; myssi&dtail; hur, &amp; was wrot&hbar; &thorn;erwith,
&amp; come vnto &thorn;e preste &amp; say&dtail;, "&thorn;ou
cursi&dtail; preste!  Whi hase &thorn;ou take&ntail; my wife fro me?"
And whe&ntail; he had say&dtail; so, he strake hy&mtail; opo&ntail;
&thorn;e breste, at he spytt blude with iij dayes; &amp; o&ntail;
&thorn;e thri&dtail; day he dye&dtail;.  And we rede also how
&thorn;at a fen&dtail; hel&dtail; a woma&ntail; vj yere, &amp; come
vnto hur ilk nyght in lyknes of a knyght, &amp; lay with hur in
bed&dtail; as he ha&dtail; bene a ma&ntail;.  And onone as sho made
ane oppy&ntail; [confession] &thorn;erof vnto Saynt Barnar&dtail; sho
was delyver&dtail;; and he come neuer to hur after.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Demon decipit viros.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede of a scoler &thorn;at was a lustie yong ma&ntail;, &amp;
so he agrei&dtail; with a womma&ntail; at he sulde co&mtail; vnto hur
o&ntail; a nyght; &amp; sho agrei&dtail; &thorn;erto.  So o&ntail;
&thorn;e nyght he come noght to hur, bod a fen&dtail; in lyknes of hur
come vnto hy&mtail; &amp; lay with hy&mtail; a&llbar; nyght, &amp;
lete hy&mtail; hafe his liste.  And o&ntail; &thorn;e mor&ntail;
&thorn;is fen&dtail; aski&dtail; &thorn;is scoler if he wuste whame he
ha&dtail; lige&ntail; with a&llbar; nyght, &amp; he say&dtail;, ya,
with suc&hbar; a womma&ntail;.  And he say&dtail;; "Nay, &thorn;ou
hase lige&ntail; &amp; ha&dtail; at do with &thorn;e devu&llbar;;"
&amp; &thorn;at he say&dtail; it in suc&hbar; fowle wurdis at it wer
shame to te&llbar;.  &amp; with &thorn;at &thorn;e devu&llbar;
vanysshi&dtail; away.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Demon eciam iocalia offert vt ametur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how &thorn;e devu&llbar; luffi&dtail; a yong womma&ntail;,
and apperi&dtail; vnto hur oft-sithis o&ntail; &thorn;e night with
grete lightis aboute hy&mtail;, so &thorn;at a&llbar; &thorn;e chawmer
myght be see&ntail; with &thorn;e light, &amp; &thorn;e droppis of
&thorn;e seargis myght be sene; &amp; he gaff vnto hur rynges &amp;
o&thorn;er iewels of gol&dtail;, and many other &thorn;ingis.  And sho
come vnto hur confessio&ntail;, &amp; shewid &thorn;aim vnto &thorn;e
preste. et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Demon orationibus sanctorum a malo inchoato

impeditur 
<NOTE ID="P180.N1">MS. inpeditur.</NOTE> .  Supra Barnardi.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Demon impedit audire sermonem.  Supra de audire

sermonem.

<PB N="181">
</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Demon conscribit peccata hominum.  Supra

Augustini.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Demon insidiatur clericis in choro.  Supra de.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Demonis forma est terribilis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Libro de Dono Timoris,' how &thorn;er was a religious
ma&ntail; &thorn;at lay in his dortur with his brethir, and sodanlie
as [he] lay, he bega&ntail; to cry vgsomlie.  And &thorn;e covent rase
and come vnto hy&mtail;; and &thorn;ai fand hy&mtail; gloran&dtail;
faste agayns &thorn;e wa&llbar;, &amp; he wolde speke no wur&dtail;,
bod he was evy&ntail; as he had bene flaye&dtail;.  So in &thorn;e
mornyng he come to hy&mtail; selfe, and &thorn;e <NOTE ID="P181.N1">MS. &thorn;i.</NOTE> priour aski&dtail; hy&mtail; what hy&mtail;
ayli&dtail;.  And he sai&dtail; at he saw &thorn;e devu&llbar;; "and
his shap," he say&dtail;, "was so vglie, it mot not be
discryvi&dtail;; bod I say &thorn;is," say&dtail; he, "&thorn;at &amp;
&thorn;er war a hate ove&ntail; o&ntail; &thorn;e ta side me, &amp;
&thorn;e shap&ptail; of hy&mtail; o&ntail; &thorn;at other partie, me
had levur crepe in-to &thorn;at hate ove&ntail; &thorn;a&ntail; ans
behol&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; as I di&dtail;."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Depositum vsurarij non est servandum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how some tyme &thorn;er was ane vsurer &thorn;at
lent a certay&ntail; of mony vnto a selerer of &thorn;e Ceustus ordur;
and he seli&dtail; it &amp; lay&dtail; it in a kyste besyde a
certa&ntail; money of &thorn;er aw&ntail;.  So afterwar&dtail;
&thorn;is vsurar aski&dtail; it agay&ntail;; and &thorn;e monke went
vnto &thorn;e kiste, an&dtail; he fan&dtail; nowder &thorn;er
aw&ntail; money nor itt.  And he luki&dtail; &amp; saw at no bodie had
tuchi&dtail; &thorn;e lokk bod hy&mtail; selfe, &amp; &thorn;e selis
of &thorn;e sakettis safe, at he mot know no suspecio&ntail; of
&thorn;ifte. &thorn;a&ntail; he conseyvi&dtail; in his myn&dtail;
&thorn;at &thorn;e mony of &thorn;e vsuraris had devowri&dtail; and
distroye&dtail; &thorn;e money of &thorn;er monasterie.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Depositum debet reddi eo modo quo commissum est.

Supra de Cautela.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>



<PB N="182">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Depositum non debet recipi servandum nisi prius
videatur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Johannes Belet&hbar; tellis how o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;er was a
womma&ntail; &thorn;at had iij pottis fu&llbar; of gol&dtail;, &amp;
sho delyver&dtail; &thorn;aim to kepe vnto Julianus Apostata <NOTE ID="P182.N1">The Latin MSS. <HI REND="i">explain</HI>, aurum illud ne appareret in orificijs ollarum, cinere operuit.</NOTE> , for sho trowi&dtail; &thorn;at he was a gude holie
monke befo&rtail; other of his brether.  An&dtail; sho tol&dtail;
hy&mtail; not &thorn;at &thorn;er was gol&dtail; in &thorn;aim.
Tha&ntail; &thorn;is monke tuke &thorn;ies pottis, &amp; fan&dtail;
&thorn;er was so meku&llbar; gol&dtail; in &thorn;aim, &amp; he stale
it &amp; filli&dtail; &thorn;e pottis agay&ntail; fu&llbar; of
ass&hbar;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e womma&ntail; come &amp;
aski&dtail; &thorn;e pottis agay&ntail;, he delyver&dtail; hur
&thorn;aim, &amp; &thorn;ai war fu&llbar; of ass&hbar;; &amp; sho
sai&dtail; at sho ha&dtail; delyver&dtail; <NOTE ID="P182.N2">MS. <HI REND="i">has another</HI> hym <HI REND="i">here</HI>.</NOTE>
&thorn;aim vnto hy&mtail; fu&llbar; of gol&dtail;.  Bod sho cuthe
neuer gett no mendis o&ntail; hy&mtail; becauce sho had no witnes, and
his brethir &thorn;e monkis, at war by, saw no &thorn;ing abow&ntail;
&thorn;e pottis bo&dtail; ass&hbar;. et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Desiderium celestis patrie lacrimas corporales
excitat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Jacobus de Vetriaco tellis &thorn;at he had sene bothe me&ntail;
&amp; wommen sett vnto Godwar&dtail; with so mervalos &amp; so
spiritua&llbar; affeccio&ntail;, &thorn;at for desyre &thorn;ai wex
seke, &amp; so&mtail; so meku&llbar;, &thorn;at many yeris &thorn;ai
lay in &thorn;er beddis, and myght not ryse vp bod seldo&mtail; tymys.
&amp; &thorn;ai had none other cauce of sekenes bod at &thorn;er
hertis was so sett vnto Godwar&dtail;, &amp; of &thorn;e ioy of
hevy&ntail;.  And als lang as &thorn;ai war in &thorn;at thoght
&thorn;ai war evur seke &amp; at male ease. et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Desiderium carnale est reprimendum.  Supra de

abstinencia.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Desperacio.  Desperacionem inducunt tristitia et
accidia.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;er was a religious
ma&ntail; &thorn;at liffid lovable emang his brethir fro his youthe
vnto his age, so &thorn;at






<PB N="183">

&thorn;er was none &thorn;at was more religious &thorn;a&ntail; he
was.  So o&ntail; a tyme hy&mtail; happen&dtail; to fa&llbar; in-to
suche a sadnes &amp; a hevynes, &thorn;at he dowti&dtail; of his
synnys, &amp; fe&llbar; in-to a dispayr.  And he mot not be broght
oute &thorn;er-of with none auctorite of scriptur, nor he mot not be
broght into no hope of forgifnes, not-with-stondyng he had not done no
grete sy&ntail;.  And whe&ntail; his brethir aski&dtail; hy&mtail;
what hy&mtail; <NOTE ID="P183.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, what hym.</NOTE> ayli&dtail; at he was
falle&ntail; into suche a drede &amp; a dispayr, he ansswer&dtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "I may not as I was wunte to do say my
prayers, &amp; &thorn;erfo&rtail; I a&mtail; fer&dtail; to be
dampny&dtail;."  And &thorn;a&ntail; he was putt in a fermorie
a&llbar; a nyght, &amp; o&ntail; &thorn;e mor&ntail; he come vnto his
maister &amp; say&dtail;; "I may no longer feght agayns Go&dtail;."
&amp; &thorn;a&ntail; he went furt&hbar; vnto &thorn;e
myl&ntail;-da&mtail; of &thorn;e abbay, &amp; &thorn;er he
lowpi&dtail; in &amp; drowny&dtail; hy&mtail;. et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Desperandum non est de aliquo.  Supra de Abbate

et apostata.</FOREIGN></ITEM>

<ITEM><FOREIGN>Desperans sacerdos dampnatur.  Infra de sacerdote.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Desperanti ante mortem aliquando pena infernalis
ostenditur</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Petrus Clunacensis tellis how som tyme <NOTE ID="P183.N2">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, how some time.</NOTE>
&thorn;er was in Pycardi a preste &thorn;at was fu&llbar; of vices
&amp; sy&ntail;; so o&ntail; a tyme he promysi&dtail; be counce&llbar;
for to make hy&mtail; a monke in Ceustus ordur; bod he put it in
contynance, and in the mene-while <NOTE ID="P183.N3">While<HI REND="i"> is repeated and erased</HI>.</NOTE> he fe&llbar;
seke <NOTE ID="P183.N4">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, &amp; in &thorn;e mene while he felt seke.</NOTE> .  And him thoght at &thorn;er come vnto
hy&mtail; ij dragons and wol&dtail; hafe devowri&dtail; hy&mtail;, bod
be &thorn;e prayer of &thorn;e priour of &thorn;at ordur he was
delyver&dtail;, and becounan&dtail; &thorn;at he sulde fulfy&llbar;
his promys at he had made, as he behesty&dtail;.  &amp;
&thorn;a&ntail; he cover&dtail;, and yitt he fulfilli&dtail; not his
promys, bod putt it in contynnance.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he fe&llbar;
seke agay&ntail;, &amp; cried &amp; say&dtail;; "Lo! a fyre occupyes
me for to bur&ntail; me!"  &amp; he helde v&ptail; &thorn;e coverlad
betwix hy&mtail; &amp; it; and yitt









<PB N="184">

be prayers of &thorn;e monkis he was delyver&dtail;, and
&thorn;a&ntail; he fulfilli&dtail; at he beheste.  And &thorn;a&ntail;
he was ravisshi&dtail; vnto &thorn;e dome, and &thorn;er he har&dtail;
a sentans, at he sulde be dampne&dtail;, put furthe agay&ntail;
hy&mtail;.  And whe&ntail; he come agay&ntail; vnto hy&mtail; selfe,
&thorn;a&ntail; he tol&dtail; his brether &amp; say&dtail;; "Lo! two
fendis brynges a grete arow to slo me with:" &amp; &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;er fe&llbar; fro &thorn;is arow a dro&ptail; &thorn;at
&thorn;rilli&dtail; his han&dtail; vnto &thorn;e bare bone.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; he crye&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Now
takis &thorn;e fendis me, &amp; castis me into a frying pa&ntail; to
bole me &thorn;erin."  And with &thorn;at he swelte.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Desponsat virgo Maria se amantes.  Infra de

Maria 
<NOTE ID="P184.N1">MS. Infra de amantes.  The Latin MSS. <HI REND="i">have</HI>, de Maria.</NOTE> .</FOREIGN></ITEM>

<ITEM><FOREIGN>Despectus.  Despiciunt superbi alios.  Infra de

Gloria.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Detraccio est fugienda.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' how &thorn;er was ij religious me&ntail;
&thorn;at o&ntail; a tyme went furt&hbar; of &thorn;er abbay, &amp;
&thorn;ai waxe&dtail; faynt for travellyng; &amp; so &thorn;ai warr
hosti&dtail; with ane hermett, and he sett befo&rtail; &thorn;aim
suche as he had in his ce&llbar;.  So o&ntail; &thorn;e nyght as
&thorn;ai lay samen, he har&dtail; &thorn;e tone of &thorn;aim say
vnto &thorn;e toder; "This hermett hase better meate, &amp; is better
fe&dtail; &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai er &thorn;at liffis in abbays."
And whe&ntail; he har&dtail; &thorn;aim say so he hel&dtail; his tong.
And o&ntail; &thorn;e mor&ntail; he had &thorn;aim vnto a noder
hermett, &amp; bad <NOTE ID="P184.N2">Latin MSS. "Salutate eum ex me, et dicite ei; 'obserua et noli illud irrigare scilicet olera'."  Quod ille intelligens, tenuit eos.</NOTE> at &thorn;ai sulde hayls
hy&mtail;, &amp; te&llbar; hy&mtail; how he had made &thorn;aim at
fare.  And &thorn;ai bad hy&mtail; &thorn;at, &amp; he had any gude
meate, &thorn;at he sul&dtail; kepe it &amp; giff &thorn;aim nothyng
bod potage.  And he vnderstude &thorn;aim we&llbar; enog&hbar;, &amp;
hel&dtail; &thorn;aim with hy&mtail; &amp; garte &thorn;aim wurk with
hy&mtail; euer-ilk day, &amp; make skuttels &amp; lepis of wandis
evy&ntail; vnto evy&ntail;; &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai went vnto
&thorn;er prayers.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he say&dtail; he was nott
wunte to supp, bod he sulde sup&ptail; for &thorn;er sake; and he sett
befo&rtail; &thorn;aim sture brede &amp; salte.  And &thorn;a&ntail;
he say&dtail; he wol&dtail; fare better for &thorn;er sake, and







<PB N="185">

he sett befor a little ayse&llbar; &amp; garlyk&ktee;; &amp;
whe&ntail; &thorn;ai had suppi&dtail; &thorn;ai went vnto &thorn;er
prayers agay&ntail; vnto it was myr&ktee; nyght.  &amp;
&thorn;a&ntail; he say&dtail; &thorn;at he myght not for &thorn;aim
saw a&llbar; his prayers.  And o&ntail; &thorn;e mor&ntail; &thorn;ai
wol&dtail; hafe gane &thorn;er way &amp; tuke &thorn;er lefe, &amp; he
wolde not latt &thorn;aim, bod he say&dtail; &thorn;at he wol&dtail;
for charite hol&dtail; &thorn;aim iij dayes.  And o&ntail; &thorn;e
night after &thorn;ai rase and stale away &amp; wolde no langer abide
with hy&mtail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Detractoribus non est credendum.  Supra de credere.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Detrahendum non est eciam mortuis.  Infra de

mortuis.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Detrahitur bonis frequenter iniuste.  Infra de sancto

Lupo.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
