</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLXX. 
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Dileccio.  Diligit canis dominum suum, et est
ei fidelis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Solinnus tellis how &thorn;at Apius, Funius <NOTE ID="P188.N1">Latin MSS. Iunio.</NOTE>
&amp; Puplius, &amp; dyvers other with &thorn;aim, wer dampne&dtail;
att Rome; &amp; whe&ntail; &thorn;ai war dea&dtail;, one of &thorn;aim
had a hon&dtail;, &amp; he satt at &thorn;e galos att &thorn;ai hang
o&ntail; iij dayes murnan&dtail; for his maister, &amp; wolde neuer
eate meate of no mans han&dtail;.  &amp; whe&ntail; his maister was
take&ntail; dow&ntail;, &thorn;ai put brede in his maister mouthe,
&amp; he tuke it &amp; eate it; &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai keste
his maister in-to Tybur, &amp; euer as he flett in &thorn;e watir,
&thorn;e dogg swa&mtail; with hy&mtail;, &amp; at his power hel&dtail;
v&ptail; his hea&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLXXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Diligit canis vsque ad mortem.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Solinus tellis how &thorn;at whe&ntail; Iasalicius <NOTE ID="P188.N2">MS. Harl. Infelicio interfecto. MS. Arund. Iasolicio interfecto.</NOTE> was slay&ntail;, his hon&dtail; lay by hy&mtail;
&amp; wol&dtail; neuer eate meate after.  And &thorn;e kyng saw
&thorn;at, &amp; garte make a grete fyre, &amp; caste &thorn;e
dea&dtail; bodie in; &amp; onone &thorn;e hunde folowi&dtail; into
&thorn;e fyre, and gruchi&dtail; not to be burny&dtail; with his
maister bodie.





<PB N="189">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLXXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Discere.  Discendum est in omni etate.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis of ane of &thorn;e vij sagis, &amp; he wol&dtail;
a&llbar;-way say &thorn;at he was redie to ler&ntail;; so hy&mtail;
happen&dtail; o&ntail; a tyme for to fa&llbar; seke, &amp; was
bow&ntail; to dye, and a&llbar; hys ffrendis come aboute hy&mtail;
&amp; comfurthi&dtail; hy&mtail;.  And evy&ntail; sodanlie, als seke
as he was, he sett hy&mtail; vp emang &thorn;aim, &amp; tuke a buke
&amp; luki&dtail; &thorn;ero&ntail;; and &thorn;ai aski&dtail;
hy&mtail; whi he di&dtail; so, and he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
sayd at he wol&dtail; ler&ntail; somwhatt of a disputacio&ntail;,
&amp; &thorn;a&ntail; lay hy&mtail; dow&ntail; &amp; dye.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLXXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Discendi multiplex est causa.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Jacobus de Vetriaco tellis &thorn;at o&ntail; a tyme he
aski&dtail; a passand wyse ma&ntail; and a wele-letter&dtail;, how he
had lerny&dtail; so meku&llbar;.  And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail;
&amp; say&dtail;; "I had iij spiritua&llbar; maisters, and &thorn;e
furste was drede, &amp; the secunde was shame, and &thorn;e iij was
luff.  And me &thorn;oght evur in my myn&dtail; &thorn;at I saw
&thorn;aim, &amp; ilkone of &thorn;aim a wan&dtail; in his han&dtail;
to bete me wit&hbar;.  And becauce I was euer ferde to be bett, I
sesi&dtail; neuer to ler&ntail;.  And also me &thorn;oght &thorn;at my
felows &thorn;at was yonger &thorn;a&ntail; I passi&dtail; me, and
euer I vmthoght me at I wol&dtail; not be lawer &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;ai.  And so doctryne ffe&llbar; somwhatt vnto me, &amp; keste
me in a grete luff &thorn;erto, so &thorn;at I lerny&dtail; not
alonelie for drede nor yitt for shame, bod rather for perfite luff
&amp; curage &thorn;at I had vnto lernyng."

</P>
<P>
