<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLXXIV. 
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Diuicie spirituales preponende sunt
corporalibus.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis how &thorn;at whe&ntail; Anaxagoras &thorn;e
philosophur had travel&dtail; far for &thorn;e studie of philosophie,
&amp; whe&ntail; he come agay&ntail; he fan&dtail; a&llbar; his gudis
destroye&dtail;; "Ya," he sai&dtail;, "no fors of my gudis &amp; I
hafe con&nmacr;yng &amp; my hea&llbar; of my bodie; for &thorn;ies two
er wurt&hbar; meku&llbar; riches."  And so he cownti&dtail; more be
riches of connyng &amp; of hele &thorn;a&ntail; he di&dtail; be riches
of gudis.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLXXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Diuicie spirituales homine inuito perdi non
possunt.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis how ane of &thorn;e vij sagis, whe&ntail; his
enmys come into his contrey &amp; tuke a&llbar; his gudis &amp; his
riches &amp; fle&dtail; away &thorn;erwith, he was aski&dtail; whi he
folow&dtail; not o&ntail; &thorn;aim &amp; tuke so&mtail; of his gudis
fro &thorn;aim.  And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;;
"Forsuthe whar-so&mtail;-evur I go, I bere a&llbar; my gudis with me."
For he bare &thorn;aim in his breste and noght o&ntail; his shulder,
&amp; not be syght of his ene, bod rather in his myn&dtail; &amp; his
witt; "ffor &thorn;at," he say&dtail;, "&thorn;at is closi&dtail; in a
mans mynde &amp; in his harte may not be taky&ntail; away with no mans
han&dtail;, nor &thorn;ai may not stele nor fle away &thorn;erwith."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLXXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Diuicijs preponende sunt condiciones
bone.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Jacobus de Vetriaco tellis how &thorn;er was a pure ma&ntail;
&thorn;at with &thorn;e labur off his handis vnnethis cuthe gett his
lifelo&dtail;, ffor whe&ntail; he had suppi&dtail;, &thorn;er lefte
right noght ouer night vnto in &thorn;e mornyng; &amp; evur he was merie, to
so meku&llbar; &thorn;at euerilk night, whe&ntail; he was

<PB N="191">

in his be&dtail; with his wife, he wolde, &amp; sho, syng a sang
merelie at a&llbar; &thorn;er neghburs mott here; &amp;
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai wol&dtail; fa&llbar; o&ntail; slepe.  So
&thorn;er neghburs had grete merva&llbar; &thorn;eroff, and one of
&thorn;aim sai&dtail;; "I sa&llbar; make swilk a way at I sa&llbar;
gar hy&mtail; lefe hys syngyng."  &amp; in presens of so&mtail; of his
neghburs, opo&ntail; a night he tuke a sache&llbar; fu&llbar; of
sylver, &amp; lete fa&llbar; afo&rtail; &thorn;is pure mans dure.  And
whe&ntail; at he rase &amp; sulde go furth to seke his lifelo&dtail;,
he fande &thorn;is bagg, &amp; he tuke it vp &amp; turny&dtail;
agay&ntail; &thorn;er-with in-to his howse &amp; hi&dtail; it.  So
o&ntail; &thorn;e night after, als tyte as he was in his be&dtail;, he
vmthoght hy&mtail; in his mynde what he wolde do &thorn;er-with; &amp;
he was fer&dtail; &thorn;erfo&rtail; &thorn;at he war not culpi&dtail;
with felony &thorn;erfo&rtail;, &amp; also at no thevis sulde stele it
fro&mtail; hy&mtail;, or if so be at he boght or solde &thorn;er-with,
or boght any lande, he mon&dtail; be suspecte, vnto so meku&llbar; at
he was so occupye&dtail; in his thoght &thorn;at at &thorn;at nyght he
sang not, nor was not merie; bod a grete while after he was
passan&dtail; hevy &amp; thoghtfu&llbar;.  &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; his
neghburs aski&dtail; hy&mtail; whi he was so hevie, and whi he sang
nott as he was wunte to do; and he wolde nott te&llbar; &thorn;aim
&thorn;e treut&hbar;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he at aght &thorn;is money
sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "I knaw &thorn;e treut&hbar;; for suche a
day &amp; in suche a place &thorn;ou fande my money, &amp; tuke it vp
at I &amp; myne neghburs saw, &amp; had it in-to &thorn;i howse."  And
whe&ntail; he har&dtail; &thorn;is he wex fer&dtail; &amp;
shamefu&llbar;, &amp; say&dtail;; "woo wurt&hbar; &thorn;at money
&thorn;at hase turment me thus; for se&ntail; &thorn;at I fan&dtail;
it I had neuer ioy in my harte; &amp; I hafe bene trubbled in my witt
euer syne, more &thorn;a&ntail; euer I was before whe&ntail; I with
grete labur of my bodie &amp; my handis gat my meat.  And
&thorn;erfo&rtail; take &thorn;i mony &thorn;i selfe agay&ntail;, at I
may syng &amp; be mery as I was wunte to done."  And so he di&dtail;;
and fro it was gone, &thorn;is pure ma&ntail; made als merie as evur
did he.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Diuicie temporales impediunt spirituales.  Infra de

fideiussore.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLXXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Diuicias habere et non amare virtus est.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Gregu&rtail; tellis of ane hermett &thorn;at was a ma&ntail;
of grete vertue &amp; lefte a&llbar; maner of gudis for Goddis sake,
to so mekle

<PB N="192">

at he had no gude lefte bod a catt.  And he prayed vnto God at He
wulde vuchsafe to latt hy&mtail; witt who sulde be his felow in
&thorn;e blis of hevy&ntail;.  And it was ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail;
fro&mtail; a&llbar;-myghtie God &amp; say&dtail;, &thorn;at Gregur
sulde be his felow.  And whe&ntail; he har&dtail; &thorn;is he made
meku&llbar; sorow, &amp; &thorn;oght his wilfu&llbar; pouertie
profetti&dtail; hy&mtail; bod little, se&ntail; Gregur &thorn;at had
so meku&llbar; riches sulde be his felow in hevy&ntail;.  So o&ntail;
a nyght as he was in his prayers, hy&mtail; &thorn;oght &thorn;at he
har&dtail; almighti God say vnto hy&mtail;; "Gregur, &thorn;at is so
riche of gudis, is als pure in his spiritt as &thorn;ou erte, for
&thorn;ou hase more lykyng in &thorn;i pouertie &thorn;a&ntail; he
hase in his riches."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLXXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Doctrina.  Doctor debet ostendere facto quod
verbo docet.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede ex 'Dictis Patrum' &thorn;at &thorn;e abbott Ioh&ntail;
was aski&dtail; whi he liffi&dtail; so straytelie emang his disciples,
&amp; gaff &thorn;aim so strayte chargis &amp; commaundmentis, and he
&amp; &thorn;ai bothe mott hafe comme&ntail; vnto hevy&ntail; be other
menys.  And he made sorow &amp; ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; with grete
wepyng, an&dtail; sayde; "In a&llbar; my life I did neuer myne
aw&ntail; wi&llbar;, nor I taght nevur no ma&ntail; to do noght bod at
I di&dtail; my selfe befo&rtail;."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Doctor debet habere discretum modum et gestum

compositum.  Infra de predicacione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Dolor.  Dolendum est non de re que recuperari non

potest.  Supra de Consilio.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Dolor quandoque prodest corpori.  Infra de

gaudio.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Dolendum non est de morte amici temporalis.  Infra

de morte.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Doluspunitur grauiter.  Supra de adulterio.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>

<PB N="193">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLXXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Dominicus ordinem per beatam virginem
predicatorum impetrauit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; Saynt Dominyk was in his
prayers at Rome, and labur&dtail; beselie vnto &thorn;e pope for
confirmacio&ntail; of his ordur, o&ntail; a tyme he saw in his spiritt
almyghti God in &thorn;e ayre, shakand iij speris like as He
wol&dtail; hafe destroye&dtail; a&llbar; &thorn;is werl&dtail;.  And
our Ladie, His meke moder, come vnto Hy&mtail; and aski&dtail;
Hy&mtail; whatt He wul&dtail; do; &amp; He say&dtail; &thorn;at <NOTE ID="P193.N1">Latin MSS.  "Mundum," inquit, "tribus vicijs corruptum, punire uolo."</NOTE> He wolde destrow &thorn;is werl&dtail;, with iij
vicis &thorn;at was corrupte; &thorn;at was, with pride, concupiscens
&amp; avarice.  And &thorn;a&ntail; sho say&dtail;; "Dere Son! Meng
&thorn;i rightwusnes with mercie!  For I hafe a trew servan&dtail; at
sa&llbar; ca&llbar; &thorn;is werl&dtail; agay&ntail; vnto &thorn;e;
&amp; in euer-ilk place sha&llbar; destroy vicis."  And
&thorn;a&ntail; hur So&ntail; was sober&dtail; &amp; say&dtail;; "I
wol&dtail; se hy&mtail; at sulde be ordan&dtail; vnto suche ane
offes."  &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; our Lady shewi&dtail; Hy&mtail; ffurst
Saynt Dominyk, &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; Saynt Frauncys; &amp; hur
So&ntail; commendid &thorn;aim gretelie.  And after &thorn;is
visio&ntail; Saynt Dominyk mett Saynt Frawncis &thorn;at he neuer saw
befo&rtail; bod in &thorn;e vysio&ntail;, &amp; he kend hy&mtail; wele
enog&hbar;, &amp; kissy&dtail; &amp; say&dtail;; "&thorn;ou erte my
felow; latt vs ston&dtail; bothe samen, &amp; none aduersarie
sa&llbar; prevayle ayeyns vs."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLXXX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ad-huc de Sancto Dominico.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in his Legend how o&ntail; a tyme, whe&ntail; he come home
&amp; fande his brether at &thorn;er reste, &amp; &thorn;e yate
sparri&dtail;, he wal&dtail; not wake&ntail; &thorn;aim, bod with his
holie prayers he oppyn&dtail; &thorn;e yate, &amp; he &amp; his felow
went in.  And a no&thorn;er tyme he had with hy&mtail; a mon&ktee; of
Ceustus ordur, &amp; o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; &thorn;ai wol&dtail;
hafe gone into a kurk to say &thorn;er prayers, &amp; fand &thorn;e
dure lokki&dtail;, &thorn;urgh his prayers &thorn;e dure oppyn&dtail;,
&amp; &thorn;ai went in &amp; say&dtail; &thorn;ar deuocions.



<PB N="194">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLXXXI.  
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Dominici precibus habitum ordinis virgo Maria
attulit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Also we rede in his Legen&dtail; ewhils Mayster Raynal&dtail;, at
was dene of Aurilianens &amp; a maister of law, was essuri&dtail; vnto
Saynt Dominyk to co&mtail; into his ordur, &amp; hy&mtail;
happen&dtail; for to fa&llbar; seke, &amp; was in despayr of
lechecrafte, &thorn;is holie Saynt prayed feruentlie for his
hea&llbar;.  And our Ladie &amp; ij virgyns with hur apperi&dtail;
visible &amp; enoynti&dtail; &thorn;is seke ma&ntail; with ane
oyntement &thorn;at ane of &thorn;ies virgyns bare, &amp; curi&dtail;
hy&mtail; bothe spirituallie &amp; bodelie, to so meku&llbar;
&thorn;at fro thens furt&hbar; he feli&dtail; nevur movyng of his
fless&hbar; vnto sy&ntail;; &amp; sho schewi&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;e
abbett of &thorn;e ordur at &thorn;e toder virgy&ntail; broght.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLXXXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Dominici oratio semper auditur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede also in his Legen&dtail; how &thorn;at Saynt Domynyk
o&ntail; a tyme [come] vnto a priour of Ceustus ordur, &thorn;at was a
devote ma&ntail; &amp; famyliari with hy&mtail;, that aski&dtail;
hy&mtail; in privatie &amp; praye&dtail; hy&mtail; to te&llbar;
hy&mtail; so&mtail; of &thorn;e gracis at God had giffe&ntail;
hy&mtail;; and he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "I
tolde neuer ma&ntail; at I sa&llbar; te&llbar; you, and I war&ntail;
you te&llbar; no ma&ntail; whils I liff, ffor I latt you witt
&thorn;at I aski&dtail; neuer of God no thyng bod I had my desyre."
So &thorn;is priour thoght &thorn;at he wol&dtail; prufe &thorn;is,
&amp; sai&dtail;; "Besoght <NOTE ID="P194.N1">Latin MSS.  "Impetretis ergo a deo ut magister C. Theutonicus intret ordinem uestrum."</NOTE> ye of Go&dtail;,
&amp; I pray you beseke it, at Maister C[lemet] enter in-to your
ordur, for your brether gretelie desyris hy&mtail;, &amp; he hase no
wi&llbar; &thorn;er-to; &amp; he is a famos ma&ntail; and a gracious
&amp; a wele-letter&dtail;."  &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is holie
ma&ntail; say&dtail;; "Ye hafe aski&dtail; of me a grete &thorn;ing.
Not-withstondyng pray ye with me &thorn;erfor &thorn;is night, &amp;
to-mor&ntail; sa&llbar; maister




<PB N="195">

Clemett co&mtail; befo&rtail; day &amp; aske &thorn;e abett of our
ordur."  And so he di&dtail;, &amp; liffi&dtail; in &thorn;e ordur
many day in perseuerans of gude holynes.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLXXXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Dormiencium septem.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in &thorn;er Legen&dtail;, whe&ntail; Decius &thorn;e
Emperour persewi&dtail; Criste&ntail; me&ntail;, &thorn;er was vij
yong Criste&ntail; me&ntail;, &amp; &thorn;ai fle&dtail; a&llbar;
samen for drede off &thorn;is Decius vnto &thorn;e mownt of
Celio&ntail; beside &thorn;e cetie of Ephesim, whar &thorn;ai war
bor&ntail;, &amp; &thorn;er &thorn;ai hi&dtail; &thorn;aim in a
de&ntail;.  And &thorn;ai warr accusi&dtail; vnto Decius Cesar at
&thorn;ai war &thorn;er, &amp; he garte close vp &thorn;e den mouthe
at &thorn;ai sulde not co&mtail; oute, bod at &thorn;ai sulde dy
&thorn;er.  And as God wol&dtail;, sodanlie &thorn;ai fe&llbar;
o&ntail; slepe; and &thorn;er was o&thorn;er privay Criste&ntail;
me&ntail; &thorn;at wrate &thorn;er martirdo&mtail; &amp; put it
betwix ij stonys.  And &thorn;a&ntail; whe&ntail; Decius &amp;
a&llbar; his kynri&dtail; was dea&dtail; ccclxxij [yeris], after
&thorn;e xxx<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> yere of Theodoce &thorn;e Emperour, &thorn;at was a
Cristenma&ntail; &amp; made grete sorow for ane heresye &thorn;at
&thorn;a&ntail; bega&ntail; at rise in &thorn;aim &thorn;at
trusti&dtail; not in vprysyng of fless&hbar;, almighti God
raysi&dtail; &thorn;aim in &thorn;is maner of wyse.  The&rtail; was in
&thorn;e cetie of Ephesie a cetisy&ntail; &thorn;at went vnto
&thorn;is mownt &amp; &thorn;oght to make &thorn;er a stable for his
cate&llbar;.  And he oppyn&dtail; &thorn;is de&ntail;, and whe&ntail;
it was oppy&ntail;, thies Saynttis rase vp and trowe&dtail; at
&thorn;ai had slepi&dtail; bod a nyght; and one of &thorn;aim
&thorn;at hight Malchus, &thorn;at vsi&dtail; to seriff &thorn;aim,
&thorn;ai sent hy&mtail; in-to &thorn;e cetie to by &thorn;aim
brea&dtail;, &amp; for to witt whatt Decius sayde.  And he tuke with
hy&mtail; v soldi of &thorn;er money.  And whe&ntail; he come att
&thorn;e cetie yate, he saw a cros set v&ptail; &thorn;er-opo&ntail;,
&amp; he had grete mervayle; and &thorn;a&ntail; he went vnto euer-ilk
yate, &amp; he fan&dtail; it so.  And &thorn;an he went agay&ntail;
vnto &thorn;e furste yate, &amp; he trowi&dtail; &thorn;at he had
dremy&dtail;, and with grete ferdnes he went into &thorn;e cetie.  And
whe&ntail; he har&dtail; &thorn;at euer-ilk ma&ntail; was a
Criste&ntail; ma&ntail;, and [purseyvid] at &thorn;e cetie was
o&thorn;erwice biggi&dtail;; &amp; at he cuthe know no ma&ntail; at he
saw, he aski&dtail; if &thorn;at was &thorn;e cetie of Ephesim; and
ane ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; say&dtail; ya.  &amp; he tuke oute
his syluer to by bread with, &amp; he was take&ntail; onone, &amp;
&thorn;ai

<PB N="196">

say&dtail; at he had fo&ntail; a tresur, &amp; &thorn;ai putt a rape
aboute his nekk &amp; harli&dtail; hy&mtail; <NOTE ID="P196.N1">MS. &thorn;aim.</NOTE>
&thorn;urg&hbar; &thorn;e cetie to &thorn;er bissho&ptail;; &amp; he
trowi&dtail; at &thorn;ai had drawe&ntail; hy&mtail; vnto Decius
Cesar.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e bissho&ptail; aski&dtail; hy&mtail; if
he had fo&ntail; any tresurrie, he ansswer&dtail; &amp; say&dtail;
&thorn;at he had &thorn;at syluer of his fadur &amp; his moder.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; he aski&dtail; hy&mtail; whyne he was, &amp; who was
his fadur &amp; his moder; &amp; he sai&dtail;; "&thorn;ai dwe&llbar;
in &thorn;is Cetie, in suche a place, &amp; here-in I was bor&ntail;
&amp; &thorn;is be Ephesim."  And &thorn;er was no ma&ntail; &thorn;at
ken&dtail; nowder his fadur nor his moder; &amp; he luke&dtail; aboute
hy&mtail; if he saw any of his cussyns, and he was evy&ntail; emang
&thorn;aim as he had bene fon&dtail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e
bisshop&ptail; sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "How may it be trew at
&thorn;ou ha&dtail; &thorn;is syluer of &thorn;i fadur, &amp; &thorn;e
scriptur of &thorn;aim is mo&rtail; &thorn;a&ntail; ccclxxij yere
ol&dtail;, &amp; &thorn;ai hafe &thorn;e figur of Decius Cesar made
opo&ntail; &thorn;aim?"  And &thorn;a&ntail; he had grete merve&llbar;
&amp; say&dtail;; "Liffis not Decius Cesar yit?"  And &thorn;e
bissho&ptail; say&dtail;; "Nay, so&ntail;, &thorn;er is none now in
a&llbar; &thorn;is lan&dtail; &thorn;at is calli&dtail; Decius, bod
here hase bene a noder emperour of long tyme."  And &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;is Malchus; "In &thorn;is I hafe a grete mervayle, ffor
yisterday I saw Decius co&mtail; into &thorn;is cetie, &amp; &thorn;is
be Ephesim, bod no ma&ntail; trowis me; bod folow me &amp; ye
sa&llbar; trow my felows."  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e
bisshop&ptail; vmthoght hy&mtail;, &amp; say&dtail; vnto &thorn;e
iustice; "&thorn;is is so&mtail; visio&ntail; att God wi&llbar; shew
vs."  An&dtail; &thorn;ai rase v&ptail; &amp; fan&dtail; betwix ij
stonys letters seli&dtail; with gol&dtail;; &amp; &thorn;e
bissho&ptail; garte semble &thorn;e peple, &amp; red it befo&rtail;
&thorn;aim.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai come at &thorn;e de&ntail;,
&thorn;ai luki&dtail; opo&ntail; &thorn;ies Sayntis <NOTE ID="P196.N2">Harl. MS. videntesque facies sanctorum in spelunca quasi rosas florentes, procidentes glorificauerunt deum.</NOTE> , and &thorn;ai fe&llbar; evy&ntail; dow&ntail;
in-to wele-saueryng rosis.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e Emperour
har&dtail; te&llbar; of &thorn;is, he come vnto &thorn;aim &amp; he
saw &thorn;er facis shyne, &amp; fe&llbar; dow&ntail; o&ntail; kneis
befor &thorn;aim &amp; wepi&dtail;, an&dtail; halsi&dtail; &thorn;aim
&amp; &thorn;anki&dtail; Go&dtail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail;
Maximia&ntail; sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "For &thorn;e almyghti
Go&dtail; hase raysi&dtail; vs, &thorn;at &thorn;ou may trow
vndowtable at &thorn;e rysyng of deade folk sa&llbar; be trew.  For
now we hafe ryssy&ntail; &amp; liffi&dtail;, and we wer evy&ntail; as
a childe is in his moder wambe, bod slepi&dtail; &amp; feli&dtail; no
hurte."  And with &thorn;is &thorn;ai leny&dtail; &thorn;aim
dow&ntail;, &thorn;at a&llbar; folk saw, &amp; yeldi&dtail; v&ptail;
&thorn;er sawlis vnto a&llbar;mighti Go&dtail;. et c&curl;.






<PB N="197">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLXXXIV. 
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Dormicio.  Dormiendum non est in oratione
privata.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;er was a young mon&ktee; &thorn;at was
a gude liffer, &amp; he was so wayke &amp; so feble &thorn;at
hy&mtail; yrki&dtail; to liff <NOTE ID="P197.N1">Latin MSS. sed uite sancte adeo debilis erat corpore, vt eum viuere tederet.</NOTE> .  And o&ntail; a
nyght whe&ntail; matyns was done, he leny&dtail; hy&mtail; dow&ntail;
opo&ntail; a tre befo&rtail; ane altar vnto Laudes tyme, as was his
ordur, &amp; &thorn;er he fe&llbar; o&ntail; slepe.  And our Ladie,
Saynt Marie, come & <NOTE ID="P197.N2">Latin MS. et ueste eum feriens.</NOTE> putt opo&ntail; hy&mtail;
&amp; say&dtail;; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Non est hic locus
dormiendi;</FOREIGN> here is not &thorn;e place off slepyng, bod
rather of praying."  And with &thorn;at he waken&dtail; &amp; luke
aboute hy&mtail; who spak&ktee;, &amp; he saw &thorn;e bak of a
womma&ntail;, &amp; perseyvi&dtail; at itt was a wommans voyce at
spak.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Dormire parum debet sufficere religioso.  Infra de

labore.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLXXXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Dormiendum non est in choro.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis of ane olde mon&ktee; &thorn;at was a grete
sleper; so o&ntail; a nyght as he stude at &thorn;e psalmodie at
matyns &amp; slepi&dtail;, hy&mtail; thoght at he saw in his slepe,
standan&dtail; befo&rtail; hy&mtail;, a long ma&ntail; &amp; a
diffor&mtail;, &thorn;at hel&dtail; in his han&dtail; a lang, grete,
clayie wispe <NOTE ID="P197.N3">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats here</HI>, in his hand.</NOTE> , as it had wypi&dtail; hors.
&amp; he luki&dtail; angrelie of &thorn;is monk &amp; sai&dtail; vnto
hy&mtail;; "Wharto stondis &thorn;ou he&rtail; al night &amp; slepis?"
And he hytt hy&mtail; in &thorn;e face with &thorn;is clayie wispe.
And with &thorn;at he waken&dtail;, &amp; was fer&dtail; at he
sul&dtail; hafe streky&ntail; hy&mtail;.  And he plukki&dtail; his
hede so hastelie bak&ktee;, at he brakk it behyn&dtail; hy&mtail;
o&ntail; &thorn;e wa&llbar;. et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Duplicitas semper est vitanda.  Infra de honore

parentum.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Dux.  Ducis vxor siue ducissa delicate viuens eciam

in presenti punitur.  Supra de delicijs.</FOREIGN>



<PB N="198">
</ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Dux malus in infernum portatur.  Infra de Inuidia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Dux bonus in fine conuertitur.  Infra de morte.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLXXXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ebrietas.  Ebrius grauiter punitur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;er was a pylgra&mtail; at, whe&ntail;
he fan&dtail; gude wyne o&ntail; a tyme, he sel&dtail; his
slavy&ntail; &amp; drank it &thorn;er-att.  And he drank so
meku&llbar; at he was dronke&ntail;, and fe&llbar; evy&ntail; wude, to
so meku&llbar; at me&ntail; trowi&dtail; at he was

<NOTE ID="P198.N1">MS. repeats, was.</NOTE> verelie dea&dtail;.  So his spiritt was
taky&ntail; &amp; le&dtail; &thorn;er paynys was, and &thorn;er he saw
&thorn;e devu&llbar; sitt in a hy tre, as him thoght, couer&dtail;
with burdis.  And emang o&thorn;er &thorn;er was broght befo&rtail;
hy&mtail; &thorn;e abbott of Corbey&curl;; and &thorn;e devu&llbar;
rase v&ptail; &amp; haylsi&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; servi&dtail; with a
drynk mengi&dtail; with burnsto&ntail; o&ntail; a burnyng chales.  And
whe&ntail; he had dronky&ntail;, he was commandi&dtail; vnto &thorn;e
depe pitt.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e pylgra&mtail; saw &thorn;is he was
passan&dtail; fer&dtail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e devu&llbar;
crye&dtail; with a hy voyce &amp; sai&dtail;; "Bryng hedur &thorn;at
lor&dtail; of ours &thorn;at late sel&dtail; hys pylgra&mtail;
clothyng &amp; drank it att &thorn;e gude wyne, an&dtail; was
dronky&ntail;."  And whe&ntail; &thorn;is pylgra&mtail; har&dtail;
&thorn;is, he luki&dtail; vppo&ntail; his gude aunge&llbar; &thorn;at
broght hy&mtail; thedur, &amp; sai&dtail;, &amp; he wol&dtail; delyver
hy&mtail; fro thens, he sul&dtail; neuer after be dronke&ntail;.  And
so he come agay&ntail; vnto hy&mtail; selfe, and noti&dtail; &thorn;e
day &amp; how&rtail;, &amp; went &amp; shrafe hy&mtail; &amp;
di&dtail; his pylgramege, &amp; come home agay&ntail; vnto his
aw&ntail; lan&dtail;.  And he fan&dtail; att &thorn;e same Abbott
dye&dtail; &thorn;e same tyme at he saw his saule commytt vnto
perpetua&llbar; pay&ntail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Ebrietatis causas sapientes fugiunt.  Supra de

abstinencia.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLXXXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ecclesia de vsuris et rapinis construi non
debet.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how o&ntail; a tyme, whe&ntail; ane vsurar of his
ravy&ntail; &amp; his vsurye ha&dtail; byggi&dtail; a kur&ktee;, he
desiri&dtail; a bisshop&ptail; to co&mtail; &amp; halow



<PB N="199">

itt.  And as &thorn;e bissho&ptail; an&dtail; his clergie di&dtail; &thorn;e
offes of consecracio&ntail;, he was war of &thorn;e devu&llbar;
syttan&dtail; vppo&ntail; &thorn;e hy alta&rtail; in a chare,
&thorn;at sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "Why halows &thorn;ou my kurk?
Sese! for &thorn;e iuridiccio&ntail; &thorn;eroff longis vnto me; ffor
it is byggi&dtail; a&llbar; of ravy&ntail; &amp; vsurie."  And with
&thorn;is, &thorn;e bisshop&ptail; &amp; his clerkis wer fer&dtail;
&amp; went &thorn;er ways.  And onone as &thorn;ai wer gette&ntail;
oute &thorn;er-of, &thorn;er was a grete noyce &thorn;er-in, &amp;
&thorn;e devu&llbar; sett fire &thorn;erin &amp; burny&dtail; it vp
&amp; destroye&dtail; itt euere dele, att a&llbar; folke mott se. et
c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Ecclesie dedicacione expellitur demon.  Supra de

dedicacione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Ecclesie sepultura parum prodest aliquando.  Infra

de sepultura.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLXXXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ecclesiis non sunt bona temporalia
subtraenda.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Petrus Damyanus tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was ane erle
&thorn;at was of gude name and liffi&dtail; we&llbar;; and whe&ntail;
he was dea&dtail;, a ma&ntail; of religio&ntail; was ravisshi&dtail;
in his spiritt, and <NOTE ID="P199.N1">Harl. MS. vidit ... dictum Comitem in inferno, in supremo gradu cuiusdam scale erecte(s)* inter stridentes et crepitantes flammas.  * Arund. MS. erecte.</NOTE> he saw [&thorn;is erle] in
he&llbar; in a grete degre, syttand vppo&ntail; a hy leddir in myddest
of burnan&dtail; paynys; and as hy&mtail; thoght, &thorn;at stie stude
evy&ntail; in myddeste of he&llbar;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he
aski&dtail; whi &thorn;is erle &thorn;at was so gude a ma&ntail; and
liffi&dtail; so rightwuslie, was so turmente.  It was tolde hy&mtail;
&thorn;at it was for a possessio&ntail; &thorn;at he had take&ntail;
fro &thorn;e kur&ktee; off Metence, &thorn;at was giffe&ntail; vnto
God &amp; Saynt Stephan; and for &thorn;is, fro hensfurt&hbar;,
a&llbar; his sequele at holdis &thorn;is same possessio&ntail; &amp;
knowis &thorn;erof mo&ntail; be punysshi&dtail; vppo&ntail; &thorn;is
same stye.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Elacio cordis semper causatur ex adulacione et ex

vestium apparatu.  Supra de augurio.</FOREIGN></ITEM>

<ITEM><FOREIGN>Elacio cordis aufert graciam a deo concessam.  Infra

de locucione.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>



<PB N="200">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCLXXXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Eleccio.  Eligi semper debet melior ad
officium.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Petrus Clariuall tellis how in a Cathedra&llbar;-kurk of Fraunce
&thorn;er fe&llbar; a <NOTE ID="P200.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, a.</NOTE> dis-corde for chesyng of
&thorn;er bisshop&ptail;.  So &thorn;ai compromysi&dtail; vnto a
cardina&llbar; &thorn;at was &thorn;er, &thorn;at he sulde chese
&thorn;aim one of ij, whame &thorn;ai namy&dtail;.  And &thorn;is
Cardina&llbar; tuke counce&llbar; att &thorn;is holie ma&ntail; Petrus
Clariua&llbar;, whethur hy&mtail; was bettir to chese to be
bisshop&ptail;; and he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sayde,
&thorn;at of ij fals penys &thorn;e bettur may nott be chosy&ntail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Eligi non debet puer in prelatum vel iudicem.  Infra

de puero.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Eligi non debet prelatus racione carnalitatis.  Infra

de prelato.  Et supra de abbate.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Elemosina semper est danda.  Supra de dacione et

dono.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Elemosina pauperi negari non debet.  Infra de

paupertate.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Elemosina eciam in presenti deus reddit.  Supra de

auaricia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Elemosina temperata auget, negata, temporalia tollit

quandoque.  Supra de auaricia.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXC.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Elemosina temporalia auget.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Petrus Damianus tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a bisshop&ptail;
&thorn;at thursty&dtail; gretelie to dryn&ktee; wyne, and
commandi&dtail; it to be broght vnto hy&mtail;; an&dtail; &thorn;e
butler powri&dtail; furt&hbar; a&llbar; &thorn;at was in &thorn;e
flakett &amp; broght it vnto hy&mtail;.  And sodanlie &thorn;er come a
pure ma&ntail; &amp; praye&dtail; &thorn;aim to giff hy&mtail; it, or
els he monde dye for threste; and &thorn;e byssho&ptail;
commandi&dtail; it to be giffe&ntail; vnto hy&mtail;.  And whe&ntail;
he



<PB N="201">

had dronke&ntail; it he crye&dtail; for more, &amp; sai&dtail; his
thriste was not slaki&dtail;; and &thorn;e bissho&ptail; bad giff
hy&mtail; more.  And &thorn;e butler sai&dtail; at &thorn;er was no
more; and &thorn;a&ntail; he bad &thorn;aim go vnto &thorn;e
vyne-gart&hbar; &amp; luke if &thorn;er war lefte any vynys growyng,
&amp; feche hy&mtail;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai come &thorn;er,
&thorn;e vyne-gart&hbar;, at no frute was in befor, was growyng
fu&llbar; of rype grapis.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXCI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Elemosina reddit plus quam datur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Petrus Damianus tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a pure
husband-ma&ntail;, and he had no mo&rtail; money lefte to by hy&mtail;
with soule vnto his brea&dtail; bod a peny; and sodanlie &thorn;er
come a pure ma&ntail; &amp; aski&dtail; hy&mtail; a peny for Goddis
sake, &amp; he gaff hy&mtail; &thorn;is peny with gude wi&llbar;.  And
so he went home &amp; sett hy&mtail; dow&ntail; to his meatt, and his
wife sett brea&dtail; befo&rtail; hy&mtail; &amp; no soule.  And
sodanlie &thorn;er come in ane vncut&hbar; ma&ntail; hastelie with xx
soldi bo&ntail; in a clothe, &amp; putt it in his han&dtail;, &amp;
sai&dtail; his lorde sent hy&mtail; it.  &amp; he thanki&dtail;
hy&mtail; &amp; praye&dtail; hy&mtail; bide &amp; drynke.  And ewhils
&thorn;ai went at feche hy&mtail; a drynk, sodanlie he was away.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXCII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Elemosina remuneratur in presenti.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Gestis Iohannis Elemosinarij' how &thorn;er was a
knyght at was robbi&dtail;, and he come vnto &thorn;is Iohannes &amp;
tol&dtail; hy&mtail; of his myschefe; and he commandi&dtail; a
servan&dtail; of his to gyff hy&mtail; xv libra of gol&dtail;, and he
gaff hy&mtail; bod v libra.  And &thorn;er come a wedow vnto hy&mtail;
with a by&llbar;, &amp; xv <NOTE ID="P201.N1">Latin MSS. dedit ei ... noticiam exennij v. centenariorum auri.</NOTE> markis of gol&dtail;
wrety&ntail; &thorn;erin, &amp; he tuke it &amp; delyvir&dtail; it
vnto his me&ntail;, &amp; aski&dtail; &thorn;aim what &thorn;ai gaff
&thorn;e pure ma&ntail;, &amp; &thorn;ai sai&dtail; xv libra, as
&thorn;ai had in commandment; &amp; he had knowlege at &thorn;ai did
wrong &amp; aski&dtail; &thorn;aim &thorn;e by&llbar; agay&ntail;, and
&thorn;er was wrette&ntail; &thorn;erin bod v <NOTE ID="P201.N2">The Latin MSS. further explain that Iohannes said, "Si dedissetis xv ut iusseram, que attulit v. centenaria xv attulisset."</NOTE> .
And &thorn;a&ntail; he aski&dtail; &thorn;e wedow how







<PB N="202">

meku&llbar; at sho had writte&ntail;, &amp; sho sai&dtail; xv, bod x
was away; and sho sai&dtail; sho trowe&dtail; it was Goddis wi&llbar;
att sho sul&dtail; offer bod v.  An&dtail; &thorn;a&ntail; his
servan&dtail; was ashamy&dtail; &amp; grawnti&dtail; treut&hbar;,
&amp; telli&dtail; hy&mtail; a&llbar;, &amp; besoght hy&mtail; of
forgifnes.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXCIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Elemosina remuneratur in futuro.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Gregorie tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a shomaker
&thorn;at wol&dtail; wurk a&llbar; &thorn;e weke day, &amp; o&ntail;
&thorn;e Satturday <NOTE ID="P202.N1">Latin MSS. die Sabbato.</NOTE> he wol&dtail; evur go vnto
&thorn;e kur&ktee;.  So &thorn;er was a gude halie ma&ntail;, &amp;
he saw be revelacio&ntail; of &thorn;is ma&ntail;, &thorn;at a howce
was byggi&dtail; for hy&mtail; in hevy&ntail;, and &thorn;ai at
bigi&dtail; it wroght alway o&ntail; &thorn;e Satturday; and he
spyrri&dtail; of &thorn;at mans life, &amp; he fan&dtail; how
&thorn;at he wroght a&llbar; &thorn;e weke day, &amp; what at he mott
safe ouer his meatt &amp; his clothe, he wol&dtail; go vnto &thorn;e
kur&ktee; vpo&ntail; &thorn;e Satturday &amp; giff it vnto pure
me&ntail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXCIV. 
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Elemosina facta de rapinis et iniuste acquisitis
non valet.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Petrus Damianus tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a
bisshop&ptail;, and in a visyo&ntail; he saw a pope at hight Benett,
att wol&dtail; new be dede, &amp; hy&mtail; &thorn;oght he saw
hy&mtail; bodelie syttan&dtail; o&ntail; a blak hors.  And &thorn;is
bisshop&ptail; sai&dtail;; "Allas! erte &thorn;ou nott pope Benett, at
is newlie dea&dtail;?"  &amp; he sai&dtail;; "Yis, I a&mtail; &thorn;at
same vnhappy ma&ntail;; and here," he say&dtail;, "I am grevuslye
turment, bod I despayr nott of &thorn;e mercie of Go&dtail;, &amp; I
may gett any helpe.  And &thorn;erfo&rtail; I pray &thorn;e go vnto my
successur, &amp; bi&dtail; hy&mtail; do almos for me in suche a place,
for &thorn;at almos at is giffe&ntail; for me hedur-towar&dtail;
profettis me noght, for it was a&llbar; of robbery &amp; of
wrong-gette&ntail; gudis."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Elemosina debet fieri de vestibus.  Infra de

histrionibus.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>



<PB N="203">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> 
<CORR SIC="CCCXV">CCXCV</CORR>. 
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Elemosina non debet esse causa vane
glorie.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Heraclides tellis how a halie womma&ntail; of Rome, &thorn;at
hight Sancta Melama <NOTE ID="P203.N1">Harl. MS. Melana.</NOTE> , broght o&ntail; a tyme
vnto abbott Pampus <NOTE ID="P203.N2">Harl. MS. Paulo. Arund. MS. Pambo.</NOTE> iij c. libra, &amp; he
thanki&dtail; hur &thorn;erfo&rtail; &amp; bad God rewar&dtail; hur
<NOTE ID="P203.N3">MS. hym.</NOTE> ; &amp; he gaff it vnto his servan&dtail; &amp;
bad hy&mtail; go devide it emang his brethir.  And sho stude
sti&llbar; an&dtail; &thorn;oght sho sul&dtail; hafe ha&dtail;
owder grete lovyng, or grete blissyng, for &thorn;is gifte; &amp;
whe&ntail; sho har&dtail; he wol&dtail; say no mo&rtail;, sho
sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;: "Sur, I latt &thorn;e witt &thorn;er is in
&thorn;att pokett iij c. libra."  &amp; yit he luki&dtail; not
v&ptail;; &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; he said: "Doghter, &thorn;ou sulde say
&thorn;is easyelie whe&ntail; &thorn;ou hase gyffe&ntail; &thorn;ine
almos <NOTE ID="P203.N4">Latin MSS. "Si inde, o filia, hoc offerens, competenter hoc diceres."</NOTE> .  And &thorn;erfo&rtail; be sti&llbar;
&amp; luke after no lawde of ma&ntail;, bod of Hy&mtail; &thorn;at
&thorn;ou giffes it fo&rtail;; ffor He &thorn;at made a&llbar;
&thorn;ing of noght, He ca&ntail; rewar&dtail; &thorn;e whe&ntail; att
Hy&mtail; plesis; &amp; &thorn;erfo&rtail; luke after no no&thorn;er
than&ktee; nor rewar&dtail; bod of Hy&mtail;."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Elemosina data amore alicuius sancti ipsi datur, et

in presenti aliquando remuneratur.  Infra de

peregrino.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> 
<CORR SIC="CCCXVI">CCXCVI</CORR>.   
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Elemosina eciam non ex deuocione data
valet.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iohannes Elemosinarius tellis how &thorn;er was a riche
tol-gadurer &thorn;at hyght Peirs, &amp; he luffi&dtail; no pure
me&ntail; nor wol&dtail; giff &thorn;aim none almos; &amp; whe&ntail;
&thorn;ai come to his howse he wol&dtail; shute &thorn;aim oute, &amp;
giff &thorn;aim noght.  So o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;er was a grete
meneya of pure me&ntail; samen, &amp; &thorn;ai made grete complaynt
emang &thorn;aim how &thorn;ai cuthe gett none almos of &thorn;is
riche ma&ntail;, &thorn;is Peirs Toller.  So emang &thorn;aim a&llbar;
ane starte v&ptail; &amp; say&dtail;; "I dar lay with you a&llbar; a
grete wageour att I sa&llbar; &thorn;is day or evy&ntail; gett almos
o&ntail; hy&mtail;."  &amp; &thorn;ai lai&dtail; a wageour agayns
hy&mtail;.  So &thorn;is pure ma&ntail; went vnto










<PB N="204">

his howse &amp; stude at &thorn;e dure, &amp; aski&dtail; almos.  So
&thorn;is Peirs bad hy&mtail; pak&ktee;, &amp; said he sulde hafe
none; and euer he crie&dtail; for almos &amp; wol&dtail; not sease.
So &thorn;is Peirs wex wrothe with hy&mtail;, an&dtail; soght a stone
to caste at hy&mtail;, &amp; he cuthe fyn&dtail; none.  So &thorn;er
happen&dtail; a servan&dtail; of his aw&ntail; to co&mtail; in at
&thorn;e dure in the mene-while with a baskett fu&llbar; of ry lovis,
and in a grete tene he tuke ane of &thorn;ies rye lovis &amp; slang it
att &thorn;is pure ma&ntail;, and gaff hy&mtail; a grete strake
&thorn;erwith; &amp; &thorn;e pure ma&ntail; was fay&ntail; of
&thorn;is lafe &amp; tuke itt &amp; went vnto his felous &amp;
tol&dtail; &thorn;aim how he ha&dtail; it at &thorn;e han&dtail; of
&thorn;is Peirs Toller.  And with[in] ij dayes after &thorn;is
ma&ntail; fe&llbar; seke, lyke to dye.  And he was taky&ntail; in a
vysyo&ntail; &amp; hy&mtail; &thorn;oght at he was broght befor a
iuge, &amp; hy&mtail; &thorn;oght &thorn;er was fowle blakk me&ntail;
&thorn;att putt a&llbar; his i&llbar; dedis in a wey-skale.  And
o&ntail; &thorn;e toder han&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;oght &thorn;er was
fay&rtail; me&ntail;, bod &thorn;ai wer passan&dtail; hevy, &amp;
sai&dtail; &thorn;ai had no gude dede of his to putt in &thorn;e toder
wey-skale agayns his i&llbar; dedis, bod alonelie a rye lofe &thorn;at
he had giffy&ntail; Go&dtail; halfe agay&ntail; his wy&llbar;.  And
&thorn;ai putt it in &thorn;e toder wey-skale, &amp; yitt it was
&thorn;e lighter be a grete dele, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ies me&ntail;
ba&dtail; hy&mtail; eke more weght to putt in &thorn;at wey-skale
agayns his evu&llbar; dedis, or els &thorn;ies blak me&ntail; wulde
take hy&mtail;.  And with &thorn;at he waken&dtail; &amp; was
delyver&dtail;, &amp; sent after &thorn;e preste &amp; tolde hy&mtail;
a&llbar; &thorn;e cace, &amp; sai&dtail; in &thorn;is maner of wyse;
"Se&ntail; a rye lafe &thorn;at I keste in ane anger fro me
profetti&dtail; me so meku&llbar;, &thorn;a&ntail; I wote we&llbar;
&thorn;at &amp; I giff a&llbar; my gudis for Goddis sake, att
&thorn;at wi&llbar; gretelie profett me."  And so he di&dtail;
afterwar&dtail; &amp; become a gude ma&ntail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Elemosina occulte debet dari.  Supra de amicicia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Elemosinam impedit avaricia.  Supra de auaricia.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXCVII.  <LB> <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Elemosinam deus aliquando
sibi datam ostendit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iohannes Elemosinarius tellis how o&ntail; a day afterwar&dtail;,
whe&ntail; &thorn;is same Peirs was araye&dtail; in &thorn;e beste
clothyng at he ha&dtail;, a pure shipma&ntail; at was nere-han&dtail;
naki&dtail; come vnto hy&mtail; &amp; aski&dtail; hy&mtail; almos, &amp; he
gaff hy&mtail; his vppermeste garmen&ttee;.  And whe&ntail; he had it,

<PB N="205">

onone he sol&dtail; itt.  And whe&ntail; Peirs had knowlege
&thorn;erof, he was somwhat trubbli&dtail; in his myn&dtail; &amp;
sai&dtail;; "I was nott worthi at &thorn;is pure ma&ntail; sulde were
my clothe, nor hafe me in remembrance."  And o&ntail; &thorn;e nyght
after, whe&ntail; he was o&ntail; slepe, he was war a ma&ntail;
&thorn;at was bryghter &thorn;an &thorn;e so&ntail;, &amp; hy&mtail;
thoght he sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "Peirs, whi wepis &thorn;ou?
Knowis &thorn;ou &thorn;is clothyng?"  &amp; he sai&dtail;; "Ya, sur."
And our Lor&dtail; say&dtail; agay&ntail; vnto hy&mtail;; "&thorn;at
clothyng at &thorn;ou gaff &thorn;e pure ma&ntail;, &thorn;ou gaff it
me; an&dtail; &thorn;is is it at I a&mtail; cled in."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXCVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Elemosina eciam viuis prodest quando pro eis
fit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iohannes Elemosinarius tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was
<NOTE ID="P205.N1"><HI REND="i">After</HI> was, &thorn;at, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> a ma&ntail; &thorn;at was take&ntail; with <NOTE ID="P205.N2">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, with.</NOTE> &thorn;e Persies &amp; putt in-to priso&ntail;.  So
other prisoners of his aw&ntail; contre &thorn;at was with hy&mtail;
esskapi&dtail; &amp; went home vnto his contrey, and tol&dtail; his
wyfe &thorn;at he was dea&dtail; &amp; beri&dtail;.  And his wyfe &amp; his
frendis garte iij yere to-gedur &thorn;e preste euer-ilk a day do a
colett for hy&mtail; in his mes.  And in &thorn;e iiij yere hy&mtail;
happen&dtail; esskape and co&mtail; home.  And &thorn;ai war
fay&ntail; o&ntail; hy&mtail; &amp; tol&dtail; hy&mtail; how &thorn;ai
had done for hy&mtail;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai ha&dtail; tolde
hy&mtail;, he sai&dtail; &thorn;at euer-ilk a day at &thorn;at colett
was sai&dtail; for hy&mtail;, aboute mes-tyme, &thorn;er come a fayr
ma&ntail; &amp; lowsi&dtail; hy&mtail; oute of his yrnys.  And so he
was lowse a&llbar; day afterwar&dtail; to nyght come; and &thorn;a&ntail; he
wol&dtail; lay hy&mtail; dow&ntail;, &amp; o&ntail; &thorn;e
mor&ntail; he feli&dtail; hym-selfe bo&ntail; agay&ntail; in yrnys as
he was befo&rtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCXCIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Elemosinam recipiens et non orans pro dante punitur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a pylgra&mtail;
&thorn;at tuke sekenes, an&dtail; dyed in his pylgramege.  And he
bewitt &thorn;e preste his slavy&ntail;, &amp; &thorn;e preste tuke
it, bo&dtail; he had litle charge of &thorn;e saule.  So it
happen&dtail; afterwar&dtail; at &thorn;is preste made hy&mtail; a
monke in Ceustus





<PB N="206">

ordur; and as he lay o&ntail; a nyght in his dortur, he was
ravisshi&dtail; in his spiritt, &amp; had vnto &thorn;e place of
paynys, &thorn;er he saw many sawlis grevuslie punysshi&dtail;.  And
he hi&dtail; hy&mtail; behyn&dtail; &thorn;e dure.  So he was war of
&thorn;is slavy&ntail;, &thorn;er hy&mtail; &thorn;oght, at &thorn;e
pylgram had giffe&ntail;, and &thorn;e devu&llbar; aski&dtail; who
aght it; &amp; &thorn;ai tol&dtail; hy&mtail; at it was &thorn;e
prestis at stude behyn&dtail; &thorn;e dure, &amp; at a pylgra&mtail;
had giffe&ntail; hy&mtail; itt to pray for hy&mtail;, &amp; he had
owder lite&llbar; praye&dtail; for hy&mtail; or noght.  And &thorn;e
devu&llbar; [said] <NOTE ID="P206.N1">Latin MSS. ad quod diabolus.</NOTE> ; "Latt vs rewar&dtail;
hy&mtail;"; &amp; he tuke &thorn;is slavy&ntail; &amp; putt it in
hate, bulyng, stynkan&dtail; watir, &amp; clappi&dtail; &thorn;e
preste in &thorn;e face &thorn;er-with.  And with &thorn;at he
waken&dtail; &amp; crye&dtail;; "Helpe me! helpe me! ffor I a&mtail;
so burny&dtail; &thorn;at I dye."  And &thorn;e monkis his bruther
rase vp &amp; come vnto hy&mtail;, &amp; &thorn;ai fan&dtail; a&llbar;
his face &amp; his hea&dtail; burny&dtail; a&llbar; &thorn;e
fless&hbar; nerehan&dtail; of, &amp; hy&mtail; halfe dea&dtail;; &amp;
&thorn;ai tuke hy&mtail; vp &amp; had hy&mtail; in-to &thorn;er
ffermorye, &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; he tol&dtail; &thorn;aim
&thorn;er-of.  &amp; ilk-one of &thorn;aim say&dtail; mes &thorn;at
day for &thorn;is pylgra&mtail;; &amp; onone after &thorn;is monke
amendi&dtail; &amp; was als hole as he was befo&rtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCC. 
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Elemosina propter vanam gloriam facta non prodest.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis of a visio&ntail; &thorn;at was sene in Balmarie
<NOTE ID="P206.N2">Arund. MS. Balbaria.  Harl, MS. Balwaria.</NOTE> , how &thorn;at a ryche lor&dtail;, att was
dea&dtail;, vppo&ntail; a nyght apperi&dtail; vnto his wife, and sho
aski&dtail; hy&mtail; whatt estate he stude in; &amp; he
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail; &thorn;at he was
dampny&dtail;.  And sho aski&dtail; hy&mtail; whi he sai&dtail; so,
&amp; said; "Whatt profettis you your grete almos-de&dtail;, &amp;
&thorn;e herberie at ye di&dtail;?"  And he sai&dtail; &thorn;ai
profett hy&mtail; no thyng vnto evurlastan&dtail; life, for he
say&dtail; he did &thorn;aim nott be way of charite, bod rather for
vay&ntail; glorie.  And sho aski&dtail; hy&mtail; meku&llbar;
mo&rtail;, &amp; he sai&dtail; &thorn;at he myght nott abyde &amp;
tarye with hur, for his maister &thorn;e devu&llbar; bade hy&mtail;
with-oute &thorn;e dure.  And he sai&dtail;, &amp; &thorn;e levis of
a&llbar; treis in &thorn;is werl&dtail; wer turny&dtail; into tonges,
&thorn;ai might nott a&llbar; te&llbar; his paynys.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; his maister calli&dtail; hy&mtail;; and whe&ntail; he
wente a&llbar; &thorn;e caste&llbar; shuke with.





<PB N="207">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Elemosina que fit de re que, et-si in se non fuit
rapta, tamen si de re <NOTE ID="P207.N1">MS. se.</NOTE> rapta ortum habuerit, non
valet.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a riche ma&ntail;, and
vndernethe &thorn;e colour of almos-dede, he made pure me&ntail; a
feste.  So emang &thorn;aim &thorn;er was one and he wol&dtail; not
ete, nor a noder &thorn;at satt by hy&mtail; &thorn;at wol&dtail; hafe
ety&ntail;, he wol&dtail; not latt hy&mtail;, bod euer as he putt
meatt vnto his mowt&hbar;, he tuke it fro hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;ai
att wer aboute hy&mtail; aski&dtail; hy&mtail; whi he wol&dtail; nott
suffre &thorn;e ma&ntail; to eatt; and he ansswer&dtail; &amp;
sai&dtail;; "I wi&llbar; nott att he sy&ntail;; ffor &thorn;is almos is
done of stoltherie."  And &thorn;ai sai&dtail; he leyi&dtail;, ffor he
&thorn;at di&dtail; &thorn;e almos was a gude ma&ntail;.  And he
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "Nay, I lee nott; ffor
&thorn;is calfe &thorn;at is devidi&dtail; he&rtail; in almos emang
pure me&ntail;, in &thorn;e v generacio&ntail; fro hyne was of a cow
&thorn;at he had stolle&ntail;."  And &thorn;ai &thorn;at wer aboute
had grete merva&llbar; here-off.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Elemosine vsurariorum eciam non sunt grate deo.

Infra de vsuris.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Elemosina in centuplum redditur
deo.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iacobus de Vetriaco tellis how at &thorn;er was a bisshop&ptail;
&thorn;at made a sermo&ntail;, &amp; in his sermo&ntail; he sai&dtail;
at &thorn;ai &thorn;at delte &thorn;er gudis to pure men sul&dtail;
hafe &thorn;erfo&rtail; a hondrethfolde rewar&dtail;.  And &thorn;er
was a riche ma&ntail; at har&dtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; a&llbar; &thorn;e
gudis att he had, he putt &thorn;aim vnto &thorn;e bisshop&ptail;,
&amp; he delte &thorn;aim vnto pure me&ntail; for Goddis sake.  So
hy&mtail; happen&dtail; to dy, &amp; his childre tuke a sute
agay&ntail; &thorn;is bissho&ptail; &amp; aski&dtail; &thorn;er fadur
gudis agay&ntail;.  And he was not in power to giff &thorn;aim
agay&ntail;.  Not-with-stondyng he was a holie ma&ntail;, &amp; had a
commandment be revelacio&ntail;, and he and &thorn;ai to-gedur
sul&dtail; go vnto &thorn;er fader grafe; &amp; so &thorn;ai
di&dtail;, &amp; tuke hy&mtail; vp&ptail;.  &amp; &thorn;ai fan&dtail;
in his han&dtail; a quytans, wrete&ntail; &amp; seli&dtail; with his
aw&ntail; seale, &thorn;at he not alonelie had reseyvi&dtail;
agay&ntail; a&llbar; &thorn;e gudis at he




<PB N="208">

had delyver&dtail; &thorn;e bisshop&ptail;, bod also &thorn;att he had
reseyvi&dtail; a hondret&hbar; tymys mo&rtail;.  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;is riche mans childer saw &thorn;is, &thorn;ai lete hy&mtail;
alone &amp; sewi&dtail; hy&mtail; no more.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Elemosina eciam in presenti redditur in centuplum.

Infra de Hospitalit[at]e.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Elemosinam recipientes ab vsurarijs
puniuntur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Legenda Sancti Fursij,' whe&ntail; &thorn;e sawle of
hy&mtail; was passid oute of his bodye, ffendis accusi&dtail;
hy&mtail; befo&rtail; almighti Go&dtail;, and &thorn;ai cuthe not
fyn&dtail; nothyng to accuse hy&mtail; off, bod at he had o&ntail; a
tyme take&ntail; a cape of ane vusurar, &amp; &thorn;is sentans
&thorn;ai fan&dtail; agay&ntail; hy&mtail;.  And gude angels stude
o&ntail; &thorn;e toder syde &amp; pleyi&dtail; agayns &thorn;aim, and
almighti [God] gaff eniugement &thorn;at his sawle sulde go
agay&ntail; vnto his body &amp; do penans &thorn;erfor.  So with
&thorn;is &thorn;er was a fen&dtail; wrothe, &amp; in a tene he tuke
&thorn;is vsurar saule &amp; keste in his face.  And so his saule come
vnto his bodye; and euer after &thorn;er was in his saule <NOTE ID="P208.N1">Saule, <HI REND="i">for</HI> face, Lat. MSS. apparuit in facie.</NOTE> a spott as it war byrny&dtail; with &thorn;is vsurar
saule.  Yit not-with-stondyng &thorn;is holie ma&ntail; had nott
&thorn;is cape of &thorn;is vsurar <NOTE ID="P208.N2">MS. vsusar.</NOTE> bod as
almos-dede.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Elemosinarius per preces pauperum liberatur a

dampnacione.  Ex miraculis Beate Virginis vt infra

Laurencij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Eleuatur cor hominis quando honoratur.  Supra de

Augurio.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Episcopus a demone citatur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Libro de Dono Timoris,' how o&ntail; a tyme a
bisshop&ptail; happen&dtail; to fa&llbar; seke, an&dtail; a fen&dtail;
come &amp; somon&dtail; hy&mtail; to co&mtail; afo&rtail;





<PB N="209">

&thorn;e pope, &amp; for to giff rekynyng of his adminystracio&ntail;.
So vppo&ntail; &thorn;e day at was assigne&dtail; hy&mtail;, hy&mtail;
thoght &thorn;at he was drawe&ntail; vnto iugement befo&rtail;
&thorn;e pope, and at &thorn;e devu&llbar; sul&dtail; article agayns
hy&mtail; for to giff a rekenyng.  And he cuthe not giff a due
rekynyng; so hy&mtail; thoght hy&mtail; was assigny&dtail; a day to
take his fu&llbar; sentance o&ntail;, and he&rtail;-for he wex passyng
hevy, and calli&dtail; a&llbar; his howshol&dtail; afor&ntail;
hy&mtail;, &amp; tol&dtail; &thorn;aim how it was.  So a noder day
hy&mtail; thoght at a fen&dtail; come &amp; constreyny&dtail;
hy&mtail; to co&mtail; to his rakenyng befo&rtail; &thorn;e hye iuge
of hevy&ntail;, and he vgge&dtail; so with &thorn;e fen&dtail;
&thorn;at he crye&dtail; hugelie, &amp; sai&dtail; he wol&dtail; nott
go with hy&mtail;; &amp; he cleki&dtail; a pyler in his armys to
hol&dtail; hy&mtail; by &thorn;at he sul&dtail; nott take hy&mtail;,
and with &thorn;at his hea&dtail; was plukki&dtail; off &amp; he
dye&dtail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Episcopus de religione sumptus, cibaria delicata

vitare debet.  Infra de Gula.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Episcopus a demone temptatur. de Andrea supra.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Episcopus bonus deuote moritur.  Supra de

Communione.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Episcopus a sanctis accusatur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Libro de Dono Timoris,' how &thorn;er was in &thorn;e
cetie of Tura&ntail; a gude ma&ntail;; and he vsi&dtail; of
costo&mtail; to co&mtail; o&ntail; &thorn;e night to matyns vnto
&thorn;e cathedra&llbar;-kurk &thorn;er.  So o&ntail; a tyme hy&mtail;
happen&dtail; co&mtail; tymelie, &amp; he fan&dtail; &thorn;e yatis
opy&ntail;, &amp; he saw a grete light in &thorn;e kur&ktee;, &amp; a
iuge syttan&dtail; in a trone.  And hy&mtail; &thorn;oght &thorn;er
come Saynt Marty&ntail; &amp; many o&thorn;er Saynttis with hy&mtail;,
and accusi&dtail; &thorn;e archbisshop&ptail; of &thorn;e same
kur&ktee;, &amp; he was city&dtail; &amp; come.  And he was sett in a
chayr in his pontifica&llbar; aray, and he was grevuslie accusi&dtail;
and wol&dtail; giff none ansswer, to so muche &thorn;e iuge wex
wrot&hbar; with hy&mtail;, &amp; smate &thorn;e chayre &amp; hy&mtail;
bothe ow&rtail; with his fute.  &amp; with &thorn;at &thorn;e
visio&ntail; vanysshi&dtail; away, &amp; &thorn;is gude ma&ntail; went
vnto &thorn;e bisshoppis place, &amp; spirri&dtail; how &thorn;e
bissho&ptail; di&dtail;; &amp; his meneya went in-to his chawmer &amp;
luki&dtail;, and fan&dtail; hy&mtail; stark dea&dtail; in his
be&dtail; sodanly.

<PB N="210">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Episcopalis status periculosus est.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;er was a mon&ktee; of
Clariua&llbar; &thorn;at was chosy&ntail; to be a bisshop&ptail;; and
he forsoke to take it &amp; wol&dtail; not agre &thorn;erto, nowder be
commandment of his abbott nor yitt of &thorn;e archbisshop&ptail;.  So
with-in a while after hy&mtail; happen&dtail; to dy, and o&ntail;
&thorn;e night after he apperi&dtail; to a ma&ntail; &thorn;at he
luffi&dtail;, a bruther of his, and he aski&dtail; hy&mtail; of
&thorn;is inobediens, whether it noye&dtail; hy&mtail; or nay.  And he
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail; nay, it noye&dtail; him
not; "ffor," he sai&dtail;, " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">si episcopatum
suscepissem, eternaliter dampnatus essem.</FOREIGN> And I ha&dtail;
take&ntail; &thorn;e bisshopprike, I had bene dampny&dtail; for evur."
And he eki&dtail; to &amp; sayd a fu&llbar; ferdfu&llbar; wur&dtail;,
&amp; &thorn;at was &thorn;is, &thorn;at &thorn;e estate of &thorn;e
kur&ktee; sulde happe&ntail; so, at it sul&dtail; not be wurthi to be
gouerny&dtail; bod with reprevable bisshoppis.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Episcopus habens iusticiam secularem diligenter

debet auertere quid balliuis suis precipiat.  Infra

de iudice.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Episcopus debet esse sobrius.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Petrus Damyanus tellis how &thorn;er was so&mtail; tyme a
bisshop&ptail;, &amp; he garte ordan&dtail; for hy&mtail; selfe a
lawmpro&ntail;; and whe&ntail; he had sai&dtail; mes, he garte giff
&thorn;is lampro&ntail; vnto a pure ma&ntail; for Goddis sake.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Evagacio cordis.  Euagatur cor frequenter in

oracione.  Supra Barnardi.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Eukaristia sumpta ab infideli a combustione eum
protexit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;er was a childe &thorn;att was
a Iew so&ntail;; and he was fayr and genty&llbar;, so &thorn;at
criste&ntail; me&ntail; childre luffid hy&mtail;

<PB N="211">

passandlie wele, vnto so muche &thorn;at vppo&ntail; a tyme &thorn;ai
desyrid hy&mtail; to go into a kur&ktee; of our Ladye with
&thorn;aim, an&dtail; &thorn;er for to take &thorn;e sacrament as
&thorn;ai di&dtail;; and he did so.  And onone as he come home he
tolde his fadur, &amp; he was hetand ane ove&ntail;, and he was so
wroth &thorn;er-wit&hbar; &thorn;at he tuke &thorn;is chylde, his
aw&ntail; so&ntail;, &amp; keste hy&mtail; in &thorn;e hote
ovy&ntail;.  And &thorn;e childes moder saw how he had putt hy&mtail;
in &thorn;e ovy&ntail;, &amp; how &thorn;e low come oute at &thorn;e
mout&hbar; &thorn;er-of; &amp; sho wex evy&ntail; wude and ra&ntail;
oute att &thorn;e dure an&dtail; cryed as sho war wude.  And
criste&ntail; me&ntail; had grete merva&llbar; &amp; ra&ntail; into
&thorn;e Iewis howse, and with-drew &thorn;e fyre oute of &thorn;e
ove&ntail; mouthe, and fand &thorn;e chil&dtail; in &thorn;e
ovy&ntail;, syttan&dtail; opo&ntail; &thorn;e hate colis, right as had
sytty&ntail; opo&ntail; fayr flowris; and hy&mtail; ayli&dtail; no rew
sore.  And &thorn;ai tuke hy&mtail; furt&hbar;, &amp; he tol&dtail;
&thorn;aim a&llbar; &thorn;e cace.  And onone &thorn;ai tuke &thorn;is
Iew, his fadur, &amp; threste hy&mtail; in-to &thorn;e ove&ntail;; and
onone &thorn;e fire had made a nen&dtail; o&ntail; hy&mtail;, so
&thorn;at &thorn;ai cuthe nowder fynd of hy&mtail; bone nor lit&hbar;.
And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e childe tol&dtail; &thorn;aim how
&thorn;at womma&ntail; <NOTE ID="P211.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, &thorn;at womman.</NOTE> &thorn;at was in
&thorn;e kur&ktee; &thorn;er he had ety&ntail; brea&dtail; with his
felous, syttan&dtail; in a chayr, &thorn;at had a little chylde
syttand o&ntail; hur kne wappi&dtail; in a clothe, cover&dtail;
hy&mtail; with hur manty&llbar; &thorn;at &thorn;e fyre shul&dtail;
nott bur&ntail; hy&mtail;.  And so &thorn;is childe and his moder, and
many other Iewis, wer cristend enspecia&llbar; for &thorn;is fayr
meracle of &thorn;e sacrament.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Eukaristia propter fidei roboracionem versa est in
carnem.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Gregur tellis how &thorn;er was a womma&ntail; at Rome, and
sho had grete devocio&ntail; to make offran&dtail; vnto &thorn;e pope,
and in esspecia&llbar; opo&ntail; &thorn;e Sononday.  So opo&ntail; a
day sho come with other to be howsyl&dtail; of &thorn;e popis
han&dtail;, and whe&ntail; &thorn;e pope sulde howse&llbar; hur, &amp;
sai&dtail;; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Corpus Domini nostri, Iesu Cristi, et
c&curl;,</FOREIGN>" sho smyli&dtail;; &amp; he pursayvid itt, and
with-drew &thorn;e sacrament fro hur, &amp; lai&dtail; it o&ntail;
&thorn;e altar fro &thorn;e toder.  And whe&ntail; he had done, he
calli&dtail; &thorn;is womma&ntail; o&ntail; syde, and aski&dtail; hur
whatt &thorn;ing was in hur harte &thorn;at



<PB N="212">

sho smyli&dtail; whe[n] he sulde hafe howsel&dtail; hur.  And sho
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Sur, I vmthoght me
&thorn;at &thorn;at porcio&ntail; of brea&dtail; was of &thorn;e same
offrand &thorn;at I made with myne aw&ntail; handis; and whe&ntail; I
har&dtail; you ca&llbar; itt a body, &thorn;a&ntail; I smyli&dtail;."
And evy&ntail; furt&hbar;-with &thorn;is holie ma&ntail; hereof made a
sermo&ntail; vnto &thorn;e peple, &amp; he &amp; &thorn;ai fe&llbar;
in &thorn;er prayers vnto almyghti Go&dtail;, &amp; evy&ntail;
opynlie, at &thorn;ai a&llbar; saw, &thorn;is porcio&ntail;
turny&dtail; in-to a little fynger a&llbar; bludy.  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;is womma&ntail; &amp; a&llbar; &thorn;e peple saw &thorn;is,
&thorn;ai war passan&dtail; fay&ntail; <NOTE ID="P212.N1">MS. fayr.</NOTE> , &amp;
meku&llbar; more stirri&dtail; into deuocio&ntail; &amp; confermyng of
&thorn;e faithe &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai wer afor.  et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Eukaristia liberat a purgatorio.  Infra de

proprietario.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Eukaristia sustentatur aliquis sine aliquo cibo.

Supra de cibo.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Eukaristia vbique est adoranda.  Infra de Milite.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCX. 
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Eukaristie loco nulla alia hostia administrari
debet.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how &thorn;at whe&ntail; Hugo de Sancto Victore, &thorn;at
was ane excellent doctur and a devoute in religio&ntail;, agay&ntail;
he sulde dye labur&dtail; gretelie in sekenes &amp; no meate mott
hol&dtail;, he praye&dtail; his brethir with a grete instans for to
giff hy&mtail; &thorn;e sacrament.  And his brethir &thorn;oght
&thorn;ai wul&dtail; somwhat slake his truble, and &thorn;ai tuke a
symple oste &amp; broght hy&mtail; in-stea&dtail; of &thorn;e
sacrament.  And he conseyvi&dtail; in his spiritt at &thorn;ai
di&dtail; wrong, &amp; say&dtail;; "God hafe mercie of you, brether,
whi wul&dtail; ye hafe disseyvi&dtail; me?  For &thorn;is is not my
Lor&dtail; at ye hafe broght."  And &thorn;ai had grete merve&llbar;
here-of, and went and fechi&dtail; &thorn;e sacrament.  And whe&ntail;
he saw &thorn;at he myght not resayfe it, he hel&dtail; vp&ptail; his
handis vnto hevy&ntail; and praye&dtail; o&ntail; &thorn;is maner of
wyse; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ascendat filius ad patrem et</FOREIGN>



<PB N="213">


<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">spiritum sanctum qui me fecit <NOTE ID="P213.N1">Latin MSS. "Ascendat filius ad patrem et spiritum sanctum, ad deum qui fecit illum."</NOTE> .</FOREIGN>" And in &thorn;ies wurdis saying he
swelte; and &thorn;e sacramente evy&ntail; &thorn;er emang &thorn;aim
vanysshi&dtail; away.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Eukaristie loco falsus denarius malo rustico

administratur.  Infra de oblacione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Eukaristie sumpcio eciam obstinatum de

obstinacione et dolentem reuocat ad penitenciam.

Infra de obstinacione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Eukaristia a religioso proprietario non potest sumi.

Infra de proprietate.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Eustacij Placidi.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in &thorn;e Legen&dtail; of Saynt Eustace &thorn;at
befo&rtail; was calli&dtail; Placidus, how o&ntail; a tyme as he went
o&ntail; huntyng att &thorn;e harte, emang a&llbar; o&thorn;er he
fan&dtail; a fayre harte, and hy&mtail; he pursewi&dtail; &amp;
folow&dtail;.  So at &thorn;e laste &thorn;is harte turny&dtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; luki&dtail; o&ntail; hy&mtail;, and he behel&dtail;
&thorn;is harte, and he saw betwix his hornys a cros and &thorn;e
ymage of our Lor&dtail; Iesu, &thorn;at spakk vnto hy&mtail; be
&thorn;e mouthe of &thorn;is harte, &amp; tolde hy&mtail; &amp; taght
hy&mtail; &thorn;e faythe of &thorn;e kur&ktee;, &amp; bad hy&mtail;
teche &thorn;e same vnto his wyfe &amp; his childer; and so he did,
&amp; &thorn;ai trowi&dtail; &thorn;er-in.  And &thorn;ai war
cristen&dtail; at Rome; and Placidus was calli&dtail; Eustachius, and
his wife was calli&dtail; Theospita, and his sons Agapitus and
Theospitus.  And opo&ntail; &thorn;e mor&ntail; our Lor&dtail;
aperi&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; in &thorn;e same place &amp; in &thorn;e
same figur, and tolde hy&mtail; &thorn;at he sulde suffer meku&llbar;
&thorn;ing bod he sulde giff hy&mtail; &thorn;e vertue of paciens.  So
with-in a little while after, dea&dtail; come and tuke a&llbar; his
hows-meneya, and thevis come and robbi&dtail; hy&mtail; of a&llbar;
his gudis, so &thorn;at hy&mtail; was lefte right noght, bod was
almoste naki&dtail;.  So o&ntail; a nyght he fle&dtail; away with his
wife &amp; his childer, and went our att a ferie, and had nothyng to
pay for his ferilay,




<PB N="214">

[&] &thorn;e maister of &thorn;e ship&ptail; tuke his wyfe fro&mtail;
hy&mtail; for his ferilay, mawgre his tethe, becauce sho was a fayr
womma&ntail;.  And he made grete sorow &amp; went o&ntail; his wayis
with his childer.  So hy&mtail; happen&dtail; to co&mtail; vnto a
watur, and itt was so grete he myght nott bere &thorn;aim ouer bothe
att onys.  So he tuke &thorn;at one o&ntail; hys bak &amp; bare it
our, &amp; lefte &thorn;at other behyn&dtail;; and whe&ntail; he come
agay&ntail; for &thorn;e toder, &amp; was in &thorn;e myddeste of
&thorn;e watir, &thorn;er co&mtail;e a lyo&ntail; o&ntail; &thorn;e
tone syde &amp; tuke &thorn;at one of his barnys, and a wulfe o&ntail;
&thorn;e toder syde &amp; tuke &thorn;at o&thorn;er.  And he,
whe&ntail; he was in &thorn;e myddeste of &thorn;e watir, saw
&thorn;is, and morny&dtail; &amp; made myki&llbar; sorow, &amp;
luhi&dtail; &thorn;e hare of his hea&dtail;, and turny&dtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; went o&ntail; his wayis mornan&dtail;.
Not-with-stondyng, at he wyste not, hurde-me&ntail; &amp;
plew-me&ntail; rescowi&dtail; his childer fro &thorn;is lyo&ntail;
&amp; &thorn;is wulfe, &amp; &thorn;ai war bothe nurisschi&dtail;
&amp; broght vp in &thorn;e next tow&ntail;.  So Eustace wiste nevur
what he moght do, &amp; he become a mans hird-ma&ntail;, &amp;
kepi&dtail; his cate&llbar; xv yere; and almighti God kepi&dtail; his
wyfe.  Tha&ntail; &thorn;e Emperour of Rome happend to be
oppressi&dtail; with enmys, and he vmthoght hy&mtail; of &thorn;e
nobylnes of &thorn;is Eustas, and he sent ij knyghtis to seke
hy&mtail; in euere place; so &thorn;ai happend to co&mtail; by
hy&mtail; &thorn;urg&hbar; &thorn;e fel&dtail; &thorn;er he
walki&dtail;, and &thorn;ai aski&dtail; hy&mtail; if he war oght wer
of a pylgra&mtail; at hight Placidus, &amp; his ij sonys &amp; his
wife: and he sai&dtail; he saw &thorn;aim noght.  Neuer-&thorn;e-les
he knew &thorn;aim, and he had &thorn;aim home vnto his maister howse;
and as he servi&dtail; &thorn;aim, be dyvers tokens &thorn;ai
ken&dtail; hy&mtail; wele, &amp; &thorn;ai tuke knowlege vnto
hy&mtail; and kissi&dtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; spirri&dtail; hy&mtail; of
his wyfe &amp; his childer; and he tol&dtail; &thorn;aim at his wife
was take&ntail; fro&mtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; how his childer war
dea&dtail;.  So &thorn;ai broght hy&mtail; vnto &thorn;e Emperour, and
he resayvi&dtail; hy&mtail; with meku&llbar; ioy and wurshu&ptail;,
made hy&mtail; maister of &thorn;e knyghtis as he was befor.  And he
fan&dtail; few knyghtis &thorn;at war able vnto &thorn;e were, and he
garte gadur to-gedur yong me&ntail; &thorn;at wer able vnto chyvalrie,
emang &thorn;e whilk was his ij sons broght; and &thorn;ai
plesi&dtail; hy&mtail; gretelie.  So &thorn;urg&hbar; &thorn;e grace
of God &thorn;aim happen&dtail; to hafe &thorn;e victorie of &thorn;er
enmys.  And as God wol&dtail;, &thorn;is ij yong me&ntail; war att
hoste in &thorn;er moder howse, and be knowlege &thorn;at ather of
&thorn;aim tol&dtail; other, how &thorn;ai war taky&ntail; fro wylde
bestis, athir of &thorn;aim knew other we&llbar; enogh; and &thorn;er
moder &thorn;oght of &thorn;is in hur harte, bott

<PB N="215">

sho knew nothyng &thorn;eroff.  So with-in a little while, whe&ntail;
sho saw &thorn;is maister of &thorn;e knyghtis, sho knew hy&mtail;
we&llbar; enog&hbar; &amp; he hur; and sho aski&dtail; hy&mtail; of
&thorn;er childer, &amp; he tol&dtail; hur how &thorn;ai war
devowri&dtail; with wylde bestis.  And &thorn;a&ntail; sho tol&dtail;
hy&mtail; how &thorn;ies ij yong me&ntail; had tol&dtail; hur, and he
was passan&dtail; fay&ntail; &amp; sent for &thorn;aim &amp; knew
&thorn;aim wele enog&hbar;.  And &thorn;ai wer a&llbar; passan&dtail;
fay&ntail; to-gedur, an&dtail; thanki&dtail; Go&dtail;.  And
afterwar&dtail; &thorn;ai wer a&llbar; martyr&dtail; samen for Goddis
sake.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Exactor talliarum grauiter punitur.  Infra de gula.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXII.  
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Excommunicacio.  Excommunicatus 
<NOTE ID="P215.N1">MS. Excomminicatus.</NOTE>  ab omnibus debet evitari.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Jacobus de Vetriaco tellis how som tyme in &thorn;e bisshopprik of
Lincol&ntail; &thorn;er was a smyt&hbar;, and he dispysy&dtail;
&thorn;e sentens of &thorn;e kur&ktee;; and &thorn;ai cursi&dtail;
hy&mtail;.  So o&ntail; a day he satt at meatt with o&thorn;er
fol&ktee;, and &thorn;er come in-to &thorn;e howse vnto &thorn;aim a
swyne of Saynt Antons.  And he tuke bread &amp; keste vnto it, &amp;
sai&dtail;; "Now sa&llbar; itt appere whe&thorn;er &thorn;is
Anto&ntail; swyne wi&llbar; eatt of my brea&dtail; &thorn;at a&mtail;
cursy&dtail;, or nay."  And &thorn;e swyne smelli&dtail; &thorn;e
brea&dtail; &amp; wolde not eate it.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he bad one
of his felous take &thorn;e same brea&dtail; &amp; giff it; and so he
di&dtail;, &amp; yitt it wol&dtail; not tuche it.  And &thorn;e toder
&thorn;at satt aboute gaff it of &thorn;er brea&dtail;, an&dtail;
onone &thorn;e swyne eate itt.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Excommunicatus 
<NOTE ID="P215.N2">MS. Excomminicatus.</NOTE>  quantecumque auctoritatis

ecclesiam intrare non debet.  Supra de adulterio.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Excommunicacio lata in viuum eciam post mortem
durat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in &thorn;e 'Legen&dtail; of Saynt Benedicte' how o&ntail;
a tyme &thorn;er was ij wurthie nonnys in a monasterie, and oft
sithes, with &thorn;er vnthrifti





<PB N="216">

language, hy&mtail; at ha&dtail; rewle of &thorn;aim &thorn;ai
provoke&dtail; &amp; stirri&dtail; to be angrie and wrothe.  And
&thorn;is holie ma&ntail; purseyvy&dtail; &thorn;is, &amp; gaff
&thorn;aim a charge &amp; sai&dtail;; "Amen&dtail;, &amp; correcte
your tongis, or els here I curse you."  And &thorn;ai wol&dtail; not
amen&dtail; &thorn;aim; &amp; with-in a little while after &thorn;ai
dye&dtail;, &amp; was beri&dtail; in &thorn;e kur&ktee;.  And
&thorn;er was ane vsage, &thorn;at euere day afo&rtail; mes, a
deke&ntail; stude v&ptail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "He &thorn;at is curste,
go his ways!"  So &thorn;er was a noryss of &thorn;airs &thorn;at
euer-ilk day offer&dtail; for &thorn;aim, &amp; sho saw &thorn;aim
rise oute of &thorn;er gravis &amp; go oute of &thorn;e kur&ktee;.
And sho went &amp; tol&dtail; Saynt Benett; he tuke ane offran&dtail;
hy&mtail; selfe and gaff vnto &thorn;er nuress; "Goo &amp; offyr for
&thorn;aim &thorn;is offran&dtail;, and fro hyne furt&hbar; &thorn;ai
sa&llbar; not be cursi&dtail;."  And so sho di&dtail;; and whe&ntail;
&thorn;e deky&ntail; crye&dtail; as he was wunte to done, &thorn;ai
war neuer after sene go furt&hbar; of &thorn;e kur&ktee;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Excommunicacio non debet cito proferri.  Supra de

absolucione.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXIV. 
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Executoris necligencia quandoque testatorem
retinet in purgatorio.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Turpinus the Archebisshop&ptail; tellis how so&mtail; tyme in
&thorn;e felowship&ptail; of greatt Charles, &thorn;er was a knyght
&thorn;at happen&dtail; seke, &amp; he made his testament an&dtail;
commawndi&dtail; a cussy&ntail; of his to take his hors, and he
dye&dtail;, and se&llbar; itt, &amp; giff the pryce &thorn;er-off vnto
pure me&ntail; &amp; clerkis, to pray for hy&mtail;.  And whe&ntail;
he was dea&dtail; he selli&dtail; a noder hors &amp; spendi&dtail;
&thorn;e price &thorn;er-of for hy&mtail; in meate &amp; dryn&ktee;.
And with-in xxx<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> dayes after, &thorn;is dead ma&ntail; apperi&dtail;
vnto hy&mtail; and say&dtail;; "Be-cauce I gaff my gudis for the to
deale for my sawle, &amp; &thorn;ou did not as I bad &thorn;e,
&thorn;ou sa&llbar; vnderstan&dtail; &thorn;at a&llbar; my synnys er
forgiffe&ntail; me; bod becauce &thorn;ou hase with-holde&ntail; myne
almos &thorn;is xxx<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> dayes, &amp; latty&ntail; me be in purgatorie,
&thorn;erfo&rtail; I latt &thorn;e wett, &thorn;at to-mor&ntail;
sa&llbar; I be take&ntail; into paradice, &amp; &thorn;ou sal be putt
in he&llbar;."  And &thorn;e same day as he rade with his felows,
&amp; tol&dtail; &thorn;aim a&llbar; &thorn;is cace, sodanly &thorn;er
bega&ntail; a cry in &thorn;e ayre, as it

<PB N="217">

had bene of lyons, wulvis &amp; beris; and sodanlie he was take&ntail;
vp&ptail; with fendis, &amp; putt &thorn;er he was ordan&dtail; to be.
And his felows went &amp; soght hy&mtail;; and his body was fo&ntail;
dea&dtail; oppo&ntail; a hy hi&llbar; &amp; revy&ntail; in sonder,
iiij day iorney fro&mtail; &thorn;e place &thorn;er he was
take&ntail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT"> Exemplum bonum plus monet quam predicacio
subtilis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Bede tellis in 'Gestis Anglorum' how, whe&ntail;
Englon&dtail; was oute of &thorn;e belefe, &thorn;e pope sente in-to
it to preche a bissho&ptail; &thorn;at was a passyng sute&llbar;
cler&ktee;, &amp; a we&llbar;-letter&dtail;; and he vsi&dtail; so
meku&llbar; soteltie &amp; strange saying in his sermons, &thorn;at
his prechyng owder litle profetti&dtail; or noght.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;er was sent a noder &thorn;at was les of
connyng of literatur &thorn;a&ntail; he was, &amp; he vsi&dtail; talis
&amp; gude exsample in his sermo&ntail;; and he with <NOTE ID="P217.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, with.</NOTE> -in a while <NOTE ID="P217.N2">MS. <HI REND="i">has</HI>, he, <HI REND="i">again here</HI>.</NOTE> conuerty&dtail;
<NOTE ID="P217.N3">MS. coneruertyd.</NOTE> nere-hand a&llbar; Englon&dtail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Exemplo vnius debet alius edoceri.  Infra de Iudice.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Exemplum bonum aliquando conuertit peccatorem.

Supra de Abbate.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Exemplum malum multis nocet.  Infra de monacho.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Exemplum a meliori est sumendum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' how o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;er was two,
&thorn;at was to say, a ma&ntail;, &amp; a womma&ntail; his wyfe.  And
&thorn;e ma&ntail; was a holie ma&ntail;, bod he was infortunatt in
werdlie <NOTE ID="P217.N4">MS. werlrdlie.</NOTE> thyngis, to so meku&llbar; &thorn;at
o&ntail; &thorn;e day at he was beri&dtail; o&ntail;, &thorn;er
fe&llbar; suche a wete and a ray&ntail;, &thorn;at ij dayes after
&thorn;ai mott nott berie hy&mtail;.  And his wife was ane i&llbar;
liffer, bod scho was fortunatt; and whe&ntail; &thorn;ai war bothe
dead, a doghter at &thorn;ai had bega&ntail; to vmthynk hur whedur of
&thorn;er lyvis sho wolde folow.  So after-war&dtail; hur happend to
be in a trans,









<PB N="218">

&amp; hur thoght sho saw a fayr place &amp; a merie; and &thorn;er hur
&thorn;oght sho saw hur fadur, and sho hawsi&dtail; hy&mtail; and
kyssyd hy&mtail;, &amp; besoght hy&mtail; at sho mott abyde &thorn;er
sti&llbar; with hy&mtail;.  &amp; he sai&dtail; nay, sho mott nott;
bott and sho led hur lyfe as he di&dtail;, he sai&dtail; sho suld
co&mtail; thedur.  And onone sho was removi&dtail; fro thens, &amp;
had vnto a noder place.  And &thorn;er sho lukyd behyn&dtail; hur,
&amp; sho saw hur moder in ane horrible turment.  And sho made sorow,
&amp; cryed o&ntail; hur doghter &amp; sai&dtail;; "Doghter!  Se what
I suffer for myne vnclene lyfe!"  And with &thorn;att sho come
agay&ntail; vnto hur selfe, &amp; thankid God of &thorn;at att sho had
sene.  And scho confermy&dtail; to folow &thorn;e lyfe of hur fadur,
and so sho di&dtail;, and afterwar&dtail; sho was a holie
womma&ntail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Facundia necessaria est clerico.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis how &thorn;at whe&ntail; Demostenes moght not
easylie bryng furth certay&ntail; lettres, he labur&dtail; so
agay&ntail; a vice &amp; ane impediment in his mouthe, &thorn;at no
ma&ntail; myght speke fayrer &thorn;at at he wol&dtail; speke
&thorn;a&ntail; he di&dtail; <NOTE ID="P218.N1">The latter part of this tale differs from the Lat. MSS., which give the well-known version.</NOTE> .  So o&ntail; a
tyme hy&mtail; happend go vnto &thorn;e se-side, &amp; &thorn;er he
harde grete noyse &amp; dusshyng of &thorn;e wawis to-gedur; and he
gaff grete hede &thorn;er-to.  And evur whe&ntail; his <NOTE ID="P218.N2">MS. he.</NOTE> mowthe was fu&llbar; of sentance &amp; reso&ntail;,
he wolde speke meku&llbar;, &amp; be long in spekyng; and whe&ntail;
it was tome, &thorn;a&ntail; it was redie &amp; as it had bene lowse.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Fallacia mulieris.  Infra de muliere.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Falsitas testium nocet.  Infra de testimonio.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Falsum iurans punitur.  Infra de iuramento.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Falsum impositum debet denudari.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Legenda Sanctorum Prothi et Iacincti,' how Eugenia,
&thorn;at was Phili&ptail; doghter &thorn;at was governer of
Alexandria,






<PB N="219">

wol&dtail; not be we&dtail; vnto a wurthi ma&ntail; &thorn;at
wol&dtail; hafe had hur whe&ntail; sho was xv yere olde.  And sho fled
away and gatt hur mans clothyng, &amp; fenyd at sho sulde be a
ma&ntail;, &amp; went vnto ane abbay &amp; made hyr <NOTE ID="P219.N1">MS. hy&mtail;.</NOTE> a ma&ntail; of religio&ntail;; and sho calli&dtail;
hur selfe Eugenius.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;er principa&llbar; was
dead, sho was made principa&llbar;.  So &thorn;er was in Alexandria a
wurthi womma&ntail;, a wedow, &thorn;at was passan&dtail; riche, and
sho trusti&dtail; at he had bene a ma&ntail;, &amp; fe&llbar; in ane
amorositie vnto hy&mtail;, vnto so meku&llbar; at sho fenyd hur seke
&amp; sent for hy&mtail;, and sai&dtail; sho wol&dtail; speke with
hy&mtail;.  And whe&ntail; he was befo&rtail; hur be&dtail;, &amp;
none was &thorn;er bod &thorn;aim two, sho wol&dtail; hafe
halsy&dtail; &amp; kyssy&dtail; &thorn;is Eugenius, &amp; tol&dtail;
hy&mtail; &thorn;e matir, and desyri&dtail; hy&mtail; to hafe at do
with hur.  And he vgge&dtail; &thorn;er-with, and wol&dtail; not
consent vnto hur, bod reprovi&dtail; hur &amp; blamy&dtail; hur for
hur desyre.  An&dtail; &thorn;a&ntail; sho was fer&dtail; at he
sul&dtail; discure hur, and sho bega&ntail; to cry, an&dtail;
sai&dtail; at &thorn;is Eugenius wolde hafe ravisshi&dtail; hur.  And
a&llbar; hur howse-meneya come and har&dtail;, and went &amp; tolde
&thorn;is Philip&ptail;, &amp; bare witnes &thorn;eroff.  And
&thorn;is womma&ntail; accusi&dtail; hi&mtail; als-so, als strongli as
sho cuthe.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is Eugenius was broght
befo&rtail; &thorn;is Philip&ptail; to giff ane ansswer, &amp; he
suffyr&dtail; meku&llbar; truble.  And so at &thorn;e last, whe&ntail;
he saw it wol&dtail; no bettyr be, he bega&ntail; to speke &amp;
sai&dtail;; "Now it is tyme to speke, ffor it is not right at a lichur
putt a fals cryme vnto &thorn;e servan&dtail; of almi&yogh;tty God;
and &thorn;erfo&rtail;, to decla&rtail; &thorn;e treut&hbar;, I
sa&llbar; shew my selfe whatt I a&mtail;."  And with &thorn;at
&thorn;is Eugenius with a knyfe cutt dow&ntail; a&llbar; hur cote,
&amp; shewi&dtail; at sho was a womma&ntail;, &amp; say&dtail; vnto
&thorn;is Philip&ptail;; "Forsuthe &thorn;ou erte my fadur, and
&thorn;i wyfe Elendia is my moder, and I a&mtail; Eugenia your
doghter."  And whe&ntail; hur fadur &amp; hur moder hard &thorn;is,
&thorn;ai tuke hur in armys &amp; kissi&dtail; hur.  And &thorn;ai
&amp; a&llbar; &thorn;er howsol&dtail; become cresten&dtail;,
&thorn;at war haythe&ntail; befo&rtail; and vncristen&dtail;.

</P>
<P>
