Infamacione.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>



<PB N="220">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Fames multa mala cogit facere.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in &thorn;e 'Cronicles' &thorn;at whe&ntail; Titus had
vmsegi&dtail; Jerusalem ij yere, &thorn;er was suc&hbar; a honger in
&thorn;e cetie &thorn;at &thorn;e fathir fro &thorn;e so&ntail;, &amp;
&thorn;e so&ntail; fro &thorn;e fadir, and &thorn;e husban&dtail; fro
hys wife, and &thorn;e wife fro hur husban&dtail;, not alonelie tuke
meate oute of &thorn;er handis, bod also &thorn;ai wol&dtail; refe it
furt&hbar; of &thorn;er mowthis.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;er meate
fayli&dtail; &thorn;aim, &thorn;ai dye&dtail; so thik for hungre
&thorn;at &thorn;ai mot not suffre &thorn;er caryons lygg with-in
&thorn;e cetie for stynke, bod &thorn;ai keste &thorn;aim ouer
&thorn;e wallis.  And &thorn;a&ntail; Titus saw how &thorn;e dykis was
fylli&dtail; with cario&ntail;, &amp; at &thorn;e contre bega&ntail;
to be corrupte with savur of &thorn;aim, &thorn;a&ntail; he made his
prayers &amp; sai&dtail;; "Lor&dtail;! &thorn;ou seis I do nott
&thorn;is, &thorn;ai do itt &thorn;er selfe."  &amp; &thorn;ai had so
meku&llbar; honger emang &thorn;aim att &thorn;ai eete &thorn;er shone
&amp; a&llbar; &thorn;ing &thorn;at was made of leddur.  So &thorn;er
was emang &thorn;aim a riche huswiffe, and a wurthie, and a&llbar; hur
gudis was take&ntail; fro hur, &amp; no thyng lefte hur &thorn;at sho
might eate.  And sho had no chil&dtail; bod one; &amp; &thorn;at sho
slew, &amp; sethi&dtail; &thorn;e tone halfe &thorn;erof.  And onone
as &thorn;e lurdans in &thorn;e cetie feli&dtail; savur of sody&ntail;
fless&hbar;, &thorn;ai ra&ntail; in-to &thorn;e howse &amp;
aski&dtail; hur parte; &amp; sho tuke &thorn;e toder parte &amp;
shewi&dtail; &thorn;aim &amp; tol&dtail; &thorn;aim how sho had done
with hur aw&ntail; bar&ntail;.  And &thorn;ai vggi&dtail;
&thorn;er-with, &amp; went &thorn;er ways.  And so in &thorn;e
secun&dtail; yere Ierusalem was yolde&ntail; vp&ptail;, and xxx Iewis
war sol&dtail; for one penye becauce &thorn;ai solde Criste for
xxx<HI REND="sup">&dtail;</HI>.  And, as Iosephus tellis, lxxxxvij thowsan&dtail; war
solde, an&dtail; xi C. M&lbar;. was slay&ntail; &amp; perisshi&dtail;
for hungre.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Fames terrenorum est insaciabilis.  Infra de sacietate.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Fame temptantur ieiunantes.  Supra de abstinencia.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXX. 
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Familiaritas 
<NOTE ID="P220.N1">MS. Familieritas.</NOTE>  eciam matris ad proprium filium
nimis expressa est periculosa.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in &thorn;e 'Meracles of Ou&rtail; Ladie, Saynt Marie' how
som tyme in Rome &thorn;er was a wurthie womma&ntail;, and scho had
with hur



<PB N="221">

husban&dtail; a so&ntail;, an&dtail; &thorn;att sho broght vp&ptail;
passan&dtail; tendurlie, &amp; luffi&dtail; it so wele &thorn;at,
whe&ntail; he was a grete yong sprynhol&dtail;, sho wol&dtail; kys
hy&mtail; &amp; halsse hy&mtail; &amp; lat hy&mtail; lig with hur as
he ha&dtail; bene a bar&ntail;.  So o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; hur
husban&dtail; was gone of pilgramege in-to a fer lan&dtail;, as hur
so&ntail; lay by hur he had at do with hur, and belife sho was with
childe; &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; sho wex passan&dtail; hevy, &amp; had
grete sorow in hur harte, and sho fe&llbar; to hur prayers as sho was
wunte to do, &amp; besoght God &amp; our dere Ladie to helpe hur.  So
at &thorn;e laste sho travel&dtail;; &amp; whe&ntail; &thorn;e
bar&ntail; was vnnethis bor&ntail;, sho slew it &amp; eki&dtail;
sy&ntail; vppo&ntail; sy&ntail;, &amp; keste it in-to a sege.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e fende had despite he&rtail;-att, and
&thorn;oght for to gar hur be destroye&dtail;, &amp; made hy&mtail; in
habett like a cler&ktee;, and come afo&rtail; &thorn;e iugges &amp;
&thorn;e me&ntail; of law, and desyri&dtail; &thorn;aim to here
hy&mtail;, &amp; he sulde te&llbar; &thorn;aim a huge mervayle for any
ma&ntail; to here, &amp; a passan&dtail; crue&llbar; dede: "ffor
suc&hbar; a womma&ntail;, at ye trow is a passan&dtail; halie
womma&ntail;, is a passan&dtail; wikkid womma&ntail;, &amp; a
crewe&llbar;, &amp; fu&llbar; of sy&ntail;.  For sho conseyvi&dtail; a
childe of hur aw&ntail; so&ntail;, &amp; yit also whe&ntail; it was
bor&ntail;, sho slew it &amp; keste it into a sege."  And &thorn;ai
had grete merve&llbar; here-of, &amp; sai&dtail; &thorn;ai
trowi&dtail; it was not so.  And he bad feche hur &amp; examy&ntail;
hur; "&amp; in &thorn;e mene while make a fire, and if sho grawnt or
be convicte &thorn;er-in, latt kaste hur whik in &thorn;e fire &amp;
bur&ntail; hur."  And if sho wer nott, he ba&dtail; &thorn;aim take
and bur&ntail; hy&mtail;.  And sho was fechi&dtail; and broght
befo&rtail; &thorn;e iuggies &amp; &thorn;e me&ntail; of law; and
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e iuge say&dtail; vnto hur; "Womma&ntail;, we
hafe he&rtail; a new prophett in Rome, &amp; he, &thorn;uff a&llbar;
vs for-thyn&ktee; it gretelie, hase accusi&dtail; &thorn;e in grete
trispasis.  And &thorn;erfo&rtail; &thorn;ou muste owder knowlege
&thorn;i trispas, or els &thorn;ou must excuse &thorn;e &thorn;eroff."
And &thorn;a&ntail; sho aski&dtail; of &thorn;e law a respecte, &amp;
had it grawnti&dtail;.  &amp; scho went home &amp; made grete sorow
for hur trispas, an&dtail; went vnto a preste, &amp; with hartlie
contricio&ntail; sho shrafe hur &amp; tol&dtail; hy&mtail; a&llbar;
how sho had done.  And he saw &thorn;at scho wepi&dtail; &amp; made
grete sorow, &amp; comfurthi&dtail; hur, and enioyny&dtail; hur in
penans to say bod one pater noster.  And he bad hur at sho sulde pray
hartelie vnto ou&rtail; dere Ladie to helpe hur.  And so sho
di&dtail;, with grete deuocio&ntail;.  And so vppo&ntail; &thorn;er
courte-day, sho was sent after agay&ntail;; &amp; sho come <NOTE ID="P221.N1"><HI REND="i">After</HI> come, n, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE>



<PB N="222">

onone with a&llbar; hur houshol&dtail;, &amp; hur frendis with hur.
And sho was sett in myddeste &thorn;e courte, at a&llbar; me&ntail;
might se hur; and &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e Iustis chargi&dtail;
a&llbar; to be pease, &amp; sai&dtail; vnto &thorn;is cler&ktee; at
accusi&dtail; hur; "Loo! he&rtail; is sho at &thorn;ou hase
accusi&dtail;.  Say now vnto hur &amp; &thorn;ou hase oght at say."
And &thorn;is fen&dtail; behel&dtail; &thorn;is womma&ntail;, &amp;
had grete mervay&llbar; off hur, what sho sulde be.  &amp;
&thorn;a&ntail; he sai&dtail;; "This is not &thorn;att synner nor
&thorn;at man-queller &thorn;at I accusi&dtail;; ffor &thorn;is is a
holie womma&ntail;, and Marie, &thorn;e moder of Criste, stondit&hbar;
by hur &amp; kepis hur."  And &thorn;a&ntail; a&llbar; &thorn;at evur
was aboute had grete mervayle, &amp; lifte&dtail; vp&ptail; &thorn;er
handis &amp; sayny&dtail; &thorn;aim.  And &thorn;e fen&dtail; myght
not suffre &thorn;is &amp; vanysshi&dtail; away with a grete reke and
a stynkkan&dtail;; and &thorn;us &thorn;is womma&ntail; was
delyver&dtail;.  et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Familiaritas mulieris eciam sanctis
nocet.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Legenda Sancti Remigij' how &thorn;er was one
&thorn;at hight Genelandus, &amp; he was a wurthi ma&ntail;, &amp; wed
Saynt Re[mi]gius <NOTE ID="P222.N1">MS. Saynt Regius.</NOTE> sister doghter vnto his wife.
And so be conce&llbar; of &thorn;is gude holie ma&ntail; &thorn;ai
departi&dtail; <NOTE ID="P222.N2">Lat. MSS. Et se religionis causa mutuo absoluissent.</NOTE> ; and &thorn;is Genelandus was
made bisshop&ptail; of Lugdu&ntail;, and he was a gude cler&ktee;
&amp; a wurthi prechur.  And his wife wol&dtail; oft sithis co&mtail;
vnto hy&mtail; becauce of instruccio&ntail;, &amp; to here hy&mtail;
preche.  And so att &thorn;e laste, be temptacio&ntail; sho
conseyvi&dtail;, &amp; was with chil&dtail; with hy&mtail;; and
whe&ntail; &thorn;is chil&dtail; was bor&ntail;, &thorn;is
bisshop&ptail;, &thorn;e fadur &thorn;eroff, garte ca&llbar; it Latro,
becauce it was gette&ntail; be stoltherie.  Not-with-stondyng, becauce
of suspicio&ntail;, he suffre&dtail; his wife co&mtail; to hy&mtail;
agay&ntail; as sho did befo&rtail;; and belife scho was with childe
agay&ntail;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e childe was bor&ntail;, &thorn;e
fadur garte ca&llbar; it Vulpiculus.  So at &thorn;e laste hy&mtail;
repenti&dtail;, and went vnto Remigius, and shrafe hy&mtail; to
hy&mtail; &amp; knowlegi&dtail; his sy&ntail;.  And he closi&dtail;
hy&mtail; v&ptail; in a ce&llbar; vij yere, &amp; in &thorn;e mene
while he gouerne&dtail; his bisshoppri&ktee;.  And at &thorn;e vij
yere en&dtail;, ane ange&llbar; aperi&dtail; vnto &thorn;is Genelandus
<NOTE ID="P222.N3">MS. Gelelandus.</NOTE> , &amp; tol&dtail; hy&mtail; at his sy&ntail;
was forgyffy&ntail;







<PB N="223">

hy&mtail;, and bad hy&mtail; go furt&hbar;, &amp; opyn&dtail; &thorn;e
dure and savi&dtail; &thorn;e seale hale at Saynt Remigius sett
o&ntail; itt.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is Genelandus lay&dtail;
hy&mtail; dow&ntail; in &thorn;e dure opo&ntail; &thorn;e ert&hbar; in
liknes of a cros, &amp; sai&dtail; vnto &thorn;e aunge&llbar;; "And my
Lord, almighti God Hy&mtail; selfe, co&mtail; vnto me I wi&llbar; not
away bod if my maister Remigius at sparri&dtail; me here co&mtail;
&amp; take me furt&hbar;."  And &thorn;a&ntail;, be commandment of
&thorn;e ange&llbar;, &thorn;is Remigius come vnto hym &amp; tuke
hy&mtail; oute, &amp; had hy&mtail; vnto Lugdo&ntail; &amp;
restori&dtail; agay&ntail; vnto his bisschopprik.  And he was a halie
ma&ntail; a&llbar; his life-dayes after; and whe&ntail; he dye&dtail;,
&thorn;is Latro his elder so&ntail; was made bisshop&ptail; after
hy&mtail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Familiaritas 
<NOTE ID="P223.N1">MS. Familieritas.</NOTE>  eciam mulieris sapientibus est

periculosa.  Infra de muliere.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXXII. 
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Fatuitas.  Fatuitatem causa humilitatis sancti
similant aliquando.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Heraclides tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was in a monasterie
of nonnys a maydy&ntail;, and for Goddis luff sho made hur selfe
evy&ntail; as a fule, &amp; meke &amp; buxho&mtail; to euer-ilk bodis
commandment; &amp; sho made hur selfe so vile, &amp; so grete ane
vnderlowte, &thorn;at ilkone vggi&dtail; with hur, to so myke&llbar;
&thorn;at &thorn;ai wol&dtail; not eate with <NOTE ID="P223.N2">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, with.</NOTE>
hur, bod ilkone strake hur &amp; skorny&dtail; hur: &amp; evur sho
tuke it in plesans.  So sho passi&dtail; neuer &thorn;e kichy&ntail;,
bod bade &thorn;er, &amp; wasshi&dtail; dysshis &amp; skowri&dtail;
pottys, and di&dtail; a&llbar; maner of fowle labur.  And sho satt
neuer at meatt, bod hel&dtail; hur selfe content with crombys &amp;
crustis &thorn;at war lefte at &thorn;e bur&dtail;; &amp;
&thorn;er-with sho liffi&dtail;, and sho wa&rtail; nevur shone nor
hose, &amp; sho had nothyng o&ntail; hur hea&dtail; bod revy&ntail;
clothis, &amp; raggi&dtail;.  And sho was seruyciable to euerilk
creatur, and wol&dtail; do no bodye wrong, and what at evur was done
vnto hur, &thorn;er was none at har&dtail; hur gruche &thorn;er-with.
So emang a&llbar; &thorn;ies, be &thorn;e commawndment of ane
aunge&llbar;, Saynt Patryk, at was a holie ma&ntail; &amp;
liffi&dtail; in wildrenes, come vnto &thorn;is same monasterie, and
calli&dtail; befo&rtail; hy&mtail; a&llbar; &thorn;e nonnys &amp;
a&llbar; &thorn;e susters of &thorn;e place, at he might





<PB N="224">

se &thorn;aim, and sho come not: &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; he sai&dtail;;
"Ye er not a&llbar; here."  And &thorn;ai sai&dtail;; "Yis, fadur, we
er a&llbar; here, outtaky&ntail; one &thorn;at is bod a fule."  And he
bad &thorn;aim ca&llbar; hur; and als sone as he saw hur he knew in
his spiritt &thorn;at sho was mo&rtail; halie &thorn;a&ntail; he.  And
he fe&llbar; dow&ntail; o&ntail; his kneis befo&rtail; hur &amp;
sai&dtail;; "Spiritua&llbar; moder! giff me &thorn;i blissyng!"  And
sho fe&llbar; dow&ntail; o&ntail; kneis before hy&mtail; &amp;
sai&dtail;; "Nay, fathur, rathur &thorn;ou sulde blis me."  And with
&thorn;at &thorn;e susters of &thorn;e howse had grete wonder, &amp;
sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "Fathir, suffer not &thorn;is eniorie, for
sho is bod a fulle."  And he sai&dtail;; "Nay, sho is wise, &amp; ye
er bod fules; ffor sho is bettyr &thorn;a&ntail; owder ye or I."  And
&thorn;a&ntail; a&llbar; &thorn;e susters fe&llbar; o&ntail; &thorn;er
kneis befor hur, &amp; asky&dtail; hur forgifnes of wrangis &amp;
iniuries &thorn;at &thorn;ai <NOTE ID="P224.N1">MS. &thorn;ai &thorn;a.</NOTE> had done vnto hir,
ffo&rtail; <NOTE ID="P224.N2">The MS.<HI REND="i"> has a contraction sign above</HI> ffo&rtail;.</NOTE> scho forgiffes &thorn;aim ilkone
with a&llbar; hur harte.

</P>
<P>     
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Feruor fidei laudabilis est.  Infra de Martirio.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Festinacio, licet aliquando nimia, tamen est bona
<NOTE ID="P224.N3">Lat. MSS. Festinacio nimia non est bona.</NOTE>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Jacobus de Vetriaco tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a
ma&ntail; &thorn;at had a guse, &amp; sho warpyd euer-ilk day ane egg.
And on a tyme he vmthoght &thorn;at he wol&dtail; hafe a&llbar;
&thorn;ies eggis at ons, &amp; he slew his guse &amp; oppen&dtail;
hur, and he fan&dtail; bod one egg in hur.  And so for grete haste
&thorn;at he had of &thorn;at at was for to co&mtail;, he loste
a&llbar;.  et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Festinacio nimia hominem retardat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> The same Jacobus tellis how, o&ntail; a tyme in France, &thorn;er
was a grete meneya of me&ntail; rydan&dtail; in a carte.  And
agay&ntail; evy&ntail; &thorn;ai ouertuke Saynt Marty&ntail; rydand
vppo&ntail; ane ass, &amp; &thorn;ai asky&dtail; hy&mtail; if
&thorn;ai myght co&mtail; with day vnto Pariss.  And he sai&dtail;;
ya, &amp; &thorn;ai drafe bod playnlie &amp; softelie.  And &thorn;ai
gaff no hede vnto his









<PB N="225">

wurde, &amp; drafe faste, &amp; garte &thorn;er carte ry&ntail; als
faste as &thorn;e hors mot preke.  So &thorn;aim happen&dtail; breke
&thorn;er whele; &amp; Saynt Marty&ntail; went bod softelie &amp; he
come to Pariss&hbar; at a gude how&rtail;, lang befo&rtail;
evy&ntail;, whar &thorn;ai lefte behyn&dtail; with &thorn;er hastynes.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Fides trinitatis confirmatur per
miraculum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how, o&ntail; a tyme, in &thorn;e Cetie of Nazarencis <NOTE ID="P225.N1">Lat. MSS. in urbe Nasatense.</NOTE> , whe&ntail; &thorn;e bisshop&ptail; was at mes, he
was war of iij clere droppis, a&llbar; elike meki&llbar; <NOTE ID="P225.N2">Latin MSS. vidit tres guttas clarissimas, equales magnitudinis.</NOTE> , drop&ptail; opo&ntail; &thorn;e alta&rtail;; &amp;
&thorn;ai flewi&dtail; to-gedur &amp; turny&dtail; into a precious
stone.  And he garte take &thorn;is stone &amp; sett itt in myddeste
of a cros of gol&dtail; emang many other precious stonys; and onone as
it was sett in, a&llbar; &thorn;e other precious stonys fe&llbar;
oute.  et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Fides corroboratur per eukaristiam protegentem

a combustione.  Supra de Eukaristia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Fides roboratur per corporale sanguinolentum.  Supra

de corporali.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Fides roboratur per crucifixum sanguinolentum.

Supra de crucifixo.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Fides roboratur per eukaristiam in carne versam.

Supra de Eukaristia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Fides fracta displicet Deo.  Infra Iacobi.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Fides contra naturam aliquando subuenit.  Supra de

Apostolis et Augustino.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Fidelis est canis domino suo.  Supra de dileccione.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Fidelitatem racione inuidie multi deserunt.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Justinus tellis in 'Gestis Alexandri' how at Alexander had a hy
natura&llbar; witt aboue a&llbar; other me&ntail;, vnto so muche
&thorn;at his






<PB N="226">

knyghtis had such a fait&hbar; in hy&mtail;, at als lang as he was
present &thorn;ai trusti&dtail; &thorn;at, &amp; &thorn;ai had bene
vnarmy&dtail;, yit &thorn;er enmys sulde nott hafe ouer-comme&ntail;
&thorn;aim, &amp; at what peple at &thorn;ai sulde feght with,
&thorn;ai trusti&dtail; to our-co&mtail; &thorn;aim, &amp; what cetie
at &thorn;ai vmsegi&dtail;, &thorn;ai trusti&dtail; to gett &amp;
wy&ntail; itt.  For &thorn;er was neuer enmy &thorn;at he faght with
bod he ouer-come hy&mtail;, nor neuer cetie &thorn;at he segi&dtail;
bod he wa&ntail; it, nor neuer peple nor nacio&ntail; att he rase
agay&ntail; bo&dtail; he ha&dtail; &thorn;e ouer-han&dtail; of
&thorn;aim.  And neuer-&thorn;e-les, at &thorn;e laste en&dtail;, he
was ouer-comme&ntail;, &amp; not in bate&llbar; be feghtyng with his
enmys, bod <NOTE ID="P226.N1">Lat. MSS. sed insidiis suorum et fraude civili.</NOTE> with gyle &amp; dessayte of ane of
his aw&ntail; knyghtis &thorn;at poyson&dtail; hy&mtail; with a drynk.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Fidelis seruus corpus suum pro domino suo
exponit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a ma&ntail; &thorn;at
hight Papulio&ntail; <NOTE ID="P226.N2">Lat. MSS. Papinion.</NOTE> , and be chance be
&thorn;e peple he was condempnyd vnto dea&dtail;.  And &thorn;er was
knyghtis sent be &thorn;e law to punyss&hbar; hy&mtail; after &thorn;e
decre.  And he had in his howse a servan&dtail; &thorn;at luffi&dtail;
hy&mtail; hugelie wele, and whe&ntail; he wiste at &thorn;ies knyghtys
war comme&ntail; to sla his maister, he did o&ntail; his maister
clothyng, &amp; putt o&ntail; his ryng on hys fynger, &amp; put oute
his maister at a poster&ntail;, &amp; went in-to his maister chawmer
hy&mtail; selfe.  And onone &thorn;ies knyghtis come &amp; fand
hy&mtail; in &thorn;e chawmer, and &thorn;ai went he had bene
Papulio&ntail; hy&mtail; selfe, &amp; slew hy&mtail; in-stede of his
maister.  et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Fidelis amicus omnia sua exponit pro Amico.  Supra

de Amicicia.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Fideiussor pro alio nullus fieri debet de facili.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' how som tyme &thorn;er was ane holie
hermet, &amp; o&ntail; a tyme hy&mtail; happend to be herber&dtail; at
a maso&ntail;





<PB N="227">

howse.  And be &thorn;er commonyng samen at evy&ntail;, &thorn;is
hermet fande wele &thorn;at &thorn;is maso&ntail; despendi&dtail; his
adlyng, one parte in suche thyng as hy&mtail; nedy&dtail;, &amp; a
noder parte in almos-dede, and &thorn;e thri&dtail; parte in herberyng
of pure fol&ktee;.  And here-fo&rtail; &thorn;is hermett, whe&ntail;
he come at home at his ce&llbar;, made his prayer vnto Go&dtail;, and
besoght Hy&mtail; at He wol&dtail; multiplie &thorn;is maso&ntail;
gudis, becauce he spendi&dtail; &thorn;aim so wele.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; it was ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; in a visio&ntail;,
&thorn;at it wol&dtail; not be expedient vnto hy&mtail; &thorn;at he
had mo&rtail; gude &thorn;a&ntail; he had.  And &thorn;e hermett
sai&dtail; yis, &amp; sai&dtail; at he wol&dtail; beco&mtail; his
borg&hbar;.  And vppo&ntail; &thorn;at it was grawnti&dtail;
hy&mtail;, vnto so meku&llbar; &thorn;at vpo&ntail; &thorn;e
mor&ntail;, as &thorn;is maso&ntail; was brekan&dtail; ane ol&dtail;
wa&llbar;, he fan&dtail; a grete so&mtail; of golde stoppy&dtail; in a
hole.  And he tuke it, &amp; gaff ou&rtail; his crafte, and went to
cowrte in-to &thorn;e emperour howshol&dtail;.  And belife he was so
grete with &thorn;e Emperour at he was made a baillay; &amp;
&thorn;a&ntail; he was a grete oppresser of pure me&ntail;.  So it
happen&dtail; &thorn;is hermett in a visio&ntail; was take&ntail;
&amp; led vnto &thorn;e dome; and &thorn;er he saw aungels
compley&ntail; of &thorn;is maso&ntail;.  And it was ansswer&dtail;
&thorn;aim &thorn;at his borg&hbar; sul&dtail; ansswer for hy&mtail;;
and &thorn;is hermett was passan&dtail; fer&dtail;, and besoght our
Ladie, Saynt Marie, to helpe hy&mtail;.  And scho gat grant at
&thorn;is hermet sulde be sent vnto hy&mtail; to make hy&mtail; to
amen&dtail; hy&mtail;.  And whe&ntail; he come at hy&mtail; &amp;
tol&dtail; hy&mtail; here-of, he sett lity&llbar; &thorn;er-by, &amp;
wol&dtail; not amend hy&mtail;, nor speke a wur&dtail; vnto &thorn;is
hermett, bod with his staff he bett &thorn;is hermett a&llbar; to
clowtis.  And &thorn;is hermett was sorowfu&llbar; &amp; went home
agay&ntail; vnto his ce&llbar;.  And o&ntail; &thorn;e night after, he
was ravisshi&dtail; agay&ntail; vnto &thorn;e dome, and accusi&dtail;
as he was befo&rtail;, bod our Ladie, Saynt Marie, helpi&dtail;
hy&mtail; wele.  And with-in a little while after &thorn;is Emperour
dye&dtail;, &amp; a noder was made in his steade, &thorn;at wol&dtail;
hafe tane &thorn;is maso&ntail; &amp; punysshi&dtail; hy&mtail; for
his mysgouernans.  And he fled, &amp; a&llbar; his gude was loste,
vnto so mekle he was fay&ntail; to tur&ntail; agay&ntail; vnto his
crafte, &amp; do as he was wunte to do; &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; he
feli&dtail; at he had displesi&dtail; Go&dtail;, &amp; amendi&dtail;
hy&mtail; &amp; devydi&dtail; his adlyng in-to werkis of charitie as
he did befo&rtail;.  et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Filij parum curant de animabus parentum post

mortem.  Infra de morte.
</FOREIGN>

<PB N="228">
</ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Filij non sunt maledicendi a parentibus.  Infra de

honore.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Filij propter deum derelinq[u]unt parentes.  Infra de

visitacione.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Filia diligenter debet custodiri.</FOREIGN></HEAD>


<P> Seutonius Philosophus tellis how &thorn;at Augustus Cesar garte
ordan&dtail; so for a doghter &amp; a sister doghter &thorn;at he had,
&thorn;at he mott wunte &thorn;aim &amp; make &thorn;aim perfite
in wirkyng of wu&llbar;; and he forbad &thorn;aim to speke any thyng
bod opynlie, and dischargi&dtail; &thorn;aim &thorn;e company &amp;
spekyng with of any strangiers.  So it happen&dtail; a wurthi
ma&ntail; Licrinius, for to co&mtail; to &thorn;e Emperour doghter
&amp; halsi&dtail; hur, &amp; sho wolde speke no wur&dtail;
agay&ntail;.  So afterwar&dtail; it wal&dtail; tolde &thorn;e
Emperour, and he wrote vnto hy&mtail; &amp; sai&dtail; at he had done
hy&mtail; a litle sober trispas, for als mike&llbar; as he come to
haylse his doghter contrary vnto his commandment.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Finem malum quandoque habent mali.  Infra de

salutare.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Fletus malus vel multiplex.  Infra de lacrima.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Fornicacio.  Fornicaria mulier infamat aliquando

innocentes.  Supra de accusacione.  Et infra de

infamia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Fornicacionem committunt aliqui incaute se

custodientes.  Supra de Confidencia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Fortitudo semper est laudabilis in vtentibus 
<NOTE ID="P228.N1">Arund. MS. bene utentibus ea.</NOTE>  ea.

Infra de milite.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Fortitudo animi.  Infra de morte.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Forcior aliquando est vnus quam plures.  Supra de

commestione.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>



<PB N="229">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXXX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Fortes nimis sunt canes vt in alio
latere.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Solinus tellis &thorn;at &thorn;er er bred in Albanye hondis
&thorn;at &amp; &thorn;ai be set at any maner of beste, &thorn;ai will
ki&llbar; it &amp; halde sti&llbar; what at evur &thorn;aim happynd to
mete.  So whe&ntail; kyng Alexander went into Ynde, &thorn;e kyng of
Albany sent hy&mtail; ij of &thorn;ies hundes, and &thorn;e tane of
&thorn;aim wolde nowder luke o&ntail; swyne nor on bere, and he
wal&dtail; eate no meat, in his kene&llbar; &thorn;er he lay.  And
kyng Alexander garte lowse hy&mtail; &amp; lete hy&mtail; go.  And
&thorn;e toder, evur whe&ntail; he was commandi&dtail; be &thorn;aim
at folowi&dtail; hy&mtail;, he wol&dtail; sla lyons or any other wylde
beste.  So &thorn;ai lete hy&mtail; se ane olyfante, and he
chasi&dtail; so &thorn;at he was werie; and at &thorn;e laste he
pulli&dtail; hy&mtail; dow&ntail; &amp; killi&dtail; hy&mtail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Fortuna est variabilis 
<NOTE ID="P229.N1">So Harl. MS. The Engl. MS. has, inenarrabilis.</NOTE> .  Infra de gloriacione et
ordinacione.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXXXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Francisci.  De Sancto Francisco.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how som tyme &thorn;er was a womma&ntail; &thorn;at had a
grete deuocio&ntail; vnto Saynt Frawncis; so hur happen&dtail; to dye,
and &thorn;e &thorn;restis come &amp; sang hur a dirige.  So sodanlie
sho spak vnto one of &thorn;e prestis at stude abowte hur, &amp;
sai&dtail;; "Fadur, I wulde be shrevy&ntail;; I was dea&dtail; &amp;
commaundi&dtail; vnto a grevus preso&ntail; for a sy&ntail; &thorn;at I
was neuer shrevy&ntail; of, &thorn;at I sa&llbar; now confess me off
to the.  Bod Saynt Frawncis prayed for me, at my saule mott co&mtail;
agay&ntail; vnto my bodye &amp; confes &thorn;at sy&ntail;, &amp; so
hafe forgyfnes &thorn;erof."



<PB N="230">

And &thorn;er sho shrafe hur &thorn;eroff, &amp; tuke hur
absolucio&ntail;, &amp; onone after sho swelt agay&ntail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Fraus.  Fraudem debent omnes vitare.  Infra de
negociacione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Fuga.  Fugienda est turba.  Infra de turba.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXXXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Fur.  Furis audacia magna est
frequenter.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Libro de Dono Timoris' how &thorn;at a thefe come
privalie o&ntail; a nyght vnto a philosophur be&dtail; &thorn;er he
lay, &amp; nemelie he drew at &thorn;e couerla&dtail; att lay o&ntail;
hy&mtail;, &amp; wolde hafe stollen it away.  And he feli&dtail; at
one pulli&dtail; at itt, &amp; put vp his han&dtail; &amp; drew it
agay&ntail;.  And with-in a while after, &thorn;is thief drew
agay&ntail;, &amp; he hel&dtail;; and &thorn;us &thorn;ai di&dtail;
twice or thrice.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai had long done so, &thorn;e
philosophur spak vnto hy&mtail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "&thorn;ou vnhappie
ma&ntail;!  Take &thorn;e couerlad, &amp; go &thorn;i wais
&thorn;er-with, &amp; latt me lygg in reste."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Fur videtur aliquando quando credit non videri.

Supra de deo.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXXXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Fures quandoque associant se in furtis
suis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> In a tow&ntail; in Normundie &thorn;a&rtail; standis a kurk
with-oute &thorn;e tow&ntail;, vppo&ntail; a hy&llbar;; and ij thevis
mett &thorn;er in ane evynyng, and &thorn;ai made counan&dtail; at
&thorn;e tane of &thorn;aim &thorn;at night sulde go stele a lambe, an
&thorn;e tother sulde go stele nuttis.  And he &thorn;at ha&dtail;
furste spe&dtail; sulde furste co&mtail; vnto &thorn;e kur&ktee;,
&amp; &thorn;er abide his felow in &thorn;e porc&hbar;.  And he
&thorn;at stale &thorn;e nuttis was spe&dtail; belife, &amp; come
furste, &amp; satt dow&ntail; &amp; abade his felow, &amp;
krakki&dtail; nuttis in &thorn;e kurk-porche &amp; ete &thorn;aim.  So
with-in nyght, late, &thorn;e clerk come to &thorn;e kurk to ryng
curfur.  And onone as he come in &thorn;e porche &amp; harde

<PB N="231">

at one was &thorn;er, &amp; he trowe&dtail; it had bene &thorn;e
Devu&llbar;; and als faste as he cuthe he ra&ntail; home vnto &thorn;e
prestis howse &amp; was passan&dtail; fer&dtail;, &amp; sai&dtail;
&thorn;e Devu&llbar; was in &thorn;e kurk-porche.  So &thorn;er was in
&thorn;e howse a halte ma&ntail;, &amp; he scorny&dtail; &thorn;e
cler&ktee;, &amp; sai&dtail; &thorn;at he dughte nott.  So &thorn;er
was a noder yong strong felow, &amp; &thorn;is halte ma&ntail;
sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;, and he wolde bere hy&mtail; to &thorn;e
kurk in his nek&ktee;, he sulde go luke whether &thorn;e Devu&llbar;
war in &thorn;e kurk-porche or nay.  And he sai&dtail; yis.  And
&thorn;is halte crepy&llbar; was sett vpp in hys ne&ktee;, &amp; he
bare hy&mtail; vnto &thorn;e kur&ktee;.  And &thorn;is thief at was
in &thorn;e kurk-porche saw a ma&ntail; co&mtail; &amp; a thyng in his
nekk, &amp; he trowe&dtail; it had bene his felow at had broght a
lambe.  And whe&ntail; he was nerehan&dtail; at &thorn;e porche dure,
he crye&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; &amp; say&dtail;; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Est ne crassus?</FOREIGN> Is it not fatt?"  And so
&thorn;is yong felow at bere &thorn;is crippi&llbar; har&dtail; what
he sai&dtail;, &amp; ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;;
"Whethur he be fatt or lene I sa&llbar; lefe it with the."  And with
&thorn;at he keste hy&mtail; fro hy&mtail;, &amp; ra&ntail; hame als
faste as he cuthe.  And &thorn;is cripy&llbar; gadur&dtail; his
strent&hbar; vnto hy&mtail;, &amp; bega&ntail; at ry&ntail; home
alsso.  And yit he was furste at &thorn;e howse &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e
yong ma&ntail; at ba&rtail; hy&mtail;.  And evur after he went
o&ntail; his fete &thorn;at stude not o&ntail; &thorn;aim vij yere
before.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Furis societas periculosa est.  Supra de Angelo et

heremita.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXXXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Fures possunt dici multi principes et
prelati.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Austy&ntail; tellis how &thorn;er was a maister of a
shi&ptail; &thorn;at hight Dironides, &amp; he was a grete robber be
&thorn;e se; so o&ntail; a tyme hy&mtail; happen&dtail; to be
take&ntail; &amp; broght befo&rtail; kyng Alexander.  And kyng
Alexander aski&dtail; hy&mtail; whi he vsi&dtail; suche robburi with
his shup&ptail;; and he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;;
"Whi laburs &thorn;ou to hafe dominacio&ntail; of a&llbar; &thorn;is
werl&dtail;, and I &thorn;at vsi bo&dtail; a little schu&ptail;, I
a&mtail; calli&dtail; a thefe, and &thorn;ou &thorn;at vsis to rob
&amp; refe with a grete navie of schuppis erte calli&dtail; ane
Emperour?  And forsuthe, &thorn;ou sa&llbar; verelie know, &thorn;at,
&amp; rightwusnes be removi&dtail; away, what er kyngisdoms?

<PB N="232">

Not els bod grete thyfte; &amp; what er little kyngdoms?  Not els bod
little thifte.  And &thorn;us, &thorn;ou erte a grete thefe, &amp; I
a&mtail; bod a little thefe."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Fures in presenti sepe puniuntur.  Supra de agro.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXXXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Furtum non potest celari.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Legenda Sancti Patricij' how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er
was a ma&ntail; at stale his neghbur shepe, &amp; ete it; and
&thorn;is ma&ntail; at aght &thorn;is shepe come vnto Saynt Patryk,
&amp; tol&dtail; hy&mtail; how a shepe was stolle&ntail; fro&mtail;
hy&mtail;: &amp; he chargi&dtail; oft sithis &thorn;at who
so&mtail;-evur ha&dtail; it sulde bryng it agay&ntail;, and no
ma&ntail; wolde grawnte it.  So o&ntail; a haly day, whe&ntail;
a&llbar; &thorn;e peple was in &thorn;e kur&ktee;, Saynt Patrik
spirri&dtail; &amp; commandi&dtail;, in &thorn;e vertue of Iesu, at
&thorn;is shepe sulde blete in his belie &thorn;at had ety&ntail; itt,
at a&llbar; me&ntail; might here.  And so it di&dtail;; &amp;
&thorn;us &thorn;e thefe was knowe&ntail;, &amp; made amendis for his
trispas.  And a&llbar; o&thorn;er &thorn;at har&dtail; euer after was
fer&dtail; to stele.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXXXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Furtum committendo eciam bruta se peccasse
cognoscunt.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Seuerius <NOTE ID="P232.N1"><HI REND="i">For</HI> Severus.</NOTE> tellis how so&mtail; tyme
&thorn;er was ane hermett &thorn;at dwelt in wyldernes, and euer-ilk
day, at meate tyme, &thorn;er come vnto his yate a sho-wulfe;
an&dtail; sho wulde neuer away or he gaff hur somwhatt at eate.  So
o&ntail; a day &thorn;is hermett was with a noder bruther of his in
occupacio&ntail;, &amp; come not <NOTE ID="P232.N2">Not, <HI REND="i">omitted and added above the line</HI>.</NOTE> home att
meate-tyme of &thorn;e day.  And &thorn;is wulfe come &amp; fan&dtail;
hy&mtail; not &thorn;er, &amp; was war of a litle brea&dtail; in a
wyndow, &amp; sho brak in &amp; tuke it, &amp; eete it &amp; went
away.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e hermett come home, he fan&dtail;
&thorn;e crombis of &thorn;e brea&dtail; at &thorn;e wyndow, &amp; he
demy&dtail; who had taky&ntail; it.  And &thorn;is wulfe knew hur
defaute, &amp; wolde not co&mtail; at &thorn;is hermett a sennett
afterwer&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;is hermet myssi&dtail;
&thorn;is wulfe, at vsi&dtail; to co&mtail;





<PB N="233">

daylie vnto hy&mtail;, he made his prayer vnto Go&dtail;; &amp;
&thorn;is wulfe come agay&ntail; vppo&ntail; &thorn;e sennet day, bod
sho stude of ferro&mtail;, &amp; durste not co&mtail; nere hy&mtail;.
And sho lay&dtail; hur dow&ntail; &amp; hel&dtail; dow&ntail; hur
hea&dtail;, as sho sul&dtail; aske hy&mtail; forgyfnes; and he tuke it
for a confessio&ntail;, &amp; bad hur co&mtail; ner hy&mtail; boldly,
&amp; he sul&dtail; forgiff hur. &amp; sho come to hy&mtail; &amp;
fe&llbar; dow&ntail; o&ntail; kneis; &amp; he forgaff hur, an&dtail;
gaff hur als meky&llbar; to brede as he was wunte to giff hur.  And
fro thens furt&hbar; evur after, scho come at tyme of &thorn;e day,
and di&dtail; hur offes as sho was wunt.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Furtum restituere 
<NOTE ID="P233.N1">MS. sustenere. Lat. MSS. <HI REND="i">as above</HI>.</NOTE>  eciam bruta animalia

compelluntur per oracionem.  Infra de oracione.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXXXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Furtum eciam nimium
<NOTE ID="P233.N2">Lat. MSS. minimum.</NOTE> in purgatorio punitur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a preste of
&thorn;e Templer ordur, and whe&ntail; he was a childe hy&mtail;
happen&dtail; for to fa&llbar; seke, and he aski&dtail; for to be
enoynty&dtail;, and he was not.  So hy&mtail; <NOTE ID="P233.N3"><HI REND="i">After</HI> hy&mtail;, hyn, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE>
happen&dtail; to dy, &amp; when his saule passi&dtail; furt&hbar; of
his bodye, he aski&dtail; helpe, an&dtail; ane ange&llbar; come, &amp;
sai&dtail; it was euy&llbar; done att he dye&dtail; with-oute
enoyntment.  So &thorn;is sawle was present before &thorn;e iuge, so
&thorn;at &thorn;e chil&dtail; saw hy&mtail; &amp; was passan&dtail;
angry agay&ntail; hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; come &thorn;e
devu&llbar;, &amp; accusi&dtail; &thorn;is childe, &amp; sai&dtail;;
"Lor&dtail;! &thorn;is childe stale ane halpeny fro&mtail; his
bruther-germa&ntail;, &amp; nowder yit hedurtowar&dtail; di&dtail;
penans &thorn;erfo&rtail;, nor rewardi&dtail; itt agay&ntail;."  And
&thorn;a&ntail; ow&rtail; Lor&dtail; ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail;
agay&ntail;, &amp; sai&dtail;; "Wol&dtail; &thorn;ou at I
dampny&dtail; &thorn;is childe for suche a lity&llbar; thyng?  Bod
&thorn;ou sa&llbar; vnderstan&dtail; att my rightwusnes is
mengi&dtail; with mercie."  And &thorn;a&ntail; prayed <NOTE ID="P233.N4">MS. prayer.</NOTE> for &thorn;is childe &thorn;e xxiiij seniores; and
so &thorn;is childe was forgyffe&ntail; his tryspas.
Neuer-&thorn;e-les, be &thorn;e commandment of our Lor&dtail;, he was
caste&ntail; in-to a byrnan&dtail; pitt, wha&rtail;-in he
suffer&dtail; so mekle pay&ntail;, &thorn;at he cuthe not
afterwar&dtail; te&llbar; with his mouthe.  And after &thorn;is he was
drawe&ntail; oute of &thorn;e pitt, &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; hy&mtail;
thoght &thorn;at &thorn;e iuge shewi&dtail; hy&mtail; frendlie







<PB N="234">

chere; and &thorn;a&ntail; he gaff a sentance &thorn;at his saule
sulde be restori&dtail; agay&ntail; vnto &thorn;e bodie, and so it
was.  &amp; whe&ntail; he come vnto hy&mtail; selfe, he tol&dtail;
a&llbar; att was abowte hy&mtail; how it ha&dtail; happen&dtail;
hy&mtail;; and a&llbar; &thorn;at har&dtail; hy&mtail; had grete
mervell here-off.  And be signes &thorn;at &thorn;ai fan&dtail; of
burnyng opo&ntail; his bodie, &thorn;ai knew at a&llbar; &thorn;at he
sai&dtail; was trew. et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
