</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXLV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Gregorio celebranti angeli respondent.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> On a tyme whe&ntail; Saynt Gregur opo&ntail; Pac&hbar; day sang
mes in Rome, in Sancta Maria Maiori, and say&dtail;, " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pax Domini,</FOREIGN>" et c&curl;, Aungels of ou&rtail;
Lorde ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; and say&dtail;; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Et cum spiritu tuo.</FOREIGN>" And herefo&rtail; &thorn;e
pope at &thorn;at kur&ktee; ordan&dtail; &thorn;e stacio&ntail;
vppo&ntail; Pac&hbar; day.  And in witnes here-of, whe&ntail; &thorn;e
pope synges &thorn;er o&ntail; &thorn;at day and says, " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pax Domini,</FOREIGN>" &thorn;er ansswer&dtail; no body
hy&mtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXLVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Gula aliquando in peccatum carnis innocentes
inducit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Petrus Damianus tellis how o&ntail; a tyme as a monke bare
frye&dtail; fruturs in-to &thorn;e fratur, he was prikki&dtail; with
glotonny, and onone he withdrew one of &thorn;aim, &amp; keste it in
his mouthe, &amp; ete it privalie at none of his neghburs saw.  And
onone after he was streky&ntail; with a luste of his flessc&hbar;, at
he labur&dtail; hy&mtail; selfe in suc&hbar; for&mtail; as he
di&dtail; neuer befo&rtail;, vnto so muche, at with his aw&ntail; hand
fretyng he had a pollucio&ntail; of his sede.  And so after &thorn;e
morse&llbar; at he stale, onone &thorn;e fende entir&dtail; in-to
hy&mtail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Gulam refrenare expedit.  Supra de Episcopo et

Abbate.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Gulosi cibum sumunt sine benediccione et puniuntur.

Supra de benediccione.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>

<PB N="239">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXLVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Gulosi in cibarijs vetitis
<NOTE ID="P239.N1">MS. vetidis.</NOTE> contra deum vtuntur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;er was som tyme a wurthie ma&ntail;
&thorn;at hight Otto de Normu[n]borgis <NOTE ID="P239.N2">Harl. MS. Normanburgis.</NOTE> ,
&thorn;at made grevus accions ayeyns his neghburs; and sodanlie he was
streke&ntail; with a grete sekenes, and he had a passan&dtail;
pay&ntail; &thorn;er-with, ffor a&llbar; lentre&ntail; tyme he had
suc&hbar; ane appetite to ete fless&hbar;, at he wol&dtail; not
alonelie hol&dtail; hy&mtail; contente in etyng &thorn;erof hy&mtail;
selfe, bod also he compelli&dtail; a&llbar; at was aboute hy&mtail; to
do &thorn;e same.  And whe&ntail; he had done so a&llbar; &thorn;e
lentre&ntail;, and Gude Fryday come, his meneya spakk vnto hy&mtail;
&amp; say&dtail;; "Sur, &thorn;is day is Gude Friday, &amp; &thorn;e
day of &thorn;e passio&ntail; of ou&rtail; Lor&dtail;, and &thorn;is
day christe&ntail; me&ntail; liffis in abstinence; &amp;
&thorn;erfo&rtail; it is not lefu&llbar; to eat fless&hbar; as
&thorn;is day."  And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;;
"This day I sa&llbar; ete ffless&hbar; as I hafe done
hedirtowar&dtail;."  And so he di&dtail;.  And o&ntail; &thorn;e
Pac&hbar; day it happen&dtail; mervaluslie with hy&mtail;, for
whe&ntail; other trew cryste&ntail; peple ete fless&hbar;, evy&ntail;
be &thorn;e dome of almighti Go&dtail; he tuke suc&hbar; ane vgsomnes
with fless&hbar;, &thorn;at he mot not eate it, bod ete fyss&hbar;.
&amp; so he di&dtail; euer whils he liffi&dtail; after.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXLVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Gule peccatum quam detestabile sit visibiliter deus
ostendit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;er was som tyme monkes &thorn;at war
prestis, and opo&ntail; &thorn;e fastynggang evy&ntail; &thorn;ai satt
etan&dtail; &amp; drynkan&dtail; in a prest howse vnto mydnyght; and
at mydnight &thorn;ai satt sti&llbar; &amp; ete o&ntail; as &thorn;ai
had nevur ety&ntail; a morse&llbar;.  And so whe&ntail; cokkis krew
&amp; &thorn;ai war bow&ntail; at ryse, &thorn;e gudema&ntail; of
&thorn;e howse say&dtail;; "Yit we wi&llbar; not parte or we ete
somwhatt."  &amp; he bad his servan&dtail; feche &thorn;aim a <NOTE ID="P239.N3"><HI REND="i">After</HI> a, rosti&dtail;, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> he&ntail;, "&thorn;e beste at &thorn;ou fyndis
sittan&dtail; next &thorn;e kok&ktee;, &amp; sla hur &amp; roste
hur."  And he went &amp; fechi&dtail; hur, &amp; slew hur &amp;
skaldi&dtail; hur &amp; oppen&dtail; hur.  And whe&ntail; he putt in
his han&dtail;







<PB N="240">

att draw hur, he went he had drawe&ntail; furt&hbar; a&llbar; hur
guttis, &amp; he drew oute a gre[te] whik tade.  And with &thorn;at he
gaff a grete cry; and &thorn;ai come a&llbar; &amp; luke&dtail; whatt
hy&mtail; ayle&dtail;.  And he lete &thorn;aim se; and whe&ntail;
&thorn;ai saw att &thorn;e he&ntail;-bowels was turny&dtail; in-to a
whik tade, &thorn;ai vnder-stude at &thorn;ai had servi&dtail;
&thorn;e Devu&llbar; &amp; displesi&dtail; Go&dtail;, &amp; &thorn;ai
were a&llbar; confusi&dtail; &amp; went &thorn;er ways. et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXLIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Gula impedit hominem ne penitentiam sibi
iniunctam proficiat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;er was o&ntail; a tyme, in &thorn;e
bisshoppryk of Colay&ntail;, a certa&ntail; meneya of knyghtis
&thorn;at was att grete were with a grete lor&dtail;.  &amp; &thorn;ai
gader&dtail; &thorn;aim samen in-to a strang place &amp;
harnessi&dtail; &thorn;aim, &amp; tuke &thorn;e keyis &amp; gaff
&thorn;aim vnto ane of &thorn;er servandis, att &thorn;ai went had
bene a trew ma&ntail;.  And &thorn;is servan&dtail; went &amp;
agrei&dtail; with his maisters enmys, &amp; made &thorn;ai[m]
co&mtail; at mydday, whe&ntail; &thorn;e knyghtis was o&ntail; slepe;
and he oppyn&dtail; &thorn;e yatis &amp; lete &thorn;aim co&mtail; in,
and gaff &thorn;aim his maisters swerdis <NOTE ID="P240.N1">MS. swerders.</NOTE> .  And
&thorn;ai come o&ntail; &thorn;aim &amp; slew &thorn;aim.  So
afterwar&dtail; &thorn;is wrichi&dtail; traytur was compuncte, &amp;
forthoght his dede; &amp; he wente vnto &thorn;e pope &amp; shrafe
hy&mtail;, and tuke his penance.  And ofte sithes he brakk his
penance, and euer he went vnto &thorn;e popis penytawnser agay&ntail;,
&amp; tolde hy&mtail;.  So o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;e penitawncer wax
wery o&ntail; hy&mtail;, and he aski&dtail; hy&mtail; if &thorn;er war
any thyng &thorn;at hy&mtail; selfe wol&dtail; grawnt to doo for
penance.  And he sai&dtail;, yis, he mott neuer ete garlyk&ktee;.
And his confessur bad hy&mtail; go home, &amp; eniony&dtail; hy&mtail;
for his penans &thorn;at he sulde neuer whils he liffi&dtail; eatt
garlyk&ktee;; &amp; he grawnti&dtail; &thorn;erto and went home.  So
o&ntail; a tyme afterwar&dtail;, hy&mtail; happen&dtail; co&mtail;
in-to a gart&hbar; &thorn;er garlyk&ktee; grew, &amp; he bega&ntail;
to hafe a liste to eatt &thorn;eroff, and he durste not neg&hbar; itt.
So o&ntail; a noder tyme he come vnto &thorn;e same gart&hbar;, &amp;
he had suc&hbar; a luste vnto &thorn;is garlyk&ktee;, &thorn;at he
brakk his penance &amp; tuke &thorn;eroff, &amp; ete it raw, &thorn;at
befo&rtail; he myght nowder ete raw nor sode&ntail;.  And belife



<PB N="241">

after hy&mtail; for <NOTE ID="P241.N1">for, <HI REND="i">omitted and added above the line</HI>.</NOTE> -thoght itt, &amp; went
vnto &thorn;e penytawnser &amp; tol&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; he with
grete indignacio&ntail; putt hy&mtail; fro&mtail; hy&mtail;, &amp;
wol&dtail; enioy&ntail; hy&mtail; no mo&rtail; penans, bod
reprovi&dtail; hy&mtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCL.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Gula religiosos aliquando decipit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a mon&ktee; of
Ceustus ordur, and hy&mtail; happen&dtail; be made a bisshop&ptail;,
and afterwar&dtail; a cardina&llbar;.  So o&ntail; a tyme hy&mtail;
happen&dtail; to ride, &amp; emang a&llbar; &thorn;e felashi&ptail;
&thorn;at was with hy&mtail; he spak vnto a mon&ktee; &thorn;at was
bod lightlie letter&dtail;, &amp; sai&dtail;; "Te&llbar; vs now
so&mtail; gude wur&dtail; or so&mtail; gude tale as we ride."  And he
excusi&dtail; hy&mtail; faste, &amp; sai&dtail; he cuthe nott; &amp;
be no mene cuthe he gytt excusi&dtail;.  So at &thorn;e laste he
bega&ntail; att te&llbar;, &amp; sai&dtail; vnto &thorn;is
cardyna&llbar;; "When we sha&llbar; be dea&dtail; &amp; broght into
paradice, &thorn;a&ntail; sa&llbar; Saynt Benett co&mtail; &amp; take
vs in, &thorn;at er culli&dtail; with grete ioy &amp; myrt&hbar;.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; he sa&llbar; speke vnto &thorn;e, &thorn;at is a
bissho&ptail; &amp; a cardyna&llbar;, &amp; say, 'Whatt erte
&thorn;ou?'  And &thorn;ou sa&llbar; ansswer agay&ntail; &amp; say,
'ffathur, I a&mtail; a monke of Ceustus ordur.'  And he [sa&llbar;
say] <NOTE ID="P241.N2">MS. sai&dtail;.</NOTE> , 'Nay, &thorn;at erte &thorn;ou nott;
ffor a monke is nott so gaylie araye&dtail; as &thorn;ou erte.'  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ou sa&llbar; alege many thyngis for &thorn;e.
And &thorn;a&ntail; sa&llbar; Saynt Benett giff a sentance, &amp;
bi&dtail; &thorn;e porters oppy&ntail; &thorn;i bodye &amp; luke what
at &thorn;ai fyn&dtail; &thorn;er-in; 'and if ye fyn&dtail; &thorn;ar
cale &amp; peas &amp; benys, &amp; no noder meatt, latt hy&mtail;
co&mtail; in with &thorn;e monkis: &amp; if ye fynde &thorn;erin grete
ffiss&hbar;, or delicatt meatis, lat hy&mtail; stand &thorn;eroute.'
What may &thorn;ou &thorn;a&ntail; say, &thorn;at now faris so wele, and we
fa&rtail; so i&llbar;?"  So &thorn;is Cardina&llbar; smyli&dtail;,
&amp; commendi&dtail; hy&mtail; for his gude tale.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Gulosi in morte a demone
degluciuntur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Grego&rtail; tellis of a mon&ktee; &thorn;at hight
Theodorus, &thorn;at euer feny&dtail; hy&mtail; as he had liffid in
grete abstinens, &amp; in priuatie be hy&mtail; selfe, he wol&dtail;
evur eate whe&ntail; hy&mtail; liste.  So hy&mtail; happen&dtail; to
fa&llbar;





<PB N="242">

seke, &amp; was bow&ntail; at dye.  And sodanlie he bega&ntail; to
cry, &amp; say&dtail; &thorn;at &thorn;e devu&llbar; in liknes of a
drago&ntail; swalo&dtail; hy&mtail; han&dtail; &amp; fute, &amp; put
his hede in his mouthe, and swelu&dtail; his sawle.  And evy&ntail; in
&thorn;is saying he deyi&dtail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Habitus religionis aliquando a deo inuenitur.

Supra Dominici.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Habitus monachalis apostate contrito morienti eciam

post mortem a deo redditur.  Supra de

apostatis et infra de voluntate.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Hereticus recipiscens a combustione
liberatur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis &thorn;at in &thorn;e cetie of Attrabicens
o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;er was taky&ntail; many heretikis; and for
drede of dead &thorn;ai forsuke &thorn;er fals title.  And &thorn;ai
wi&llbar; prufe &thorn;aim with a hate burnyng yr&ntail;, &amp;
&thorn;ai &thorn;at war foun giltie war burny&dtail;.  And emangis
&thorn;aim &thorn;er was a wurthi cler&ktee;, and &thorn;e
bisshop&ptail; entreti&dtail; hy&mtail; to lefe his heresie, and do
penans &thorn;erfo&rtail;.  And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
say&dtail;, he knew wele he had erri&dtail;, bod it was to late to do
penaunce.  And &thorn;e bissho&ptail; ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;, &thorn;at verray penans was neuer done
ouer late.  So &thorn;ai calli&dtail; a preste, &amp; he
confessi&dtail; hy&mtail; of a&llbar; hys synys; &amp; &thorn;e hate
yr&ntail; was in his han&dtail;, and be &thorn;e vertue of
confessio&ntail;, a&llbar; &thorn;e hete of &thorn;e yr&ntail;
vanysshi&dtail; away, &amp; &thorn;er it had burny&dtail; hy&mtail;,
sodanlie it heli&dtail; agay&ntail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai
broght hy&mtail; befo&rtail; &thorn;e iuge, &amp; tolde hy&mtail;
&thorn;e matir, &amp; lete hy&mtail; se how his han&dtail; was
byrny&dtail; &amp; sodanlie in his confessio&ntail; heli&dtail;
agay&ntail;.  And &thorn;us he was savi&dtail;, and a&llbar; &thorn;e
toder war dampne&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Hereticus per contricionem a pena liberatur, et
recidiuus eciam in penam relabitur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis &thorn;at in &thorn;e cetie of Argentyne &thorn;er
was ane heretike, at was purseyvu&dtail; be burnyng with a hate
yr&ntail;; bod he renayi&dtail;

<PB N="243">

&amp; shrafe hy&mtail;, &amp; tuke his penance.  And whe&ntail; he had
done, his wyfe chiddi&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "O &thorn;ou
vnhappye ma&ntail;! Whatt hase &thorn;ou done?  For &thorn;ou sulde
titter hafe putt &thorn;i bodie in a hondret&hbar; fyris,
&thorn;a&ntail; for to recede away fro so provi&dtail; a faithe."  And
so be fals cownce&llbar; of his wife, he turny&dtail; agay&ntail; vnto
his fals error &thorn;at he was in befo&rtail;.  And onone he was
take&ntail;, &amp; &thorn;e hate yr&ntail; lay&dtail; in his
han&dtail;, and it burny&dtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; his wife was
burny&dtail; also hir handis, evy&ntail; vnto &thorn;e har&dtail;
bonys.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai war latty&ntail; go, &amp;
&thorn;a&rtail; handis war so sore at &thorn;ai might not forbere
crying; &amp; &thorn;ai durst not cry in &thorn;e cetie for
purseyvyng, &amp; &thorn;ai went vnto &thorn;e wuddis.  &amp;
&thorn;er &thorn;ai war so turment with &thorn;er burnyng, at
&thorn;ai crye&dtail; and yowli&dtail; as &thorn;ai had bene wulvis,
vnto so meku&llbar;, at &thorn;ai of &thorn;e cetie fan&dtail;
&thorn;aim &amp; broght &thorn;aim home, &amp; keste &thorn;aim bothe
in a grete fyre.  An&dtail; onone &thorn;ai war burny&dtail; vp&ptail;
vnto verray ass&hbar;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Hereticus pretermittens formam non baptizat.  Supra

de baptismo.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Herodis Agrippe.  Supra de Augurrio.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Herodis nequicia.  Infra de nequicia.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Hillarij.  De vita eius.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in his Legen&dtail;, how &thorn;at a pope &thorn;at hight
Leo was dampni&dtail; of heresye, and he gadur&dtail; samen to a
cownce&llbar; a&llbar; &thorn;e bisshop&ptail;[is].  And &thorn;is
Hillarius come to &thorn;is cownce&llbar; vncalli&dtail;; and &thorn;e
pope har&dtail; te&llbar; att he come, &amp; warny&dtail; at no
ma&ntail; sulde rise nor giff hy&mtail; rowme.  And whe&ntail; he come
in, &thorn;e pope sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "&thorn;ou erte Hillarie
&amp; a Frawnc&hbar;e ma&ntail;!"  And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail;
&amp; sai&dtail;; "I a&mtail; no Franche ma&ntail;, bod I a&mtail;
bissho&ptail; of France."  And &thorn;e pope ansswer&dtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "And I a&mtail; Leo, &thorn;e pope, and
a iustis."  And Hillarius ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
say&dtail;; "Thuff a&llbar; &thorn;ou be Leo, yitt &thorn;ou erte
noght of &thorn;e trybe of Iuda; &amp; &thorn;uff a&llbar; &thorn;ou
be a iustis, yitt &thorn;ou sittis no&yogh;t in &thorn;e seate of
magestie."  Tha&ntail; &thorn;e pope wex wrothe, &amp; sai&dtail;;
"Bide a while

<PB N="244">

vnto I co&mtail; agay&ntail;, and I sa&llbar; giff &thorn;e att
&thorn;ou adlis."  And with &thorn;at he rase &amp; went his ways.
And Hillarius sayde; "And &thorn;ou co&mtail; not agay&ntail;, who
sha&llbar; answer for the?"  And he answer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
say&dtail;; "Dowte not I sa&llbar; co&mtail; agay&ntail; onone, and
meke a&llbar; &thorn;i pride."  And he went vnto a seage, &amp; sett
hy&mtail; dow&ntail; &thorn;er-o&ntail; to ease hy&mtail;.  And
&thorn;er he fe&llbar; in-to suche a flux, &thorn;at a&llbar; his
bowels ra&ntail; oute att his hynderhen&dtail;.  And &thorn;er he
deye&dtail; in grete myserie.  And in &thorn;e mea&ntail; while
&thorn;is Hillarius saw att no ma&ntail; rase vnto hy&mtail;, and
mekelie he sett hy&mtail; dow&ntail; opo&ntail; &thorn;e erthe &amp;
sayde; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Domini est terra,</FOREIGN>" et c&curl;.
And onone, &thorn;urg&hbar; &thorn;e ordinance of allmighti
God&dtail;, &thorn;e erthe att he satt oppo&ntail; rase vp&ptail; als
hy as &thorn;e toder bisshoppis satt att was aboute hy&mtail;.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; come tythandis at &thorn;e pope was myserablie
dea&dtail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is Hillarie rase, &amp;
confermy&dtail; a&llbar; &thorn;ies bisshoppis in &thorn;e trew
fayt&hbar;.  &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; he wente home agay&ntail; in-to his
aw&ntail; bisshoprykk.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Hirundo singulis annis eadem loca
repetit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how <NOTE ID="P244.N1">MS. ho&mtail;.</NOTE> so&mtail; tyme
&thorn;er was a husban&dtail;-ma&ntail;, &thorn;at had bygan&dtail; in
his howse euer-ilk yere many swalows.  So at tyme of &thorn;e yere
whe&ntail; &thorn;ai wer bow&ntail; att goo, he tuke ane of &thorn;e
ol&dtail; swalows, &amp; he wrate a by&llbar; with &thorn;ir wurdis
&thorn;er-in; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">O Irundo <NOTE ID="P244.N2">MS. Irunde.</NOTE> !
vbi habitas in yeme?</FOREIGN>" &amp; he ban&dtail; it vnto &thorn;e
fute &thorn;er-of, &amp; lete hur goo; for he knew be experiens
&thorn;at sho wol&dtail; co&mtail; agay&ntail; &thorn;e nexte yere.
And so sho flow hur wais with other in-to &thorn;e lande of Asie;
&amp; &thorn;er sho biggi&dtail; in a howse a&llbar; wynter.  And so
&thorn;is gude ma&ntail; of &thorn;e howse o&ntail; a tyme
behel&dtail; hur.  And he tuke &thorn;is bur&dtail;, &amp;
lowsi&dtail; &thorn;e bi&llbar;, &amp; luki&dtail; whatt was
&thorn;er-in; &amp; he tuke it away, &amp; wrate a noder of &thorn;ies
wurdis; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">In Asia, in domo Petri.</FOREIGN>" &amp;
he knytt it vnto hur fute, and lete hur go.  And sho come agay&ntail;
att sommer vnto &thorn;is husban&dtail; howse, w&hbar;a&rtail; sho had
bred befo&rtail;; &amp; he tuke hur &amp; lowsi&dtail; &thorn;is
bi&llbar;, &amp; redd it.  &amp; he tol&dtail; &thorn;e storie
&thorn;er-of vnto many me&ntail;, evy&ntail; as it had bene a meracle.





<PB N="245">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Histrionibus nichil est dandum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Gestis Francorum' how Philyp&ptail;, at som tyme was
kyng of France, o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; he saw mynstrallis &amp;
iogullurs hafe gay clothyng &amp; grete giftis giffe&ntail; &thorn;aim
oute of courte; and he promysi&dtail; with a&llbar; his harte,
&thorn;at als lang as he liffi&dtail;, &thorn;er sulde no
mynstra&llbar; were no clothe at lange&dtail; vnto his bak&ktee;.
For, he sai&dtail;, hy&mtail; had levur clethe Criste &thorn;er-with,
or pure me&ntail;, &thorn;a&ntail; for to giff &thorn;aim to
mynstrallis.  "For," he sai&dtail;, "it was no noder to giff to
mynstrals bod for to offyr to fendis."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Histriones aliquando maliciose se
vindicant.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iacobus de Vetriaco tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was ane
abbott of Ceustus ordur; and whe&ntail; he was a monke, he was a
passand har&dtail; ma&ntail;, &amp; a sparan&dtail;.  So hy&mtail;
happyn&dtail; be made hostele&rtail;, to kepe gestis in &thorn;er
ostrie, afo&rtail; he was made abbott.  So o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;er
come vnto &thorn;is abbay o&ntail; a day a mynstra&llbar;, &amp; was
sett in &thorn;e ostrie att dyner.  And &thorn;is monke servi&dtail;
hy&mtail; of passan&dtail; gray brea&dtail;, &amp; thyn <NOTE ID="P245.N1">MS. thyng.</NOTE> potage, &amp; a little salte; &amp; he had no drynk
bod watir.  &amp; at evy&ntail; he was lay&dtail; in a uy&llbar;
bed&dtail;, &amp; a har&dtail;.  And opo&ntail; &thorn;e mor&ntail;
&thorn;is mynstra&llbar; was i&llbar; plesi&dtail;, &amp; vmthoght
hy&mtail; how &thorn;att he mott venge hy&mtail; o&ntail; &thorn;is
monke at had servi&dtail; hy&mtail; so evu&llbar;.  So as he went
furth of his chamber &thorn;er he lay, hy&mtail; happen&dtail; to mete
with &thorn;e abbot, and &thorn;is mynstra&llbar; come vnto hy&mtail;
&amp; haylsi&dtail; hy&mtail;, and sai&dtail;; "My lor&dtail;, I
thanke you &amp; your wurthie covent of grete che&rtail; at I hafe had
here, &amp; of grete coste &thorn;at I hafe take&ntail; of you; ffor
yone gude libera&llbar; monke, your hostley, servi&dtail; me
yistrevy&ntail; at my supper wurthelie, with many dyvers costious mece
of ffiss&hbar;, &amp; I dran&ktee; passan&dtail; gude wyne.  And now,
whe&ntail; at I went, he gaff me a pay&rtail; of new butis, &amp; a
gude payr of new knyvis, and a poynt to hy&mtail; &thorn;aim with."



<PB N="246">

And whe&ntail; &thorn;e abbott had har&dtail; &thorn;is, onone he went
vnto &thorn;e closter, &amp; calli&dtail; &thorn;is monke befo&rtail;
a&llbar; <NOTE ID="P246.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, a&llbar;.</NOTE> his covent, &amp; beti&dtail;
hy&mtail; grevuslie here-fo&rtail;, &amp; putt hy&mtail; furt&hbar; of
his offes for &thorn;is mynstra&llbar; saying, &thorn;uf a&llbar; he
war not wurthi.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Histriones non sunt accusandi.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis how o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;e cetie of Massalience
<NOTE ID="P246.N2">Lat. MSS. Civitas Massiliensis.</NOTE> wol&dtail; suffer no mynstra&llbar; co&mtail;
with-in it, &amp; if any happen&dtail; at co&mtail;, &thorn;ai
wol&dtail; reprufe hy&mtail;.  So &thorn;er was a philosophur, &amp;
he reprovi&dtail; &thorn;aim of &thorn;e cetie &thorn;er-of, &amp;
tolde &thorn;aim &thorn;at &thorn;ai sulde with-in a while hafe war
mynstra&llbar;s &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai war.  And so it
happen&dtail; with-in a while after, &thorn;e cetie was evy&ntail;
fu&llbar; of commo&ntail; womme&ntail;; and &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai
purseyvi&dtail; at it was trew at he tol&dtail; &thorn;aim.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Homagium factum est Diabolo.  Supra de ambicione,

iij. et de amore. iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Honestas est moribus servanda.  Supra de amicicia.

iiij<HI REND="sup">a</HI>. et c&curl;.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Honorem parentibus non exhibentes
puniuntur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a yong ma&ntail;
&thorn;at hight Henrye, &amp; his moder was a wedow &amp; a riche
wommo&ntail;.  So &thorn;is yong ma&ntail; o&ntail; a tyme keste
hy&mtail; to begile his moder, &amp; say&dtail; vnto hur; "Gyff me
a&llbar; &thorn;i gudis, at &thorn;urg&hbar; name of &thorn;aim I may
richelie be mari&dtail; &amp; gett a gude wyfe; and &thorn;ou
sa&llbar; hafe &thorn;aim agay&ntail; whe&ntail; I a&mtail;
mari&dtail;.  An&dtail; in &thorn;e mene while I sa&llbar; honestelie
provide for &thorn;e."  And sho granti&dtail; to hy&mtail;, &amp; gaff
hy&mtail; it.  So belyfe after he was wed&dtail;, and with-in a while
after he was we&dtail;, hys wyfe garte hy&mtail; putt hur oute; &amp;
so sho had nothyng bod att sho beggi&dtail; hur meatt, &amp; evur
whe&ntail; sho come &amp; compleyny&dtail; hur vnto hy&mtail;, he





<PB N="247">

sparri&dtail; his eris &amp; wol&dtail; not here hur.  So o&ntail; a
day he &amp; his wife satt at meat to-gedur and his moder come vnto
his dure &amp; knokki&dtail;, &amp; aski&dtail; meatt for Goddis sake.
And he sai&dtail;; "Lo! yonder is &thorn;e devu&llbar; at cryes at
&thorn;e dure!"  And his moder come in &amp; besoght hy&mtail; to hafe
mercie of hur &amp; giff hur so&mtail; meatt; &amp; he flate with hur
as he had bene wude.  So at &thorn;e laste he bad a childe go feche
&thorn;e reuersio&ntail; of a pulett &thorn;at was sett in a kiste,
&amp; giff hir it.  &amp; &thorn;e childe went &amp; lifte v&ptail;
&thorn;e kiste li&dtail;, &amp; wha&rtail; &thorn;e pullett was
o&ntail; &thorn;e platir he fan&dtail; nothyng bod a wrethy&ntail;
serpent; &amp; he was fer&dtail;, &amp; tol&dtail; his maister what he
saw.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he sente a mayde&ntail; &amp; bad hur go
feche it, &amp; sho come agay&ntail; &amp; was i&llbar; flaye&dtail;,
&amp; tol&dtail; hy&mtail; at sho had sene &thorn;e same.  And he rase
v&ptail; in a wret&hbar; hy&mtail; selfe, &amp; say&dtail;; "&amp;
&thorn;e devu&llbar; lig o&ntail; &thorn;e dubbler, I sa&llbar; go
feche hy&mtail;."  &amp; he lifti&dtail; vp &thorn;e kiste li&dtail;
&amp; stowpy&dtail; vp to take &thorn;e platir.  &amp; &thorn;e
serpent clappi&dtail; aboute his throte, &amp; dubble&dtail;
evy&ntail; aboute his nek&ktee;; &amp; evur as he eatt, sho ete; and
ay &thorn;e more at &thorn;ai labur&dtail; to gett hur lowse, &thorn;e
faster clave sho, vnto so meku&llbar; at his vesage was so
bolny&dtail; at his ene fe&llbar; oute o&ntail; his chekis.  &amp; so
he liffi&dtail; xiij yere &amp; more, blyn&dtail;, &amp; alway
&thorn;is serpent aboute his nek&ktee;.  And he was cari&dtail; vnto
dyvers placis of pylgramege, &amp; cuthe gett no bute.  And his moder
at &thorn;e laste had&dtail; compaciens of his pay&ntail; &amp;
forgaff hy&mtail;, &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; he dye&dtail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Honoratur qui facit quod debet sine accepcione

persone.  Supra Ambrosij.  ij<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Honorandi sunt parentes in secreto, sed non in
publico.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Helinandus <NOTE ID="P247.N1">MS. Heliandus.</NOTE> tellis of ane &thorn;at hight
Taurus, &thorn;at was rewler of &thorn;e cetie of Athenys.  So
o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;e prince of Crete come vnto Athenys, &amp;
broght with hy&mtail; his so&ntail; &amp; his ayre.  And &thorn;is
Taurus desyri&dtail; &thorn;aim to co&mtail; dyne with hy&mtail;,
&amp; so &thorn;ai di&dtail;.  &amp; he ba&dtail; &thorn;e



<PB N="248">

fadur sytt hy&mtail; dow&ntail;, and &thorn;e fadur bad his so&ntail;
sit dow&ntail; furste, for cauce at he had a gouernans &amp; a
maistershu&ptail; of &thorn;e pepu&llbar; at Rome.  And &thorn;a&ntail;
Taurus saye&dtail; vnto &thorn;e prince; "Sit &thorn;ou furste
dow&ntail; befo&rtail; &thorn;i so&ntail; vnto we examy&ntail;
&thorn;e cauce, whethir is wurthi to sit aboue att the table, &thorn;e
fathur or &thorn;e so&ntail;."  And whe&ntail; he was sett, &thorn;ai
sett a chayr &thorn;a&ntail; for his so&ntail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; Taurus
say&dtail; to &thorn;aim at satt abowte; "In oppe&ntail; placis, &amp;
&thorn;er &thorn;e so&ntail; hathe a reule, or a maistershup&ptail;,
or a gouernans abow&ntail; &thorn;e fadur, &thorn;er it is
seman&dtail; &thorn;at &thorn;e fathur suffer &thorn;e so&ntail; to
hafe a prioritie.  Bod att home, or in o&thorn;er privan placis, or in
gude felowshup&ptail; wha&rtail; &thorn;ai walk samen, or etis samen
or sittis samen, &thorn;er sul&dtail; a&llbar; publica&llbar; honor
and wurshu&ptail; sese betwix &thorn;e fadur &amp; &thorn;e so&ntail;,
&amp; &thorn;er sul&dtail; natura&llbar; curtasy &amp; honor be
kepi&dtail;: &thorn;at is to say, &thorn;a&rtail; &thorn;e so&ntail;
sul&dtail; wurshu&ptail; &thorn;e fadur or &thorn;e mother, &amp; lett
for no thyng."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Honorande sunt reliquie sanctorum.  Infra de

reliquijs.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Honore exhibito cor hominis eleuatur et superbit.

Supra de augurrio.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Honorandi sunt sancti in cantu secundum merita

sua.  Infra Thome martiris.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">
<NOTE ID="P248.N1">This heading has been transposed from Tale CCCLXII, and the heading of Tale CCCLXI to CCCLXII; Saint Martin is the 'hospes' of Antisiodorens in the Lat. MSS., which, however, follow the same order of headings as that of the Eng. MS.</NOTE>Honorant se mutuo
<NOTE ID="P248.N2">MS. nutuo.</NOTE> sancti.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in &thorn;e 'Life of &thorn;e Hermett Saynt Paule' how
o&ntail; a tyme Saynt Anto&ntail; come to luke how he di&dtail;, &amp;
he resayvi&dtail; hy&mtail; wurshupfullie.  So at tyme of day
whe&ntail; &thorn;ai sul&dtail; go to meatt, a rave&ntail; come &amp;
broght hy&mtail; ij smale lavis.  And Saynt Anto&ntail; had
merve&llbar; here-of; and &thorn;a&ntail; Saynt Paule say&dtail; vnto
hy&mtail;; "Almighti God euer-ilk day hase servi&dtail; me &thorn;us,
and &thorn;is day He dubbles itt for &thorn;i sa&ktee;e."  And &thorn;a&ntail;
betwix &thorn;aim &thorn;er was a meke






<PB N="249">

stryfe whethur of &thorn;aim sul&dtail; blis &thorn;e brede; and Paule
ba&dtail; his oste do it, &amp; he bad hy&mtail; do itt.  So at
&thorn;e laste &thorn;ai put bothe &thorn;er handis &thorn;erto &amp;
did it to-gedur; an&dtail; &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai parti&dtail;
&thorn;e brede evy&ntail; betwix &thorn;aim.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Honorandi sunt hospites. et c&curl;.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; &thorn;e Normondis
destroyi&dtail; France, the bodie of Saynt Marty&ntail; was translatt
vnto &thorn;e cetie of Antysiodorence; and &thorn;er, for grete
mervals &amp; meracles at it di&dtail;, &thorn;er was grete
offran&dtail; made therto.  So &thorn;er fe&llbar; a grete debate
be-twix &thorn;e me&ntail; off Turans <NOTE ID="P249.N1">St. Martin's body had been translated from Tours; St. German's remains were at Antisiodorens=Auxerre.</NOTE> &amp; of
Antisiodorens, for skiftyyng of &thorn;is money betwix &thorn;aim.  So
&thorn;ai made a counan&dtail;, at &thorn;ai sul&dtail; take a lepre
ma&ntail; &amp; lay hy&mtail; a&llbar; nyght betwix &thorn;e bonys of
Saynt&curl; Marty&ntail; &amp; Saynt Germa&ntail;, at luke be vertue
of whe&thorn;er of &thorn;aim he was cury&dtail;, &amp; &thorn;ai to
hafe &thorn;e money; and so &thorn;ai di&dtail;.  &amp; o&ntail;
&thorn;e mor&ntail;, whe&ntail; &thorn;ai come &amp; luki&dtail;
hy&mtail;, &thorn;at side at was next Saynt Marty&ntail; was
curi&dtail; &amp; hale, &amp; &thorn;e tother syde was lepre; &amp;
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai turny&dtail; &amp; lay&dtail; &thorn;e sare
syde to Saynt Martynwar&dtail;, &amp; &thorn;e hale syde vnto
Saynt&curl; Germa&ntail;war&dtail;.  And o&ntail; &thorn;e to&thorn;er
mor&ntail; he was hale ouer a&llbar; his bodie.  And &thorn;us
&thorn;e me&ntail; of Turence had &thorn;e offran&dtail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Honorare se mutuo debent omnes eiusdem status.

Infra de Reuerencia.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Honorare.  Horas canonicas necligenter dicentes
puniuntur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;at in ane abbay of Saynt Saluaturs, of
Ceustus ordur, &thorn;er dye&dtail; a damyse&llbar; of &thorn;e age of
x yere or mo&rtail;.  So opo&ntail; a day whe&ntail; a&llbar; &thorn;e
covent of &thorn;e nonnys stude in &thorn;e where at




<PB N="250">

&thorn;er serves, sho come v&ptail; in-to &thorn;e where &amp;
lowti&dtail; u&ptail; vnto &thorn;e altar; &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; sho
went vnto &thorn;e place &thorn;er sho was wunte to sytt in, &amp;
bade &thorn;er sti&llbar; to sho had sai&dtail; evynsang &amp;
commendacio&ntail; of ou&rtail; Ladie.  And att &thorn;e colett sho
bowed dow&ntail; vnto &thorn;e erthe, &amp; whe&ntail; it was done sho
went hur wayis.  So &thorn;er was a noder damyse&llbar; of &thorn;e
same age, &thorn;at hight Margrett, &thorn;at satt next hur; &amp; sho
saw hur &amp; tel&dtail; &thorn;er abbatis a&llbar; at sho had sene,
&amp; [t]he Abbatis bad hur &thorn;at, &amp; scho come agay&ntail;
o&ntail; &thorn;e nexte day, sho sul&dtail; aske hur how it stude with
hur.  And o&ntail; &thorn;e mor&ntail;, at &thorn;e same how&rtail;,
sho come agay&ntail;, and &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is Margrett
say&dtail; vnto hur; "Gude suster Geretrude, fro whens come &thorn;ou,
&amp; what duse &thorn;ou now here at vs whe&ntail; &thorn;ou erte
deade?"  And sho ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Suster,
I come hedur to make satisfaccio&ntail;, for I rowny&dtail; oft sithis
with &thorn;e in &thorn;e where in serves-tyme, &amp; sai&dtail; not
oute &thorn;e wurdis fu&llbar;.  And &thorn;erfo&rtail;, in the same
place &thorn;er I truspasi&dtail;, a&mtail; I commanddi&dtail; to come
&amp; make a sethe.  And &thorn;er-fo&rtail; be &thorn;ou war of
rownyng in &thorn;e where, at &thorn;ou suffer not &thorn;e same
pay&ntail; whe&ntail; &thorn;ou erte deade."  And opo&ntail; &thorn;e
iiij day sho sai&dtail;; "Suster, now I trow &thorn;at I hafe
fulfilli&dtail; my penance, &amp; fro hyne furthe &thorn;ou sa&llbar;
se me no mo&rtail;."  And &thorn;us sho was had vnto hevy&ntail; with
aunge&llbar;-sang.  et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Hore non sunt pretermittende.  Supra Augustini. ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Horas beate Marie Virginis deuote dicentibus
apparebit in hora mortis. et c&curl;.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;at in Spay&ntail;, in ane abbay of
&thorn;e ordur of Ceustus, was &thorn;er a yong mon&ktee; &thorn;at
was passan&dtail; devowte in saying of ou&rtail; Ladie serves &amp;
hur howres, vnto so meku&llbar; &thorn;at not alonelie att euer-ilk
vers, bod at euer-ilk wur&dtail; at he sai&dtail;, he had mynde of
hur; and &thorn;is he vsi&dtail; many day with grete labur.  And
whe&ntail; he ha&dtail; vsi&dtail; &thorn;is xvj yere, hy&mtail;
happen&dtail; fa&llbar; seke and drew to deadwar&dtail;.  And a
bruther of his aski&dtail; hy&mtail; how he di&dtail;,

<PB N="251">

and he sai&dtail;, wele, an&dtail; tol&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;at our
Lady Saynt Marie had visett hy&mtail; &amp; tolde hy&mtail; &thorn;at
he sulde dye opo&ntail; &thorn;e vij day after &thorn;att, and go vnto
hevy&ntail;.  And he tol&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;at our Lady
say&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;, &thorn;at for gude serves &amp; trew at he
had done hur, sho sulde do vnto hy&mtail; &thorn;at sho did neuer vnto
no noder.  And with &thorn;at sho tuke hy&mtail; abowte &thorn;e
nek&ktee; and kissi&dtail; hy&mtail;.  And o&ntail; &thorn;e vij day,
as he tol&dtail; &thorn;aim, he deyi&dtail;, &amp; passi&dtail; vnto
Go&dtail; with a grete sang of angels. et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Hospitalitas libenter exhiberi debet, quia quandoque
Christus in ea recipitur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Gregur tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a
husban&dtail;-ma&ntail; whilk &thorn;at vsi&dtail;, &amp; a&llbar; his
howse-meneya, gretelie to herbar pure fol&ktee;; and he vsi&dtail;
ilk day to hafe att his burde owder pylgrams or pure me&ntail;.  So
o&ntail; a day &thorn;er was a pylgra&mtail; emang &thorn;e pure
me&ntail;, and so as he was wunt to do he servi&dtail; &thorn;aim of
watir; &amp; whe&ntail; he sul&dtail; take &thorn;e lavur &amp;
pow&rtail; watir o&ntail; &thorn;is pylgra&mtail; handis, sodanlie he
was away.  And he luki&dtail; abowte for hy&mtail;, &amp; cuthe not
fyn&dtail; hy&mtail;; and he had grete merve&llbar; here-off.  And
&thorn;e same night whe&ntail; he was in his be&dtail;, almighti
Go&dtail; apperi&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "Other dayes
&thorn;ou hase reseyvi&dtail; me in my membrys, and yisterday
&thorn;ou receyvi&dtail; [me] to &thorn;ine hoste in myne aw&ntail;
perso&ntail;." et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Hospitalitatis gratia soluendum est interdum
ieiunium.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cassianus tellis how o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; he &amp; other war
samen in &thorn;e lan&dtail; of Egipte, &thorn;ai fasti&dtail; not
o&ntail; &thorn;e Fryday.  And so &thorn;er was certay&ntail; persons
&thorn;at aski&dtail; hy&mtail;, whi he an&dtail; his felowship&ptail;
brak &thorn;er faste so as &thorn;ai di&dtail;.  An&dtail; he
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "I faste always, for I
hafe not halfe meate enog&hbar;; &amp; &thorn;erfo&rtail;,

<PB N="252">

be way of charite, &amp; for to gar my felows eate at &thorn;ai be
strong to do &thorn;er pylgramege, I breke my faste to make &thorn;aim at
eate whe&ntail; &thorn;ai wol&dtail; nott."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Hospitalitas subtracta eciam bona temporalia
aliquando subtrahit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how som tyme ther was ane Abbott of &thorn;e Blak
Ordur, &thorn;at was passan&dtail; mercefu&llbar; in hospitalitie,
&amp; anence pure me&ntail;.  And he helde servandis evy&ntail;
therefo&rtail;, &amp; ay &thorn;e more att he gaff in hospitalitie or
to pure me&ntail;, ay &thorn;e mo&rtail; God blissi&dtail; his howse,
and multiplied &thorn;e gudis &thorn;erof.  So hy&mtail; happend to
dye.  And after his dea&dtail;, his successur was covatus, &amp; he
putt oute &thorn;ies offisurs at his predecessur had ordan&dtail; to
do warkis of mercy.  And &thorn;e charitie at was giffe&ntail; vnto
pure me&ntail; in &thorn;e toder abbott dayes, he withdrew itt, and
herefo&rtail; almighti God with-drew His han&dtail;; &amp; he put in
offisurs at war hard &amp; strayte, &amp; wal&dtail; vse none
hospitalitie, for he say&dtail; it was ane vndiscrete defawte.  And
with-in a while his cornys fayli&dtail;, so &thorn;at he &amp; his
brethir had skantlie at &thorn;ai myght eate.  So vppo&ntail; a day a
ma&ntail; happend att co&mtail; &amp; aski&dtail; hospitalitie, and
&thorn;e porter tuke hy&mtail; in privalie, &amp; with grete ferdnes,
of suche litti&llbar; meat as he had with-in hy&mtail;, he
servi&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "Now it is so
&thorn;at I may serve &thorn;e of na bettyr meatt, &thorn;uff a&llbar;
I hafe som tyme sene in &thorn;is place &thorn;at, &amp; a greate
bisshop&ptail; had comme&ntail; hedur, he sulde hafe bene
reseyvi&dtail; with greate habundans &amp; plentet&hbar;."  And
&thorn;is pure <NOTE ID="P252.N1"><HI REND="i">After</HI> pure, p, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> ma&ntail; ansswer&dtail;
hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Two brether er putt oute of
&thorn;is place, and &thorn;e tone was calli&dtail; Dare, and &thorn;e
toder Dabitur; and vnto &thorn;ies two co&mtail; agay&ntail; sa&llbar;
neuer plentie nor welt&hbar;e be in &thorn;is monasterie."  And with
&thorn;att, sodanly he vanysshe&dtail; oute of his sight.  And
&thorn;is porter went vnto &thorn;e abbott &amp; &thorn;e covent, and
tol&dtail; &thorn;aim.  And &thorn;ai tuke &thorn;aim to cownce&llbar;
att &thorn;ai wal&dtail; resume hospitalite, &amp; giff almos
agay&ntail; as &thorn;ai war wunte.  And so &thorn;ai



<PB N="253">

di&dtail;; and onone almighti God blissi&dtail; &thorn;aim, &amp;
&thorn;ai had als gude plentie as evur &thorn;ai had afor of
cor&ntail; &amp; a&llbar; o&thorn;er gudes.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Hospites sunt honorandi.  Supra de honore. ij &amp; iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Hospitalitas eciam bona temporalia
conservat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Sigilbertus tellis how a tow&ntail; &thorn;at hight Anthiochia was
subuerty&dtail; be &thorn;e sande of Go&dtail;, and be &thorn;is maner
of wyse.  The&rtail; was a cetysyne &thorn;erof &thorn;at was so
giffe&ntail; vnto hospitalite and almos-dede, to so meku&llbar;
&thorn;at he wolde neuer day eate with-oute a pure ma&ntail; or a
geste.  So o&ntail; a day hy&mtail; happen&dtail; go &thorn;urg&hbar;
&thorn;e cetie to it was nyght, to se&ktee;e owde&rtail; a pure
ma&ntail; or a geste to eate with hy&mtail;, and he cuthe fyn&dtail;
none.  So att &thorn;e laste he fan&dtail; a fayr olde ma&ntail;
standyng, &amp; two felos with hy&mtail;, in &thorn;e myddeste of
&thorn;e cetie.  And he prayed &thorn;aim co&mtail; &amp; be his
hostis &amp; eate with hy&mtail;; and <NOTE ID="P253.N1">Harl. MS. Hoc responsum accepit ab eo; "Non poteras, o homo Dei, cum vostro Simeone hanc urbem saluare ne subuerteretur?"</NOTE> he
ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; in &thorn;is maner of wyse &amp; sai&dtail;;
"O, &thorn;ou ma&ntail; of Go&dtail;! &thorn;ou may not with our
Symon&dtail; safe &thorn;is cetie at it be not subuerti&dtail;."  And
with &thorn;at he keste &thorn;e sudurye at he hel&dtail; in his
han&dtail; opo&ntail; &thorn;e tone halfe of &thorn;e cetie, &amp;
onone &thorn;at halfe &amp; a&llbar; &thorn;e howsis &thorn;erof &amp;
&thorn;ai &thorn;at dwelte in &thorn;aim was destroye&dtail;.  &amp;
he tuke agay&ntail; his sudarie and wolde hafe caste&ntail; it
o&ntail; &thorn;e toder halfe, and vnnethis his felows myght
restre&ntail; hy&mtail; to spare it; and with &thorn;at he
vanysshi&dtail; away.  And &thorn;is was done, &amp; &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;e ma&ntail; was passan&dtail; fer&dtail; &amp; went home vnto
his howse, &amp; fan&dtail; safe &amp; thanki&dtail; God &thorn;er-of.
et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Hospitalitate aliquando Deus recipitur.  Infra Iuliani.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Hospitalitatis gratia eciam pluries in die
concedendum [est].</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cassianus tellis in &thorn;is maner of wise &amp; says; "Som tyme
&thorn;er was a halie ma&ntail; &thorn;at tuke me to hoste &amp;
refresshi&dtail; me, &amp; spirri&dtail;




<PB N="254">

me &amp; exhorti&dtail; me what I wol&dtail; eate.  And I
answer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail; I myght not eatt.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; he ansswer&dtail; &amp; say&dtail;; '&thorn;is day I
hafe sett &thorn;e bur&dtail; to dyvers brether vij sythes, &amp;
desyri&dtail; &thorn;aim att ete <NOTE ID="P254.N1">Harl. MS. hortansque singulos, cum omnibus cibum sumpsi.</NOTE> , and yit I
a&mtail; hongrie.  And &thorn;ou, at yit ete no &thorn;ing, says now
at &thorn;ou may nott eate.'  And o&ntail; &thorn;is <NOTE ID="P254.N2">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, &thorn;is.</NOTE> maner &thorn;ai war wunt in commyng of &thorn;er
brether for to solve &thorn;er faste, and in refeccio&ntail; of
&thorn;aim &thorn;ai helde it a charitiable contynans." et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLXX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Hospitalitas regnum temporale
confert.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in &thorn;e 'Legen&dtail; of Saynt Germa&ntail; of
Antissiodorens,' how o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; Saynt Germa&ntail;
prechi&dtail; in Britannye, and &thorn;e kyng denye&dtail; hy&mtail; a
benyfice, &thorn;at was to say, meat &amp; dryn&ktee; &amp;
herbe&rtail;.  So &thorn;e kyngis nowte-har&dtail; come home with his
cate&llbar; fro &thorn;er pastur, &amp; tuke provan&dtail; in &thorn;e
kyngis pales to his cate&llbar;, &amp; had it home vnto his
tofa&llbar; at he dwelte in.  And he was war of Saynt Germa&ntail;
&amp; his felos sare laburyng, &amp; war passan&dtail; calde &amp;
hongrie; and he reseyvi&dtail; &thorn;aim buxsomly into his place.
And he had no calfe bod one, &amp; &thorn;at he slew vnto &thorn;er
supper.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai had suppi&dtail;, &thorn;is holie
ma&ntail; gadder&dtail; samen &thorn;e bonys of &thorn;is calfe in
&thorn;e sky&ntail; &thorn;er-of, an&dtail; onone, at his commandment,
&thorn;is calfe rase agay&ntail; whi&ktee;.  And o&ntail; &thorn;e
day next after, he went vnto &thorn;e kyng, and aski&dtail; hy&mtail;
whi he denye&dtail; meat &amp; hospitalitie vnto Saynt Germa&ntail;
&amp; his felows, and &thorn;is kyng was so astony&dtail; &thorn;at he
cuthe not ansswer hy&mtail;.  And with &thorn;at he bad hy&mtail; go
furthe, &amp; lefe his kyngdo&mtail; vnto a better ma&ntail;
&thorn;a&ntail; he was.  And &thorn;a&ntail; Saynt Germa&ntail;, be
&thorn;e commandment of almyghti Go&dtail;, made &thorn;is
nowter&dtail; &amp; his wife to co&mtail; afor&ntail; hy&mtail;; and,
at a&llbar; me&ntail; had wonder of, he made hy&mtail; kyng.  And evur
sethe&ntail;, &thorn;e kynges &thorn;at come of &thorn;e
nowther&dtail; kynre&dtail; hase reingne&dtail; vppo&ntail; &thorn;e
pepu&llbar; &amp; &thorn;e lan&dtail; of Brytany.  et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Hospitalitas non propter Deum facta parum valet.

Infra de intencione.
</FOREIGN>


<PB N="255">
</ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Hospitis curialitate et libertate multi abutuntur.

Supra de detraccione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Hospes male receptus aliquando vindicat se de

