<PB N="256">
</ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Humilitatem ostendere debent religiosi eciam in

persecucione iuris 
<NOTE ID="P256.N1">MS. viris.</NOTE>  sui.  Infra de Religiosis.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLXXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Humilis pacienter conuicia tolerat
<NOTE ID="P256.N2">MS. tollerat.</NOTE>.  et c&curl;.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Grego&rtail; tellis of a holie ma&ntail; &thorn;at hight
Constantinus, &amp; he was passan&dtail; litle of perso&ntail; &amp;
of a feble makyng.  So o&ntail; a tyme a buxtus ma&ntail; come fer fro
vp o lan&dtail; to se hy&mtail;, and whe&ntail; he saw hy&mtail;, at
he was so febu&llbar; &amp; of so little a statur, he trowed not at it
had bene he; notwithstandyng ilk ma&ntail; tolde hy&mtail; at it was
he.  And he dispysi&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; skorny&dtail; hy&mtail;,
&amp; sai&dtail;; "I trowe&dtail; at &thorn;is ma&ntail; had bene a
grete ma&ntail;, and he hase nothyng of a ma&ntail;."  And onone as
&thorn;is holie ma&ntail; har&dtail;, onone he hawsi&dtail; &thorn;is
buxtos ma&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "&thorn;ou alonelie is he &thorn;at
hase had in me &thorn;ine ee&ntail; oppy&ntail; &amp; sene me."  Be
&thorn;e whilk &thorn;ing it is for to trow what meknes he had,
&thorn;at so luffi&dtail; &thorn;is buxtus ma&ntail; &thorn;at
despysi&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; set hy&mtail; at noght befo&rtail;;
ffor be &thorn;e language at was sayd of hy&mtail; myght me&ntail; se
what mekenes he had.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLXXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iacobi Maioris.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in his 'Meracles' how xxx me&ntail; of Lothoringia come
vnto Saynt Iamys, &amp; &thorn;ai a&llbar; bod one made hy&mtail; a
privey athe of serves.  So one of &thorn;aim fe&llbar; seke, &amp; his
felows bade [with] hy&mtail; xv dayes; neuer-&thorn;e-les &thorn;ai
lefte hy&mtail; behyn&dtail; &thorn;aim, and &thorn;er wolde none at
bade with hy&mtail; bod he &thorn;at was not swor&ntail; to kepe
felowshu&ptail;: &amp; he bade with hy&mtail; &amp; kepi&dtail;
hy&mtail; sti&llbar; at &thorn;e fute of &thorn;e Mownt Saynt
Miche&llbar;, &amp; &thorn;er o&ntail; a day he dye&dtail;.  And onone
Saynt Iamys [com] &amp; comfurthi&dtail; &thorn;e whik ma&ntail;.  And
he had a gude hors, &amp; he bad &thorn;is whik man <NOTE ID="P256.N3">MS. may.</NOTE> lay &thorn;e dead ma&ntail; ouerthwarte befo&rtail;
hy&mtail;, &amp; lepe o&ntail; hy&mtail; selfe behyn&dtail; hy&mtail;;
and so he di&dtail;.  And opo&ntail; &thorn;at night &thorn;ai went xv
day iorney and come ad Montem Gaudii, whilk &thorn;at is bod halfe a
lewke fro Saynt Iamys, and &thorn;er &thorn;ai lightid; &amp; he bad
hy&mtail; charge &thorn;e chanons of Saynt Iamys to bery &thorn;is
pilgra&mtail;.  And







<PB N="257">

he bad hy&mtail; te&llbar; his felows &thorn;at, for &thorn;ai had
broke&ntail; &thorn;er faithe, &thorn;er pylgramege was no wurt&hbar;
nor of no valew.  And he did as he was biddy&ntail; &amp; tolde his
felows as Saynt Iamys had chargi&dtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; &thorn;ai had
grete wonder &thorn;eroff.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLXXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iterum Iacobi.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in his 'Meracles' how &thorn;at a Duche-ma&ntail; &amp;
his so&ntail;, abowte &thorn;e yere of ou&rtail; Lor&dtail; M &lbar;
xx, went vnto Saynt Iamys.  And in &thorn;e cetie of Thososti <NOTE ID="P257.N1">Lat. MSS. in urbe Tolosa.</NOTE> a syluer pece was put in his skrip&ptail; <NOTE ID="P257.N2">MS. skip&ptail;</NOTE> privalie, at he wiste not off; and o&ntail; &thorn;e
mor&ntail; &thorn;ai went &thorn;er wayis.  And &thorn;er oste folowed
&thorn;aim &amp; tuke &thorn;aim as thevis; &amp; he oppyn&dtail;
&thorn;er skri&ptail;, &amp; onone he fande &thorn;is syluer pece, and
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai war broght befo&rtail; &thorn;e iuge.  &amp;
onone &thorn;e sentans was giffe&ntail; &thorn;at a&llbar; &thorn;at
&thorn;ai had sulde be giffen vnto &thorn;er oste.  &amp; &thorn;e
tane of &thorn;aim was demyd to be hangi&dtail;, &amp; &thorn;e fadir
wol&dtail; hafe dye&dtail; for &thorn;e so&ntail;, &amp; &thorn;e
so&ntail; for the fadur; bod neuer-&thorn;e-les &thorn;e so&ntail; was
hange&dtail;.  And &thorn;e fadur made grete sorow &amp; went his ways
o&ntail; to Saynt Iamys.  And xxxvj dayes he come agay&ntail;
&thorn;er away, &amp; come vnto &thorn;e galos &thorn;er his so&ntail;
hang, &amp; wepi&dtail; &amp; made mekle sorow.  And his so&ntail;,
&thorn;at hang, spak &amp; bega&ntail; to comfurt&hbar; hy&mtail;,
&amp; sai&dtail;; "Swete fathir!  Wepe noght! ffor it was neuer so
wele to me; ffor Saynt Iamys beris me yit v&ptail;, &amp; fedis me
with hevynlie swetnes."  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e fadur hard &thorn;is,
he ra&ntail; vnto &thorn;e cetie &amp; tolde &thorn;e pepu&llbar; how
it was; and &thorn;ai come &amp; tuke dow&ntail; &thorn;is
pylgre&mtail; so&ntail; hale &amp; sown&dtail;.  &amp; &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;ai tuke his oste &amp; hanged hy&mtail;, whe&ntail; he had
grauntid how he had done.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLXXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iterum Iacobi.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Hugo de Sancto Victore tellis how o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;e
devu&llbar; apperi&dtail;, in liknes of Saynt Iamys, vnto a
pylgra&mtail; &thorn;at was bow&ntail; to Saynt





<PB N="258">

Iamys, &amp; sai&dtail; &thorn;at he sulde be passand happie &amp; so
wer he wolde, for honor of hy&mtail;, sla hy&mtail; selfe.  And he
onone, as he bad hy&mtail;, tuke his swer&dtail; &amp; slew hym selfe
&thorn;er he was hosti&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; his oste fande
hy&mtail;, he was passan&dtail; fer&dtail; to be suspecte for
hy&mtail;.  And with &thorn;at, he &thorn;at was dea&dtail;
turny&dtail; vnto life agay&ntail;, &amp; sai&dtail; &thorn;at
whe&ntail; &thorn;e devu&llbar; wolde hafe drawe&ntail; hy&mtail; vnto
pay&ntail;, Saynt Iamys come and delyver&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; broght
hy&mtail; befo&rtail; a iuge.  And be &thorn;e sentance of &thorn;at
iuge he was restori&dtail; agay&ntail; vnto life, &amp; his
wown&dtail; heli&dtail;, &thorn;at ilk ma&ntail; might se itt.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLXXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iterum Iacobi.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Hugo Clunacensis tellis how o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;er was a yong
ma&ntail; &thorn;at went in pylgramege vnto Saynt Iamys.  And
hy&mtail; happend to do fornicacio&ntail; be &thorn;e way.  And
&thorn;e devu&llbar; apperi&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; in fygur of Saynt
Iame, &amp; reprovid hy&mtail; for his fornicacio&ntail; &amp;
sai&dtail; &thorn;er-fo&rtail; his pylgramege was na wurt&hbar;.  And
he cowncel&dtail; hy&mtail; for Goddis sake and his, to cutt of his
membris and so to ky&llbar; hy&mtail; selfe; and he did so, &amp; was
dead onone.  And onone his sawle was taky&ntail; with fendis; &amp;
&thorn;urg&hbar; &thorn;e merettis &amp; prayers of Saynt Iamys, onone
it was delyver&dtail;, &amp; &thorn;e bodie restori&dtail; agay&ntail;
vnto life and hale, safeyng onelie hy&mtail; wantid his membrys euer
after.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLXXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iactancia maxime iuuenum compescenda est.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Seuerus.  He tellis how o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;er was ij brethir,
&amp; &thorn;at one was of xv yere age, &amp; &thorn;e tother of xij
yere; and as &thorn;ai went samen in wyldernes, &thorn;aim
happen&dtail; mete with a passyng grete neddur.  And &thorn;ai war
bathe me&ntail; of religio&ntail; in ane abbay.  And &thorn;e les of
&thorn;aim tuke vpp &thorn;is nedder in his han&dtail;, &amp;
wappi&dtail; it in his skyrte, and come home &thorn;er-with.
An&dtail; befo&rtail; a&llbar; his brether he

<PB N="259">

putt it oute of his skyrte, &amp; lete &thorn;aim se how &thorn;at it
had hurte hy&mtail; nothyng.  And &thorn;a&rtail; <NOTE ID="P259.N1"><HI REND="i">After</HI> &thorn;a&rtail;, p, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> brether telli&dtail; it ilkone vnto other, &amp;
sai&dtail; it was be fait&hbar; &amp; vertue att Godd had giffe&ntail;
&thorn;aim at it hurte &thorn;aim nott.  So &thorn;er Abbott was a
passan&dtail; wyse ma&ntail;, &amp; &thorn;urg&hbar; grete
cownce&llbar; he tuke a wan&dtail; and skowri&dtail; &thorn;aim bathe,
&amp; blamy&dtail; &thorn;aim &thorn;at &thorn;ai lete &thorn;e vertue at God
had giffe&ntail; vnto &thorn;aim be knawe&ntail;; to &thorn;e entent
&thorn;at &thorn;er yong elde sulde nott wax wanto&ntail; nor prowde,
bod at &thorn;ai sulde rather seryff God in mekenes &thorn;a&ntail;
for to hafe a ioy or a cumfurt&hbar; of suc&hbar; vertue as God had
giffe&ntail; &thorn;aim.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Iactantia in verbis vitanda est.  Infra de

presumpcione.  ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
