<ITEM><FOREIGN>Impetracio.  Impetrat beata Maria vitam eciam dampnatis.  Infra de
Maria.</FOREIGN></ITEM><ITEM><FOREIGN>Impetracioni possunt multa adaptari que dicuntur de
oratione.  iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM><ITEM><FOREIGN>Impetratur peccatoribus gratia oracionibus.
Infra de oratione.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST></P> <PB></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLXXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Indulgencie valent defunctis. et c&curl;.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Legenda Lombardica' how o&ntail; a tyme a legatt of
&thorn;e courte of Rome gatt a grete pardo&ntail; vnto his fadur,
&thorn;at was dea&dtail;, of &thorn;e pope.  And he sent
&thorn;er-with a wurthi knyght in-to the contre of Albygensis to a
kurk &thorn;er his fadur lay; &amp; &thorn;is knyght taryd
&thorn;er-with a&llbar; a lentre&ntail;.  And &thorn;is done,
vppo&ntail; a nyght his fadur apery&dtail; vnto &thorn;is legatt,
clerar &thorn;a&ntail; any light, and thonki&dtail; hy&mtail; hartelie
for his pardo&ntail; at he was delyver&dtail; by.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLXXX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Infamia.  Infamatur aliquis sine culpa.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Heraclides tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a preste &thorn;at
had a doghter, and sho happend to be corrupte &amp; be with childe;
and sho put &thorn;e cryme &thorn;er-of apo&ntail; a deky&ntail;, &amp;
made a lye o&ntail; hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;e bisshop&ptail; &amp;
&thorn;e preste hur fadur sent after hy&mtail;, &amp; inquyred
hy&mtail; &thorn;erof; and he denyed itt.  And &thorn;e bisshop&ptail;
wax wrote &thorn;erwith, and sai&dtail; &thorn;at he was bod a lyer;
and &thorn;e cler&ktee; ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;;
"For suthe, sur, I hafe sayde as it is in my consciens, and ye
wol&dtail; here me now; for it was not I &thorn;at di&dtail; &thorn;is
dede."  And whe&ntail; he had &thorn;us sai&dtail;, &thorn;ai putt
hy&mtail; oute of his dekynshu&ptail;, and garte hy&mtail; wedd hur.
And he commendid hur vnto a monasteri &amp; hy&mtail; selfe was
closi&dtail; v&ptail; in a ce&llbar;; &amp; &thorn;er, with grete
prayers &amp; wepyngis he besoght God at &thorn;e treut&hbar; mott be
knawe&ntail;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e day of hur byrt&hbar; drew
nere, sho trauel&dtail; vij dayes to-gedur, &amp; was hugelie
vexi&dtail; with grete paynys, so meku&llbar; &thorn;at sho mot nowder
eate, nor drink, nor slepe, bod trowed hur selfe verelie at sho sulde
dye.  And sho was passan&dtail; fer&dtail; at sho sulde be
dampny&dtail;, and &thorn;a&ntail; sho bega&ntail; to cry horrible
&amp; say&dtail;; "Wo is me, wriche! for I a&mtail; falle&ntail; into
a dubble peri&llbar;.  Furst, for I hafe loste my maydenhe&dtail;; and
&thorn;e secun&dtail;, I hafe putt a fals cryme vppo&ntail; &thorn;e
Deke&ntail;."  And &thorn;e susters of &thorn;e place har&dtail; hur,
&amp; went to &thorn;er prayers for hur, at God wol&dtail; vuchesafe
at sho mot be

<PB N="262">

delyver; bod it profett nott, vnto so meku&llbar; &thorn;e
bisshop&ptail; sent vnto &thorn;is Deky&ntail; &amp; bad hy&mtail;
pray for hur.  Bod he wolde nott here &thorn;e messangers, nor giff
&thorn;aim none ansswer.  So at &thorn;e laste &thorn;e bissho&ptail;
come vnto hy&mtail; and bad hy&mtail; lowse &thorn;at he had
bu&ntail;.  And at &thorn;e bisshoppis commandment he praye&dtail; for
hur, &amp; onone sho was delyver.  And o&ntail; &thorn;is maner of
wyse &thorn;is deky&ntail; was purgi&dtail; of &thorn;is defame, &amp;
restori&dtail; agay&ntail; vnto his offes.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Infamat aliquando meretrix quos ad peccatum trahere

non potest.  Infra de meretrice.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLXXXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Infamata fama aliquando restituitur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Prudencius tellis in &thorn;e 'Life of Iohannes Damascenus' how at
&thorn;is Iohannes was a passan&dtail; holie ma&ntail; emang his
brethir, &amp; a mayde&ntail;, and passand devowte vnto ou&rtail;
Ladie; and bothe in Grew &amp; in Laty&ntail; he was passandlie wele
lerny&dtail;, in wrytyng &amp; endytyng and syngyng.  So o&ntail; a
tyme hy&mtail; happend be take&ntail; with &thorn;e Sarrazens, and
&thorn;at lor&dtail;, &thorn;at happen&dtail; to hafe hy&mtail; in his
parte, had a so&ntail;.  And &thorn;is Iohannes Damascenus
lerny&dtail; hy&mtail; so in writyng &amp; in endytyng &amp; in
syngyng, and in other &thorn;ingys &thorn;at perteyny&dtail; vnto
&thorn;is sciens, so &thorn;at in writyng, in endytyng, &amp; in
voyce, his werk semy&dtail; no noder bod at it had bene &thorn;is
Iohannes Damascenus his maister.  So the Emperour Theodosius send for
hy&mtail; &amp; payed his rawnso&ntail;, &amp; borow&dtail; hy&mtail;;
&amp; his disciple wol&dtail; hafe gone with hy&mtail;, &amp; he
wol&dtail; not latt hy&mtail;.  And ffor envy here-of this his <NOTE ID="P262.N1">his, <HI REND="i">omitted and added above the line</HI>.</NOTE> disciple, with-in a few yeris after, endity&dtail; a
<NOTE ID="P262.N2"><HI REND="i">After</HI> a, luru, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> lettyr &amp; wrate &thorn;er-in treso&ntail; of
&thorn;e Emperou&rtail;, &amp; how he was in purpos to destroy hys
roal&mtail;; and &thorn;is lettre he garte hafe privalie vnto
Constantynople, &amp; caste it in &thorn;e Emperours pales.  And
onone, as it was fo&ntail; &amp; red&dtail;, &thorn;e maner &amp;
&thorn;e for&mtail; of &thorn;e lettir &amp; of &thorn;e endytyng was
knowe&ntail;, at it was of &thorn;is Iohannes Damascenus.  And
&thorn;e Emperour whe&ntail; he saw it accusi&dtail; hy&mtail;, &amp;
&thorn;er





<PB N="263">

he was take&ntail; &amp; fowle far&ntail; with &amp; calli&dtail;
traytur.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e lettre was shewi&dtail; hy&mtail;,
he ansswer&dtail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "Forsuthe, surs, &thorn;is I knaw
wele is &thorn;e for&mtail; of my wrytyng &amp; of myne endytyng, bod
God I take to witnes &thorn;at I did it noght."  And a&llbar;
me&ntail; wondred &amp; cryed o&ntail; hy&mtail; becauce he wolde not
say &thorn;e treut&hbar; &amp; graunt, &amp; &thorn;ai crye&dtail;
&amp; say&dtail; he was wurthi to dy; &amp; &thorn;er he was broght
befo&rtail; &thorn;e iuges.  And becauce he was &thorn;e
Emperou&rtail; cussy&ntail; &thorn;ai wol&dtail; not deme hy&mtail; to
dy, bod &thorn;ai demy&dtail; at his han&dtail; at he did &thorn;is
trispas with sulde be cutt off.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;is was done, in
reprefe of &thorn;is felony at &thorn;ai trowed &thorn;at he had done,
his hand at was cut off, &thorn;ai hang it in his aw&ntail; kurk.  So
o&ntail; &thorn;e night after, &thorn;is Iohannes Damascenus with a
han&dtail; come befo&rtail; a specia&llbar; ymage of ou&rtail; Lady,
&amp; bari&dtail; his wown&dtail; &amp; shewi&dtail; hur his
ar&mtail;.  And mekelie he flate with hur &amp; sai&dtail; in
&thorn;is maner of wyse; "Behalde, swete lady!  What rewardis is of vs
&thorn;i servandis?  Behol&dtail; ou&rtail; rewar&dtail;!  Lady,
&thorn;ow hase willi&dtail; me, a synner, &thorn;i servan&dtail;, for
my rewar&dtail; to suffre suche a turmentrie, at &thorn;ou sufferd
&thorn;e instrument of &thorn;ine offes for to be &thorn;us cut off.
For &thorn;is han&dtail; at is cutt off wrate oft sythis sangis of
&thorn;i lovyng, &amp; oft sithes sacre&dtail;, &amp; offer&dtail;
&thorn;e fless&hbar; &amp; &thorn;e blude of &thorn;i so&ntail;."  And
whe&ntail; he had &thorn;us made his complaynt &amp; his prayers, he
went vnto his be&dtail;; and as he was halfe slepan&dtail;, halfe
wakan&dtail;, &thorn;e blissi&dtail; mayde&ntail;, our Lady Saynt
Marie, apperid vnto hy&mtail; with grete light &amp; a gude chere,
&amp; sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "My trew childe, what duse
&thorn;ou?"  And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;;
"Allas!  Lady, wharto askis &thorn;ou me?  For rather I sulde aske
&thorn;e wha&rtail; &thorn;ou was whe&ntail; I suffer&dtail;
&thorn;is.  Behal&dtail;, Ladie, how, bathe to &thorn;i shame &amp;
myne, &thorn;i hand of &thorn;i servan&dtail; at was cutt of is
honge&ntail; vp in &thorn;e kurk."  And &thorn;a&ntail; sho
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "So&ntail;, be of gude
comfurt&hbar; in Go&dtail;!"  And &thorn;is sai&dtail;, evy&ntail; att
he myght see, sho went into &thorn;e kur&ktee; &amp; broght his
han&dtail; fro thens, &amp; restori&dtail; it agay&ntail; vnto
&thorn;e ar&mtail; &amp; made it hale.  And he hel&dtail; vp his
handis &amp; thanki&dtail; hur, &amp; with &thorn;at sho
vanysshi&dtail; away.  And o&ntail; &thorn;e mor&ntail; he rase &amp;
calli&dtail; samen his brethyr, &amp; shewi&dtail; &thorn;aim his
han&dtail;; and onone, with a mery voyce &amp; a lowde, he bega&ntail;
ou&rtail; Ladie mes.  And o&ntail; &thorn;e mor&ntail;, whe&ntail;
&thorn;e Emperou&rtail; har&dtail; te&llbar; of &thorn;is meracle,

<PB N="264">

he come o&ntail; his fete vnto hy&mtail; &amp; sett hy&mtail;
dow&ntail; o&ntail; his kneis, and kyssi&dtail; his han&dtail;, and
aski&dtail; hy&mtail; if he knew any &thorn;at had his maner &amp;
for&mtail; of writyng &amp; endityng.  And he tol&dtail; hy&mtail; how
&thorn;at he had lernyd one it; and &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e
treut&hbar; was serchid &amp; it was fo&ntail; who it was.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLXXXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Infans in baptismo loquitur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede ex 'Gestis Beati Amandi' how &thorn;at whe&ntail; &thorn;e
kyng of Fraunce had no chylde, he made a grete prayer vnto
Allmi&yogh;ty Go&dtail;, &amp; Go&dtail; sent hy&mtail; one.  And
whe&ntail; it was bor&ntail;, he vmthoght hy&mtail; whome he mot make
to baptys itt.  And so &thorn;is Amandus come in his mynde &amp; he
made hy&mtail; to baptis it.  And whe&ntail; it was namy&dtail; &amp;
crysten&dtail;, &thorn;e childe ansswer&dtail; &thorn;at a&llbar;
myght here, and sai&dtail;, "Amen!"


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLXXXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Infans vnius diei loquitur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in &thorn;e 'Legend of Symond &amp; Iude' how o&ntail; a
tyme a dukis doghter happen&dtail; to do fornycacio&ntail;, &amp; was
with childe.  And sho putt it vppo&ntail; a deky&ntail;, and hur fadur
tuke &thorn;is deky&ntail; &amp; wolde hafe putt hy&mtail; to
dea&dtail;.  And &thorn;e Apostels Symon&dtail; &amp; Iude askyd
whe&ntail; &thorn;e childe was bor&ntail;, and it was ansswer&dtail;
&thorn;aim &amp; sai&dtail;, &thorn;at same day in &thorn;e mornyng.
And at commandment of &thorn;e apostels, &thorn;is deky&ntail; &amp;
&thorn;is childe was fechi&dtail; afor &thorn;aim.  And &thorn;e
apostels say&dtail; vnto &thorn;is yong chil&dtail;, "In &thorn;e
Name, speke, &thorn;ou yong childe, &amp; te&llbar; if &thorn;is
deky&ntail; did &thorn;is trispas!"  And &thorn;e yong childe
ansswer&dtail; &amp; sai&dtail;, at a&llbar; me&ntail; mot here;
"&thorn;is deky&ntail; fyli&dtail; neuer his fless&hbar; with
lichorye."  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is duke besoght &thorn;aim to
spur who did &thorn;is trispas.  And &thorn;e Apostels ansswer&dtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "It is ow&rtail; parte to excuse
&thorn;aim &thorn;at er innocentis, and not for to discure &thorn;aim
&thorn;at er mysdoers."

<PB N="265">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLXXXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Infernus.  Infernalis pene consideracio inducit
hominem a[d] penitenciam.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Bede tellis in 'Gestis Anglorum' how &thorn;er was a
ma&ntail; &thorn;at was dead &amp; restori&dtail; agay&ntail; vnto
life, abowte &thorn;e yeris of ou&rtail; Lor&dtail; cccc vj.  And he
was so fer&dtail; for paynys &thorn;at he had sene, &thorn;at he fled
in-to wyldernes, &amp; &thorn;er biggi&dtail; hy&mtail; a ce&llbar;
beside a grete watir.  And he wolde gang in-to &thorn;e watir with his
clathis o&ntail; vp to &thorn;e ne&ktee;, and &thorn;a&ntail; he
wol&dtail; co&mtail; v&ptail; &amp; latt &thorn;aim frese o&ntail;
hy&mtail; vnto his fless&hbar;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; onone he wolde go
into a hate bat&hbar;, &amp; &thorn;us evur whils he liffi&dtail;, he
suffer&dtail; ay &thorn;e tone after &thorn;e toder vnto he
dye&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai <NOTE ID="P265.N1">MS. &thorn;at.</NOTE> att saw
hy&mtail; reprovi&dtail; hy&mtail; whi he did so, he ansswer&dtail;
&thorn;aim agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "And ye had sene &thorn;at I
saw, ye wol&dtail; hafe done &thorn;e same with me &thorn;at I
di&dtail;." et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Infernalis meditacio.  Supra de Apostasia.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLXXXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Infernalis pena est multum acerba.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Libro de Dono Timoris' a grete meracle &amp; a
solempne, how so&mtail; [tym] at Pariss&hbar;, a scolar &thorn;at was
dea&dtail;, in a garthy&ntail; apperi&dtail; vnto his maister, and
shewi&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;e pay&ntail; of he&llbar; att he was
dampny&dtail; vnto in &thorn;is maner of wyse; he lete a drope of hys
pay&ntail; fa&llbar; of his <NOTE ID="P265.N2"><HI REND="i">After</HI> his, maister, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> fynger apo&ntail;
his maister han&dtail;, whilk &thorn;at evy&ntail; furt&hbar;-with a
grete warke went &thorn;urg&hbar; his han&dtail;.  So &thorn;at evur
after vnto he dye&dtail; &thorn;er was ay a hole &thorn;urg&hbar; his
han&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLXXXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Infernalis pena est magnitudinis inestimabilis
<NOTE ID="P265.N3">MS. inextinguibilis, Lat. MSS. <HI REND="i">as above</HI>.</NOTE>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' how o&ntail; a tyme as Macharius went in
wyldernes he fan&dtail; a dead mans hea&dtail;, and he had grete
mervay&llbar; whose it was.  And he commandi&dtail; it to spek &amp;
te&llbar; hy&mtail;, &amp; so it








<PB N="266">

di&dtail;, and say&dtail; it was a prestes hea&dtail; &thorn;at was a
gentyle, &thorn;at was vncristen&dtail;.  And he aski&dtail; it
wha&rtail; &thorn;e saule &thorn;er-of was in pay&ntail;.  And it
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail; &thorn;at it was in
he&llbar;, als depe as is fro hevy&ntail; vnto erthe, &amp; he
sai&dtail; &thorn;at it was als depe vnder-nethe hy&mtail;.  And
&thorn;er he say&dtail; wer fals criste&ntail; me&ntail;.  And a noder
tale like &thorn;is tellis Saynt Gregur in his 'Dialoggis' of a grete
ma&ntail; &thorn;at hyght Reperatus; and o&ntail; a tyme he was
kepy&dtail; as dea&dtail; &amp; sodanly turny&dtail; vnto life
agay&ntail;.  &amp; he telli&dtail; how &thorn;at he had sene a grete
kyngdo&mtail; and it was a&llbar; cover&dtail; ouer; and hy&mtail;
thoght &thorn;e heght &thorn;er-of was als hy as is fro hevy&ntail;
vnto ert&hbar;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLXXXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Infernalis pena est eterna.  Supra de Conuersione.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> A tale like vnto &thorn;e same tellis Saynt Gregu&rtail;, how
o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;er was a fon&dtail; womma&ntail; &thorn;at
somwhatt vnderstude Laty&ntail;.  And o&ntail; a tyme as sho was in
&thorn;e kurk at a Dirigie, sho harde &thorn;aim syng; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">In inferno nulla est redempcio.</FOREIGN>" And whe&ntail;
sho had har&dtail; it, sho crye&dtail; with ane horrible voyce &amp;
sayde; "I wi&llbar; neuer co&mtail; &thorn;er, ffor &thorn;at is ane
i&llbar; place for me to putt my truste in." et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Infernalis pena intolerabilis 
<NOTE ID="P266.N1">MS. intollerabilis.</NOTE>  est.  Supra de

conuersione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Infernales pene horribiles sunt ad videndum.  Infra

de sciencia nigromancie. et c&curl;.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Infernales pene viuis 
<NOTE ID="P266.N2">MS. vicijs. Harl. MS. viuis.</NOTE>  aliquando ostenduntur.  Supra

