<ITEM><FOREIGN>Infidelis a deo occiditur.  Infra de vindicta, v.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Infidelis aliquando bonas leges condit.  Infra de

lege, j.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLXXXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Infirmitas propria pacienter debet
sustineri.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Grego&rtail; tellis in his 'Dialoggis' how som tyme
&thorn;er was a ma&ntail; &thorn;at hight Seruulus, and he was passand
pure of gudis, bod he was riche of merettis.  And a&llbar; his
lyfe-tyme he lay alway in &thorn;e peralysye, &thorn;at he neuer rase
oute of his bed, nor neuer put his hand vnto his mowthe, nor neuer
myght tur&ntail; hy&mtail;.  And his moder and his bruther come vnto
hy&mtail; to kepe hy&mtail; &amp; seryff hy&mtail;; and what at evur
he gatt of almos ouer &thorn;at at &thorn;ai expundi&dtail;, he made
&thorn;aim to deale it vnto pure folke.  And with any money
&thorn;at he gatt, euer he boght hy&mtail; bukys of holie scriptur;
and he garte religios me&ntail; &thorn;at herbar&dtail; with hy&mtail;
rede &thorn;aim vnto hy&mtail;, to so mekle &thorn;at with-in a proces
he, &thorn;at cuthe no wur&dtail; o&ntail; &thorn;e buke, lerny&dtail;
holie scriptur.  And whe&ntail; he knew hy&mtail; selfe &thorn;at he
drew nere his dea&dtail;, he garte ca&llbar; vnto hy&mtail; a&llbar;
&thorn;ais pylgramys &thorn;at he was wunte to herber, and
commawndi&dtail; &thorn;aim &thorn;at &thorn;ai sulde sitt abowte
hy&mtail;, &amp; say &thorn;er prayers &amp; syng &thorn;e latynie
vnto &thorn;at he dye&dtail;; and he sang with &thorn;aim.  And
evy&ntail; as he was bow&ntail; to dye, he spakk vnto &thorn;aim &amp;
say&dtail;; "Be sti&llbar;! be sti&llbar; &amp; holde your tongis!
For ye har&dtail; neuer suche voyces as I here now songe&ntail; in
hevy&ntail;."  And as he was giffan&dtail; hede vnto &thorn;aim his
holie sawle passi&dtail; furt&hbar; of his bodye vnto blis.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCLXXXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Infirmis est diligenter seruiendum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Heraclides tellis how a ma&ntail; &thorn;at hight Eulogius forsuke
&thorn;is warl&dtail; so &thorn;at he myght nothyng do be his one nor
wir&ktee; <NOTE ID="P267.N1">Lat. MSS. quia per se nichil poterat operari.</NOTE> ; and few of his gudis he
kepi&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; &thorn;at he myght liff vppo&ntail;.  And
he



<PB N="268">

mott nowder be in &thorn;e monasterie with many, nor he myght nott
liff be his one.  O&ntail; a tyme he fande a ma&ntail; &thorn;at had a
sekenes &thorn;at was calli&dtail; Morbus Elefanticus, and he had it
so fellie &thorn;at it had distroyed his fete &amp; his handis, &amp;
a&llbar; his membris bod his tonge.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is
Elogius, evy&ntail; as he had made a counande with almyghti God,
sai&dtail; o&ntail; &thorn;is wise; "Lorde God!  In &THORN;i name I
sa&llbar; take &thorn;is ma&ntail;, &amp; take hy&mtail; as &THORN;i
servan&dtail;, and kepe hy&mtail; vnto &thorn;at he dye."  And he sett
hy&mtail; o&ntail; his ass, &amp; led hy&mtail; vnto &thorn;er he was
lugi&dtail;, &amp; kepi&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; servi&dtail; hy&mtail;
his aw&ntail; han&dtail; &thorn;e space of xv yere.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is seke ma&ntail; be &thorn;e instinccio&ntail;
of &thorn;e devu&llbar; desyri&dtail; to be away fro hy&mtail;, &amp;
flate with hy&mtail; &amp; reprevi&dtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; sai&dtail;;
"Thow come &amp; stale me furthe of my howse becauce be me &thorn;ou
trowi&dtail; to hafe welthe of gudis, and to requeuer helthe of
&thorn;i bodie."  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is Eulogius spakk fayr
with hy&mtail;, &amp; prayed hy&mtail; to be in peace &amp;
sai&dtail;; "Gude sur!  Say nott so, bod te&llbar; me &amp; I hafe
oght trispasi&dtail; vnto the, &amp; I sa&llbar; amen&dtail; itt."
And he sai&dtail;; "Nay, go &thorn;i wayes, I will none of &thorn;i
fagyngis!  Lay me &thorn;eroute opynlie; me misters none of &thorn;i
refresshyng, ffor I desyre to eate fless&hbar;."  And he garte
orda&ntail; fless&hbar; sode&ntail; &amp; broght hy&mtail; itt: and
&thorn;a&ntail; he wolde none &thorn;er-off, &amp; sai&dtail;; "I may
nott dwe&llbar; with &thorn;e, for I wi&llbar; go se &thorn;e peple."
And &thorn;a&ntail; Elogius tolde hy&mtail; he sulde bryng in a grete
meneya of brethir &amp; latt hy&mtail; se.  And he ansswer&dtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "I wi&llbar; se none suche distroyers as
&thorn;ou erte; hafe me agay&ntail; &thorn;er &thorn;ou tuke me fro!"
&thorn;an &thorn;is Elogius layde hy&mtail; in a bote &amp; had
hy&mtail; vnto Saynt Anto&ntail; &thorn;e Abbott, &amp; tolde
hy&mtail; a&llbar; his reule &amp; how he wolde putt hy&mtail; oute.
And Saynt Anto&ntail; sai&dtail;; "Peraventur, &amp; &thorn;ou forsake
hy&mtail;, a bettir ma&ntail; &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ou sha&llbar;
take hy&mtail; in &amp; fynde hy&mtail;."  And &thorn;a&ntail; he
sai&dtail; vnto &thorn;is seke ma&ntail;; "&thorn;ou behaldis nowder
wurt&hbar;elie heyv&ntail; nor ert&hbar;e; knowis &thorn;ou not at
&thorn;is is Criste att servis the?  For a&llbar; &thorn;e serves at
hy&mtail; &thorn;is duse the, he duse it for Cristis sake."  And after
&thorn;att he comfurthi&dtail; &thorn;aim bothe &amp; sai&dtail;;
"Childre, parte you nott in sonder, ffor ye mo&ntail; be bothe
savi&dtail;.  And &thorn;erfo&rtail; &thorn;is temptacio&ntail;
happend you now, whe&ntail; ye er bothe nere at en&dtail; of your
life."  And &thorn;is done, &thorn;ai turny&dtail; agay&ntail; vnto
&thorn;er ce&llbar;, and within xl<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> dayes after &thorn;ai bothe
dye&dtail;.

<PB N="269">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXC.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Infirmitas corporalis aliquando prodest
spiritui.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in &thorn;e 'Legen&dtail; of Saynt Petrone&llbar;,'
&thorn;at was Saynt Petir doghter, how &thorn;at sho was a passand
fayr womma&ntail;.  And be &thorn;e wi&llbar; of hur fadur sho had
&thorn;e axes.  And o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; &thorn;e disciples come
&amp; dyny&dtail; with hy&mtail;, &thorn;ai sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;;
"Se&ntail; a&llbar; seke folk er heli&dtail; be &thorn;e, whi suffres
&thorn;ou &thorn;is Petrone&llbar; <NOTE ID="P269.N1">MS. Perone&llbar;.</NOTE> &thorn;i
doghter to lye so sore seke?"  And he ansswer&dtail; &thorn;aim
agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail; &thorn;at it was necessarie for hur.  And
becauce &thorn;ai sulde nott trow &thorn;at it wer impossible
&thorn;at sho sulde be hale be his wurdis, &thorn;erfo&rtail; he
sai&dtail; vnto hur; "Thow Petrone&llbar;!  Rise swit&hbar;e &amp;
seryff vs!"  And onone at his wurde sho rase &amp; servi&dtail;
&thorn;aim.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai had ety&ntail;, he bad hur go
vnto hur bed agay&ntail;, &amp; so sho did &amp; was als seke
agay&ntail; in &thorn;e axis as evur was sho; and so sho lay many day
vnto hy&mtail; &thorn;oght att sho was parfite in &thorn;e luff of
God&dtail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he made hur fissc&hbar;-hale.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;er come vnto hur ane erle &thorn;at hight
Flaccus, &amp; desiri&dtail; for hur fayrnes to hafe hur vnto his
wife.  And sho ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "If
&thorn;ou desire to hafe me vnto &thorn;i wyfe, comman&dtail; a
certay&ntail; of maydens to co&mtail; vnto me &amp; bere me
felachu&ptail; vnto &thorn;i place."  And so he did.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is Petrone&llbar; fasti&dtail; hugelie, &amp;
made devowte prayers vnto almyghti Go&dtail;, &amp; tuke &thorn;e
holie sacrament, and with[-in] iij dayes after sho passi&dtail; oute
of &thorn;is warl&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXCI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Infirmitas corporalis aliquando est appetenda
<NOTE ID="P269.N2">MS. appitenda.</NOTE>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede ex 'Dictis Patrum' how som tyme &thorn;er was ane olde
ma&ntail; &thorn;at evur-ilk yere had a grete sekenes.  So it happend
a yere &thorn;at he was not seke, and &thorn;erfo&rtail; he tuke a
grete sorow &amp; wepy&dtail;, and sayd vnto hy&mtail; selfe; "
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Dereliquit me Deus, et c&curl;.</FOREIGN> Almighti
God hase forsake&ntail; me, becauce He vissettis not me as He was
wunt."





<PB N="270">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXCII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Infirmitas corporalis aliquando de superbo facit
humilem.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Jacobus de Vetriaco tellis how som tyme in &thorn;e bysshoppryke
of Pariss&hbar; &thorn;er was a paress cler&ktee;, &amp; he
vsi&dtail; to co&mtail; vnto a knyghtis place with halie water
evur-ilk wuke; &amp; he cuthe neuer gett nott o&ntail; hy&mtail; bod
flytyng &amp; bannyng.  And it happend o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;is
knyght fe&llbar; seke, and whe&ntail; &thorn;e clerke come with holi
watyr &amp; keste o&ntail; hy&mtail;; he praye&dtail; &thorn;is clerk
to pray for hy&mtail;.  And he garte giff hy&mtail; a kir&ktee;.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is cler&ktee; spakk vnto hy&mtail; &amp;
sai&dtail;; "How is &thorn;is happend, sur, &thorn;at ye &thorn;at so
ofte hase flitty&ntail; with me, &amp; bannyd me so oft, is now
&thorn;us turny&dtail; at ye pray me now for to pray for you?"  And
&thorn;e knyght ansswer&dtail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "Seis &thorn;ou not
how I a&mtail; seke, &amp; how &thorn;e gowte is in my fute o&ntail;
&thorn;e to syde?"  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e cler&ktee;
sai&dtail;; "Sur, I sa&llbar; pray God &thorn;at it may be also in
&thorn;e toder fute."  And &thorn;e knyght asky&dtail; hy&mtail; what
he sai&dtail;. And &thorn;e clerk ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail;
&amp; sai&dtail;; "&thorn;ou was als prowde as a lio&ntail; whe&ntail;
&thorn;ou was hale, and now in &thorn;i sekenes &thorn;ou erte made
als meke as a lambe.  And yit for &thorn;i gude I sa&llbar; pray for
the."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Infirmus aliquando convalescit per votum religionis.

Infra de voto.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Ingratus Deo de beneficio percepto ab eo merito

perdit illud.  Supra de heretico.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Ingratitudinis vicium incurrit vane glorians de

beneficio percepto, et ideo merito illud perdit.  Supra

de confessione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Ingratus homini de beneficio ab eo recepto multum

est reprehensibilis.  Supra de Infirmo.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXCIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iniuria propter Deum debet dimitti.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede ex 'Dictis Patrum' how &thorn;at &thorn;e Abbot
Hillario&ntail;, whe&ntail; o&ntail; a tyme he visit a certay&ntail;
bisshop&ptail;, and whe&ntail; &thorn;ai war at

<PB N="271">

meatt, &thorn;is bissho&ptail; sett befo&rtail; hy&mtail; a
capo&ntail; &amp; bad hy&mtail; eatt.  And &thorn;e Abbott
ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "Sen I tuke
&thorn;is abbett I ete neuer &thorn;ing &thorn;at suffred dea&dtail;."
Tha&ntail; &thorn;e bissho&ptail; ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail;
&amp; sai&dtail;; "And I, se&ntail; I tuke &thorn;is abbett, suffred
neuer man to slepe &thorn;at had oght agay&ntail; me.  Nor I
slepi&dtail; nevur als lang as I had oght agayns&curl; hy&mtail; vnto
we war in charite."  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is Abbott sai&dtail;;
"Fathir! fforgiff me; for &thorn;i conuersacio&ntail; is more
&thorn;a&ntail; myne."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Iniurie sunt aliquando dissimulande.  Supra de

amicicia, viij et ix.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Inobediencia.  Infra de obediencia et religione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Insidie.  Insidiantur superbi bonis operibus.  Infra

de superbia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Insidiantur demones hominibus multipliciter.  Supra

de demonibus pluribus locis.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Insidiantur mali quandoque bonis.  Supra de carne,

iiij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXCIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Intencio mala eciam bonum opus viciat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Gregorie tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a holie
ma&ntail; &thorn;at hight Fortunatus, &amp; he was a
bissho&ptail;. And o&ntail; a day he drafe oute ane evu&llbar; spiritt
oute of a ma&ntail; &thorn;att was vexi&dtail; &thorn;er-with, whilk
spiritt agay&ntail; evy&ntail; feny&dtail; hy&mtail; selfe like a
pylgre&mtail;, &amp; went aboute in &thorn;e cetie &thorn;urg&hbar; &thorn;e
stretis, &amp; sai&dtail; &amp; crie&dtail;; "O! &thorn;ou holie
ma&ntail;, Fortunatt &thorn;e bisshop&ptail;, &thorn;at putt oute a
pylgra&mtail; oute of his hoste!  And I seke now in his cetie
&thorn;er I mot be lugi&dtail;, &amp; I ca&ntail; gett no herberie."
And &thorn;er was a ma&ntail; &thorn;at satt in his howse be &thorn;e
fyre with his wife &amp; his childre, and he come furt&hbar; &amp;
aski&dtail; hy&mtail; what &thorn;e bissho&ptail; had done vnto
hy&mtail;; &amp; he tolde hy&mtail;.  &amp; he tuke hy&mtail; in &amp;
herber&dtail; hy&mtail;, and as &thorn;ai satt talkan&dtail; be
&thorn;e fyre, &thorn;is same spiritt keste a bar&ntail; of hys in
&thorn;e fyre and burnyd it o dea&dtail;.  And with &thorn;at he flew
away with a grete noyse.  And &thorn;is sorie ma&ntail;

<PB N="272">

purseyvi&dtail; &thorn;at he &thorn;at he had resayvid was not putt
oute be &thorn;e bisshop&ptail;, bod at it was ane i&llbar; spiritt
&thorn;at come for to disclander hy&mtail; <NOTE ID="P272.N1">Harl. MS. Qui miser orbatus ... quia non hospitalitatis pietate delectabatur sed episcopi derogacione.</NOTE>.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Inuencio.  Inuenta res debet
restitui.  Infra de promisso.  </FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Inuidia inter religiosos
inuenitur.  Infra de

obediencia.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXCV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Invidie stimulis agitati religiosi aliquando se
excusant.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a monke &thorn;at was
stirri&dtail; with envie, and he accusid a yong ma&ntail; vnto &thorn;e
Abbott, &amp; putt vppo&ntail; hy&mtail; grevus trispas.  And &thorn;e
Abbott belevi&dtail; hy&mtail; no&yogh;t, &amp; so oppynlie in
&thorn;e chapit&rtail; he putt furt&hbar; a&llbar; &thorn;ies trispas
of &thorn;is yong ma&ntail;, whe&ntail; &thorn;er visitur was
&thorn;er.  And &thorn;e visitur belevi&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; putt
&thorn;ies trispas vnto &thorn;is yong ma&ntail;; and he sai&dtail; he
was nott giltie, &amp; &thorn;at he tuke God to witnes.
Notwithstondyng he was commytt vnto prison; and onone after &thorn;is
envious ma&ntail; fe&llbar; seke and was ferde to dye.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; he graunti&dtail; opynlie how he for envye had
accusi&dtail; &thorn;is yong ma&ntail;.  And so &thorn;is yong
ma&ntail; with grete ioy be his visitur was take&ntail; oute of
priso&ntail; agay&ntail;, &amp; restori&dtail; vnto his olde estate as
he was befo&rtail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Inuident mali bonis.  Supra de
carne, iiij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXCVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Inuidia aliqualis eciam in puellis paruis
reperitur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;at in Freselan&dtail; in a nonrie
&thorn;er was ij little maydens &thorn;at lernyd o&ntail; &thorn;e
buke, &amp; euer &thorn;ai strafe whethur of &thorn;aim shulde
ler&ntail; mo&rtail; &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e toder.  So &thorn;e tane of
&thorn;aim happen&dtail; to fa&llbar; seke, and sho garte ca&llbar;
&thorn;e Priores vnto hur &amp; say&dtail;; "Gude ladie!  suffre nott
my felow to ler&ntail; vnto I cover of my sekenes, and I sa&llbar;




<PB N="273">

pray my moder to gif me vj&dtail; &amp; &thorn;at I sa&llbar; giff you
&amp; ye do so; ffor I drede &thorn;at whils I a&mtail; seke,
&thorn;at sho sa&llbar; pas me in lernyng, &amp; &thorn;at I wolde not
at sho di&dtail;, et c&curl;."  And at &thorn;is wurde &thorn;e
priores smyli&dtail; &amp; had&dtail; grete mervayle of &thorn;e
damyse&llbar; conseyte. et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXCVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Invidus in morte eciam non cessat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis &thorn;at whe&ntail; &thorn;e Duke of Siringie was
deade, &thorn;er was harde a voyce besyde &thorn;e Mownt of Tybir <NOTE ID="P273.N1">Arund. MS. Montem Geber.  Harl. MS. Montem Ciber.</NOTE> , &thorn;at spat fyre, &amp; it say&dtail;; "Ordand
fyre!"  And a noder voyce ansswer&dtail; &amp; sayd; "I wote neuer
whatt, nor to whame I sa&llbar; orda&ntail;."  And &thorn;e toder
sai&dtail; agay&ntail;; "Our gude &amp; wele-beluffi&dtail;
fren&dtail;, &thorn;e Duke of Siringie, commys hedur."  And onone it
was knaw&ntail; &thorn;at in &thorn;e Empyre of Frederyke, vnto whome
&thorn;ies wa&rtail; wrete&ntail;, &thorn;e same day &amp; how&rtail;
was Bertolfus <NOTE ID="P273.N2">Lat. MSS. Bertoldus.</NOTE> , &thorn;at was Duke of Siringie,
dea&dtail;; &thorn;at was a grete tyrand and a robber bothe of riche
me&ntail; &amp; pure me&ntail;.  And for als meky&llbar; as he had no
chil&dtail;, or he dye&dtail; he praye&dtail; &thorn;at a&llbar; his
tresurs, &thorn;at war of grete valow, mott be molte&ntail; in-to a
grete mace, &amp; say&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; selfe; "I gnaw we&llbar;
at my cussyns wi&llbar; be fay&ntail; of my dea&dtail;; and if
&thorn;ai fyn&dtail; me tresurs, sone &thorn;ai wi&llbar; devide
&thorn;aim emang &thorn;aim.  And if &thorn;ai be a&llbar; in a grete
lompe &thorn;ai er noght ethe to parte emang &thorn;aim." et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXCVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Inuitis prestat Deus multa beneficia.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in &thorn;e 'Legend of Saynt Marty&ntail;' how &thorn;at
&thorn;er was two at war felowse to-geder, &amp; &thorn;ai war
beggers; &amp; &thorn;e tone was blynde &amp; &thorn;e toder myght not
goo.  And he &thorn;at was blynde was a strong ma&ntail; &amp; bare
<NOTE ID="P273.N3"><HI REND="i">After</HI> bare, to, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> the tother in his nekk, &amp; he telli&dtail;
hy&mtail; alway how he sulde goo; and &thorn;us &thorn;ai beggi&dtail;
many day &amp; gatt mekle syluer.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai har&dtail;
te&llbar; how &thorn;at att Saynt Marty&ntail; tombe many seke folke
wer heli&dtail;, opo&ntail; &thorn;e day of his translacio&ntail; it
was vse to
<PB N="274">
bere his bonys furt&hbar; of &thorn;e kur&ktee;, and &thorn;ai come
thedir.  And yit &thorn;ai war afer&dtail; &thorn;at peraventur, and
&thorn;ai abade in &thorn;e strete &thorn;er his bonys war bor&ntail;
thrug&hbar;, &thorn;at &thorn;ai sulde be made hale; &amp; &thorn;a[i]
wol&dtail; not be made hale for drede &thorn;er begyng sulde defayle
&thorn;aim.  And &thorn;ai went furt&hbar; of &thorn;at strete.  And
sodanlie &thorn;aim happen&dtail; mete with his shryne in a noder gate,
&amp; &thorn;er &thorn;ai war made hale agay&ntail; &thorn;er wy&llbar;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCXCIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iohannis
<NOTE ID="P274.N1">MS. Iohannes.</NOTE> Euuangeliste.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cassianus tellis how o&ntail; a tyme a ma&ntail; come &amp; broght
Saynt Ioh&ntail; Euuangeliste a pertryk&ktee; whikk, &amp; gaff
hy&mtail; it; and he tuke it &amp; hel&dtail; it in his han&dtail; &amp;
straki&dtail; it &amp; made meky&llbar; &thorn;er-off.  And &thorn;er
was a yong felow at saw &amp; skoryn&dtail; hy&mtail;, sai&dtail; vnto
his felows att stude abowte hy&mtail;; "Wi&llbar; ye se yone olde felow
how he laykis with yone byr&dtail; as it wer a yong bar&ntail;?"  And
Saynt Ioh&ntail; be &thorn;e Holie Gaste purseyvi&dtail; &thorn;is,
and calli&dtail; &thorn;e yong ma&ntail; vnto hy&mtail; &amp;
asky&dtail; hy&mtail; what &thorn;at was at he hel&dtail; in his
han&dtail;.  And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;
&thorn;at it was a bow.  And he aski&dtail; hy&mtail; what he
di&dtail; &thorn;erwith, and &thorn;e yong ma&ntail; say&dtail;; "I
shute burdis &amp; bestis &thorn;erwith."  And &thorn;e aposte&llbar;
aski&dtail; hy&mtail; whi it was vnbendi&dtail;, and he sai&dtail;,
for &amp; he helde it allway bendy&dtail;, it wolde be &thorn;e wayker
to shute away his shaftis with.  Tha&ntail; &thorn;e aposte&llbar;
ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sayde; "So&ntail;, o&ntail;
&thorn;e same wise mans freletie wolde be passan&dtail; wayke &amp; it
wer allway bendy&dtail; in &thorn;oght of contemplacio&ntail;; ffor as
&thorn;e egle emang a&llbar; burdis fleis hyest &amp; seis nexte
&thorn;e so&ntail;, &amp; yit hur muste nedelyng co&mtail; dow&ntail;
vnto &thorn;e law placis, right so mans witt, whe&ntail; it withdrawis
it a little fro&mtail; contemplacio&ntail; &amp; hase a litle
comfurt&hbar;, afterwar&dtail; it is mo&rtail; ardent vnto hevynlie
matyrs." et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCC.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iohannis Baptiste et Iohannis
Euuangeliste.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Legenda Lombardica' how som tyme &thorn;er was ij
docturs of dyvynyte, and &thorn;e tone of &thorn;aim luffe&dtail; in
esspecia&llbar; afo&rtail;



<PB N="275">

a&llbar; o&thorn;er Saynttis Saynt Ioh&ntail; Baptiste <NOTE ID="P275.N1">MS. Saynt Iohn of Baptiste.</NOTE> , &thorn;e toder Saynt Ioh&ntail; Euuangeliste, into
so meku&llbar; &thorn;at betwix &thorn;aim &thorn;ai made grete
disputacions of &thorn;er ioy &amp; &thorn;er excellence, vnto so
meku&llbar; at ather of &thorn;aim war passan&dtail; besy to
fyn&dtail; resons &amp; auctorities to prefer &thorn;e Saynt
Ioh&ntail; &thorn;at he luffi&dtail; with.  And so &thorn;ai
poynti&dtail; a day of disputacio&ntail;.  And in &thorn;e menewhile
ather of &thorn;ies Sayntis aperi&dtail; vnto his doctur at hel&dtail;
with hy&mtail;, &amp; say&dtail;; "We er wele acordi&dtail; in
hevy&ntail;, and &thorn;erfo&rtail; dispute nott of vs in erthe."  And
whe&ntail; &thorn;ai mett samen, ather of &thorn;aim afor&ntail;
a&llbar; &thorn;e peple telli&dtail; other &thorn;er visio&ntail;, and
thanki&dtail; Almi&yogh;ti God &amp; &thorn;ase holie sayntis.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iohannis Baptiste.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede ex 'Legenda Lombardica' how one &thorn;at hight Pawle,
&thorn;at was historiographus Longobardorum, and a deky&ntail; of
&thorn;e kurk of Rome, and afterwar&dtail; a mon&ktee; of Cassynence,
o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; he sulde hafe halowi&dtail; &thorn;e
pasca&llbar;, hy&mtail; happend to wex do&mtail;, &thorn;at he cuthe
not als meku&llbar; as say A, &thorn;at is &thorn;e furst vowe&llbar;.
And he made hys prayer vnto Saynt Ioh&ntail; at he mott speke
agay&ntail;, &amp; in wurshu&ptail; of hy&mtail; he made &thorn;is
ympne, " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vt queant laxis, et c&curl;,</FOREIGN>"
&amp; als tyte as he had made &thorn;at he mot speke.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iterum Iohannis Baptiste.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in &thorn;e same 'Legen&dtail;' how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was
a huswyff &thorn;at punysshi&dtail; hur selfe with fastyng &amp;
prayers.  And euer sho prayed Almyghti Go&dtail; to send hur so&mtail;
of &thorn;e relikkis of Saynt Ioh&ntail; Baptiste.  And sodanly
apo&ntail; ane alta&rtail; sho saw a thombe &thorn;at was passand
white, and sho was glad &thorn;erof &amp; tuke itt.  An&dtail;
&thorn;er come vnto hur iij bysshoppis, whe&ntail; &thorn;ai harde
te&llbar; &thorn;at sho had suc&hbar; a relyk, &amp; desyri&dtail; to
hafe parte &thorn;erof; &amp; sho lete iij droppis



<PB N="276">

of blude drop&ptail; opo&ntail; a clothe, &amp; &thorn;ai cut it in
sonder &amp; tuke ilkone of &thorn;aim a dro&ptail;, and went home
&thorn;erwith &amp; was passyng gla&dtail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Iohannis Damasceni.  Infra de infamia.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ira aliquando est dissimulanda.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis how o&ntail; a tyme ane arschedeky&ntail; <NOTE ID="P276.N1">Harl. MS. archidiaconus Canentinus.</NOTE> &thorn;at was callid Carentinus, o&ntail; a tyme
whe&ntail; a bondma&ntail; of his had grevid hy&mtail;, he sai&dtail;
o&ntail; &thorn;is maner vnto hy&mtail;; "Had I not bene angre&dtail;
vnto &thorn;e I sulde hafe putt &thorn;e vnto grete punyssment."  And
so he had levur lefe &thorn;e blame vnpunysshi&dtail; &thorn;a&ntail;
fulfy&llbar; &thorn;e movyng of his yre.  We rede also of Plato,
whe&ntail; o&ntail; a tyme he was grevi&dtail; agayns his
servan&dtail; for a tryspas, ffor drede &thorn;at he sulde be
vengeable &amp; pas mesur, he commytt &thorn;e chastiment of his
seruan&dtail; vnto &thorn;e fre liste of a noder ma&ntail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Ire signa.  Supra de Correcione, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Irasci non debet iudex corrigendo.  Supra de

correccione, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iracundus naturaliter eciam solus existens irascitur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' how som tyme &thorn;er was a brother
&thorn;at was passan&dtail; angrie in hy&mtail; selfe.  So o&ntail; a
tyme he sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; selfe; "&THORN;ou bodie!  &amp;
&thorn;ou war be &thorn;ine ane, &thorn;ou sulde not be so ofte
movi&dtail; vnto angrynes."  So he went vnto wildernes &amp; liffid be
hy&mtail; selfe.  &amp; o&ntail; a tyme he tuke a little pott &amp;
filli&dtail; itt fu&llbar; of watyr, and he turny&dtail; vp &thorn;e
pott &amp; powri&dtail; it oute.  So &thorn;e secun&dtail; tyme he
fylli&dtail; it &amp; wex angrie &amp; powri&dtail; it oute
agay&ntail;; and &thorn;a&ntail; he wex so tene &thorn;at he tuke
&thorn;e vesse&llbar; &amp; brakk it a&llbar; to gobettis.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; he come vnto hy&mtail; selfe &amp; knew &thorn;at he
was stirri&dtail; to wrat&hbar; be a fen&dtail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail;
he sai&dtail;; "Lo! &thorn;uff a&llbar;



<PB N="277">

I be be myne ane, neuer-&thorn;e-less I a&mtail; ouer-comme&ntail;
with angrynes."  And &thorn;a&ntail; he turny&dtail; agay&ntail; vnto
his felashu&ptail;; for wha&rtail; &thorn;er is labur &amp;
felashu&ptail; commonlie &thorn;er is paciens &amp; Goddis helpe.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iracundus eciam visibiliter punitur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a riche mans doghter,
and sho was so angrie &thorn;at whare at evur sho wa&rtail; sho made
stryfe &amp; debate; &amp; yit sho lete hur selfe holye &amp; sho mott
nott restrene hur tong.  So at &thorn;e laste hur happend to dye,
&amp; &thorn;ai berid hur in &thorn;e kur&ktee; porche.  And o&ntail;
&thorn;e mor&ntail; whe&ntail; folk come vnto &thorn;e kur&ktee;,
&thorn;ai saw reke co&mtail; oute of hur grafe, &amp; &thorn;ai had
merve&llbar; &thorn;er-of, &amp; was fer&dtail; &amp; opynde it, &amp;
keste oute &thorn;e erthe.  &amp; &thorn;ai fande &thorn;e vpper halfe
of hur bodie to hur navi&llbar; burny&dtail; clene away with fyre,
&amp; &thorn;e lawer partie lay hale, in betokynyng &thorn;at sho was
a clene maydy&ntail; bod yit sho was passan&dtail; angrie.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Irreuerencia facta sanctis punitur.  Supra de

blasfemia, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iudei expectantes Messiam per clericum
decipiuntur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how so&mtail; tyme in &thorn;e cetie of
Londo&ntail; <NOTE ID="P277.N1">Harl. MS. Lomodonensis. Arund. MS. Lomonidensis.</NOTE> a clerk gatt a Iewis doghter with
childe; &amp; he was ferde for grevans of hur fadur &amp; hur moder,
&amp; he gatt hy&mtail; a long rede &amp; come o&ntail; &thorn;e night
to &thorn;e wa&llbar; &thorn;er hur fadur &amp; hur moder lay within.
&amp; he put &thorn;e vpper en&dtail; of &thorn;e rede in at a hole,
&amp; he spak&ktee; in att &thorn;e toder en&dtail; &amp; sai&dtail;;
"O! ye rightwus folk, in God wele-beluffi&dtail;!" &amp; calli&dtail;
&thorn;aim be &thorn;er names &amp; bad &thorn;aim be merie, for
&thorn;er doghter had conseyvi&dtail; Messias &amp; yit sho was a
mayde&ntail;.  And with &thorn;at &thorn;e ma&ntail; was estony&dtail;
&amp; aski&dtail; his wife if sho har&dtail; &thorn;is voyce, and sho
sai&dtail; nay; &amp; &thorn;ai made &thorn;er prayers at &thorn;ai
myght here it agay&ntail;.  And &thorn;e clerke stude sti&llbar; &amp;
harde &thorn;aim; and as he did befo&rtail;, he spak&ktee;



<PB N="278">

agay&ntail;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai har&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;ai
war passan&dtail; fay&ntail;, &amp; trowi&dtail; &thorn;at it had bene
trew; &amp; vnnethis &thorn;ai abade a day vnto &thorn;ai grapi&dtail;
&thorn;er doghter bodie &amp; fan&dtail; at sho was with childe.
&amp; &thorn;ai aski&dtail; hur how sho conseyvi&dtail;, and sho
ansswer&dtail; as &thorn;e clerk ha&dtail; bedy&ntail; hur, &amp;
say&dtail;; "I wote neuer whe&thorn;er I be with childe or nay, bod I
know wele I a&mtail; a mayde&ntail; &amp; had neuer at do with
ma&ntail;." And &thorn;er was hur fadur &amp; hur moder so ioyfu&llbar;
&thorn;at onone &thorn;e noyse ra&ntail; &thorn;urg&hbar; &thorn;e
cetie &thorn;at &thorn;er doghter was with childe with Messias.  So
tyme come sho sulde be delyver, &amp; &thorn;er come vnto hur many
Iewis with grete myrt&hbar; &amp; ioy, &amp; abade to sho war delyver
at &thorn;ai mot se what sho had bor&ntail;.  And in hur travellyng
sho had grete pay&ntail;, &amp; at &thorn;e laste with grete sorow
&amp; crying sho bare a doghter, &thorn;at cryed &amp; grete &amp;
made meky&llbar; mornyng.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai saw &thorn;is
&thorn;ai a&llbar; war confusi&dtail; passynglie, to so meki&llbar;
&thorn;at ane of &thorn;aim in a tene tuke &thorn;is childe be
&thorn;e legg &amp; threw it agay&ntail; &thorn;e wa&llbar; &amp;
killi&dtail; it. et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Iudei filius in fornacem missus per beatam Mariam

est liberatus.  Supra de eukaristia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Iudei canonicum accusantes vsum loquendi

perdiderunt.  Supra de contricione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Iudei ymaginem crucifixi verberantes sanguine ex ea

prosiliente conuersi sunt ad Christum.  Supra

de cruce.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iudex iniuste iudicans puniendus est.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Helinandus tellis <NOTE ID="P278.N1">of Cambises <HI REND="i">added above the line.</HI></NOTE> of Cambises, &thorn;at
was Cyrus <NOTE ID="P278.N2">MS. Ciri.</NOTE> &thorn;e kyng of Perce so&ntail;,
whe&ntail; he had opteny&dtail; his kyngdo&mtail; &amp; fande a iustis
&thorn;at had giffe&ntail; a wronges eniugement, he commandi&dtail; at
he sulde be flane, &amp; his so&ntail; to be made iustis after
hy&mtail;; &amp; at &thorn;e sete at his so&ntail; sul&dtail; sitt in
for iugement sulde be couerde with his fadir





<PB N="279">

sky&ntail;, at he sulde hafe mynde of hys <NOTE ID="P279.N1">MS. hy&mtail;</NOTE>
faders iugement &amp; of &thorn;e pay&ntail; att he had
&thorn;erfo&rtail;, and so at he sulde be ferde to giff a fals
eniugement.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Iudex a ueritate non debet deuiare propter

amiciciam 
<NOTE ID="P279.N2">MS. amicisiam.</NOTE> .  Supra de amicicia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Iudex debet esse sobrius maxime in potu.  Supra

de abstinencia, vij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Iudex non debet eligi puer.  Infra de puero.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Iudex non debet constitui pauper vel auarus, vt supra

de balliuo.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Iudex cito credere non debet.  Supra de credere, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Iudex veritatem vendere et aliena rapere non debet.

Infra Laurencij, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Iudex debet astutus esse in causis obscuris

inquirendis.  Infra de muliere.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iudex sine causa reum absoluere non
debet.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis of a bisshop &thorn;at was a holie ma&ntail; &amp;
a devowte, and o&ntail; a tyme in &thorn;e Lentre&ntail; he red
ow&rtail; his psalter, and whe&ntail; he come at &thorn;is place in
his psalter, " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Quis loquetur potentias Domini,
auditas [faciet] omnes laudes eius?</FOREIGN> <NOTE ID="P279.N3"><HI REND="i">This comes after</HI>: Confitemini Domino, quoniam in saeculum misericordia eius.</NOTE> "
sodanly ane of his iustis come in vnto hy&mtail; and aski&dtail;
hy&mtail; what he sulde do with a ma&ntail; &thorn;at had done a grete
cryme &amp; a trispas.  And &thorn;is bisshop&ptail; was fu&llbar; of
mercie and bad hy&mtail; spare hy&mtail; for &thorn;e holie tyme.  And
with &thorn;at &thorn;e Iustis turny&dtail; agay&ntail; purposyng to
lat hy&mtail; go.  And &thorn;e bisshop red o&ntail; o&ntail; &thorn;e
psalter &thorn;er he lefte, &amp; onone he fande &thorn;is verce, "
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Beati qui custodiunt iudicium et faciunt iusticiam
in omni tempore, et c&curl;.</FOREIGN>" And with &thorn;is he was
flaye&dtail; as he had bene reson&dtail; be almighti God.  And onone
he garte ca&llbar; &thorn;is iustis agay&ntail; &







<PB N="280">

sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "Serche diligentlie &thorn;e cauce &amp;
deme hy&mtail; rightwuslie."  And so be &thorn;e voyce of &thorn;e
prophett he &thorn;at was giltie loste his lyfe.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iudex debet esse adeo iustus vt eciam propinquis
delinquentibus non parcat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis of one &thorn;at hight Zaleucius &thorn;at was a
iustis.  And o&ntail; a tyme hys so&ntail; for avowtrie was
condempny&dtail; afo&rtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;at bothe his ee&ntail;
sulde be putt oute.  And a&llbar; &thorn;e cetie withstude it for
wurshi&ptail; of his fadir a grete while, vnto so myki&llbar; he was
evy&ntail; ouercomme&ntail;.  And at &thorn;e laste, becauce he wolde
&thorn;e law war kepid trewlie &amp; not broke&ntail;, he garte furst
put furt&hbar; one of his awn ee&ntail; for his so&ntail;, &amp; syne
one of his so&ntail; ee&ntail;, at his so&ntail; sulde not hafe bothe
putt oute.  And so be temperans of a mervalos evynhe&dtail; <NOTE ID="P280.N1">Arund. MS. sibique mirabili equitatis temperamento, se misericordie patrem et iustum legislatorem ostendit.</NOTE> , ather of &thorn;aim loste ane ee.  And &thorn;us
he shewi&dtail; hy&mtail; selfe bothe a rightwus ma&ntail; of law
&amp; a mercyfu&llbar; fadur. et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Iudex debet esse compositus in sensibus exterioribus.

Supra de aspectu.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Iudici malo frequenter succedit deterior.  Supra de

balliuo 
<NOTE ID="P280.N2">MS. balneo.</NOTE></FOREIGN> .</ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Iudices 
<NOTE ID="P280.N3">MS. Iudeces.</NOTE>  frequenter mutare non expedit.  Supra de

balliuo, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iudex bonus non debet differre iusticiam
<NOTE ID="P280.N4">So Lat. MSS. Eng. MS. causam.</NOTE> sine
causa rationabili.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Helynandus tellis of &thorn;e Emperour Traiane, how o&ntail; a
tyme whe&ntail; he sulde go vnto bate&llbar; and lepid opo&ntail; his
hors, a wedow come










<PB N="281">

&amp; tuke hy&mtail; be &thorn;e fute; &amp; with grete sorow &amp;
lamentacio&ntail; sho praye&dtail; hy&mtail; at sho mott hafe right of
&thorn;aim at had slay&ntail; hur so&ntail; wronguslie.  And sho
sai&dtail;; "Sur!  &thorn;ou reingnes as emperour, &amp; whi lattis
&thorn;ou me suffer &thorn;is fowle eniurie?"  And he sai&dtail; he
sulde make it to be amendi&dtail; whe&ntail; he come agay&ntail;; and
sho aski&dtail; hy&mtail; how sho sulde do &amp; he neuer come
agay&ntail;, and he sai&dtail; his successur sulde make hur to be
asethi&dtail;.  And sho aski&dtail; hy&mtail; how scho sulde know
&thorn;at; "and if he do," sho sai&dtail;, "whatt wi&llbar; &thorn;at
profett the?  And if no ma&ntail; make me a sethe, yit &thorn;ou erte
dettur vnto me, &amp; &thorn;ou mo&ntail; be rewardi&dtail; aftir
&thorn;i warkis.  And &thorn;i successur is bo&ntail; for the, bod a
noder mans rightwusnes sa&llbar; not delyvir &thorn;e for &thorn;at at
&thorn;ou sulde hafe done &thorn;ine aw&ntail; selfe."  And with
&thorn;ies wurdis &thorn;is Emperour Traiane was somwhat movi&dtail;
lighti&dtail; of his hors, and in his aw&ntail; perso&ntail; he
exsamyn&dtail; &thorn;e wedous cauce, &amp; he comfurthi&dtail; hur
&amp; made hur to hafe a due satisfaccio&ntail; for hur hurte.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iudicia Dei frequenter sunt occulta.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iacobus de Vetriaco tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was ane hermett
&thorn;at was tempi&dtail; with &thorn;e spiritt of blasfemyng, vnto
so mek[ill] <NOTE ID="P281.N1">MS. mekyng.</NOTE> he thoght in his aw&ntail;
myn&dtail; &thorn;at &thorn;e domys of Almi&yogh;tti God wer nott
rightwus, &thorn;at suffer&dtail; synners &amp; i&llbar; me&ntail; to
hafe prospertie &amp; welefar of &thorn;is warlde, &amp; gude
me&ntail; &amp; rightwus to hafe disease &amp; tribulacio&ntail;.  And
&thorn;er apperi&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; ane ange&llbar; o&ntail; a tyme
in a mans liknes, &amp; sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "Folow me &amp;
&thorn;ou sa&llbar; se &thorn;e privay Iugementtis of almi&yogh;tti
Go&dtail;."  So &thorn;ai come vnto a gude mans hows &thorn;at
herber&dtail; &thorn;aim al nyght <NOTE ID="P281.N2">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, with gude chere.</NOTE> , &amp; made
&thorn;aim gude chere.  &amp; o&ntail; &thorn;e mor&ntail; whe&ntail;
&thorn;ai went, &thorn;e aunge&llbar; stale &thorn;e syluer cop&ptail;
at &thorn;ai dranke of, &amp; tuke it with hy&mtail;; whilk cop
&thorn;e gudema&ntail; luffid beste of any thyng &thorn;at he
ha&dtail;.  And &thorn;ai wente &thorn;er wayse, &amp; on &thorn;e
nexte nyg[ht] &thorn;ai herber&dtail; with ane i&llbar; ma&ntail;
&amp; a wykki&dtail;, whare &thorn;ai were reseyvid with i&llbar;
wi&llbar; &amp; fure i&llbar;.  And &thorn;e cop&ptail; at he tuke fro
&thorn;e toder ma&ntail;, &thorn;e ange&llbar; gaff &hbar;y&mtail;
itt.  And &thorn;is hermett thoght





<PB N="282">

i&llbar; &thorn;er-with, bod he sayde noght.  And o&ntail; &thorn;e
iij nyght &thorn;ai wer hostid at a gudemans howse &thorn;at
reseyvi&dtail; &thorn;aim with gude wi&llbar; &amp; made &thorn;aim
wele at fare.  And o&ntail; &thorn;e mor&ntail; he sent a
servan&dtail; of hys furt&hbar; with &thorn;aim to teche &thorn;aim
&thorn;e way, &amp; whe&ntail; &thorn;ai war a&llbar; o&ntail; a bryg
&thorn;is aunge&llbar; keste &thorn;is mans servan&dtail; ou&rtail;
&thorn;e bryg &amp; drowny&dtail; hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;is hermett
saw &amp; had grete mervayle &thorn;er-of &amp; yit he sai&dtail;
noght; and o&ntail; &thorn;e iiij nyght &thorn;ai war herber&dtail; in
a gude mans howse &amp; had grete chere.  And he had a yong childe
&thorn;at wepi&dtail; a&llbar; nyght &amp; wolde nott lat &thorn;aim
slepe, and &thorn;is aunge&llbar; rase v&ptail; &amp; wrathe &thorn;e
nekk in-sonder &thorn;eroff.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e hermett saw
a&llbar; &thorn;is, he thoght &thorn;at he wolde sodanlie stele away
&amp; lefe hy&mtail;, &amp; trowi&dtail; &thorn;at he had bene rather
ane aunge&llbar; of &thorn;e devu&llbar; &thorn;a&ntail; off
Go&dtail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e aunge&llbar; bad hy&mtail;
abyde, &amp; sayde vnto hy&mtail;; "Almi&yogh;tti God sent me vnto
&thorn;e at I mot shew &thorn;e His privay domys.  The furste
ma&ntail; at reseyvid vs so wele, luffid &thorn;at cop&ptail;
abow&ntail; a&llbar; o&thorn;er thyngis; &thorn;erfo&rtail; I tuke it
fro hy&mtail; for his gude, &amp; gaff it vnto hy&mtail; at
reseyvi&dtail; vs with i&llbar; wi&llbar;, at he may resayfe his mede
in &thorn;is werlde.  And our thrid oste servan&dtail; &thorn;at I
drowny&dtail;, he was purposi&dtail; als tite as he had comme&ntail;
home, to hafe slay&ntail; his maister.  And so I delyver&dtail; our
gude oste fro dea&dtail;, &amp; &thorn;e toder fro mansslaghter, at
his punyssment myght be les in he&llbar;.  And our iiij hoste, befor
he had a childe, did grete almos dede, bod als sone as his childe was
bor&ntail;, he withdrew his han&dtail;, &amp; &thorn;oght to be
covatus &amp; gadir gudes vnto his childe.  And &thorn;erfo&rtail; I
hafe take&ntail; fro hy&mtail; &thorn;e cauce of his covatice, at he
may be as he was befo&rtail;.  And &thorn;e saule of &thorn;e innocent
childe I hafe putt in Paradice."  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e hermett
har&dtail; &thorn;is, he thanki&dtail; Go&dtail; &amp; tuke his lefe
at &thorn;e aunge&llbar;; &amp; fro thens furt&hbar; he was
delyver&dtail; fro al maner of suche temptacio&ntail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iudicium humanum.  Iudicantes secundum
apparenciam exteriorem frequenter decipiuntur; vt
patet.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Som tyme &thorn;er was a kyng, &amp; he garte make iiij kistis of
tre.  And ij of &thorn;aim he filli&dtail; fu&llbar; of stynkan&dtail;
banys of dead fol&ktee;, &amp; he

<PB N="283">

garte cover &thorn;aim clene abow&ntail; with platis of golde; &amp;
&thorn;e toder ij he filli&dtail; fu&llbar; of fyne precious stonys;
&amp; enoynti&dtail; &thorn;aim withoute with pykk &amp; tarr.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; he calli&dtail; afor&ntail; hy&mtail; a&llbar;
&thorn;e wyse me&ntail; of his cownce&llbar;, and aski&dtail;
&thorn;aim whilk of &thorn;ies war moste wurthie.  And &thorn;ai
sai&dtail; &thorn;ase at war cover&dtail; with golde, &amp; &thorn;e
toder &thorn;ai reprovid &amp; sett at noght.  And &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;e kyng say&dtail;; "I wiste wele ye walde say so."  &amp;
&thorn;a&ntail; he commawndi&dtail; at oppy&ntail; &thorn;ies kystis
at war gilti&dtail;; &amp; so &thorn;ai war, &amp; &thorn;ar come oute
of &thorn;aim a fowle stynke &amp; ane i&llbar;.  And &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;e kyng sai&dtail;; "This is a figur of &thorn;aim &thorn;at er
cled withoute with gay aray, and within er fu&llbar; of sy&ntail;
&amp; i&llbar; dedys."  And he garte oppy&ntail; &thorn;e toder, and
&thorn;er come oute a swete sme&llbar; at a&llbar; me&ntail; myght
fele.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e kyng sayde, "This is a figur of
&thorn;aim &thorn;at er cled with feble clothis withoute, &amp; within
hase a grete fayrnes in a &thorn;er sawle, &amp; er fu&llbar; of gude
warkis."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Iudicare non debent religiosi seculares.  Infra de

religiosis et supra de Basilio.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iudicandum non est de proximis eciam peccatoribus.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Legenda Iohannis Elemosinarij' of a yong ma&ntail;
&thorn;at ravisshid a no&ntail;.  And whe&ntail; clerkis broght
&thorn;is ma&ntail; befo&rtail; Johannes Elemosinarius, &thorn;ai
reprovi&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; sai&dtail; he was wurthi to be
cursi&dtail; as he &thorn;at had slay&ntail; ij sawlis, &thorn;at was
to say, bothe his &amp; hurs.  And &thorn;is holie ma&ntail;,
Ioh&ntail;, snybbi&dtail; &thorn;aim, &amp; sai&dtail;; "Not so
brether, not so! ffor I sa&llbar; shew you ye do ij synys; ffurst ye
do agayns &thorn;e commandment of Go&dtail; &thorn;at sais; ' <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Nolite iudicare.</FOREIGN>' And &thorn;e secun&dtail;, [ye
wote noght <NOTE ID="P283.N1">Harl. MS. "secundo, quia nescitis pro certo si usque hodie peccent aut peniteant."</NOTE> ] whethir &thorn;ai forthynk
&thorn;er sy&ntail; &amp; hafe done penans &thorn;erfo&rtail; or
noght, nor whethir &thorn;ai contynue in sy&ntail; to &thorn;is day or
noght."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Iudicium plurimorum aliquando comprobatur.  Infra

de suspicione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Iudicando aggrauantes facta aliorum aliquando eciam

visibiliter puniuntur.  Supra de contricione, iij.</FOREIGN>




<PB N="284">
</ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Iudicium medicorum de infirmis frequenter non

evenit.  Supra de Basilio, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iudicij vltimi aduentum incertum est hominibus
quantum ad tempus.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede of a husbandma&ntail; &thorn;at o&ntail; a tyme went fro
home, &amp; he lefte behyn&dtail; hy&mtail; to kepe his place iij
servandis, and he tolde none of &thorn;aim whe&ntail; he wolde com
home.  So emang &thorn;ies iij servandis &thorn;er movi&dtail; a
questio&ntail; of &thorn;e commyng home of &thorn;er maister,
whe&ntail; it sulde be.  And one sai&dtail; he wolde co&mtail; home
sone, &amp; &thorn;e secun&dtail; sai&dtail; nay, it wolde be lang or
he come home.  And &thorn;e iij sai&dtail;; "Forsuthe I wote neuer
whe&ntail; he wi&llbar; co&mtail; home."  And so it is certay&ntail;
at &thorn;e thrid sai&dtail; &thorn;e moste trew.  And so it is of
&thorn;e laste day, &thorn;e day of dome; we wote wele it mo&ntail;
co&mtail;, bod we wote neuer whe&ntail;, nor what tyme.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iudicium vltimum debet timeri.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede of a kyng &thorn;at travel&dtail; be &thorn;e way with his
baronage in a gay kyngis charyott.  So hy&mtail; happend to mete ij
me&ntail; cled in hevie clothyng, whilk &thorn;at war i&llbar;
hewi&dtail;, &amp; had pale facis, and &thorn;e kyng come dow&ntail;
oute of his chariott &amp; wurshuppi&dtail; &thorn;aim.  And his
baronage tuke it to i&llbar;, &amp; be &thorn;er cownce&llbar; his
bruther reson&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;erfo&rtail;.  And in &thorn;at
real&mtail; &thorn;is was &thorn;e custo&mtail;, &thorn;at vnto
&thorn;e yate of hy&mtail; &thorn;at sulde be iugied vnto dea&dtail;,
sulde &thorn;e kyngis messanger be sent befo&rtail;, to make ane oyas.
And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai come home &thorn;e kyng garte &thorn;at be
done befo&rtail; his bruther yate.  And &thorn;at done, his bruther
&amp; his wife &amp; his childer come in a mornyng clothyng vnto
&thorn;e kyng, wepan&dtail; &amp; makan&dtail; sorow.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e kyng spak vnto his bruther &amp; say&dtail;;
"O, &thorn;ou fule!  If &thorn;ou hafe dred &thorn;e bede&llbar; of
&thorn;i bruther, whome &thorn;ou knowis &thorn;ou trispasi&dtail;
no&yogh;t vnto, how durste &thorn;ou take o&ntail; han&dtail; to
chalange me becauce I meken&dtail; me befo&rtail; &thorn;e bedels
&amp; &thorn;e messangiers of a&llbar;mighti Go&dtail;

<PB N="285">

whome &thorn;at I know &thorn;at I hafe grevi&dtail; many tymys &amp;
ofte, and &thorn;at grevuslie?"

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Iudicio vltimo redditur racio de omnibus.  Supra

de episcopo, et infra de risu et de mercatore.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Iudicio vltimo reddetur cuilibet iuxta opera sua 
<NOTE ID="P285.N1">A Tale of Silvanus in illustration omitted from the English MS.</NOTE>.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iuliani Confessoris.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how &thorn;at whe&ntail; Saynt Iulia&ntail; was a yong
ma&ntail; &amp; went o&ntail; huntyng, he pursewi&dtail; o&ntail; a
tyme after a harte.  &amp; &thorn;is harte turnyd agay&ntail; &amp;
spak vnto hy&mtail;, &amp; say&dtail;; "Thow &thorn;at mo&ntail; sla
bothe &thorn;i fadir and &thorn;i moder, whar-to pursewis &thorn;ou
me?"  And he had grete wonder here-of, and becauce &thorn;is sulde not
happy&ntail; hy&mtail;, he went away oute of a fer contret&hbar; &amp;
servi&dtail; a wurthi prince: &amp; he made hym a knyght and gaff
hy&mtail; a warde, a grete gentylwomma&ntail;, vnto his wife.  And his
fadur &amp; his moder at home, hafyng grete sorow &thorn;at he was
gone oute of &thorn;e contrey fro &thorn;aim, went &amp; soght
hy&mtail; many mylis.  So o&ntail; a tyme when he was furthe, be a
soda&ntail; cace &thorn;aim happyn&dtail; to co&mtail; vnto his
caste&llbar;.  And be wurdis at &thorn;ai sai&dtail; &thorn;er, his
wyfe vnderstude at &thorn;ai war fadir &amp; moder vnto hur husband,
be a&llbar; &thorn;e proces at sho had har&dtail; hur husband say.
And whe&ntail; scho had made &thorn;aim wele to fare, sho lai&dtail;
&thorn;aim samen in hur aw&ntail; bed&dtail;; and &thorn;is
Iulia&ntail; come home sodanlie in &thorn;e mornyng &amp; wente vnto
his chamb&rtail;, &amp; fan&dtail; &thorn;aim ij samen in &thorn;e
be&dtail;.  And he, trowyng &thorn;at it had bene one &thorn;at had
done avowtry with his wyfe, he slew &thorn;aim bothe and went his
ways.  &amp; he mett his wife fro &thorn;e kurkwar&dtail;, and sho
tolde hy&mtail; how his fadir &amp; his moder was comme&ntail;, &amp;
how sho had lay&dtail; &thorn;aim in hur aw&ntail; bed&dtail;.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; he bega&ntail; to wepe &amp; make sorow, &amp;
sai&dtail;; "Lo! &thorn;at at &thorn;e harte sai&dtail; vnto me, now I
a sarie wriche hafe fulfilli&dtail; itt."  &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; he
went oute of contre &amp; di&dtail; penans, &amp; his wyfe wolde neuer
forsake hy&mtail;.  &amp; &thorn;er &thorn;ai come vnto a grete watir,
&thorn;er many war perisschi&dtail;, and &thorn;er he byggi&dtail; a
grete hostre;



<PB N="286">

&amp; a&llbar; &thorn;at euer come he herbar&dtail; &thorn;aim, &amp;
had &thorn;aim ouer &thorn;is watyr.  And &thorn;is he vsyd a lang
tyme.  So on a nyght aboute mydnyght, as he lay in his bed and it was
a grete froste, he har&dtail; a voyce cry petifullie, &amp;
say&dtail;; " Iulian!  co&mtail; &amp; feche me ow&rtail;, I pray
the!"  And he rase onone &amp; went ou&rtail; &thorn;e watir, &amp;
&thorn;er he fand a ma&ntail; &thorn;at was nerehand frosy&ntail; to
dea&dtail;, and he had hy&mtail; ou&rtail;, &amp; broght hy&mtail;
into his howse &amp; refresshi&dtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; lai&dtail;
hy&mtail; in his aw&ntail; be&dtail; &amp; happid hy&mtail;.  And
within a little while he &thorn;at was in &thorn;e be&dtail;,
&thorn;at semy&dtail; seke &amp; like a leppre, ascendid vnto
hevy&ntail; &amp; say&dtail; o&ntail; &thorn;is maner of wyse;
"Iulya&ntail;!  Almighti God hase reseyvi&dtail; &thorn;i penans.  And
with-in a little while ye bothe sha&llbar; co&mtail; vnto Hy&mtail;."
And with &thorn;at he vanysshi&dtail; away.  et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iuramento aliquos compellere non est
bonum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how o&ntail; a tyme a gude, trew, innocent ma&ntail; lent
vnto one of his neghburs a certa&ntail; &thorn;ing, &amp; whe&ntail;
he wol&dtail; hafe had it agay&ntail; he sai&dtail; he had
borowi&dtail; none swilk o&ntail; hy&mtail;, &amp; wolde nott giff
hy&mtail; it agay&ntail;.  And he was compelli&dtail; to swe&rtail;
&thorn;erfo&rtail;, &amp; sware; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;e gude, trew
ma&ntail; loste it.  So vppo&ntail; &thorn;e same nyght &thorn;is
ma&ntail; was ravisshi&dtail; vnto &thorn;e dome of Almighti
Go&dtail;.  And he was aski&dtail; o&ntail; &thorn;is maner of wyse;
"Whi hase &thorn;ou made yone ma&ntail; to swe&rtail; ane athe whilk
&thorn;ou knew was a fals athe?"  And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail;
&amp; sai&dtail;; "For he gaynsai&dtail; me &thorn;e &thorn;ing
&thorn;at I lent hy&mtail;."  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e iustis said
vnto hy&mtail;; "It had bene bettir to &thorn;e to hafe loste &thorn;i
&thorn;ing &thorn;a&ntail; for to lat hy&mtail; lose his saule."  And
&thorn;er &thorn;e iustis commawndi&dtail; &thorn;at for his truspas
he sulde be bett.  And with &thorn;at he waken&dtail; &amp;
grapy&dtail; his bak&ktee;, &amp; it was passand sare &amp; fu&llbar;
of yeddyrs &amp; wowndis as he had bene bety&ntail;.  And &thorn;us
his trispas, after he was &thorn;us amendi&dtail;, was forgiffe&ntail;
hy&mtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iurare supra reliquias sanctorum falsum est
periculosum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how so&mtail; tyme ij me&ntail; war at debate, &amp;
&thorn;at grete; and &thorn;e iustis cuthe nott witt whethir of
&thorn;aim was gyltie.  And he

<PB N="287">

broght &thorn;aim bothe vnto ane altar &amp; garte &thorn;aim purge
&thorn;aim be &thorn;er athe.  And he besoght &thorn;e aposte&llbar;
at aght &thorn;e altar to send hy&mtail; so&mtail; taky&ntail;
&thorn;at he mot knaw &thorn;e treuthe.  And whe&ntail; he &thorn;att
was giltie sware <NOTE ID="P287.N1">Arund. MS. et nichil mali passus esset, iudex, eius malicie conscius, exclamauit; "Senior iste Petrus aut nimis misericors est, aut iunioribus defert."</NOTE> , he bega&ntail; to wax
a&llbar; seke &amp; i&llbar; at ease.  And &thorn;e iustis
purseyvi&dtail; it, &amp; he sai&dtail;; "Owder is &thorn;is gude
aposte&llbar; Petur passand mercefu&llbar;, or els he differs
&thorn;is martyr.  And &thorn;erfo&rtail;," he said, "we wi&llbar; go
vnto Pancrace grafe."  And whe&ntail; he &thorn;at was gyltie sware
o&ntail; Pancrace grafe, he wol&dtail; hafe taky&ntail; his han&dtail;
away bod he myght nott, bod it hel&dtail; hy&mtail; sti&llbar;.  &amp;
with-in a little while after, &thorn;er he swelte.  et c&curl;.  And
so yit vnto &thorn;is day in &thorn;at <NOTE ID="P287.N2">MS. &thorn;an.</NOTE> contrey
&thorn;ai swe&rtail; yit vppo&ntail; Saynt Pancras tombe, and any
&thorn;ing be in varyans emang &thorn;aim.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Iuliani Apostate.  Infra de sancto et de signo de

vindicta et de vsu.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Iusticia aliquando temperanda est.  Supra de Iudice,

iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Iusticie execucio non debet differri sine causa.

Supra de iudice, iiij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iustitia eciam in proprio filio debet
excerceri.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how o&ntail; a tyme, whe&ntail; a so&ntail; o Traiane rade
prowdlie &thorn;urg&hbar; &thorn;e cetie, hy&mtail; happen&dtail; or
racklesnes with his hors to ky&llbar; a wedow so&ntail;; and &thorn;e
wedow with meki&llbar; sorow [co&mtail;] &amp; telli&dtail;
Traia&ntail; &thorn;e Emperour.  And he gaff &thorn;e wedow in-stede
of hur so&ntail; his so&ntail;, &thorn;at had done hur &thorn;e
trispas, and magnifie&dtail; hur with riche giftis.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iusticia eciam exerceri debet in propriis parentibus.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Herkenwaldus <NOTE ID="P287.N3">MS. Harl. Herkyndaldus de Bornayre, vir nobilis, etc.</NOTE> tellis of ane &thorn;at hight
Bormar, &thorn;at was a noble ma&ntail; and a myghti, &amp; in dome he
sett by no ma&ntail;.  So o&ntail; a tyme









<PB N="288">

he fe&llbar; seke &amp; lay in his bed in his chambre, and as he lay
he har&dtail; in &thorn;e nexte chamb&rtail; by hy&mtail; grete
cryingis as it had bene of womme&ntail;.  And he spurri&dtail; what it
was &amp; &thorn;ai wol&dtail; not te&llbar; hy&mtail;.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; he sent one of his childer &thorn;edur and
warny&dtail; hy&mtail;, a pay&ntail; of puttyng oute of bothe his
ee&ntail;, to te&llbar; hy&mtail; &thorn;e treut&hbar;.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; he went &amp; saw it &amp; co&mtail; agay&ntail;,
&amp; with grete drede telli&dtail; hy&mtail; what it was &amp;
sai&dtail;; "Sur! my felow, your sister so&ntail;, wol&dtail;
&thorn;er hafe oppresi&dtail; a womma&ntail; &amp; defowli&dtail; hur,
and &thorn;is was &thorn;e cauce of &thorn;e cry."  And at &thorn;is
wur&dtail; he was gretely grevi&dtail;, and bad ij of his knyghtis go
&amp; hang hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;ai sai&dtail; &thorn;ai sulde, and
went furt&hbar; &amp; tolde &thorn;e yong ma&ntail; what his ea&mtail;
had bydde&ntail; &thorn;aim doo.  And &thorn;ai bad hy&mtail; withdraw
hy&mtail; oute of his ea&mtail; sight at he saw hy&mtail; not, &amp;
&thorn;ai sulde te&llbar; hy&mtail; at &thorn;ai had done as he bad
&thorn;aim do; for &thorn;ai durst not sla &thorn;is yong ma&ntail;.
And with-in a few howris &thorn;ai come agay&ntail; vnto &thorn;er
maister, &amp; tolde hy&mtail; &thorn;ai had done as he
commanddi&dtail; &thorn;aim.  And vppo&ntail; &thorn;e fifte day after
&thorn;is yong ma&ntail;, trowyng &thorn;at his ea&mtail; had
forgette&ntail; &thorn;is trispas, putt oppy&ntail; &thorn;e
chamb&rtail;-dure &amp; luki&dtail; in.  And onone as &thorn;is seke
ma&ntail; saw hy&mtail;, he calli&dtail; hy&mtail; vnto hy&mtail;
&amp; gaff hy&mtail; fayr language, &amp; made hy&mtail; to sitt
dow&ntail; by hy&mtail;.  And sodanlie with his one ar&mtail; he gatt
hy&mtail; aboute &thorn;e nek&ktee;, &amp; hel&dtail; hy&mtail;;
&amp; with &thorn;e toder ar&mtail; he drew his knyfe &amp;
shewi&dtail; it in his throte &amp; kylli&dtail; hy&mtail;.  And
a&llbar; &thorn;at was aboute wondre&dtail; &thorn;erof &amp; vgged
&thorn;erwith.  So his sekenes swagi&dtail; a litty&llbar;, &amp;
&thorn;a&ntail; he sent for &thorn;e bissho&ptail; Herkenwaldus <NOTE ID="P288.N1">Harl. MS. Episcopus uocatus cum sacris aduenit.  Herbinbaldus, cum multis lacrimis et cordis contricione, omnia peccata sua confessus est, tacita iuuenis interfectione.</NOTE> , and he come with &thorn;e sacrament &amp; shrafe
hy&mtail;, &amp; howsel&dtail; hy&mtail; not <NOTE ID="P288.N2">MS. not <HI REND="i">added above the line</HI>.</NOTE> .
&amp; he made grete sorow &amp; had grete contricio&ntail; in his
harte for his sy&ntail;.  And in his confessio&ntail; he spak no
wur&dtail; of &thorn;e slayng of his cussy&ntail;.  And &thorn;e
bissho&ptail; had grete merva&llbar; &thorn;erof, &amp; sai&dtail;;
"Whi lay&ntail; ye &thorn;e mansslaghter of your cussy&ntail; at ye
slew?"  And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "Sur, was
&thorn;at a sy&ntail;?"  &amp; &thorn;e bisshop sai&dtail;, ya, it was a
crue&llbar; sy&ntail;.  And &thorn;e seke ma&ntail; ansswer&dtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "I a&mtail; a Iustis &amp; hafe &thorn;e
law in gouernans, &amp; nowder I deme it a sy&ntail;, nor I wi&llbar;
neuer aske God forgifnes &thorn;erof."  &THORN;a&ntail;





<PB N="289">

&thorn;e bisshop&ptail; ansswer&dtail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "I wi&llbar;
neuer gyff you &thorn;e sacrament or ye shryfe you &thorn;eroff."
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is Iustis ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail;
&amp; sai&dtail;; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Non ex rancore, sed ex zelo
iusticie et Dei timore illum interfeci;</FOREIGN> I slew hy&mtail; not
of rankor nor of il wi&llbar;, bod for luff of rightwusnes &amp; drede
of God; ffor &thorn;er was neuer ma&ntail; luffi&dtail; his sister
so&ntail; bettyr &thorn;a&ntail; I di&dtail; hy&mtail;.  And
&thorn;er-for &amp; ye deny me &thorn;e holi sacrament &thorn;at is
Goddis bodie, I betake bothe my body &amp; my saule vnto &thorn;at
holie sacrament, &thorn;at is God Hy&mtail; selfe."  And &thorn;us
&thorn;e bissho&ptail; went away &amp; wulde not howsy&llbar;
hy&mtail;.  And onone after, &thorn;is seke ma&ntail; sent for
hy&mtail; agay&ntail;.  And whe&ntail; he come att hy&mtail;,
&thorn;is seke ma&ntail; bad hy&mtail; luke in his box if &thorn;e
sacrament war &thorn;er.  And so he did &amp; fande ri&yogh;t not
&thorn;erin.  &THORN;a&ntail; &thorn;is seke ma&ntail; said vnto
hy&mtail;; "Lo! &thorn;at at ye denyed me, Almi&yogh;tti God Hy&mtail;
selfe hase giffe&ntail; me &amp; not denyed me."  And with &thorn;at
he oppyn&dtail; his mouthe, &amp; &thorn;ai mot se &thorn;e sacrament
&thorn;erin; and &thorn;a&ntail; he dye&dtail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;e bisshop&ptail; was fer&dtail; &amp; had grete sorow
herefo&rtail;, &amp; prechi&dtail; &thorn;is in euer-ilk place for a
grete meracle.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iuuentus facit homines diligenter mulieres
considerare.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede of a profeste of &thorn;e ordur of Premonstracence,
o&ntail; a tyme as he rade wit&hbar; a yong ma&ntail;, a bruther of
his howse, &thorn;aim happen&dtail; to mete a fayr yong damyse&llbar;;
&amp; &thorn;is profeste stoppi&dtail; his hors &amp; haylsi&dtail;
hur honestelie, &amp; sho stude sti&llbar; &amp; lowti&dtail; vnto
hy&mtail; &amp; thanki&dtail; hy&mtail;.  And whe&ntail; sho was
passi&dtail; &thorn;aim a litty&llbar;, &thorn;is profeste &thorn;oght
he wol&dtail; prufe &thorn;is yong ma&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail; vnto
hy&mtail;; "Me &thorn;oght &thorn;is was a passand fayr maydy&ntail;."
&amp; &thorn;is yong ma&ntail; ansswer&dtail; &amp; sai&dtail;, so
&thorn;oght hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e profest
sai&dtail; agay&ntail;; "A thyng difformys hur hugelie, &thorn;at is
sho hase bod one ey."  And &thorn;e yong ma&ntail; sai&dtail;; "Sur,
forsuthe sho hase bothe hur ene, ffor I behelde hur graythelie."  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e profest sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "And I
sa&llbar; considur &thorn;i bakk, ffor &thorn;ou sulde be of so
meky&llbar; symeplenes, &amp; &thorn;ou met a womma&ntail; &thorn;ou
sul&dtail; not luke whe&thorn;er sho had bothe hur ee&ntail; or bod
&thorn;e tane."  And &thorn;a&ntail; he

<PB N="290">

turny&dtail; agay&ntail; vnto his monasterie &amp; sai&dtail; vnto his
brethir; "Ye repruvi&dtail; me for I take no yong me&ntail; furt&hbar;
with me."  And &thorn;a&ntail; he telli&dtail; &thorn;aim &thorn;e
cauce, &amp; snybbi&dtail; &thorn;is yong ma&ntail; &amp;
chasti&dtail; hy&mtail; for his truspas.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Iuuenes puelle pulcritudinem corporalem abscondere

debent.  Infra de temptacione et supra de

abscondere.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Iuuenis non debet prefici mulieribus.  Supra de

carne.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Karolus.  De statura et vita Karoli
regis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> This kyng Charlis was of a fay&rtail; statur, for he was viij fute
long &amp; wele shapy&ntail; &amp; awfu&llbar; to sight; &amp; he was
passan&dtail; large of renys, &amp; he was clenlie bothe in bely &amp;
in armys &amp; had grete theis; &amp; he was a passan&dtail; wyse
knyght &amp; a bitter &amp; strong of ly&mtail;.  &amp; his face was
in lenthe oderhalfe palme (an&dtail; his ber&dtail; a fute long),
&amp; his nese emyddiste &thorn;erof &amp; halfe &thorn;at lent&hbar;.
&amp; his fore&dtail; was a fute long, and he had ee&ntail; like a
lyo&ntail; &thorn;at shane as a precious stane, and his browis was a
pal&mtail; brede.  And if he had bene wrathe &amp; luki&dtail;
o&ntail; a ma&ntail; he wolde hafe flaye&dtail; hy&mtail;.  And his
gyrdy&llbar; was viij fute lang with-oute &thorn;at at hang.  And he
ete bod littyl brede, bod at ans he wolde ete a quarter of a weddur,
or ij hennys, or a guse, or a swyne shulder, or a pacok, or a crane,
or a hale hare.  And he wolde drynk bod esy wyne, bod if it war
medli&dtail; with watir.  &amp; he was of suche strenthe &thorn;at, at
a strake with his swer&dtail;, he wal&dtail; cut in sonder ane armyd
knyght syttand o&ntail; a hors fro &thorn;e crow&ntail; of &thorn;e
hede vnto &thorn;e sole of &thorn;e fute, &amp; his hors als; and he
wolde lightlie breke iiij hors shone at ans, and he wol&dtail; lifte
eselie to his hede ane armyd knyght stondyng o&ntail; &thorn;e luff of
his han&dtail;.  An&dtail; he bare tables with hy&mtail; &thorn;at he
bare a&llbar; his actis in.  And he drank bod seldo&mtail; mo&rtail;
&thorn;a&ntail; thrise at his meat.  And he luffi&dtail; wele to ride
and bere armys, and he made his doghters to be clothe-makers, &amp;
for to lere at spy&ntail; o&ntail; &thorn;e rok&ktee;, at &thorn;ai
sulde nott be ydi&llbar;.  And at Coley&ntail; he garte byg ij briggis

<PB N="291">

ou&rtail; &thorn;e watir of Reine.  And whe&ntail; he come to Rome he
wol&dtail; light a myle with-oute &thorn;e tow&ntail;, &amp; go vnto
&thorn;e cetie apo&ntail; his fute, &amp; kys euer-ilk kurk dure,
&amp; giff grete rewardis vnto euer-ilk kur&ktee;.  And he
delyver&dtail; &thorn;e Holie Lande oute of Saracens handis, and come
fro thens-ward be Constantynople; and he broght thens many wurthi
relikkis, &thorn;at is to say, parte of &thorn;e crow&ntail; of
ou&rtail; Lor&dtail;, whilk &thorn;at florisshi&dtail; in his syght,
and ane of &thorn;e naylis &thorn;at our Lor&dtail; was nayli&dtail;
vnto &thorn;e cros with, and His sudarie, &amp; ou&rtail; Ladie sarke,
and Saynt Symeo&ntail; ar&mtail;.  And a&llbar; &thorn;ies he putt in
a kurk of our Layde &thorn;at he byggi&dtail;, and he fowndi&dtail;
&amp; byggi&dtail; als many abbays as &thorn;er was lettres in
&thorn;e Abce.  And in euer-ilk one of &thorn;aim he lefte a letter of
golde.  And at &thorn;e laste, whe&ntail; his so&ntail; Lowis was
crowny&dtail;, he was fu&llbar; of gude werkis &amp; decesi&dtail;,
and was beri&dtail; at Aquis Granum in a kurk of ou&rtail; Ladye
&thorn;at he byggi&dtail;.  And yit or he dye&dtail; he calli&dtail;
samen a&llbar; his prelattis, &amp; gaff &thorn;aim a&llbar; his
tresurs to distribute &thorn;aim wha&rtail; &thorn;aim &thorn;oght
nede emang &thorn;er kurkis.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Katerine Virginis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Som tyme &thorn;er come a monk of Rothomagence vnto &thorn;e
monkes &amp; &thorn;e abbay &thorn;at is o&ntail; &thorn;e Mownte of
Synay, and &thorn;er he abade in serves of God &amp; Saynt
Katry&ntail; vij yere.  And he was a passand devoute ma&ntail;; and he
prayed evur vnto Saynt Katry&ntail; at he mott hafe so&mtail;
relyk&ktee; of hur bonys.  And sodanlie, as he satt at his prayers,
&thorn;er was putt in his han&dtail;, at he wiste nevur how come, hur
little fynger; and he thanki&dtail; God &thorn;erof, &amp; Saynt
Katry&ntail;, &amp; had it home vnto his monasterie, and &thorn;er it
is wurshuppi&dtail; vnto &thorn;is day.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iterum de Sancta Katerina.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede of a ma&ntail; &thorn;at was passand devoute vnto Saynt
Katry&ntail;, &amp; made his prayers speciallie vnto hur <NOTE ID="P291.N1">MS. hy&mtail;.</NOTE> a long while &amp; besoght hur to helpe hy&mtail;.
So afterwer&dtail; he forgatt hur, &amp; made nott his



<PB N="292">

prayers nor his offran&dtail; vnto hur, nor did hur nott wurshu&ptail;
as he was wunte to doo, bod cesi&dtail; &thorn;eroff.  So o&ntail; a
tyme as he was in his prayers he fe&llbar; o&ntail; slepe, and
hy&mtail; &thorn;oght &thorn;at he saw in a visio&ntail; a grete
multitude of virgyns goyng o&ntail; a raw by hy&mtail;.  And emang
&thorn;aim ane &thorn;at was passan&dtail; shynan&dtail; &amp; fayr
forby a&llbar; &thorn;e toder, whe&ntail; sho come nere hy&mtail; sho
cover&dtail; hur face &thorn;at he sulde not se hur, and so sho
passi&dtail; away by hy&mtail; &amp; he mot se a&llbar; &thorn;e toder
facis bod hurs.  And he had grete merve&llbar; what sho was at
shyny&dtail; so forbe a&llbar; &thorn;e toder, &amp; hid hur face
&thorn;at he sulde not se hur.  And one of &thorn;aim, whe&ntail; he
spurryd what sho was, tolde hy&mtail; at sho was Katry&ntail;, whilk
&thorn;at he was wunte to know &amp; to do wurshu&ptail; to.  "And
becauce," sho sai&dtail;, "at &thorn;ou hase now forgetty&ntail; hur
&amp; giffes none almos-dede in wurshu&ptail; of hur, nor makis no
prayer vnto hur nor wurshuppis her no&yogh;t as &thorn;ou was wunte to
do, &thorn;erfo&rtail; sho covers hur face whe&ntail; sho passis by
the, att &thorn;ou sulde nott know what sho was becauce &thorn;ou had
forgette&ntail; to know hur."  et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Labor manuum est necessarius.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Arsenius a&llbar; his life-tyme he vsi&dtail; at sitt &amp; wurk a
crafte with his handis, &amp; he had evur so meki&llbar; &thorn;oght
of &thorn;e Passio&ntail; of ou&rtail; Lor&dtail;, &thorn;at he had
alway in his boso&mtail; a clothe to wype his ene with, he wepi&dtail;
so whe&ntail; he thoght &thorn;ero&ntail;.  And a&llbar; &thorn;e
night he wolde be in his prayers &amp; slepe nott, &amp; in &thorn;e
mornyng whe&ntail; he was wery for wakyng &amp; liste slepe,
&thorn;a&ntail; he walde say &thorn;us; "Co&mtail;, &thorn;ou
vnthrifti servan&dtail;, slepe!"  And so sittan&dtail; he wol&dtail;
slepe a while, and &thorn;a&ntail; onone he wolde rise &amp; say; "Itt
sufficis vnto a mon&ktee;, &amp; he had neuer so grete labur, to hafe
a nyght slepe ans in a yere, or ilk nyght to hafe ane how&rtail;
slepe."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Laborem in presenti Deus reddet in futuro, et quanto
plus laborauerunt, tanto magis merentur.  et c&curl;.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede of ane hermet &thorn;at dwelte in wildernes, and &thorn;e
watir was passand far&rtail; fro his ce&llbar;.  And o&ntail; a tyme
as he went for

<PB N="293">

watir he wex ir&ktee;, &amp; sett hy&mtail; dow&ntail; &amp;
sai&dtail;; "Whatt nedis me &thorn;us to labur whe&ntail; I may
dwe&llbar; harde be &thorn;e watir &amp; I wi&llbar;?"  And alssone he
was war of a ma&ntail; &thorn;at folowed after hy&mtail; &amp;
telli&dtail; his fute-steppis, and he aski&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp;
sai&dtail;; "What erte &thorn;ou?"  And he sai&dtail; agay&ntail;; "I
a&mtail; &thorn;e aunge&llbar; off God sent for to nowmer &thorn;i
fute-steppis, at &thorn;i mede may a noder day he rewardid vnto
&thorn;e after &thorn;at &thorn;i labur is."  And &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;is hermett with a strong wytt removi&dtail; his ce&llbar; v
myle ferrer fro &thorn;e watir.  et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Lacrimarum habundancia multum valet ad
compassionem.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> On a day whe&ntail; Sancta [Maria] de Oginiez <NOTE ID="P293.N1">MS. Sancta Deoginiez.</NOTE> satt &thorn;inkan&dtail; of &thorn;e benefice of
Almighti God, how largelie he gaff &thorn;aim vnto mans kyn&dtail;,
sho tuke suche a compunccio&ntail; &amp; fe&llbar; opo&ntail;
suc&hbar; a wepyng, &thorn;at as sho went abowte in &thorn;e kurk
me&ntail; mot hafe folow&dtail; hur steppis be &thorn;e confluens of
&thorn;e teris of hur ee&ntail; &thorn;at fe&llbar; dow&ntail;
o&ntail; &thorn;e payment, vnto so meku&llbar; &thorn;at a long tyme
sho mot nowder luke o&ntail; &thorn;e crucifyx nor speke, nor yitt
here no noder speke, of &thorn;e Passio&ntail; of Criste,
&thorn;atte&ntail; evur sho fe&llbar; in swone as sho had bene
dea&dtail;.  &amp; &thorn;erfo&rtail; to restrene hur wepyng sho lefte
thynkyng of &thorn;e manhede of Criste &amp; toke hur to vmbethynkyng
of His godde&dtail;, at be &thorn;inkyng &thorn;erof sho mott take a
comfurt&hbar;.  Nevur-&thorn;e-les hur wepyng was evur mo&rtail; &amp;
more whe&ntail; sho thoght of His godhed, als meku&llbar; as it was
whe&ntail; sho thoght of His manhede.  And &thorn;us hur sorow was
renewi&dtail; and hur sawle prikki&dtail; with a swete
compunccio&ntail;.  et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Laborare debet monachus vt cogitaciones malas
euadat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Paulus Heremita, &thorn;at was a moste provid ma&ntail; emang alde
fadurs, o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; he liffi&dtail; in wildrenes, &amp;
had bod esi fude bod of &thorn;e frute of &thorn;e pal&mtail; tre, and
if he wroght oght with his handis no ma&ntail; wolde giff hy&mtail;
noght &thorn;erfo&rtail; becauce he was so fer fro townys &amp; no
ma&ntail; come nere hy&mtail;, becauce he wol&dtail; somwyse be



<PB N="294">

occupye&dtail; ilka day, he wal&dtail; gaddur samen a grete meneya of
palmelevis &amp; bry&ntail; &thorn;aim, in exsample &thorn;at he did
so&mtail; bodele labur for his sustentacio&ntail;; provand be
&thorn;att a monk myght not be in a place with-oute laboryng with his
handis, or els he mot not esskape many i&llbar; thoghtis &amp;
vnthrifti.  et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Lacrimarum impetus retineri non possunt quia
flante spiritu vehementi fluunt aque.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> On a day befo&rtail; &thorn;e Gude Fryday, <NOTE ID="P294.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">has another</HI> whe&ntail; <HI REND="i">here</HI>.</NOTE>
Maria de Oginiez, whe&ntail; &thorn;e passio&ntail; of A&llbar;myghti
God neghid nere, sho &thorn;oght sho wol&dtail; suffer a passio&ntail;
hur selfe in wurshu&ptail; of His passyo&ntail;; and sho fe&llbar;
vpo&ntail; a grete wepyng &amp; a sorow &amp; a syghyng
&thorn;erfo&rtail;.  And so as sho sat &thorn;us wepand in &thorn;e
kur&ktee;, a preste come to hur &amp; blamy&dtail; hur &amp; bad hur
lefe hur wepyng &amp; say hur prayers in sylens.  And sho, knowyng
wele enogh at sho mot not forbere wepyng, rase vp&ptail; &amp; went
furt&hbar; of &thorn;e kur&ktee; and hid hur in a privay place far
thens; &amp; &thorn;er sho wepi&dtail; &amp; besoght Almighti God in
hur prayers &thorn;at he wolde shew vnto &thorn;is preste &thorn;at a
ma&ntail; may not restre&ntail; hy&mtail; fro wepyng whe&ntail; it
flewis vppo&ntail; be grace of &thorn;e Holie Gaste.  And o&ntail; a
day as &thorn;is preste was att mes, be prompyng of &thorn;e Holie
Gaste he fe&llbar; o&ntail; suche a wepyng &thorn;at he was
nerehan&dtail; strang&lbar;ed &thorn;er-with.  And ay &thorn;e mare at
he labur&dtail; to restrene hy&mtail; &thorn;e more he wepy&dtail;,
vnto so meku&llbar; at nott alonelie hy&mtail; selfe, bod also his
buke &amp; a&llbar; &thorn;e alta&rtail; clothis war a&llbar; bod
water with his wepyng.  And afterwar&dtail; &thorn;is holie
maydy&ntail; come vnto &thorn;is preste and tel&dtail; hy&mtail;
a&llbar; &thorn;is als playnlie as sho had sene it hur aw&ntail;
selfe, &amp; sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "Now ye hafe lerny&dtail; be
experiens &thorn;at a ma&ntail; may not with-draw hy&mtail; fro wepyng
for &thorn;e passyo&ntail; of Almighti Go&dtail;, whe&ntail; he
thynkys &thorn;ero&ntail; &amp; is movid &thorn;erto be the Holie
Gaste."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Lacrime contricionis impetrantur orationibus

sanctorum.  Infra de Oratione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Laicus non debet stare in choro et audire diuina.

Supra Ambrosij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>



<PB N="295">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXXX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Lantgrauius Lowicus.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how &thorn;at &thorn;is Lantgrauius Lowicus was a
passan&dtail; grete tyran&dtail; and a mysdoer.  And agay&ntail;
&thorn;at he sulde dye he commawndi&dtail; &thorn;aim at was aboute
hy&mtail; &thorn;at als tyte as he was dea&dtail; &thorn;ai sulde
clethe hy&mtail; in a monkis cowle of &thorn;e Ceustus ordur, bod not
or he war dea&dtail;; &amp; so &thorn;ai di&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; he
was so cled, one of his knyghtis luki&dtail; opo&ntail; hy&mtail;
&amp; sai&dtail; &thorn;us in skor&ntail;; "Lo! hy&mtail; &thorn;is is
not now like my lor&dtail; in a&llbar; his vertues, ffor he was a wurthi
knyght, &amp; now he is a passan&dtail; gude monke &amp; kepis his
sylence passand wele."  So his sawle was broght vnto &thorn;e prince
of He&llbar; syttan&dtail; opo&ntail; &thorn;e pytt bra, &amp; he
hel&dtail; a cop&ptail; in his han&dtail; &amp; sai&dtail; vnto
hy&mtail;; "Welco&mtail;, ou&rtail; wele-belufi&dtail; fren&dtail;!
Shew hy&mtail;," he sai&dtail;, "your chawmers!"  And belife was
shewi&dtail; hy&mtail; a&llbar; &thorn;e paynys.  And &thorn;a&ntail;
he say&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; agay&ntail;; "Drynk, fren&dtail;, of my
cop&ptail;!"  And &thorn;uf a&llbar; he war not <NOTE ID="P295.N1">Not <HI REND="i">omitted, and added above the line</HI>.</NOTE>
welewilli&dtail; &thorn;erto, yit he was compelli&dtail; to
dryn&ktee;; and als sone as he had done &thorn;er come oute stynkkand
flawmys oute of his ene, his nease-thrillis, &amp; his eris.  And
after &thorn;is he sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "Now &thorn;ou sa&llbar;
se my pitt &thorn;at is withoute&ntail; botho&mtail;."  And belife it
was opyn&dtail; &amp; he caste&ntail; &thorn;erin.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Latroni possunt adaptari que supra dicuntur de

ffure, et infra de predone et raptore.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Laudacio.  Laudant multi aliquem in comparacione

alterius.  Supra de comparacione.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXXXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Laudem appetunt aliqui de bonis
operibus.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how o&ntail; a tyme, whe&ntail; a ma&ntail; spirri&dtail;
Macharius whi he suffer&dtail; so meku&llbar; honger in wyldernes,
&thorn;at <NOTE ID="P295.N2">Harl. MS. qui in monasterio ebdomadis integris abstinens non sensisse esuriem.</NOTE> mot wekelie hafe





<PB N="296">

byddy&ntail; in his abbay &amp; suffred no honger, he ansswer&dtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "For here is no wittnes of &thorn;i
faste &thorn;at sulde nuriss&hbar; &thorn;e with lovyng, nor at mot
sustey&ntail; &thorn;e.  And &thorn;er mans serves &amp; refresshyng
of a vay&ntail; glorie makis &thorn;e fatt."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Laudem nolunt aliqui acquirere per facta enormia.
Infra de memoria.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Laudes adulatoris contempnunt sapientes.  Supra
de adulacione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Laudem fugiunt aliqui ne in ea dilectentur.  Infra
de vanitate.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXXXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Laurencij Martiris.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Legenda Lombardica,' of Eusodia &thorn;at was doghter
vnto Theodose &thorn;e Emperour, how sho was vexi&dtail; with a
fen&dtail;, and was had vnto Constantynople to &thorn;e body of Saynt
Stephan to be curi&dtail;.  And &thorn;is fen&dtail; spak within hur
&amp; sai&dtail;; "I will not pas oute o&ntail; hur bod if Stephan
co&mtail; to Rome, for so it is &thorn;e apostels wi&llbar;."  And so,
be &thorn;e consent of &thorn;e pope &amp; &thorn;e Emperou&rtail;,
&thorn;e bodie of Saynt Stephan was sent vnto Rome be &thorn;e Grekis,
with counand at &thorn;ai sul&dtail; bryng vnto Constantynople
&thorn;e bonys of Saynt Laurens.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai come at
Rome with hy&mtail; &amp; sett dow&ntail; his bodie in ecclesia Sancti
Petri ad Uincula, &thorn;ase at sulde bere hy&mtail; myght gett
hy&mtail; no ferrer.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is fen&dtail; cryed
agay&ntail; in &thorn;e maydy&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Ye labur in
vay&ntail;, for he hase not chosy&ntail; his seate here, bod att his
bruther Laurens."  And &thorn;ai bare &thorn;e bodye thedur, &amp;
onone &thorn;e maydy&ntail; was hale.  And Saynt Laurens, as he had
bene ioyfu&llbar; of his bruther commyng, remowi&dtail; hy&mtail; vnto
&thorn;e ta side of &thorn;e sepulc&rtail;, &amp; left &thorn;e toder
syde voyde vnto his bruther.  An&dtail; &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e
Grekis putt &thorn;er handis to take Saynt Laurence away, &amp;
&thorn;ai fe&llbar; dow&ntail; vnto &thorn;e erth as &thorn;ai had
bene fonde.  And with-in x dayes after &thorn;ai war a&llbar;
dea&dtail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; a voyce was harde in Rome &thorn;at sayde;
" <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">O, felix Roma! et c&curl;.</FOREIGN> O!
&thorn;ou happy Rome, &thorn;at sparris bothe in a grafe &thorn;e
bodie of Saynt Laurens &thorn;e Hyspany, &amp; &thorn;e bodie of Saynt
Stephan of Ierusalem."

<PB N="297">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXXXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Laurencius accusat facientes sibi
iniuriam.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in &thorn;e 'Meracles of ou&rtail; Ladie,' how at Rome
&thorn;er was a yong ma&ntail; &thorn;at hyght Stepha&ntail;,
&thorn;at vsi&dtail; gladlie to take giftis &amp; so for to forbar
right of many folke in &thorn;e law.  And he wronguslie tuke away
&amp; hel&dtail; in possessio&ntail; vnto hy&mtail; selfe iij howsis of
Saynt Laurens kurk, and a garthy&ntail; of Saynt Agnes kur&ktee;.  So
hy&mtail; happen&dtail; to be seke &amp; sulde dye, and hy&mtail;
&thorn;oght he was broght befo&rtail; &thorn;e iugement of Almighti
Go&dtail;.  And onone as Saynt Laurens saw hy&mtail;, he come vnto
hy&mtail; with a grete indignacio&ntail; &amp; iij tymys he
thrusti&dtail; hy&mtail; be &thorn;e ar&mtail;, &amp; &thorn;at sare,
&amp; crusi&dtail; it att it warki&dtail; gretlie with.  And Saynt
Agnes nor none o&thorn;er vyrgy&ntail; wol&dtail; nott ans luke
o&ntail; hy&mtail;, bod turny&dtail; &thorn;er facis fra
hy&mtail;-war&dtail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e iustis gaff a
sentans of hy&mtail; &amp; sai&dtail;; becauce he tuke o&thorn;er mens
gude fro &thorn;aim &amp; selde &thorn;e treut&hbar; for takyng of
giftis, he sulde be putt into &thorn;e place at Iudas &thorn;e traytur
was in.  And &thorn;a&ntail; come Sanctus Proiectus, whome &thorn;is
Stephan had had grete deuocio&ntail; to in his life, &amp; prayed
Saynt Laurens &amp; Saynt Agnes to forgiff hy&mtail;.  And so
ou&rtail; Ladye &amp; &thorn;ai prayed for hy&mtail; vnto &thorn;is
iustis, to so meku&llbar; he graunti&dtail; &thorn;at his saul [sul]de
<NOTE ID="P297.N1">MS. his saulde goo.</NOTE> goo agay&ntail; vnto his body, &amp; &thorn;er
he sulde do penans xxx<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> dayes.  And our Ladie gaff hy&mtail; in
commandment &thorn;at he sulde daylie say &thorn;is psalme, ' <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Beati immaculati,</FOREIGN>' whils he liffi&dtail;.  And
whe&ntail; his saule come vnto his bodie agay&ntail;, his ar&mtail;
was als bla &amp; als sare with &thorn;e thrustyng of Saynt Laurens as
he had suffre&dtail; it evy&ntail; o&ntail; his body, whilk
taky&ntail; was apo&ntail; hy&mtail; ewhils he liffi&dtail;.  And
&thorn;at at he had wronguslie taky&ntail; away, he restori&dtail; itt
and did penans &thorn;erfo&rtail;.  &amp; opo&ntail; &thorn;e xxx<HI REND="sup">ti</HI>
day he passi&dtail; vnto Almighti God&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXXXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Laurencius se honorantes in necessitate adiuuat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Legenda Lombardica' whe&ntail; &thorn;e Emperour
Henrie and Ranegunde <NOTE ID="P297.N2">MS. Ranegude.</NOTE> his wyfe abade alway clene
virgyns, &thorn;urg&hbar;





<PB N="298">

instigacio&ntail; of &thorn;e fen&dtail;, he suspecte his wyfe with a
knyght, &amp; made hur for to gang o&ntail; hate coles, barefute, xv
fute lang.  And als sone as sho bega&ntail; to ga sho sai&dtail; in
&thorn;is maner of wise; "Lor&dtail; Criste!  As &thorn;ou knowis that
I a&mtail; vnfyli&dtail; bothe of Henry my husban&dtail; &amp;
a&llbar; o&thorn;er, so I beseke &thorn;e helpe me!"  &amp; with
&thorn;at &thorn;is Emperour was esshamy&dtail; &amp; gaff hur
o&ntail; &thorn;e cheke with hys nefe.  And &thorn;a&ntail; a voyce
sayde vnto hur; "Marie &thorn;at is a mayde&ntail; hase delyver&dtail;
&thorn;e becauce &thorn;ou erte a mayde&ntail;."  And &thorn;a&ntail;
sho passi&dtail; &thorn;urg&hbar; a&llbar; &thorn;is fire vnhurte.
And efterwar&dtail;, agay&ntail; &thorn;is Henry sulde dye, a grete
multitude of fendis come be &thorn;e ce&llbar; of ane hermett, and he
oppyn&dtail; his wyndow &amp; aski&dtail; one of &thorn;aim what
&thorn;ai wer.  And &thorn;ai ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
sai&dtail;; "We er a legio&ntail; of fendis &thorn;at bownys vs vnto
&thorn;e dea&dtail; of &thorn;e Emperour Henrie, to luke if we
ca&ntail; fyn&dtail; any thyng of owrs in hy&mtail;."  And he
chargi&dtail; hy&mtail; to co&mtail; agay&ntail; by hy&mtail; &amp;
te&llbar; hy&mtail; how &thorn;ai had done.  And he come agay&ntail;
&amp; tolde hy&mtail; &thorn;ai had not spe&dtail;, &amp; sai&dtail;;
"Ewhils &thorn;e fals suspecte &thorn;at he had in his wife &amp;
a&llbar; his oder i&llbar; dedis war weye&dtail; in a weyscale with
his gude dedis, &thorn;at swythy&ntail; Laurens broght a grete hevy
pott of gol&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; his evu&llbar; dedis was like to
hafe bene &thorn;e heviar, he kest it in-to &thorn;e tother weyscale,
&amp; it was hevyar &amp; weye&dtail; a&llbar; dow&ntail;.  &amp; with
&thorn;at," he sai&dtail;, "I was angrie, and starte vnto &thorn;e
pott &amp; brakk of &thorn;e tone ere &thorn;eroff; and &thorn;is pott
was a chales at &thorn;is Henre had giffe&ntail; vnto Ceustus ordur,
in wurshu&ptail; of Saynt Laurens.  And becauce it was so grete, he
garte make it ij eris, at it mot be lifti&dtail; vp by."  And
&thorn;is Emperour was dede &thorn;e same tyme as &thorn;e hermett had
knowlege.  And he garte luke &thorn;e chales an&dtail; [&thorn;e] ta
ere wanty&dtail;, as &thorn;e fen&dtail; say&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXXXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Leonis Pape.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in his 'Meracles <NOTE ID="P298.N1">Latin MSS. Ex Miraculis Beate Virginis.</NOTE> ' how Leo &thorn;e
pape opo&ntail; a Pace day sai&dtail; mes in a kurk of ou&rtail;
Ladie, and as he was howsyllan&dtail; criste&ntail; me&ntail;, ilkone
in &thorn;er ordur, a certa&ntail; womma&ntail; kissi&dtail; his
han&dtail;, &thorn;urg&hbar;



<PB N="299">

&thorn;e whilk he had a huge temptacio&ntail; in his fless&hbar;.  And
so &thorn;is holie ma&ntail; &thorn;oght he wolde venge &thorn;is
temptacio&ntail; in hy&mtail; selfe, &amp; &thorn;e same day &thorn;at
han&dtail; at slander&dtail; hy&mtail; so, privalie he cut it off
&amp; keste it fro hy&mtail;.  And in &thorn;e mene while &thorn;er
rase emang &thorn;e commo&ntail; peple a gret murmor whi &thorn;e pope
sai&dtail; not mes as he was wunt to doo.  Tha&ntail; &thorn;is Leo
made his prayer vnto ou&rtail; Ladie, Saynt Marie, &amp; commytt
hy&mtail; a&llbar; vnto hur providens; and sho onone come vnto
hy&mtail; &amp; with hur holie handis sho restori&dtail; his
han&dtail; agay&ntail; vnto his ar&mtail;, &amp; commawndi&dtail;
hy&mtail; for to go furt&hbar; &amp; do his mes, &amp; offer &thorn;e
sacrament vnto hur so&ntail; as he was wunte to do.  And tha&ntail;
&thorn;is Leo prechid befo&rtail; a&llbar; &thorn;e pepy&llbar;, &amp;
tolde &thorn;aim what had happen&dtail; hy&mtail;, and shewi&dtail;
&thorn;aim his han&dtail; how it was cott off, &amp; &thorn;orow
ou&rtail; Ladie restori&dtail; agay&ntail; vnto his ar&mtail;. et
c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXXXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Leonardi Confessoris.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in his Legen&dtail; how &thorn;er was a knyght
preson&dtail; in Bretany, &amp; he made his prayers speciallie vnto
Saynt Leonar&dtail; to helpe hy&mtail;.  And onone, at a&llbar;
me&ntail; saw &amp; might know hy&mtail;, Saynt Leonar&dtail;
apperi&dtail; in myddest of &thorn;e mute-ha&llbar;, &amp; went into
&thorn;e preso&ntail; &amp; brak his fetters &amp; put &thorn;aim in
&thorn;e mans han&dtail;, &amp; opynlie emang a&llbar; me&ntail; he
broght hy&mtail; furth &thorn;orow &thorn;aim.  And a&llbar; &thorn;at
saw had so meku&llbar; wonder &thorn;erof &thorn;at &thorn;ai
wa&rtail; passynglie astony&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXXXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Legatum male custoditum amittitur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how som tyme &thorn;er was a ma&ntail; &thorn;at
whe&ntail; he dye&dtail; bewytt vnto iij sonnys &thorn;at he had ane
ass, so &thorn;at one sul&dtail; labur it a day, and a noder a noder
day, an&dtail; &thorn;e iij &thorn;e thri&dtail; day, &amp; at &thorn;ai sulde
vpholde it &amp; giff it meate emang &thorn;aim.  And opo&ntail;
&thorn;e furste day &thorn;e eldeste bruther had &thorn;is ass, &amp;
labur&dtail; it sore and gaff it nothyng to eate, ffor he vmthoght
hy&mtail; &thorn;at his medy&llbar; bruther sul&dtail; hafe it
&thorn;e secun&dtail; day &amp; he wolde giff it meate enog&hbar;.
And o&ntail; &thorn;e secun&dtail; day

<PB N="300">

&thorn;is secun&dtail; brother had &thorn;is ass, &amp; labur&dtail;
it sore, &amp; gaff it no mo&rtail; meat no mo&rtail; &thorn;an his
furste bruther di&dtail;; ffor he vmthoght hy&mtail; &thorn;at his
thrid bruther, &thorn;at was richest of &thorn;aim a&llbar;, sulde
hafe it o&ntail; &thorn;e thri&dtail; day, &amp; he sai&dtail; he
wol&dtail; giff it enog&hbar;.  And vppo&ntail; &thorn;e thrid day
&thorn;e iij bruther had it, &amp; labur&dtail; it &amp; gaf it no
meate, ffor he vmthoght hy&mtail; &thorn;at his ij brethir had bothe
ha&dtail; it, &amp; &thorn;ai had giffe&ntail; it meat enog&hbar;, for
&thorn;ai war richer me&ntail; &thorn;a&ntail; he.  And &thorn;us for
grete labur &amp; no sustentacio&ntail; &thorn;is ass dye&dtail;;
&amp; &thorn;us for &thorn;er covatis none of &thorn;aim had gude
o&ntail; itt.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Legatarij debent pro legatoribus 
<NOTE ID="P300.N1">MS. legatarijs.  Lat. MSS. legatoribus.</NOTE>  orare.  Supra de

elemosina, xi 
<NOTE ID="P300.N2">MS. iij.</NOTE> .</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Leo virginem defendebat a corrupcione.  Infra de

virginitate, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXXXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Leo custodiebat asinum ex precepto beati
Ieronimi.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> O&ntail; a day whe&ntail; Saynt Iero&mtail; satt with his brethir,
sodanlie &thorn;er come a haltand lio&ntail; &amp; went into &thorn;e
abbay.  And onone as &thorn;e brethir saw hy&mtail; &thorn;ai fled
a&llbar;, and Saynt Iero&mtail; rase &amp; mett [him] as he had bene a
geste.  And &thorn;is lyo&ntail; lifte v&ptail; his sare fute &amp;
lete hy&mtail; se it, and he calli&dtail; his brethir &amp; garte one
of &thorn;aim wassh it, &amp; lay&dtail; salvis &amp; medcyns
&thorn;erto, made of herbys, &amp; onone &thorn;is lio&ntail; was hale
and was als meke as a hors.  And Saynt Iero&mtail; chargid hy&mtail;
&thorn;at he sul&dtail; evur[e]day take charge of &amp; kepe ane ass
&thorn;at broght hy&mtail; &amp; his brethir fewe&llbar; fro &thorn;e wud,
&amp; he wolde euerilk day at dew tyme hafe &thorn;is ass of &thorn;e
felde &amp; bryng it hame, &amp; kepid hur surelie.  So o&ntail; a day
as &thorn;is ass was pasturan&dtail;, &thorn;is lyo&ntail; liste wele
slepe, &amp; layde hy&mtail; dow&ntail; &amp; fe&llbar; apo&ntail; a
sad slepe; and &thorn;er come merchandes with camels be &thorn;is ass
away, &amp; saw at no bodie was stirran&dtail;, &amp; &thorn;ai tuke
&thorn;isass with &thorn;aim.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai war gone,
&thorn;is lyo&ntail; waken&dtail; &amp; myssy&dtail; his felow, &amp;
soght here &amp; &thorn;er romyan&dtail; &amp; couthe not fynde hit.
And whe&ntail; he saw he cuthe not fyn&dtail; it, he went home
a&llbar; hevylie vnto &thorn;e Abbay, &amp; stude at





<PB N="301">

&thorn;e yate oferro&mtail; &amp; durste co&mtail; no ne&rtail;
becauce he broght not hame &thorn;e ass; &amp; he durste not co&mtail;
in as he was wunte to do.  And &thorn;e monkis, whe&ntail; &thorn;ai
say hy&mtail; at he come home &amp; broght not &thorn;e ass with
hy&mtail; as he was wunt to do, &amp; &thorn;ai trowed he had
ety&ntail; hur, &amp; here-for &thorn;ai withdrew his meate fro
hy&mtail; at &thorn;ai war wunte to giff hy&mtail; &amp; wol&dtail;
not giff hy&mtail; it, bod bad hy&mtail; go &amp; ete &thorn;e
hynder-en&dtail; of &thorn;e ass as he had ety&ntail; &thorn;e
for-en&dtail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; Saynt Iero&mtail; chargi&dtail;
&thorn;is lyo&ntail; to do &thorn;e ass offes, &amp; to bryng home wod
o&ntail; his bak daylie to &thorn;e kychy&ntail; as it was wunt to do;
&amp; mekelie he di&dtail; it as he was commandi&dtail; &amp;
gruchi&dtail; nothyng &thorn;erwith.  So o&ntail; a day as &thorn;is
lyo&ntail; was walkan&dtail; be his one, he was war of &thorn;ies
merchandis co&mtail; of ferro&mtail; with &thorn;er camels
lady&ntail;, &amp; &thorn;is lyo&ntail; ass&curl; at he kepi&dtail;
emang &thorn;aim.  And with a grete romying he ra&ntail; opo&ntail;
&thorn;aim, &amp; a&llbar; &thorn;e me&ntail; fled &amp; war passand
fer&dtail;, and a&llbar; &thorn;ies camels &amp; &thorn;is ass, bothe
with merchandis as &thorn;ai war lady&ntail;, he broght vnto &thorn;e
Abbay.  And whe&ntail; Saynt Iero&mtail; saw, he commawndi&dtail; his
brethir to giff &thorn;ies cate&llbar; meate, and &thorn;a&ntail; to
abyde &thorn;e wi&llbar; of Go&dtail;.  &amp; &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;is lio&ntail; come into &thorn;e abbay as he was wunte to do,
&amp; wente to Saynt Iero&mtail; &amp; syne fro monk to monke, &amp;
fawny&dtail; &thorn;aim &amp; lowti&dtail; vnto &thorn;e ert&hbar;,
evy&ntail; as he had aski&dtail; &thorn;aim forgyfnes.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e merchandis come &amp; knew &thorn;er fawte
&amp; aski&dtail; Saynt Iero&mtail; forgyfnes; &amp; he forgaff
&thorn;aim whe&ntail; &thorn;ai confessi&dtail; how &thorn;ai
di&dtail;, &amp; lete &thorn;aim hafe a&llbar; &thorn;er gudis
agay&ntail;.  And &thorn;ai gaff &thorn;e abbay to amendis a messur of
oyle, and ban&dtail; &thorn;aim &amp; &thorn;er successurs for evur
more yerelie to giff vnto &thorn;at abbay &thorn;e same messur, and so
&thorn;ai do yerelie vnto &thorn;is day.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Lena impetrat quod petit.  Infra de oratione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Letania cantari 
<NOTE ID="P301.N1">MS. cantaria.</NOTE>  debet.  Supra de cantu, vj.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXXXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Leprosus.  Leprosis seruire est deo
seruire.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Theobaldus, &thorn;at was &thorn;e noble Erle of Campanye, with
grete deuocio&ntail; wol&dtail; visit layser howsis, and befo&rtail;
his caste&llbar;-yate &thorn;er dwelte a layser.  And &thorn;is
lor&dtail; had in condicio&ntail;, &thorn;at als ofte as



<PB N="302">

he come be his howse away he wolde go in &amp; wass&hbar; hys fete
&amp; giff hy&mtail; almos.  So it happend afterwar&dtail; &thorn;is
layzer dye&dtail; &amp; was beri&dtail;, &amp; &thorn;e erle wiste
[not].  So hy&mtail; happen&dtail; afterwar&dtail; co&mtail; be
&thorn;is howse &amp; wiste not at &thorn;e layzer was dead, bod he
went in as he was wunt to do, &amp; &thorn;er he fan&dtail;, not
&thorn;e layzer, bod Almyghti God in &thorn;e layser clothyng, and he
did hy&mtail; serves as he was wunte to do; and in his harte he felid
a grete swetnes.  And whe&ntail; he was gone furt&hbar;, one of his
me&ntail; tolde hy&mtail; &thorn;at &thorn;is layzer was dea&dtail;
&amp; berid in suche a place.  And als tite as he harde &thorn;is,
&thorn;is trew ma&ntail; thanki&dtail; Almi&yogh;tty Go&dtail;, whome
&thorn;at he adli&dtail; to serve in His aw&ntail; presens; and
afterwar&dtail; he servi&dtail; Hy&mtail; ofter in his membres.  et
c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXL.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Leprosis seruire credens deo servit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> In Frawnce &thorn;er was a ma&ntail; of grete mekenes &amp;
mercie, &amp; inspecia&llbar; vnto laysers, vnto so meku&llbar;
&thorn;at wharesom-evur he mett &thorn;aim he wolde giff &thorn;aim
almos.  So o&ntail; a tyme hy&mtail; happyn&dtail; to mete a ma&ntail;
&thorn;at was passan&dtail; horrible lepre, &amp; wolde hafe
giffe&ntail; hy&mtail; almos.  And he sai&dtail;; "Nay, I wi&llbar; no
money.  Bod I pray &thorn;e wype &thorn;e filthe fro my nease."  And
&thorn;is ma&ntail;, furste with his fynger &amp; syne with his sarke
skirte, wypid it als softlye as he cuthe.  &THORN;a&ntail; &thorn;e
layser ma&ntail; say&dtail;; "I may not suffer so meky&llbar;
sharpnes, &amp; &thorn;erfo&rtail; I pray &thorn;e lyk&ktee; it away
with &thorn;i tong."  And he neuer-&thorn;e-les, &thorn;uf a&llbar;
his natur vggid &thorn;er-wit, yit he lykki&dtail; it away with his
tong.  And sodanlie oute of &thorn;e layzer nese in-to his mouthe
&thorn;er fe&llbar; ij precious stonys <NOTE ID="P302.N1">Lat. MSS. Subito gemma preciosissima in os suum de naribus leprosi cecidit, et, ipso uidente, ad celum ascendit.</NOTE> , &amp;
furthwith, evy&ntail; at he say, &thorn;is layser steven&dtail;
v&ptail; vnto hevy&ntail;. et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Leprosi specie deus hospicio recipitur.  Supra de

hospicio.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Leticiam aliquando gerit paupertas, et diuicia

tristiciam.  Supra de diuicijs.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Lex.  De Lege, et c&curl; 
<NOTE ID="P302.N2">A discourse on Law <HI REND="i">omitted here.</HI></NOTE> .</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>



<PB N="303">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXLI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Leges imperatorum debent obseruari.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Commestor Mallius Torquetus <NOTE ID="P303.N1">Harl. MS. Manlius Torquatus.</NOTE> , &thorn;at was
a conselur of Rome, whe&ntail; he had bety&ntail; his so&ntail; with a
wan&dtail;, he strake hy&mtail; with ane ax, becauce he faght with his
enmys agayns &thorn;e commandment of &thorn;e concelurs; &amp;
neuer-&thorn;e-les yit he ouer-come &thorn;aim.  et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Leges quas imperatores faciunt eciam ipsi observare

debent.  Infra de prelato.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXLII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Liberalitas.  De Liberalitate.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Lantigonus <NOTE ID="P303.N2">Lat. MSS. Antigonus.</NOTE> , &thorn;at was kyng of
Macydony, o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; a pure ma&ntail; <NOTE ID="P303.N3">Lat. MSS. amicus.</NOTE> askid hy&mtail; a peny, he ansswer&dtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; said &thorn;at it was mare &thorn;a&ntail; a pure
ma&ntail; <NOTE ID="P303.N4">Lat. MSS. plus esse quam amicus deberet petere.</NOTE> sulde aske.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he
aski&dtail; hy&mtail; a halpeny, &amp; he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail;
&amp; sai&dtail;; "It is les &thorn;a&ntail; it semys a kyng for to
giff."  And Senec stude by &amp; saw, &amp; he sai&dtail; &thorn;is
was a fowle cauillacio&ntail;, whe&ntail; he mot nowder se &thorn;e
kyng giff &thorn;e pure ma&ntail; a peny, nor &thorn;e pure ma&ntail;
resayfe a halpeny of &thorn;e kyng; ffor &thorn;er is no &thorn;ing so
meku&llbar; made of as is &thorn;at &thorn;yng &thorn;at a ma&ntail;
giffis with his gude wy&llbar;. et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXLIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iterum de Liberalitate.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede of &thorn;e Emperou&rtail; Titus, how &thorn;at he was so
libera&llbar; of gifte &thorn;at o&ntail; a day whe&ntail; no
ma&ntail; come &amp; askid hy&mtail; noght, he sayd at evy&ntail; vnto
hys me&ntail;; "O, ye frendis!  This day hafe I loste!"

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Liberacio.  Liberat Maria incarceratos.  Infra de

Maria, ij.</FOREIGN>

<PB N="304">
</ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Liberant diuersi sancti diuersos.  Supra et infra in

locis suis.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Libido.  Infra de muliere.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Lingua mala multum est detestabilis.  Supra de

excommunicacione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Lingua aduocati est venalis.  Supra de Aduocato, iiij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Lingua mala turbat multos.  Supra de Iracundia, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXLIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Locucio.  Loqui non debent religiosi de rebus
pertinentibus
<NOTE ID="P304.N1">MS. impertinentibus.  Harl. MS. as above.</NOTE> ad uitam.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Whe&ntail; a meneya <NOTE ID="P304.N2">MS. meneza.</NOTE> of brether war at a
calacio&ntail; &amp; &thorn;ai spak to-gedur of &thorn;ingis &thorn;at
perteyny&dtail; vnto &thorn;e bodie, &thorn;er was one alde ma&ntail;
emang &thorn;aim &thorn;at hyght Corpreys.  &amp; he rase &amp; went
away, &amp; knokki&dtail; o&ntail; his breste &amp; sai&dtail;; "Wo is
&thorn;e, Corpres!  For &thorn;ou levis &thorn;ase &thorn;ingis
&thorn;at God commandi&dtail; &thorn;e, &thorn;at is to say, meknes
&amp; paciens &amp; sike o&thorn;er thingis lyke, and <NOTE ID="P304.N3">Harl. MS. et loqueris de hijs que deus non requirit a te.</NOTE> spekis nothyng of swilk &thorn;ingis as God askis of
&thorn;e." et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXLV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Loquendum est de rebus pertinentibus ad
saluacionem anime et edificacionem proximi.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> O&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; Saynt Petur prechi&dtail;, &thorn;er
was so&mtail; &thorn;at wolde mofe vnto hy&mtail; vnprofitable
questions, &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; he wolde say vnto &thorn;aim;
"&THORN;e tyme is shorte, &amp; &thorn;e dome of God drawis nere,
&amp; &thorn;erfo&rtail; befo&rtail; al thyngis latt vs seke how &amp;
of what maner of wise we sulde doo to gett vs euer-lastand life."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXLVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Loquentes multum verba stulta puniuntur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Som tyme &thorn;er was a no&ntail; &thorn;at was chaste of bodie,
bod sho wol&dtail; nott restrene hur tong fro fowle langwage; so hur
happend to dy









<PB N="305">

&amp; be berid in &thorn;e kur&ktee;.  And opo&ntail; &thorn;e night
after, he &thorn;at kepid &thorn;e kur&ktee; saw hur broght
befo&rtail; ane altar &amp; cut in sonder evy&ntail; be &thorn;e
myddeste.  &amp; &thorn;e [tone] parte was burny&dtail; and &thorn;e
toder parte putt in &thorn;e grafe agay&ntail;; and o&ntail; &thorn;e
mor&ntail; &thorn;ai mot se &thorn;e prynte apo&ntail; &thorn;e
merby&llbar; stonys, like as a woma&ntail; had bene bodelie
burny&dtail; &thorn;er.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Loquendum non est indifferenter coram omnibus.

Supra de augurio 
<NOTE ID="P305.N1">MS. augurrio.</NOTE> .</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Loqui non debemus de defectibus aliorum.  Supra

de iudicio, iij 
<NOTE ID="P305.N2">MS. i.</NOTE> .</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Loquendum est semper caute et non est demon

denominandus.  Supra de demone.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXLVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Loquendum non est nimis superbe.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> In &thorn;e iiij yere of Iustinya&ntail; was &thorn;er ij
bisshoppis, and &thorn;er enmys come o&ntail; &thorn;aim &amp;
pulli&dtail; &thorn;er tongis oute of &thorn;er hedis.
Afterwar&dtail; be revelacio&ntail; &thorn;ai wer restori&dtail; vnto
&thorn;er tongis &amp; mot speke, &amp; di&dtail; many meracles.  So
at &thorn;e laste &thorn;ai bega&ntail; to wax prowde of speche, and
onone, as God wol&dtail;, &thorn;ai wex bothe do&mtail;, &amp; did
neuer meracles after.  And Saynt Grego&rtail; tellis in his
'Dialoggis' &thorn;at &thorn;e tone of &thorn;aim fe&llbar; vnto
&thorn;e sy&ntail; of lichorie, &amp; he&rtail;-fo&rtail; God
deprivi&dtail; hy&mtail; of meracles-doyng; and &thorn;e toder of
&thorn;aim fe&llbar; vnto pride, &amp; loste a&llbar; &thorn;e vertue
of his meracles-doyng.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXLVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Lucrum quod cito adquiritur cito
expenditur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> The&rtail; was so&mtail; tyme in a cetie a passan&dtail; curios
barbur, and for euer-ilk man &thorn;at he shufe he tuke a peny, and at
&thorn;e weke-en&dtail; he mot pay for his bur&dtail; &amp; putt in
his purs ij or iij shelyng.  So hy&mtail; happen&dtail; o&ntail; a
tyme to here te&llbar; of a noder cete &thorn;at barburs tuke for ilk
ma&ntail; shavyng in a shelyng, and he tuke his instrumentis





<PB N="306">

with hy&mtail; &amp; &thorn;oght he wolde go dwe&llbar; &thorn;er.
Not-withstondyng, or he went, a&llbar; &thorn;at evur he gatt of his
wynnyng he spendid it &amp; made hy&mtail; mery &thorn;erwith.  So he
come vnto &thorn;e toder cetie &amp; sett vp his crafte, &amp;
o&ntail; &thorn;e furste day he gatt meku&llbar; money.  And he was
fay&ntail; &thorn;erof &amp; wente vnto &thorn;e bowcherie &amp;
thoght to by hy&mtail; fless&hbar; vnto his supper, &amp; it was
spitefu&llbar; dere, and so with-in a while he conseyvi&dtail;
&thorn;at, if a&llbar; he tuke neuer so meku&llbar; for a mans
shavyng, yit his meat &amp; his drynke koste so meki&llbar; &thorn;at
he mot not spare no syluer bod spendi&dtail; it euer as he gatt it.
And &thorn;a&ntail; he vmthoght hy&mtail; &amp; sai&dtail; vnto
hy&mtail; selfe; "I spend a&llbar; my wynnyng of my meatt &amp; my
drynk &amp; ca&ntail; not safe a peny, &thorn;uf a&llbar; I take a
shelyng for a shavyng, and whe&ntail; I tuke bod a peny for a shavyng,
I couthe wele spar so&mtail; syluer euer-ilk day, &amp; now I
ca&ntail; not so, for here I may not get my lyfelo&dtail;."  And he
gatt his gere to-gedur &amp; went agay&ntail; vnto &thorn;e toder
cetie &amp; right not in his purs.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXLIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ludus debet esse honestus.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Whe&ntail; Altibiades Socrasticus was with ane eame of his &amp;
lerny&dtail; &thorn;e vij scians libera&llbar;, his <NOTE ID="P306.N1">MS. he.</NOTE> eame gaff a tromper a trompe &thorn;at is
calli&dtail; Tibia, to thentent &thorn;at he sulde ler&ntail; his
cossy&ntail; to trompe &thorn;erwith &amp; to syng &thorn;erwith, ffor
in &thorn;at contre it was a commo&ntail; mynstraly.  And he sett
&thorn;is trompe to his mouthe &amp; bega&ntail; to blaw, &amp; it was
foyste &amp; i&llbar;-saver&dtail; &amp; garte hym make grete chekis,
&amp; as hy&mtail; &thorn;oght, it deformy&dtail; his face whe&ntail;
he blew &thorn;erin.  And he&rtail;-fo&rtail; he keste it fra
hy&mtail; &amp; brak it.  And be exsample of hy&mtail;, &thorn;at he
luffid it nott, he chargi&dtail; a&llbar; &thorn;e contre &thorn;er he
dwelte afterwar&dtail; &thorn;at &thorn;ai sulde neuer vse &thorn;at
mynstralcie, and so &thorn;ai vsi&dtail; it neuer vnto &thorn;is day.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCL.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ludit miles ad taxillos cum demone.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> In &thorn;e Cetie of Susa&ntail;, with-in &thorn;e dioces of
Cola&ntail;, &thorn;er was a knyght, and he was so giffe&ntail; vnto
playing at &thorn;e dice, at nyght



<PB N="307">

&amp; day he was evur redie to play with any &thorn;at wolde
co&mtail;; and he was passand fortunat in playing &amp; temyd many
mans purs.  So o&ntail; a nyght &thorn;e devu&llbar; come in a mans
liknes &amp; desyri&dtail; to play with hy&mtail;, &amp; he went in-to
&thorn;e howse with hy&mtail;, &amp; a grete sakett fu&llbar; of mony
in his han&dtail;, &amp; &thorn;ai played to-gedur to &thorn;is knyght
had nere-han&dtail; loste a&llbar; &thorn;e mony &thorn;at he
ha&dtail;.  And &thorn;is knyght, whe&ntail; he had loste, bega&ntail;
to wax angrie &amp; sai&dtail;; "&THORN;ou erte &thorn;e devu&llbar;,
hope I."  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e toder sai&dtail;; "Now we hafe
played enoghe, and vs bus now go."  And he tuke &thorn;e knyght be
&thorn;e nekk &amp; drew hy&mtail; oute &thorn;urg&hbar; &thorn;e
thakk of &thorn;e howse.  And his body breste &amp; his bowels
cleuy&dtail; o&ntail; &thorn;e sclathe stonys.  And o&ntail; &thorn;e
mor&ntail; his bowels was fo&ntail;, bod what at wurthed of &thorn;e
bodie cuthe neuer ma&ntail; te&llbar; to &thorn;is day, &amp;
&thorn;ai went &amp; beri&dtail; his bowels.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Ludus avium in hoc seculo punitur.  Supra de Aue.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Lupi confessoris.  Supra de Amore.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Lupus puellam invasit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how o&ntail; a tyme a wulfe ouercome a damyse&llbar; &amp;
gatt hur be &thorn;e ar&mtail; in a tow&ntail;, &amp; sho crye&dtail;
faste; &amp; euer whe&ntail; sho cryed he wolde strene hur sore, &amp;
whe&ntail; sho hel&dtail; hur tong he spari&dtail; hur.
Notwithstondyng he hayli&dtail; hur vnto &thorn;e wu&dtail; vnto a
noder wulfe &thorn;at had a bane stykkan&dtail; in his throte, and he
was gretely turment &thorn;er-with &amp; he gapi&dtail; wyde.  &amp;
&thorn;e <NOTE ID="P307.N1">After &thorn;e, j, erased.</NOTE> damyse&llbar; saw &thorn;e bane stik
in his throte, &amp; sho put in hur han&dtail; in his mowthe &amp;
pulli&dtail; it oute.  And he &amp; his felow broght hur agay&ntail;
vnto &thorn;e tow&ntail; safe &amp; sown&dtail;, &amp; lowtid vnto hir
and went &thorn;er wayes.  et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Lupa vindicauit quantum potuit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> In companye scolers o&ntail; a tyme had remedy &amp; went to
play &thorn;aim, &amp; &thorn;ai fande in &thorn;e wud a wulfe
de&ntail;; &amp; &thorn;er was wulfe-whelpis



<PB N="308">

&thorn;erin, bod &thorn;er da&mtail; was away.  So one of &thorn;ies
scolers cut of a&llbar; &thorn;e fete of &thorn;e wulfe-whelpis, and
whe&ntail; &thorn;e scolers was gone &thorn;e wulfe come vnto hur
de&ntail; and fan&dtail; hur whelpe fete cut of.  &amp; sho gat oute
&amp; folowi&dtail; opo&ntail; &thorn;ies scolers, and sho sewi&dtail;
alonelie o&ntail; hy&mtail; &thorn;at did &thorn;e dede.  And he was
passand fer&dtail; &amp; clambe vp in-to a tre, and whe&ntail; sho saw
sho mot not gett hy&mtail;, sho bega&ntail; to skrape &amp; grafe
abowte &thorn;e rowte with hur naylis.  &amp; whe&ntail; sho saw sho
mot not so co&mtail; to hy&mtail;, sho cryed &amp; gader&dtail; samen
a grete meneya of wulvis to helpe hur.  And in &thorn;e mene-while
&thorn;e scolers tolde me&ntail; in &thorn;e tow&ntail;, and &thorn;ai
come oute with clubbis and staffis &amp; flayed &thorn;ies wulvis <NOTE ID="P308.N1">MS. wufvis.</NOTE> away, &amp; broght &thorn;is scolar hame emyddeste
of &thorn;aim a&llbar;.  &THORN;e wulfis folowi&dtail; &thorn;aim
oferro&mtail;, bod sho alonelie come evur o&ntail; &thorn;aim &amp;
wolde not lett for &thorn;aim a&llbar;, bod come rynan&dtail; in emang
&thorn;aim &amp; gatt &thorn;is scolar be &thorn;e nekk, &amp; onone
sho weri&dtail; hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;ai fe&llbar; vpo&ntail; hur
&amp; slew hur. et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Luporum more currit et vlulat aliquis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Petrus de Lombardia tellis &amp; says; "I saw ans a yong ma&ntail;
&thorn;at was bor&ntail; in Fraunce &amp; broght vnto he was at mans
age <NOTE ID="P308.N2">Harl. MS. educatus vt more luporum semper ad manus et pedes sciuit currere atque ululare.</NOTE> , and he cuthe gang o&ntail; his fete &amp;
his handis as a beste and crye like a wulfe."

</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM><FOREIGN>Lupanari expositam virginem custodiuit deus.  Infra

de virgine.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Luxuria multa mala facit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> In &thorn;e Cetie of Susace was &thorn;er a womma&ntail; &thorn;at
keste hur harte hugelie o&ntail; a clerk &thorn;at had fay&rtail;
ee&ntail;, to hafe at do with hy&mtail;, vnto so meku&llbar; at sho
sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "And &thorn;ou wi&llbar; hafe at do with me
a&llbar; my gude sal be thyne."  And he excusi&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp;
wolde nott.  And sho saw &thorn;at &amp; went vnto &thorn;e iustis
&amp; accusi&dtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; sai&dtail; he






<PB N="309">

wol&dtail; hafe oppressi&dtail; hur.  And &thorn;e iustis sente for
hy&mtail; &amp; dampnum <NOTE ID="P309.N1"><HI REND="i">For</HI> dampnatus est?</NOTE> for lichori vnto
priso&ntail;.  And sho contynod sti&llbar; in hur fals sy&ntail; &amp;
luste, &amp; gatt a stye &amp; cla&mtail; vp at a hy wa&llbar; to a
wyndow of &thorn;e priso&ntail;, &amp; clambe our &amp; lepyd
dow&ntail; vnto hy&mtail; &amp; labur&dtail; hy&mtail; to hafe att do
with hy&mtail;, and he wolde not grawnt vnto hur.  And als tyte as sho
was fo&ntail; with hy&mtail; &thorn;ai went &amp; telli&dtail;
&thorn;e iudgies, and &thorn;ai trowi&dtail; he had bene a wyche &amp;
vsi&dtail; sorcerye, &amp; demy&dtail; hy&mtail; to be burny&dtail;,
and so he was.  &amp; whe&ntail; his ribbys was burny&dtail; &thorn;at
me&ntail; myght se his longis, he bega&ntail; to syng "Ave Maria," at
a&llbar; folke har&dtail;.  And onone one of &thorn;e wommans cussyns
putt a grete colle in his mouthe &amp; sai&dtail;; "I sa&llbar; putt
away &thorn;i prayers."  &amp; with &thorn;at he woro&dtail;
hy&mtail;; &amp; his bonys war beri&dtail; in &thorn;e felde &amp; did
many grete meracles.  And now vpo&ntail; his grafe is &thorn;er made a
wurthi kurk.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Luxuriosa mulier.  Infra de muliere,
iiij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Luxuriosa mulier conceptum infantem
necat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede of a no&ntail; of &thorn;e dioces of Cola&ntail;, and sho
conseyvi&dtail; &amp; bare a chil&dtail; &amp; whe&ntail; it was
bor&ntail; she slew it.  So afterwar&dtail; hur happend fa&llbar; seke
&amp; was bow&ntail; to dye, and sho shrafe hur of a&llbar; hur synys
outtakyn &thorn;is sy&ntail; of &thorn;e slayng of hur childe; and
&thorn;a&ntail; sho dye&dtail;.  So afterwar&dtail; sho apperi&dtail;
vnto a cussy&ntail; of hurs at prayed for hur, and sho bare in hur
armys a burnande childe, &amp; sai&dtail;; "&thorn;is childe I
conseyvi&dtail;, &amp; whe&ntail; it was bor&ntail; I slew it.  &amp;
&thorn;erfo&rtail; euer I mo&ntail; bere it abowte &amp; it is a
passan&dtail; byrnan&dtail; fyre vnto me.  And if I had bene
shrevy&ntail; &thorn;erof I had had grace, &amp; now I mo&ntail; hafe
none for I a&mtail; dampny&dtail;."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Luxurie peccatum committunt eciam religiosi, vt

hic et supra et infra diuersis locis.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Luxuria religiosos religionem relinquere facit.  Infra

de Maria, vij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>



<PB N="310">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Luxuriosam mulierem diabolus ad infernum
portauit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede of a prestis concubyne, &thorn;at whe&ntail; sho was
bow&ntail; to dye sho crie&dtail; opo&ntail; &thorn;aim at was aboute
hur with grete instans, &amp; bad &thorn;aim gar make hur a payr of hy
bottois &amp; putt &thorn;aim o&ntail; hur leggis for &thorn;ai war
passan&dtail; necessarie vnto <NOTE ID="P310.N1"><HI REND="i">After</HI> vnto, h, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> hur, and so
&thorn;ai di&dtail;.  And opo&ntail; &thorn;e night after &thorn;e
mone shane bryght, and a knyght &amp; his servan&dtail; was
rydan&dtail; in &thorn;e feldis to-gedur, and &thorn;er come a
womma&ntail; rynan&dtail; fast vnto &thorn;aim, cryan&dtail; &amp;
praye&dtail; &thorn;aim helpe hur.  &amp; onone &thorn;is knyght light
&amp; betaght his ma&ntail; his hors, &amp; he kenny&dtail; &thorn;e
womma&ntail; wele enog&hbar;, &amp; he made a cerkle abowte hy&mtail;
with his swer&dtail;, &amp; tuke hur in vnto hy&mtail;; &amp; sho had
nothyng o&ntail; bod hur sarke &amp; &thorn;ies buttois.  And belife
he harde a blaste of ane vgso&mtail; hor&ntail; at a hunter blew
horrible, &amp; huge barkyng of hundis, and als sone as &thorn;ai
har&dtail;, &thorn;is womma&ntail; was passand ferde.  And &thorn;is
knyght spirri&dtail; hur whi sho was so fer&dtail;, &amp; scho
telli&dtail; hy&mtail; a&llbar;; and he light &amp; tuke &thorn;e
tressis of hur hare &amp; wappid it strayte abowte his ar&mtail;,
&amp; in his right ar&mtail; he helde his swer&dtail; drawe&ntail;.
And belife &thorn;is hunter of he&llbar; come at han&dtail;, &amp;
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is womma&ntail; sai&dtail;; "Lat me go, ffor he
commys."  And &thorn;is knyght hel&dtail; hur sti&llbar;, &amp;
&thorn;is womma&ntail; pulli&dtail; faste &amp; wolde hafe bene away.
So at &thorn;e laste sho pulli&dtail; so faste at a&llbar; hur hare
braste of hur heade, &amp; sho ra&ntail; away &amp; &thorn;is
fen&dtail; folow&dtail; after &amp; tuke hur, &amp; keste hur ouerthwarte
behyn&dtail; hy&mtail; o&ntail; his hors at hur hede &amp; hur armys
hang dow&ntail; o&ntail; &thorn;e ta syde, &amp; hur legis o&ntail;
&thorn;e toder syde.  &amp; &thorn;us, whe&ntail; he had his pray, he
rade his ways, and be &thorn;a&ntail; it was nere day.  &amp;
&thorn;is knyg[ht] went in &thorn;e mornyng vnto &thorn;e tow&ntail;,
&amp; he fan&dtail; &thorn;is womma&ntail; new dea&dtail;, &amp; he
tel&dtail; a&llbar; as he had sene, &amp; shewi&dtail; &thorn;e hare
at was wappi&dtail; abowte his ar&mtail;.  And &thorn;ai luky&dtail;
hur hea&dtail; &thorn;er sho lay, and &thorn;ai fande how a&llbar;
&thorn;e hare was plukki&dtail; of be &thorn;e rutis.  And &thorn;is
happen&dtail; in &thorn;e bisshopprik of Magentyne.



<PB N="311">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Luxuriosam mulierem canes dentibus
comminuerunt.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> In &thorn;e dioces of Coley&ntail; &thorn;er was a yong
damyse&llbar; &thorn;at was rakles &amp; lichoros.  So at &thorn;e
laste, after grete sekenes, hur happen&dtail; to dye, and as sho lay
naki&dtail; o&ntail; &thorn;e flure, couerde with a shete, a&llbar;
&thorn;e doggis of &thorn;e tow&ntail; come samen into &thorn;e howse,
&amp; drew of &thorn;e shete and pulli&dtail; hur a&llbar; to gobettis
so &thorn;at vnnethis &thorn;e husbandis <NOTE ID="P311.N1"><HI REND="i">After</HI> husbandis, &thorn;e h, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> myght
dyng &thorn;aim away.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai gader&dtail;
samen &thorn;e pecis of hur body &amp; beri&dtail; it.  And &thorn;e
dogis come agay&ntail; vnto hur grafe &amp; skrapi&dtail; vp &thorn;e
pecis agay&ntail;, &amp; bate &thorn;aim as &thorn;ai di&dtail;
befo&rtail; in sonder, &amp; faght ilk one with o&thorn;er als faste
as &thorn;ai myght, to &thorn;ai had a&llbar; ety&ntail; hur for oght
at any ma&ntail; cuthe lett &thorn;aim.

</P>
