</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Maria deuotis sibi eciam honorem mundi
procurat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Ou&rtail; Ladie Meracles' how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er
was a noble knyght of Kurkby &thorn;at was deuowte vnto ou&rtail;
Ladie, and o&ntail; a tyme as he went vnto &thorn;e were, he went
in-to ane abbay &thorn;at was fowndi&dtail; of ou&rtail; Ladie &amp;
was in his way, &amp; &thorn;er he har&dtail; mes.  And whe&ntail; ilk
mes was done after o&thorn;er, &amp; he for wurshu&ptail; of our Ladie
wol&dtail; not go or he had har&dtail; &thorn;aim a&llbar;, at
&thorn;e laste he wente furt&hbar; of &thorn;is abbay &amp;
hasti&dtail; hy&mtail; vnto &thorn;is turnament.  He mett meneya
comman&dtail; fro &thorn;e turnament, &amp; a&llbar; was done;
&thorn;ai sai&dtail; at he had foghte&ntail; manlelie in &thorn;e
bate&llbar; &amp; bor&ntail; hy&mtail; passan&dtail; wele.  An&dtail;
&thorn;ai stude sti&llbar; vnto a&llbar; come aboute, &amp; ilk
ma&ntail; with a hale voyce commendi&dtail; &amp; sai&dtail; he had
foghte&ntail; wurthelie.  And &thorn;er come so&mtail; &amp;
offer&dtail; &thorn;aim vnto hy&mtail; &amp; sai&dtail; &thorn;at he
ha&dtail; take&ntail; &thorn;aim prisoners in &thorn;e bate&llbar;.
So &thorn;e ma&ntail; was discrete and purseyvi&dtail; how our Ladie
had rewardi&dtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; he gaff vp a&llbar; werldlie
&thorn;ingis &amp; servi&dtail; hur So&ntail; &amp; hur euer after
whils he liffi&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Maria incarceratos liberat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in hur 'Meracles' how &thorn;er was a wedow &thorn;at had
no childe bod a so&ntail;, whilk &thorn;at sho luffi&dtail;
passandlie.  So o&ntail; a tyme hy&mtail; happyn&dtail; to be
take&ntail; with his enmys and putt in priso&ntail;, and his moder was
passan&dtail; devowte vnto ou&rtail; Ladie &amp; made hur prayers
hertlie vnto hur for hur so&ntail;.  And so sho saw at it
profetti&dtail; nott, &amp; sho wente vnto &thorn;e kurk &thorn;er
ou&rtail; Ladie was beri&dtail;, and &thorn;er was a

<PB N="316">

fayr ymage of ou&rtail; Ladie with hur So&ntail; opo&ntail; hur kne,
and be hur one sho sett hur dow&ntail; o&ntail; hur kneis &amp;
sai&dtail; vnto ou&rtail; Ladie o&ntail; &thorn;is maner of wyse;
"Thow blissi&dtail; Ladie!  I hafe ofte prayed vnto &thorn;e for my
so&ntail;, &amp; &thorn;ou hase not har&dtail; me, &amp;
&thorn;erfo&rtail; as my so&ntail; is taky&ntail; fro me, so sa&llbar;
I take &thorn;i So&ntail; fro the, &amp; kepe hy&mtail; in wed for my
so&ntail;."  &amp; sho tuke away &thorn;e ymage of ou&rtail; Ladie
So&ntail; &thorn;at satt o&ntail; hur kne &amp; had it home, &amp;
wappi&dtail; it in a clene shete, and putt it in hur arke &amp;
lokki&dtail; it, &amp; was ioyfu&llbar; &amp; trowi&dtail; sho had a
gude wed for hur so&ntail;.  And o&ntail; &thorn;e night after,
ou&rtail; Ladie apperi&dtail; vnto &thorn;e yong ma&ntail; and
lowsi&dtail; his fetters, &amp; oppen&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;e
priso&ntail; dure &amp; lete hy&mtail; furt&hbar; &amp; sent hy&mtail;
vnto his moder, and bad hy&mtail; say vnto his moder &thorn;at sho
sul&dtail; bryng hur hur So&ntail; <NOTE ID="P316.N1">MS. Sons.</NOTE> agay&ntail;
for sho had sent hur hurs.  And &thorn;is yong ma&ntail; come vnto his
moder &amp; telli&dtail; hur a&llbar; how ou&rtail; Ladie had
delyuer&dtail; hy&mtail;.  And sho was passan&dtail; fay&ntail;, &amp;
ba&rtail; agay&ntail; &thorn;e ymage-childe vnto &thorn;e kur&ktee;
and sai&dtail;, "Blissi&dtail; Ladie, I thank &thorn;e at &thorn;ou
hase giffe&ntail; me my so&ntail; agay&ntail;, &amp; behol&dtail;, lo,
I bryng &thorn;e thyne agay&ntail;."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Maria deuotos sibi a morte liberat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in hur 'Meracles' how som tyme &thorn;er was a thefe,
&amp; he had a grete deuocio&ntail; vnto ou&rtail; Ladie, &amp;
sai&dtail; hur salutacio&ntail; oft vnto hur.  So at &thorn;e laste he
was taky&ntail; with thift &amp; hange&dtail;, and our Ladie come
&amp; hel&dtail; hy&mtail; vp iij dayes, hur aw&ntail; handis, so
&thorn;at he feli&dtail; no sare.  So &thorn;ai &thorn;at hange&dtail;
hy&mtail; happen&dtail; be cace to co&mtail; by hy&mtail; away, &amp;
fan&dtail; hy&mtail; mery an&dtail; liffan&dtail;, and &thorn;ai
trowe&dtail; he ha&dtail; not bene wele hange&dtail;.  &amp; &thorn;ai
wer avysi&dtail; to hafe stykki&dtail; hy&mtail; with a swer&dtail; as
he hang, and as &thorn;ai wol&dtail; hafe stryke&ntail; hy&mtail;, our
Lady putt it away with hur han&dtail;, so at &thorn;ai noyed hy&mtail;
noght.  And he tol&dtail; &thorn;aim how our Ladie helpi&dtail;
hy&mtail;, &amp; &thorn;ai tuke hy&mtail; dow&ntail; &amp; lete
hy&mtail;.  &amp; he went vnto ane abbay &amp; &thorn;er servi&dtail;
ou&rtail; Ladie ewhils he liffi&dtail;.



<PB N="317">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Marie virginis horas deuote dicentes per ipsam
a miserijs seculi liberantur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in hur 'Meracles' how &thorn;er was a devowte cler&ktee;,
and euer-ilk day he wolde say deuotelie &thorn;e howris of our Ladye.
So his fadur &amp; his moder dye&dtail;, and he was &thorn;er heir
&amp; had a grete heritage.  So he was compelli&dtail; &amp;
cowncel&dtail; be his frendis to take hy&mtail; a wyfe, and so he
di&dtail;.  &amp; o&ntail; &thorn;e day at he was wed, as he went
hamwar&dtail; fro &thorn;e kur&ktee;, &thorn;er was ane abbay of
ou&rtail; Ladie in his way, &amp; he had forgette&ntail; to say his
howris &amp; went into &thorn;e abbay to say &thorn;aim, &amp; sett
hy&mtail; dow&ntail; on his kneis befo&rtail; ow&rtail; Ladie &amp;
sai&dtail; &thorn;aim.  And sodanlie ou&rtail; Ladie spak to hy&mtail;
&amp; sai&dtail;; "O, &thorn;ou fule, &amp; vnwise clerk!  Whi
forsakis &thorn;ou me, &thorn;i best frend <NOTE ID="P317.N1">MS. frendis.</NOTE> ,
&amp; takis a noder spowse?"  And with &thorn;is wurdis he was gretlie
compuncte &amp; went hame &amp; made a nen&dtail; of his weddyng.
&amp; att evy&ntail; he lefte his wife &amp; a&llbar; his
lifelo&dtail;, &amp; went vnto &thorn;e abbay &amp; made hy&mtail; a
monke, &amp; servi&dtail; God &amp; our Ladie a&llbar; his life.  et
c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Marie placet missa de eadem 
<NOTE ID="P317.N2">MS. eo.</NOTE>  dicta.  Infra Thome

martiris, v.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Marie se commendans ab incendio
liberatur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in hur 'Meracles' of a ma&ntail; &amp; a womma&ntail;
&thorn;at wunte nere &thorn;e cetie of Lugdu&ntail;, abowte &thorn;e
yere of our Lor&dtail; M. C., &amp; &thorn;ai had no childe bod a
doghter.  &amp; &thorn;ai mari&dtail; hur with a yong ma&ntail;, &amp;
&thorn;ai helde hy&mtail; in &thorn;er howse, &amp; &thorn;e moder
luffi&dtail; hy&mtail; als wele as sho did hur aw&ntail; doghter.  And
kurste tongis sai&dtail; &thorn;at sho luffi&dtail; hy&mtail; not
alonelie for hur doghter sake, bod rather becauce sho lete hy&mtail;
lig by hur in-stede of hur doghter, &amp; sho har&dtail; te&llbar;
&thorn;eroff &amp; was fer&dtail; &thorn;at sklander&dtail; sulde rise
of hur betwix hy&mtail; &amp; hur, and





<PB N="318">

privalie scho slew hy&mtail; whe&ntail; hur husban&dtail; &amp; hur
doghter war away, &amp; lay&dtail; hy&mtail; in hur doghter bed.  So
in &thorn;e mornyng, as &thorn;ai satt at dener sho bad hur <NOTE ID="P318.N1">MS. our.</NOTE> doghter go waky&ntail; hur husban&dtail;, &amp;
by&dtail; hy&mtail; rise.  And sho went &amp; fan&dtail; hy&mtail;
dea&dtail;, &amp; crye&dtail;, and sho &amp; &thorn;e moder made bathe
meku&llbar; sorow; neuer-&thorn;e-les sho forthoght hur &thorn;erof,
&amp; wente vnto &thorn;e preste &amp; shrafe hur, &amp; tolde
hy&mtail; a&llbar; how sho had done.  So afterwar&dtail; &thorn;is
womma&ntail; &amp; &thorn;is preste fe&llbar; at debate, and he
disclander&dtail; hur &amp; tolde hur cownce&llbar;, &amp; vpbrayed
hur &thorn;erwith.  And whe&ntail; it come to knowlege of &thorn;e
yong ma&ntail; fathir &amp; his moder, thai garte take hur &amp; bryng
hur befo&rtail; a iustis, &amp; &thorn;er sho was demyd to be
byrny&dtail;.  And scho wepy&dtail; &amp; betuke hur vnto our Ladie.
And whe&ntail; &thorn;e fyre was kyndle&dtail; abowte hur, sho stude
sti&llbar; vnhurte, and hur enmys kyndled &thorn;e fire ner hur &amp;
it profeti&dtail; &thorn;aim noght.  So &thorn;ai tuke forkis &amp;
stowris &amp; thruste hur dow&ntail; with, &amp; it stedi&dtail;
&thorn;aim of noght.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e iustis had grete
merve&llbar; &amp; behel&dtail; hur graythlie, &amp; he cuthe se no
taky&ntail; of burnyng o&ntail; hur, bod alonelie wowndis &thorn;at
sho had with &thorn;e forkis &amp; &thorn;e stowris.  So sho was
taky&ntail; furt&hbar; &amp; led hame, &amp; balmyd &amp;
refresshi&dtail;, and with-in iij dayis after sho, perseuerand in
grete lovyngis of our Ladie, gaff vp hur gaste, and passi&dtail; vnto
Almighti Go&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Maria ad se confugientes deo
reconsiliat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in hur 'Meracles,' &thorn;at aboute &thorn;e yere of
ou&rtail; Lor&dtail; CCC vij <NOTE ID="P318.N2">Lat. MSS. xxxvij.</NOTE> , in &thorn;e
lan&dtail; of Cecilie, [was] one &thorn;at hight Theophil, at was
chauncelur vnto a bisshop&ptail;, &amp; was wise &amp; gracious.  So
o&ntail; a tyme he was putt oute of his offes, and he&rtail;-fo&rtail;
he fe&llbar; in a grete sorow &amp; a dispayr.  And so hy&mtail;
happend speke with &thorn;e devu&llbar;, and be comman&dtail; of
hy&mtail; he forsuke Criste &amp; His moder, &amp; he renownce&dtail;
his faithe, and herefo&rtail; he made hy&mtail; a cyrographatt
wrette&ntail;, &amp; seli&dtail; it with his aw&ntail; ryng.  And
whe&ntail; it was seli&dtail; he delyver&dtail; it vnto &thorn;e
devu&llbar;, and ban&dtail; &hbar;y&mtail; to do hy&mtail; serves
whils he liffi&dtail;.  So with-in a while after, be procuryng of
&thorn;e fen&dtail;, he was





<PB N="319">

restori&dtail; agay&ntail; vnto his offes.  So after hy&mtail;
forthoght, and calli&dtail; opo&ntail; our Ladie, &amp; made his
prayer vnto hur; &amp; sho apperi&dtail; vnto hym and blamy&dtail;
hy&mtail; for &thorn;at at he had done.  And be hur commandmend [he]
forsuke &thorn;e devu&llbar; and tuke hy&mtail; vnto God &amp; our
Ladie, and he was broght befo&rtail; a iustis.  And &thorn;e
devu&llbar; shewi&dtail; &thorn;is cirographatt, and our Ladie tuke it
fro hy&mtail; &amp; lai&dtail; it o&ntail; Theophi&llbar; breste,
&thorn;er he was slepan&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; he waki&dtail; he
fan&dtail; it, &amp; was passand fay&ntail; &thorn;er-of, and
evy&ntail; opynlie, befo&rtail; &thorn;e bisshop&ptail; &amp; a&llbar;
&thorn;e peple, he stude vpp &amp; confessi&dtail; hy&mtail;.  And
a&llbar; me&ntail; had grete mervayle &thorn;er-off, &amp; he did his
penans &thorn;at was ioyned hy&mtail; &thorn;erfo&rtail;, &amp;
with-in a while after he decesi&dtail; &amp; made a gude endyng.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Marie salutacio causa est miraculi post 
<NOTE ID="P319.N1"><HI REND="i">After</HI> post, p, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE>  mortem.

Supra de annunciacione dominica.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Maria protegit a combustione.  Supra de eukaristia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Maria liberat de infamia.  Supra de infamia, ij, et de

abbatissa, j.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Maria ordinem predicatorum attulit.  Supra

Dominici, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Maria deuotis sibi in necessitate adiuvat.  Supra de

familiaritate.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Maria horas de se dicentibus apparet in morte.  Supra

de horis, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Maria consolatur suos.  Supra de consolacione.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Maria officium seruitorum suorum eis absentibus
implet.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Som tyme &thorn;er was a no&ntail; &thorn;at hight Betres, a
passand fayr womma&ntail;, &amp; sho was sacrista&ntail; of &thorn;e
kur&ktee; and sho had grete deuocio&ntail; vnto our Ladie; and oft
sithis me&ntail; desiri&dtail; hur to sy&ntail;.



<PB N="320">

So at &thorn;e laste sho consenti&dtail; vnto a cler&ktee; at go away
with hy&mtail; whe&ntail; comply&ntail; was done, and or sho yode sho
went vnto ane altar of ou&rtail; Ladie &amp; sai&dtail; vnto hur;
"Lady, as I hafe bene deuoute vnto &thorn;e, now I resigne vnto
&thorn;e &thorn;ies keyis, for I may no langer sustey&ntail; &thorn;e
temptacio&ntail; of my fless&hbar;."  &amp; sho lai&dtail; &thorn;e
keyis o&ntail; &thorn;e altar &amp; went hur wayes vnto &thorn;e
cler&ktee;.  And whe&ntail; he had defowli&dtail; hur, with-in a few
dayes he lefte hur &amp; went away; &amp; sho had nothyng at liff
o&ntail; &amp; thoght shame to gang home agay&ntail; vnto hur clostre,
and sho fe&llbar; to be a commo&ntail; woma&ntail;.  And whe&ntail;
sho had liffi&dtail; in &thorn;at vice xv yere, o&ntail; a day sho
come vnto &thorn;e nonrie yate, &amp; aski&dtail; &thorn;e porter if
he knew evur a no&ntail; in &thorn;at place &thorn;at hight Betres,
&thorn;at was sacrista&ntail; &amp; keper of &thorn;e kur&ktee;.  And
he sai&dtail; he knew hur o&ntail; &thorn;e beste wyse, and sai&dtail;
sho was a wurthi womma&ntail; &amp; a halie of bar&ntail; little,
"&amp; euer hase kepud hur clene &amp; in gude name."  And sho
vnderstode not &thorn;e wurdis of &thorn;is ma&ntail;, &amp; went hur
wayis.  And ou&rtail; Lady apperi&dtail; vnto hur &amp; sai&dtail;;
"Behol&dtail;!  I hafe fulfilli&dtail; &thorn;ine offes &thorn;is xv
yere, and &thorn;erfo&rtail; tur&ntail; agay&ntail; now into &thorn;i
place &amp; be agay&ntail; in &thorn;ine offes as &thorn;ou was, &amp;
shryfe &thorn;e &amp; do &thorn;i penance, for &thorn;er is no creatur
he&rtail; at knowis &thorn;i truspas, for I hafe euer bene for the in
&thorn;i clothyng &amp; in &thorn;ine abbett."  And onone sho was in
hur abbett &amp; went in &amp; shrafe hur &amp; di&dtail; her panance,
and tol&dtail; a&llbar; &thorn;at was happen&dtail; vnto hur.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Marie salutacio fantasma disparere facit et
demonem fugat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how &thorn;at &thorn;e fen&dtail; oft sithis in liknes of
a gude ange&llbar; apperi&dtail; vnto ane ancres.  So at &thorn;e
laste he tol&dtail; hur &thorn;at he come to comfurt&hbar; hur, and
sho had a grete comfurt&hbar; &thorn;erof, &amp; tol&dtail; hur
confessur of his apperans.  &amp; he was a gude ma&ntail; &amp; bad
hur, whe&ntail; he come agay&ntail;, &thorn;at sho sulde [bid him]
<NOTE ID="P320.N1">Harl. MS. 'Dic ei vt ostendat tibi beatam Mariam.'</NOTE> shew vnto hur ou&rtail; Ladie, Saynt Marie; and
if he did so &thorn;at onone as sho saw hur sho sulde say, " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ave Maria.</FOREIGN>" And &thorn;e next tyme he come
agay&ntail; sho desiri&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;at sho mot se our
Ladie, and he sai&dtail; it nedid not, ffor it suffisi&dtail; vnto hur
his presens.  And euer sho desyri&dtail; hy&mtail; more



<PB N="321">

&amp; mo&rtail; at sho mot se ou&rtail; Ladie.  So o&ntail; a tyme
&thorn;is fend formy&dtail; hy&mtail; selfe in lyknes of a fayr
womma&ntail;, and apperi&dtail; vnto hur.  And onone as sho saw
&hbar;ur, sho fe&llbar; o&ntail; kneis befo&rtail; hur and sai&dtail;;
" <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ave Maria.</FOREIGN>" And onone sho
dispayri&dtail; away as a fantasie.

<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Hec valet ad decepcionem demonis.</FOREIGN>
</P>

<P>So fure it o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;e Devu&llbar; aperi&dtail; oft
sithis vnto ane hermett in lyknes of a ma&ntail; of law, so a noder
wise ma&ntail; cowncel&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;at whe&ntail; at he
come, he sul&dtail; say his Ave Maria; and so he di&dtail;.  &amp;
&thorn;e fen&dtail; flow away in liknes of a whorle-wyn&dtail; &amp;
gnaysti&dtail; his tethe, &amp; wari&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;at taght
hy&mtail; to say it.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLXX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Marie salutacio immittit timorem et malum
cogitatum emittit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> So&mtail; tyme a no&ntail;, tempi&dtail; for luff of a yong
ma&ntail;, wol&dtail; hafe gane into &thorn;e werl&dtail;, and sho mot
not gett oute bod if sho had went &thorn;urgh &thorn;e kur&ktee;.
And so as sho went &thorn;urg&hbar; &thorn;e kurk sho <NOTE ID="P321.N1">MS. &amp; set.</NOTE> set hur dow&ntail; befo&rtail; our Ladie, as sho was
wunt to doo, &amp; lowti&dtail; dow&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail; hur Ave
Maria.  And sodanlie &thorn;er come o&ntail; hur so grete a drede
&thorn;at sho mot no ferrer go furt&hbar;; and so it happen&dtail; oft
sithes with hur.  And at &thorn;e laste sho was tempi&dtail; with so
grete temptacio&ntail;, to so meku&llbar; at sho thoght at sho
sul&dtail; pas furthe by our Ladie &amp; nothyng lowte vnto hur, nor
at sho wol&dtail; not say hur Ave Maria.  And &thorn;is done &thorn;e
devu&llbar; tuke a power in hur, and gaff hur a hardynes to go oute of
hur ordur with, &amp; &thorn;us o&ntail; a tyme sho went hur wayes
&amp; fulfilli&dtail; &thorn;e luste of hur fless&hbar;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLXXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Marie ymago infeccionem aeris fugat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Grego&rtail;, whe&ntail; &thorn;at he was pope, agay&ntail;
&thorn;e infeccio&ntail; of &thorn;e ayre &thorn;at was cauce in Rome
of grete dea&dtail; &amp; mortalitie <NOTE ID="P321.N2">MS. <HI REND="i">inserts</HI> and <HI REND="i">here</HI>.</NOTE> , he garte
make solempne processions: and ane ymage of ou&rtail; Ladie &thorn;at
Saynt





<PB N="322">

Luke had paynti&dtail;, evy&ntail; after &thorn;e lyknes of our Ladie,
he garte bere befo&rtail; &thorn;e processio&ntail;.  And onone
&thorn;is infeccio&ntail; of &thorn;e ayr vanysshi&dtail; away and
fled fra &thorn;e ymage, and a grete reste &amp; a quietnes come.  And
abow&ntail;, &thorn;e aunge&llbar; in &thorn;e ayr enence &thorn;e
ymage sang; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Regina celi letare, Alleluia!  Quia
quem meruisti portare, Alleluia!  Resurrexit sicut dixit,
Alleluia!</FOREIGN>" And onone Saynt Gregur &amp; his felashup&ptail;
addid &thorn;erto &amp; sang; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ora pro nobis
Deum, Alleluia!</FOREIGN>"

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Marini qui eciam Marine dicitur.  Supra de

accusacione, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLXXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Marthe corpus per dominum
sepelitur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Legenda Lombardica' &thorn;at [when] Saynt Martha was
dea&dtail; at Clarasco&ntail; <NOTE ID="P322.N1">Harl. MS. Tharasconem.</NOTE> , apo&ntail;
&thorn;e day afterwar&dtail; at Pictagoras <NOTE ID="P322.N2">Latin MSS. Petragoricas.</NOTE> our
Lor&dtail; apperi&dtail; vnto Saynt Francon <NOTE ID="P322.N3">Harl. MS. beato Frontoni Episcopo.</NOTE> ,
&thorn;e bisshop&ptail;, as he was at mes and after &thorn;e
epistu&llbar; was falle&ntail; o&ntail; slepe in his chayr, and
sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "My welebeluffi&dtail; Franco <NOTE ID="P322.N4">Harl. MS. "Dulce mi Fronto!"</NOTE> !  Ryse tite &amp; folow me!"  And so he di&dtail;;
and sodanlie &thorn;ai come vnto Therasco&ntail; bothe to-gedur, and
&thorn;ai sang aboute &thorn;e bodie of Saynt Martha, &amp; a&llbar;
&thorn;at was abowte ansswer&dtail; &thorn;aim.  And &thorn;us
&thorn;ai di&dtail; a&llbar; &thorn;e offes, &amp; lay&dtail; hur in
hur grafe.  And at Pictagoras, whe&ntail; a&llbar; &thorn;e sang after
&thorn;e epistu&llbar; was done, &amp; &thorn;e deky&ntail; sul&dtail;
go rede &thorn;e gospe&llbar; &amp; take &thorn;e blissyng of &thorn;e
bisshop&ptail;, he was o&ntail; slepe.  And &thorn;e deky&ntail; went
to hy&mtail; a waken&dtail; hy&mtail;, and &thorn;a&ntail; he
sai&dtail;; "Brethir, whi wakken&dtail; ye me?  For our Lor&dtail;
Iesu Criste had led me vnto &thorn;e bodie of Martha his hoste, &amp;
he &amp; I hase beri&dtail; hur.  And &thorn;erfo&rtail; send faste
thedur for to feche vs ou&rtail; gol&dtail; ryng &amp; our glovis,
&thorn;at we hafe lefte &thorn;er, whilk &thorn;at I betuke vnto
&thorn;e sacrista&ntail; whe&ntail; we putt hur in hur grafe.  And
becauce ye calli&dtail; me so tyte or &thorn;e mes was done,
&thorn;erfo&rtail; I hafe lefte &thorn;aim behyn&dtail; me."  And
&thorn;ai sent a messanger ono&ntail; &amp; fan&dtail; a&llbar; as
&thorn;e bisshop&ptail; sai&dtail;, bothe &thorn;e ryng &amp;
&thorn;e gluvis, &amp; broght &thorn;aim home.  And in toky&ntail;
here-of &thorn;e sacrista&ntail; kepi&dtail; &thorn;e ta glufe, &amp;
so &thorn;ai hafe it yitt for a relikk.









<PB N="323">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLXXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Martini, Episcopi et Confessoris.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Seuerus <NOTE ID="P323.N1">MS. Severius.</NOTE> in his 'Dialoggis' tellis how
o&ntail; a ffestiua&llbar; day a pure naki&dtail; ma&ntail;
folowi&dtail; Saynt Marty&ntail; vnto &thorn;e kurk-war&dtail;, and he
commandy&dtail; his archedeky&ntail; to garr hy&mtail; be cled&dtail;,
and he lachi&dtail; &thorn;erin.  And Saynt Marty&ntail; saw
&thorn;at, &amp; went in-to his secretorie &amp; doffi&dtail; his cote
&amp; gaff it vnto &thorn;is pure ma&ntail;, and bad hy&mtail; go
faste his wayis &thorn;erwith.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e
archdeky&ntail; desyri&dtail; at he wol&dtail; go to mes, &amp; he,
spekan&dtail; of hy&mtail; selfe, sai&dtail; &thorn;at he mot not go
to mes vnto &thorn;is pure ma&ntail; was cle&dtail;.  And so in a tene
&thorn;is archdeky&ntail; went in-to &thorn;e markett &amp; boght a
sary ol&dtail; cote for v&dtail;, &amp; broght it vnto Saynt
Marty&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail; he cuthe not fyn&dtail; &thorn;is
ol&dtail; pure ma&ntail;.  And Saynt Marty&ntail; bad hy&mtail; giff
hy&mtail; &thorn;e clothe, &amp; &thorn;e pure ma&ntail; sul&dtail;
nott want itt.  And in a tene he threw it vnto hy&mtail;, and he tuke
it &amp; went privalie &amp; gatt it o&ntail; hy&mtail;, &amp;
&thorn;e slevis &thorn;erof come bod vnto his elbow, &amp; &thorn;e
lenthe &thorn;erof was bod vnto his kne; and so he went vnto mes.  And
as he was att mes, a byrnyng globe aperi&dtail; abow&ntail; his
hea&dtail;, whilk &thorn;at many folk saw, and for &thorn;at he was
calli&dtail; <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Par Apostolis</FOREIGN>, Evy&ntail;
vnto &thorn;e Apostels.  And vnto &thorn;is meracle addi&dtail;
maister Ioh&ntail; Belet&hbar;, and says &thorn;at whe&ntail; he was
at mes and sulde lifte, as &thorn;e vse is, his ly&ntail; slevis slafe
bakk, &amp; his armys was bod sma&llbar;, and &thorn;e slevis of
&thorn;e olde cote come bod vnto his elbow, and so whe&ntail; he
lifti&dtail;, his armys war bare.  And &thorn;a&ntail; a mervalos
wrethe of golde &amp; precious stonys was sene aboute his armys,
&thorn;at cover&dtail; his armys vnto his elbow.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Martinus eciam inuitis beneficia prestitit.  Supra de
invitis 
<NOTE ID="P323.N2">MS. inimicis.</NOTE> .</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLXXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Martini sepulture interfuit Ambrosius.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Opo&ntail; &thorn;e same day at Saynt Marty&ntail; decesi&dtail;,
Saynt Ambros &thorn;e bisshop&ptail; was att mes at &thorn;e cetie of
Mediola&ntail;, and as he leny&dtail; o&ntail;





<PB N="324">

&thorn;e alta&rtail;, betwix &thorn;e prophesie &amp; &thorn;e
epistu&llbar;, he fe&llbar; o&ntail; slepe; and &thorn;er was none at
durste waky&ntail; hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;e subdeky&ntail; sulde go
rede &thorn;e piste&llbar;, &amp; he durst not go or &thorn;e bisshop
assigne&dtail; hy&mtail;.  And so &thorn;ai stude &thorn;e space of ij
or iij howris abydan&dtail; hy&mtail;.  So at &thorn;e laste one of
&thorn;aim waken&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; sai&dtail; &thorn;e peple
recedi&dtail; away, and desyri&dtail; hy&mtail; to command <NOTE ID="P324.N1">MS. commandid.</NOTE> &thorn;e deky&ntail; to rede &thorn;e episti&llbar;.
And &thorn;a&ntail; he sai&dtail;; "Brether, be not truble&dtail;,
ffor my bruther Marty&ntail; is passi&dtail; vnto God and I di&dtail;
&thorn;e obseruance at his berya&llbar;.  &amp; becauce ye
waken&dtail; me so sone I hafe lefte &thorn;e laste colett
vnsai&dtail;."  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai noti&dtail; &thorn;e day
&amp; &thorn;e how&rtail;, and &thorn;ai fan&dtail; at Saynt
Marty&ntail; was decesi&dtail; &thorn;e same tyme, &amp; passid vnto
God&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLXXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Martirium sustinent aliqui ex magno
fervore.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Ambrose tellis how o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; a grete
multitude of cristenme&ntail; war drawe&ntail; vnto martirdo&mtail;,
&thorn;er come a mayde&ntail; of hur fre liste with a hertelie desyre
vnto &thorn;aim for to be slay&ntail; with &thorn;aim.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; a ryche ma&ntail; &thorn;at was a payno&mtail; spak
vnto hur &amp; sai&dtail;; "Womma&ntail;, whedur rynys &thorn;ou so
faste?"  And sho ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "I go
vnto my fren&dtail; &thorn;at hase biddi&ntail; me with o&thorn;er
vnto &thorn;e weddyng &thorn;er grete daynttys er."  And so he
vmthoght hy&mtail; at sho calli&dtail; Criste hur fren&dtail;, and at
she ra&ntail; to be martyr&dtail;, &amp; trowi&dtail; sho had bene a
fule &amp; skornyd hur, &amp; sai&dtail;; "Say vnto &thorn;i
fren&dtail; at sen&dtail; me ane of his rosis."  And so sho was
martir&dtail; emang o&thorn;er.  &amp; als sone as sho was dede and
fally&ntail; dow&ntail;, a fayr chyl&dtail; come vnto hym with a white
cop&ptail; fu&llbar; of rosis &thorn;at saver&dtail; passan&dtail;
wele, &amp; tol&dtail; hy&mtail; at &thorn;e womma&ntail; fren&dtail;
&thorn;at was passi&dtail; sent hy&mtail; so&mtail; of his rosis as he
ha&dtail; aski&dtail;.  &amp; he sett &thorn;aim dow&ntail; &amp;
onone he was vanysshi&dtail; away.  And &thorn;is ma&ntail; was
passan&dtail; fer&dtail; &amp; compuncte, for als meku&llbar; as it
was not rose tyme; and he vmthoght hy&mtail; at God of criste&ntail;
me&ntail; had calli&dtail; hy&mtail; vnto martyrdo&mtail;.  And
evy&ntail; furt&hbar;-with he went vnto &thorn;e place of &thorn;e
martyrdo&mtail; and sai&dtail; he was a criste&ntail; ma&ntail;.
&amp; onone



<PB N="325">

he was hedi&dtail; &amp; cristen&dtail; in his awn blude, &amp; broght
vnto &thorn;e rosary of paradyce.

</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM><FOREIGN>Mater tenere diligit filium suum.  Infra de morte, ij 
<NOTE ID="P325.N1">MS. iij.</NOTE> , et de visitacione, ij 
<NOTE ID="P325.N2">MS. j.</NOTE> .</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLXXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Matrimonium contrahi debet magis inter personas
bonarum condicionum quam diuitum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iustinus tellis how o&ntail; a tyme a ma&ntail; aski&dtail;
cownce&llbar; at Theristides <NOTE ID="P325.N3">Harl. MS. Thimistidem.</NOTE> of Athenys
whe&thorn;er <NOTE ID="P325.N4">Vtrum filiam suam pauperi sed ornato, uel locupleti sed parum probato collocaret.</NOTE> hy&mtail; was bettir giff his
doghter vnto a pure ma&ntail;, or to a riche ma&ntail;.  And he
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "I hafe levur &thorn;e
money of &thorn;e ma&ntail; &thorn;a&ntail; money be boght vnto
&thorn;e ma&ntail;."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Matrimonio debet accipi vxor prudens magis quam

diues.  Infra de vxore.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLXXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Matrimonio plus queritur substancia frequenter
quam persona.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Agellius tellis how &thorn;at Cato&ntail; som tyme had a doghter,
and whe&ntail; hur furst husband was dea&dtail; sho come &amp;
aski&dtail; hur fader whi he wol&dtail; not make hur to hafe a noder
husban&dtail;.  And he ansswer&dtail; hur agay&ntail; &amp;
sai&dtail;; "For I ca&ntail; not fynde a ma&ntail; bod he wolde titter
hafe &thorn;i gudis &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;i selfe."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLXXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Matrimonialis coniunccio periculosa est.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis how o&ntail; a tyme a yong ma&ntail; come vnto
Socrates &amp; aski&dtail; hy&mtail; cownce&llbar;, whether hy&mtail;
was bettir wed hy&mtail; a wife or nay.  And he ansswer&dtail;
hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Ather of &thorn;aim










<PB N="326">

is a grete penance to do, for &amp; &thorn;ou be not we&dtail;,
&thorn;ou may happely sy&ntail; in fornicacio&ntail;, or in avowtrie,
or els be i&llbar; defamy&dtail; &amp; sklandre&dtail; &amp; neuer be
at no certantie with &thorn;i selfe.  And if &thorn;ou be we&dtail;
&thorn;ou may happe&ntail; we&dtail; a shrew at will be &thorn;i
maister, an&dtail; &thorn;ou bus be fer&dtail; for hur frendis, &amp;
euer be besy &amp; labur, &amp; ofte in stryfe an&dtail; debate, &amp;
suffer many grete wur&dtail; &amp; say nothyng agay&ntail;, &amp; hafe
a snowryng cowntenance, &amp; happelie bryng vp o&thorn;er mens
childer.  &amp; if &thorn;ou do nott wele to &thorn;i wyfe &thorn;ou
sa&llbar; be bosti&dtail; with hur frendis, &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ou
sa&llbar; euer liff in trubble &amp; in dissese."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLXXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Matrimonialis coniunccio tediosa est.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Theofrastus &thorn;e philosophur say&dtail;, a womma&ntail; is
owder fayr or fowle, and if sho be fayr onone sho sa&llbar; be
luffi&dtail; &amp; desyri&dtail; to be had, and if sho be fowle sho
wi&llbar; desyre to be had.  And &thorn;erfo&rtail; it is har&dtail;
to kepe &thorn;at at many me&ntail; desyris, and it is hevie to hafe
&thorn;at in welde &thorn;at no ma&ntail; dedengnys to hafe.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mediatrix mulier.  Infra de muliere.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Medicorum iudicia de infirmis non semper eveniunt.

Supra de Basilio.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Medicus proprietarius monachus in sterquilinio

sepelitur.  Infra de proprietate, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Medicus debet infirmis ea que sunt salutis sue

proponere.  Infra de predestinacione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Meditacio inferni penitentem corporaliter extenuat,

et meditacio paradisi exhilarat 
<NOTE ID="P326.N1">MS. exhillarat.</NOTE> .  Supra de

apostasia.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLXXX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Memoriam sui acquirunt aliqui per aliqua facta
interdum eciam mala
<NOTE ID="P326.N2">So Harl. MS. The translator's heading is incomplete.</NOTE>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis &amp; says how &thorn;at, som tyme <NOTE ID="P326.N3">MS. <HI REND="i">adds</HI> som while <HI REND="i">here</HI>.</NOTE> , certay&ntail; fol&ktee;, for to assecute
euerlastan&dtail; memorie, dowtis not for to do grete








<PB N="327">

trispas, whase namys he sai&dtail; &thorn;at he kenny&dtail; nott.  So
&thorn;er was a ma&ntail; &thorn;at spirri&dtail; Ermodeus how clere
he might be ha&dtail; <NOTE ID="P327.N1">Lat. MSS. quo modo subito clarus posset haberi.</NOTE> ; he ansswer&dtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;, &thorn;at &amp; he slew any wurthi
ma&ntail;, it sul&dtail; tur&ntail; hy&mtail; vnto grete <NOTE ID="P327.N2">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI> grete.</NOTE> glorie.  And so he slew one &thorn;at hight
Philip&ptail;, and he was take&ntail; &amp; putt to dea&dtail;
&thorn;erfo&rtail;.  And after-ward it was fo&ntail; &thorn;at he
di&dtail; it be commandment of &thorn;e Dya&ntail; of Ephesie <NOTE ID="P327.N3">Harl. MS. Sic eciam inuentum est, quod Diane Ephesei sic templum incendere uellet, ut opere pulcherrimo consumpto nomen suum per totum orbem innotesceret.</NOTE> , for sho wolde hafe burny&dtail; &thorn;e temple.
et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLXXXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Memoria mulieris in corde viri remanere non
debet.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' how &thorn;at a noble womma&ntail;, ane
olde wyfe <NOTE ID="P327.N4">Lat. MSS. Matrona quedam nobilis et senex.</NOTE> , come vnto ane abbot &thorn;at hight
Arsenius, to se hy&mtail;, &amp; he prayed &thorn;e bisshop at sho
sul&dtail; not se hy&mtail;, &amp; he wol&dtail; not graunt
&thorn;erto.  So sho come vnto his ce&llbar; dure, &amp; fan&dtail;
hy&mtail; &thorn;er-att, &amp; fe&llbar; dow&ntail; o&ntail; hir kneis
afor&ntail; hy&mtail;.  &amp; he with grete dedeyng tuke hur vp&ptail;
and sai&dtail; vnto hur; "And &thorn;ou wi&llbar; se my face, se itt
now."  And sho for shame durst not luke vpo&ntail; hy&mtail;, bod sho
went away &amp; praye&dtail; hy&mtail; to pray for hur vnto Go&dtail;,
&amp; hafe hur in his mynde always.  And he sai&dtail;, nay, he
wol&dtail; nott, he sulde pray Go&dtail; to do away &thorn;e
myn&dtail; of hur oute of his harte.  And whe&ntail; sho hard
&thorn;is, sho was gretelie trubble&dtail;, and went in-to &thorn;e
cetie &amp; fe&llbar; into &thorn;e axis.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e
bissho&ptail; come to vyssit hur, sho sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "I
a&mtail; so hevie &thorn;at I mo&ntail; dy."  &amp; &thorn;e
bisshop&ptail; ansswer[d] hur agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "Knowis
&thorn;ou not at &thorn;ou ert a womma&ntail;?  And &thorn;e
devu&llbar; tempis me&ntail; with womme&ntail;, &amp; specia&llbar;
haly me&ntail;.  And &thorn;erfo&rtail; yone ma&ntail; sai&dtail; vnto
the as he di&dtail;.  Bod &thorn;uf a&llbar; he sai&dtail; so, yit he
prayis for &thorn;i saule."  And so he comfurthi&dtail; hur and sho
wente home vnto hur aw&ntail; place.  et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Memoria mortis est multum vtilis.  Supra de

conuersione, iiij, et de confessore, v, et infra de morte.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Memorie labiles <NOTE ID="P327.N5">MS. labilis.</NOTE> sunt aliqui.  Infra de
muliere, iiij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>



<PB N="328">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLXXXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mendacium eciam corporaliter nocet.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rea&dtail; in 'Legenda Lombardica' how Iulius &amp; Iulianus
wer brether, and &thorn;ai bygi&dtail; a kurk, and be commandment of
&thorn;e Emperour Theodoce, a&llbar; &thorn;at evur come by &thorn;aim
&thorn;ai wol&dtail; gar &thorn;aim abyde, &amp; helpe &thorn;aim.  So
&thorn;er happen&dtail; a meneya co&mtail; &thorn;er-away [with] a
carte, &amp; &thorn;ai lai&dtail; ane of &thorn;er felows in &thorn;e
carte, &amp; cover&dtail; hy&mtail; with a clothe as he had bene
dea&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai come be &thorn;is werke,
&thorn;ies ij saynttis bad &thorn;aim abide with &thorn;er carte &amp;
helpe &thorn;aim, and &thorn;ai sai&dtail; &thorn;ai had in &thorn;er
carte a dead ma&ntail; &amp; &thorn;erfo&rtail; &thorn;ai had nede
at haste &thorn;aim away.  And &thorn;e sayntis ansswer&dtail;
&thorn;aim &amp; sai&dtail;; "Whi lie ye?  Go your wais, &amp; as ye
say so be it vnto you."  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai war passi&dtail;,
&thorn;ai calli&dtail; vppo&ntail; &thorn;er felow and &thorn;ai
fan&dtail; hy&mtail; starke dea&dtail;.  And fro &thorn;ens furt&hbar;
&thorn;er was nane at come &thorn;er-away at durst ans make a le vnto
&thorn;ies sayntis.  et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLXXXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mendacium aliquibus temporaliter nocet.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Ex 'Legenda Lombardica' we rede how &thorn;at a grete aduocatt of
&thorn;e Ceustus ordur was made a mon&ktee;, &amp; he went oft sithis
for to defend cawsis of &thorn;e abbott, &amp; euer he was
caste&ntail; &amp; had &thorn;e war.  And &thorn;e abbott &amp;
&thorn;e monkis wax wrathe with hy&mtail; &amp; sai&dtail; vnto
hy&mtail;; "How is it at &thorn;ou fallis alway in our cawsis, and
whils &thorn;ou was in &thorn;e werl&dtail; &thorn;ou prevayli&dtail;
alway in o&thorn;er mens cawsis?"  And he ansswer&dtail; &thorn;aim
agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "While I was secular I was not
fer&dtail; to lie, ffor oft sythes be my fraudis &amp; be my lesyngis
I ouercome myne aduersaries.  And now becauce I dar say no &thorn;ing
bod treut&hbar;, it happens me &thorn;e contrarie."  And so he was
commawndi&dtail; vnto his cloystur.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mentiri non debet religiosus.  Infra de religione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mendacium eciam punitur in presenti.  Infra de

periurio et de paupertate.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>

<PB N="329">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLXXXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mercatorum
<NOTE ID="P329.N1">MS. Marcatorum.</NOTE> vita amota
<NOTE ID="P329.N2">MS. ammota.</NOTE> computacione, a multis
approbatur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Libro de Dono Timoris,' how ane Erle of Pictauence
cled hy&mtail; dyuers tymys in pure mans clothyng whils he had sene
a&llbar; maner of craftis &amp; offes.  And whe&ntail; he had
serchi&dtail; a&llbar; &thorn;ies, he sai&dtail; at &thorn;e
merchan&dtail; crafte war &thorn;e beste crafte &thorn;at he
fan&dtail;, &amp; &thorn;e beste offes, war not a thyng war, &thorn;at
is <NOTE ID="P329.N3">MS. it.</NOTE> to say, cowntyng &amp; rekynyng in &thorn;e
en&dtail;.  For, he sai&dtail;, at evy&ntail; whe&ntail; &thorn;ai
come home &thorn;ai made rekkenyng of &thorn;e leste peny at &thorn;ai
reseyvi&dtail;, and at &thorn;ai expundi&dtail;, and he &thorn;at made
not a gude rekynyng was caste&ntail; in priso&ntail; &amp;
holde&ntail; &thorn;er.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLXXXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mercatores in empcione et vendicione frequenter
menciuntur vt lucrentur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis of ij cetisens of Colay&ntail; confessi&dtail;
&thorn;aim of ij maners of syns, &amp; &thorn;e tane was leyng &amp;
&thorn;e toder manesweryng.  And &thorn;ai tolde &thorn;e preste
&thorn;at with-oute&ntail; &thorn;ies ij &thorn;ai myght nowder by nor
se&llbar;.  And &thorn;e preste tol&dtail; &thorn;aim at &thorn;ies
was grete synnys, bod he bad &thorn;aim vse &thorn;aim o&ntail;
&thorn;is maner of wyse; "Furste lofe your gude as ye wi&llbar; giff
it, and it sa&llbar; be wele with you, I waran&dtail;."  And &thorn;ai
promysi&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;ai sulde so doo &thorn;at yere.  Bod
be lettyng of &thorn;e devu&llbar; &thorn;at yere &thorn;ai wa&ntail;
no thyng, and at &thorn;e yere en&dtail; &thorn;ai come vnto &thorn;e
preste &amp; tolde hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;e preste tol&dtail;
&thorn;aim at it was bod a temptacio&ntail; of &thorn;e fende, &amp;
bad &thorn;aim trow hy&mtail;; bod he sai&dtail;, "Feste it faste in
your mynde, and &thorn;in&ktee; at ye wi&llbar; kepe hit fro hens
forwhar&dtail;, and it sa&llbar; be wele enog&hbar; with you."  And so
&thorn;ai di&dtail;, and with a few yeris &thorn;ai war passan&dtail;
riche me&ntail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mercator de bonis suis et non de alienis debet

mercari.  Supra de abbate.
</FOREIGN>


<PB N="330">
</ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mercator 
<NOTE ID="P330.N1">MS. marcator.</NOTE>  vicium rei non debet celare.  Infra de
negociacione.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLXXXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mensura semper debet esse iusta.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how in &thorn;e bisshopprik in Cola&ntail; som
tyme &thorn;er was a wedow at was a brewster, &amp; vsi&dtail; to
se&llbar; ale, &amp; fyre happen&dtail; in &thorn;e tow&ntail; &amp;
byrnyd a grete dele &thorn;eroff.  And whe&ntail; sho saw it come nere
hur howse, sho wol&dtail; nothyng remow furt&hbar; of hur howse, bod
tuke hur mettis &amp; hur messurs at sho filli&dtail; ale with, and
sett &thorn;aim at hur dure with-oute, &amp; sai&dtail;; "O, &thorn;ou
rightwus &amp; mercifu&llbar; God!  If I hafe rightwuslie &amp;
trewlie mesur&dtail; with thies mesurs to &thorn;aim at I selde ale
to, I beseke ye at &thorn;is tyme to behalde my myster, and at
&thorn;ou wolde vuchesafe to spare me and my hows &amp; my
howsol&dtail; &thorn;at is &thorn;er-in.  And if I hafe with
&thorn;ies messurs messur&dtail; wrang, or disseyvi&dtail; any
creatur, &thorn;a&ntail;, Lor&dtail;, I wi&llbar; at my howse be
burnyd &amp; a&llbar; &thorn;e gudis at I hafe." Lo! &thorn;is was a
mervalos faythe of &thorn;is womma&ntail;!  And yit was &thorn;e
mercie of God mo&rtail; mervalos, ffor whe&ntail; &thorn;e fire come
at hur howse, at a&llbar; folk saw &amp; had grete wonder
&thorn;eroff, as God <NOTE ID="P330.N2">MS. gold.</NOTE> wol&dtail;, &thorn;e
fflawme at had burny&dtail; a&llbar; &thorn;e tow&ntail;-end to thedir
sesi&dtail;, &amp; wol&dtail; bur&ntail; no maner of &thorn;ing of
[hur] howse, nowder thak nor tymmer.  &amp; yit not-withstandyng,
a&llbar; &thorn;e howse semy&dtail; clene our with fire as it had
burny&dtail;, &amp; yit was it nothyng hurte with &thorn;e fyre, nor
no gude of hurris &thorn;at was &thorn;erin.  And &thorn;e fire
sesi&dtail; &amp; burny&dtail; no ferrer, &thorn;at a hondret&hbar;
me&ntail; cuthe not sease befo&rtail;.  And here-by hur neghburs
vnderstude &thorn;at hur messurs warr gude &amp; trew.  et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLXXXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Meretrix.  Mulier accusat quos ad peccatum
trahere non potest.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a commo&ntail;
womma&ntail; &thorn;at was fayr, and sho folowi&dtail; a grete
lor&dtail; fro tow&ntail; to tow&ntail;, for &thorn;e lordis me&ntail;
synny&dtail; with hur euer whe&ntail; &thorn;aim liste, and &thorn;e
lor&dtail;





<PB N="331">

wiste not.  &amp; at &thorn;e laste &thorn;e lor&dtail; preste
accusi&dtail; hur vnto &thorn;e lor&dtail;, &amp; &thorn;e lor&dtail;
garte ca&llbar; hur befo&rtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; sho denyed itt and
accusi&dtail; &thorn;is preste, &amp; sai&dtail; he compleny&dtail;
o&ntail; hur becauce sho wol&dtail; not consent vnto hy&mtail;, and
&thorn;is sho oblisshi&dtail; hur to prufe.  So at &thorn;e laste sho
feny&dtail; hur contrite, &amp; come vnto &thorn;is same preste &amp;
shrafe hur.  And in &thorn;e en&dtail; of hur confessio&ntail; sho
sai&dtail; &thorn;at sho was so tempi&dtail; with his luff &thorn;at
bod if sho had itt sho sulde sla hur selfe.  And &thorn;is preste was
afer&dtail; o&ntail; hur &amp; had no faste purpos to sy&ntail; with
hyr, yit he assigne&dtail; hur a place &amp; a tyme &thorn;er he
sul&dtail; co&mtail; vnto hur; and sho was fay&ntail; &thorn;erof
&amp; went &amp; telli&dtail; &thorn;e lor&dtail; how &thorn;e prest
had promissi&dtail; vnto hur.  And &thorn;is preste come to &thorn;e
place befo&rtail; &thorn;e how&rtail;, &amp; he made in &thorn;e same
place a bed of dry wu&dtail;, &amp; put stra &thorn;erin &amp; put
fyre vnder-nethe in tow, &amp; cover&dtail; it clenlie with a shete.
And belife sho come &amp; &thorn;e fyre bega&ntail; to kynde&llbar; in
&thorn;e be&dtail;, &amp; &thorn;e prest went &thorn;erto, &amp;
lai&dtail; hy&mtail; dow&ntail; &thorn;ero&ntail;, evy&ntail; in
&thorn;e fire, &amp; bad hur co&mtail; vnto hy&mtail;.  &amp; &thorn;e
fire rase a&llbar; abowte hy&mtail; &amp; sho calli&dtail; o&ntail;
hy&mtail; &amp; wol&dtail; hafe ha&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;ine, &amp;
he lay sti&llbar; &amp; was nothyng burny&dtail;, nor his clothes
nowther.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is wrichi&dtail; womma&ntail; was
conpuncte &amp; reknowlegi&dtail; hur selfe &thorn;at sho
accusi&dtail; &thorn;is holye ma&ntail; of verray rancor &amp;
i&llbar; wi&llbar;.  And &thorn;is done &thorn;is holie preste went
&amp; made hy&mtail; a mon&ktee;.

</P>
<P>
