<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLXXXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Miles malus per seram penitentiam
saluatur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis of a knyght &thorn;at <NOTE ID="P331.N1">MS. &thorn;an.</NOTE> on a
tyme was take&ntail; with his enmys &amp; slay&ntail;.  And whe&ntail;
he saw &thorn;at hy&mtail; burde nedelyngis dy, he sai&dtail;
&thorn;ies iij wurdis, " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Domine, miserere
mei.</FOREIGN> Lor&dtail;, hafe



<PB N="332">

mercie o&ntail; me."  And whe&ntail; he dye&dtail;, a ma&ntail;
&thorn;at was vexi&dtail; with a fen&dtail; was delyver&dtail;.  So
afterwar&dtail; &thorn;e fen&dtail; come agay&ntail; vnto &thorn;is
ma&ntail; and vexi&dtail; hy&mtail; hugelie, more &thorn;a&ntail; he
di&dtail; afo&rtail;.  And a gude holie ma&ntail; come vnto hy&mtail;
&amp; aski&dtail; hy&mtail; whi &thorn;at he did so.  And he
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "We war many fendis
gadur&dtail; samen at &thorn;e dea&dtail; of swylk a knyght, and
becauce we gatt nothyng &thorn;er, &thorn;erfo&rtail; a&llbar;
&thorn;at I ca&ntail; sa&llbar; I venge me in hy&mtail; &thorn;is."
And &thorn;is holie ma&ntail; spirri&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;e cauce
how &thorn;ai had no power of &thorn;at knyght, and he ansswer&dtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail; &thorn;at &thorn;e knyght say&dtail;
alonelie iij wurdis or he dye&dtail;, "be &thorn;e whilk a&llbar;
&thorn;e power &thorn;at we had in hy&mtail; was loste."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCLXXXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Miles punitur et saluatur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;er was a knyght of
Saxo&ntail;, &thorn;at was cled in new skarlett clothes, and o&ntail;
a day as he was rydan&dtail;, he mett a husban&dtail;-ma&ntail;
dryvan&dtail; his carte.  And with &thorn;e sprenclyng &amp; dasshyng
of &thorn;e whelis, &thorn;is knyghtis clothis war al todasshi&dtail;
with myre.  And &thorn;is knyght, as a prowde ma&ntail; &amp; a
tyran&dtail;, drew hys swer&dtail; &amp; smate of &thorn;e ta legg of
&thorn;is husban&dtail; be his kne.  So afterwar&dtail; &thorn;urgh
&thorn;e grace of Go&dtail; he wex sorowfu&llbar; for his sy&ntail;,
&amp; made hy&mtail; a mon&ktee; of &thorn;e Seustus ordur.  And
with-in a few yeris after he was made monke, &thorn;er bega&ntail; to
brede a sur like a sylk threde in his legg, o&ntail; &thorn;e same
syde &amp; in &thorn;e same place whar he cutt of &thorn;e
husbandma&ntail; legg.  And be little &amp; little it bega&ntail; to
rote, so &thorn;at att &thorn;e laste mawkis bre&dtail; &thorn;erin.
And &thorn;a&ntail; he wex fay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Now I trow
for to hafe forgyfnes, ffor I se o&ntail; my body &thorn;e syngne of
Iob."  And so he liffi&dtail; many day in grete contricio&ntail;, and
at &thorn;e laste, &thorn;urg&hbar; &thorn;is maledie, he dye&dtail;
&amp; yeldy&dtail; God a gude sawle.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXC.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Miles demone
<NOTE ID="P332.N1">MS. deuocione.</NOTE> vt famulo vtitur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis of a knyght &thorn;at dwelte in Saxo&ntail;, and
he was famos &amp; noble in armys, and his name was Albert
Stobber&dtail;.  So



<PB N="333">

o&ntail; a day hy&mtail; happen&dtail; to co&mtail; vnto a place
&thorn;er a damyse&llbar; was vexi&dtail; with a fen&dtail;, and onone
as he come sho bega&ntail; to cry and say&dtail;, " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ecce! amicus meus venit.</FOREIGN> Lo! my fren&dtail; is
comme&ntail;."  And evur as he come inwar&dtail; sho bad gyff
hy&mtail; row&mtail;, and lat hur fren&dtail; co&mtail; ner hur.  And
&thorn;uf a&llbar; he war wrothe &thorn;erwith, yitt he smyli&dtail;
&amp; sai&dtail;; "&thorn;ou fende, &thorn;ou ert bod a fole!  Wharto
vexis &thorn;ou &thorn;is womma&ntail; o&ntail; &thorn;is maner,
&thorn;at is so innocent?  Lefe hur &amp; go with me vnto turnamentis
&amp; batels."  And &thorn;is fend sai&dtail; he wol&dtail; gladlie go
with hy&mtail; and he wol&dtail; latt hy&mtail; entre into his bodie,
"or els to lat me in &thorn;i sadle or in &thorn;i brydi&llbar;, or in
so&mtail; other parte at longis vnto the."  And &thorn;is knyght had
grete compassio&ntail; of &thorn;is noble maydy&ntail; and sai&dtail;;
"And &thorn;ou wi&llbar; pas fro&mtail; hyne I wi&llbar; grawnt
&thorn;e a plyte of my gow&ntail; vnder-nethe a condicio&ntail;, at
&thorn;ou sa&llbar; not hurte me, bod whe&ntail; at I wi&llbar;, onone
&thorn;ou sa&llbar; pas fro me."  And he beheste hy&mtail; &thorn;at
he shul&dtail;.  And with &thorn;at he went oute of &thorn;e
maydy&ntail; &amp; come in-to a plite of &thorn;e gow&ntail; and made
&thorn;er a grete movyng.  And fro&mtail; &thorn;at how&rtail;
&thorn;is knyght had so gret a strent&hbar; &amp; a comfurt&hbar;, at
whoso-euer he wold he mot ouerthraw &thorn;aim, &amp; who&mtail; so
euer hy&mtail; liste take, and &thorn;ai war ne so swyfte, yit he mott
take &thorn;aim.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e knyght satt in &thorn;e
kur&ktee; at his prayers, &thorn;is fen&dtail; made a grete gruchyng
and sai&dtail; hy&mtail; thoght &thorn;at he taryd long &thorn;er.
And he kaste holie watir o&ntail; him <NOTE ID="P333.N1">MS. he.</NOTE> ,
&thorn;is fend wolde byd hy&mtail; war at the tuchyd not hy&mtail;.
So o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;is knyght happend to co&mtail; in-to a kurk
whar &thorn;er was made a sermo&ntail; of &thorn;e cros.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e fend said vnto hy&mtail;; "What duse
&thorn;ou her?"  And &thorn;is knyght ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
sai&dtail;; "Now I wu&llbar; forsake &thorn;e &amp; seryff Almightie
Go&dtail;."  And &thorn;e fen&dtail; ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
sai&dtail; "What displesans haste &thorn;ou fo&ntail; in me!  I neuer
yit hurte &thorn;e, bod I hafe broght &thorn;e vnto meku&llbar;
wurshup and riches, and &thorn;urg&hbar; me &thorn;ou erte made
passyng glorious." &thorn;is knyght ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "Loo! now I behol&dtail; &thorn;e cros,
and I comman&dtail; &thorn;e now, in vertue of Hy&mtail; &thorn;at was
done o&ntail; &thorn;e cros, &thorn;at fro&mtail; hens furt&hbar;
&thorn;ou nevur tur&ntail; vnto me agay&ntail;."  And with &thorn;at
&thorn;is fend lefte hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;is knyght burnyd hy&mtail;
with &thorn;e cros, and went to beyon&dtail; se, &amp; &thorn;er he
servid Almightie God ij yere.



<PB N="334">

And after &thorn;at he come home agay&ntail;, and byggi&dtail; ane
hospita&llbar;.  And &thorn;erin he abade a&llbar; his life after,
&amp; serryffed seke folk of swilk as &thorn;aim nedu&dtail;.  And so
in peas &thorn;er he endi&dtail; his life.

</P>
