<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> CCCCXCI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Miles cruce signatus vxorem et liberos relinquens
multum meretur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iacobus de Vetriaco tellis how o&ntail; a tyme a knyght &thorn;at
was marki&dtail; with &thorn;e cros went fro&mtail; his aw&ntail;
place to beyon&dtail; &thorn;e se.  Or he wente, afo&rtail; a grete
parte of his frendis, he calli&dtail; a&llbar; his childer afor&ntail;
hy&mtail;, &amp; he hawsi&dtail; &amp; kyssi&dtail; &thorn;aim frendlye,
&amp; kyssy&dtail; &thorn;aim tenderly, &amp; wepyd swetelie.  So one
come in &amp; callid o&ntail; hy&mtail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "Sur, your
felows abydis you, lefe &thorn;ies childer &amp; co&mtail; your
wayes!"  And &thorn;is knyght ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
say&dtail;; "I do &thorn;is to make me mo&rtail; hevie &amp; sad
whe&ntail; I parte with &thorn;aim, at my mede may be &thorn;e
mo&rtail; for &thorn;e levyng of &thorn;aim."

</P>
<P>
