<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mors aliquando differtur orationibus sanctorum.

Supra de Basilio, ij 
<NOTE ID="P346.N1">MS. iij.</NOTE> .</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Morte subita moriuntur aliquando peccatores,
eciam in actu peccandi.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Petrus Damyanus tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a prynce
&thorn;at hight Salamitanus <NOTE ID="P346.N2">Lat. MSS. Princeps Salamitanus, Salanitanus.</NOTE> .  So o&ntail; a
day hy&mtail; happen&dtail; to luke vp vnto a hy&llbar;, and he saw
bruste oute at &thorn;e top of &thorn;e hi&llbar; grete low &amp;
smoke.  And whe&ntail; he saw it he sai&dtail; vnto &thorn;aim at
stude abowte hy&mtail;; "Withoute&ntail; dowte &thorn;er is so&mtail;
curste ryche ma&ntail; dea&dtail; &amp; gane vnto he&llbar;, ffor
&thorn;er is swilk a custo&mtail; in &thorn;at contret&hbar;,
&thorn;at whe&ntail; &thorn;e dea&dtail; of a curste riche ma&ntail;
drawis nere, &thorn;at hy&llbar; wi&llbar; caste oute low &amp; stynk
of pykk and burnte stane." And whe&ntail; &thorn;is was sai&dtail;,
apo&ntail; &thorn;e nexte nyght after, as &thorn;is prince thoght he
was sekur enoghe &amp; lay in his bed with a strompett, sodanlie he
dye&dtail;.  Whame, as sho tel&dtail; afterwar&dtail;, sho
suffre&dtail; lyg long vppo&ntail; hur body, and at &thorn;e laste sho
feli&dtail; he was no ma&ntail; bod a stynkyng caryo&ntail;, &amp;
keste hy&mtail; of hur.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mors eciam omnes ditissimos spoliat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Cronicles' of ane &thorn;at hight Saladinus,
whe&ntail; o&ntail; a tyme he knew &thorn;at he sulde dye att Damaske,
he calli&dtail; his hansma&ntail; vnto hy&mtail; &amp; sai&dtail;;
"&thorn;ou at was wunt to bere my banor vnto bate&llbar;, bere now
&thorn;e banor of my dea&dtail;, &thorn;at is to say a fowle clothe,
&thorn;urg&hbar; a&llbar; Damaske, &amp; cry &amp; say &thorn;us,
'Behol&dtail;! &thorn;e kyng of &thorn;e Orient is bow&ntail; to dye,
and he mo&ntail; nothyng bere with hy&mtail; bod &thorn;is fowle
clothe.'"  And onone after he dye&dtail;, &amp; was wo&ntail; in
&thorn;e same clothe.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Morientes in hora mortis temptati per orationes

sanctorum adiuuantur.  Supra de demone, iij 
<NOTE ID="P346.N3">MS. iiij.</NOTE> .
</FOREIGN>


<PB N="347">
</ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mors est timenda.  Infra de timore.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Morte improvisa 
<NOTE ID="P347.N1">MS. inprovisa.</NOTE>  moriuntur aliquando aliqui.  Supra

de Archidiacono.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mors omnia facit relinquere.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Libro de Dono Timoris' how &thorn;at &thorn;e kyng of
Lothoringe, &thorn;at was bod a yong ma&ntail;, o&ntail; a tyme
whe&ntail; he was in a trans of dea&dtail;, he behel&dtail; his palas
&amp; his grete howsis and say&dtail;; "O! &thorn;ou Lord Go&dtail;!
How meku&llbar; &thorn;is werl&dtail; aght to be dispysy&dtail;!  For
I, &thorn;at hase had so many grete palas and so many howsis to lygg
in, &thorn;is nyght I wate nott whythir I mo&ntail; goo, nor who
&thorn;at mo&ntail; take me to herberye."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mors quantumcunque magnos humiliat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Petrus Alphonsis <NOTE ID="P347.N2">MS. Alphensis.</NOTE> tellis how &thorn;at
whe&ntail; kyng Alexander was dea&dtail; &amp; his tombe was gaylie
made of sylver &amp; of golde, in his palas &thorn;er gader in many
philosophers.  And ane of &thorn;aim sai&dtail;; "Alexander yisterday
made tresur of golde and now it is evy&ntail; contrarie, for golde
makis tresur of hy&mtail;."  And &thorn;a&ntail; a noder sai&dtail;;
"Yisterday wolde not a&llbar; &thorn;is werl&dtail; suffis vnto
hy&mtail;, and &thorn;is day for yerdis of gron&dtail; alonelie
sufficis hy&mtail;."  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e thrid sai&dtail;;
"Yisterday he had rewle of a&llbar; &thorn;e peple, and &thorn;is day
&thorn;e peple hase rewle of hy&mtail;."  Tha&ntail; &thorn;e iiij
sai&dtail;; "Yisterday he myght hafe delyver&dtail; many peple fro
dea&dtail;, and &thorn;is day, for a&llbar; his power, he mot [not]
esshew dea&dtail;."  Tha&ntail; &thorn;e v sai&dtail;; "Yisterday he
le&dtail; a grete hoste, and today he is led of &thorn;aim &amp; putt
vnto berya&llbar;."  Tha&ntail; &thorn;e sext say&dtail;; "Yisterday
he thristi&dtail; dow&ntail; &thorn;e ert&hbar;, and &thorn;is day
&thorn;e ert&hbar; &thorn;rustis hy&mtail; dow&ntail;."  And
&thorn;a&ntail; a noder sai&dtail;; "Yisterday &thorn;e peple dred
hy&mtail; gretelie, and &thorn;is day &thorn;ai sett right not by
hy&mtail;."  And &thorn;a&ntail; a noder sai&dtail;; "Yisterday





<PB N="348">

he had bothe many frendis and enmys, and &thorn;is day a&llbar; er in lyke
vnto hy&mtail;."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mortis eciam consideracio multum valet homini
in dignitate constituto.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Ysidorus tellis how so&mtail; [tyme] &thorn;er was a custo&mtail;,
&thorn;at o&ntail; &thorn;e furste day of &thorn;e crownyng of
&thorn;e Emperour of Constantynople, whe&ntail; he was in his moste
ioy, a maso&ntail; sulde co&mtail; &amp; bryng hy&mtail; iiij or v
maner of stonys of marble and say vnto hy&mtail; o&ntail; &thorn;is
maner of wyse, and byd hy&mtail; chese of &thorn;ies of whilk he wolde
hafe his grave made.  And so it was wunt to be done in &thorn;e cowrte
of Rome, for whe&ntail; &thorn;e Pope was chose&ntail; &thorn;er was
broght afor&ntail; hy&mtail; a pece of lyne-tow, &amp; whe&ntail; fyre
was sett in it, &thorn;a&ntail; was sayd vnto hy&mtail;; "Thus gose
&thorn;e ioy of &thorn;is werl&dtail; away, as &thorn;is fyre bryngis
&thorn;is tow in-to a spar&ktee;, and afterwar&dtail; in-to right
noght."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mortis certitudo quantumcunque differetur multos
inducit ad bonum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Libro de Dono Timoris' how &thorn;er was a ma&ntail;
&thorn;at had meky&llbar; connyng in literatu&rtail; of phisykis, and
he was giffe&ntail; vnto vanyties of &thorn;is werl&dtail;.  So
o&ntail; a tyme hy&mtail; happend to be at matyns o&ntail; a Sonday,
&amp; &thorn;er he harder in &thorn;e legen&dtail; of lang life of
olde fadurs, and how alway in &thorn;e en&dtail; of ilkone it was
say&dtail;, '<FOREIGN>Mortuus est</FOREIGN>, he is dea&dtail;.'  He vmbethoght hy&mtail;
&thorn;at it wol&dtail; happe&ntail; so o&ntail; hy&mtail;, and he
liffi&dtail; neuer so lang, and whe&ntail; he conseyvi&dtail;
&thorn;is, he dispysid &thorn;e werlde &amp; entre&dtail; into
&thorn;e ordur of freer prechurs.  And &thorn;er he was made a freer
prechur at vniuersitie of Paryss&hbar;, and he was a ma&ntail; of
grete auctoritie and holynes.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mortis certitudo multum terret aliquos
immortalitatem appetentes.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in `Historia Dragmanorum,' how &thorn;at &thorn;ies
Dragmans, like philosophurs, beand in wyldernes, dispysyd a&llbar;
werldly thyngis.

<PB N="349">

And kyng Alexander sent message vnto &thorn;aim &amp; sai&dtail;, aske
what &thorn;ai wol&dtail; &amp; &thorn;ai sulde hafe it.  And
&thorn;ai wrote vnto hym agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "Grant vs
&thorn;at we sha&llbar; nevur dy, for &thorn;at we desyre moste of
a&llbar;."  And he wrote vnto &thorn;aim agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;;
"Whe&ntail; I a&mtail; morta&llbar; &amp; mo&ntail; dy my selfe, how
mot I graunt you &thorn;at ye sa&llbar; nevur dye?"  And &thorn;ai
wrote vnto hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Sen &thorn;ou
knowis at &thorn;ou mo&ntail; dye, whi duse &thorn;ou so meku&llbar;
i&llbar; &amp; puttis &thorn;i selfe in so many perels?"

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mortis certitudo inducit hominem ad provisionem

necessariorum post mortem.  Infra de

providencia, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mortis certitudo confirmat hominem in bono

inchoato.  Infra de sortilegio.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mortui corpus aliquando vegetur 
<NOTE ID="P349.N1">MS. vegetatur.</NOTE>  a demone.  Infra

de suffragijs.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Moritur homo aliquando dum est in maiore
festo.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in `Libro <NOTE ID="P349.N2">MS. repeats, in Libro.</NOTE> de Dono Timoris' how at
&thorn;e cetie of Dyvyo&ntail; &thorn;er was ane vsurar &thorn;at wed
a wyfe, and &thorn;er was made abow&ntail; &thorn;e porche-dure many
ymagis of stone.  And emang other &thorn;er was made ane ymage of ane
vsurar with a grete purs in his hand of stone, and sodanly as
&thorn;is vsura&rtail; stude at &thorn;e porche-dure to be we&dtail;,
&thorn;is ymage of &thorn;e vsurar abo&ntail; lete fa&llbar; &thorn;e
purs of stone apo&ntail; &thorn;e vsura&rtail; hea&dtail; &thorn;at
shulde be we&dtail;, &amp; kylli&dtail; hy&mtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mors hominem quantumcunque adnichilat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in &thorn;e `Gestis of Alexander' how at &thorn;er was
sent o&ntail; a tyme vnto Alexander &thorn;e kyng a stone, and
whe&ntail; it was put in &thorn;e balance to be weye&dtail; in
&thorn;e to skale, it weyed more &thorn;an <NOTE ID="P349.N3">MS. &thorn;at.</NOTE>
a&llbar; &thorn;at evur &thorn;ai cuthe put in &thorn;e toder skale.
And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai put







<PB N="350">

a little powder &thorn;ero&ntail;, it weyi&dtail; les &thorn;an <NOTE ID="P350.N1">MS. &thorn;at.</NOTE> any thyng di&dtail; at &thorn;ai cuthe put in
&thorn;e toder skale.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai say &thorn;is, many
wise me&ntail; had grete merve&llbar; &thorn;erof.  And emangis
&thorn;aim ane said vnto kyng Alexander; "&thorn;is stone shewis vnto
you what ye er; ffor now ye wey mo&rtail; &thorn;a&ntail; duse
a&llbar; &thorn;e werl&dtail;, for it may skantlie bere you.  Bod fro
ye be deade and a little powder of ert&hbar; caste&ntail; o&ntail;
you, &thorn;a&ntail; shall ye be les &thorn;a&ntail; any thyng
&thorn;at is in &thorn;is werl&dtail;."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mortis horror aliquos ad bonum
inducit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in `Libro de Dono Timoris,' whe&ntail; &thorn;e kurk of
Crepsie <NOTE ID="P350.N2">Harl. MS. Cresby.</NOTE> shulde be halowe&dtail;, &amp; for
&thorn;at &thorn;ai wolde take oute &thorn;e bodie of ane erle
&thorn;at was beri&dtail; &thorn;er, &thorn;ai fan&dtail; a tade
sittan&dtail; o&ntail; his face knawan&dtail;, &amp; many wormys and
serpentis, to so meku&llbar; at a&llbar; &thorn;at &thorn;er was
fle&dtail;, a&llbar; bod a so&ntail; of his aw&ntail;.  And he come to
it &amp; saw it, &amp; tuke hy&mtail; so meku&llbar; &thorn;oght
&thorn;erfo&rtail; &thorn;at he lefte a&llbar; his gude &amp; tuke
hy&mtail; to pouertie, &amp; was so pure at efterwar&dtail; he
beggi&dtail; his meat.  And so he persever&dtail; many day.  So
hy&mtail; happen&dtail; o&ntail; a tyme to co&mtail; vnto Rome, &amp;
&thorn;er he become a collear to gett hy&mtail; meat with, &amp; he
had no noder place to lig in bod vnder-nethe a grece in &thorn;e howse
of a cardina&llbar;.  And &thorn;er he lay vnto he dye&dtail;, and
made a gude en&dtail;.  And o&ntail; &thorn;e nyght whe&ntail; he
dye&dtail;, a&llbar; &thorn;e bellis of &thorn;e kur&ktee; rang be
&thorn;er one.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mortis timor reddit hominem tristem et cogitatiuum.

Infra de timore, iij &amp; iiij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mortuis valent suffragia et orationes et oblaciones.

Supra de missa, iij, et infra de suffragio, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mortis memoria inducit homines ad
penitentiam.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in `Libro de Dono Timoris' how o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;er
was a cursi&dtail; knyght, and he wolde do no penance &thorn;at was
eniony&dtail;





<PB N="351">

hy&mtail; for his sy&ntail; be Pope Alexander.  &amp; so &thorn;e Pope
gaff hy&mtail; his ryng, &amp; enionyd hy&mtail; to penans for to bere
itt, vndernethe &thorn;is condicio&ntail;, &thorn;at evur whe&ntail;
he luki&dtail; &thorn;er-vppo&ntail;, he sulde vmthynk hy&mtail; of
his dea&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; he had wor&ntail; it many day, and
done as he bad hy&mtail;, he turnyd agay&ntail; vnto &thorn;e Pope,
&amp; sai&dtail; &thorn;at he was redie to fulfy&llbar; whatt penans
at he wolde enioy&ntail; hy&mtail;.  &amp; so he di&dtail; &amp; was a
gude ma&ntail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mortuis prodest penitencia a viuis facta loco
defunctorum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Maister Nicholas, &thorn;e Archebissho&ptail;, tellis how
so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was ij felowis at war passand trew to-gedur,
and ane of &thorn;aim happen&dtail; to do a grete sy&ntail;.  So be
counce&llbar; of &thorn;at o&thorn;er he went vnto Rome &amp; shrafe
hy&mtail; &thorn;erof, &amp; hy&mtail; was eniony&dtail;
&thorn;erfo&rtail; iij yere penance, &amp; &thorn;is take&ntail;,
hy&mtail; happen&dtail; fa&llbar; into a grete sekenes.  And he made
grete sorow at he might not fulfy&llbar; his penance, and his felow
beheste hy&mtail; &thorn;at, &amp; he dye&dtail;; he shul&dtail; do
itt for hy&mtail;.  And whe&ntail; he was dea&dtail; &amp; his felaw
had done &thorn;is penance for hy&mtail;, in &thorn;e en&dtail; of
&thorn;e furste yere he &thorn;at was dea&dtail; apperi&dtail; vnto
hy&mtail;, and &thorn;e thri&dtail; parte of his bodie was passand
white and &thorn;e toder ij partis blak as pykk.  And in &thorn;e
en&dtail; of &thorn;e secund yere he apperi&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;,
&amp; ij parties of his body white &amp; &thorn;e iij blak&ktee;.
And in &thorn;e en&dtail; of &thorn;e iij yere he apperid vnto
hy&mtail; a&llbar; white, and thanki&dtail; hy&mtail; gretelie for his
delyverans.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mortuis valet restitucio ablatorum facta pro
eis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in `Libro de Dono Timoris' how a duches so&ntail; was
bow&ntail; to dye, &amp; he was shrevy&ntail; &amp; yit he was bod ix
yere olde.  And whe&ntail; he was dea&dtail; he aperi&dtail; vnto his
moder &amp; tol&dtail; hur he was in grevus pay&ntail;, becauce <NOTE ID="P351.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, becauce.</NOTE> he had not paye&dtail; dettis &thorn;at he had
borowi&dtail; of his fadur meneya to play hy&mtail; with, becaus



<PB N="352">

he had no thoght &thorn;ero&ntail; whe&ntail; &thorn;at he dye&dtail;.
And his moder garte spyr att whome he borowi&dtail; it, &amp; garte
pay it vnto &thorn;aim.  And afterwar&dtail; &thorn;e chil&dtail;
apperi&dtail; vnto hur agay&ntail;, &amp; lete hur hafe knowlege that
he was delyverd oute of pay&ntail;, &amp; put in grete ioy and
felicitie.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mors pulcritudinem et omnes gratias corporales
destruit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede of ane, Isabe&llbar;, &thorn;at was hy Whene of
Naver&ntail;, and whe&ntail; sho drew nere hur dea&dtail; sho garte
light many lightis aboute hur be&dtail;, and garte feche in many
knyghtis &amp; grete men of &thorn;e cetie.  Sho sayde vnto &thorn;aim
o&ntail; &thorn;is maner of wyse; "Vmthynk you &amp; se &thorn;at I,
&thorn;e Whene of Naver&ntail;, &thorn;e Cowntas of Campanye, and
&thorn;e doghter of &thorn;e Kyng of Fraunce, whilk &thorn;at was
clere &amp; fayr &amp; discrete, and gracious in euer-ilk mans sight,
now, as ye see, dead wy&llbar; co&mtail; to me &amp; destroy all
&thorn;ies."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mori debet religiosus in habitu suo.  Supra de

monacho, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Morientes aliquando demones asserunt.  Infra de

vsurario, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mortui eciam in odio morientes post mortem illud

retinent.  Infra de odio.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mortuorum peccatorum corpora eciam post mortem

visibiliter puniuntur.  Supra de luxuria.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mortui aliquando monent viuos pro eis vt ablata
restituant.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;er was a knyght, &thorn;at hight
Fredericus of Kelle, whe&ntail; he was dead apperi&dtail; vnto a
ma&ntail; sittan&dtail; vppo&ntail; a blak stede, &amp; oute of his
nese-thrilles come a grete reke &amp; flaw&mtail;

<PB N="353">

&amp; he was cover&dtail; a&llbar; with skynnys &amp; bare a grete
lumpe of ert&hbar; betwix his shulders.  And &thorn;e ma&ntail;
&thorn;at he apperi&dtail; vnto aski&dtail; hy&mtail; if he war
Fredericus, and he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail; he was.
&amp; he axki&dtail; hy&mtail; fro whyne he come, and what a&llbar;
&thorn;at bement att he saw.  And he ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; said; "I a&mtail; in grete paynys, and &thorn;ies
skynnys I tuke fro a wedow &amp; now I fele &thorn;aim burnan&dtail;
vppo&ntail; me.  Also &thorn;er was solde vnto me wronguslie a
certay&ntail; porcio&ntail; of lan&dtail;, &amp; now it burnys
o&ntail; my bak&ktee; &amp; thrustis me dow&ntail;.  Bod &amp; my
childer wulde restore it agay&ntail;, my pay&ntail; mo&ntail; be
lestend."  And &thorn;us he vanysshi&dtail; away.  And whe&ntail; his
childer har&dtail; te&llbar; of &thorn;er fadur wurdis be &thorn;is
ma&ntail; &thorn;at spak with hy&mtail;, &thorn;ai wolde not yelde
&thorn;is lande agay&ntail;, bod had levur at &thorn;er fadur sawle
war evur in pay&ntail; &thorn;an at &thorn;ai parti&dtail; with
&thorn;is lande.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mortui aliquando apparentes infestant
viuos.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;at in &thorn;e bisshoppry&ktee; of
Tryuarens &thorn;er was som tyme a knyght &thorn;at hight Henrie,
&amp; he vsid robborie, avowtrie, inceste, &amp; to be
mane-swor&ntail;.  And whe&ntail; he was dea&dtail; he apperi&dtail;
vnto many folk.  So at &thorn;e laste he apperi&dtail; vnto a doghter
&thorn;at he gatt in avowtrie, &amp; afterwar&dtail; lay by hur
hy&mtail; selfe, and he wolde nowder lett for crossyng nor strykyng
with swer&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; he was stryke&ntail;, he mott not be
wowndi&dtail;, and &thorn;er come fro hy&mtail; swilk a sown&dtail;
like as &thorn;e bed had bene donge&ntail; o&ntail; with mellis.  So
at &thorn;e laste, whe&ntail; he wol&dtail; no wyse away, thurg&hbar;
cownce&llbar; of &thorn;e archebisshop&ptail; &thorn;ai tuke holy
watyr o&ntail; a Sononday, &amp; keste o&ntail; hur &amp; ou&rtail;
a&llbar; &thorn;e chawmer.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;is was done
&thorn;ai saw hy&mtail; nevur after.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mors amicorum debet pacienter tolerari
<NOTE ID="P353.N1">MS. tollerari.</NOTE>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis of ane &thorn;at hight Anaxagor, a whilosophur,
whe&ntail; one tolde hy&mtail; &thorn;at his so&ntail; was dea&dtail;
he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;;



<PB N="354">

"Tell me not &thorn;at I wate, ffor I knew whe&ntail; he was
bor&ntail; &thorn;at he sulde dye."  Also Oracius tellis of a
bissho&ptail; &thorn;at hight Iovis <NOTE ID="P354.N1">Harl. MS. Oracius, quoque Iouis pontifex.</NOTE> , how
o&ntail; a tyme as he was halowand a howse, as he was enoynttan&dtail;
&thorn;e poste with his han&dtail;, ane come &amp; tel&dtail;
hy&mtail; &thorn;at his so&ntail; was dea&dtail;; and he nowder
removi&dtail; his hand fro &thorn;e poste, nor left his observance for
no sorow, &thorn;at he sulde not be sene of &thorn;e peple to do
mo&rtail; &thorn;at longed vnto a fadur &thorn;a&ntail; vnto a
bisshop&ptail;.  Also we rede of Socraticus, whe&ntail; &thorn;at he
did his offran&dtail;, one lete hy&mtail; witt &thorn;at &thorn;e more
<NOTE ID="P354.N2">Harl. MS. maiorem e duobus filijs.</NOTE> of his sons was dea&dtail;, he wol&dtail; not
lefe his offran&dtail;, neuer-&thorn;e-les he doffe&dtail; his
crow&ntail;.  Neuer-&thorn;e-les he spurri&dtail; how he dye&dtail;,
&amp; it was tol&dtail; his so&ntail; dye&dtail; &amp; faght manlelie
in &thorn;e felde; &amp; whe&ntail; he harde tel&dtail; of &thorn;at
he tuke &thorn;e crow&ntail; agay&ntail; &amp; don&dtail; it o&ntail;
his hea&dtail;, and sai&dtail; he made mo&rtail; gladnes &thorn;at his
so&ntail; dyed manlely &thorn;a&ntail; sorow for his dea&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Morientes liberantur a temptacionibus demonum
per deuotas orationes.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Gregur tellis &thorn;at in his monasterie &thorn;er was a
childe &thorn;at hight Theodorus, whame he was passand fe&llbar; &amp;
grevus with, &amp; &thorn;is childe wolde be passand wrothe with any
&thorn;at tolde hy&mtail; oght for his gude, and gladlie he wol&dtail;
not here &thorn;aim.  So be proces of tyme hy&mtail; happend to be
seke &amp; lay in trans of dea&dtail;, and whe&ntail; a&llbar;
&thorn;e monkis stude aboute hy&mtail; he bega&ntail; to cry, &amp;
say&dtail;; "Go your ways!  Go your ways!  For I a&mtail; gyffe&ntail;
vnto &thorn;e drago&ntail; to devow&rtail;.  Now he hase swolod in-to
his mouthe my hea&dtail;, bod for you he may not swolow me a&llbar;.
Gyff hy&mtail; rome &thorn;at he no langer turment me, bod &thorn;at
he may do att he come for to do."  And one of &thorn;aim bad hy&mtail;
say&ntail; hy&mtail;, &amp; he sai&dtail; he wold fay&ntail; bod he
myght nott.  So &thorn;ai fe&llbar; vnto &thorn;er prayers devoutelie,
&amp; &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is seke childe bega&ntail; to cry, &amp;
say&dtail;; "I thank a&llbar;-myghti [God], for &thorn;urg&hbar; your
prayers &thorn;e drago&ntail; is fle&dtail; &amp; I a&mtail;
delyver&dtail;."







<PB N="355">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mortuis non est detrahendum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede ex 'Legenda Lombardica,' how &thorn;at in &thorn;e
monasterie of Saynt Gregor &thorn;er was a monk &thorn;at was so
vexi&dtail; with &thorn;e axis at he was like to dye.  &amp; his
brethir sai&dtail; &thorn;er psalters aboute hy&mtail;, trowyng
&thorn;at he sulde dye.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai had done &thorn;ai
bega&ntail; to bakbyte hy&mtail;.  So yitt hy&mtail; happen&dtail; to
tur&ntail; agay&ntail; vnto lyfe, &amp; he lifte vp his ene &amp;
smylid &amp; sai&dtail;; "God forgyf you, brethir!  Whi wolde ye
bakbyte me?  Ye hafe done vnto me a grete impediment, ffor I was bothe
at onys accusi&dtail; bothe of you &amp; of &thorn;e devu&llbar; and I
wiste neuer to whethur dissease I might ansswer.  And
&thorn;erfo&rtail; when ye se any ma&ntail; bow&ntail; to dy, bakbite
hy&mtail; not, bod hafe compassio&ntail; o&ntail; hy&mtail;, at ye
make hy&mtail; no lettyng whe&ntail; he commys afo&rtail; &thorn;e
strayte iugement of almyghtie Go&dtail;."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mulierem tangere non est bonum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Tha&rtail; was a ma&ntail; of religio&ntail; &thorn;at o&ntail; a
tyme went o-gatewar&dtail; <NOTE ID="P355.N1">Latin, cum matre sua iter faceret.</NOTE> with his moder.  And
whe&ntail; &thorn;ai come vnto a watyr, &amp; he sulde bere our his
moder, he <NOTE ID="P355.N2">MS. &amp; he.</NOTE> tuke his handis &amp; wappi&dtail;
&thorn;aim in his skirte, at he sulde not tuche &thorn;e handis of his
moder.  And whe&ntail; he had bor&ntail; hur our, sho aski&dtail;
hy&mtail; whi he did so.  And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
sai&dtail;, "&thorn;e body of a womma&ntail; is fyre, &amp; becauce I
thoght what womme&ntail; er, &thorn;erfor I wol&dtail; not tuche
&thorn;e for pere&llbar; &thorn;at mot happe&ntail; &thorn;er
vppo&ntail;."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulier debet cauere ne 
<NOTE ID="P355.N3">MS. ne donis ornatu.</NOTE>  ornatu, vel pulcritudine, vel

alloquio provocet virum.  Supra de abscondere.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulier casta est amanda.  Supra de castitate, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulieribus naturaliter inest compassio.  Supra de

compassione, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulier diligenter debet custodiri.  Supra de ffilia.</FOREIGN>



<PB N="356">
</ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulier vltro se ingerit viro.  Supra de castitate, v,

et de luxuria, i.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulier amore castitatiseciam propria membra corporis

debet contempnere.  Supra de castitate, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulier amore castitatis eciam propriam patriam

debet relinquere.  Supra de Clemente.</FOREIGN></ITEM><ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulier amore castitatis
eciam corpus proprium

exponit periculo.  Vt supra.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulieris cohabitacio non est secura viro.  Supra de

cruce, ij, et de carne, i.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mulier eciam amicum nititur decipere.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis of one &thorn;at hight Zenocrates Platonicus,
whilk &thorn;at was a ma&ntail; of suc&hbar; vertue, &thorn;at he
wolde lat no ma&ntail; swere for no maner of cauce, bod att euere
ma&ntail; sulde be trowi&dtail; be his play&ntail; wur&dtail;; &amp; he
was ffamilier vnto a womma&ntail; of Athenis.  So o&ntail; a day as
sho spak with o&thorn;er womme&ntail;, sho trustyng gretelie in
&thorn;e familiaritie of &thorn;is philosophur, sho lai&dtail; a grete
wageor at sho sulde bryng hy&mtail; oute of &thorn;e purpos of
chastite.  So &thorn;is philosophur o&ntail; a tyme come vnto hur,
&amp; sho made hy&mtail; mery of wyne so &thorn;at he liste slepe.
&amp; sho lenyd his hea&dtail; dow&ntail; in hur kne, &amp; of his
aw&ntail; wy&llbar; &thorn;er he lay a grete while.  And evur sho
talkid vnto hy&mtail; wurdis to provoce hy&mtail; to luste of his
bodie, and yit be no wyse myght sho induce hy&mtail; &thorn;erto,
&amp; so he went his wais &amp; sho loste hur wageor.  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;e toder womme&ntail; axked hur &thorn;at at sho had loste, sho
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;, &thorn;at sho lay&dtail;
hur wageor of a ma&ntail; &amp; not of a stok&ktee;, for he was a
stokk, sho say&dtail;, &amp; no ma&ntail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mulier virtuosa.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis how &thorn;er was a ma&ntail; &thorn;at hight
Ninus, &thorn;at had a wyfe.  &amp; whe&ntail; he was dea&dtail;,
o&ntail; a day as scho was byndan&dtail; vpp

<PB N="357">

hur hea&dtail;, it was latty&ntail; hur wit &thorn;at Babylo&ntail;
defayli&dtail; in bata&llbar;.  And with &thorn;e ta syde of hur heade
vnbun vp&ptail; sho ra&ntail; to feght agay&ntail; &thorn;aim of
Babilo&ntail;, &amp; neuer wold sitt at bynd vp hur hea&dtail; vnto
a&llbar; was wo&ntail; &amp; &thorn;ai ffle&dtail;.  &amp;
&thorn;erfo&rtail; is ane ymage made of hur &amp; sett v&ptail; in
&thorn;is maner of wyse.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXXX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mulier luxuriosa.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Orosius tellis of one &thorn;at hight Semiramis, &thorn;at was
burnand in lichorie &amp; thristie in blude, made ane ordinans and a
constitucio&ntail; &thorn;at for no maner of reuerens nor inceste
&thorn;er sulde no lettyng be, bod at betwix &thorn;e fadur &amp;
&thorn;e moder &amp; &thorn;er childer, als ofte as &thorn;aim
lyki&dtail;, it sulde be lefu&llbar; to hafe at do samen or for to
hafe to wyfe or husban&dtail;.  So o&ntail; a tyme sho desyryd hur
aw&ntail; so&ntail; to hafe at do with hur, and &thorn;er in despite
he slew hur.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXXXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Adhuc de muliere luxuriosa.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in `Cronicles' of &thorn;e wyfe of Claudius, how &thorn;at
sho was so gyffe&ntail; vnto luste &amp; lykyng, &thorn;at furste
privalie and syne opynlie sho wol&dtail; expown&dtail; hur selfe, &amp;
cownce&llbar; &thorn;erto other noble womme&ntail;, so &thorn;at sho
&thorn;oght &thorn;at sho had neuer enog&hbar; &thorn;erof.  And at
&thorn;e laste &thorn;e Emperow&rtail; &amp; hur husban&dtail;
to-gedur slew hur; and sho was so forgette&llbar; of myn&dtail;
&thorn;at whe&ntail; &thorn;ai slew hur sho aski&dtail; &thorn;aim whi
&thorn;ai wolde not co&mtail; &amp; hafe att do with hur.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulier superba et despiciens virum quandoque

postea viro capitur.  Supra de Assenec&hbar;.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulieres non expedit videre.  Infra 
<NOTE ID="P357.N1">MS. supra.</NOTE>  de videre.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulier rixosa pacienter a viro est toleranda 
<NOTE ID="P357.N2">MS. tolleranda.</NOTE> .  Infra

de paciencia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulier loquax grauiter punitur.  Supra de locucione.
</FOREIGN>


<PB N="358">
</ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulieris nequicia comparatur serpenti.  Infra de

serpente.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulier adultera virum suum contempnit.  Supra de

adulterio, j.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulier bona debet esse que ducitur in vxorem.  Infra

de vxore.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulier debet esse quieta et non vaga.  Infra de

vxore.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulier ad peccandum est parata si requiratur.  Infra

de silencio, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulier naturaliter ad se attrahit affectum viri.  Supra

de concupiscencia, j.</FOREIGN></ITEM><ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulier temptat virum.  Infra de
temptacione, v.</FOREIGN></ITEM><ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulier aliquando feruens est ad <NOTE ID="P358.N1"><HI REND="i">After</HI> ad, h, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> bonum.  Supra de

martirio.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXXXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mulier infidelis est marito suo
morienti.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how a womma&ntail;, whe&ntail; hur husband lay in dead
thrawis, callid hur mayde&ntail; &amp; bad hur go by hur iij yerdes of
hardy&ntail;, 'to wynde my husband in."  And sho ansswer&dtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Dame, ye hafe enog&hbar;e of fayr lyn
clothe.  Take &thorn;erof iiij yerdis and wynd hy&mtail; in."  And sho
was wrot&hbar; <NOTE ID="P358.N2"><HI REND="i">After</HI> wroth, s, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> &amp; sai&dtail;; "May not iij
yerdis of harde&ntail; serriff hy&mtail; we&llbar; enog&hbar;?"  So
&thorn;is ma&ntail; at lay seke happend for to here hur, and
whe&ntail; he come to hy&mtail; selfe, als i&llbar; as he myght, yitt
he sai&dtail;; "Ya, make it shorte enog&hbar; &thorn;at it be not
fyli&dtail; with clay <NOTE ID="P358.N3"><HI REND="i">A hand with</HI> Nota <HI REND="i">above it points to this tale</HI>.</NOTE> ."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXXXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mulieres quandoque pro parua re litigant.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in `Libro de Dono Timoris' how &thorn;er was ij
wome&ntail; pleyd befor a iuge for a clew of threde.  And &thorn;e
iuge axkid ather







<PB N="359">

of &thorn;aim wha&rtail;-of &thorn;e botho&mtail; at &thorn;e clew was
wo&ntail; o&ntail; was.  And &thorn;e tane sai&dtail; it was o&ntail;
a cole &amp; &thorn;e toder sai&dtail; it was o&ntail; a ly&ntail;
clowte.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he rewardi&dtail; at &thorn;e clew sulde
be wo&ntail; of, &amp; sho at sai&dtail; sothe of &thorn;e
botho&mtail; sulde hafe it.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXXXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mulieres <NOTE ID="P359.N1">MS. Muliere.</NOTE> attente respicere
non debent religiosi.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in `Vitis Patrum' how o&ntail; a tyme a monk ra&ntail; for
to se maydens as &thorn;ai come samen goyng be &thorn;e way.  And
whe&ntail; he had sene &thorn;aim he turnyd oute of &thorn;e way.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; ane olde wyfe at was with &thorn;ur maydyns sayd vnto
&thorn;is monk; "And &thorn;ou wer a parfite monke &thorn;ou sulde not
behalde vs, nor know &thorn;at we wer womme&ntail;."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulier papa creatur.  Infra de papa.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulierem demon incumbens infestat.  Supra de

demone, xj et xij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulier nobilis eciam viro aliquando se ingerit.  Infra

de temptacione, vj.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulier molestia carnis est temptata.  Infra de

temptacione, vij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulierum ornatui congaudet demon.  Infra de

ornatu, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulier virum suum in remotis partibus pergentem

debet expectare diu ante quam nubat.  Infra de

peregrino et supra de celacione, j.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulier secretum est male celans.  Supra de celacione.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXXXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mulier mala decipit virum suum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Petrus Alphonsis <NOTE ID="P359.N2">MS. Alphensis.</NOTE> ; how so&mtail; tyme a
ma&ntail; went to wede hys vynys, and his wyfe trowi&dtail; &thorn;at
he wol&dtail; hafe tari&dtail; long and calli&dtail;





<PB N="360">

hur luff into &thorn;e hows.  So &thorn;is ma&ntail; happend to be
smyte&ntail; in &thorn;e ee with a twyste, so &thorn;at he mot not se,
&amp; he mott hafe no ruste &thorn;erof &amp; went home.  And
whe&ntail; he knokki&dtail; at &thorn;e dure &thorn;e wyfe was ferde,
&amp; hid hur luff in a chawmer &amp; afterwar&dtail; oppynd &thorn;e
dure.  And hur husband went in &amp; wolde hafe gane vnto &thorn;e
be&dtail;, and sho axki&dtail; hy&mtail; what he wolde do at &thorn;e
be&dtail;, and he telli&dtail; hur a&llbar; as it had happend
hy&mtail;.  And sho bad hy&mtail; sitt dow&ntail; &amp; latt hur
char&mtail; &thorn;e hale ee, &thorn;at it happend nott &thorn;e same.
And sho putt hur mowthe vnto &thorn;e hale ee to likk it, vnto hur
luff was gone his way, at hur husband wiste nott.  And &thorn;a&ntail;
sho bad hur husband ryse, &amp; sayd vnto hy&mtail;; "Now I a&mtail;
sekur of &thorn;is ee.  And now if you like ye may go vnto your bed
and riste you."  And so he did.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXXXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mulier vna aliam in maleficijs
iuuat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Petrus Alphonsis <NOTE ID="P360.N1">MS. Alphensis</NOTE> tellis how som tyme
&thorn;er was a ma&ntail; &thorn;at went o&ntail; pylgramege, and he
betuke his wyfe to kepe vnto hur moder vnto he come home.  And
whe&ntail; he was gone sho sent for hur doghtur lemma&ntail; to
su&ptail; with &thorn;aim, &amp; &thorn;ai ete &amp; dran&ktee; samen
&amp; made merie.  And sodanlie &thorn;e gudema&ntail; come vnto
&thorn;e dure &amp; calli&dtail;, and sho was gretelie trubli&dtail;
&thorn;er-with, &amp; hid hur lemma&ntail; in &thorn;e chawmer and
&thorn;a&ntail; lete hur gudema&ntail; co&mtail; in.  An&dtail; he was
wery &amp; wete, &amp; bad &thorn;aim go make his be&dtail;.  And
&thorn;is olde wyfe bad hur doghter bryng a shete &amp; latt hy&mtail;
se it &thorn;at he sulde lig in, or sho made &thorn;e be&dtail;.  And
sho broght a fayr shete, and &thorn;e olde wyfe toke &thorn;at one end
&thorn;erof, &amp; &thorn;e yong wyfe &thorn;e toder, and held it
v&ptail; o&ntail; ege als hy as &thorn;ai might afor&ntail; &thorn;e
chawmer dure, &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ai hid &thorn;e gude ma&ntail; at
he might not se to he was gone, at &thorn;ai had hyd, oute att
&thorn;e chawmber dure.  And &thorn;e gude ma&ntail; bade sty&llbar;
&amp; had a mok&ktee; <NOTE ID="P360.N2">Latin, et maritus delusus remansit.</NOTE> .  And &thorn;an
&thorn;is olde wyfe said vnto hur doghter; "Ga now &amp; make &thorn;i
husban&dtail; bedd with &thorn;is shete at I made myne aw&ntail;
handis se&ntail; he went."  And he sai&dtail;; "Dame, ca&ntail; ye wefe
suc&hbar; clothe?"  "Ya, so&ntail;," sho sai&dtail;, "forsut&hbar; I
hafe wroght meku&llbar; suche se&ntail; I was bor&ntail;."





<PB N="361">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXXXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mulier mediatrix aliam ad peccatum
inducit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Petrus Alphonsis <NOTE ID="P361.N1">MS. Alphensis.</NOTE> tellis how som tyme
&thorn;er was a wurshupfu&llbar; ma&ntail; &thorn;at went o&ntail;
pylgramege, and he had a gude wyfe and a chaste.  So &thorn;er was a
yong ma&ntail; &thorn;at luffi&dtail; hur passandly, &amp; wolde hafe
giffe&ntail; hur grete giftis to hafe had his luste o&ntail; hur, and
sho wolde not o&ntail; no wyse.  So at &thorn;e laste he fe&llbar;
seke for sorow at he mot not spede, &amp; lay in his be&dtail;.  So
&thorn;er come in ane olde wyfe &amp; vysitt hy&mtail; &amp;
aski&dtail; hy&mtail; what was &thorn;e cauce at he was seke
fo&rtail;.  And he oppyn&dtail; his herte vnto hur &amp; tolde hur
a&llbar; &thorn;at hy&mtail; aylid.  And sho sai&dtail; hy&mtail;
&thorn;urte not be seke he&rtail;-fo&rtail;, sho cuthe hel&ptail;
hy&mtail; we&llbar; enog&hbar;.  And he promysi&dtail; hur a gude
rewarde to helpe hy&mtail;.  So sho had a little bykk whelpe, &amp;
sho hel&dtail; it fastan&dtail; ij dayes.  So o&ntail; &thorn;e iij
day sho made a cake of mustar&dtail; &amp; mele &amp; gaff it, &amp;
it ete it.  And for bytuernes of &thorn;e muster&dtail; it bega&ntail;
hugelie to grete, &amp; &thorn;e ee&ntail; &thorn;erof to ry&ntail;.
So sho went vnto &thorn;is gude wyfe hows, and &thorn;is whelpe
folowi&dtail; hur.  And sho, becauce sho was ane olde wyfe,
welcomy&dtail; hur fayre, &amp; gaff hur meat &amp; dryn&ktee;.  So
at &thorn;e laste sho aski&dtail; hur what &thorn;is whelpe
ayli&dtail; to wepe &thorn;us.  And sho ansswer&dtail; &amp;
sai&dtail;; "Dere Dame! it is no merve&llbar; if I make sorow &amp;
wepe, for &thorn;is whelpe was my doghter, &amp; was a fu&llbar;
lea&llbar; maydy&ntail;, &amp; a gude &amp; a fay&rtail;.  And becauce
sho wolde not consent&curl; vnto a yong ma&ntail; &thorn;at
luffi&dtail; hur, to be his luff, &thorn;us sho was shape&ntail; to be
a biche whelpe."  And with &thorn;at sho lete as sho swowny&dtail;
&amp; wepi&dtail; sore.  So &thorn;is gude wyfe made meku&llbar;
sorow, &amp; sai&dtail;; "What mo&ntail; I do?  Allas! for I a&mtail;
in &thorn;e same cace; ffor a yong ma&ntail; luffis me &amp; I hafe
dispysi&dtail; hy&mtail;, and I a&mtail; afer&dtail; &thorn;at I
sa&llbar; oght be mysshapen&dtail;."  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e
olde wyfe ansswer&dtail; &amp; cowncel&dtail; hur to consent vnto
hy&mtail;, &amp; latt hy&mtail; hafe his liste at sho wer not
forshapy&ntail; &amp; made a byche whelpe.  &amp; sho prayed hur to go
fo&rtail; hy&mtail;, and so sho di&dtail; &amp; fechi&dtail; hy&mtail;
vnto &thorn;is womma&ntail;, &amp; &thorn;er he had his luste &amp;
his desyre; &amp; &thorn;is false alde whe&ntail; had a gude
rewar&dtail; of ather partie.



<PB N="362">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXXXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mulier difficile custoditur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Petrus Alphonsis <NOTE ID="P362.N1">MS. Alphensis.</NOTE> tellis how so&mtail; tyme
&thorn;er was a yong wed ma&ntail;, and &thorn;urgh conse&llbar; of
ane olde wyse ma&ntail; he closi&dtail; his wyfe in a hye chawmer
&thorn;at had no dure butt one, and a wyndow, &amp; evur as he come
owder in or oute, he sparri&dtail; &thorn;e dure faste.  And o&ntail;
&thorn;e night he wolde hyde &thorn;e keyis at his bed hea&dtail;.
And &thorn;us he did a long tyme.  So o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; hur
husban&dtail; was away, sho luki&dtail; furt&hbar; at &thorn;e
wyndow, and sho was war of a fress&hbar; yong ma&ntail;, &amp; onone
sho wex iolious o&ntail; hy&mtail;.  And to &thorn;e entent at sho
mott gett oute vnto hy&mtail;, iij nyghtis or iiij, by &amp; by sho
made hu&rtail; husban&dtail; dronke&ntail;.  And o&ntail; a nyght
privalie whe&ntail; he was o&ntail; slepe, sho stale &thorn;e keyis
fro his head &amp; oppynd &thorn;e durys.  And privalie sho went vnto
&thorn;is yong ma&ntail;.  So hur husban&dtail; wakyn&dtail; &amp;
myssi&dtail; hur, &amp; compasi&dtail; &thorn;at with-owte&ntail; a
cauce sho wolde not hafe desyri&dtail; [hym] to drynk so faste
o&ntail; evyns as sho di&dtail;, &amp; sai&dtail; no &thorn;ing bod
lay sti&llbar; &amp; slepte.  So whe&ntail; sho had had hur luste, sho
come in agay&ntail;, and he lete as he myssi&dtail; hur nog&hbar;t.
So o&ntail; a night afterwar&dtail;, he feny&dtail; hy&mtail; selfe
dronke&ntail;, and &thorn;e same night sho rase v&ptail; as sho did
afo&rtail;, and went vnto hur luff.  And onone as sho was gone, he
rase privalie &amp; folowi&dtail; hur &amp; come vnto &thorn;e dure
&amp; sparri&dtail; it faste, &amp; went vp agay&ntail; &amp; stude in
&thorn;e wyndow wachan&dtail;.  And at &thorn;e laste he was war of
hur command in hur sar&ktee;.  And sho knokki&dtail;, &amp; he axkid
who was &thorn;er?  And sho besoght hy&mtail; forgyff hur at sho went
furt&hbar;, &amp; to latt hur co&mtail; in.  And he sai&dtail; sho
sul&dtail; not co&mtail; in, bod sho sulde stan&dtail; sti&llbar;
&thorn;er &amp; he sul&dtail; shew hur vnto hur fadur &amp; hur moder
in &thorn;e aray at sho was in.  And &thorn;e vse was &thorn;at
&thorn;ai &thorn;at wer fo&ntail; &thorn;er-oute at mydnyght,
wacheme&ntail; sulde take &thorn;aim &amp; o&ntail; &thorn;e
mor&ntail; sett &thorn;aim o&ntail; &thorn;e pyllorie, &thorn;at
a&llbar; me&ntail; myght wonder o&ntail; &thorn;aim.  And whe&ntail;
sho saw &thorn;at o&ntail; na wyse he wolde lat hur in, sho sai&dtail;
sho sulde lepe into a draw-we&llbar; at was bod a litle fro &thorn;e
dure, &amp; drow&ntail; hur selfe, rather or sho war taky&ntail; &amp;
shamy&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; sho saw for a&llbar; &thorn;is at he
wol&dtail; not lat hur in, sho tuke



<PB N="363">

v&ptail; a grete stone &amp; keste in-to &thorn;e draw we&llbar;, and
bad fare-wele for evurmo&rtail;.  And whe&ntail; he her&dtail; it
fa&llbar; in-to &thorn;e we&llbar;, he went it had bene sho had
loppy&ntail; in-to &thorn;e we&llbar;, and he was somwhat
asstony&dtail;, and he oppy&ntail; &thorn;e dure faste, &amp;
ra&ntail; vnto &thorn;e we&llbar; at luke if he mott gett hur oute.
And sho had hid hur be &thorn;e wa&llbar; &amp; saw &thorn;e dure was
oppy&ntail;, &amp; whippi&dtail; in &amp; lokki&dtail; &thorn;e dure
faste, &amp; gatt hur vp in-to &thorn;e wyndow.  And whe&ntail; he
har&dtail; sho was gette&ntail; in, he sai&dtail;; "O, &thorn;ou fals
womma&ntail;, and fu&llbar; of &thorn;e devuls crafte!  Lat me
co&mtail; in!"  And sho sai&dtail;, nay, he sulde nott.  And &thorn;er
sho hel&dtail; hy&mtail; oute vnto wache-me&ntail; come &amp; tuke
hy&mtail;, &amp; had hy&mtail; vnto priso&ntail;.  And o&ntail;
&thorn;e mor&ntail; sho went vnto hur fadur &amp; hur modir, and
tol&dtail; &thorn;aim how &thorn;at he went oute o&ntail; &thorn;e
nyght to his strompettis &amp; forsuke hur, &amp; &thorn;er &thorn;ai
come vnto &thorn;e priso&ntail; a&llbar; samen &amp; made playnt
o&ntail; hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;er in his sarke &amp; his breke he was
sett o&ntail; &thorn;e pellorye, at a&llbar; folk wonder&dtail;
o&ntail; hy&mtail;, &amp; &thorn;us maliciouslie sho put hur blame
opo&ntail; hy&mtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXXXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mulieris malicia quandoque in caput suum
redundat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in `Cronicles,' whe&ntail; kyng Albyo&ntail; was at
Vero&ntail; at a grete feste, he commanddi&dtail; his butler to feche
hy&mtail; a copp &thorn;at he had made of &thorn;e heade of &thorn;e
furst husban&dtail; of Rosamon&dtail;, at was his wyfe, whame he had
slay&ntail; in bate&llbar;; &amp; he garte fy&llbar; it fu&llbar; of
wyne &amp; dranke &thorn;erof, &amp; gaff Rosamon&dtail; his wyfe
&amp; made hur to drynk &thorn;erof.  And he bad hur drynk with hur
furst husban&dtail;, and sho conseyvi&dtail; what he ment &amp; was
passan&dtail; wrothe with hy&mtail;.  So &thorn;er was in &thorn;e
cowrte a duke &thorn;at hel&dtail; <NOTE ID="P363.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, &thorn;at hel&dtail;.</NOTE> a chawmerer
of &thorn;e whene, &amp; sho had knowlege &thorn;erof.  And o&ntail; a
tyme whe&ntail; &thorn;e kyng was fro home, opo&ntail; a nyght sho
went into &thorn;is chawmerer bed, &amp; sent privalie vnto &thorn;is
duke a message as it had comme&ntail; fro&mtail; hur chawmerer, &amp;
bad hy&mtail; co&mtail; &amp; lye with hur; and &thorn;er &thorn;is
duke lay bye hur.  And whe&ntail; he had done sho said vnto



<PB N="364">

hy&mtail;; "Knowis &thorn;ou what I a&mtail;?" and he sai&dtail;; "Ya,
&thorn;ou erte &thorn;e chawmerer, my lemma&ntail;."  And sho
sai&dtail;, "Nay, I am Rosamon&dtail;, att &thorn;ou has done
&thorn;is dede with; &amp; chese &thorn;e oo&ntail; of ij.  For owther
&thorn;ou sa&llbar; sla kyng Albyo&ntail; at slew my furst
husban&dtail; &amp; garte me drynk of his hea&dtail;, or els I
sa&llbar; te&llbar; hy&mtail; what &thorn;ou hase done, &amp; make
hy&mtail; to sla &thorn;e.  And &thorn;erfo&rtail; venge me of
hy&mtail; &thorn;at made my husban&dtail; head in a copp, or els
&thorn;ou sa&llbar; dye &thorn;erfo&rtail;."  And he sai&dtail;, nay,
he wol&dtail; not do it hy&mtail; selfe, bod he promysi&dtail; hur att
he sulde gett a noder &thorn;at sulde do it.  And sho gart hide
&thorn;e kyngis armor &amp; his bate&llbar;-ax at stude at his
bed-hea&dtail;, &amp; his swer&dtail; at hang sho gart byn&dtail; it,
so at it mott not co&mtail; oute of &thorn;e shet&hbar;e.  And
whe&ntail; &thorn;e kyng was in his bed &amp; of slepe, &thorn;is
manwheller come in, &amp; &thorn;e kyng gat his swer&dtail; &amp;
wol&dtail; hafe drawe&ntail; oute, &amp; it wol&dtail; not; &amp; so
he was slay&ntail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he tuke Rosamon&dtail;, &amp;
a&llbar; &thorn;e knygis tresur &amp; ffled vnto &thorn;e Cetie of
Rave&ntail; <NOTE ID="P364.N1">Lat. MSS. Ravenna.</NOTE> ; &amp; &thorn;er he wedd hur.  And
hur happen&dtail; &thorn;er o&ntail; a tyme to se a fayr yong
ma&ntail;, &amp; sho wex amoros of hy&mtail;, and &thorn;oght
&thorn;at sho wolde hafe hy&mtail; to hur husban&dtail;.  And sho gaff
hy&mtail; &thorn;at had we&dtail; hur poyse&ntail; to drynk, and
kylli&dtail; hy&mtail;.  And whe&ntail; he felid &thorn;at it was
veno&mtail;, he garte hur drynke of &thorn;e reuercio&ntail;.  And sho
wolde nott, &amp; he tuke oute hys swer&dtail; &amp; bad hur
dryn&ktee; it, or he sulde ky&llbar; hur.  And so sho drank it, &amp;
&thorn;er &thorn;ai wer bot&hbar; dea&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXL.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mulier vbique ab omnibus est
fugienda.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' how &thorn;e abbot Semestras had
certa&ntail; disciples &thorn;at o&ntail; a tyme sai&dtail; vnto
hy&mtail;; "Sur, [go] we into &thorn;e werl&dtail; a while, &amp; latt
vs dwe&llbar; &thorn;er."  And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
say&dtail;; "Go we &thorn;a&ntail; whare no womma&ntail; is."  And
&thorn;ai ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;;
"Wha&rtail; is &thorn;at place &thorn;at a womma&ntail; is not in, bod
if &thorn;at it be in wyldernes?"  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e abbott
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "The&rtail;fo&rtail; I
pray &thorn;e, lat vs abide in wyldernes."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulieris memoria in corde viri esse non debet.  Supra

de memoria, ij.</FOREIGN>



<PB N="365">
</ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulier luxuriosa in proprium filium impetit.  Supra

Andree, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulieris specie diabolus sanctos temptat.  Supra

Andree, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXLI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mulieris nobilis virtus quandoque apparet in
morte.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iustinus tellis of ane &thorn;at hight Olimpias, and whe&ntail;
she saw army&dtail; me&ntail; come an&dtail; wol&dtail; hafe
slay&ntail; hur, sho went &amp; cled hur in gay clothyng, &amp; tuke
ij maydens with hur and went to mete &thorn;aim.  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;ai saw hur in &thorn;at aray, &thorn;ai wer astony&dtail; at
sho did so &amp; &thorn;ai went agay&ntail; vnto &thorn;er maisters
[&amp; teld] how &thorn;ai fan&dtail; hur not fer&dtail; nor
flean&dtail; fro dea&dtail;, nor at sho was not fer&dtail; for
swer&dtail; nor wown&dtail;, nor wepi&dtail; wommanlyke, bod
resayvi&dtail; armyd me&ntail; mekelie with ioy &amp; murt&hbar;, and
obeyi&dtail; hur to vndergo dea&dtail;.  And &thorn;us sho was
delyver&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXLII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mulier et viuens et moriens honestatem debet
servare.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iustinus tellis of &thorn;is same womma&ntail;, how o&ntail; a
tyme <NOTE ID="P365.N1">MS. tyme whe&ntail;.</NOTE> sho was stryke&ntail; with a swer&dtail;
&amp; fe&llbar; dow&ntail; &amp; dye&dtail;, &amp; yit with hur
clothis &amp; hur hare sho cover&dtail; hur theis, so &thorn;at none
vnwurshu&ptail; of hur bodie sulde be sene.  Also we rede of the whene
of Narva&ntail; <NOTE ID="P365.N2">Harleian MS. de regina Navarre.</NOTE> , &thorn;at hight Isabe&llbar;,
&amp; was doghter vnto Saynt Lowyce &thorn;at was kyng of Fraunce,
&thorn;at if a&llbar; sho was yong and passan&dtail; fayr,
neuer-&thorn;e-les sho wolde neuer lyg with Kyng Theobal&dtail;, at
was a fayr yong ma&ntail; at ha&dtail; wed hur, bod in hur sark, nor
lat hy&mtail; lig with hur bod in his sark &amp; his breke.  Nor
&thorn;er was neuer none of hur maydens, nowder privalie nor apert,
&thorn;at nowder in bat&hbar; nor in wasshyng saw als meku&llbar; as
hur ancle bare.  And whe&ntail; sho dye&dtail;, sho commandi&dtail;
hur maydens &thorn;at &thorn;ai sulde wap&ptail; a&llbar; hur bodye
&amp; hur





<PB N="366">

membres in a long web&bbar; &amp; sew it, at whe&ntail; becauce of
sethyng hur membrus burde be cutt, &thorn;e clothe sulde be cutt, at
&thorn;ai &thorn;att cutt hur sulde not se none partie of hur body
bare.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mulier sine assensu viri non debet dare magna.  Infra

de vxore.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mundi debent esse qui contractant sancta vasa et

vestes.  Supra de corporali.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mundi pericula sunt evitanda.  Infra de risu et de

periculis.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mundo possunt adaptari que supra dicuntur de

contemptu mundi, de diuicijs et morte.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXLIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Munera parua ab amicis data sunt non
spernenda.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Senec tellis how &thorn;at whe&ntail; &thorn;e disciples of
Socrates come and broght hy&mtail; many giftis, he had a pure scolar
&thorn;at hight Escharmes, &thorn;at come &amp; offer&dtail; hy&mtail;
selfe vnto hy&mtail; an&dtail; sai&dtail;; "Sur, I giff you &thorn;e
beste &thorn;ing &thorn;at I hafe, &thorn;at is myne aw&ntail; bodye."
&amp; he sai&dtail; &thorn;at o&thorn;er &thorn;at gaff hy&mtail;
sma&llbar; giftis helde &thorn;er beste giftis behynde, &amp; so wolde
not he doo, bod he prayed his mayster to take &thorn;at pure gifte,
&amp; so labur it with a&llbar; his diligens, att it mott be better
&amp; fayrer for his sake.  And his maister ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; sayd; "I have tane a grete gyfte of &thorn;e bod if
&thorn;ou &thorn;inke &thorn;i selfe little, and giff &thorn;i selfe
besylie for &thorn;ine awn profett to do a&llbar; thyng at I
comman&dtail; the."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Munera magna non debet dare vxor sine licencia

viri.  Infra de vxore.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXLIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Munera accipere non debet princeps vel
prelatus.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis of one Marchus Thurius, &thorn;at was &thorn;e
nobyllest cowncelor within Rome.  &amp; o&ntail; a tyme a grete
ma&ntail; come vnto

<PB N="367">

hy&mtail; &amp; fan&dtail; hy&mtail; syttan&dtail; at his supper be
&thorn;i fyre, &amp; a&llbar; his meat o&ntail; a tre-dubler.  And he
offer&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; &amp; wol&dtail; hafe gyffe&ntail; a grete
porcio&ntail; of syluer vesse&llbar;, &amp; bad hy&mtail; were
&thorn;aim for his sake.  &amp; he forsuke &thorn;aim &amp; wolde not
take &thorn;aim.  And he was wrothe &thorn;erwith &amp; sai&dtail;;
"Ye sa&llbar; nevur te&llbar; &thorn;at Marchus Thurius had lere be
lorde of riches &thorn;a&ntail; for to be mai&dtail; riche of
wisdo&mtail;.  For vmthynk you &thorn;at ye neuer saw me
ourcomme&ntail; in bate&llbar;, nor yit be corrupte with money."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Murmurare non debet pauper cui datur elemosina.

Infra de paupertate.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXLV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mures eciam homines aliquando inuadunt.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Cronicles' &thorn;at in &thorn;e tyme of &thorn;e iij
Henrie &thorn;e Emperour, how &thorn;er was a riche ma&ntail; o&ntail;
a day satt at his meate.  And sodanlie he was vmlappi&dtail; with a
grete flo&ktee; of myce, and sodanly &thorn;ai lefte a&llbar; <NOTE ID="P367.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, a&llbar;.</NOTE> at was in &thorn;e howse, &amp; pursewi&dtail;
vppo&ntail; hy&mtail;.  &amp; me&ntail; tuke hy&mtail; and ha&dtail;
hy&mtail; vnto a shi&ptail; o&ntail; &thorn;e watir at he mot so
esskape &thorn;e myce, &amp; voyde &thorn;aim fro hy&mtail;.  And
&thorn;ai lepi&dtail; after hy&mtail; in-to &thorn;e watyr, &amp; come
to &thorn;e shup&ptail; &amp; gnew it &thorn;urg&hbar;. &amp; so he
mott o&ntail; no wyse kepe hy&mtail; fro &thorn;aim, vnto so muche att
he was had to lan&dtail; agay&ntail;; &amp; &thorn;er &thorn;e myce
fe&llbar; o&ntail; hy&mtail; &amp; kylli&dtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; ete
hy&mtail; vp euere morse&llbar; vnto &thorn;e bare bonys.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXLVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Musce infestant multos.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede ex 'Legenda Lombardica <NOTE ID="P367.N2">MS. ex legibus Lombardorum.</NOTE> ' how at
&thorn;er happen&dtail; o&ntail; a tyme a grete multitude of fleis in
ane abbay &thorn;at Saynt Barnar&dtail; made, vnto so meku&llbar; at
&thorn;ai di&dtail; meku&llbar; noysans vnto a&llbar; me&ntail;
&thorn;at dwelly&dtail; &thorn;erin.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai come
&amp; tolde hy&mtail;, he sai&dtail; &thorn;at he sulde curs
&thorn;aim, &amp; o&ntail; &thorn;e mor&ntail; &thorn;ai wer fo&ntail;
dea&dtail;, ilk one.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Mutacio frequens iudicum 
<NOTE ID="P367.N3">MS. iu de&ntail;. Harl. MS. iudicum.</NOTE>  non est populo vtilis.

Supra de ballivo, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>



<PB N="368">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXLVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Natalis Domini, primo.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> The birt&hbar; of our Lor&dtail; is prevy&dtail; be many
meracleys, ffor Innocencius &thorn;e iij telles how at Rome &thorn;er
was contynua&llbar; pease xij yere to-gedur, and &thorn;erfo&rtail;
&thorn;e Romans byggi&dtail; a fayre temple, &amp; sett &thorn;erin
&thorn;e ymage of Romulus, &amp; garte ca&llbar; it Templum Pacis.
And &thorn;ai asky&dtail; Appollo how long it sulde laste, &amp; he
sai&dtail; vnto a womma&ntail; &thorn;at was a clene mayde&ntail; bare
a childe.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai har&dtail; &thorn;at, &thorn;ai
sai&dtail; it sulde laste evur, &amp; wrate abowne &thorn;e dure in
golde&ntail; letters; ' <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Templum Domini <NOTE ID="P368.N1">Lat. MSS. Templum Pacis.</NOTE> in eternum manet.</FOREIGN>' And whe&ntail;
ou&rtail; Ladye bare hur childe, vppo&ntail; &thorn;at same nyght it
fe&llbar; dow&ntail; vnto &thorn;e har&dtail; ert&hbar;, and &thorn;er
is now Ecclesia Sancte Marie Noue <NOTE ID="P368.N2">MS. Sancte Marie de nouo.</NOTE> .


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXLVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Natalis Domini probatur dupliciter,
ij<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Ex 'Legenda Lombardica <NOTE ID="P368.N3">MS. Legibus Lombardorum.</NOTE> ' we rede how
&thorn;at vppo&ntail; &thorn;at day &thorn;e ymage of Romulus and
a&llbar; o&thorn;er ydolfis in Rome fe&llbar; dow&ntail; &amp; bra&ktee;.
And Saynt Iero&mtail; tellis also how &thorn;er come a toky&ntail; in
Egipte for a&llbar; &thorn;er idolfis fellis whe&ntail; our Ladye bare
hur chylde.  And he&rtail;-fo&rtail; &thorn;e prestis of &thorn;e
temple garte make ane ymage of a maydy&ntail; with a bar&ntail; in hur
ar&mtail;, and sett it in a privay place in &thorn;er temple, &amp;
vnto &thorn;at &thorn;ai did wurshu&ptail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXLIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Natalis Domini probatur multipliciter,
iij<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede ex 'Legenda Lombardica' how &thorn;at same nyght &thorn;e
derknes of &thorn;e nyght an&dtail; clerenes of &thorn;e day war
turny&dtail; evu&ntail; contrarie.







<PB N="369">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DL.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Natalis probatur, iiij<HI REND="sup">to</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Orosius and Innosins <NOTE ID="P369.N1">Harl. MS. Innocens iij.</NOTE> tellis how &thorn;at a
we&llbar; in Rome &thorn;at same nyght was turne&dtail; in-to oyle
&amp; ra&ntail; in-to Tyber, and a&llbar; &thorn;e day after
spra&ntail; habundandlye; ffor Sibilla had prophecyed &amp; sai&dtail;
&thorn;at our Savyor sulde not be bor&ntail; or a we&llbar; of oyle
sprang oute of &thorn;e erthe.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Natalis Domini probatur, v<HI REND="sup">to</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Crysostimus tellis &thorn;at vppo&ntail; &thorn;e nyght of
&thorn;e natiuitie, vnto &thorn;e kynges &thorn;at war prayan&dtail;
o&ntail; a hy&llbar;, a fayr star&ntail; appere&dtail; <NOTE ID="P369.N2">MS. appeyed.</NOTE> vnto &thorn;aim. &amp; it ha&dtail; in it a fayre
childe, and vppo&ntail; his shulder a fayr cros shynyng, whilk childe
spak vnto &thorn;e kyngis and bad &thorn;aim go in-to Iudea &amp; seke
hy&mtail;, &amp; &thorn;er &thorn;ai sulde fyn&dtail; hy&mtail;
bor&ntail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Natalis Domini probatur, vj<HI REND="sup">to</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Legenda Lombardica' how &thorn;at vppo&ntail;
&thorn;at day &thorn;er apperi&dtail; in &thorn;e este iij sonnys <NOTE ID="P369.N3">Harl. MS. qui paulatim in vnum corpus solare redacti sunt. Eusebius in Cronicis, et Magister in Historia Scolastica dicunt quod non ipso die apparuerint tres soles, sed autem per aliquod tempus, scilicet post mortem Julij Cesaris.</NOTE> , and somwhat befo&rtail; &thorn;at tyme after
&thorn;e dea&dtail; of Iulius Cesar.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Natalis Domini probatur, vij<HI REND="sup">mo</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Innocencius &thorn;e iij, pope, tellis how &thorn;at Ottouianus
&thorn;e Emperou&rtail;, &thorn;at a&llbar; &thorn;e werl&dtail; was
subgett vnto, and be his reso&ntail; he plesi&dtail; so vnto &thorn;e
senaturs of Rome, &thorn;at &thorn;ai wolde hafe wurshuppi&dtail;
hy&mtail; as God&dtail;.  And he calli&dtail; Sybilla &thorn;e
prophetice vnto hy&mtail;, &amp; axky&dtail; hur if evur &thorn;er
sulde be any bor&ntail; &thorn;at sulde be gretter &thorn;a&ntail; he
was.








<PB N="370">

So it happend o&ntail; &thorn;e yole-day, and &thorn;is Syby&llbar;
was in &thorn;e Emperour chawmer.  And evy&ntail; aboute mydday
&thorn;er apperi&dtail; aboute &thorn;e so&ntail; a golde&ntail;
cercle, and in myddeste of &thorn;e cercle was &thorn;er
standan&dtail; a fayr maydy&ntail; and a chylde in hur armys.  And sho
shewi&dtail; &thorn;is vnto &thorn;e Emperour, and &thorn;e Emperour
had grete mervai&lbar; here-of, &amp; sai&dtail; &thorn;at he
har&dtail; a voyce &thorn;at spak, saying, " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Hec
est ara celi.</FOREIGN>" And Syby&llbar; sai&dtail; &thorn;at childe
sulde be mare &thorn;a&ntail; he was, and &thorn;erfo&rtail; sho bad
hy&mtail; wurshu&ptail; hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;at chawmer is
consecrate a kurk in honor of our Ladie, &amp; is calli&dtail; to
&thorn;is day Sancta Maria de Ara Celi <NOTE ID="P370.N1">MS. Cela.</NOTE> .  And
fro thens furt&hbar; &thorn;e Emperour wurshuppi&dtail; &thorn;is
childe &amp; wolde wurshu&ptail; none o&thorn;er goddis.  And vnto
&thorn;is sentans accordis Timotheus, historiagraphus, and Orosius for
&thorn;e moste partie.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Natalis probatur, viij<HI REND="sup">uo</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede ex 'Legenda Lombardica' how &thorn;at &thorn;e oxe &amp;
&thorn;e ass, knowyng mervolosly Almighty Go&dtail; lay&dtail; in a
cryb befo&rtail; &thorn;aim, &thorn;ai fe&llbar; dow&ntail; o&ntail;
&thorn;er kneis and wurshuppid Hy&mtail;.  And Saynt Iero&mtail;
tellis &thorn;at vppo&ntail; &thorn;at nyght a&llbar; &thorn;at euer
labur&dtail; <FOREIGN>in vicio sodomitico</FOREIGN> was slay&ntail;, so &thorn;at not in
&thorn;e kyn&dtail; &thorn;at Almi&yogh;ty God had take&ntail; fro
thens furt&hbar; &thorn;er sulde be fo&ntail; so meku&llbar;
vnclennes.  For als Saynt Austy&ntail; say&dtail;; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">videns Deus vicium contra naturam in natura humana fieri,
fere desijt incarnari.</FOREIGN>"


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Negacionem dei inducit frequenter malum consilium
et inopia siue paupertas.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;at in &thorn;e dioces of Leodenensis
<NOTE ID="P370.N2">Harl. MS. Leodiensis.</NOTE> , besyde Florens, &thorn;er was som ty&mtail; a
yong knyght &amp; noble in tornamentis, &amp; giffe&ntail; vnto
vanytis of &thorn;is werl&dtail;, vnto so meku&llbar; &thorn;at
&thorn;er aboute he consumy&dtail; a&llbar; his gudis, so &thorn;at he
fe&llbar; evy&ntail; in despayr.  Vnto so meku&llbar; &thorn;at
o&ntail; a nyght he garte a ma&ntail; of his lede hy&mtail; in-to a
wude, &amp; &thorn;er &thorn;ai raysi&dtail; the devu&llbar; as
&thorn;ai was wunt to do, &amp; made





<PB N="371">

hy&mtail; to speke wit&hbar; &thorn;aim.  And &thorn;er he bad
&thorn;e knyght make no charge of his povertie, &amp; he aski&dtail;
hy&mtail; if he wol&dtail; hafe riches agay&ntail;, &amp; ioy, as he
was wunt to hafe.  And &thorn;e knyght sai&dtail;, ya, he wolde, and
it mot be done be Go&dtail; Almyghtie.  And &thorn;a&ntail; hys
ma&ntail; sayd vnto &thorn;e fende; "Here hafe I broght you a noble
ma&ntail;, my maister, at ye may restore hy&mtail; vnto &thorn;e degre
at he was in afore tyme."  And &thorn;e fende saide, hy&mtail; burde
furst forsake Almyghti God &amp; make homage vnto hy&mtail;.  And
&thorn;is knyght, &thorn;uf a&llbar; it war tremlan&dtail; &amp;
makan&dtail; sorow, neuer-&thorn;e-les, in hope of requoveryng
agay&ntail; of &thorn;at at he had loste, &thorn;urg&hbar;
cownce&llbar; of &thorn;is ma&ntail; he did itt.  And &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;e fend sai&dtail; hy&mtail; burd nede forsake Goddis moder.
And &thorn;e knyght ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;,
&thorn;at wolde he neuer doo.  And &thorn;us he parti&dtail; away fro
&thorn;aim, and went agay&ntail; vnto &thorn;e tow&ntail;.  And
&thorn;er was a kur&ktee; in his way, and he went in and sett
hy&mtail; dow&ntail; o&ntail; his kneis befo&rtail; ane ymage of
ow&rtail; Ladye, &amp; wepi&dtail; &amp; made grete sorow, at a&llbar;
&thorn;e kurk rang with.  So evy&ntail; &thorn;e same how&rtail;, a
knyght &thorn;at had boght a&llbar; his lifelod befo&rtail;, happend
co&mtail; by &thorn;e kur&ktee; away, &amp; har&dtail; grete noyse
&amp; went in, &amp; whe&ntail; he fand &thorn;e knyght, &thorn;at he
kend we&llbar; enog&hbar;, cryand &amp; makan&dtail; his prayer so
devowtly, he had grete merve&llbar;, &amp; drew hy&mtail;
be-hyn&dtail; a pyler &amp; stude sti&llbar;, &amp; &thorn;ogght he
wolde wit what a&llbar; &thorn;is bement.  And, at bathe &thorn;ies
knyghtis har&dtail;, ou&rtail; Ladie spak vnto hur So&ntail; &amp;
sai&dtail;; "O, &thorn;ou swete So&ntail;!  Hafe mercie of &thorn;is
ma&ntail;!"  And &thorn;e childe at satt o&ntail; hur kne wolde not
speke agay&ntail; vnto his moder, bod turny&dtail; his hea&dtail;
awaywar&dtail; fro hur.  And sho praye&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail;,
&amp; say&dtail; &thorn;at &thorn;e ma&ntail; was dessayvi&dtail;, and
with &thorn;at he turny&dtail; his bak opo&ntail; hur and sai&dtail;;
"This ma&ntail; hase denye&dtail; me, what shulde I do vnto
hy&mtail;?"  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e ymage of ow&rtail; Lade rase
vp &amp; sett hur So&ntail; apo&ntail; &thorn;e altar, and fe&llbar;
dow&ntail; o&ntail; hur kneis at His fete and sai&dtail;, "I pray
&thorn;e, swete So&ntail;, &thorn;at for my sake &thorn;ou forgyff
hy&mtail; his sy&ntail;."  And onone &thorn;e chil&dtail; lifty&dtail;
vp His moder and said vnto hur; "Moder, yit I neuer denye&dtail;
&thorn;e thyng att &thorn;ou axki&dtail; me.  And now, beholde, for
&thorn;i sake I forgyff hy&mtail;."  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is
knyght was fay&ntail;, &amp; rase &amp; went his ways furt&hbar; of
&thorn;e kur&ktee;, and was passyng sad&dtail; &amp; hevy for hys
sy&ntail;, &amp; glad &thorn;at it was forgyffe&ntail; hy&mtail;.  And
&thorn;e toder knyght folowi&dtail; hy&mtail; privalie, &
<PB N="372">

ouertuke hy&mtail; &amp; axkid hy&mtail; whi his ee&ntail; war so wate
&amp; so bowny&dtail;.  And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
sai&dtail; &thorn;e wynd garte itt.  And he sai&dtail; agay&ntail;;
"Sur, I knaw &thorn;e cauce of your truspas we&llbar; enog&hbar;.  And
Sur," he sai&dtail;, "I hafe a doghter &amp; no mo childer, and if ye
wu&llbar; wed hur I sa&llbar; giff you a&llbar; your lyfelo&dtail;
agay&ntail;, &amp; you ij I sa&llbar; make heyris of a&llbar; my
riches."  And he thanki&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; wed hur, &amp; was
afterwer&dtail; a gude ma&ntail; &amp; a ric&hbar;e.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Negant eciam deum religiosi.  Supra de

misericordia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Negacionem dei inducit amor carnalis.  Supra de

amore.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Negacionem dei inducit ambicio dignitatis.  Supra

de Maria, vj 
<NOTE ID="P372.N1">So Lat. MSS., Eng. MS. <HI REND="i">has</HI>, de iniuria, iij.</NOTE> .</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Neganda non est pauperi elemosina.  Infra de

paupere, ij 
<NOTE ID="P372.N2">MS. iij.</NOTE> .</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Necligencia hominis impedit ne ei ab aliquo

subueniatur.  Supra de cogitacione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Negligencia executorum nocet testatori.  Supra de

executore, j.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Negligencia vtencium aliqua re perditur aliquando

ipsa res.  Supra de legato.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Necligencia dicendi horas.  Supra de Augustino, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Negociatores sine fraude debent emere et
vendere.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Tullius tellis how o&ntail; a tyme it was disputi&dtail; betwix
Diogenes &amp; Stocius <NOTE ID="P372.N3">Arund. MS. inter Diogenem, Babilonum stoicum, et discipulum eius, Antipatrem.  Harl. MS. inter Diogenem, Babilonium storcum, etc.</NOTE> , &thorn;at was his
disciple.  And Diogenes say&dtail;; "A&llbar; &thorn;e vices of a
thyng &thorn;at is selde aw not to be expowndi&dtail; to hy&mtail;
&thorn;at byes it, bod ewhils it is constitutt be &thorn;e law; ewhils
neuer-&thorn;e-les o&thorn;er









<PB N="373">

thynges er done withoute&ntail; gyle."  And his scoler ansswerd
hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;, &thorn;at whe&ntail; &thorn;e
byer trowes att &thorn;e thyng be gude, &amp; puttis truste in
hy&mtail; &thorn;at sellis it, &thorn;e sellar aw to te&llbar;
&thorn;e byer &amp; &thorn;er be any fawte &thorn;erin.  Tha&ntail;
Diogenes say&dtail;; "It is one to be sty&llbar; &amp; anoder to
lay&ntail;, and &thorn;e tane is not profitable to &thorn;e to here,
nor it is not nedefu&llbar; to me to say."  And &thorn;a&ntail; his
scoler say&dtail;; "And it be dampne&dtail; at Athenys at a ma&ntail;
sa&llbar; not te&llbar; &thorn;e way vnto hy&mtail; &thorn;at travels,
meku&llbar; mo&rtail; dampnable it is wittandlie to suffer a ma&ntail;
fa&llbar; in-to error."  Tha&ntail; Diogenes say&dtail;; "He hase not
garte &thorn;e bye &thorn;at stirris &thorn;e not to bye; and
&thorn;ou byes &thorn;at &thorn;ing at plesis &thorn;e, and he praysis
&thorn;at &thorn;ing &thorn;at is his aw&ntail;.  And whar &thorn;e
dome is in &thorn;e byer, &thorn;er is no begyle in &thorn;e seller.
And &thorn;erfor <NOTE ID="P373.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, and &thorn;erfor.</NOTE> a <NOTE ID="P373.N2">MS. &amp;</NOTE>
seller aght to lay&ntail; nothyng vnto &thorn;e byer <NOTE ID="P373.N3">MS. seller.</NOTE> , neuer-&thorn;e-les hy&mtail; thar not te&llbar;
hy&mtail; bod if he wy&llbar;, for what-so&mtail;-evur langis to
hy&mtail; &thorn;at byes it, longes to hy&mtail; &thorn;at sellis, to
witt how &thorn;at he sa&llbar; se&llbar;."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Nequicia mulieris comparatur serpenti.  Infra de

serpente.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Nequicia Herodis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Cronicles' how &thorn;at Herode, whe&ntail; he
har&dtail; te&llbar; &thorn;at &thorn;e Iewis abade with grete
myrt&hbar; agay&ntail; he sulde dye, he garte gadur samen a&llbar;
&thorn;e noble yong me&ntail; of Iudee, &amp; garte spar &thorn;aim in
a priso&ntail;, &amp; commandi&dtail; vnto Salome his wyfe &thorn;at
als tyte as he war deade, &thorn;at sho sulde sla &thorn;aim ilkone,
at o&ntail; maner of wyse a&llbar; Iudee sulde make sorow when he was
dea&dtail; as wele as &thorn;ai dyd in his lyfe.  And so was done.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Nero.  Supra de crudelitate, et infra de prodigalitate

et Simone.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Nicholai confessoris.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in his 'Meracles,' how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a Iew
&thorn;at har&dtail; te&llbar; of &thorn;e meracles of Saynt Nicholas,
and he garte make ane







<PB N="374">

ymage of hy&mtail;, &amp; sett hy&mtail; to kepe a&llbar; his gudis.  And
whe&ntail; &thorn;e Iew o&ntail; a tyme was fro hame, thevus come &amp;
stale away his gudis, &amp; whe&ntail; he come and fand &thorn;ai wer
away, he bega&ntail; to reprufe &thorn;is ymage, and bett itt sore.  And
Saynt Nicholas apperid vnto &thorn;ies thevis, &amp; shewi&dtail;
&thorn;aim how his body was bety&ntail; for &thorn;at gude att &thorn;ai
had stolle&ntail;, and threti&dtail; &thorn;aim at &thorn;ai sulde be
hange&dtail; bod if &thorn;ai had &thorn;is gude agay&ntail; &amp; restorid
it, &amp; tel&dtail; &thorn;aim at he was Saynt Nicholas, in whose kepyng
&thorn;is Iew had putt a&llbar; his gudis.  And &thorn;ies thevis wer
ffer&dtail;, and broght a&llbar; &thorn;ies gudis agay&ntail;, and tolde
&thorn;e Iew &thorn;is meracle.  And he was turny&dtail; &amp; &thorn;ai,
bothe, and become gude me&ntail;; &amp; &thorn;e Iew was cristen&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Nicholaus scolarem suscitauit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in his 'Meracles' how &thorn;er was a gude ma&ntail;
&thorn;at vsi&dtail; yerelie, becauce of a so&ntail; &thorn;at he had
&thorn;at was a scolar, apo&ntail; Saynt Nicholas day for to make a
grete feste, &amp; dele grete almos in wurshu&ptail; of Saynt
Nicholas.  So &thorn;e devu&llbar; had a dispite &thorn;eratt, &amp;
come to &thorn;e dure in a pure mans liknes, &amp; axki&dtail; almos
vppo&ntail; &thorn;e Saynt Nicholas day.  And &thorn;e gude ma&ntail;
sent hy&mtail; almos with &thorn;is scoler, and &thorn;er &thorn;e
devu&llbar; strangel&dtail; &thorn;e childe &amp; kylli&dtail;
hy&mtail;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e fader come vnto &thorn;e dure and
fande his so&ntail; dea&dtail;, he made meku&llbar; sorow &amp; had vp
&thorn;e dea&dtail; childe in-to a chamb&rtail;, and sett hy&mtail;
dow&ntail; o&ntail; his kneis &amp; made his complaynt vnto Saynt
Nicholas, &amp; sai&dtail;; "Loo!  Saynt Nicholas! behol&dtail;, is
&thorn;is your rewar&dtail; of &thorn;e wurshu&ptail; &thorn;at I hafe
&thorn;is many day done vnto you?"  And as he was &thorn;us
complenan&dtail; &thorn;e childe oppyn&dtail; his ene &amp; rase
v&ptail; &amp; was olyfe agay&ntail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Nicholaus iuuenem de captiuitate patri
restituit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in his 'Meracles' how &thorn;at a ma&ntail;
&thorn;urg&hbar; &thorn;e merettis of Saynt Nicholas had a childe,
whilk &thorn;at whe&ntail; he was a yong ma&ntail;

<PB N="375">

was take&ntail; in &thorn;e were with &thorn;e Aragans <NOTE ID="P375.N1">Lat. MSS. ab Agarenis.</NOTE> , &amp; depute into serves with &thorn;er kyng.  So
it happen&dtail; vppo&ntail; Saynt Nicholas day &thorn;is yong
ma&ntail; broght &thorn;e kyng wyne in a copp of golde, and as he
hel&dtail; it befo&rtail; &thorn;e kyng he remembre&dtail; hy&mtail;
&thorn;at it was Saynt Nicholas day, &amp; how his fadur as &thorn;at
day was wunte to make a grete feste.  And sodanly he gaff a grete
sig&hbar;, and &thorn;e kyng wol&dtail; algattis wete &thorn;e cauce
at he sighe&dtail; for, and he tol&dtail; hy&mtail; evure dele.  And
&thorn;is vncresten&dtail; kyng thrett hy&mtail; &amp; sai&dtail;;
"What at evur &thorn;i Nicholas duse, &thorn;ou sha&llbar; dwe&llbar;
here with vs."  And with &thorn;at sodanlie &thorn;er come a grete
wyn&dtail;, &amp; smate dow&ntail; &thorn;e howse and lifti&dtail;
v&ptail; &thorn;e childe with &thorn;e cop&ptail; in his han&dtail;
&amp; &thorn;e wyne in it, &amp; sett hy&mtail; evy&ntail; at his
fadur dure.  And he went in &amp; fan&dtail; his fadur &amp; a&llbar;
his frendis at dyner, &amp; &thorn;er he tel&dtail; &thorn;aim
a&llbar; how it happen&dtail;.  And &thorn;ai war passan&dtail;
fay&ntail; &amp; thankid God &amp; Saynt Nicholas.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Nicholaus indeuotos sibi verberat.  Supra de

deuocione, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Nicholaus deuotos sibi remunerat.  Supra de

deuocione, j.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Nigromancie
<NOTE ID="P375.N2">MS. Nigromancia.</NOTE> ars est valde periculosa.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a knyght at wol&dtail;
not trow at &thorn;er was any fendis.  So o&ntail; a tyme he come vnto
one &thorn;at was calli&dtail; Phili&ptail;, &thorn;at was practyse in
nygromancye, and praye&dtail; hy&mtail; to latt hy&mtail; se so&mtail;
fendis.  And he re[cu]si&dtail; &amp; sai&dtail; he durst nott; &amp;
yit he labur&dtail; hy&mtail; beselie.  So o&ntail; a day, aboute
none, &thorn;is Phili&ptail; garte &thorn;is knyght put his swerd
abowte hy&mtail;, and at a gateshaty&llbar;, with a <NOTE ID="P375.N3"><HI REND="i">After</HI> a, w, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> swer&dtail; he made a cercle aboute &thorn;is
knyght, and bad hy&mtail; kepe hy&mtail; wele within &thorn;is cercle,
ffor and any membre of hy&mtail; come withoute itt, he mond lose itt
vnto tyme &thorn;at he come agay&ntail; vnto hy&mtail;.  And he bad
hy&mtail;, &amp; he saw any bodie, nowder







<PB N="376">

giff &thorn;aim right not, nor take right not of &thorn;aim, and he
tolde hy&mtail; &thorn;at &thorn;ai wolde bothe tempe hy&mtail; &amp;
flay hy&mtail;; bod &amp; he wolde do so he bad hy&mtail;, he
say&dtail;, &thorn;er shul&dtail; nothyng noy hy&mtail;.  And
whe&ntail; he was gone &amp; &thorn;e knyght was be his one in
&thorn;e cercle, belyfe &thorn;er come as it had bene grete fludis,
&amp; a nowder tyme as it had bene gruntyng of swyne, and now blastis
of wyn&dtail;.  And now hy&mtail; &thorn;oght he saw a ma&ntail; als
hye as treis, and whe&ntail; he come nere &thorn;e cercle he
axki&dtail; &thorn;is knyght what he wol&dtail;, &amp; bad hy&mtail;
aske &amp; he sul&dtail; te&llbar; hy&mtail;.  So he luki&dtail;
opo&ntail; hy&mtail; &amp; hy&mtail; thog&hbar;t he was a grete
ma&ntail; &amp; a blakk, &amp; of grete difformytie, so &thorn;at he
durste not verelie behal&dtail; hy&mtail;.  So att &thorn;e laste
&thorn;is knyght spa&ktee; &amp; sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "I hafe
desyri&dtail; gretelie to se &thorn;e."  And he axki&dtail; hy&mtail;,
whareto.  And &thorn;e knyght sai&dtail;, for he had har&dtail;
te&llbar; meku&llbar; i&llbar; of hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;e fen&dtail;
ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "Men demys me
oftsithis withowte&ntail; cauce, and I do no ma&ntail; skathe bod if
he gar me.  And Phili&ptail; &thorn;i maister is my fren&dtail;, &amp;
I do a&llbar; &thorn;at plesis hy&mtail;, for I grevi&dtail; hy&mtail;
nevur yitt, vnto so meku&llbar; whe&ntail; he calli&dtail; me &amp;
bad me now co&mtail; vnto &thorn;e, I come."  And &thorn;e knyght
aski&dtail; hy&mtail; wha&rtail; he was whe&ntail; he calli&dtail;
hy&mtail;.  And he sai&dtail; he was als far beyonde &thorn;e se as
&thorn;e se was fro t&hbar;ens; " &amp; &thorn;erfo&rtail;," he
sai&dtail;, "it is right at &thorn;ou rewar&dtail; me for my labur."
And &thorn;e knyght axky&dtail; hym what he wol&dtail; hafe, and he
sai&dtail; owder his gow&ntail; or his gyrdy&llbar;, or a shepe of
his flokk; &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; he aski&dtail; a he&ntail;, &amp; att
&thorn;e laste a cok&ktee;.  And &thorn;e knyght sai&dtail; hy&mtail;
evur nay, and wol&dtail; giff hy&mtail; none of &thorn;ies.  So
&thorn;e knyght axki&dtail; hy&mtail; whare he had so muche connyng as
he ha&dtail;, and he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail; at
&thorn;er was none i&llbar; done in a&llbar; &thorn;is werl&dtail; bod
he knew itt.  "And to so meku&llbar;," he sai&dtail;, "&thorn;ou in
suc&hbar; a tow&ntail; &amp; in suche a howse loste &thorn;i
maydenhede, and swylk synnys &amp; swilk hase &thorn;ou done."  And
&thorn;is knyght cut&hbar;e not agay&ntail;-say itt.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e devu&llbar; put furt&hbar; his han&dtail; as
he wol&dtail; hafe taken hy&mtail;, and &thorn;e knyght was fer&dtail;
&amp; fe&llbar; bakwar&dtail; in &thorn;e cercle, &amp; cryed as he
had bene wude.  And als sone as &thorn;is Phili&ptail; harde
hy&mtail;, he come and made a&llbar; &thorn;is fantasies to
vanyss&hbar; away.  And evur after, fro &thorn;at how&rtail;
forwar&dtail;, he was pale &amp; i&llbar; hewi&dtail;, &amp;
trowi&dtail; alway at &thorn;er was fendis.  And afterwar&dtail; he
amendi&dtail; his life &amp; become a gude ma&ntail;.

<PB N="377">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Nigromantici discipulus a demone rapitur et
deportatur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how at &thorn;e cetie of Tholett &thorn;er was ane
&thorn;at hel&dtail; a skule of nygromancy, and his scolers o&ntail; a
tyme desyri&dtail; &thorn;er maister &thorn;at he wolde prufe
&thorn;at befo&rtail; &thorn;aim &thorn;at he taght &thorn;aim.  And
&thorn;er maister, &thorn;uf a&llbar; he wer il-wylli&dtail;
&thorn;erto, o&ntail; a tyme le&dtail; &thorn;aim into &thorn;e
fel&dtail;, and with a swer&dtail; he made a cercle aboute &thorn;aim,
&amp; he bad &thorn;aim if &thorn;ai saw any thyng nowder gif it nor
take &thorn;er-off, bod at &thorn;ai sulde holde &thorn;aim iustelie
within &thorn;e cercle.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he went a litty&llbar;
fro &thorn;aim, &amp; bega&ntail; to say his enchawntmentis.  &amp;
belyfe fendis &thorn;at war calli&dtail; come, so&mtail; in liknes of
a ma&ntail;, so&mtail; of a womma&ntail;, &amp; so&mtail; makand
mynstralcy, &amp; so&mtail; dawnsan&dtail;.  And emang &thorn;aim
&thorn;er was ane like a fay&rtail; womma&ntail;, fayrer
&thorn;a&ntail; a&llbar; &thorn;e toder was, and sho profur&dtail; a
golde ryng vnto ane of &thorn;e scolers ofte sythes, &amp; lang he
forsuke it, &amp; at &thorn;e laste he tuke it, and onone sho
cleki&dtail; hy&mtail; oute of &thorn;e cercle &amp; &thorn;e ryng,
bothe, &amp; onone sho was away with hy&mtail;.  And his felos
bega&ntail; to cry, &amp; &thorn;er maister come onone, &amp;
&thorn;ai tol&dtail; hy&mtail;.  And onone he calli&dtail; vp &thorn;e
maister-fen&dtail;, and tolde hy&mtail; of &thorn;e wrong at was done
vnto his scolar, and desyryd to haffe hy&mtail; agay&ntail;.  And
&thorn;is fen&dtail; calli&dtail; a&llbar; &thorn;e toder fendis vnto
a cownce&llbar;, and reprovi&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;at did &thorn;e
dede.  And he excusi&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; say&dtail; he dyd no
wrong, becauce &thorn;e scoler was inobedyent vnto his maister.
Neuer-&thorn;e-les a sentans was gyffe&ntail; at he sulde be
delyver&dtail; agay&ntail; vnto his maister, for he was a behufable
scolar vnto his maister, and &thorn;us he was restory&dtail;
agay&ntail; vnto his maister.  And fro &thorn;at day forwar&dtail; his
felows &thorn;oght att his face was lene &amp; pale, evy&ntail; as he
had bene take&ntail; oute of his grafe.  &amp; he tol&dtail; his
felows what he saw at he&llbar; yatis, &amp; tol&dtail; &thorn;aim it
was cursi&dtail; scule at &thorn;ai wer at, &amp; desyri&dtail;
&thorn;aim to lefe itt.  And he went and made hy&mtail; a monk of
Ceustus ordur, and afterwar&dtail; was a hali liffer.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Nigromanticam scienciam adipiscens dampnatur.

Infra de sciencia, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>

<PB N="378">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Nomen Christi semper est in corde
habendum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Legenda Beati Ignacij,' &thorn;at whe&ntail; he was in
dyvers grete turmentis, he wol&dtail; neuer sease of calling of
&thorn;e name of Cryste, &amp; &thorn;e turmenturs axki&dtail;
hy&mtail; whi he rehersyd &thorn;at name so ofte.  And he
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "I hafe &thorn;at name
wrette&ntail; in my herte, &amp; &thorn;erfo&rtail; I may not sese fro
calling &thorn;er-vppo&ntail;."  And whe&ntail; he was dead, &thorn;ai
tuke his harte oute of his body, &amp; cut it sonder be &thorn;e
myddeste.  And &thorn;ai fand a&llbar; his herte writte&ntail; within
with &thorn;ies namys, Iesus Christus, &amp; a&llbar; of letters of
golde.  And herefo&rtail; many oo&ntail; trusted in hy&mtail; &amp;
was cristen&dtail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Nomen acquirunt aliqui eciam per aliqua mala opera.

Supra de memoria, i.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Nouicius debet semper in deuocione profiscere et
non tepescere.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' how &thorn;er was one &thorn;at wolde
entir into religio&ntail;, and he lete his mode&rtail; hafe knowlege
of his purpos.  And sho cowncel&dtail; hy&mtail; nay; &amp; he
wol&dtail; not lefe his purpos for hur, bod say&dtail; &thorn;at he
wolde go safe his sawle.  And whe&ntail; he was entred into &thorn;e
religio&ntail; &amp; governy&dtail; hy&mtail; wele, &amp; was fervent
in &thorn;e begynnyng, fro he had contynued awhile he bega&ntail; to
wax slaw, &amp; yrke&dtail; with &thorn;e strate[nes] of his
religio&ntail;.  So o&ntail; a tyme hy&mtail; happend to fa&llbar;
seke &amp; lay in a trans.  So hy&mtail; &thorn;oght &thorn;at he was
broght vnto his dome, &amp; &thorn;er hy&mtail; thoght he fand his
moder &thorn;at was dea&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; sho saw hy&mtail; sho
sayd vnto hy&mtail;; "So&ntail;, how is it with the?  Come &thorn;ou
hedu&rtail; to be demyd with vs?  Wha&rtail; is it now at &thorn;ou
sai&dtail; vnto me, 'I wi&llbar; go safe my sawle ?'"  And at
&thorn;is wurde he was confusi&dtail;, &amp; wuste nevur what he
sul&dtail; say vnto hur agay&ntail;.  And with &thorn;at he
waken&dtail; of his trans, &amp; amendi&dtail; of his sekenes, and
vmthoght hy&mtail; &thorn;at for he wex somwhatt yrke in his
religio&ntail; he was in way of dampnacio&ntail;, &amp; he

<PB N="379">

turnyd hy&mtail; vnto &thorn;e fervor &amp; &thorn;e luff &thorn;at he
ha&dtail; vnto his religio&ntail; at his furste entre, an&dtail;
sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; selfe; "I &thorn;at myght not abyde &amp;
suffer &thorn;e blame &amp; chalange of my moder, how may I abyde
&thorn;e blame of A&llbar;mi&yogh;ttie God &amp; a&llbar; his aungels
&amp; a&llbar; &thorn;e saynttis off hevy&ntail;?"

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Nouicius confirmatur in religione ex consideracione

penarum inferni.  Supra de conuersione 
<!-- P379.N1 --> .</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Nouicius confirmatur in religione ex certitudine

mortis.  Supra de conuersione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Nouicij dissoluti debent corripi.  Supra de correccione,

iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Nouicij orationibus iuuantur ad perseuerandum.

Infra de oracione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Nouicio possunt adaptari multa que dicuntur supra

de contemptu mundi, conuersione 
<NOTE ID="P379.N1">MS. conuersacione.</NOTE> , monacho, et

infra de religione et obediencia.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Nupcie secunde non sunt appetende.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Ieronimus tellis how o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;er was a yong wedow
&thorn;at hight Ann, an&dtail; whe&ntail; hur husband was dea&dtail;
sho thoght sho wolde not <NOTE ID="P379.N2"><HI REND="i">Added above the line</HI>.</NOTE> be we&dtail; with a
noder ma&ntail;.  Hur frendis come &amp; cowncel&dtail; hur yis, &amp;
said vnto hur; "Thow erte yit bod of a myddi&llbar; age, &amp; a
fay&rtail; womma&ntail; &amp; a listie, take &thorn;e a noder
husban&dtail;."  And sho sai&dtail;; "Nay, &thorn;at wi&llbar; I not
doo; ffor &amp; I hafe als gude a husban&dtail; as I had befo&rtail;,
I wi&llbar; evur be fer&dtail; &thorn;at I sa&llbar; lose hy&mtail;,
&amp; if he be y&llbar;, me wy&llbar; gretelie repent &thorn;at I
ha&dtail; ane i&llbar; after a gude."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Obediencia debet esse parata.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' of a monk &thorn;at was a writer,
&thorn;at hight Marchus, &amp; as he was writan&dtail; &amp; in makyng
of ane O,





<PB N="380">

his abbott calli&dtail;, &amp; he lefte it half vnmade &amp; went at
his ca&llbar;, becauce he wolde not breke his obedyans.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Obediendum est eciam in impossibilibus
<NOTE ID="P380.N1"><HI REND="i">So</HI> Arund. MS., Eng. MS. in possibilibus.</NOTE> a viris
perfectis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Sene&ktee; <NOTE ID="P380.N2">Arund. MS. Seuerus. Harl. MS. Seuarius.</NOTE> tellis how &thorn;at vnto a
ma&ntail; &thorn;at shulde entre in-to religio&ntail; &thorn;e abbott
declari&dtail; &thorn;e grevus laburs &thorn;erof, &amp; how &thorn;at
hy&mtail; bur&dtail; doo a&llbar; suche &thorn;ing as was commanddid
hy&mtail;; &amp; he was nothyng fer&dtail; &thorn;erfo&rtail; &amp;
recusi&dtail; nott to co&mtail; into religio&ntail;, bod
promysi&dtail; to be always pacient &amp; obedient.  So
afterwar&dtail; his maister &thorn;oght at he wol&dtail; prufe
hy&mtail;, so be cace it happen&dtail; at &thorn;e ove&ntail; of
&thorn;er abbay was hate, redie to sett brea&dtail; in; and his
maister commawndi&dtail; of obedyans to go into &thorn;is ovy&ntail;.
And he left not to do his maister commandment, bod went in boldlie
with a gude belefe; &amp; whe&ntail; he was in &thorn;e ove&ntail;,
&thorn;e hete &thorn;erof turny&dtail; in-to col&dtail;, so &thorn;at
he feli&dtail; nothyng bod as it had bene sprencle&dtail; ouer with
dew.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Obediunt perfecti eciam contra spem optinendi
quod precipitur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Seruius <NOTE ID="P380.N3">Lat. MSS. Severus.</NOTE> tellis how o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;e
same abbott &thorn;oght &thorn;at he wol&dtail; prufe a novace, &amp;
he tuke a dry stowre &thorn;at he vsi&dtail; to bere in his han&dtail;
&amp; smate it into &thorn;e ert&hbar;, &amp; bad a novice &thorn;at
he sulde watir it evurilk day vnto &thorn;at it waxi&dtail; grene
&amp; bare liffis agay&ntail; kynde.  And he did as he commandi&dtail;
hy&mtail;, and evur-ilk day bare a grete pott fu&llbar; fro a watur ij
myle thens, &amp; watyr&dtail; &thorn;is stow&rtail; unto he had done
it a yere; and yitt he wex nott werie bod did o&ntail; as he did
afo&rtail;.  And &thorn;uf a&llbar; hy&mtail; thoght &thorn;er come no
frute o&ntail; his warke, yit hy&mtail; thoght he wolde not breke his
obediens, bod enduri&dtail; in his labur a&llbar; &thorn;e
secun&dtail; yere.  And in &thorn;e iij yere whe&ntail;









<PB N="381">

&thorn;is watir-ber sesi&dtail; not of his labur, &thorn;is
stow&rtail; at was dry florisshi&dtail;, &amp; bare levis &amp; frute.
And he went vnto his abbott &amp; tol&dtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; he tuke
a&llbar; his monkis with hy&mtail; &amp; come &amp; saw it &amp;
say&dtail;; "Loo! brethur, &thorn;urg&hbar; vertue of fulfyllyng of
obediens, &thorn;is dry stow&rtail; agay&ntail; kynde is now fayr
florisshi&dtail; &amp; beris levis."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Obediens verus non attendit quid
precipitur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cassianus tellis how o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;er was ane abbott
&thorn;at commawndi&dtail; his dissiple &amp; sai&dtail; vnto
hy&mtail;; "Go, ry&ntail;," he sai&dtail;, "als faste as &thorn;ou
may, and als tyte as &thorn;ou may tur&ntail; me yone grete stone."
And onone his dissiple a grete stone, &thorn;at many me&ntail; myght
not hafe turny&dtail;, now with lifte at his hea&dtail; &amp; now at
his breste, with grete strent&hbar; he turny&dtail; it ouer; &amp; he
swett so &thorn;at a&llbar; his clothis war&rtail; wett thrug&hbar;,
for he supposi&dtail; &thorn;at nothyng was commandi&dtail; vnto
hy&mtail; &thorn;at was impossible to doo.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Obediencia perfecta amorem naturalem postponit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cassianus tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was oo&ntail; take&ntail;
in-to ane abbay, &amp; he broght with hy&mtail; his so&ntail; of viij
yere olde; and he was dissever&dtail; fro hy&mtail; &amp; put in
a-noder ce&llbar;.  So &thorn;is abbot &thorn;oght &thorn;at he wolde
[prufe] his obedians &amp; his affeccio&ntail;, &amp; he
commaundi&dtail; hy&mtail; to caste his so&ntail; in-to a grete watir.
And onone as he had commandi&dtail; hy&mtail;, he gatt his so&ntail;
in his armys and come vnto &thorn;e watur-syde, and wol&dtail; hafe
casty&ntail; in his aw&ntail; bar&ntail; bod at &thorn;er was monkis
&thorn;at wachi&dtail; what he wolde doo &amp; letti&dtail; hy&mtail;.
And yitt for a&llbar; at &thorn;ai cut&hbar; do he keste it in, &amp;
onone &thorn;ai gatt it oute and savyd itt olyfe.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Obediunt quandoque creature eciam insensibiles
<NOTE ID="P381.N1">MS. ininsensibiles.</NOTE>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Gregorie tellis how &thorn;at in &thorn;e cetie of Placens
&thorn;e watur &thorn;at was <NOTE ID="P381.N2">MS. wal&dtail;.</NOTE> cal&dtail; Padus
rase vp opo&ntail; a grete spate and ow&rtail;yode a&llbar; &thorn;e





<PB N="382">

feldis &thorn;at langid vnto ane abbay.  &amp; &thorn;er was a gude,
holie ma&ntail; &thorn;at hight Sabinus, a bisshop&ptail;, and
whe&ntail; he saw &thorn;is he garte a notorie of his write a
by&llbar; &amp; caste in &thorn;e flude, and &thorn;is was &thorn;e
wrytyng; "Sabinus, &thorn;e servan&dtail; of ow&rtail; Lor&dtail; Iesu
Criste commandis vnto &thorn;e, Pado, &thorn;at ou&rtail; &thorn;i
bankis &thorn;ou pas no mo&rtail; fro hens furt&hbar;, nor at
&thorn;ou hurte nott landis &thorn;at longis vnto &thorn;e
kur&ktee;."  And his notarie di&dtail; as he bad hy&mtail;.  And
onone &thorn;e watir fe&llbar; of &thorn;e kurk-lan&dtail; and come
vnto &thorn;e bowndis at it was wunte to ry&ntail; in; and nevur after
vnto &thorn;is day rase it ouer &thorn;e bankis nor passi&dtail;
&thorn;e bowndis.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Obediunt sanctis eciam bruta animalia.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Gregorie tellis how &thorn;at Florencius, &thorn;e
servan&dtail; of Almighti Go&dtail;, dwelt alone be hy&mtail; selfe in
a ce&llbar;, &amp; he had v or vj shepe.  And he made his prayer vnto
A&llbar;myghti God &amp; besoght Hy&mtail; at He wol&dtail; send
hy&mtail; somwhatt to dwe&llbar; with hy&mtail; to comfurt&hbar;
hy&mtail;.  And onone as he had made his prayer, he fand at his
ce&llbar;-yate, standan&dtail;, a bere, whilk &thorn;at lowti&dtail;
vnto hy&mtail; and fawny&dtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; was nothyng wylde.
And he conseyvi&dtail; at it was sent hy&mtail; be Almyghti
God&dtail;, &amp; bad it go hafe his shepe furt&hbar; &amp; kepe
&thorn;aim, &amp; at it sulde bryng &thorn;aim home at sex of &thorn;e
clok at evy&ntail;; and it did trewlie as he bad it.  And in &thorn;e
mornyng he commandi&dtail; it not to co&mtail; home or ix of &thorn;e
clo&ktee;, and he fasti&dtail; evur to it come home.  And evur
&thorn;is bere did as he bad itt, and so he tari&dtail; long
fastan&dtail; o days <NOTE ID="P382.N1">Harl. MS. cepit ex hoc fama eius longe lateque crebrescere; cui inuidentes, quatuor discipuli Euthici, eo quod magister eorum, Euthicius, signa non faceret, latenter vrsum occidunt.</NOTE> .  And he had iiij
disciples &thorn;at war wrothe with &thorn;is bere becauce it
hel&dtail; &thorn;aim long fastan&dtail; o days, &amp; &thorn;ai dwelt
with anoder ma&ntail; in &thorn;e wyldernes &thorn;at hyght Euticius.
Becauce &thorn;er maister did no swilk takens, and privalie, &thorn;ai
slew &thorn;is bere.  And &thorn;is holie ma&ntail; bade of his dener
to evy&ntail;, &amp; evur luki&dtail; aftur &thorn;is bere, &amp; she
come nevur home.  So opo&ntail; &thorn;e mor&ntail; he went vnto
&thorn;e felde and fand &thorn;is bere slay&ntail;, and als sone as he
saw hur <NOTE ID="P382.N2">MS. hym.</NOTE> he knew wele






<PB N="383">

enog&hbar; who did itt, and he fe&llbar; opo&ntail; a wepyng, more for
&thorn;e malice of his bredur &thorn;a&ntail; for &thorn;e dead of
&thorn;e bere.  And &thorn;us he sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; selfe; "I
trow &thorn;at in &thorn;is life at vengeange sa&llbar; be take&ntail;
o&ntail; &thorn;aim for &thorn;er males."  And belyfe after it
happen&dtail; as he sai&dtail;, ffor &thorn;ies iiij brethur war onone
streke&ntail; with a soda&ntail; sekenes, &amp; rotid abow&ntail; erde
at &thorn;ai stynky&dtail; with.  And he&rtail;-vppo&ntail; &thorn;is
holie ma&ntail; had conciens &amp; tolde his brethur &thorn;at
hy&mtail; forthoght at he had say&dtail;.  And a&llbar; &thorn;e dayis
of his lyfe he had sorow &thorn;erfo&rtail;, &amp; wepud &amp; made
muche murnyng, and hel&dtail; hy&mtail; selfe as a crowe&llbar;
ma&ntail; &amp; a vengeable homycide.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Obediencia prefertur alijs
<NOTE ID="P383.N1">MS. alij.</NOTE> virtutibus.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' how so&mtail; tyme iiij brethir
&thorn;at was cled a&llbar; in pylchis come vnto ane abbott &thorn;at
hyght Pambo, &amp; ilkone of &thorn;aim tolde hy&mtail; &thorn;e
vertue of o&thorn;er, whe&ntail; &thorn;ai war away at &thorn;ai spak
off.  So one of &thorn;aim was a grete faster, and anoder was
passan&dtail; pure, and &thorn;e iij had passand meku&llbar; charitie,
and &thorn;e iiij had xij yere dwelte in obediens emang olde me&ntail;
&amp; brak neuer his obedyens.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is abbot
Pambo sayde; "I saw &thorn;at &thorn;e vertue of hy&mtail; &thorn;is
is mo&rtail; &thorn;a&ntail; of a&llbar; &thorn;e toder, ffor ilkone
of you &thorn;e vertue &thorn;at he hase holdys it &thorn;urg&hbar;
his aw&ntail; wy&llbar;, and he this makis his wy&llbar; his
servan&dtail;.  And suc&hbar; me&ntail; er acordable in
religio&ntail;, and speciallie &thorn;ai &thorn;at perseuers
&thorn;erin vnto &thorn;er lyfis en&dtail;."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Obediencia debet aliquando a superiori probari.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a husban&dtail;
&thorn;at had a servan&dtail; &thorn;at was profetable &amp; trew vnto
hy&mtail;.  And whe&ntail; he har&dtail; te&llbar; of &thorn;e
inobediens of Ada&mtail;, ow&rtail; former fadur, he had grete
dedey&ntail; &thorn;eratt.  And o&ntail; a tyme he sai&dtail; vnto his
master &thorn;at hy&mtail; &thorn;oght &thorn;at Ada&mtail; was a
grete fole, &thorn;at wolde not kepe his maisters commandment.  "For,"
he say&dtail;, "&amp; ye commandi&dtail; me a



<PB N="384">

thyng I sulde not breke itt."  So with-in a few dayes afterwar&dtail;
his maister delyver&dtail; hy&mtail; a box at was sparri&dtail;, bod
nott bod at he myg&hbar;t oppy&ntail; itt, and sai&dtail; vnto
hy&mtail;; "&thorn;is boyste I delyver &thorn;e; bod I charge &thorn;e
att &thorn;ou oppy&ntail; it natt, for &amp; &thorn;ou do, &thorn;ou
sa&llbar; lose my grace, &amp; I wu&llbar; giff &thorn;e no hyre."
And whe&ntail; he had taky&ntail; &thorn;is box and was be his one, he
turnyd it abowte &amp; say&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; selfe; "I a&mtail;
now be myne one, whatt &amp; I oppy&ntail; &thorn;is boyste?  Na
ma&ntail; may se me &amp; I doo."  So &thorn;us he was
ouercomme&ntail; with temptacio&ntail; and oppyn&dtail; &thorn;is
boyste.  And &thorn;er was &thorn;erin a little burde, &amp; it flow
away; and &thorn;a&ntail; he was passan&dtail; hevy &amp; fe&llbar;
o&ntail; kneis befo&rtail; his maister &amp; aski&dtail; hy&mtail;
forgyfnes, bod he had it no&yogh;t.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Obediencia eciam aliquando in minimis
<NOTE ID="P384.N1">MS. nimis. Harl. MS. <HI REND="i">as above</HI>.</NOTE> non seruatur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how som tyme &thorn;erfo&rtail; &thorn;er was a
knyght &thorn;at had a wurthi genty&llbar;-womma&ntail; vnto his wyfe,
and a gude, whilk &thorn;at had a grete skor&ntail; &amp; a hethyng
agayns [Eve], &thorn;at sho sulde be so vnobedient vnto Ada&mtail; hur
husban&dtail;.  And &thorn;is knyght blamy&dtail; his wyfe
herefo&rtail; and sai&dtail; &thorn;at sho was inobediente vnto
hy&mtail; in les &thorn;ing &thorn;a&ntail; evur was Eve vnto
Ada&mtail;.  And sho say&dtail; nay, &amp; he yis.  So he
chargi&dtail; hur in pay&ntail; of xl<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> mar&ktee; &thorn;at
opo&ntail; &thorn;at day at sho shulde be wasshi&dtail; or
bathi&dtail;, at sho sulde not entre in-to &thorn;e cowrte nor into
&thorn;e dyke barefute.  And lo! so mervaloslie it happen&dtail;; ffor
fro thens furt&hbar; sho was so turment with temptacio&ntail;
&thorn;at o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; sho was bathi&dtail;, sodanlie
sho sterte oute of hur bathe &amp; went barefute in-to &thorn;e cowrte
&amp; in-to &thorn;e dyke vp to &thorn;e kneis.  And one at saw hur
come &amp; telli&dtail; his lor&dtail;, &amp; he come vnto &thorn;e
ladie &amp; tel&dtail; hur &thorn;at sho had broke&ntail; hur obediens
in les &thorn;ing &thorn;a&ntail; Eve di&dtail;, &amp; &thorn;er he
blamy&dtail; hur gretelie &amp; made hur pay hur money at he had putt
hur in pay&ntail; of evurilk dele.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Obedienciam tollit aliquando temptacio gule.  Supra

de gula.</FOREIGN>



<PB N="385">
</ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Obedire nolens quandoque visibiliter 
<NOTE ID="P385.N1">MS. invisibiliter. Harl. MS. <HI REND="i">as above</HI>.</NOTE>  punitur.  Infra

de religione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Obediunt perfecti suscipere penitenciam quam non

meruerunt.  Supra de accusacione.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Obediencia debet impleri usque ad reuocacionem
precepti.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' how a gude, symple ma&ntail;, &thorn;at
hight Paule, left a&llbar; his gudis &amp; went vnto Saynt Anto&ntail;
&thorn;e abbott.  And &thorn;e furste nyght &thorn;is abbott
commawndi&dtail; hy&mtail; at he sulde sitt hy&mtail; dow&ntail; in
his prayers vnto he come vnto hy&mtail;.  And he sett hy&mtail;
dow&ntail; befo&rtail; &thorn;e olde ma&ntail; ce&llbar; dure &amp;
made his prayers, and nowder for &thorn;e dew of &thorn;e nyght, nor
yit for hete of &thorn;e day, he wol&dtail; not move hy&mtail; nor go
away or his maister come.  So it happen&dtail; o&ntail; a tyme
whe&ntail; he was emang his brether, he aski&dtail; &thorn;aim whethur
was furste, Criste or His profettis; and so Saynt Anto&ntail; was
ashamy&dtail; with his questio&ntail; &amp; commaundi&dtail; hy&mtail;
to go his wais &amp; holde his tong.  And onone he did so; and fro
thens furth he kepy&dtail; sylens so ferventlie, at he wol&dtail;
neuer speke bod whe&ntail; his fadur commawndi&dtail; hy&mtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Oblacio non debet fieri nisi de bono.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iacobus de Vetriaco tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a
husband-ma&ntail; &thorn;at was ane y&llbar; payer of his tenndis, and
he wol&dtail; seldo&mtail; offer bod if it wer o&ntail; solempne
dayis, and &thorn;a&ntail; he wol&dtail; off&rtail; a fals peny or ane
y&llbar;.  So o&ntail; a passc&hbar;-day hy&mtail; happen&dtail; emang
o&thorn;er to co&mtail; vnto &thorn;e howselburde, and &thorn;e
preste, &thorn;at knew &thorn;at he vsi&dtail; evur to offer a fals
peny, whe&ntail; he had gyffe&ntail; o&thorn;er me&ntail; &thorn;er
howse&llbar;, he gaf &thorn;is husban&dtail;, in-stea&dtail; of his
howse&llbar;, &thorn;e same y&llbar; peny &thorn;at he offer&dtail;.



<PB N="386">

And he chewi&dtail; &amp; fel&dtail; at it was har&dtail;, &amp;
grapi&dtail; in his mouthe what it was, &amp; he fan&dtail; it was
&thorn;e same fals peny &thorn;at he had offer&dtail;; &amp;
whe&ntail; he saw it he had grete merve&llbar; &thorn;erof, and made
meku&llbar; sorow.  So whe&ntail; mes was done, he come vnto &thorn;e
preste wepan&dtail; &amp; say&dtail;; "A! sur, my sy&ntail; is so
grete &thorn;at it happen&dtail; me &thorn;is day at &thorn;e
sacrament att ye gaff me is turny&dtail; in-to a fals peny."  And
&thorn;e preste ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;;
"This thyng happyn&dtail; not vnto &thorn;e with-oute so&mtail; cawce,
and &thorn;erfo&rtail; &thorn;ou haste done so&mtail; horrible
sy&ntail;.  Te&llbar; me what it is!"  And with grete shame he tolde
hy&mtail; in confessio&ntail;, &amp; sai&dtail;; "I shryfe me
&thorn;at I was so attempti&dtail; with <NOTE ID="P386.N1"><HI REND="i">After</HI> with, ov, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE>
covatice, &thorn;at evur whe&ntail; o&thorn;er folk offer&dtail; gude
syluer I offer&dtail; alway ane i&llbar; penye."  And &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;e preste sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "This was &thorn;e iugement
at &thorn;ou tolde me off; and herefo&rtail; in-stede of &thorn;e
sacrament &thorn;ou fan&dtail; in &thorn;i mouthe ane i&llbar; peny.
And &thorn;erfo&rtail; &thorn;ou moste make restitucio&ntail;."  And
so he di&dtail;, &amp; promysi&dtail; &thorn;at evur after fro thens
furt&hbar; he sulde trewlie pay his ten&dtail; &amp; offer gude
syluer.  An&dtail; so &thorn;e preste asoyli&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp;
gaff hy&mtail; his howse&llbar;, and evur after he was a gude
ma&ntail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Oblacio sacramenti in missa valet ad viuos et

defunctos.  Supra de missa.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Obligatus pro aliquo, vel hic vel in futuro, persoluet
illud ad quod se obligauit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Petrus Damianus tellis how &thorn;er was a monke &thorn;at was a
grete synner, &amp; grete penance at was enionyd hy&mtail; he besoght
one &thorn;at was familiarie vnto hy&mtail; to helpe hy&mtail; to do.
And he vndertuke to do &thorn;at one halfe of his penance, &amp; bad
hy&mtail; be not fer&dtail; &thorn;erfo&rtail;.  So hy&mtail;
&thorn;is at ban&dtail; hy&mtail; selfe &thorn;us, with-in a while
after deyi&dtail;, and he was a gude ma&ntail; emangis his brethir;
and with-in a little while he apperi&dtail; vnto &thorn;is o&thorn;er
mon&ktee;.  And he axki&dtail; hy&mtail; how it stude with hy&mtail;,
and he sai&dtail;; "I&llbar; &amp; hardlie, not for my selfe bod



<PB N="387">

for the; ffor whe&ntail; I was fre of myne aw&ntail; selfe I bande me
for &thorn;e.  And &thorn;erfo&rtail;," he sai&dtail;, "go, &amp; pray
&thorn;e covent at &thorn;ai fullfy&llbar; a&llbar; &thorn;at at I
promysi&dtail; to do for the."  And whe&ntail; &thorn;at was done he
apperi&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; agay&ntail;, and lete hy&mtail;
witt &thorn;at onone he was delyver&dtail; &thorn;urg&hbar; his
brethir prayer.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Obligare se 
<NOTE ID="P387.N1">MS. Obligare se semper pro aliquo.</NOTE>  pro aliquo non semper est securum.

Supra de fideiussore.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Obliuio scitorum prius causatur aliquando ex

minucione.  Supra de minucione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Obliuissi debet confessor ea que in confessione

audiuit.  Supra de confessione, iiij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Obloquendum non est sanctis.  Supra de blasfemia,

iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Obstinacio.  Obstinatus
<NOTE ID="P387.N2">MS. Obstinatutus.</NOTE> in peccatis suis
dampnatur sepius.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Bede tellis in 'Gestis Anglorum' of one &thorn;at was
turny&dtail; in name bod he was shrewi&dtail; in condicions, and
whe&ntail; he was correcte he wolde not amen&dtail; hy&mtail; bod was
ay longer war; bod becauce he cuthe gude sky&llbar; of ane offes,
&thorn;erfo&rtail; he was suffred more.  So at &thorn;e laste
hy&mtail; happend to fa&llbar; seke, and he garte ca&llbar; a&llbar;
his brethir afor&ntail; hy&mtail;, and was a&llbar; come&ntail;, he
telli&dtail; &thorn;aim his sete was ordan&dtail; in he&llbar;, noght
ferr fro Pylatt &amp; Cayphas.  And whe&ntail; his brethir cryed
o&ntail; hy&mtail; &amp; bad hy&mtail; aske mercye &amp; do penans for
his sy&ntail;, he sai&dtail; he might not forthyn&ktee; his
sy&ntail;, for iugement was passi&dtail; agayns hy&mtail;.  And
&thorn;us he dye&dtail; in wrichidnes.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Obstinacio impedit restitucionem forisfactorum.

Infra de vsurario, vj et x.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Obstinacio impedit contricionem.  Supra de</FOREIGN><PB N="388"><FOREIGN> contricione, v, et de heretico, ij; de accusacione, et de

aduocato, iiij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Occasionem querit potens et princeps contra

impotentem.  Infra de potente.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Ocium est semper fugiendum.  Supra de labore, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXXX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ocium detestantur sancti.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was ane
hermett in wyldernes, neuer-&thorn;e-les, &thorn;uf a&llbar; he mott
nott se&llbar; &thorn;aim, yit he wolde make baskettis and swyllis of
palme levis, &thorn;at he sulde not be ydi&llbar;, and for to kepe his
harte fro ydu&llbar; thoghtys &amp; vanyties &thorn;at wi&llbar;
co&mtail; in a mans myn&dtail; and he be not occupie&dtail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Ociosa verba non sunt dicenda.  Infra de verbo, j,

&amp; ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXXXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ociosa verba precipue in ecclesia non sunt
dicenda.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iacobus de Vetriaco tellis at &thorn;e devu&llbar; wrate in a
kur&ktee; a&llbar; maner ydul wurdis &thorn;at was wrette&ntail;
&thorn;er <NOTE ID="P388.N1">Lat. MSS. verba ociosa que ibi dicebantur.</NOTE> , and whe&ntail; he had not
parchement enog&hbar; to write o&ntail; he drew it oute with his tethe
&amp; his handis, &amp; he drew so faste at he rappi&dtail; his
hea&dtail; agay&ntail; &thorn;e wa&llbar;.  And &thorn;er was a holie
ma&ntail; at saw hy&mtail;, and he aski&dtail; hy&mtail; what he
di&dtail;, and he tolde hy&mtail; a&llbar; &thorn;at is befo&rtail;
sai&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXXXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Oculi sunt reprimendi.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' of one &thorn;at hight Gladius <NOTE ID="P388.N2">Harl. MS. Claudius.</NOTE> , whe&ntail; he had bene lang in his ce&llbar;, xx
yere or more, yit he luki&dtail; neuer vp, nor neuer saw &thorn;e rufe
&thorn;erof within.





<PB N="389">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXXXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Oculus est inimicus cordis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Gestis Petri Clareuallis' how o&ntail; a tyme,
whe&ntail; he had &thorn;urg&hbar; raklesnes loste ane of his
ee&ntail; and was made monoculus, afterwarde in his sporte he wolde
say he had loste ane of his enmys, &amp; at he was mo&rtail;
dredefu&llbar; for &thorn;at ee &thorn;at was lefte hy&mtail;
&thorn;a&ntail; for &thorn;e los <NOTE ID="P389.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, of &thorn;e los.</NOTE> of &thorn;e
toder ee.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXXXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Odore contingit peccare.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' off ane &thorn;at hight Arsenius,
&thorn;at was a passand grete laburer with his handis, whe&ntail; he
was in wyldernes he wolde nevur skyfte his clothis bod ons in a yere,
to so meku&llbar; &thorn;at whe&ntail; he doffi&dtail; &thorn;aim
&thorn;ai stynki&dtail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he wolde say vnto
hy&mtail; selfe; "For &thorn;e vntement and gude savurs &thorn;at I
hafe feli&dtail; in &thorn;e werl&dtail;, &thorn;erfo&rtail; it is
necessarie to me to fele &thorn;is stynke."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Odore nimis delicati eciam corporaliter puniuntur 
<NOTE ID="P389.N2">MS. peruniuntur.</NOTE> .

Supra de delicijs.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Offertorio possunt adaptari que supra dicuntur de

oblacione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Officialis malus est ammonendus 
<NOTE ID="P389.N3"><HI REND="i">Reference missing in the</HI> MSS.</NOTE> .</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXXXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Oracio debet esse continua et cum
reuerencia.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Iero&mtail; tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a ma&ntail;
&thorn;at hight Ioh&ntail;, &amp; in a banke vndernethe a grete stone
he contynue&dtail; iij yere in his prayers, and a&llbar;-way
standdan&dtail;.  And he neuer satt nor lay, nor neuer slepi&dtail;
bod standan&dtail;, and he had neuer meate bod o&ntail; &thorn;e
Sonday whe&ntail; a preste come vnto hy&mtail; and sai&dtail; a mes
afor&ntail; hy&mtail;; and &thorn;at was his fude.  So at &thorn;e
laste he was ou&rtail;-comme&ntail; &amp; myght







<PB N="390">

stand no langer, for his leggis &amp; his fete warr roty&ntail;
vndernet&hbar; hy&mtail; &amp; ware come oute of &thorn;aim.  And
whe&ntail; &thorn;ies iij yere was done, aungels come vnto hy&mtail;
&amp; heli&dtail; hy&mtail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Oratione impeditur raptor et restituere compellitur.

Infra de raptore, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXXXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Oracioni devote obediunt bruta.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Gregur tellis how o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; &thorn;e holie
ma&ntail; Boniface stude vppo&ntail; a grece lenan&dtail; ou&rtail;,
&thorn;er come a fox &amp; tuke a he&ntail; evy&ntail; befo&rtail;
hy&mtail;.  And whe&ntail; he saw &thorn;at, he went in-to &thorn;e
kur&ktee; &amp; fe&llbar; dow&ntail; in his prayers &amp; sai&dtail;;
"Lorde!  Plesis it &thorn;e at I may not eatt of &thorn;at at my moder
bryngis v&ptail;?  Lorde, behal&dtail;, sho bredis hennys, &amp;
&thorn;e fox commys &amp; eatis &thorn;aim."  And whe&ntail; he had
done his prayer he rase &amp; went furt&hbar; of &thorn;e kur&ktee;;
and onone &thorn;e fox come agay&ntail;, &amp; &thorn;e he&ntail; att
he had taky&ntail; lete hur fa&llbar; owte of his mouthe.  And with
&thorn;at he fe&llbar; dea&dtail; befo&rtail; &thorn;is holie
ma&ntail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXXXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Oracio eciam dampnatos ad vitam et penetentiam
revocat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Petrus Damascenus <NOTE ID="P390.N1">Lat. MSS. Petrus Damianus.</NOTE> tellis how o&ntail; a
tyme &thorn;er was a mon&ktee; at was dea&dtail;, &amp; was
bor&ntail; in-to &thorn;e kur&ktee; whils a mes sulde be songe&ntail;
for hy&mtail;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e Agnus Dei was said, &thorn;is
dead monke rase evy&ntail; vp sodanlie &amp; spakk &amp;
blasfemy&dtail; Go&dtail; &amp; bannyd Hy&mtail;, &amp; spitt
vppo&ntail; &thorn;e crucifix, and wolde hafe revy&ntail; dow&ntail;
&thorn;e ymage of ow&rtail; Ladie.  &amp; he sai&dtail; vnto &thorn;e
monkis; "Wharefo&rtail; syng ye or prayes for me?  I a&mtail; dampnyd
and in &thorn;e paynys of he&llbar;."  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e
monkis with a&llbar; &thorn;er hertis prayed for hy&mtail;, &amp; did
of &thorn;er clothis &amp; bete &thorn;er selfe for hy&mtail;, &amp;
made tunsions o&ntail; &thorn;er breste.  So at &thorn;e laste,
&thorn;urg&hbar; &thorn;er prayer, he come agay&ntail; vnto



<PB N="391">

hy&mtail; selfe, and bega&ntail; to dispice &thorn;e fen&dtail; &amp;
lofe God &amp; ou&rtail; Ladie, &amp; wurshuppi&dtail; &thorn;e cros
&amp; aski&dtail; confessio&ntail; &amp; penance.  And &thorn;er he
confessi&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;at after he had forsake&ntail;
a&llbar; &thorn;e werl&dtail; he had falle&ntail; in-to
fornicacio&ntail; &amp; laynyd it, &amp; was neuer shrevy&ntail;
&thorn;eroff.  And &thorn;us he liffi&dtail; to o&ntail; &thorn;e
toder day in prayer &amp; in penance.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he
passi&dtail; vnto Go&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXXXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Oraciones non iuuant finaliter dampnatos.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iacobus de Vetriaco tellis &thorn;at whe&ntail; Saynt Marie of
Oigniez <NOTE ID="P391.N1">MS. Ogimet.</NOTE> apo&ntail; a day had made hur prayer
vnto God for a certay&ntail; dead ma&ntail;, hur was bydde&ntail; at
sho sulde no mo&rtail; pray for hy&mtail;; "ffor he is reprovi&dtail;
of Almi&yogh;tty Go&dtail;."  And whe&ntail; &thorn;at he vnhappelie
was slay&ntail; in turnament, he was dampny&dtail; vnto evurlastyng
pay&ntail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DLXXXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Orationibus iuuantur anime in purgatorio.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iacobus de Vetriaco tellis how o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;is Saynt
Marie of Oigniez <NOTE ID="P391.N2">MS. Oxninez.</NOTE> was in hur ce&llbar;, and sho
saw afo&rtail; hur a grete multitude of handis haldyng v&ptail; as it
had bene to pray vnto hur.  And sho besoght God to latt hur hafe
knowlege what it bement.  And it was ansswer&dtail; hur at &thorn;ai
war sawlis of &thorn;aim &thorn;at war in purgatorie, &thorn;at
besoght hur to pray for &thorn;aim.  And sho was fay&ntail;
&thorn;erof &amp; prayed speciallie for &thorn;aim.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Oracio avis audita est.  Supra de aue, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Oracione Deus aliquando mortem tardat.  Supra de

Basilio.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Orantes impedit demon.  Supra de oracione, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Oraciones aliquas dicere omni die vtile est.  Infra

de remuneracione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Oracioni cordis plus attendit deus quam vocis.

Supra de Annunciacione.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>



<PB N="392">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXC.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Oracioni corde est attendendum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Iero&mtail; tellis how &thorn;at whe&ntail; Hillario&ntail;
had lefte a&llbar; maner of o&thorn;er &thorn;ingis and was
giffe&ntail; alonelie vnto his prayers, he suffer&dtail; many snybbis
of &thorn;e fen&dtail;; &amp; whe&ntail; he was in his prayers
&thorn;e fen&dtail; apperi&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; in many lyknessis.
So it happen&dtail; o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; he was in his prayers,
becauce he wolde be lett with no maner of sight, he sett hy&mtail;
dow&ntail; o&ntail; his kneis &amp; o&ntail; his elbowys, &amp;
lay&dtail; his face dow&ntail; vnto &thorn;e ert&hbar;.  And onone
&thorn;e devu&llbar; come &amp; sett hy&mtail; stridlyngis on his
bak&ktee;, &amp; dang hy&mtail; in &thorn;e sydes with sharpe
spurris, &amp; lai&dtail; o&ntail; his hea&dtail; with a swi&ptail;
&amp; sai&dtail;; "Wharto syttys &thorn;ou &thorn;us scornan&dtail;
&amp; nappis?"  And he was als hevy o&ntail; his bakk as it had bene a
grete sekk fu&llbar; of barlie.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXCI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Orantes illuduntur a demonibus.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patru&mtail;' how o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;e
devu&llbar; sai&dtail; vnto &thorn;e Abbott Macharie; "Go we vnto
gaderyng samen of ou&rtail; brethir."  And he aski&dtail; hy&mtail;
what he had at do with &thorn;e gaderyng samen of &thorn;aim, and
&thorn;e fend ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;;
"Knowis &thorn;ou not at withoute&ntail; vs &thorn;er is no gaderyng?
Co&mtail; and &thorn;ou sa&llbar; se ou&rtail; besynes."  And he went
with hy&mtail; &amp; saw, &amp; &thorn;er was a&llbar; &thorn;e
kur&ktee; our as it had bene litty&llbar; me&ntail; of Ynde, &amp;
let &thorn;e monkis to make &thorn;er prayers, &amp; turnyd &thorn;aim
in womme&ntail; liknes &amp; made &thorn;aim thynke o&ntail;
&thorn;aim, &amp; samen &thorn;ai garte slepe &amp; be wery of
&thorn;er prayers.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;is holie ma&ntail; saw
&thorn;at, he made his prayers vnto God, &amp; sodanlie &thorn;ai
vanyshi&dtail; away.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Oracionibus iuuantur morientes.  Supra de morte,
xix.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Oracio predonis ei vitam prolongat.  Infra de
remuneracione, viij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>

<PB N="393">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXCII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Oracione reuocatur ab inferis dampnatus.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Gestis Beati Gregorij' how o&ntail; a tyme as Saynt
Grego&rtail; walkid befo&rtail; &thorn;e palace of Traia&ntail; and
vmthoght hy&mtail; of his mekenes, he bega&ntail; to fa&llbar;
opo&ntail; a sore wepyng.  And he prayed hy&mtail; so long for
hy&mtail; at Saynt Petur alta&rtail;, wepyng &amp; makyng sorow, vnto
a voyce spak vnto hy&mtail; &amp; say&dtail;, &thorn;at Traiay&ntail;
&thorn;urgh his prayers was delyver&dtail; oute of &thorn;e pay&ntail;
of he&llbar;; bod it bad hy&mtail; at fro thens furt&hbar; he sulde
bewar, &amp; not presume hy&mtail; to pray for none vncristend
ma&ntail; &thorn;at was dampne&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXCIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ordinacio dei non potest impediri.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Cronicles' &thorn;at in &thorn;e yere of ou&rtail;
Lorde M &lbar; XV, the erle &thorn;at was calli&dtail; Corandus <NOTE ID="P393.N1">Lat. MSS. Conradus.</NOTE> , beyng fer&dtail; o&ntail; a tyme for &thorn;e
emperow&rtail; wret&hbar;, ffled with his wife in-to a wudd, &amp;
&thorn;er he hid hy&mtail; in a tufa&llbar;.  So &thorn;e Emperour
happen&dtail; o&ntail; a tyme to co&mtail; to &thorn;is wud o&ntail;
huntyng, &amp; folowi&dtail; a dere so lang at it was nyght, &amp; he
cuthe fynd none of his meneya; so hy&mtail; happen&dtail; co&mtail; to
&thorn;is tofa&llbar;.  Bod &thorn;e Erle was gone &amp; &thorn;e
ladie was &thorn;er be hur one, grete with childe; so hy&mtail; burde
nedis be herberd &thorn;er &thorn;at nyght &amp; sho, als i&llbar; as
sho myght, made hy&mtail; a be&dtail;.  &amp; &thorn;at nyght sho
travel&dtail; &amp; was delyver&dtail; of a so&ntail;, and whe&ntail;
&thorn;e childe was bor&ntail; &thorn;e emperour har&dtail; a voyce
say vnto &thorn;e childe; "Childe! &thorn;is emperour sa&llbar; be
&thorn;i fadyr-in-lay."  And vpo&ntail; &thorn;e mor&ntail; &thorn;e
Emperour rase &amp; went his wais, &amp; commandi&dtail; ij of his
squeyers to feche &thorn;is childe in &thorn;e wu&dtail;, &amp; for to
sla itt &amp; bryng hy&mtail; &thorn;e harte &thorn;eroff.  And
whe&ntail; &thorn;ai saw &thorn;is childe &thorn;ai had
compassio&ntail; &thorn;ero&ntail;, and &thorn;ai gat a hare &amp;
tuke &thorn;e harte &thorn;erof, &amp; broght it vnto &thorn;e
emperour, and lefte &thorn;e childe lygan&dtail; in &thorn;e wudd.
&amp; onone after &thorn;er come a duke &amp; fand &thorn;is childe,
and he sent it home vnto his wyfe becauce he had no childe hy&mtail;
selfe, and bad &thorn;aim te&llbar; hur



<PB N="394">

at he had gette&ntail; it, &amp; bad name it Henrie.  So whe&ntail;
&thorn;is chylde was waxe&ntail; he was fayr &amp; semely &amp;
wele-spoke&ntail;, and passand gracious.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e
emperour saw at &thorn;is childe was fayr &amp; wyse, he tuke
hy&mtail; into his cowrte.  So o&ntail; a tyme he keste in his mynde a
dowte whe&thorn;er &thorn;is was &thorn;e childe at he
commaundi&dtail; to sla or nay.  And he thoght he wolde be sekur, and
he garte make a lettre vnto his wyfe in &thorn;is maner of wyse; "As
&thorn;ou luffis &thorn;i lyfe, onone as &thorn;ou hase red &thorn;is
lettre sla &thorn;is childe"; &amp; he sent &thorn;is childe with
&thorn;e same letter.  So as he went vnto &thorn;e whenewar&dtail;
hy&mtail; happen&dtail; co&mtail; into a kurk, &amp; he was werie
forgone &amp; leny&dtail; hy&mtail; dow&ntail; &amp; fe&llbar;
o&ntail; slepe; &amp; his purs at &thorn;e lettyr was in hang oute of
his boso&mtail;.  So &thorn;er come a preste &amp; fande hy&mtail;
&amp; opynd his purs &amp; luki&dtail; &thorn;e letter, and hy&mtail;
vgged with &thorn;e wykkydnes at was &thorn;er-in, &amp; he skrapid
oute, " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">puerum hunc necabis,</FOREIGN>" &amp; sett
in &thorn;ies wurdis; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">puero filiam meam
dabis.</FOREIGN>" And so he went furt&hbar; with &thorn;is lettre
&amp; he was wele welcom&dtail;; and onone he wed &thorn;e Emperours
doghter.  So whe&ntail; &thorn;e Emperour come home &amp; saw how it
was, ffro he wiste &thorn;at he was ane erle so&ntail; his sorow
bega&ntail; to slake.  And he made meku&llbar; off hy&mtail;, &amp;
after whe&ntail; &thorn;e Emperour was dea&dtail; he was made
Emperour.  And in &thorn;e place &thorn;er he was bor&ntail; he byggid
a wurthie abbay.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXCIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ornatus immoderatus corporis dampnacionis est
causa.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Libro de Dono Timoris' how som tyme &thorn;er was a
holie ladie in Fraunce.  So o&ntail; a tyme sho was ravysshi&dtail; in
hur spirutt and sho saw a cowntas dead &thorn;at sho was passan&dtail;
familiarie with, and sho saw hur drawe&ntail; with fendis vnto
he&llbar;.  And sho made grete sorow, &amp; crie&dtail; &amp;
sai&dtail;; "Allas!  Allas!  I sary wric&hbar;, I was chastie
enog&hbar; &amp; a grete almos-deler, &amp; I a&mtail; now
dampny&dtail; &amp; for none o&thorn;er &thorn;ing bod for varios
&amp; prowde arayment &thorn;at I luffi&dtail; passan&dtail; wele;
&amp; whe&ntail; I was snybbe&dtail; &thorn;erfo&rtail; yitt I wolde
not lefe it <NOTE ID="P394.N1"><HI REND="i">This and the following tale are marked</HI> Nota.</NOTE> ."



<PB N="395">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXCV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ornatus immoderatus causa est exultacionis
demonum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a preste at hight
Catus, &amp; o&ntail; a tyme he saw a womma&ntail; co&mtail; fro
&thorn;e kur&ktee;, &amp; he met hur at &thorn;e kur&ktee;-dure.
&amp; sho was gaylie atyri&dtail; in cowrchevis, and sho had a
passan&dtail; lang tayle folowan&dtail; hur, and &thorn;er was
&thorn;er-vppo&ntail; dawnsand a huge multitude of fendis, as it had
bene blak me&ntail; of Ynde, skornan&dtail; with &thorn;er mowthes
an&dtail; clappand with &thorn;er handis.  And &thorn;ai war als thykk
as it had bene fyss&hbar; in a nett.  So he commaundy&dtail; a&llbar;
&thorn;e peple to stand sty&llbar;, and he coniuri&dtail; &thorn;ies
fendis at &thorn;ai sulde nott go away, &amp; he made his prayer &amp;
besoght God att &thorn;e peple myght se &thorn;aim; &amp; so
&thorn;ai di&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;is womma&ntail; saw at
&thorn;e fendis had so meku&llbar; power o&ntail; hur for &thorn;e
pryde of hur clothyng, &amp; at &thorn;e peple yrkid for to luke
o&ntail; hur, sho went home and skyfti&dtail; hur clothyng &amp; wold
neuer were tayle after.  And bathe vnto hur and a&llbar; o&thorn;er at
say &thorn;is visio&ntail; it was ane occasio&ntail; of mekenes, &amp;
at &thorn;ai sulde neuer after vse prowde clothyng.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Ornare se potest mulier interdum per virum.  Infra

de vxore, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXCVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ornatus vestium non debet esse nimis
sumptuosus.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Helynandus tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a kyng in
Ynglan&dtail; &thorn;at hight Gillelmus, and he wolde were no clothyng
bod of a huge price; and if it war light of price, &amp; it war neuer
so gude, he wol&dtail; hafe grete dedey&ntail; &thorn;er-att.  So on a
tyme hys chamberlay&ntail; did o&ntail; hy&mtail; a payr of new hose,
and he axki&dtail; hy&mtail; what &thorn;ai coste, &amp; he say&dtail;
iij <ABBR EXPAN="shelyng">s</ABBR>; and he grynny&dtail; &amp; had
grete dedy&ntail; &thorn;eratt &amp; sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;;
"&thorn;ou hureso&ntail;!  Wha&rtail; saw &thorn;ou evur kyng were
hose off so vile a price?  Go," he say&dtail;, "faste, &amp; bryng me
a payr of a marke price."  And he went furt&hbar; &amp; broght
hy&mtail; a payr &thorn;at was meku&llbar; better &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;e toder, bod he made a lee of &thorn;e price of &thorn;aim.
And

<PB N="396">

whe&ntail; &thorn;e kyng saw &thorn;aim he sai&dtail;; "Ya, thies
acordis vnto a kyng to were."  And fro &thorn;at tyme evur
afterwar&dtail; his chawmberlay&ntail; telli&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;e
price of his clothyng as hy&mtail; lyste, and as it plesi&dtail;
hy&mtail;.  And bod if he sai&dtail; it coste meku&llbar; he wold not
were it.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Ornatus vestium quandoque eleuat cor hominis in

superbiam.  Supra de augurio, ij 
<NOTE ID="P396.N1">MS. iij.</NOTE> .</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXCVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Paciencia.  Paciens eciam ab inferioribus suis
iniurias tollit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Iero&mtail; tellis how Socrates had ij wyfis, &amp; oft
sithes ather of &thorn;aim wol&dtail; flite with other, &amp; evur he
wolde do bod scor&ntail; &thorn;aim.  And att &thorn;e laste &thorn;ai
wex bothe wrothe with hy&mtail; &amp; calli&dtail; hy&mtail;
bellu&dtail; chule, &amp; sai&dtail; his nease droppi&dtail; &amp; his
ee&ntail; ra&ntail;, and &thorn;e harys on his browis war lyke
swyne-brustyls.  And &thorn;us &thorn;ai made hy&mtail; fay&ntail; fle
fro &thorn;aim &amp; leve &thorn;aim be &thorn;er one.  And a
ma&ntail; axki&dtail; hy&mtail; whi he wol&dtail; not bete &thorn;aim,
and he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail; &thorn;at womman,
ay &thorn;e mo&rtail; sho was bett, &thorn;e wars was sho.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
