</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXCVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Paciens bonum pro malo reddit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Gestis Iohannis Elemosinarij' how o&ntail; a tyme
whe&ntail; a cussy&ntail; of his had a grete wrang of a tavurner,
&amp; whe&ntail; he made playnt vnto &thorn;e patriarke, he mott gett
no comfurt&hbar;, and &thorn;e patryarke said vnto hy&mtail;; "Who is
he att dar gaynsay &thorn;e or oppy&ntail; his mouthe agayns &thorn;e?
Truste, so&ntail;, vnto me, &thorn;at I sha&llbar; do to-day vnto
hy&mtail; suche a thyng &thorn;at a&llbar; Alexandria sa&llbar; hafe
merve&llbar; &thorn;eroff."  And whe&ntail; he har&dtail; &thorn;is he
tuke a grete comfurt&hbar;, &amp; trowi&dtail; &thorn;at he wol&dtail;
gar hy&mtail; be grevuslie bety&ntail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail;
whe&ntail; Ioh&ntail; saw he tuke a grete comfurt&hbar;, he
kyssi&dtail; his breste &amp; sai&dtail;; "So&ntail;, &amp; &thorn;ou
will be cussy&ntail; vnto my mekenes, &thorn;ou bus make &thorn;e to
be bety&ntail; &amp; suff&rtail; stryfe &amp; debate of ilka
ma&ntail;, for a trew thoght is nowder of fless&hbar; nor blude, bod
it is knowy&ntail; of trewt&hbar; of &thorn;e myn&dtail;."  &amp;
onone &thorn;ai sent for &thorn;is ma&ntail;, and he made hy&mtail;
fre of al maner of tributt &amp; pensio&ntail;.  And a&llbar;
&thorn;at evur har&dtail; &thorn;is had grete mervayle and vnderstude
what he ment whe&ntail; he say&dtail;; "I sa&llbar; do vnto hy&mtail;
suche a thyng &thorn;at a&llbar; Alexandria sha&llbar; hafe
merve&llbar; &thorn;eroff."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DXCIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pacientes iniuste deus in fine eciam in hac vita
honorat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Legen&dtail; Longabardica' of ane &thorn;at hight
Theodora, a noble womma&ntail; &amp; a fay&rtail;, &thorn;at had a
husband at Alexander in tyme of Zenonis &thorn;e Emperour; and hur
husband was a gud ma&ntail; &amp; a riche, and dowti&dtail; Go&dtail;.
So &thorn;er was a yong ma&ntail; &thorn;at wex passand ameros of hur
and begylid hur be &thorn;e mene of ane alde wyfe, &thorn;at tolde hur
at Godd knew not &thorn;at at was done o&ntail; &thorn;e nyght, bod
alonelie &thorn;at at was done o&ntail; &thorn;e day.  And &thorn;us
sho

<PB N="398">

made hur to latt &thorn;e ma&ntail; lygg by hur.  So afterwar&dtail;,
whe&ntail; sho come to hur selfe, &amp; feli&dtail; at sho had done
wrong and at God knew a&llbar; maner of &thorn;ing &thorn;at was done,
sho wepi&dtail; &amp; made muc&hbar; sorow &amp; garte cut hur
hea&dtail;, &amp; gatt hur mans clothyng of hur husbandis &amp; did it
o&ntail; hur &amp; went vnto ane abbay far thens &amp; made hur a
mon&ktee;, &amp; say&dtail; hur name was Theodorus.  &amp; &thorn;er
sho liffi&dtail; a gude haly lyfe and did meracles.  So o&ntail; a
tyme hur <NOTE ID="P398.N1">MS. hym.</NOTE> happen&dtail; to be hosti&dtail; with
his camels at sho drafe vnto &thorn;e cetie be &thorn;e commandment of
&thorn;e abbott, at a mans howse &thorn;at had a fayr doghter; and on
&thorn;e night sho come vnto &thorn;is Theodora &amp; wol&dtail; have
lyggy&ntail; with hur, &amp; sho wol&dtail; not latt hur.  So with-in
a while after &thorn;is wenche was with bar&ntail;, and sho sai&dtail;
at &thorn;is Theodora had getty&ntail; itt; and hur abbott gretelie
blamy&dtail; hur &thorn;erfo&rtail;, and whe&ntail; &thorn;e childe
was bor&ntail; it was broght &amp; lay&dtail; in hur skurte.  And sho
&amp; it was putt furt&hbar; of &thorn;e abbay for vij yere, and with
mylke &amp; swilk as sho cuthe gett [sho nurisshid it].  And in
&thorn;is menewhile sho was gretlie tempy&dtail; with &thorn;e
devu&llbar; to sy&ntail;, bod he prevaylid not o&ntail; hur.  And
whe&ntail; vij yere was gone &thorn;e abbott consydur&dtail; hur
paciens &amp; tuke bothe hur &amp; &thorn;e childe in agay&ntail;.
And &thorn;er sho &amp; it to-gedur was spary&dtail; samen in a
ce&llbar;.  And &thorn;er with-in ij yere to-gedur sho passi&dtail;
vnto Go&dtail;; and yit sho had enformy&dtail; &thorn;is chil&dtail;
or sho dye&dtail; in lernyng &amp; in holie liffyng to persevur.  And
&thorn;at night at sho dyed, &thorn;e Abbott &thorn;oght at he saw
a&llbar; &thorn;e ordurs of Aungels &amp; Patriarkis &amp; Prophettis
&amp; a&llbar; Saynttis co&mtail; &amp; feche hur sawle vnto
hevy&ntail;; &amp; hy&mtail; thoght &thorn;ai made grete ioy.  And
&thorn;er was a voyce at say&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "&thorn;is
Theodorus was falsly accusi&dtail; of &thorn;is childe-gettyng."  And
with &thorn;at &thorn;e Abbott waken&dtail; an&dtail; calli&dtail; vp
his brether, and went vnto hur ce&llbar; &amp; fan&dtail; hur
dea&dtail;; and whe&ntail; &thorn;ai naken&dtail; hur &thorn;ai
fan&dtail; sho was a womma&ntail;. And he garte ca&llbar; &thorn;e
wenche fadur &amp; sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "Lo! now, whethur he
this corrupte &thorn;i doghter or nay."  And a&llbar; me&ntail; had
wonder he&rtail;-of.  So &thorn;er come a voyce vnto &thorn;e Abbot
&amp; ba&dtail; hy&mtail; go in-to &thorn;e cetie.  And so he did,
&amp; &thorn;er mett hy&mtail; a ma&ntail;, and he axki&dtail;
hy&mtail; whyter he was bow&ntail;.  And he sai&dtail;; "My wyfe is
dea&dtail; &amp; I go to se hur."  And &thorn;e Abbott &amp; he went
samen



<PB N="399">

wepan&dtail;, and with grete devocio&ntail; &thorn;ai bery&dtail; hur.
And &thorn;a&ntail; hur husban&dtail; made hy&mtail; monke &amp;
dwelte in hur ce&llbar;, &amp; was a gude ma&ntail; evur whils
&thorn;at he liffi&dtail;.  And &thorn;is childe persevur&dtail; in
gude warkis &amp; was made a monk in &thorn;at same place.  And
afterwar&dtail;, whe&ntail; &thorn;e Abbott was dead, he was
chosy&ntail; vnto Abbott.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DC.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Paciens vilia a vilibus personis tolerat
<NOTE ID="P399.N1">MS. tollerat.</NOTE>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Gestis Alexij' &thorn;at &thorn;is Alexius was
&thorn;e so&ntail; of Eufemia&ntail; at was a wurthi offesur in
&thorn;e Emperour ha&llbar;, and he was made rewler of iij M &lbar;
childir at wer a&llbar; cled in sylk &amp; had gurdils of gol&dtail;.
And &thorn;is Eufemya&ntail; &amp; Aglaes <NOTE ID="P399.N2">MS. Alglaes, <HI REND="i">with the first</HI> l <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> his
wyfe war passan&dtail; mercyfu&llbar; &amp; fu&llbar; of gude werkis;
and &thorn;ai had no childe bod &thorn;is Alexius, and hy&mtail;
&thorn;ai marye&dtail; vnto a wurthie womma&ntail; of &thorn;e
emperou&rtail; howsol&dtail;.  So vppo&ntail; &thorn;e nyght after
&thorn;ai war we&dtail;, he desyri&dtail; his wyfe to kepe hur in
clene virginytie.  And whe&ntail; sho had graunti&dtail; hy&mtail;, he
lefte hur a gol&dtail; ryng and a bygyrdy&llbar; fu&llbar; of
gol&dtail;, and went privalie away fro&mtail; hyr &amp; fled far thens
into Syrie, vnto &thorn;e cetie of Egissa&mtail;, wha&rtail; &thorn;er
is ane ymage of oure Lor&dtail; &thorn;at nevur was made be mans
han&dtail;.  &amp; &thorn;er he come in-to ane almos howse at was
calli&dtail; Syndo, &amp; &thorn;er he satt in ane entry emang pure
me&ntail;, &amp; liffi&dtail; of almos &thorn;at was giffe&ntail;
&thorn;aim.  And his ffadur sent me&ntail; &thorn;urg&hbar; a&llbar;
&thorn;is werl&dtail; to seke hy&mtail;.  So one of &thorn;aim at
soght hy&mtail; come &thorn;urg&hbar; &thorn;is entry &amp; gaff
hy&mtail; almos, and he knew hy&mtail; wele enog&hbar;, bod he knew
not hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;
selfe; "Lor&dtail;, I thanke The at &THORN;ou hase made me to reseyfe
almos of myne aw&ntail; servan&dtail;."  So a&llbar; &thorn;ies
messangers come agay&ntail; &amp; tolde his fadur &thorn;ai cuthe not
fynde hy&mtail;, and he &amp; his wyfe &amp; his doghter made
meku&llbar; sorow for hy&mtail;.  An&dtail; whe&ntail; he had bene in
&thorn;is hospita&llbar; xviij yere in pouertie &amp; in Goddis
serves, &thorn;e ymage of ou&rtail; Ladie spak vnto hy&mtail;
&thorn;at kepi&dtail; &thorn;e kur&ktee;, &amp; sai&dtail;; "Make
&thorn;e ma&ntail; of Almyghti God to co&mtail; in, for he is wurthie
&thorn;e kyngdo&mtail; of hevy&ntail;."  And &thorn;is keper wiste not
whome sho





<PB N="400">

ment off, and sho sai&dtail;; "He &thorn;at is withoute &thorn;e dure,
&thorn;at is he."  And whe&ntail; he was broght in &amp; &thorn;is was
knowe&ntail; vnto a&llbar; his felows, &thorn;ai bega&ntail; to
wurshup&ptail;, and he saw &thorn;at &amp; fled away fro &thorn;aim
&amp; gatt ou&rtail; &thorn;e see.  And as God wol&dtail;, hy&mtail;
happyn&dtail; to lan&dtail; at Rome, and whe&ntail; he conseyvi&dtail;
&thorn;at he sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; selfe; "I sa&llbar; ga
dwe&llbar; vnknowe&ntail; in my fadurs hows, and I sa&llbar; bere no
grete coste of hy&mtail;."  So he come vnto his fadur place &amp;
say&dtail; vnto his ffadur whe&ntail; he mett hy&mtail;; "Thow
servan&dtail; of Almyghti Go&dtail;, take me into &thorn;i howse at I
may liff of &thorn;e crombis commys fro &thorn;i bur&dtail;, for
&thorn;i so&ntail; sawle &thorn;at was a pylgra&mtail;."  And he tuke
hy&mtail; in for his so&ntail; sake, &amp; commandi&dtail; hy&mtail;
into a place in his howse, &amp; gaff hy&mtail; meate euerilk day
fro&mtail; his aw&ntail; bur&dtail;, &amp; made hy&mtail; his
aw&ntail; servand.  And he di&dtail; a&llbar; &thorn;ing &thorn;at
evur any bodye bad hy&mtail;, &amp; none knew hy&mtail;, ffor with
fastyng &amp; with wakyng he made hym selfe lene and oute of knowlege,
and he&rtail;-fo&rtail; &thorn;e servandes of &thorn;e howse wolde
skor&ntail; hy&mtail;, &amp; stryke hy&mtail;, &amp; pow&rtail; watyr
at &thorn;ai had wasshi&dtail; vesse&llbar; in vppo&ntail; his
hea&dtail;; and a&llbar; &thorn;is he suffre&dtail; xvij yere &amp;
nevur was knowe&ntail;.  So at &thorn;e laste he knew be
reuelacio&ntail; at his dead drew nere, and he wrate a&llbar; &thorn;e
cowrs of his lyfe in a grete ro&llbar;.  And vppo&ntail; &thorn;e
Sononday at evy&ntail; &thorn;er was a voyce har&dtail; in &thorn;e
kur&ktee; at Rome, &thorn;at sai&dtail;; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Venite
ad me omnes qui laboratis et onerati estis, et ego [refficiam
uos].</FOREIGN>" And a&llbar; &thorn;at har&dtail; it fe&llbar;
dow&ntail; o&ntail; &thorn;er kneis &amp; had grete merve&llbar;
&thorn;eroff.  And &thorn;a&ntail; it sai&dtail; agay&ntail;; "Go,
seke &thorn;e seruan&dtail; of God, at he may pray for Rome."  And
&thorn;ai soght hy&mtail; &amp; cuthe not fynde hy&mtail;.  So
&thorn;ai har&dtail; it say agay&ntail; &thorn;at he was in &thorn;e
howse of Eufemya&ntail;; and &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e pope and
&thorn;e imperour, a bissho&ptail; &amp; ane archdeky&ntail; come vnto
&thorn;is mans howse and desyri&dtail; to se &thorn;is pure ma&ntail;
&amp; bad hy&mtail; luke graythelie whethir it war his so&ntail; or
nay, for he was a ma&ntail; of gude life &amp; of grete pacyens.  And
Eufemianus ra&ntail; in-to &thorn;e howse vnto hy&mtail; and fand
hy&mtail; dea&dtail;, and his face shane as it had bene ane
ange&llbar;.  And he had a ro&llbar; in his han&dtail;, &amp;
Eufemya&ntail; wolde hafe taky&ntail; it &amp; sene it, &amp; he
wol&dtail; not latt it goo; bod whe&ntail; &thorn;e pope come he lete
it go alredy.  And whe&ntail; it was red befo&rtail; his fadur, at
a&llbar; &thorn;e peple har&dtail;, his fadur wex nerehan&dtail; mad
&amp; drew of &thorn;e hare of his hea&dtail; &amp; of his ber&dtail;,
&amp; fe&llbar; dow&ntail;

<PB N="401">

vppo&ntail; &thorn;e body of his so&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "A!
so&ntail;, fu&llbar; wo is me &thorn;at I se &thorn;e &thorn;us lygg
in a bed&dtail; &amp; may not speke vnto me."  And &thorn;a&ntail; his
moder come, &amp; whe&ntail; sho saw hy&mtail; sho swony&dtail; &amp;
made grete wepyng &amp; sai&dtail;; "Allas! so&ntail;, whi did
&thorn;ou so vnto vs, &thorn;at whe&ntail; &thorn;ou saw &thorn;i
fadur &amp; me wepe for ow&rtail; so&ntail; &thorn;ou wolde neuer shew
&thorn;e vnto vs? &thorn;ine aw&ntail; servandis hat&hbar; done
&thorn;e grete wrong, &amp; &thorn;ou hase evur suffyr&dtail; it."
&amp; evur sho swony&dtail; &amp; crye&dtail; &amp; made meku&llbar;
sorow, &amp; say&dtail;; "A&llbar; &thorn;at bene here, I pray you
wepe with me, ffor xvij yere I hafe had myne aw&ntail; so&ntail; in my
howse daylie, &amp; knew hy&mtail; noght."  And &thorn;a&ntail; his
wyfe come &amp; made &thorn;e maste sorow of a&llbar;.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e pope, &thorn;e Emperour, &thorn;e
bissho&ptail; &amp; &thorn;e archedeky&ntail; tuke vp his body
o&ntail; a bere, &amp; bare it o&ntail; &thorn;er aw&ntail; shuldres
vnto &thorn;e berya&llbar;; &amp; &thorn;ai myght nott pass away
&thorn;er-with, ffor nerehan&dtail; a&llbar; Rome was gadur&dtail;
&thorn;edur, &amp; &thorn;e peple was passan&dtail; thrang.  And
&thorn;ai garte caste golde &amp; syluer by &thorn;e way at peple
sulde be besy &thorn;er aboute &amp; so lat &thorn;aim pas, bod
&thorn;e peple luki&dtail; nowder after &thorn;e gol&dtail; nor yit
&thorn;e sylver, bod evur was besy abowtewar&dtail; for to tuche his
bodye.  So at &thorn;e laste with grete labur &thorn;ai broght
hy&mtail; vnto his grafe.  And &thorn;er &thorn;e peple abade vij
dayes &amp; made grete lovyng vnto Almyghti God.  &amp; &thorn;er [he]
was beri&dtail; &amp; his grafe coverd with golde and precious stonys;
and fro his body &thorn;er come a passyng gude odur.  And he dyed xvij
Kalends of Auguste, in &thorn;e yere of our Lor&dtail; CCC xviij.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Paciens in amissione membrorum pacienter tolerat 
<!-- P401.N1 --> .

Infra de oculo, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Paciens eciam mortem pro deo tolerat 
<NOTE ID="P401.N1">MS. tollerat.</NOTE> .  Supra de

martirio.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Paganus aliquando bonas leges condit.  Supra de

lege, j.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Papa.  Papa mulier creatur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Cronicles' how som tyme &thorn;er was a yong
damyse&llbar;, and a luff of hurs went away with hur &amp; broght hur
in mans



<PB N="402">

clothyng vnto Rome; and &thorn;er sho went vnto &thorn;e scule and wex
so parfyte in connyng &thorn;at sho had no make in a&llbar; Rome.  So
att &thorn;e laste, be ane hole consent, sho was chosy&ntail; to be
pope and was made pope.  And whe&ntail; sho was pope hur luff lay with
hur &amp; gatt hur with chylde, so he wiste not at sho was with childe
to sho was evy&ntail; at travellyng <NOTE ID="P402.N1">Harl. MS. verum autem partum ignorans, cum de Sancto Petro, &amp;c.</NOTE> .  So hur
happen&dtail; o&ntail; a day to co&mtail; in processio&ntail; fro
Saynt Peturs vnto Saynt Ioh&ntail; Latarenens, and &thorn;er sho
bega&ntail; at trave&llbar;, and bare hur chylde betwix Colliseum
&amp; Saynt Clemett kur&ktee;; &amp; &thorn;er sho dye&dtail;, &amp;
&thorn;er &thorn;ai beri&dtail; hur.  And becauce of &thorn;at
detestable dea&dtail;, &thorn;e pope vsi&dtail; neuer syne to
co&mtail; &thorn;er-away with processio&ntail;, and here-for hur name
is not putt emang other popes namys in the Martiloge.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Papa per diaboli procuracionem creatur.  Supra de

ambicione.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Papa multipliciter dehonestatur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Cronicles' of one &thorn;at hight Formosus, at was
furste a cardyna&llbar; &amp; syne pope.  And pope Ioh&ntail;
cursy&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; degradid hy&mtail; agay&ntail; vnto the
lay astate, and made hy&mtail; swere &thorn;at he sulde nevur
co&mtail; in Rome, nor desyre nor take &thorn;e papeshu&ptail;
o&ntail; han&dtail;.  Neuer-&thorn;e-les after-war&dtail;, of
&thorn;is pope Joh&ntail; successour he was asoyli&dtail;, &amp;
restori&dtail; to co&mtail; agay&ntail; vnto Rome; and he tuke
&thorn;e popeshu&ptail; agay&ntail; on han&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; he
was dede, Stephanus VI garte take his bodye, &amp; doff a&llbar;
&thorn;e his pope clothyng &amp; clethe hy&mtail; in lay wede, &amp;
garte cutt of <NOTE ID="P402.N2">Harl. MS. et duobus digitis dextere abscisis, manu priuauit, et eam in Tiberim iactari precepit.</NOTE> ij of hy[s] fyngers of ather
han&dtail; &amp; cutt of bothe his handis &amp; keste hy&mtail; into
Tybur.  So vnto &thorn;is Stephan succedid Joh&ntail;, and he
reprovi&dtail; a&llbar; &thorn;e warkis off Stephan, &amp;
provi&dtail; &thorn;e warkis of &thorn;is Formosius.  Tha&ntail; after
hy&mtail; come Sergius III, &amp; he garte take Formosius oute off his
grafe &amp; vnordur&dtail; a&llbar; &thorn;at he had gyffe&ntail;
ordurs to, &amp; garte caste hy&mtail; in Tybur.  And ffysshers
happen&dtail; at ffyn&dtail; hy&mtail; in &thorn;er nettis, &amp;
&thorn;ai broght hy&mtail;







<PB N="403">

into Saynt Peturs; and whe&ntail; &thorn;ai broght hy&mtail; in,
a&llbar; &thorn;e ymagis in &thorn;e kurk, att a&llbar; me&ntail;
myght se, as he come by &thorn;aim lowti&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; &amp;
wurshuppi&dtail; hy&mtail;. And here-by &thorn;ai wyste he was a gude
ma&ntail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Papa bonus.  Supra de Gregorio.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Pape possunt adaptari multa que infra dicuntur 
<NOTE ID="P403.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, infra <HI REND="i">after</HI> dicuntur.</NOTE>  de

prelato, et supra de morte.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Paradisus.  Paradisi disposicio.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Gregur tellis how som ty&mtail; at Rome &thorn;er was a
knyght &thorn;at fe&llbar; seke, &amp; was evy&ntail; bow&ntail; to
dye &amp; lay in a trans.  And whe&ntail; he come agay&ntail; vnto
hy&mtail; selfe, he sai&dtail; &thorn;at he saw a bryg, and
vndernet&hbar; it ra&ntail; a grete blak watur at keste owte
intollerable savurs &amp; stynkis.  And whe&ntail; he was passi&dtail;
&thorn;is brygg, o&ntail; &thorn;e toder syde of &thorn;is watyr was
fayr medows &amp; grene, &amp; fu&llbar; of gude flowris wele
savuran&dtail;.  And &thorn;er he saw a grete company of white
me&ntail; in albys; and &thorn;er was suche a gude savur emang
&thorn;aim at &thorn;ai war saciatt &amp; fulfylli&dtail;
&thorn;er-with as it had bene with meate or dryn&ktee;.  &amp;
&thorn;er he saw dyvers mansions for evure ma&ntail;, at war fu&llbar;
of grete light.  And &thorn;er was byggi&dtail; a howse, and a&llbar;
&thorn;e sydis &thorn;eroff wer off fyne gol&dtail;, for he cuthe not
wytt whose it was.  And &thorn;er was many habitacles apo&ntail;
&thorn;e banke of the same watir; and he sai&dtail; he saw many
o&ntail; &thorn;is brygg &thorn;at, &thorn;urg&hbar; felyng of &thorn;e
i&llbar; savur o&ntail; &thorn;e watur, &thorn;ai fe&llbar; in-to itt.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Parentes frequenter visitare non expedit religiosis.

Supra de affectu carnali.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Parentes debent filij honorare.  Supra de honore, j.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Parentes non debent filijs maledicere.  Infra de

Stephano.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Parentes sunt relinquendi perfectis.  Infra de

relinquere.
</FOREIGN>


<PB N="404">
</ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Paruulus male disciplinatus eciam deum blasfemans

dampnatur.  Supra de blasfemia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Patris necligencia circa correccionem filiorum

frequenter est ipsis filijs in detrimentum.  Supra

de blasfemia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Pater filios 
<NOTE ID="P404.N1">So Latin version. English MS. has liberos.</NOTE>  instruere debet.  Supra de ffilia, j.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Patriarchia.  Infra de veste.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pauli Apostoli.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in his legen&dtail; how o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; Pawle
was hosti&dtail; att &thorn;e Ile of Mustela&ntail;, &thorn;er come
ane erdur in-to his skurte and hurte hy&mtail; noght, &amp; he keste
it in &thorn;e fyre.  &amp; &thorn;e gude ma&ntail; was wrothe, ffor
a&llbar; &thorn;at evur was bor&ntail; of the kynre&dtail; of
&thorn;at perso&ntail; at he was at hoste with was neuer hurte with
&thorn;ase venomos bestis.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;er childer war
bor&ntail;, &thorn;ai wolde put &thorn;ies serpentis in &thorn;e
creduls with &thorn;aim, at &thorn;ai mot prufe whethur &thorn;ai wer
&thorn;er trew fadurs or nay.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Paulus velum restituit Plautille.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede of Saynt Pawle &thorn;at whe&ntail; he went vnto his
passio&ntail;, Plautilla, at was his disciple, delyver&dtail;
hy&mtail; hur curchyff to wype &thorn;e swete of his face, &amp; to
covur his ee&ntail; in &thorn;e how&rtail; of his passio&ntail;.
An&dtail; whe&ntail; &thorn;e turmaturs smate of his hea&dtail;,
evy&ntail; in &thorn;e strake he tuke &thorn;is curchyff an&dtail;
<NOTE ID="P404.N2">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, and.</NOTE> gadur&dtail; &thorn;erin a&llbar; his aw&ntail;
blude.  And he wappi&dtail; [it] samen [&amp; gaff it] vnto &thorn;is
Plautille <NOTE ID="P404.N3">Harl. MS. Paulus in ipso ictu uelum explicuit, et in eo sanguinem proprium collegit, obuoluit, et tradidit Plautille.</NOTE> .  Whe&ntail; &thorn;e turmatur was
gone, &thorn;is Ploatty&llbar; mett hy&mtail; &amp; axki&dtail;
hy&mtail; whare he had done hur maister Pawle, and he tel&dtail; hur
&thorn;at he lay









<PB N="405">

with his felow dea&dtail; with-oute &thorn;e cetie.  And sho
sai&dtail; agay&ntail; vnto hy&mtail;; "Petur &amp; Pawle is gone
in-to &thorn;e cetie, &amp; fayr crownys vppo&ntail; &thorn;er hedis,
&amp; &thorn;ai er cled in gay clothyng."  &amp; sho tuke furt&hbar;
hur curchiff fu&llbar; <NOTE ID="P405.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, fu&llbar;.</NOTE> of blude &amp;
shewi&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; many o&thorn;er.  And herefo&rtail; many
folke become crysten&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pauli caput proprio corpori post mortem per se
coniungitur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Dionisius tellis how &thorn;at many yeris after &thorn;e
passio&ntail; of Saynt Pawle, his <NOTE ID="P405.N2">MS. he.</NOTE> head was
fo&ntail; i&ntail; &thorn;e felde with a hur&dtail;-ma&ntail;, &amp;
he sett it v&ptail; o&ntail; a rod&dtail;.  &amp; oppo&ntail; &thorn;e
nyght a grete light shane &thorn;er-oppo&ntail; fro hevy&ntail;; and
whe&ntail; &thorn;e pope har&dtail; te&llbar; of &thorn;is, he tuke
&thorn;e hede &amp; lai&dtail; it at Saynt Paule fete.  And, at
meku&llbar; pepu&llbar; saw, &thorn;e body of Saynt Pawle rase &amp;
turny&dtail; it, &amp; ionyd in vnto &thorn;e hede; &amp; meku&llbar;
pepu&llbar; had grete mervayle &thorn;eroff.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Pauli primi 
<NOTE ID="P405.N3">MS. prime.</NOTE>  heremite.  Paulus honorat hospitem 
<NOTE ID="P405.N4"><HI REND="i">So</HI> Latin MSS. The English MS. <HI REND="i">has</HI> hostem.</NOTE> 

suum.  Supra de honore, iij 
<NOTE ID="P405.N5">MS. j.</NOTE> .</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pauper humilis ditabitur et pauper superbus
pauperabitur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>Iacobus de Vetriaco tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was ij pure
me&ntail;, ane meke an&dtail; a noder prowde; bod &thorn;e meke
ma&ntail;, whare-so-evur &thorn;ai beri&dtail; cor&ntail;, he
wol&dtail; co&mtail; with his glofe &amp; ask &thorn;aim itt
fu&llbar;, &amp; no ma&ntail; gruci&dtail; bot gaff hy&mtail;.  And
with-in a while he was a <NOTE ID="P405.N6">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, a.</NOTE> r[i]che ma&ntail;.
And &thorn;e prowde pure ma&ntail; wolde co&mtail; with a sek&ktee;
and ax cor&ntail;.  And &thorn;e gretnes of &thorn;e sakk flaye&dtail;
ilk ma&ntail; so and &thorn;ai wolde giff hy&mtail; noght; and so he
was neuer bod a pure ma&ntail;.














<PB N="406">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pauperi non est neganda elemosina.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Sigilbertus tellis how &thorn;er was a pure ma&ntail; axki&dtail;
almos of a shi&ptail;ma&ntail;, and he wolde giff hy&mtail; none.  And
the shipma&ntail; bad hy&mtail; lefe his almos-axking for &thorn;ai
had nothyng &thorn;er bod stonys.  And &thorn;e pure ma&ntail;
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "Stonys be &thorn;ai
&thorn;a&ntail;."  &amp; a&llbar; &thorn;at evur was in &thorn;e shi&ptail;
was turny&dtail; in-to stonys, &amp; &thorn;e color &amp; &thorn;e
facio&ntail; abade sty&llbar;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Pauperis meritis bona temporalia augentur.  Supra

de elemosina, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Pauperi data elemosina datur deo.  Supra de

abbate, iiij 
<NOTE ID="P406.N1">MS. iij.</NOTE> .</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Pauper plus dilectatur in minimis quam diues in

magnis.  Supra de Basilio.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Pauperi est gratis consulendum.  Supra de

Augustino, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Pauperi datum datur deo.  Supra de abbate, iiij, et

de Gregorio, i 
<NOTE ID="P406.N2">MS. iij.</NOTE> .</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pauper murmurans tolerandus
<NOTE ID="P406.N3">MS. tollerandus.</NOTE> est.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Gestis Iohannis Elemosinarij' whe&ntail; Iohannes
Elemosinarius, &thorn;at was patriar&ktee; of Alexander, vnto a pure
ma&ntail; &thorn;at axki&dtail; hy&mtail; almos commandi&dtail; to be
gyffe&ntail; v &dtail; he had grete dedeyng at he wol&dtail; gyff
hy&mtail; no more.  And onone he fe&llbar; at debate with hy&mtail;,
&amp; bega&ntail; to flite.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e patriark
servandis saw &thorn;is, &thorn;ai wol&dtail; hafe bety&ntail;
hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;is holy ma&ntail; Ioh&ntail; sayd nay, and
sai&dtail;; "Suffre hy&mtail;, brethur, to ba&ntail; me; ffor I
a&mtail; lx yere ol&dtail; and I have oftsithis blasfemyd almyghti
Go&dtail;; &amp; &thorn;erfo&rtail; I may suffer a flytyng of
&thorn;is ma&ntail;."  And with &thorn;at he garte
<PB N="407">
bryng a sache&llbar; fu&llbar; of syluer and lay befo&rtail;
hy&mtail;, &amp; bad hy&mtail; take enog&hbar; &thorn;eroff.
</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Pauper non debet fieri villicus aut balliuus.  Supra
de balliuo, j<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Pauper[es honorare debent 
<NOTE ID="P407.N1"><HI REND="i">Supplied from the</HI> Latin MSS. The English MS. <HI REND="i">leaves a blank</HI>.</NOTE> ] principes et prelati.

Supra de iudicio.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Pauperes non sunt deridendi.  Supra de apostasia, j.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Pax.  Pace&mtail; semper cum omnibus quantum possibile

est debet habere bonus christianus.  Supra de

odio et inuidia.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Peccatum multiplex nocet homini.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' how som tyme &thorn;er was a voyce at
sai&dtail; vnto &thorn;e abbot Arsenius; "Co&mtail;, and I sa&llbar;
shew &thorn;e werkis of me&ntail;."  And he went furt&hbar; &amp; he
saw a ma&ntail; of Ynde cuttant treis and makan&dtail; a burdy&ntail;
&thorn;at he mot not bere.  And &thorn;e voyce say&dtail;; "Thies er
&thorn;ai &thorn;at ekys sy&ntail; vppo&ntail; sy&ntail;."  And
&thorn;a&ntail; he saw a temple &amp; ij me&ntail; syttan&dtail;
o&ntail; hors, holdan&dtail; v&ptail; a brade tre for &thorn;e whilk
&thorn;ai myght not entre in.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e voyce
say&dtail;; "&THORN;ies er &thorn;ai &thorn;at beris rightwusnes with
pride."  And &thorn;a&ntail; he saw a ma&ntail; standan&dtail;
vppo&ntail; a dyke, &amp; fillan&dtail; a vese&llbar; with watir
&thorn;eroff &amp; puttant it in-to ane i&llbar; cister&ntail;.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e voyce sai&dtail;; "Thies er &thorn;ai
&thorn;at hase som gude dedis, and blendis &thorn;aim with evu&llbar;
warkis."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Peccatores aliqui benigne eciam recipere debent
<NOTE ID="P407.N2"><HI REND="i">So</HI> Latin MSS. The English <HI REND="i">has</HI> sunt sancti.</NOTE>
sancti.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Heraclides tellis &amp; sais &thorn;at o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail;
he visitt ane olde ma&ntail; &thorn;at had &thorn;e grace of
prophecyin&gtail; &amp; spak with hy&mtail;, &thorn;er come &thorn;e mayr of
&thorn;e cetie, and he forsuke Heraclides &amp; talkyd with hy&mtail;.







<PB N="408">

&amp; afterwar&dtail; whe&ntail; &thorn;ai commone&dtail; to-geder,
&thorn;ai common&dtail; of &thorn;is, at he sulde forsake hy&mtail;
&amp; talk with &thorn;e mayr, &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; he sai&dtail;;
"Wherefor hase &thorn;ou reprovi&dtail; me in &thorn;i saule?
&thorn;ou &amp; I luffi&dtail; wele athur of vs to co&mtail; vnto
o&thorn;er, at ather of vs myght hafe solas &amp; comfurt&hbar; of
other with ow&rtail; talkyng; and he is gyffe&ntail; a&llbar; vnto
&thorn;e devuls power, and vnnethis he may brethe in ane how&rtail;.
And now he as a servan&dtail; come hedur fro&mtail; his lorde to seke
refute, it wer ane vnsondaby&llbar; thyng to do, if it sulde be he
lefte &amp; [I] tary&dtail; with &thorn;e <NOTE ID="P408.N1">MS. if it sulde be tary&dtail; with &thorn;e &amp; he left &thorn;at hase, &amp;c.</NOTE>
&thorn;at hase bene wunte beselye to ca&llbar; me vnto &thorn;i hele."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Peccatum incurrit aliquando nimis de se presumere.

Supra de carne, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Peccata remittuntur orationibus sanctorum.  Supra

de Basilio, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Peccata venialia impossibile est vitare.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iacobus de Vetriaco tellis how &thorn;er was a monk &thorn;at
luffi&dtail; passan&dtail; wele clennes and innocentrie fro &thorn;e
state of childy&dtail; vnto &thorn;e state of ma&ntail;.  And he
wol&dtail; eatt, bod he wol&dtail; not hafe delectacio&ntail;
&thorn;erin, and he study&dtail; for to put away sy&ntail;, and for to
luff <NOTE ID="P408.N2"><HI REND="i">Should be</HI> liff; Harl. MS. ducere uitam sine omni peccato.</NOTE> with-owte&ntail; any sy&ntail;.  And
becauce for ane impossible thyng <NOTE ID="P408.N3">Harl. MS. et quia laborabat ad impossibile, decidit in desperacionem, ad eo [ut] quia sine veniali non poterat uiuere, iudicabat se saluari impossibile.</NOTE> he fe&llbar;
into a dispayre, vnto so meku&llbar; &thorn;at he myght not liff
with-owte&ntail; venya&llbar; sy&ntail;, [he] demy&dtail; hy&mtail;
selfe &thorn;at it was impossible &thorn;at he sulde be savy&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Peccantes simul in morte simul in vita puniuntur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Helynandus tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a colyer <NOTE ID="P408.N4">Lat. MSS. uir carbonarius, pauper sed religiosus, et comiti Munensi plurimum familiaris.</NOTE> &amp; he was servan&dtail; vnto religious me&ntail;
and vnto &thorn;e commontie of Meruernens.













<PB N="409">

So o&ntail; a nyght as he was kepan&dtail; his cole-pitt, &amp;
&thorn;er was a light fyre by hy&mtail;, he was warr of a naky&dtail;
womma&ntail; rynan&dtail;, and ane o&ntail; a blak hors with a
swer&dtail; in his han&dtail; drawe&ntail;, folowan&dtail; after hur
for to take hur.  And as sho come, sho ra&ntail; vnto &thorn;e
cole-pytt, &amp; &thorn;er he tuke hur &amp; strake hur
&thorn;urg&hbar; with his swer&dtail;; &amp; whe&ntail; sho was nere
dea&dtail; he keste hur into &thorn;e fyre.  And whe&ntail; sho was
a&llbar; to-swythy&ntail;, he drew hur oute, &amp; lay&dtail; hur
befo&rtail; hy&mtail; o&ntail; &thorn;e hors &amp; rade away.  And
&thorn;is he saw dyvers nyghttis; and a&llbar; &thorn;is he tolde vnto
&thorn;e sai&dtail; commontie <NOTE ID="P409.N1">Lat. MSS. Quod ille comiti predicto per ordinem narrauit.</NOTE> .  So o&ntail; a
nyght &thorn;er come a felow <NOTE ID="P409.N2">Ac comes vna cum carbonario ad prefatum locum ... veniens.</NOTE> with &thorn;is
colleyer vnto &thorn;e same place, and he saw a&llbar; as &thorn;e
colyer tol&dtail;.  And he tuke &thorn;is hors-ma&ntail; be &thorn;e
brydi&llbar; whe&ntail; a&llbar; was done, and asky&dtail; hy&mtail;
what he was.  And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "I
was swilk a knyght, and &thorn;is was &thorn;e wyfe of swylk a knyght
whome sho slow for my luff, att sho &amp; I mot mo&rtail; frelie
hawnte our sy&ntail;; and in &thorn;at sy&ntail; we er bothe
dea&dtail;.  And vnnethis whe&ntail; we dye&dtail; we forthoght our
sy&ntail;; and &thorn;us ilk a nyght I sla hur &amp; burnys hur, and
sho suffers mo&rtail; pay&ntail; with &thorn;e strake of my
swer&dtail; &thorn;at I stryke hur with, &thorn;a&ntail; evur sho
di&dtail; with dea&dtail;; and with &thorn;e burnyng sho felis
meku&llbar; mo&rtail;."  And &thorn;a&ntail; he aski&dtail; hy&mtail;
what hors &thorn;at was at he satt o&ntail;, and he sai&dtail;; "It is
a fen&dtail; &thorn;at turmentis vs."  Tha&ntail; he asky&dtail;
hy&mtail; if any &thorn;ing mot helpe &thorn;aim, &amp; he say&dtail;;
"Ya, and ye wol&dtail; gar syng so many messis &amp; gar say so many
psalters for vs, onone we sulde be helpy&dtail; &amp; ou&rtail;
pay&ntail; relesi&dtail;."  And &thorn;us &thorn;ai parti&dtail;, and
&thorn;is ma&ntail; garte do &thorn;ies messis &amp; say &thorn;ies
psalters for &thorn;aim, &amp; &thorn;ai wer neuer sene after.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Peccatum punit Deus quandoque in hac vita.  Supra,

ambulacio, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Peccator per que peccat per hec et punitur.  Supra

de agro, i &amp; ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Peccata esse remissa ostendit aliquando deus aliquibus

signis.  Infra de remissione.</FOREIGN>




<PB N="410">
</ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Peccatum quandoque dissimulat 
<NOTE ID="P410.N1">MS. dissimilat.</NOTE>  Deus ut plus

puniat.  Supra de dissimulacione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Peccata sua eciam bruta aliquando cognoscunt.

Supra de furto, ij 
<NOTE ID="P410.N2">MS. iij.</NOTE> .</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Peccata delet confessio quandoque de memoria

confessoris.  Supra de confessione, iiij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Peccata delet confessio de consciencia penitentis.

Supra de confessione, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Peccata celat confessio multiplex.  Supra de

confessione in pluribus locis.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Peccatum unum quandoque inducit in aliud.  Supra

de contricione, vj.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Peccata sunt causa aduersitatum que nobis
eveniunt.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' how &thorn;er was som tyme a gude
ma&ntail; &thorn;at suffred wrong of a noder, and he compleynyd
hy&mtail; vnto ane olde ma&ntail;.  And &thorn;e old ma&ntail;
ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail; "He di&dtail;
not &thorn;is, bod &thorn;i synnys did itt.  And &thorn;erfo&rtail;
blame not &thorn;is ma&ntail; in nothyng at he duse vnto &thorn;e, nor
at is happend vnto &thorn;e, bod say at &thorn;i synnys hat&hbar;
adli&dtail; &thorn;aim."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Peccatum fetet coram deo et angelis.  Supra de

Angelo, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Peccatum onerat hominem et animam.  Infra de simia.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Peccatum trahit hominem ad infernum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' how &thorn;at o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail;
ane ypocryte was dea&dtail;, mea&ntail; &thorn;at wer present aboute
hy&mtail; har&dtail; a voice say vnto fendes o&ntail; &thorn;is maner
of wyse; "Draw hy&mtail; oute wheder





<PB N="411">

he wi&llbar; or nay.  And as he gaf me no reste in &thorn;e synnys
&thorn;at he di&dtail; beselie befo&rtail; me, on &thorn;e same maner
of wyse giff ye hy&mtail; no reste."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Peccatores portat demon ad infernum.  Supra de

demone in pluribus locis.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Peccator in inferno punitur.  Supra de Langrauio.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Pena infernalis est multiplex.  Supra de inferno per

totum.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Penam debitam minuunt suffragia.  Infra de

suffragijs.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Pena respondent culpe.  Supra de agro.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Penitencia pocius est hic facienda quam in
futuro.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iacobus de Vetriaco tellis &amp; says; "So&mtail; tyme I saw a
holye womma&ntail; whilk &thorn;at whe&ntail; sho was long dea&dtail;,
or hur body was beryd &amp; layd in ert&hbar;, hur sawle turny&dtail;
agay&ntail; vnto hur bodye.  &amp; sho had grawnti&dtail; at sho
sul&dtail; liff sty&llbar; in &thorn;is werl&dtail;, and sho sulde
suffre in purgatorie penans for hur sy&ntail; &amp; sho wol&dtail;,
&amp; if sho wol&dtail; not, sho sul&dtail; suffre penance in
&thorn;is werl&dtail;: &amp; sho tuke hur to suffre penance in
&thorn;is werl&dtail;.  So a long tyme, as God wol&dtail; <NOTE ID="P411.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, a long tyme, <HI REND="i">here</HI>.</NOTE> , sho was gretelye turment, to so muche at sho
wol&dtail; som tyme weltyr in &thorn;e fyre, and so&mtail; tyme in
wynter sho wolde lay hur dow&ntail; in frosy&ntail; watyr &amp; lay
hur &thorn;er a long while; an&dtail; so&mtail; tyme sho was
constreyny&dtail; to entyr dead mens gravis.  So at &thorn;e laste sho
had grace graunti&dtail; of almyghtie Go&dtail; at sho was oft sythes
ravysshi&dtail; in hur spyritt at sho le&dtail; dyvers tymys &thorn;e
sawlis of &thorn;aim at wer dea&dtail; into purgatorie, &amp;
thrug&hbar; purgatorie, &amp; sho had no hurte, vnto &thorn;e
kyngdo&mtail; of hevy&ntail;."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Penitere potest interdum unus pro alio.  Infra de

satisfaccione.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>



<PB N="412">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Penitencia perfecta delet peccata et nichil
formidat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a blak mon&ktee;
&thorn;at fe&llbar; in apostasye, &amp; syne he was a Premonstracence
&amp; went oute; and at &thorn;e laste he was a mon&ktee; of Ceustus.
And evur he gaff hy&mtail; vnto luste &amp; lykyng of his bodie, &amp;
vnto o&thorn;er innumerable vices.  So at &thorn;e laste, as God
wol&dtail;, he tuke &thorn;e ordur &amp; habett of Ceustus ordur, and
onone he shrafe hy&mtail; and tuke his penance.  And he di&dtail; his
penance trewlie, in wepyngis, prayer, &amp; fastyng, &amp; in a&llbar;
o&thorn;er thyngys.  So at &thorn;e laste he fe&llbar; seke and was
bow&ntail; to dye, &amp; evur he contynewi&dtail; in syngyng,
prayers-saying, and wurshippyng our Lady vnto &thorn;e stounde of
dea&dtail;.  And in presens of his abbot &amp; his brethyr he
sai&dtail; o&ntail; &thorn;is maner of wyse; "Wurshupfu&llbar;
brethur, I, a synner &amp; a penytent, ye beryng me wytnes, covettis
of almyghtie God to hafe a space to make a clere confessio&ntail;,
&amp; to do verray penans for my synnys.  And if God wy&llbar; graunt
me lyfe, I a&mtail; redie to make a sethe, and for to vnder-go
a&llbar; maner of turment, and a&llbar; maner of har&dtail; thyng
&amp; labur; ffor nothyng is har&dtail; nor inpossible vnto hy&mtail;
&thorn;at is verray penytent."  And &thorn;us, emang &thorn;ies
wurdis, with a grete compunccio&ntail; &amp; a grete forthynkyng, he
gaff vp vnto God a gude sawle; and &thorn;er was sene co&mtail; vnto
hy&mtail; aungels, whilk &thorn;at bare his sawle into hevy&ntail;
with a grete myrt&hbar; &amp; a ioy.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Penitencia magis unum quam alium attenuat.  Supra

de apostata, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Penitere facit hominem cogitacio penarum.  Supra

de delicijs et de inferno, i.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Penitencia modica
<NOTE ID="P412.N1">MS. inordita. Lat. MSS. <HI REND="i">as above</HI>.</NOTE> ex corde facta placet Deo.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' how som tyme &thorn;er was a mon&ktee;
&thorn;at aski&dtail; abbott Pastor, &amp; sai&dtail; o&ntail;
&thorn;is maner of wyse; "I hafe done a



<PB N="413">

grete sy&ntail;, &amp; I wi&llbar; <NOTE ID="P413.N1"><HI REND="i">After</HI> will, not, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> &thorn;is
iij yere be penytent &thorn;erof."  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is
abbot Pastor ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail;, &amp; say&dtail;;
"&thorn;at is meku&llbar;!" &amp; &thorn;is mon&ktee; bad hy&mtail;
commawnd hy&mtail; a yere, &amp; yitt &thorn;e abbott sai&dtail;
&thorn;at was meku&llbar;.  And &thorn;ai at was aboute desyri&dtail;
at he sulde be eniony&dtail; &thorn;erfo&rtail; XL<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> dayes, and yitt
&thorn;is abbott sai&dtail; it was meku&llbar;, &amp; sai&dtail;
o&ntail; &thorn;is maner of wyse; "I trow &thorn;at &amp; a ma&ntail;
forthynk his sy&ntail; with a&llbar; his harte, &amp; tur&ntail; not
&thorn;erto agay&ntail;, at God wi&llbar; for iij dayes penans-doyng
forgyff hy&mtail; hys sy&ntail;."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Penitenciam impedit gula.  Supra de gula, iiij et v<HI
REND="sup">to</HI>.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Penitenciam facit peccator inductus.  Supra de

abbate, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Penitencia debet esse firma et perseverans.  Supra

de familiaritate et infra de perseuerancia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Penitencia in fine vite valet.  Supra de peccato, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Penitencia nimis tarda nichil prodest.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iacobus de Vetriaco tellis how o&ntail; a tyme Charlis &thorn;e
Emperour garte ca&llbar; befor hy&mtail; his iij sonnys, Gobardus,
Lotharius, and Lodouicus; and he helde ane appy&llbar; in his
han&dtail; &amp; bad &thorn;aim a&llbar; oppy&ntail; &thorn;er
mouthes.  &amp; &thorn;e ij yonger oppyn&dtail; &thorn;er mouthis,
&amp; &thorn;is Gobardus wol&dtail; nott.  And he gaff vnto &thorn;e
ij yonger, &thorn;e tone a kyngdo&mtail;, and &thorn;e toder a
dukedo&mtail;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;is Gobardus saw, he sai&dtail;
vnto his fader at he wolde oppy&ntail; his mouthe &amp; hafe parte of
&thorn;is appy&llbar;.  And his ffadur ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail; "&THORN;ou oppyn&dtail; &thorn;i mouthe
to late, &amp; &thorn;erfo&rtail; I wy&llbar; nowder gyff &thorn;e
appy&llbar; nor lan&dtail;."  And hereof come a proverb &thorn;at is
sai&dtail; in Franche, " <FOREIGN LANG="FR">A tart bea <NOTE ID="P413.N2">MS. 'Acarbea Gobard,' &amp;c.</NOTE> Gobard, qe eu la tere nout parte.</FOREIGN>"

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Penitent simul qui simul peccant.  Supra de

peccato, iiij 
<NOTE ID="P413.N3">MS. iij.</NOTE> .</FOREIGN>


<PB N="414">
</ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Penitencia viuorum facta pro mortuis valet eis.

Supra de morte, xiij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Penitencia debet a confessore acceptari quam a

confitente potest extorquere.  Supra de confessore.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Peregrinum demon subito reportauit
<NOTE ID="P414.N1">MS. temptauit.  Lat. MSS. <HI REND="i">as above</HI>.</NOTE>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how so&mtail; tyme in &thorn;e tow&ntail; of
Halybac&hbar;, &thorn;er was a knyght &thorn;at hight Gerar&dtail;,
and he had grete deuocio&ntail; vnto Saynt Thomas &thorn;e apostell.
So o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;e devu&llbar; in lyknes of a pure ma&ntail;
come vnto hy&mtail;, &amp; asky&dtail; hy&mtail; gestynnyng for Saynt
Thomas luff; &amp; he graunti&dtail; hy&mtail; it.  And whe&ntail; he
was gone vnto his be&dtail;; &thorn;is knyght sent vnto hy&mtail; his
beste furry&dtail; gow&ntail; to hap&ptail; hy&mtail; with for colde,
and he vppo&ntail; &thorn;e nyght had &thorn;is cape away, &amp; wolde
not be fo&ntail; in &thorn;e mornyng.  And &thorn;e knyghtis wyfe was
wrothe here-with, &amp; blamyd hugelie <NOTE ID="P414.N2">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, hugelie.</NOTE> hur
husban&dtail; for herberyng of pure beggers, &amp; sai&dtail;;
"&THORN;ou sulde nevur do hy&mtail; mo&rtail; gude."  And &thorn;is
knyght ansswer&dtail; hur agay&ntail; mekelie &amp; sai&dtail;; "Saynt
Thomas is in power to do me als gude a tur&ntail; as my gow&ntail; was
wurt&hbar;."  So o&ntail; a tyme after &thorn;is knyght wol&dtail; go
in pylgramege vnto &thorn;er Saynt Thomas lay, and he brak a golde
ryng in ij befo&rtail; hys wyfe, &amp; he gaf &thorn;e tone halfe vnto
his wyfe and say&dtail;; "Trust vnto &thorn;is toky&ntail;, &amp; I
send &thorn;e itt, and abyde my commyng home vnto v yere be passyd."
And sho sai&dtail; yis &amp; tuke &thorn;is ryng, &amp; he went his
ways.  So after dyvers yeris he come vnto &thorn;e cetie of Saynt
Thomas, and whe&ntail; he was in &thorn;e kur&ktee; &amp; made his
prayer vnto Saynt Thomas, &amp; commendi&dtail; in his prayers his
wyfe and his childer &amp; his meneya, he was war of &thorn;e
fen&dtail; walkand vp &amp; dow&ntail; in his furry&dtail; gow&ntail;.
And &thorn;e fen&dtail; come vnto hy&mtail; &amp; say&dtail;;
"Gerar&dtail;! knowis &thorn;ou oght me?"  And he sai&dtail;; "Nay, I
know &thorn;e not, bod I know &thorn;at gow&ntail; we&llbar;
enog&hbar;."  An&dtail; &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e fen&dtail;
sai&dtail;; "I a&mtail; &thorn;e devu&llbar; &thorn;at in lyknes of a
pure ma&ntail; was herbar&dtail; with &thorn;e, and I stale &thorn;i
gow&ntail;; &amp; herefo&rtail; I hafe bene gretely





<PB N="415">

punysshi&dtail;.  And I a&mtail; chargi&dtail; at I sha&llbar; onone
hafe &thorn;e home agay&ntail; vnto &thorn;i place safe &amp;
sown&dtail;, for als meku&llbar; as &thorn;is day &thorn;i wyfe is
we&dtail; with a noder ma&ntail;; for now it is xv yere se&ntail;
&thorn;ou come fro hur."  And with &thorn;at, whe&ntail; he had
offer&dtail;, he tuke hy&mtail; vp&ptail; in Ynde, and onone he broght
hy&mtail; home to his aw&ntail; yate in Duchelan&dtail;.  And his wyfe
&amp; hur husband, att war we&dtail; &thorn;at same day, wer at meatt,
&amp; he come in &amp; keste in hur cop&ptail; &thorn;er sho satt
&thorn;e halfe of &thorn;e golde ryng.  And whe&ntail; sho saw it sho
tuke &thorn;e tuder parte &thorn;er-of &amp; putt &thorn;erto, &amp;
&thorn;ai acordi&dtail;; &amp; here-by sho wyste he was hur
husban&dtail;, and &thorn;er sho forsuke hur new husban&dtail; &amp;
tuke hur to hur olde.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Peregrinos deus in morte consolatur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' how som tyme &thorn;er was ij brethir,
&amp; &thorn;e tone was a pylgrem, and &thorn;e toder gaff hy&mtail;
vnto quiete &amp; ryste.  So it happi&dtail; at &thorn;is
pylgra&mtail; dye&dtail;, and angels tuke his saule &amp; flow
u&ptail; vnto hevy&ntail; &thorn;er-with, &amp; wolde hafe broght it
in.  And &thorn;an our Lor&dtail; sai&dtail;; "He was a little
necligent, bod becauce he was a pylgra&mtail;, &thorn;erfo&rtail; take
hy&mtail; in."  So onone after his other bruther dye&dtail;, and a
gude olde ma&ntail;, &thorn;at saw aungels co&mtail; to &thorn;e furst
&amp; not to &thorn;e latter, he axke&dtail; our Lor&dtail; why
&thorn;is was.  And ou&rtail; Lor&dtail; ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "&THORN;is pylgra&mtail; in a&llbar; his
life ha&dtail; no comfurt&hbar; of none of his frendis, and
&thorn;erfo&rtail; me behuvis comfurthe <NOTE ID="P415.N1">MS. comfuthe.</NOTE>
hy&mtail; with myne angels; bod his bruther in his life had
comfurt&hbar; of his gude frendis, &amp; &thorn;er-for I
comfurthi&dtail; hy&mtail; not with myne aungels."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Peregrinus a deo remuneratur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a cetysy&ntail; of
Tulpytt &thorn;at hight Cono, &amp; he went with other pylgramys vnto
&thorn;e see; and &thorn;er he fe&llbar; passan&dtail; seke and
dye&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; he was



<PB N="416">

dea&dtail;lyke, he bega&ntail; to wax passan&dtail; mery, an&dtail;
his felows axki&dtail; hy&mtail; whatt was cauce att he was so merye.
He ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Whi sulde I nott be
mery?  Our Ladie was here &amp; say&dtail; vnto me, 'Cono! becauce
&thorn;ou left &thorn;i wife, &thorn;i childer, &amp; a&llbar;
&thorn;i gudis for &thorn;e luff of my so&ntail;, I sha&llbar; wele
rewar&dtail; &thorn;e.'"  And with &thorn;at he crye&dtail; &amp;
sai&dtail;; "Behol&dtail;! I se hevy&ntail; oppy&ntail; &amp; a seatt
ordan&dtail; for me."  And with &thorn;at he passi&dtail; away, &amp;
his sawle went vp&ptail; vnto hye hevy&ntail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Peregrino inclinat ymago crucifixi.  Supra de

misericordia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Peregrinacio mentalis valet.  Infra 
<NOTE ID="P416.N1">MS. Supra.</NOTE> , Petri martiris.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pericula mundi sunt pertimenda
<NOTE ID="P416.N2"><HI REND="i">So</HI> Lat. MSS. The English MS. <HI REND="i">has</HI> percanenda.</NOTE>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Dictis Barlaam' how som tyme &thorn;er was a ma&ntail;
&thorn;at fled fro&mtail; ane vnycor&ntail;, and hy&mtail;
happen&dtail; fa&llbar; in-to a grete pytt.  And as he fe&llbar;,
hy&mtail; happend with his handis to gett holde be a buske at grew in
&thorn;e syde of &thorn;e pytt, and his fete wer strayte in a
vesse&llbar; <NOTE ID="P416.N3">Harl. MS. pedibus uase quodam impressus, <HI REND="i">for</HI> pedibus base quadam lubrica impressis.</NOTE> .  So he luki&dtail; aboute
hy&mtail; &amp; he saw ij myce, ane white &amp; a noder blak&ktee;,
&amp; daylie &thorn;ai gnew vppo&ntail; &thorn;e rute of &thorn;is
buske, to it was nerehan&dtail; in sondre.  And he consydur&dtail;
&thorn;e depenes of &thorn;is pytt, &amp; he saw &thorn;er-in ane
vglie drago&ntail; spowtand fyre.  So he luki&dtail; vnto &thorn;e
grown&dtail; &thorn;eroff, &amp; &thorn;er he saw iiij neddyr-hedis
knytt to-gedur.  So he lukyd wpwar&dtail;, &amp; he saw a drop&ptail;
of hony drope in &thorn;e bewis of &thorn;is buske, &amp; he,
negligent of &thorn;e sai&dtail; perels, he thoght he wol&dtail; no
lefe, bod he wol&dtail; hafe &thorn;is drope of honye.  et c&curl;.
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Moraliter sic.</FOREIGN> Frendis!  Be &thorn;is
vnycor&ntail; is vnderston&dtail; deade, &amp; be &thorn;is pytt
&thorn;e werl&dtail;, and be &thorn;is buske &thorn;e lenthe of our
lyfe, whilk &thorn;at be howris of &thorn;e day &amp; of &thorn;e
nyght, as a white mowce and a bla&ktee;, cuttis it dow&ntail;; &amp;
be &thorn;e iiij neddyrs is vnderstan&dtail; &thorn;e iiij elementis
&thorn;at mans body is made of, &amp; be &thorn;e drago&ntail;









<PB N="417">

is vnderstan&dtail; he&llbar;, and be &thorn;is drope of hony,
&thorn;e swettnes of &thorn;is life, whilk who-so covattis er
caste&ntail; in &thorn;e sai&dtail; perels.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Periculis possunt adaptari multa que dicuntur

supra de morte et de mundo.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Periurium eciam in hac vita punitur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;at &thorn;e dea&ntail; of Bononye <NOTE ID="P417.N1">Harl. MS. decanus Bonnensis.</NOTE> , beyng in &thorn;e dioces of Colay&ntail;, lent
vnto a bruther &thorn;at he ha&dtail; xx marcis of cone of mony of his
kur&ktee;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;is dea&ntail; was dea&dtail;, his
<NOTE ID="P417.N2">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, his.</NOTE> bruther, a knyght, denye&dtail; &thorn;is
sai&dtail; dett.  And &thorn;e chanons, &thorn;at had no prefe
&thorn;er-in, made &thorn;is knyght for to swere &thorn;erfo&rtail;,
and so he di&dtail;, an&dtail; forswore hy&mtail;.  Bod whe&ntail; he
went fro Bononye, wha&rtail; he sware, vnto his aw&ntail;
howse-war&dtail;, hy&mtail; happen&dtail; to stan&dtail; in myddest of
&thorn;e way sty&llbar;, &amp; mott go no ferrer nor yitt tur&ntail;
bak&ktee;.  And his tong was take&ntail; fro&mtail; hy&mtail;, vnto
he promysi&dtail; in his harte &thorn;at he sulde tur&ntail;
agay&ntail; vnto Bono&ntail; &amp; knowlege his maneswor&ntail; athe
&amp; resto&rtail; &thorn;e sai&dtail; money vnto &thorn;e chanons
agay&ntail;.  And so he did &amp; was hale.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Periurio possunt adaptari que supra dicuntur de

iuramento.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Perseuerancia.  Perseuerandum semper est in bono.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede of one &thorn;at hight Ioh&ntail;, &thorn;at was ane
ankyr, &thorn;at was a ma&ntail; &thorn;at had lede ane i&llbar; lyfe.
And whe&ntail; he was compu[n]cte, he garte spar hy&mtail; selfe in a
grafe, and &thorn;er he wasshi&dtail; away his synnys with salte
teris, and he lay o&ntail; his kneis &amp; his elbows, and wolde not
lifte v&ptail; his ee&ntail; nor name &thorn;e name of almyghtie
Go&dtail;, bod &thorn;ar he enduryd a long tyme in his prayer.  So
&thorn;er come fendis into &thorn;is grafe vnto hym, and crye&dtail;
vppo&ntail; hy&mtail; &amp; sayde;





<PB N="418">

"&THORN;ou cursi&dtail; caytuff!  Whatt duse &thorn;ou here?  For
whe&ntail; &thorn;ou was fulfylli&dtail; with al maner of sy&ntail;
&amp; vnclennes, &amp; now &thorn;i strent&hbar; sufficies not to do
no sy&ntail;, now &thorn;ou wi&llbar; liff in chastite and seme a gude
ma&ntail;.  Tur&ntail; agay&ntail; vnto vs, ffor &thorn;ou erte one of
vs."  An&dtail; &thorn;a&ntail; a noder spak vnto hy&mtail; &amp;
sayd; "What hopis &thorn;ou att &thorn;is place sha&llbar; do &thorn;e
gude?  Do as &thorn;ou hase done befor, &amp; lyff in luste &amp;
lykyng of &thorn;i fless&hbar;; ffor what pay&ntail; mott &thorn;ou
suffer mo&rtail; in he&llbar; &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ou suffres now?"
And euer he lay sty&llbar; &amp; nothyng wol&dtail; say.  And
whe&ntail; &thorn;e fendis saw &thorn;att, &thorn;ai bett hy&mtail;
&amp; gaff hy&mtail; many a sore wownde, and &thorn;at anys, twyse,
thryce, to so meku&llbar; &thorn;at att &thorn;e laste &thorn;ai lefte
hy&mtail; halfe deade.  And &thorn;ai crye&dtail; with a hedus noyce
&amp; say&dtail;: " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vicisti!  Vicisti!</FOREIGN>"
And with &thorn;at &thorn;ai vanyshi&dtail; away, and nevur after
apperi&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Perseuerans in bono eciam mortem contempnit.  Infra

de silencio, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Perseuerare debent novicij in deuocione.  Supra de

Novicio.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Peticio.  Petitur aliquando contrarium
uolito.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis how o&ntail; a tyme Grete Alexander was
streke&ntail; in a grete yre, &amp; thoght to kaste dow&ntail;
&thorn;e cetie of Lapsatum. So hy&mtail; happen&dtail; mete sodanlie
one &thorn;at was calli&dtail; Anaximetes, &thorn;at was his preceptur
&amp; his maister, and he was ashamyd to mete his maister becauce he
was in suche ane angre, and he grawnti&dtail; his maister &thorn;at
what &thorn;ing so&mtail;-evur at he wulde axke hy&mtail;, he wolde
grawnt hy&mtail; itt.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;is Anaximetes har&dtail;
&thorn;is he sai&dtail;; "Sur Kyng, I aske at &thorn;ou dof &thorn;ine
envie ayeynste &thorn;e cetie of Lapsatt."  And he grawnti&dtail;
hy&mtail; it.  And &thorn;us &thorn;urg&hbar; his benefice was
&thorn;e cetie savi&dtail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Petri Apostoli.  Petrus cum voluit Petronillam

sanauit et cum placuit eidem infirmitatem

reddidit.  Supra de infirmitate, iiij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>

<PB N="419">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Petri Martiris.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in his Legend how o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; he was at
&thorn;e cetie of Melay&ntail; <NOTE ID="P419.N1">Lat. MSS. Apud Mediolanem.</NOTE> &amp; prechid
&thorn;er, he disputi&dtail; with a maister &thorn;at hight Hesiarcha
<NOTE ID="P419.N2">Harl. MS. et quemdam magistrum heresiarcham examinante.</NOTE> in presens of a&llbar; &thorn;e prelattis of
&thorn;e cetie.  And &thorn;is Hesyarcha sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;;
"O! &thorn;ou frawar&dtail; Petur!  And &thorn;ou be als holie as
&thorn;ies fon&dtail; peple trowis, whi prayes &thorn;ou noght
&thorn;i Go&dtail; to putt a clowde betwix &thorn;aim &amp; &thorn;e
so&ntail;, at &thorn;ai dye nott for so grete hete as &thorn;ai
d[oo]?"  And &thorn;is Petur ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail;
&amp; sai&dtail;; "And &thorn;ou wi&llbar; promytte me at &thorn;ou
sha&llbar; renownce &thorn;ine heresie, I sha&llbar; do as &thorn;ou
hase axki&dtail;."  And &thorn;e heretykis, trowyng at &thorn;at myght
not be done, cryed oppo&ntail; &thorn;is maister, and bad hy&mtail;
make a promys.  And yitt he wolde nott.  Neuer-&thorn;e-les &thorn;is
Petur, to shew &thorn;e power of almightie God, and at He was former
of al thyngis visible and invisible, made his prayer &amp; made a cros
agay&ntail; &thorn;e so&ntail;; and &thorn;er apperi&dtail; betwix
&thorn;e so&ntail; &amp; &thorn;e peple a little clowde like a tent
&thorn;at cover&dtail; &thorn;e peple fro &thorn;e so&ntail;.  And
befo&rtail; &thorn;a&rtail; was no clowde in a&llbar; &thorn;e ayre.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Petrus mortuum suscitauit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede also in his Legend how &thorn;er was som tyme a
womma&ntail; in Flawndres, and whe&ntail; sho had bor&ntail; iij
childer sho praye&dtail; Saynt Petur for to helpe hur.  And sho bare
&thorn;e iiij childe and it was &dtail;ea&dtail;, and sho tuke
&thorn;is childe &amp; broght it vnto Saynt Petur &amp; besoght
hy&mtail; hertelie &thorn;erfo&rtail;.  And onone &thorn;is dea&dtail;
childe become whi&ktee;.  And whe&ntail; it was ordan&dtail;
&thorn;at at his bapty&mtail; he sulde be calli&dtail; Joh&ntail;,
&thorn;e preste, not wittan&dtail; what he sul&dtail; say, namy&dtail;
hy&mtail; Petur; and &thorn;at name remayny&dtail; with hy&mtail;
ewhils he liffi&dtail;.






<PB N="420">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Petrus monialem absentem sanauit
<NOTE ID="P420.N1">MS. absentem nominauit et sanauit.</NOTE>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede also in his Legen&dtail; how &thorn;er was a no&ntail; in
Lombardye &thorn;at had &thorn;e gutt grevuslie in hur kne, and sho
cuthe not be heli&dtail; with no medcy&ntail;.  And whe&ntail; sho
hard te&llbar; at it was bod xiiij day iorney fro hur place vnto
Mylay&ntail;, &thorn;at at sho mot not do with hur bodye sho thoght to
go in hur mynde.  And ilka day sho say&dtail; a hondret&hbar; patyr
noster, and &thorn;us sho thoght ilk day to make a iorney.  And onone
as sho bega&ntail; &thorn;us for to go in hur <NOTE ID="P420.N2">MS. his.</NOTE> 
mynde, sho wex evur bettur and bettyr.  And whe&ntail; sho di&dtail;
hur laste day iorney, &amp; in hur mynde went vnto his tombe, kneland
o&ntail; hur kneis as sho had bene at hys tombe in hur prayer, sho
sai&dtail; ou&rtail; hur psalter with a grete devocio&ntail;.  And be
sho had done it, sho feli&dtail; bod a litle of hur sekenes.  And so
sho turny&dtail; agay&ntail; with hur prayers as sho bega&ntail;, and
be sho had done a&llbar; hur day iorneys, sho was al hole &amp;
sown&dtail; as evur sho was.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Pietas.  Pietati conueniunt multa [que dicuntur

supra de elemosina, hospitalitate, leprosis et

pauperibus 
<NOTE ID="P420.N3"><HI REND="i">From the</HI> Harl. MS.</NOTE> ].</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXXX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pigricia.  Pigricia semper est uitanda
<NOTE ID="P420.N4"><HI REND="i">Heading from the</HI> Arun. MS.</NOTE>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Iero&mtail; tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was ane olde
monke, &amp; he thoght to comfurt&hbar; a slaw bruther of his, and
say&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; in &thorn;is maner of wyse; "Som tyme
&thorn;er was a ma&ntail; &thorn;at had lande to be sawe&ntail;, bod
becauce of his negligens it grew fu&llbar; off thornys &amp; breers.
So he bad his so&ntail; go &amp; clence itt of &thorn;aim.  And
whe&ntail; he come &thorn;erto, &amp; saw &thorn;er was so grete
multitude of thornys &amp; breers, he bega&ntail; to fayle in his
herte &amp; say&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; selfe; "Whe&ntail; sha&llbar; I
hafe clensi&dtail; a&llbar; &thorn;ies?"  And with &thorn;att he layed










<PB N="421">

hy&mtail; dow&ntail; &amp; slepy&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; his fadur
knew how he di&dtail;, he sayd vnto hy&mtail; "So&ntail;! wurke &amp;
clence evurilk day als meku&llbar; grownd as &thorn;ou occupyes
whe&ntail; &thorn;ou lyes o&ntail; &thorn;e erthe &amp; slepis."  And
he obeye&dtail; his fadurs commawndment and did so.  And &thorn;us be
little &amp; little he clensi&dtail; a&llbar; &thorn;is grown&dtail;

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Piscator.  Infra purgatorij, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Pollucio nocturna aliquando non impedit

communionem et aliquando impedit.  Supra de

communione, v.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXXXI. 
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Potencia.  Potentes frequenter querunt occasiones
contra pauperes.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Esopus tellis in his fables how &thorn;e lambe &amp; &thorn;e
wulfe war bothe thrustie, and &thorn;ai come bothe vnto &thorn;e watir
to dryn&ktee;; &amp; &thorn;e wulfe dranke abow&ntail;, &amp;
&thorn;e lambe benethe.  Tha&ntail; &thorn;e wulfe sayd vnto &thorn;e
lambe; "Whi haste &thorn;ou truble&dtail; &thorn;e watyr vnto me?"
And &thorn;e lambe ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
say&dtail;; "How sulde I make &thorn;e watir drovy whe&ntail; itt come
fro the vnto me?"  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e wulfe sai&dtail;; "Whi
<NOTE ID="P421.N1">MS. wha&ntail;. Lat. MSS. cur.</NOTE> bannys &thorn;ou me?"  And &thorn;e lambe
say&dtail;; "Nay, I ba&ntail; &thorn;e nott."  And &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;e wulfe sai&dtail;; "Thi fadur did vnto me meku&llbar;
i&llbar;, and now I sa&llbar; venge me of the."  And with &thorn;at he
ra&ntail; on&ntail; &thorn;e selie lambe and woro&dtail; itt.  And
&thorn;is had &thorn;e lambe &thorn;at did no tryspas

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Potus superfluus est vitandus.  Supra de abstinencia,

ebrietate et gula.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXXXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Preceptum.  Preceptum eciam indiscretum nocet

subdito inobedienti.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;er was a mon&ktee; som tyme of Ceustus
ordur &thorn;at dye&dtail; and he apperid vnto a bruther of his and
requiri&dtail; hy&mtail;



<PB N="422">

of his estate.  And &thorn;e dead monk ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail;
&amp; say&dtail;; "I trowe&dtail; neuer God had bene so strayte, ffor
He thynkis of &thorn;e leste thyng.  Bod God," he sai&dtail;,
"for-giff ou&rtail; prelattis, for &thorn;ai make vs oftsithis to
vnder-go great paynys, &amp; many.  And He byndys hugelie &thorn;e
preceptis of &thorn;aim whe&ntail; &thorn;ai commawn&dtail; anythyng
vndiscretelie, &amp; &thorn;er subgettis giffis little hede
&thorn;erto, or els sett it at noght; &amp; so it is reservi&dtail;
vnto &thorn;e laste iugementt."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Precepto conveniunt que dicuntur supra de

obediencia.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXXXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Predestinacio.  Predestinacioni innitentes multi

decipiuntur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis of one &thorn;at hight Lodowicus, Lattgravius
Thurungie, &thorn;at was a letter&dtail; ma&ntail;, &amp; he was
deseyvi&dtail; with suche ane errour at he sai&dtail; hy&mtail;
bur&dtail; nedis be savy&dtail; &amp; he wer destanye&dtail;
&thorn;erto, or els he sulde be dampne&dtail; and he war
destany&dtail; &thorn;erto.  And also he sai&dtail; he mott not fle
&thorn;e how&rtail; of his dea&dtail;, nor nowder lenthe it nor
shorte&ntail; itt; and for &thorn;is, with-owty&ntail; any drede, he
gaff hy&mtail; vnto a&llbar; maner of vices.  So att &thorn;e laste he
fe&llbar; in a huge sekenes, &amp; he garte gett hy&mtail; a leche,
and praye&dtail; hy&mtail; to take hy&mtail; in cure and amend
hy&mtail; of his sekenes.  And &thorn;is leche was wele lerny&dtail;,
not alonelie in lechecrafte, bod also in dyvynyte, and knew wele
enog&hbar; his errour, and sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; in &thorn;is
maner of wyse; "Sur, and &thorn;e day of your dead be comme&ntail;,
&thorn;a&ntail; it wer in vay&ntail; &thorn;at I sulde do any cure
vppo&ntail; you."  And &thorn;e seke ma&ntail; axki&dtail; hy&mtail;
why he say&dtail; so, &amp; sai&dtail;; "I know we&llbar; enog&hbar;
bod if I hafe sone helpe I mo&ntail; dy befo&rtail; &thorn;e tyme."
Tha&ntail; &thorn;e leche say&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "And ye trow at
your lyfe may be lenthen&dtail; be &thorn;e vertue of medcyns, wharto
denye ye to do penance, &thorn;at is medcy&ntail; of &thorn;e sawle?"
And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is Lattgravius, consydurand &thorn;e vertue
of his wurdis, say&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; in &thorn;is maner of wise;
"Fro hens furth be &thorn;ou &thorn;e leche of my sawle; ffor be
&thorn;i medycynable tong I trow at God sha&llbar; delyver me
fro&mtail; my moste errour."

<PB N="423">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXXXIV. 
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Predicacio.  Predicandum sincere 
<NOTE ID="P423.N1">MS. scincere.</NOTE>  est propter deum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;er was ane of &thorn;e Premonstracencis
ordur &thorn;at, whe&ntail; he ha&dtail; prechi&dtail; of &thorn;e
cros, he dye&dtail; and apperi&dtail; vnto his felow.  And he
axki&dtail; hy&mtail; how at it stude with hy&mtail;, and he
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Whe&ntail; I dye&dtail;
devuls vmbelappi&dtail; me <NOTE ID="P423.N2">MS. &thorn;aim. Lat. MSS. circumdederunt me demones.</NOTE> , and ane of
&thorn;aim say&dtail;, '&thorn;ou kepy&dtail; neuer trewlye &thorn;ine
ordur.'  And a noder sai&dtail;, '&thorn;ou prechi&dtail; neuer
trewlie for Goddis cauce.'  An&dtail; I vnderstude at &thorn;ai
sai&dtail; bothe trewlie, and I was nerehan&dtail; in despayr becauce
&thorn;er was none att ansswer for me.  And &thorn;a&ntail; almyghti
God hel&dtail; me with His han&dtail; &amp; say&dtail;; 'ffolow Me,
ffor &thorn;ou prechi&dtail; for Me.'  And onone &thorn;e fendes
fledd, and I folowi&dtail; Cryste vnto evurlastand ioy; and I had none
other pay&ntail; bod alonelie &thorn;is drede."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXXXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Predicatori infundit deus aliquando scienciam.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how some tyme &thorn;er was a symeple monke, &amp;
he was bod ane ydiott, bod he was devowte.  And o&ntail; a tyme
hy&mtail; thoght in his slepe &thorn;at he was ravisshi&dtail; in-to
hevy&ntail; &amp; was cled in aray like a deky&ntail; befo&rtail;
Go&dtail;, as he sulde hafe re&dtail; &thorn;e gospe&llbar;.  And
whe&ntail; he sulde hafe axke&dtail; &thorn;e blissing <NOTE ID="P423.N3">MS. blissid.  Harl. MS. a quo cum benedictionem acciperet.</NOTE> , hy&mtail; &thorn;oght at &thorn;is was say&dtail;
vnto hy&mtail;; "Fro &thorn;is day forwar&dtail; &thorn;ou sha&llbar;
hafe connyng &amp; vertue in prechyng &thorn;e wur&dtail; of God."
And he was gretelie mervayli&dtail; of &thorn;is visio&ntail; at
hy&mtail; &thorn;oght he saw so oppynlie, and &thorn;oght he
wol&dtail; rede &thorn;e gospe&llbar; &thorn;at day, if so wer at
&thorn;e sacresta&ntail; ordan&dtail; hy&mtail; suche a stole and a
vestement as he saw in hevy&ntail; ffor &thorn;a&ntail; he wol&dtail;
trow at his visio&ntail; wer trew.  And so whe&ntail; he come in-to
&thorn;e revestiarie, &amp; saw &thorn;e stole and &thorn;e vestiment
at was lay&dtail; furt&hbar; for &thorn;e deky&ntail;, he knew it wele
enog&hbar;; &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; he was certay&ntail; of his
visio&ntail; and went vnto his abbott &amp; tolde hy&mtail; a&llbar;
&thorn;at he had









<PB N="424">

sene.  And he commandi&dtail; hy&mtail; go rede &thorn;e gospe&llbar;
&amp; for to preche.  And so he di&dtail;, and he fe&llbar; vnto
prechyng and prechi&dtail; so clerklie at vnto &thorn;is day his
saying is take&ntail; for auctorite.  And a&llbar; me&ntail; &thorn;at
har&dtail; hy&mtail; had grete mervayle how &thorn;at he, &thorn;at
had no connyng befo&rtail;, had so connynglie prechud, &amp; had so
grett perfeccio&ntail; in conyng.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Predicantes demon nititur impedire.  Supra de

auditu.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXXXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Predicator ea que predicat debet facere.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iohannes Anachorita was a monk in wyldernes, and was
enowrne&dtail; with &thorn;e flour of a&llbar; maner of vertues; and
he was in bodye lyke vnto ane aunge&llbar;.  And he was sent ilk day
his fude fro&mtail; almyghti Go&dtail;, ffor evure day he wol&dtail;
go into his cafe, &amp; &thorn;er he fand a burd, &amp; brea&dtail;
sett &thorn;er vppo&ntail; &thorn;at was passand white &amp; of a
mervalus swetnes.  &amp; whe&ntail; he had ety&ntail; &thorn;er-of, he
wol&dtail; &thorn;onk Go&dtail; &amp; go vnto his prayers and his
ympnes.  And whe&ntail; he bega&ntail; to hafe a ioy of his merettis,
onone &thorn;er entred into hy&mtail; certa&ntail; desyris of his witt
be little &amp; litle, at he mot vunethis purseyve &thorn;aim, and
afterwar&dtail; gretter, vnto so muc&hbar; at he wexid necligent,
&amp; mo&rtail; slow in his prayers &thorn;a&ntail; he was wunte to
be.  And so &thorn;er folowi&dtail; in his hert fowle thoghtis &amp;
wykki&dtail;, &amp; he made no charge to correcte hy&mtail; for
&thorn;ies little thyngis.  So o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; he was
streky&ntail; with a grete luste of his fless&hbar;, he went into his
cafe to take hy&mtail; brea&dtail;, and he fand brea&dtail;, bod it
was browner somwhatt &thorn;a&ntail; <NOTE ID="P424.N1">MS. &thorn;at.</NOTE> &thorn;e
toder was; &amp; he had grete merve&llbar; &thorn;eroff &amp; was
passan&dtail; hevye.  Notwithstondyng he ete &thorn;erof and
refresshi&dtail; hy&mtail;.  And vppo&ntail; &thorn;e toder day his
thoghtis grew apo&ntail; hy&mtail;, &amp; o&ntail; &thorn;e nyght
hy&mtail; thoght he lay be a womma&ntail;; neuer-&thorn;e-les in
&thorn;e mornyng he went vnto his prayers, &amp; stude with a waveryng
ee and a waveryng mynde.  So he went into his



<PB N="425">

cave to take hy&mtail; meate, and he fan&dtail; a lafe, bod it was
passand brow&ntail;, &amp; hard &thorn;erwith, and as it had bene
gnawe&ntail; a&llbar; aboute with myce.  An&dtail; &thorn;a&ntail; he
bega&ntail; to make sorow &amp; weppyd, bod his sorow was not so great
to distroy &thorn;e flawmys of his i&llbar; thoghtis.  So at &thorn;e
laste he was ouercomme&ntail; with thoghtis, to so muc&hbar; &thorn;at
at mydnyght he rase &amp; went vnto &thorn;e cetie; and whe&ntail; it
was day he was war of a lity&llbar; ce&llbar; of freers &amp; he was
werye, &amp; &thorn;er he resti&dtail; hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;e
brethur bega&ntail; to axke of hy&mtail;, as of a wyse fadur, who may
esshew &thorn;e temptacions of &thorn;e devu&llbar; &amp; evu&llbar;
thoghtis.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he sufficientlie techan&dtail;
&thorn;ai&mtail; turny&dtail; agay&ntail; vnto hy&mtail; selfe &amp;
say&dtail;; "How may I comman&dtail; other me&ntail; &amp; is
deseyvi&dtail; my selfe?"  And &thorn;a&ntail; he sai&dtail; vnto
hy&mtail; selfe &thorn;us; "O &thorn;ou wriche!  Do furste &thorn;i
selfe at &thorn;ou techis o&thorn;er me&ntail; to do."  And he tuke
his lefe at his brethur &amp; ra&ntail; als faste as he myght into
wyldernes vnto his cafe agay&ntail;, &amp; &thorn;er he sparri&dtail;
hy&mtail; selfe &thorn;erin, &amp; cled his bodie in hare &amp; putt
askis o&ntail; his hea&dtail;.  &amp; &thorn;er he lay a long tyme in
prayers &amp; wepyngis, vnto ane ange&llbar; come vnto hy&mtail; &amp;
say&dtail; "Almighti God hase reseyvi&dtail; &thorn;i prayers and
&thorn;i penance, bod fro hens furt&hbar; bewar at &thorn;ou wex no
mo&rtail; prowde, and so be deseyvi&dtail; whe&ntail; &thorn;ou leste
wenys."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXXXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Predicator devotus vbique feruenter predicat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in &thorn;e 'Gestis of Bede' whe&ntail; for grete age his
sight fayli&dtail; hy&mtail;, he had a leder to lede hy&mtail; to
townes &amp; castels, &amp; in evur-ilk place &thorn;er he come he
wolde preche &thorn;e wurde of God.  So o&ntail; a tyme as &thorn;ai
went &thorn;urg&hbar; a valie fu&llbar; of stonys, his leder in a
skor&ntail; tolde hy&mtail; at &thorn;er was a huge peple, &thorn;at
bade vppo&ntail; hy&mtail; in sylence to here hy&mtail; preche, and
&thorn;a&ntail; he bega&ntail; ferventlie to preche.  And whe&ntail;
he had done, &amp; concludi&dtail; his sermo&ntail; with ' <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">per omnia secula seculorum,</FOREIGN>' onone, as me&ntail;
sais, &thorn;e stonys with a hye voyce crie&dtail; &amp; say&dtail;; "
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Amen!  Venerabilis pater!</FOREIGN>" So&mtail;
says &thorn;at aungels ansswer&dtail; &amp; say&dtail;; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Amen!  Bene, venerabilis pater, dixisti!</FOREIGN>"

<PB N="426">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXXXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Predicator discrete debet predicare secundum

condiciones audientium.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was at Athens a yong
ma&ntail; &thorn;at hight Pollonius, &amp; he was gyffe&ntail; to
suche luste of his bodie &thorn;at he had grete ioy in his infame.  So
o&ntail; a tyme he was at a feste, &amp; he satt &thorn;er not
alonelie vnto &thorn;e so&ntail; sett, bod also vnto &thorn;e
mor&ntail; at &thorn;e so&ntail; rase.  &amp; he was fu&llbar; of wyne
and of gude meatis, &amp; had enoynti&dtail; hy&mtail; with precious
oyntementis, he cled hy&mtail; in gay clothyng, &amp; made hy&mtail; a
gay hea&dtail; &amp; went home.  So hy&mtail; happend se &thorn;e
scolehowse dure oppy&ntail; of one &thorn;at hight Zenoccrates
&thorn;at was techan&dtail;; he went in at he mot here what he
sai&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; a&llbar; &thorn;e scolers loghe at
hy&mtail; &amp; had grete disdey&ntail; at he come in, &thorn;is
Zenocrates with a merie chere bega&ntail; to preche hy&mtail; of
sobernes and temperans, not-with-stondyng a&llbar; &thorn;at he
say&dtail; befo&rtail;.  And &thorn;urg&hbar; sadnes of his wurdis
&thorn;is Pollonius was gretelie movi&dtail;, so &thorn;at he keste of
&thorn;e hatt &thorn;at was o&ntail; his head, &amp; afterwar&dtail;
he keste of his gay clothyng &amp; was passan&dtail; glad of his
prechyng.  And at &thorn;e laste he lefte a&llbar; his luste &amp;
lykyng &thorn;at he had in lychorie, and become a gude ma&ntail;.  And
&thorn;us with medcy&ntail; of ane how&rtail; he was heli&dtail; of
a&llbar; hys infame. et c&curl;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXXXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Predicacio cum bono modo et gestu multum
valet.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis of one &thorn;at hight Eschines commendid gretelie
Demostenis eloquens <NOTE ID="P426.N1">MS. Eschines Demostenis commendid gretelie eloquens.  Harl. MS.  Eschines Demostenis eloquentiam commendabat.</NOTE> ; and he sai&dtail; he
consydur&dtail; &thorn;erin a bytter strent&hbar; of ee&ntail; and a
ferdfu&llbar; chere, and a hevye burdy&ntail;, &amp; in evure
wur&dtail; a sown&dtail; of voyce, &amp; at he knew &thorn;er-in
&thorn;e spedefu&llbar; movyngis of &thorn;e bodie, vnto so
meki&llbar; &thorn;at nothyng mot be putt vnto &thorn;e nede
&thorn;eroff.  Neuer-&thorn;e-les a grete parte of Demostenes wantys
whe&ntail; it is re&dtail;, mo&rtail; &thorn;a&ntail; whe&ntail; it is
har&dtail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Predo.  Predonem deus in hac vita remunerat si aliqua

bona ab eo sint facta.  Infra de remuneracione.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>




<PB N="427">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXL.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Prelatus racione carnalitatis non debet
eligi.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis of one Fabius, &thorn;at was a grete cowncelur of
Rome; &amp; he govern[id] nobyllie after his grawncer &amp; his fadur
&thorn;e offes of cownce&llbar; &thorn;at he bare.  So o&ntail; a tyme
&thorn;e peple desyrid gretelie &thorn;at his so&ntail; sulde be made
a cowncelur of Rome, and he alone, als muche as he myght, laburde to
lett it.  Notwithstondyng he was not dowtan&dtail; of &thorn;e vertues
of hys sc&ntail;, for he was passan&dtail; connyng, bod for cauce he
wol&dtail; not hafe many maisters in one howshol&dtail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Prelatus non debet eligi puer.  Infra de puero, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Prelatus non debet eligi pauper vel auarus.  Supra

de balliuo.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXLI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Prelatus debet condescendere moribus subditorum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis how o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;e consullis of Rome
desyri&dtail; gretelie one &thorn;at hyght Manliciosus <NOTE ID="P427.N1">Harl. MS. Cum consulatus Manlio, seni, . . . offerreretur.</NOTE> to be of cownce&llbar; with &thorn;aim, and evur he
excusi&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; say&dtail; nay, &amp; sai&dtail; his
syght fayli&dtail; hy&mtail;; bod nevur-&thorn;e-les &thorn;ai
a&llbar; labur&dtail; hy&mtail; hugelie therto <NOTE ID="P427.N2">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, hugelie, <HI REND="i">here</HI>.</NOTE>
.  And evur he bad &thorn;aim take a noder in-to &thorn;at
wurschu&ptail;, ffor he sai&dtail;; "And ye make me to bere itt, I may
not suffer your maners, nor ye may not suffer me to hafe rewle
abow&ntail; you, nor ye wu&llbar; not fulfy&llbar; my commandmenttis."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXLII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Prelatus non debet se ingerere.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Hugo Florianensis tellis whe&ntail; &thorn;e knyghtis of Rome saw
Vaspasya&ntail;, at he was a nobyl ma&ntail; and a redy to
cownce&llbar;, and comfurthable to yong men in bate&llbar;, &thorn;ai
besoght hy&mtail; at he wol&dtail; take governance of &thorn;e empyre
of Rome.  And whe&ntail; he denye&dtail;






<PB N="428">

&thorn;aim &amp; say&dtail; he was not wurthie &thorn;erto, &amp;
&thorn;ai labur&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;erto daylie, at &thorn;e laste
he graunty&dtail; vnto &thorn;aim, &thorn;uf a&llbar; it wer agayns
his wi&llbar;, at he wulde furste tytter take &thorn;e charge of
&thorn;e empyre rather &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e wurschu&ptail;
&thorn;eroff.  And whe&ntail; he had reseyvi&dtail; &thorn;e empyre he
say&dtail; &thorn;at in his begynyng onone he wol&dtail; clens
&thorn;aim at wer fowle, &amp; putt vnwurthi me&ntail; oute of
&thorn;er placis and fulfy&llbar; &thorn;air row&mtail; with honeste
me&ntail;.  And he was neuer prowde nor statelye, bod a&llbar;-way
consydur&dtail; of what kynry&dtail; at he come; &amp; he wol&dtail;
neuer do grete punysshment for offens.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXLIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Prelatus non debet superbire.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Helinandus tellis how som tyme in &thorn;e kyngdo&mtail; of Iurie
&thorn;er was a hurd-ma&ntail; &thorn;at hight Gygens, &thorn;at
o&ntail; a tyme after a grete ray&ntail; he went dow&ntail; in-to a
law cra&ktee; in &thorn;e erde, and &thorn;er he fande a ma&ntail;
dead, syttand vppo&ntail; a hors of bras.  And vppo&ntail; his fynger
he fande a ryng, be &thorn;e whilk he made hy&mtail; selfe invisible,
&amp; lay be &thorn;e whene; &amp; als sone as sho knew &thorn;is sho
garte sla &thorn;e kyng <NOTE ID="P428.N1">MS. kyngdo&mtail;, -do&mtail; <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> , &amp; he
vsurpi&dtail; &thorn;e kyngdo&mtail;.  And Valerius tellis &thorn;at
whe&ntail; he had gette&ntail; &thorn;e kyngdo&mtail; be &thorn;is
chawnce, he wexi&dtail; so prowde &thorn;at he axki&dtail;
cownce&llbar; of Apollo his go&dtail;, if &thorn;er war any in
&thorn;is werl&dtail; &thorn;at was happyer &thorn;a&ntail; he was.
And Apollo ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;;
"&thorn;ou sulde be bettur provi&dtail; with sekurtie of a sheperde
tofa&llbar; &thorn;a&ntail; for to hafe a grete ha&llbar; &amp;
lathis, &amp; giff &thorn;i selfe to grete charge an&dtail; besynes;
for it is bettur vnto a ma&ntail; [hafe] bod att hy&mtail; nedis vnto
his lyfe, and so for to hal&dtail; hy&mtail; plesi&dtail;,
&thorn;a&ntail; for to gett hy&mtail; samen grete tresurs &amp; evur
lyff in drede and covatyce."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXLIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Prelatus non debet esse crudelis nec facere vnde

odio habeatur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis how o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; Dionisius Situlus
shewi&dtail; hy&mtail; selfe vnto his [suggettis] <NOTE ID="P428.N2">Lat. MSS. subditis suis; Engl. MS. tyrandis.</NOTE> mo&rtail; to be a tyraunt &thorn;a&ntail; a prince,





<PB N="429">

he was so hatefu&llbar; vnto a&llbar; me&ntail; at a&llbar; folk
desyri&dtail; at he had had a myschefe.  Neuer-&thorn;e-les one
ol&dtail; wyfe evurilk day in matyn-tyme prayed vnto &thorn;er goddis
to kepe hy&mtail; hale &amp; sownd.  And whe&ntail; he axke&dtail; hur
&thorn;e cauce at sho did so fo&rtail;, and sho ansswer&dtail; hym
agay&ntail; &amp; sayd; "Me had levur hafe &thorn;e a grevus
tyran&dtail; as &thorn;ou erte, &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ou sulde dye
&amp; a war succede after &thorn;e; and &thorn;erfo&rtail; I bow
dow&ntail; hy hea&dtail; &amp; prayes for the."  &amp; whe&ntail; he
her&dtail; hur say &thorn;us <NOTE ID="P429.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, &thorn;us.</NOTE> he wexi&dtail;
confusi&dtail; &amp; ashamy&dtail;, and bega&ntail; to forthynk and
amend hy&mtail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Prelatus aliquando morte subitanea moritur.  Supra

de archidiacono.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Prelatus a demone aliquando deportatur.  Supra de

demone, v.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Prelatus eciam malus 
<NOTE ID="P429.N2">MS. malos.</NOTE>  debet subditos in disciplina

tenere.  Supra de abbatissa 
<NOTE ID="P429.N3"><HI REND="i">Reference from</HI> Lat. MSS.</NOTE> , i.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXLV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Prelatus debet esse communis et affabilis [omnibus] 
<NOTE ID="P429.N4"><HI REND="i">From</HI> Lat. MSS.</NOTE> .</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Seutonius tellis how &thorn;at whe&ntail; Titus was made emperour,
he vsi&dtail; to make mony rya&llbar; festis, &amp; he wol&dtail;
dispyse no cetysy&ntail;, bod gladlie wol&dtail; speke with &thorn;aim
&amp; here what &thorn;ai say&dtail;; &amp; he wol&dtail; neuer gyff o
ma&ntail; bettyr gyfte &thorn;an a noder.  And he was so beneuolus at
he wol&dtail; latt none go away fro&mtail; hy&mtail; with-owty&ntail;
a gude hope.  So o&ntail; a tyme his howshol&dtail;-me&ntail;
cowncel&dtail; hy&mtail; at he sulde not do so, and he ansswer&dtail;
&thorn;aim agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail; &thorn;er sulde no ma&ntail;
go hevylie away &thorn;urg&hbar; &thorn;e wurdis of a prince.  So
o&ntail; a day whe&ntail; he went to supper, he vmthoght hy&mtail; how
&thorn;at he had &thorn;at day nothyng nowder gyffe&ntail; nor lent,
and he sai&dtail; unto hy&mtail; selfe; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Diem
perdidisti.</FOREIGN>" Also Eutropius tellis of Troiay&ntail;,
&thorn;at whe&ntail; his frendis blamy&dtail; hy&mtail; for he was so
hamelie with evure ma&ntail;, he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
sai&dtail;; "Ane emperour sulde be suc&hbar; a









<PB N="430">

ma&ntail; outewar&dtail; anence his commons as he wol&dtail; &thorn;ai
war inwar&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; agay&ntail;."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Prelatus pauperes debet habere in reuerencia.  Supra

de iudicio vltimo.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
