<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXLVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Presumpcio.  Presumunt aliqui plus quam deberent

de statu suo.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' of ane abbott &thorn;at hight
Ioh&ntail;, &thorn;at &thorn;oght he wol&dtail; seryff a&llbar;myghtie
God in maner as aungels duse, and he doffi&dtail; a&llbar; his clothis
and he stude a&llbar; a weke so in wyldernes.  And whe&ntail; he was
like to periss&hbar; for hunger &amp; was shrewidlie wowndi&dtail;
with waspis &amp; fleis, he turny&dtail; agay&ntail; vnto his bruther
dure, &amp; knokki&dtail; &thorn;er-att.  And he axki&dtail; who was
&thorn;er, and he say&dtail;; "I, Ioh&ntail;."  And his bruther
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sayd; "Nay, it is not Ioh&ntail;, for
Ioh&ntail; is made ane aunge&llbar; &amp; wy&llbar; be no mo&rtail;
emang me&ntail;."  And he sai&dtail; agay&ntail;; "Forsuthe I am he."
And he wol&dtail; not oppy&ntail; &thorn;e dure, bod lete hy&mtail;
alone stondyng &thorn;er vnto in &thorn;e mornyng o&ntail; &thorn;e
toder day.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he oppyn&dtail; &thorn;e dure &amp;
sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "And &thorn;ou be a ma&ntail;, &thorn;ou
hase myster to hafe &thorn;e dure opyn&dtail;, and to hafe meatt and
war&mtail; &thorn;e; and if &thorn;ou be ane ange&llbar;, wharto
desyris &thorn;ou to come in-to my ce&llbar;?"  And &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;is Ioh&ntail; say&dtail; agay&ntail; vnto hy&mtail;; "Bruther,
I pray &thorn;e forgyff me, ffor I know my selfe &thorn;at I hafe
synny&dtail;."

</P>
<P>
