<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXLVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Presumptuosum est verb[a] subtilia et alta loqui.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Dictis Patrum' <NOTE ID="P432.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, we rede.</NOTE> of ane ankyr,
whe&ntail; he come vnto &thorn;e cetie of Pemenen, &thorn;er was a
gude ma&ntail; reseyvi&dtail; with gladnes hy&mtail;.  And as
&thorn;ai satt, &thorn;is ankyr bega&ntail; to talke of holie writt,
and of privaties of hevy&ntail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is olde
ma&ntail; turny&dtail; his face vnto a noder of his brethir, and
wol&dtail; nothyng ansswer &thorn;is ankyr; and so he went furt&hbar;
and was passand hevye.  So a disciple come vnto &thorn;is olde abbott
&amp; say&dtail;; "For &thorn;e come &thorn;is ma&ntail; hedur,
&thorn;at had grete myrt&hbar; at home in his aw&ntail; place, and
&thorn;ou dedeynys not now to speke vnto hy&mtail;."  This olde abbott
ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; ayey&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "He is a
ma&ntail; of hie placys, &amp; spekis a&llbar; of hevynlie thyngis;
and I a&mtail; a ma&ntail; of law place, and vnnethis I may vnderstond
erdlie thyngis."  And &thorn;is dissiple went furt&hbar; &amp; tolde
&thorn;is ankir what he sai&dtail;.  And he was gretelie compuncte
here-with, &amp; went in-to &thorn;is olde abbott agay&ntail; &amp;
sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "What shall <NOTE ID="P432.N2">MS. shat.</NOTE> I do,
ffadur abbott?  For &thorn;e passions of my sawle hase lordschu&ptail;
on me."  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is ol&dtail; abbott had ioy of
hy&mtail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Now &thorn;ou erte welco&mtail;, fadur.
Oppy&ntail; &thorn;erfo&rtail; my mowthe and I sa&llbar; fulfy&llbar;
it with &thorn;i gudis."  And with &thorn;is wur&dtail; &thorn;is
ankir was gretlie comfurthi&dtail; &amp; sayde; "Forsuthe it is a gude
way at &thorn;ou holdes, &amp; a trew."  And &thorn;a&ntail; he
thanki&dtail; &thorn;is olde abbott &amp; went agay&ntail; vnto his
aw&ntail; regio&ntail;.

</P>
<P>
