<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXLIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Prodigalitas multa mala facit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Seutonius tellis how &thorn;at Nero &thorn;e emperour was so
statelie &thorn;at he trowe&dtail; &thorn;e frute of <NOTE ID="P433.N2">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, of.</NOTE> riches and of money was no nodur &thorn;ing bod
ordynance made for a mans expens, vnto so meku&llbar; at he wuld nevur
were a garment twyce, and he wol&dtail; fyss&hbar; with a nett made of
gol&dtail; wyre, and a&llbar; &thorn;e duris of his pales was made of
evurye &amp; enownti&dtail; with precious oyntementis.  And he had
rown&dtail; chawmers &thorn;erin, &thorn;at day &amp; nyght
turny&dtail; abowte as &thorn;e firmament duse.  And yit at &thorn;e
laste hy&mtail; &thorn;oght he had not tresur enog&hbar;, bod he gart
punyss&hbar; and sla dyvers ryche me&ntail; at he myght hafe &thorn;er
gudis.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCL.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Promissio.  Promissum debet solui.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Petrus Alphonsis <NOTE ID="P433.N3">MS. Alphensis, <HI REND="i">as elsewhere</HI>, for Alphonsus.</NOTE> tellis how so&mtail; tyme
&thorn;er was a knygh[t], and hy&mtail; happend o&ntail; a tyme to
lose a sakett and a thowsan&dtail; talentis &thorn;erin and a serpent
of gol&dtail;; and a pure ma&ntail; happend to fyn&dtail; itt.  And he
garte cry it in &thorn;e markett, &amp; promysi&dtail; in his cry
&thorn;at he &thorn;att had fo&ntail; itt sulde hafe for &thorn;e
fyndyng &thorn;erof a hondret&hbar; of &thorn;e talentis with gude
wi&llbar;.  So &thorn;is pure ma&ntail; at fand it &thorn;oght
hy&mtail; had levur hafe les with-owte&ntail; sy&ntail;
&thorn;a&ntail; more








<PB N="434">

with sy&ntail;, &thorn;uf a&llbar; his wyfe agay&ntail;-sai&dtail; it,
[&] gaff agay&ntail; &thorn;is sakett vnto &thorn;e knyght &amp;
aski&dtail; &thorn;erof a hondret&hbar; talentis as he promysi&dtail;
in his cry.  Bod &thorn;e riche ma&ntail;, whe&ntail; he had &thorn;e
sakett agay&ntail;, wolde not pay &thorn;e salfay, and he sai&dtail;
&thorn;er was ij serpentis of gol&dtail; in &thorn;e sakett, &amp; at
&thorn;e pure ma&ntail; had with-drawe&ntail; &thorn;e tone of
&thorn;ai&mtail;.  And &thorn;e pure ma&ntail; sai&dtail; nay; so he
compleny&dtail; of &thorn;is pure ma&ntail; &amp; &thorn;ai war bothe
broght afo&rtail; &thorn;e knyg.  And evur-ilk ma&ntail; hel&dtail;
with &thorn;e riche ma&ntail;, &amp; none with &thorn;e pure
ma&ntail;.  So &thorn;er was a philosophyr &amp; he had grete petie of
&thorn;is pure ma&ntail;, and say&dtail; vnto &thorn;e kyng in
&thorn;is maner of wyse; "Sur kyng!  It is meku&llbar; to trow vnto
&thorn;is riche ma&ntail;, for he wol&dtail; not say at he loste ij
serpentis of gol&dtail; bod if he did so.  And o&ntail; &thorn;e toder
partie, &thorn;is pure ma&ntail; at fand &thorn;is gude, and he had
not bene a gude ma&ntail; and a trew, he mot hafe holde&ntail;
a&llbar; &thorn;is gude privalie, &amp; nevur giffe&ntail; it
agay&ntail;.  And &thorn;erfo&rtail; ca&llbar; &thorn;e riche
ma&ntail; &amp; say vnto hy&mtail; in &thorn;is maner of wyse; 'This
sakett and &thorn;is gol&dtail; is not &thorn;ine, for &thorn;ou says
&thorn;ou lost ij serpentynys &amp; here-in is bod one,' &amp; kepe
&thorn;is sty&llbar; in your handis &amp; gar cry agay&ntail; in
&thorn;e markett a sakett with ij serpentynys &thorn;erin."  And
whe&ntail; &thorn;is riche ma&ntail; har&dtail; &thorn;is, at he sulde
be &thorn;us bety&ntail; with his aw&ntail; staff, he grawnty&dtail;
vnto &thorn;e kyng at he sai&dtail; &thorn;er was ij serpentynys in
&thorn;e sackett whe&ntail; &thorn;er was bod one, becauce he
wol&dtail; nott hafe gyffe&ntail; &thorn;e pure ma&ntail; a
hondret&hbar; talentis to safye, as he promysi&dtail; he sulde do.
And whe&ntail; &thorn;e kyng har&dtail; &thorn;is, he made &thorn;e
riche ma&ntail; to pay vnto &thorn;is pure ma&ntail; &thorn;is
hundret&hbar; talenttis, as he promysi&dtail; he sulde doo.

</P>
