<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Prosperitas est aliquando signum aduersitatis
future.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in &thorn;e 'Legent of Saynt Ambros' how o&ntail; a tyme
as Saynt Ambros went to Rome-ward and was herber&dtail; at a riche
ma&ntail; howse in a tow&ntail; in Tussie, he emang oder carpyngis
askid hy&mtail; of his astate.  And he ansswerd agay&ntail; &amp;
sayd; "Sur, my state was evur happie &amp; glorious, ffor I hafe at
wi&llbar; grete riches, many servandis, many childer, &amp; many
cussyns, and a&llbar; &thorn;ies I hafe evur had at my liste.  And I
had nevur none aduersitie."  And whe&ntail; Saynt Ambros har&dtail;
&thorn;is, he had meku&llbar; merve&llbar; &amp; sayd vnto his felows;
"Ryse, go we hyne, for God is not in &thorn;is place; and
&thorn;erfo&rtail; haste us hyne at &thorn;e vengeange of God
ta&ktee; vs not here."  So in &thorn;e mornyng &thorn;ai <NOTE ID="P436.N2">MS. &thorn;at.</NOTE> gatt &thorn;aim faste v&ptail; &amp; wente &thorn;er
wayes; and whe&ntail; &thorn;ai war passi&dtail; a little, &thorn;ai
luki&dtail; behynd &thorn;aim, and sodanly &thorn;e ert&hbar;
oppyn&dtail; and swolu&dtail; &thorn;is ma&ntail; &amp; a&llbar;
&thorn;at longi&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;, at &thorn;er was nothyng left
aboue erde.  And whe&ntail; Saynt Ambros saw &thorn;is, he sayd vnto
his felaschu&ptail;; "Lo!  brethur, how mercyfu&llbar; at God is!
For He sparis &thorn;aim at He sendis aduersitie &amp; truble in
&thorn;is werl&dtail;, &amp; how felly He is grevud vnto &thorn;aim at
He sendis prosperite and no dissese."  And in witnes here-of yit vnto
&thorn;is day in &thorn;at <NOTE ID="P436.N3">MS. &thorn;a&ntail;.</NOTE> place &thorn;er is a
passan&dtail; depe dyke <NOTE ID="P436.N4">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, dyke.</NOTE> , calli&dtail; &thorn;e
ric&hbar;e ma&ntail; pitt of Tuscan <NOTE ID="P436.N5"><HI REND="i">This Legend has two hands pointing to it</HI>, nota, <HI REND="i">written above them</HI>.</NOTE> .












<PB N="437">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Providencia dei infallibilis est.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede of &thorn;e kyng of Crete he was a semelie ma&ntail;,
&amp; he had a nygromancier in his courte at hight Estus.  And
&thorn;is kyng had a doghter, and &thorn;is Estus happend to gett hur
with childe.  And whe&ntail; it was born, for tene &thorn;is kyng hur
fadur garte caste it oute in &thorn;e wud emang wylde bestis.  So
with-in a while after hunters fand it in a cafe emang wyle bestis,
&amp; &thorn;er it was nurisshid with hur mylk.  And whe&ntail; it was
broght home in a strayte gate whar cate&llbar; vsy&dtail; to co&mtail;
by, and whe&ntail; he saw &thorn;ai wolde do it no skathe bod rather
norysshi&dtail; it, he commaundi&dtail; at it sulde be caste&ntail;
vnto hundis &thorn;at long had bene kepy&dtail; fastyng, at &thorn;ai
mott destroy itt, &amp; &thorn;ai wol&dtail; do it no skathe.  &amp;
&thorn;a&ntail; he garte caste it emang swyne at &thorn;ai mott
devow&rtail; it; and &thorn;er it was nurisshi&dtail; o&ntail; a sew
pap&ptail;.  And whe&ntail; he saw &thorn;at, he garte caste it in-to
&thorn;e occia&ntail;; and whe&ntail; it was caste&ntail; &thorn;er,
&thorn;is Estus, &thorn;e fadur &thorn;erof, be his craft broght it
vnto &thorn;e lan&dtail; agay&ntail; whik&ktee;; &amp; &thorn;er it
was nurisshid with a hynde.  And fro thens furt&hbar; it wexid so
swyfte of fute at whare at evur &thorn;e hartys went it wol&dtail; go
with &thorn;aim.  So at &thorn;e laste it was take&ntail; in a snare,
&amp; broght to &thorn;e kyng &amp; gyffe&ntail; hy&mtail; to a
present.  And onone he knew it &amp; had compassio&ntail;
&thorn;eroff, &amp; garte name it &amp; nurtur it; &amp; &thorn;e name
&thorn;er-of was Avidus.  And afterwar&dtail; he made it his
successur.  And &thorn;is kyng Avidus, as we rede, was furste
&thorn;at evur garte tame oxe&ntail; &amp; lear&ntail; &thorn;aim to
draw; and he was furst &thorn;at evur fand pleug&hbar;, &amp; he taght
me&ntail; to plew &amp; to saw whete &amp; o&thorn;er cornys <NOTE ID="P437.N1"><HI REND="i">A sidenote here has a small hand pointing to the words</HI> [Su]pra de [in]vencione aratri.</NOTE> .

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Providet Deus suis in necessarijs.  Supra Benedicti

et de hospite, iij, et iiij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Providencia in futurum est laudabilis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Barlaa&mtail; tellis how &thorn;at in a cetie beyond se &thorn;e
cetysyns had suche a custo&mtail; &thorn;at euerilk yere &thorn;ai
wolde chalange a strange




<PB N="438">

ma&ntail;, &amp; chese hy&mtail; vnto &thorn;er kyng &thorn;at knew
nothyng of &thorn;e lawis of &thorn;e cetie.  And alway fro he war
chosy&ntail; he sul&dtail; hafe his commandmentis fulfylli&dtail; vnto
&thorn;e yere end, &amp; what at evur he bad be sude be done.  And
whe&ntail; &thorn;at yere was gone, whe&ntail; hy&mtail; thoght he was
in his moste sekurtie &amp; his moste mirthe, sodanlie &thorn;e
cetyzens wolde rise vppo&ntail; hy&mtail; and wolde take fro&mtail;
hy&mtail; &thorn;e kyngis crow&ntail; &amp; naky&ntail; hy&mtail;
&amp; harle hy&mtail; &thorn;urg&hbar; &thorn;e cetie, &amp; send
hy&mtail; in-to ane yle in &thorn;e se &thorn;er he sulde nowder hafe
mete nor clothe, bod at he sulde &thorn;er dye for honger &amp; sorow.
So o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;er was a ma&ntail; made kyng &thorn;at
vnderstude &thorn;is custo&mtail; &amp; &thorn;is law at &thorn;ai
hadd, and whe&ntail; he was made kyng he garte opy&ntail; &thorn;e
kyngis tresurie, and sent a grete copye &thorn;eroff into &thorn;is
yle.  And whe&ntail; his yere was done &amp; he was sent into
&thorn;is ile, he had habundance enog&hbar; of riches at he had ordand
fo&rtail; be hys wisdo&mtail; ewhyls he liffi&dtail; as a kyng in
&thorn;e cete.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Prudencia necessaria est multis.  Supra de cautela

et provisione.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Puer desponsauit ymaginem beate Marie
Virginis.</FOREIGN></HEAD> <P> We rede in &thorn;e 'Mereclas of Our
Ladye' how som tyme &thorn;er was a felashi&ptail; of childer
&thorn;at vsi&dtail; to play at hand-ba&llbar; befo&rtail; a
kur&ktee;; and &thorn;er was one of &thorn;aim &thorn;at had on his
han&dtail; a ryng whilk &thorn;at a maydy&ntail; &thorn;at
luffi&dtail; hy&mtail; be flesshly luff had gyffe&ntail; hy&mtail;.
And he was ferde at he with his faste rynyng at &thorn;e ba&llbar;
sulde breke it, and he went in-to &thorn;e kur&ktee; to gyff som
bodie it to kepe to he had layki&dtail; hy&mtail;.  And whe&ntail; he
come befo&rtail; &thorn;e ymage of our Lady, he stude merve&llbar;and
and beheld hur fayrnes, &amp; he set hy&mtail; dow&ntail; o&ntail; his
kne and deuotelie sayd afo&rtail; hur his Ave Maria.  And whe&ntail;
he had done he sai&dtail; vnto hur; "Forsut&hbar;, Ladie, &thorn;ou
erte fayrer &thorn;a&ntail; any o&thorn;er &amp; mo&rtail; fayr
&thorn;a&ntail; sho &thorn;at gaff me &thorn;is ryng, and
&thorn;erfo&rtail; I forsake hur.  I, fro hens furt&hbar;, I wi&llbar;
luff the, so at &thorn;ou wy&llbar; luff me agay&ntail;."  And he
profur&dtail; &thorn;e ryng vnto &thorn;e ymage fynger, and &thorn;e
ymage put furth hur fynger streght &amp; he putt it o&ntail;.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e fynger closyd agay&ntail; vnto &thorn;e ymage
as it was are.  And

<PB N="439">

whe&ntail; he saw &thorn;is he had grete merve&llbar; &thorn;eroff
&amp; calli&dtail; his felous &amp; tolde &thorn;aim &amp; lete
&thorn;aim se itt.  So afterward hy&mtail; happend breke &thorn;is
promys and was we&dtail;, and o&ntail; &thorn;e furste nyght at he was
wed our Ladie come &amp; lay betwix hy&mtail; &amp; his wyfe, &amp;
putt furt&hbar; hur hand &amp; lete hy&mtail; se &thorn;e ryng on hur
fynger, &amp; reprovid hy&mtail; &thorn;at he had broke&ntail; his
beheste.  So with &thorn;at he wakynd &amp; grapyd after &thorn;e
ymage <NOTE ID="P439.N1">MS. ymange.</NOTE> &amp; fand hur not &thorn;er, &amp; lay
sty&llbar; &amp; trowed &thorn;at it had bene bod a fantasye.  So
afterwar&dtail; sho apperid vnto hy&mtail; &amp; thretid hy&mtail; att
he was fer&dtail; for hur.  And whe&ntail; he waken&dtail; o&ntail;
&thorn;e mor&ntail;, at evy&ntail; privalie he forsuke his wyfe &amp;
a&llbar; his gudis &amp; went to wyldernes, and &thorn;er devotelie he
servid our Ladie vnto his lyfis ende.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Puer ex actibus suis quandoque declarat qualis sit

futurus.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Cronicles' how o&ntail; a tyme kyng Agibundus, kyng of
Lombardie, soiorny&dtail; in Germanye, he fasted &amp; walki&dtail;
abowte, &amp; he fan&dtail; caste&ntail; in piscinam vij childer be a
commo&ntail; womma&ntail; for to sla &thorn;aim; and a&llbar;
&thorn;ies &thorn;is same commo&ntail; womma&ntail; had bor&ntail;.
And whe&ntail; &thorn;is knyght saw &thorn;aim he had grete mervayle
and put dow&ntail; a spere-shafte vnto &thorn;aim.  And ane of
&thorn;aim gat &thorn;e shafte with his han&dtail; be &thorn;e end
&amp; helde it sty&llbar;.  And &thorn;e kyng had merve&llbar; here-of
&amp; pullid hy&mtail; v&ptail;, &amp; garte nuryss&hbar; hy&mtail;
and namyd hy&mtail; Lawncelott <NOTE ID="P439.N2">Harl. MS. Lamissionem.  Arund. MS. Lancissionem.</NOTE> , &thorn;at is
als muc&hbar; to say as he &thorn;at sal be a grete ma&ntail; in tyme
to co&mtail;.  So afterwar&dtail; hy&mtail; happend to be of so grete
nobylnes &thorn;at whe&ntail; &thorn;e kyng was dead &thorn;e
Lombardis made hy&mtail; &thorn;er kyn&gtee;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Puer in purgatorio punitur.  Supra de blasfemia.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Puer non debet eligi in prelatum vel
presulem.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> <NOTE ID="P439.N3"><HI REND="i">This Exemplum is corrupt and part has been omitted from the Latin versions.</HI></NOTE> Helinandus tellis how &thorn;at Adrianus
&thorn;e emperour o&ntail; a tyme wolde algatis make his so&ntail;
emperour in his life.  And his princes









<PB N="440">

ansswerd hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail; &thorn;at it
longi&dtail; not alonelie vnto &thorn;e blude to hafe rewle; bod
rather vnto &thorn;e adlyngis &amp; vnto the governance.  And so his
desyre contynue&dtail;, and efterward he conseyvi&dtail; in his
myn&dtail; &thorn;at childer sulde furste be broght vp&ptail; and
excercysed in vertues, at &thorn;ai mot be provid what gouernance
&thorn;ai wolde be off or &thorn;ai war putt vnto any wurshu&ptail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Puer a demone temptatur.  Supra de blasfemia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Puella debet abscondere suam pulcritudinem.  Supra

de abscondere.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Puella debet solicite custodiri.  Supra de ffilia.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pulcritudo corporis debet abscondi ne alijs sit
dampnosa.</FOREIGN></HEAD> 


<P> Valerius tellis how &thorn;er was a fayr yong ma&ntail; &thorn;at
hight Spurannus, and he was so pratie &amp; so defte at yong
womme&ntail; wex evy&ntail; fon&dtail; o&ntail; hy&mtail;, and he was
ferd at &thorn;ai or &thorn;er fadurs shulde desyre hy&mtail; to be
maryd or to fa&llbar; vnto sy&ntail;.  And he wowndi&dtail; hy&mtail;
selfe his visage and his mout&hbar; to make hy&mtail; disfygur&dtail;
at &thorn;ai sulde not desyre hy&mtail;, and &thorn;oght hy&mtail; had
lyffer be deformy&dtail; &amp; liff in halynes&curl; &thorn;a&ntail;
daylie be a preparatyfe to o&thorn;er fol&ktee; luste &amp; sy&ntail;
&amp; wykkydnes.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Punicio.  Puniuntur corizantes.  Supra de

corizare.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Puniuntur gulosi.  Supra de gula, vj, et de

benediccione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Punitur quis per hec que peccauit.  Infra de

religiosis, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Puniuntur peccatores diuersi diuersimode.  Supra

et infra in locis suis.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>

<PB N="441">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Purgatorius.  Purgatorij pene sunt
diuerse.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iacobus de Vetriaco tellis &thorn;at whe&ntail; Saynt Marie of
Oginiez prayed for a certay&ntail; sawle vppo&ntail; Saynt Petur day
&thorn;e aposte&llbar;, Saynt Petur aperid vnto hur an&dtail; tolde
hur &thorn;e paynys at it was in &amp; &thorn;e cawsis &thorn;eroff,
and how at it was turment with huge hete becauce it luffid passynglie
&thorn;is werlde &amp; &thorn;e lustis &thorn;erof.  And som tyme it
was gretelie turment with a huge caldnes, becauce it was slaw to do
gudenes, &amp; neclegentlie governyd &thorn;e chylder &amp; &thorn;e
howsholde <NOTE ID="P441.N1"><HI REND="i">A sidenote says</HI>, [n]ota bene, <HI REND="i">here</HI>.</NOTE> .  And [som]tyme it was
punysshi&dtail; with hungre and threste, becauce it had grete
dilectacio&ntail; in meat &amp; dryn&ktee;.  An&dtail; sum tyme it
was gretelie punysshid with nakidnes, becauce it had in &thorn;e life
grete delectatio&ntail; in costious clothyng, &amp; to be passynglie
war&mtail; happed.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Purgatorij pena mitigatur oratione.  Supra de

oratione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Purgatorij pena soluitur missa.  Supra de

proprietario.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Purgatorij pena modico tempore diu videtur
durasse.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iacobus de Vetriaco tellis how som tyme [&thorn;er was] a synner
&thorn;at was correcte with a grete infirmytie, to so myky&llbar; he
praye&dtail; God to feche hy&mtail; oute of &thorn;is werlde.  And
whe&ntail; he had lang prayed so, ane aunge&llbar; come vnto hy&mtail;
and bad hy&mtail; chese whethur he wolde stonde ij dayes in purgatorie
or he wolde suffre his sekenes ij yere.  And he chose &thorn;e furste,
and decesid, and his saule went vnto purgatorie.  So with-in ane houre
after it was &thorn;er, &thorn;e ange&llbar; apperi&dtail; vnto
hy&mtail;, and he axkyd; "What ert &thorn;ou?"  &thorn;e ange&llbar;
ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "I a&mtail;
&thorn;e aunge&llbar; &thorn;at apperid vnto the whe&ntail; &thorn;ou
was olyfe."  And he said; "Nay, &thorn;ou erte none aunge&llbar;, ffor
aungells wy&llbar; not lye; and &thorn;ou erte bod a lyer, for
&thorn;ou tolde me &thorn;at I sulde be bod ij dayes in purgatorie,



<PB N="442">

and I hafe stand &thorn;erin many yeris."  The aunge&llbar; ansswerd
hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "&thorn;ou sa&llbar;
vnderstand at &thorn;ou haste not bene here nott fullie ane
how&rtail;."  And &thorn;a&ntail; he praye&dtail; &thorn;e
aunge&llbar; to bryng hy&mtail; agay&ntail; vnto &thorn;is
werl&dtail;, for hy&mtail; had leuer &thorn;er suffer any sekenes at
God wol&dtail; send hy&mtail;, &thorn;a&ntail; for to be &thorn;er a
noder how&rtail; agay&ntail; in pay&ntail;."  And so his sawle was
broght agay&ntail; vnto &thorn;e bodie, &amp; mekelie he suffre&dtail;
sekenes ij yere, and &thorn;a&ntail; he decesi&dtail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Purgatorium suum faciunt aliqui aliquando inter eos

inter quos peccauerunt.  Supra de abbate, viij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Purgatorius plus timetur a bonis quam a malis.

Infra de timore, iiij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Purgantur aliqui inter viuos.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Legen&dtail; Lombardica' how &thorn;er was <NOTE ID="P442.N1">MS. was a certayn ffysshers.</NOTE> certay&ntail; ffysshers in a tow&ntail; of Saynt
Thebottis <NOTE ID="P442.N2">Latin MSS. Theobaldus.</NOTE> , and in harveste whe&ntail;
&thorn;ai went o&ntail; fysshyng, and in-stede of fyss&hbar; &thorn;ai
drew in &thorn;er nett a grete pane&llbar; of yse.  And &thorn;ai war
mo&rtail; fay&ntail; &thorn;erof &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai wul&dtail;
hafe bene of fyss&hbar;, ffor &thorn;er byssho&ptail; had a grete
surans in his fete, and &thorn;ai lai&dtail; &thorn;is yse vnder-nethe
his fete &amp; he had a grete remedie of his sekenes &thorn;erbye.  So
vppo&ntail; a day he harde oute of &thorn;is yse &thorn;e voyce of a
ma&ntail; speke &amp; say dyvurs wurdis, and &thorn;e bissho&ptail;
coniured it &amp; aski&dtail; it what it was, &amp; it ansswer&dtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "I a&mtail; a certa&ntail; saule
&thorn;at is punysshi&dtail; for my synnys in &thorn;is pane&llbar; of
yse, and I myght be delyver&dtail; and &thorn;ou wolde say for me xxx
[messis xl<HI REND="sup">ti</HI>] <NOTE ID="P442.N3">Latin MSS. si quadraginta diebus continuis .xxx. missas diceres.</NOTE> dayes to-geddur."  And he
grantty&dtail; at he sulde do so, &amp; did.  And whe&ntail; he had
sayd halfe &thorn;e messis &amp; was bow&ntail; for to say &thorn;e
toder halfe, sodanlie be &thorn;e suggestio&ntail; of &thorn;e
devu&llbar;, a&llbar; his househol&dtail; fe&llbar; at were emangis
&thorn;er selfe, &amp; ilkone of &thorn;aim was in poynt to ky&llbar;
o&thorn;er.  And so &thorn;er bisshop&ptail; was trubli&dtail;
herewith, &amp; lefte his mes-saying.  And yit he fe&llbar; vnto
&thorn;aim agay&ntail; &







<PB N="443">

say&dtail; &thorn;aim.  And whe&ntail; he had say&dtail; ij partis of
&thorn;aim and was bow&ntail; to say mes, one of his meneya come vnto
hy&mtail; &amp; tolde hy&mtail; at &thorn;er was a grete sege of
me&ntail; of armys layde abowte &thorn;e cetie; and herefo&rtail; he
put of his mess-saying &thorn;at day.  And at &thorn;e iij tyme,
whe&ntail; he had say&dtail; a&llbar; his messis bod <NOTE ID="P443.N1"><HI REND="i">After</HI> bod, iij, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> ane, &thorn;er come a ma&ntail; vnto hy&mtail;
whe&ntail; he was bow&ntail; vnto &thorn;e laste mes, &amp; tolde
hy&mtail; at &thorn;er was a grete fyre in &thorn;e cetie.  And
&thorn;e bissho&ptail; ansswerd agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "And
a&llbar; &thorn;e cetie bur&ntail; vp stowte &amp; rowte, I sa&llbar;
not ouerhyp&ptail; nor lefe &thorn;is mes vndone."  And onone as
&thorn;e mes was done, &thorn;is yse resoluy&dtail; into watir, and
&thorn;is fyre vanysshi&dtail; away and was nevur sene after.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Pena purgatorij est acerba eciam si diuturna.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pusillanimitas quando
<NOTE ID="P443.N2">Latin MSS. quandoque.</NOTE> retrahit a bono.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;er was som tyme a knyght &thorn;at made
hy&mtail; mon&ktee; of Ceustus ordur, to the intent at make a noder
knyght at was his felaug&hbar; to do &thorn;e same.  And &thorn;e
toder knyght ansswer&dtail; &amp; sayde he wol&dtail; gladely <NOTE ID="P443.N3">MS. goldely.</NOTE> entyr in-to &thorn;e ordur bod he was fer&dtail; for
lyce.  And &thorn;e toder ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
say&dtail;; "He is nowder wurthi nor noble knyght &thorn;at in
&thorn;e bate&llbar; of &thorn;e devu&llbar; dredis nowder swer&dtail;
nor spere, &amp; is in &thorn;e bate&llbar; of Cryste ferde for a few
smale wormys.  And &thorn;erfo&rtail; bewar at &thorn;ies lies take
not fro the the kyngdo&mtail; of hevy&ntail;."  And with &thorn;is
wur&dtail; &thorn;is knyght was confusid, &amp; holilie and stronglie
he tuke &thorn;e ordur and vttirly forsuke a&llbar; &thorn;is
werl&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Quies mentis in omnibus est querenda.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Iero&mtail; tellis of iij me&ntail; &thorn;at luffi&dtail;
passand wele to-gedur, &amp; &thorn;ai a&llbar; iij went and made
&thorn;aim monkis.  And one of &thorn;aim chose







<PB N="444">

to condycio&ntail; to make &thorn;aim att ane at was at debate, and
&thorn;e secun&dtail; chose hy&mtail; to seryff &thorn;aim at wer
seke, and &thorn;e iij luffyd alway to be solitarie and be hy&mtail;
selfe.  And &thorn;e furste, whe&ntail; he had done myky&llbar; &amp;
mott not agre &thorn;aim a&llbar; &thorn;at wer at discorde, he
bega&ntail; to wax irke, &amp; come vnto &thorn;e toder &amp; tolde
hy&mtail;, &amp; fande at he was ir&ktee; also becauce he mott not
seryff seke fol&ktee; to plesans.  And &thorn;ies ij war
acordy&dtail; samen &amp; come vnto &thorn;e thri&dtail; and tolde
hy&mtail; of a&llbar; &thorn;er trubbles, and praye&dtail; hy&mtail;
at he wol&dtail; te&llbar; &thorn;aim what at profettyd &thorn;aim.
And he went fro&mtail; &thorn;aim a lite&llbar; and put watir in a
cop&ptail; and say&dtail; vnto &thorn;aim <NOTE ID="P444.N1">Latin MSS. "Intendite in aquam," et turbulenta erat.  Post modicum iterum dixit; "Attendite quam limpida facta est aqua."  Cumque intenderent in aquam viderunt uultos suos.</NOTE> ;
"Behol&dtail; in-to &thorn;e watir!"  And it was drovy, &amp; so
&thorn;ai di&dtail; &amp; &thorn;ai saw &thorn;er aw&ntail; facis as
&thorn;ai had luki&dtail; in a myrrour.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he
sai&dtail;; "&thorn;us &thorn;ai &thorn;at er emang many me&ntail; may
not se &thorn;er aw&ntail; synnys no mo&rtail; &thorn;a&ntail; ye mot
se your aw&ntail; shadus in &thorn;is watir whe&ntail; it was drovye;
and whe&ntail; &thorn;ai hafe bene awhile in solatare place be
&thorn;er ane, &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai may se &thorn;aim."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLXV. 
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Quies corporis a demone aliquando impeditur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how o&ntail; a tyme Abbott Isaac tol&dtail; in a
collacio&ntail;; 'Som tyme &thorn;er was a moste holy fadur, and
o&ntail; a tyme as he went be a ce&llbar; of ane of his brethur, <NOTE ID="P444.N2">MS. <HI REND="i">inserts</HI>, and, <HI REND="i">before</HI> he.</NOTE> he was war of his bruther dyngand o&ntail; a grete
stone with a huge hammer, and ane standand by hy&mtail; lyke a
ma&ntail; of Ynde, as he had prompyd hy&mtail; vnto his war&ktee;.
And &thorn;is gude olde fadur had merve&llbar; of suc&hbar; ane
illusio&ntail; and trowid it was bod a dissayte.  And he come vnto
&thorn;e ce&llbar; and haylsyd his bruther, &amp; say&dtail;; "What
war&ktee; is &thorn;is at &thorn;ou wyrkis?"  And he ansswerd
agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Fadur, we hafe laburd agay&ntail; a
harde stone, an vnnethis we may any thyng breke it."  And &thorn;is
olde ma&ntail; ansswerd hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;;
"&thorn;ou says wele, we hafe laburd, for &thorn;ou was not be
&thorn;ine one; anoder was with the at &thorn;ou saw nott, &thorn;at
stude evur and prompy&dtail; the to wurk besylie."'






<PB N="445">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Quies corporis appetenda est a sanctis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Heraclides tellis &amp; says of hy&mtail; selfe; Whe&ntail;
variable thoghtis hase trublid me &amp; bydde&ntail; me go furt&hbar;
of my ce&llbar;, and I had nothyng to do, I compleynd vnto Anto&ntail;
of Antioce&ntail; oppo&ntail; &thorn;is hevynes.  And he
ansswer&dtail; me &amp; sayde; "Whe&ntail; &thorn;ies thoghtys commys
vppo&ntail; &thorn;e, ansswer &thorn;aim agay&ntail; &amp; say, 'ffor
Cristis sake I kepe &thorn;ies wallis and wi&llbar; do, &thorn;uf I
doo no noder thyng els.'"


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Quietem corporis et mentis nititur demon eciam

visibiliter impedire.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Grego&rtail; tellis; "som tyme &thorn;er was a ma&ntail;
&thorn;at hight Marty&ntail;, and he led a solitarie lyfe.  And
&thorn;e devu&llbar; had dispite here-att, &amp; in lyknes of a
serpent he laburd &amp; keste for to lett hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;is
serpent o&ntail; a tyme be hy&mtail; selfe come into &thorn;e cafe
wha&rtail; &thorn;is Marty&ntail; led his lyfe in wyldernes, and
whe&ntail; he was alone in his prayers, sho stude vp ryght befor
hy&mtail;, and whe&ntail; he wol&dtail; lay hy&mtail; dow&ntail;, sho
wolde lay hur dow&ntail;.  And o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;is holy
ma&ntail; putt furst his hand &amp; syne his fute nakid vnto hur,
&amp; say&dtail;; 'And &thorn;ou hase lefe for to smyte me, I
sa&llbar; not lett the.'  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai had vsid &thorn;is
iij yere samen, at &thorn;e laste &thorn;is fals enmy, &thorn;e
devu&llbar;, was ouercomme&ntail; with his mekenes &amp; vanysshid
away fro&mtail; hy&mtail;."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Rana.  Ranam peperit Nero imperator arte

medicorum.  Supra de crudelitate, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Rapina omnis fugienda est et maxime a principe vel

prelato.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Seutonius tellis how o&ntail; a tyme, whe&ntail; he had
exhorti&dtail; Tyberius Cesar &thorn;at he sulde eke &thorn;e tributis
of his regions, the emperour ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sayd;
"Nay, ffor it longis vnto a gude hur&dtail; to clypp his shepe, &amp;
not a&llbar; at ons for to worow itt."

<PB N="446">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Raptor oratione restituere compellitur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Grego&rtail; tellis how o&ntail; a tyme a company of
Gothomys <NOTE ID="P446.N1">Arund. MS. exercitus Gothorum.</NOTE> mett Libertinus, a gude holy
ma&ntail;, rydand o&ntail; his hors, and &thorn;ai threw hy&mtail; of
his hors &amp; tuke it fro&mtail; hy&mtail;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai
had take&ntail; it fro&mtail; hy&mtail;, he profurd &thorn;aim his
whip&ptail;, &amp; sayde; "Take &thorn;is with you at ye may gar
&thorn;e hors ga with."  And &thorn;ai tuke it and went &thorn;er
wayse.  And als sone as &thorn;ai war gone he fe&llbar; vnto his
prayers, and it happen&dtail; at &thorn;ai mott go no ferrer, nor with
&thorn;er spurris gar &thorn;er hors go furt&hbar;.  So &thorn;ai
vmthoght &thorn;aim at &thorn;ai had done wrang vnto &thorn;is holy
ma&ntail;, and &thorn;ai turnyd agay&ntail; &amp; restori&dtail;
hy&mtail; of his hors.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai went &thorn;er
wayes, and nothyng lettyd &thorn;aim <NOTE ID="P446.N2">Tales DCLXVIII and DCLXIX <HI REND="i">marked</HI>, Nota, <HI REND="i">in the margin</HI>.</NOTE> .

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Rapine antecessorum debent restitui.  Supra de

ecclesia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Rapine possunt adaptari ea que dicuntur supra de

fure.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLXX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Raptus spiritualis.  Rapitur aliquando anima

extra se.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iacobus de Vetriaco says; "I saw som tyme devote womme&ntail;,
&thorn;at was so hugelie ravissi&dtail; with thoght of holy liffyng,
&thorn;at of a&llbar; &thorn;e day &thorn;er was no witt in &thorn;aim
vnto none oute-ward thyng bod was evy&ntail; as &thorn;ai had bene
o&ntail; slepe.  And &thorn;ai myght not be wakynd with no maner of
criyng, nor &thorn;ai myght fele nothyng sore and &thorn;ai had bene
nevur so prykki&dtail;."  And he says he saw a noder womma&ntail;
nerehan&dtail; of xxx<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> yere ol&dtail;, and sho was kepyd with so
grete luff be hur spowse in &thorn;e clostre, at sho mot be no ways go
furt&hbar; &thorn;eroff.  And neuer so many me&ntail; had drawe&ntail;
hur be &thorn;e han&dtail;, ffor oft tymys sho was enforci&dtail; to
be drawe&ntail; oute, bod it was in vay&ntail; bod if &thorn;ai
wul&dtail; hafe rugi&dtail; hur in sonder.  Also he says &thorn;at he
had sene a noder womma&ntail; &thorn;at som tyme xx<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> sythes o&ntail;
&thorn;e day was besyde hur selfe, whilk &thorn;at in his presence
opo&ntail; a day was





<PB N="447">

vij sithes ravysshi&dtail;.  And in what state so&mtail; evur sho was
ravissi&dtail; sho abade in &thorn;at astate vnto sho was turny&dtail;
owte of hur ravisshyng.  And hur handis hand v&ptail; in &thorn;e ayre
vnmouable after &thorn;e disposicio&ntail; at sho was ravisshid in, at
sho was garte shew a bodely ioying. et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Rebellio.  Rebellis punitur.  Infra de religione, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Recidiuum.  Recidiuum nocet.  Supra de heretico, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Recognicio.  Recognoscere debemus beneficia nobis

impensa.  Supra de beneficio, i.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Recreacio interdum vtilis est religiosis.  Supra

Johannis Euangeliste.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLXXI. 
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Recreacio eciam moderata omnibus est
necessaria.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis &thorn;at whe&ntail; Socrates &thorn;e wyse clerke
wexi&dtail; alde and taght his scolers, he wol&dtail; not alway bynd
&thorn;aim in at lernyng, bod som tyme to avanyss&hbar; away &thorn;er
labur he wolde suffer &thorn;aim to have recreacio&ntail;, to cauce
&thorn;aim to be more dyligent &amp; craftie in &thorn;er lernyng
afterward, at &thorn;ai sulde not be yrke of &thorn;er labur.  And
herefo&rtail; &thorn;is wise philosophur, Socrates, [usyd] for to lope
o&ntail; a rede betwix his leggis, as barnys rydys, and ryde with
&thorn;aim as &thorn;ai do to make &thorn;aim sporte.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Redempcio nulla est in inferno.  Supra de inferno, iiij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Reddicio.  Reddit deus centuplum.  Supra de

elemosina xiiij, et de decimis.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Reddunt aliqui malum pro bono.  Infra de serpente.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLXXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Regina quanto dignior tanto magis castitatem suam

servare debet.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in &thorn;e 'Meracles of our Ladie,' how som tyme in Rome
&thorn;er was ane emperour &thorn;at had a fayr wyfe &amp; a chaste.
So <NOTE ID="P447.N1">MS. so&mtail;.</NOTE> o&ntail; a



<PB N="448">

tyme &thorn;is emperour sulde trave&llbar; furt&hbar; oute of contre
fro his empyre vnto other grete regions, and he putt a bruther
&thorn;at he had, &amp; also a&llbar; his empyre, vnto gouernans of
his whene.  And whe&ntail; he was gone, his bruther wexi&dtail;
fon&dtail; of &thorn;e whene, &amp; at &thorn;e laste he oppyn&dtail;
his harte vnto hur, &amp; sho forsuke hy&mtail; vttirlie and wolde
not graunte vnto hy&mtail; notwithstandyng he wolde not lefe, bod
labur&dtail; hur daylie &thorn;erin.  So at &thorn;e laste whe&ntail;
sho saw he wolde not lefe, sho sparri&dtail; hy&mtail; in a tow&rtail;
hor&ntail; faste, and gouerny&dtail; &thorn;e empyre peasfullie.  And
whe&ntail; v yere was passi&dtail; &thorn;is emperour come home, &amp;
be lefe of &thorn;e empryce his bruther was latty&ntail; furthe of
&thorn;e tow&rtail; &amp; come vnto &thorn;e emperour and
accusy&dtail; &thorn;e emprice hugelie vnto hy&mtail;, &amp;
say&dtail; &thorn;at sho was ane oppy&ntail; fornycatur nerehan&dtail;
with evur-ilk ma&ntail;.  And becauce he wolde not consent vnto hur to
ly by hur, &thorn;erfo&rtail; sho sparri&dtail; hy&mtail; faste in a
tow&rtail;, &amp; herefo&rtail; he sai&dtail; he was lene and i&llbar;
hewi&dtail;.  And &thorn;is emperour gaff our redelie truste vnto
hy&mtail;, &amp; tuke a grete sorow in his harte, to so myke&llbar; at
he fe&llbar; dow&ntail; in swownyng &amp; lay a grete while.  So
whe&ntail; he come vnto his spyrittis agay&ntail; he went furt&hbar;,
and &thorn;e whene mett hy&mtail; &amp; wolde hafe kissi&dtail;
hy&mtail;, &amp; he wolde not bod gaff hur a grete strake, &amp; felde
hur vnto &thorn;e ert&hbar;.  And he commaundi&dtail; ij of his
me&ntail; to take hur &amp; hafe hur vnto &thorn;e wudd &amp; smyte of
hur heade.  And &thorn;ai tuke hur &amp; had hur furt&hbar; as he
bad. &amp; whe&ntail; &thorn;ai come &thorn;er &thorn;ai sulde hafe
smyte&ntail; of hur hea&dtail;, &thorn;ai wolde bothe hafe lige&ntail;
by hur.  And sho putt &thorn;aim by and cryed &amp; made a grete
noyse.  And &thorn;er happend com by a wurthi ma&ntail;, &amp; many
me&ntail; with hy&mtail;, and harde hur cry &amp; rade to hur &amp;
slew &thorn;ies ij harlottis at was with hur, &amp; tuke hur <NOTE ID="P448.N1">MS. hym.</NOTE> home with hy&mtail; &amp; betaght hur vnto his wyfe.
And sho made hur nuress of a little yong so&ntail; at sho had&dtail;.
So &thorn;is wurthi ma&ntail; had a bruder was a knyght, &amp; he
wexid so fon&dtail; o&ntail; hur at he wiste neuer what he might doo,
&amp; oft wolde hafe had at do with hur; and evur sho putt hy&mtail;
bye.  So o&ntail; a nyght, as sho was o&ntail; slepe in hur bed &amp;
&thorn;is yong bab by hur, he come privalie with a knyfe &amp; cutt
&thorn;e bar&ntail; throte in sonder, &amp; put nemelie &thorn;e knyfe
in hur hand and sho of slepe; &amp; so he lefte hur and went his
wayes.  So sho felde war&mtail; blude



<PB N="449">

ry&ntail; aboute hyr in &thorn;e bed, &amp; wakend &thorn;er-with.
And whe&ntail; sho saw how it was sho crye&dtail;, at &thorn;e lorde
&amp; &thorn;e ladie and a&llbar; &thorn;e howshol&dtail; har&dtail;.
So &thorn;ai come vnto hur at luke what hur ayli&dtail;, and fande
&thorn;e bar&ntail; dea&dtail;.  And &thorn;e howshol&dtail; meneya
wol&dtail; hafe slay&ntail; hur, bod &thorn;e lorde and &thorn;e ladie
wolde not latt &thorn;aim.  So &thorn;e lor&dtail; commandi&dtail; at
sho sulde be delyver&dtail; vnto shipme&ntail;, &amp; at &thorn;ai
sulde hafe hur in-to a far contrey.  And so sho was delyver&dtail;
vnto shipme&ntail; &amp; broght vnto &thorn;e shi&ptail;.  And onone
&thorn;ai wolde hafe lige&ntail; by hur, and in no wyse sho wolde
consent vnto &thorn;aim, and herefore &thorn;ai wolde hafe
drowny&dtail; hur.  Bod &thorn;ug&hbar; grace of God &thorn;er
cownce&llbar; changi&dtail;, and &thorn;ai sett hur vp&ptail;
apo&ntail; a hy skar in &thorn;e see.  And &thorn;er our Ladie Saynt
Marie apperid vnto hur &amp; comfurthid hur, an&dtail; bad hur take
ane erbe &thorn;at was vnder hur hea&dtail; &thorn;er sho lay &amp;
kepe it, &amp; with &thorn;at sho sulde heale a&llbar; &thorn;aim
&thorn;at war lepre wha&rtail;-so&mtail;-evur sho come.  And sho was
&thorn;er many day &amp; ha&dtail; no meat bod herbys &amp; gress.  So
o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;er come ship&ptail;-me&ntail; by &thorn;e
lan&dtail;, and sho crye&dtail; vnto &thorn;aim and &thorn;ai had
petie o&ntail; hur, and tuke hur in-to &thorn;er shi&ptail; &amp; had
hur vnto a haven-tow&ntail;; and onone &thorn;er befo&rtail;
&thorn;aim a&llbar; sho heli&dtail; a lepre ma&ntail;.  And in
&thorn;e mene while &thorn;is vnhappie ma&ntail; &thorn;at had
slay&ntail; his bruther bar&ntail; &thorn;at sho kepi&dtail;, was
sodanlie falle&ntail; lepre, and sho was broght vnto hy&mtail; &amp;
no bodie knew hur of a&llbar; &thorn;e howshol&dtail;.  So &thorn;e
lord prayed hur to hele his bruther, and sho ansswer&dtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail; sho myght nott bod if he in presence of
&thorn;e lorde &amp; &thorn;e ladie &amp; o&thorn;er viij persons
shrafe hy&mtail; clene of a&llbar; his synnys.  And so he di&dtail;,
bod &thorn;at sy&ntail; at he di&dtail; anence hur, he wolde not
shryfe hy&mtail; &thorn;erof, and evur sho say&dtail; he was not
fu&llbar; shrevy&ntail;.  So he gatt assurans of his bruthir, &amp;
knowleged a&llbar; his sy&ntail; how he had done.  And sho
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "I a&mtail; &thorn;at
same womma&ntail;."  And &thorn;er sho heli&dtail; hy&mtail;.  And
&thorn;e lorde wolde hafe garte hur wed hy&mtail; and sho wolde not,
bod went hur way; &amp; evur wha&rtail; any was lepre sho heli&dtail;
&thorn;aim.  So at &thorn;e laste hur happend to co&mtail; to Rome,
and &thorn;er sho fand &thorn;e emperour hur husban&dtail; bruther, at
had done so vnto hur, lepre.  And sho was fechi&dtail; to hele
hy&mtail;, &amp; sho wolde not bod if he confessi&dtail; hy&mtail;
oppynlie of a&llbar; &thorn;e synnys at evur he had done befo&rtail;
a&llbar; me&ntail;; and so he di&dtail; &amp; telde opynlie how he had
done vnto hur, &
<PB N="450">

how &thorn;e emperour had garte sla hur.  And a&llbar; &thorn;e peple
&thorn;at was &thorn;er &amp; harde made sorow for los of so gude a
ladie.  So at &thorn;e laste sho lete &thorn;aim witt at it was sho,
&amp; heli&dtail; in &thorn;e cetie a&llbar; &thorn;at evur was lepur.
And be &thorn;at tyme &thorn;e emperour was dead, and &thorn;e pope
sent vnto hur; &amp; becauce &thorn;at in hur tribulacio&ntail; sho
had made a vow of chastite, he made hur to take one abbet of
religio&ntail;.  And &thorn;us sho endi&dtail; hur lyfe in clene
liffiyng. et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Regina semper honestatem suam debet tenere.

Supra de muliere, xvi.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLXXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Religiosus non debet se de secularibus
intromittere.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iacobus de Vetriaco tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a knyght
&thorn;at lefte a&llbar; his possessions &amp; his wurshuppis and his
welefaris, and made hy&mtail; a mon&ktee;.  And &thorn;e abbot saw at
he was a wyse ma&ntail; and sent hy&mtail; vnto &thorn;e markett to
se&llbar; assis of &thorn;e abbay at was olde, &amp; at he sulde by
yong; &thorn;uff a&llbar; he war displesi&dtail; &thorn;er-with,
neuer-&thorn;eles he went, and wolde not breke his obediens.  And
whe&ntail; me&ntail; axkid hy&mtail; if &thorn;e assis wer gude &amp;
yong, he ansswerd euer agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Trow ye at our
abbay is falle&ntail; vnto suche pouertie at we sulde se&llbar; our
gude assis &amp; our profetable?"  So one come &amp; axkid hy&mtail;
whi &thorn;er taylis wer so pylde, and no hare lefte o&ntail;
&thorn;aim.  He ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Becauce
&thorn;ai fa&llbar; oft sythis vnder &thorn;er lade &amp; we lifte
&thorn;aim euer vp be &thorn;e tayllis, and &thorn;at is cauce
&thorn;er tayllis er bare."  And &thorn;us he wolde nott lay&ntail;
&thorn;e treut&hbar;.  So hy&mtail; happen&dtail; se&llbar; none of
&thorn;aim, and come home vnto his cloystur.  A noder lewi&dtail;
monke at was with hy&mtail; at &thorn;e markett accusy&dtail;
hy&mtail; evy&ntail; opynlie in &thorn;er chapiter hows; and &thorn;e
abbott dysply&dtail; hy&mtail; as it had bene for a grete truspas.
And he ansswer&dtail; vnto &thorn;e abbott agay&ntail; &amp;
say&dtail;; "I lefte many assis &amp; meku&llbar; o&thorn;er gude
thyng in &thorn;e werlde, and I come hedur to seryff Go&dtail; &amp;
becauce I sulde nott lye, bod at I sulde safe my saule."  And
&thorn;us fro thens furt&hbar; he was nevur sent oute forwarde.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Religiosus mentiri non debet.  Supra de mendacio, ij.</FOREIGN>

<PB N="451">
</ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Religiosus aduocatus esse non debet.  Supra de

mendacio, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLXXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Religiosus non debet excedere in potu.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Petrus Clunacensis <NOTE ID="P451.N1">MS. Clymacensis.</NOTE> tellis how so&mtail;
tyme &thorn;er was ane holie ma&ntail; and as he lay in his prayers
o&ntail; Gude Fryday, he was ravisshi&dtail; his spyri&dtail; fro his
body vnto Pasc&hbar; day.  And whe&ntail; he come vnto hy&mtail;
selfe, he tolde how &thorn;at he saw a religious ma&ntail; of grete
penance swolu&dtail; of &thorn;e devu&llbar; in drynk &thorn;at he was
wunte to vse excesly.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he was drawe&ntail; vnto
his dome, and had noght Saynt Nicholas bene, he had bene
dampne&dtail;; bod Saynt Nicholas at he vsi&dtail; to seryff deuotelie
helpi&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; so he was nott dampny&dtail;, bod
demy&dtail; vnto &thorn;e payns of purgatorie.

</P>
