</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLXXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Religiosus inobediens aliquando eciam a deo
uisibiliter 
<NOTE ID="P452.N1">MS. inuisibiliter.</NOTE>  punitur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was ane abbot &amp;
he had a seke monke.  And he saw &thorn;at it was necessarie to
hy&mtail; to eate fless&hbar;, &amp; he commaundi&dtail; hy&mtail;
&thorn;at he sulde eate fless&hbar;; and he was passan&dtail; swaymos
&amp; wol&dtail; nott.  And for als meku&llbar; as God wolde shew
&thorn;at obediens war better &thorn;a&ntail; meat or dryn&ktee;,
&thorn;is inobedient monke onone turny&dtail; into a wudenes, and
ra&ntail; wude into &thorn;e felde.  And &thorn;er he fande a
dea&dtail; dogg &amp; a&llbar; &thorn;e fless&hbar; o&ntail; hy&mtail;
stynki&dtail;, and he fe&llbar; to and ete of hy&mtail; gredelie.  And
&thorn;us becauce he truspasi&dtail; in fless&hbar; &amp; wolde not
eatt fless&hbar; whe&ntail; his abbott bad hy&mtail;,
&thorn;erfo&rtail; he was punyssi&dtail; in fless&hbar;-etyng, et
c&curl;, for his inobedyance.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Religiosus non debet carnaliter affici ad amicos.

Supra de affectu 
<NOTE ID="P452.N2">MS. aspectu.</NOTE> , ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Religiosos temptat demon.  Supra de demone in

pluribus locis.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLXXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Religiosus potest bellare sine armis in spe diuini

auxilii defendendo ius suum quod aliter habere

non posset, quod magis est non bellare quam

bellare.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Petrus Damianus tellis how &thorn;at in &thorn;e parties of
Frawnce &thorn;er was in a place a <NOTE ID="P452.N3">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, a.</NOTE> grete debate
betwix ane abbott &amp; a myghtie seculer ma&ntail; for a
possessio&ntail; of a lyfelo&dtail;, so &thorn;at whe&ntail; &thorn;ai
had lang strevy&ntail;, ffavorers o&ntail; bothe parties arayi&dtail;
&thorn;aim evy&ntail; vnto bate&llbar;.  And &thorn;is myghti
ma&ntail; come in-to &thorn;e felde with a grete company of armyd
me&ntail; with hy&mtail;, &amp; bownd hy&mtail; to feght.  And
&thorn;is abbott, a&llbar; &thorn;at come with hy&mtail; to feght, he
commandi&dtail; &thorn;aim







<PB N="453">

stand oparte &amp; latt hy&mtail; &amp; his monkis alone, and he sett
a&llbar; his monkis o&ntail; hors, &amp; made &thorn;aim cover
&thorn;er hedis with &thorn;aire cowlis.  And in &thorn;is maner of
armur he come vnto &thorn;e place &thorn;er &thorn;ai sulde feght; and
onone his enmys, whe&ntail; &thorn;ai saw hy&mtail;, wer streky&ntail;
with suche ane vgsomnes at onone &thorn;ai lighti&dtail; of &thorn;er
horsis, &amp; keste away fro &thorn;aim &thorn;er armor &amp;
&thorn;er wapyns and fe&llbar; dow&ntail; mekelie vnto &thorn;e erde,
&amp; axki&dtail; hy&mtail; forgyfnes and nevur after made chalange
vnto &thorn;is possessio&ntail; agay&ntail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLXXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Religiosi non debent statum secularium
contempnere.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Iero&mtail; tellis of one &thorn;at hight Paphencius, whilk
&thorn;at whe&ntail; he had long tyme vsyd aunge&llbar; lyfe, he made
his prayer vnto almightie Go&dtail; at he wol&dtail; shew hy&mtail; to
whilk saynt of hevy&ntail; he sulde be like in blis.  And it was
shewi&dtail; hy&mtail; at he sulde be lyke vnto one Simphoniacus
&thorn;at dwelte in &thorn;e next strete.  And he went onone vnto
hy&mtail; and axki&dtail; hy&mtail; of his reule &amp; his gouernans.
And he tolde hy&mtail; at he had vsi&dtail; to be emang thevis &amp;
knew no gude dede, nor neuer di&dtail; none, safeyng onelie at he gatt
a damyse&llbar; fro his felows, at &thorn;ai had take&ntail; &amp;
defowli&dtail;, &amp; savi&dtail; hir honesti at &thorn;ai lay not by
hur.  And he tolde hy&mtail; also how he gaff vnto ane honeste
womma&ntail; in wyldrenes, goand wy&llbar;, iij c penys to
rawnso&ntail; hur husban&dtail; &amp; hur childer &thorn;at lay in
sore priso&ntail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is Paphencius tolde
hy&mtail; hys visio&ntail; and had hy&mtail; with hy&mtail; vnto
wyldrenes, and with-in a little while after he dyed, and he saw his
saule had vnto hevy&ntail;.  A nodir tyme &thorn;e same was shewid
hy&mtail; of &thorn;e primat of &thorn;e cetie, &thorn;at was wed
xxx<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> yere &amp; evur kepu&dtail; hy&mtail; in chastitie fro&mtail;
his wyfe, and he saw his sawle also had vnto hevy&ntail;.  And the
thrid tyme it was shewid hy&mtail; &thorn;e same of a merchan&dtail;.
And &thorn;a&ntail; whe&ntail; he sulde dye and prestis come vnto
hy&mtail;, he said vnto &thorn;aim; "No ma&ntail;, nowder thefe nor
merchan&dtail;, sulde be despysid, for emang peple of evur-ilk degre
is God plesud with so&mtail; sawlis."  And he tolde &thorn;aim in
ordur a&llbar; &thorn;at is afor&ntail; saide, and &thorn;a&ntail; he
passi&dtail; vnto God.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Religiosus non debet discurrere.  Supra de affectu.
</FOREIGN>
<PB N="454">
</ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Religiosi 
