vi 
<NOTE ID="P458.N4">MS. iiij.</NOTE> .</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Rex sapiens.  Supra de prudencia et providencia.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLXXXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Risus.  Ridere non debent habentes oculum ad

iudicium vltimum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum,' how o&ntail; a tyme ane olde ma&ntail;
saw a yong ma&ntail; lag&hbar;, &amp; he said vnto hy&mtail;;
"So&ntail;, how may &thorn;ou fyn&dtail; in &thorn;i herte to
lag&hbar;?  Mo&ntail; not &thorn;ou &amp; I &amp; we a&llbar;
befo&rtail; bothe hevy&ntail; and ert&hbar; gyf a rekynyng of a&llbar;
our lyfe?  And &thorn;erfo&rtail; me mervels," he sai&dtail;, "at
&thorn;ow may fynde in &thorn;i harte to lag&hbar;."
<PB N="459">
</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLXXXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ridere non debent aduertentes pericula
mundi.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Libro de Dono Timoris' how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er
was a kyng, and if he made nevur so great a feste, he wolde neuer
lag&hbar;.  So a fren&dtail; of his reprovi&dtail; hy&mtail;
&thorn;erfor, &amp; aski&dtail; hy&mtail; whi he did so, and he
ansswer&dtail; fenandlie.  So after-war&dtail; he ordand a chayre with
roty&ntail; fete, and he garte sett it abow&ntail; a hate burnyng
ove&ntail;, and abow&ntail; it he gar&ttee; hyng a swer&dtail; with a
wayke threde.  And &thorn;is done, he garte se t hy&mtail; &thorn;erin
&thorn;at reprovi&dtail; hy&mtail; for he wolde not lag&hbar;, &amp;
he garte sett aboute hy&mtail; iiij me&ntail; with iiij drawe&ntail;
swerdis.  And he garte bryng befo&rtail; hy&mtail; a&llbar; maner of
delicious metis &amp; drynkis, &amp; a&llbar; o&thorn;er thyngis
&thorn;at sulde make hy&mtail; merie.  So &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e
kyng come in and stirri&dtail; hy&mtail; to lag&hbar;, and he
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "I may not lag&hbar;
whe&ntail; I se &thorn;ies perels &thorn;at er aboute me."  Tha&ntail;
&thorn;e kyng ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;;
"Tha&ntail; vmthyn&ktee; &thorn;e how mot I lag&hbar; whe&ntail;
&thorn;er er grete festis made afore me, &thorn;at seis behyn&dtail;
me &thorn;e bitternes of my sy&ntail;?  And befo&rtail; me I se ane
vncertantie of &thorn;at at is for to co&mtail;, and o&ntail; my lefte
han&dtail; I see vexacions of present aduersities, and o&ntail; my
right hand I se noyes &thorn;at commys after prosperities.  And
a&llbar; &thorn;ies I se as shar&ptail; swerdis of &thorn;e sentans of
a&llbar;myghti Go&dtail;.  And I se dea&dtail; hyng abow&ntail;, whame
I wate nevur what how&rtail; wi&llbar; stryke me, and vndernethe me I
se &thorn;e pitt of he&llbar; at I a&mtail; fer&dtail; at fa&llbar;
into, &amp; with-in me I se myne aw&ntail; freletie.  And emang
a&llbar; &thorn;ies I a&mtail; sett in a frele seatt, oute of &thorn;e
whilk I a&mtail; ferde daylie to fa&llbar;.  And &thorn;efo&rtail;
hafe &thorn;ou no merve&llbar; if I may not fynd in my harte to
lag&hbar;."

</P>
<P>
