<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLXXXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sacerdos curatus infirmis debet esse paratus et

petentibus omni tempore sacramenta ministrare.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis of a preste at was a curatt, &thorn;at o&ntail; a
tyme satt playan&dtail; at &thorn;e dice with a cussy&ntail; of his.
And &thorn;er come vnto hy&mtail; a ma&ntail; hastelie and tolde
hy&mtail; at his moder was seke and bow&ntail; to dye, &amp; bad
hy&mtail; in pay&ntail; of &thorn;e pere&llbar; &thorn;at wolde
fa&llbar; &thorn;ero&ntail; &thorn;at he sulde co&mtail; in a&llbar;
haste vnto hur &amp; shryfe hur &amp; giff hur hur sacramentis.  And
&thorn;e preste ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail; &thorn;at
he wolde not vnto hys layke war done.  And euer &thorn;e ma&ntail;
stude sti&llbar; &amp; labur&dtail; hy&mtail; to ryse.  So at &thorn;e
laste &thorn;is preste sai&dtail; vnto his cussy&ntail; at he
playe&dtail; with; "Cussy&ntail;, I compley&ntail; me, &amp; at
&thorn;e I take wittnes, at &thorn;is felow wi&llbar; not lat me alone
at my gamen, bod trubbles me and lettis me."  So &thorn;is ma&ntail;
saw &thorn;at his taryng profetti&dtail; hy&mtail; nott, &amp; went
his ways.  And his moder dyed withoute&ntail; howse&llbar; or shrufte.
So it happend o&ntail; &thorn;e iij day after, &thorn;e cussy&ntail;
of &thorn;is same preste mett &thorn;is yong ma&ntail; at &thorn;e
moder was dead of, and vmthogth hy&mtail; of &thorn;e playnt at
&thorn;e preste made of hy&mtail;, &amp; pulli&dtail; oute his dagger
&amp; stykke&dtail; hy&mtail;.  And after &thorn;is and many
o&thorn;er synnys, &thorn;is preste happend fa&llbar; seke &amp;
bow&ntail; to dye.  So a cussy&ntail; of his, at was his
servan&dtail;, cowncel&dtail; hy&mtail; to be shrevy&ntail; &amp;
forthyn&ktee; hy&mtail; of his truspas.  He wolde nott bod fe&llbar;
into a despayr, &amp; ansswer&dtail; hur &amp; say&dtail;; "Seis
&thorn;ou yone grete lathe enence vs?  Forsuthe &thorn;er is not
&thorn;erin so many strais as &thorn;er is fendis gadur&dtail; here
aboute me, to take my sawle whe&ntail; I pas."

<PB N="462">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCLXXXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sacerdos indigne celebrans eciam visibiliter

sacramento priuatur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis of a preste of Saynt&curl; Petur kurk in
Colay&ntail;, how o&ntail; a day whe&ntail; he had sacred his mes
&amp; lay&dtail; dow&ntail; &thorn;e sacrament o&ntail; &thorn;e
altar, whe&ntail; he sulde take it agay&ntail; he cuthe not fynd it,
nor a&llbar; &thorn;e o&thorn;er peple &thorn;at helpi&dtail;
hy&mtail; to seke itt.  Wha&rtail;-for witty me&ntail; &thorn;at knew
hy&mtail; supposi&dtail; &thorn;at aungels had take&ntail; it
fro&mtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; translat it into hevy&ntail;, &thorn;at he
&thorn;at was a lichuros preste sulde not resayfe it vnto hy&mtail;
dampnacio&ntail;; for it was not vnknowe&ntail; at he had a
lemma&ntail; in &thorn;e tow&ntail; &amp; hel&dtail; hur opynlie.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXC.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sacerdos diligenter debet aduertere quod hostia

consecranda nullum habeat defectum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a preste besyd
Colay&ntail;, and whe&ntail; he was att mes &amp; had say&dtail;
&thorn;e gospe&llbar; &amp; layde dow&ntail; &thorn;e sacrament
vppo&ntail; &thorn;e corprax, sodanlie it was away.  And he
trowi&dtail; at &thorn;at had happen&dtail; &thorn;urg&hbar; so&mtail;
fallyng dow&ntail;, &amp; he lay&dtail; &thorn;er a noder; and onone
&thorn;at was removi&dtail; ferrer &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e toder was.
And &thorn;a&ntail; he tuke &thorn;e thri&dtail;, and onone it was
caste&ntail; of &thorn;e alta&rtail;.  And whe&ntail; he saw &thorn;at
he was ferde for &thorn;at hoste behyn&dtail; hy&mtail;, and he
consecratt a noder.  And whe&ntail; mes was done, he tuke &thorn;is
hoste &amp; broght it vnto Colay&ntail;, &amp; shewi&dtail; it vnto
parfite me&ntail; &amp; rehersi&dtail; vnto &thorn;aim a&llbar;
&thorn;e mater.  And &thorn;ai brak it afor&ntail; hy&mtail; and fand
&thorn;erin a lowse bake&ntail;.  And a&llbar; &thorn;at was &thorn;er
thanki&dtail; almighti Go&dtail; &thorn;at wi&llbar; algattis at
&thorn;e sacrament be made of clene thyng.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXCI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sacerdotem indigne celebrantem priuat deus

sumpcione sacramenti.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;er was a preste in Fraunce, so
hy&mtail; happen&dtail; o&ntail; yole nyght to go fro &thorn;e ta
tow&ntail; to &thorn;e toder, wha&rtail; he sulde say mes in bathe
placis; so he was be his one, &amp; hy&mtail; happen&dtail;

<PB N="463">

to mete with a womma&ntail; be hur ane.  And so in &thorn;at same
how&rtail; hy&mtail; happyn&dtail; to sy&ntail; with hur, and so he
mo&rtail; dredyng &thorn;e shame of ma&ntail; &thorn;a&ntail; Goddis
vengeans, whe&ntail; he had sai&dtail; his matyns, he bega&ntail;
solemplie &thorn;e furste mes.  And whe&ntail; he had consecratt bothe
&thorn;e brea&dtail; &amp; &thorn;e whyne, a white duffe light
dow&ntail; o&ntail; &thorn;e awter at &thorn;e preste saw, and sho
suppi&dtail; of a&llbar; &thorn;at was in &thorn;e chales with hur
neb, &amp; tuke &thorn;e sacrament with hur and flow away.  And
&thorn;is preste was fer&dtail;, bod not as hy&mtail; aght to be, and
wyste neuer what he sulde do.  Neuer-&thorn;e-les he sai&dtail; oute
&thorn;e wurdis &amp; fulfylli&dtail; &thorn;e sygnes of &thorn;e
sacrament, and endi&dtail; his mes.  And &thorn;e same happen&dtail;
hy&mtail; at &thorn;e secun&dtail; mes, and also at &thorn;e iij mes
&thorn;e same day.  So at &thorn;e laste he repenti&dtail; hy&mtail;,
and with a grete contricio&ntail; he went unto ane abbott of Ceustos
ordur &amp; confessi&dtail; hy&mtail;, whilk &thorn;at, when he saw
his contricio&ntail;, eniony&dtail; hy&mtail; for to ga to mes.  And
whe&ntail; with grete drede &amp; sorow he had sai&dtail; mes,
befo&rtail; his su[m]pcions <NOTE ID="P463.N1">Latin, ante sumpcionem.</NOTE> , &thorn;e same
duffe come agay&ntail;.  And &thorn;e same iij hostis at sho had had
away syngnlelie, ilkone be &thorn;er one, sho broght &thorn;aim
agay&ntail; in hur by&llbar;, &amp; lay&dtail; &thorn;aim o&ntail;
&thorn;e corprax.  And &thorn;e liquore of iij messis sho put oute of
hur throte into &thorn;e chales, and went hur ways.  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;e preste saw &thorn;is, he was passand fay&ntail; and
tol&dtail; his confessur a&llbar; &thorn;is be ordur, and besoght
hy&mtail; at he mot be resayvi&dtail; into &thorn;e ordur to be one of
his brethur.  And he grawntid hy&mtail; so at he wulde furste go &amp;
be iij yere beyon&dtail; se &amp; &thorn;er seryff seke folke of
&thorn;er religio&ntail;, and so he di&dtail;.  And &thorn;is done, he
come home; and &thorn;e abbot reseyvi&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; made
hy&mtail; a monke of his couent.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXCII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sacerdoti curato imputantur defectus
subditorum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a preste, a
curatt, at gaff hy&mtail; a&llbar; vnto etyng &amp; drynkyng and
lichorye.  And he was necligent anen&ttee; his parishyng, and gaff no
hede vnto &thorn;er sawlis.  So hy&mtail; happen&dtail; to dye, &amp;
whe&ntail; he was dea&dtail; his parisshyns at war dea&dtail;
vndernethe his cure, ilkone of &thorn;aim gat a grete stane,



<PB N="464">

and accusi&dtail; hy&mtail; vnto he&llbar;, and sai&dtail; vnto
hy&mtail;; "We wer commytt vnto &thorn;e and &thorn;ou haste
forgetty&ntail; vs; ffor whe&ntail; we syn&dtail;, &thorn;ou nowder
reuoki&dtail; with nowder gude wurde nor exsample, and
&thorn;erfo&rtail; &thorn;ou ert cauce of ow&rtail; dampnacio&ntail;."
And with &thorn;at &thorn;ai keste a&llbar; &thorn;e stanys o&ntail;
hy&mtail;, and he fe&llbar; into &thorn;e pitt of he&llbar; and neuer
efter appery&dtail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Sacerdos malus tempestate perit.  Infra de

tempestate.</FOREIGN></ITEM> <ITEM><FOREIGN>Sacerdotis <NOTE ID="P464.N1">MS. Sacerdos.</NOTE> concubina
punitur.  Supra de luxuria, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXCIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sacietas.  Saciari non potest cor
humanum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt <NOTE ID="P464.N2">MS. Sayn&dtail;.</NOTE> Barnar&dtail; say&dtail; &amp;
tellis; "Som tyme," he say&dtail;, "I saw v me&ntail; whilk I cuthe
not say bo&dtail; at &thorn;ai wer fon&dtail;, for &thorn;e furste
wal&dtail; eate no meate bod grave&llbar; of &thorn;e se, and &thorn;e
secun&dtail; of &thorn;aim had a curage to fele a&llbar; maner of
y&llbar; savyr, and &thorn;e thri&dtail; wald stan&dtail; be a byrnyng
ovy&ntail; &amp; evur gape to take in his mout&hbar;e &thorn;e byrnyng
sparkis.  An&dtail; &thorn;e iiij wol&dtail; sytt vppo&ntail; &thorn;e
pynacle of &thorn;e temple, and euer gape agay&ntail; &thorn;e weddur.
And &thorn;e v of &thorn;aim wolde luke behyn&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp;
scor&ntail; his felas, and yit he was more to be skorny&dtail;
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai, for with a&llbar; his myght he labur&dtail;
to sowke his aw&ntail; fless&hbar; &amp; he wolde neuer nowder putt
his ar&mtail; nor his han&dtail; <NOTE ID="P464.N3">han&dtail; <HI REND="i">written over</HI> mouthe, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> vnto his
mouthe.  And in &thorn;aim a&llbar; I cowde fyn&dtail; no reso&ntail;,
bo&dtail; at he be my consayte had suffre&dtail; a passan&dtail;
hu[n]ggre, mo&rtail; &thorn;a&ntail; any of &thorn;e toder."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXCIV.
<LB> 
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sacramentum altaris devote celebranti quandoque

apparet in specie pueri.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a monke of Ceustus
ordur, and vppo&ntail; &thorn;e yole day he sayd mes at a privay
alta&rtail; with grete







<PB N="465">

deuocio&ntail; and wepyng of teris.  And whe&ntail; he had made his
consecracio&ntail;, he cuthe not se &thorn;e sacrament in kyn&dtail; of
brea&dtail;, bod in lyknes of a yong childe &thorn;at was passan&dtail;
fayr.  &amp; he keste suche a luff &thorn;er-vnto &amp; was so gretele
delyti&dtail; with &thorn;e fayrnes &thorn;er-of, at he halsi&dtail; it and
kissi&dtail; it with a grete dilectatio&ntail;.  So at &thorn;e laste he was
fer&dtail; at &thorn;ai at stude aboute hy&mtail; sulde thynke lang, and he
lay&dtail; it dow&ntail; o&ntail; &thorn;e corprax, &amp; he procedi&dtail; in
&thorn;e wurdis of &thorn;e sacrament after &thorn;e for&mtail;.  And it
turne&dtail; agay&ntail; into &thorn;e substance of &thorn;e sacrament, and
&thorn;a&ntail; with grete ioy he performy&dtail; &amp; fulfylli&dtail;
furt&hbar; his mes.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXCV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sacramentum honorauerunt apes.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a womma&ntail;
&thorn;at had many beis, &amp; oft sithes &thorn;ai dye&dtail;
opo&ntail; hur.  So &thorn;er was ane &thorn;at cowncel&dtail; hur at
sho sulde gett &thorn;e sacrament an&dtail; lay in &thorn;e hyfe
emangis &thorn;aim.  So o&ntail; a day sho went vnto &thorn;e
kur&ktee; and shrafe hur, &amp; feny&dtail; at sho wolde be
howsel&dtail;, and so sho was.  And onone as sho was howsel&dtail; of
&thorn;e prestis han&dtail;, whils he turny&dtail; hy&mtail; vnto
&thorn;e altar, sho withdrew &thorn;e sacrament oute of hir mouthe
&amp; had it hame &amp; lai&dtail; it emang hur <NOTE ID="P465.N1">MS. his.</NOTE>
beis.  And onone &thorn;ai knew &thorn;er Maker, &amp; with &thorn;er
war&ktee; in &thorn;e hyfe &thorn;ai made a little chape&llbar; &amp;
&thorn;erin &thorn;ai made ane altare, and abo&ntail; &thorn;is
alta&rtail; &thorn;ai layde &thorn;e sacrament, and afterwar&dtail;
fro thens furt&hbar; &thorn;ai encresi&dtail; gretelie.  So o&ntail; a
tyme &thorn;is womma&ntail; oppyn&dtail; &thorn;e hyfe, and fande
&thorn;e wallis, &thorn;e wyndows, &thorn;e rufe &amp; &thorn;e
steple, &thorn;e duris &amp; &thorn;e altar of &thorn;is chape&llbar;,
a&llbar; made be beis as &thorn;ai wurke.  And sho went and
shewi&dtail; it vnto &thorn;e preste &amp; vnto hyr neghburs, and
&thorn;e preste sersyd what was &thorn;erin, &amp; fand &thorn;e
sacrament.  And he &amp; a&llbar; his parisshy&ntail; with greate ioy
&amp; mirthe <NOTE ID="P465.N2">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, &amp; ioy.</NOTE> had it vnto &thorn;e kur&ktee;.
And &thorn;e womma&ntail; grawnti&dtail; hur sy&ntail; &amp; was
shrevy&ntail; agay&ntail;, and reseyvi&dtail; &thorn;e same sacrament.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Sacramento possunt adaptari multa que dicuntur

supra de sacerdote, eukaristia, communione, et

cibo spirituali.

</FOREIGN>

<PB N="466">
</ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Sacra scriptura.  Infra de sciencia et supra de

Andrea, i.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Sacrista ecclesiam et res ecclesiasticas legitime debet

custodire.  Infra de silencio, iiij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Sacriste absentis officium supplet beata virgo deuote.

Supra de beata Maria, vij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Salutacio Marie multipliciter valet.  Supra de ave

Maria, annunciacione dominica, et Maria, ac

alijs locis diuersis.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Sancti aliquando accusant malos.  Supra de

episcopo, ij, et de archidiacono, et de elemosina, xv.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Sanctis non est obloquendum.  Supra de

blasfemia, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Sanctis eciam bruta reuerenciam exhibent.  Supra

de obediencia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Sancti se vindicare nolunt.  Infra de vindicta, iij 
<NOTE ID="P466.N1">MS. iiij.</NOTE> .</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>
</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXCVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sancta vasa et vestes semper munde debent
tractari.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Legen&dtail; Lombardica,' how Julianus Apostata
o&ntail; a tyme, at Antioche, gadurd samen halud vesse&llbar; &amp;
halud clothis, and keste &thorn;aim samen &amp; sett hy&mtail;
dow&ntail; vppo&ntail; &thorn;aim and dispisi&dtail; &thorn;aim with
grete reprofe.  And onone in &thorn;ase placis he was so streky&ntail;
als fer as &thorn;ai tuchid hy&mtail;, &thorn;at als lang as he
liffi&dtail; after, wormes &amp; mawkis bred in his fless&hbar; &amp;
eate it away.  And of &thorn;at passio&ntail;, ewhils he liffi&dtail;,
he mot neuer be delyver&dtail;.  So afterwar&dtail; &thorn;er was ane
&thorn;at hight Julianus also, &thorn;at was his stewer&dtail;, and be
commandment of &thorn;e emperour he tuke &thorn;ies halod vesse&llbar;
&amp; pyssi&dtail; in &thorn;aim &amp; say&dtail;; "Lo! &thorn;ies
vesse&llbar; in &thorn;e whilk &thorn;e So&ntail; of Marie was
sacrifice&dtail;, now I pis in &thorn;aim <NOTE ID="P466.N2">MS. &thorn;eraim.</NOTE> ."
And with &thorn;at sodanlie his mouthe was turny&dtail; into his ars,
&amp; efter euer whils





<PB N="467">

he liffi&dtail;, a&llbar; &thorn;e filthe an&dtail; &thorn;e
degestio&ntail; of his bodie come out at his mouthe, &amp; noght at
his nache.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Sanitas.  Sanitatem recuperant aliqui miraculose.

Supra Dominici, iij, et infra de voto, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Sapiens tempore op[p]ortuno de neccessarijs sibi

providet.  Supra de providencia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Sapientis est loco et tempore timere.  Infra de

timore, i.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Sapiencie possunt adaptari multa que dicuntur supra

de cautela, de consilio, et de pluribus alijs in

diuersis locis, et infra de studio.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXCVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Satisfaccio.  Satisfacit viuus pro
mortuo.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Legenda Lombardica,' how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was
a womma&ntail; &thorn;at was a grete synner, to so meku&llbar; at sho
had done homage vnto &thorn;e devu&llbar;.  And whe&ntail; tyme drew
nere at sho sulde dye, hur so&ntail; cowncel&dtail; hur to be
shrevy&ntail;.  And sho ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; say&dtail;
&thorn;at shrufte mot not profett hur; not-with-stondyng he
labur&dtail; hur so att sho granti&dtail;, &amp; bad hy&mtail; feche
&thorn;e preste.  Bod or &thorn;e preste come, &thorn;er apperi&dtail;
vnto hur many fendis, &thorn;urg&hbar; vgsomnes &amp; drede of
&thorn;e whilke sho dye&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; hur so&ntail; come
agay&ntail; &amp; fande sho was dea&dtail;, he made meku&llbar; sorow,
for he knew hur sy&ntail; euere dele.  And he went &amp; shrafe
hy&mtail; of &thorn;at sy&ntail; at sho had done, &amp; did
&thorn;er-fo&rtail; vij wynter penance.  And &thorn;at done, his moder
apperi&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; &amp; thanki&dtail; hy&mtail;, &amp;
tolde hy&mtail; how &thorn;at &thorn;urg&hbar; his penance-doyng sho
was delyver&dtail; out of pay&ntail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Satisfaciendum est leso.  Supra de agro, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Satisfacit eciam vnus pro alio.  Supra de obligacione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Scandalum est vitandum.  Supra de abscondere.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>

<PB N="468">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXCVIII. 
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sciencia sacre scripture opere debet
impleri.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' how whe&ntail; &thorn;e abbott Pambo was
vnletter&dtail;, he went vnto a ma&ntail; &thorn;at was letter&dtail;
and praye&dtail; hy&mtail; to ler&ntail; hy&mtail; a salme.  And
whe&ntail; he had lernyd hy&mtail; &thorn;e furste vers of &thorn;is
salme, ' <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Dixi custodiam vias meas,</FOREIGN>' he
wolde not ler&ntail; &thorn;e secund vers nor no mo&rtail;
&thorn;erof, bod sayd; ' <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Satis est,</FOREIGN>' it
was enog&hbar;.  "For," he sai&dtail;, "and I may fulfy&llbar;
&thorn;is, it sufficies me."  So afterwarde he was axki&dtail; of his
maister whi he come not at hy&mtail; ans in sex monethis, and he
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "I hafe not yit fulfyllid
&thorn;at wurde in dede."  So long after he was axki&dtail; if he had
fulfilli&dtail; it, and he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
say&dtail;; "I hafe liffi&dtail; &thorn;is xliiij yeris, and yit
vnnethis I ca&ntail; fulfy&llbar; itt."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCXCIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sciencia eciam aliquando procuracione
demonis
<NOTE ID="P468.N1">So Latin MSS. The English MS. <HI REND="i">has</HI>, mentis.</NOTE> acquiritur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a scoler of
Paryss&hbar;, &amp; he had a du&llbar; witt and a forgetty&llbar;
mynde, so &thorn;at he cuthe nothyng nowder ler&ntail; nor holde.  And
evur-ilk ma&ntail; skorny&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; calli&dtail;
hy&mtail; idiott, and he&rtail;fo&rtail; he was passynglie
confusi&dtail;, so &thorn;at &thorn;e devu&llbar; apperi&dtail; vnto
hy&mtail; and axki&dtail; hy&mtail; if he wulde do hy&mtail; homage,
and he sulde hight hy&mtail; a&llbar; maner of connyng.  And &thorn;is
scolar wolde not, bod forsuke hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e
devu&llbar; put a stane in his han&dtail; &amp; sayde vnto hy&mtail;;
"Als lang as &thorn;ou holdis &thorn;is stane in &thorn;i han&dtail;,
&thorn;ou sa&llbar; know a&llbar; maner of thyng."  And with &thorn;at
he rase &amp; went into &thorn;e scule.  And onone he put oute
questions, &amp; concludid a&llbar; &thorn;at evur was in &thorn;e
scule.  And evur-ilk ma&ntail; had merve&llbar; how &thorn;is idiott
shulde hafe suche connyng, and he wolde te&llbar; &thorn;e cauce vnto
no ma&ntail;.  So not lang after, hy&mtail; happend fa&llbar; seke,
and of a&llbar; &thorn;is he shrafe hy&mtail;, &amp; he keste away
&thorn;e stane and &thorn;is dessayvable connyng to-gedur.  And
whe&ntail; he was dea&dtail;



<PB N="469">

and prestis and clerkis sang salmys aboute hy&mtail;, devuls tuke his
saule, an[d on] &thorn;e to syde of a vayle a&llbar; of burntstone
&thorn;ai play&dtail; &thorn;erwith as wha played at &thorn;e fandyng
of &thorn;e hand-ba&llbar; our &thorn;is dale, and o&ntail; &thorn;e
toder syde of &thorn;e valley oder fendis cleki&dtail; it with
&thorn;er sharpe naylis; &amp; &thorn;is passi&dtail; a&llbar; maner
of o&thorn;er paynys.  Neuer-&thorn;e-les at &thorn;e laste, our Lorde
had bene mercyfu&llbar; of <NOTE ID="P469.N1"><HI REND="i">After</HI> of, our, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> hy&mtail; becauce he
was deseyvi&dtail;, and his saule was put vnto &thorn;e bodie.  &amp;
sodanlie he rase, &amp; a&llbar; &thorn;at was aboute hy&mtail; fled.
And he come done of &thorn;e bere and went &amp; made hy&mtail; a monk
in Ceustus ordur, and &thorn;er he turment hy&mtail; selfe with harde
penance als lang as he liffi&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCC.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sciencia nigromancie
<NOTE ID="P469.N2">MS. nigramancie.</NOTE> est mors anime.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis of ij yong me&ntail; &thorn;at was at Tholence,
&amp; &thorn;er &thorn;ai studi&dtail; in nygramancye.  So &thorn;e
tane of &thorn;aim happen&dtail; to fa&llbar; seke, bow&ntail; to dye,
and &thorn;e toder praye&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;at with-in xx dayes
after his dissese he wol&dtail; apere vnto hy&mtail;, &amp; latt
hy&mtail; witt how it stude with hy&mtail;.  And he grawnti&dtail;,
&amp; he mot be suffred &thorn;erto, with gude wi&llbar;, and
&thorn;a&ntail; he dye&dtail;.  And with-in &thorn;e tear&mtail; he
apperi&dtail; vnto his felow, and he axki&dtail; hy&mtail; of his
estate.  And he ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;;
"Wo is me, for I a&mtail; [dampnyd] <NOTE ID="P469.N3">Latin, 'Ve mihi, dampnatus sum.'</NOTE> for
&thorn;e connyng of dialetyk&ktee; &thorn;at I lerny&dtail;.  And
&thorn;erfo&rtail;," he sai&dtail;, "I counce&llbar; &thorn;e att
&thorn;ou lefe itt."  And he agrei&dtail; &amp; di&dtail; aftur his
cownce&llbar;, and lefte hitt &amp; made hy&mtail; a monk in Ceustus
ordur, &amp; &thorn;er he liffi&dtail; a&llbar; his lyffe.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCI. 
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sciencia nigromantica penas inferni videre
facit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis of one Lodowicus at was &thorn;e so&ntail; of
Lowis, Lantgrauius Thuringie <NOTE ID="P469.N4">MS. latograuii Thiringie.</NOTE> , and he covett
greteli to know how it stude with &thorn;e saule of his fadur.  And he
promytt a grete rewar&dtail; vnto









<PB N="470">

hy&mtail; &thorn;at cuthe te&llbar; hy&mtail; any thyng how it stude
with his fadur at was decesi&dtail;, &amp; te&llbar; hy&mtail; gude
tythandis of hy&mtail;.  So &thorn;er was a knyght at har&dtail;
te&llbar; here-off, and he had a bruder &thorn;at was a nygromansyer,
and he tolde hy&mtail; here-of and bad hy&mtail; do his labur herein.
So he went vnto his crafte &amp; calli&dtail; vp a devu&llbar;, and
garte hy&mtail; bere hy&mtail; vnto he&llbar;.  &amp; &thorn;er he saw
many vgso&mtail; turment and many dyvers kyndes of paynys.  And
&thorn;er he saw a fen&dtail; sytt apo&ntail; &thorn;e coueryng of
&thorn;e pitt, and whe&ntail; &thorn;e coueryng was taky&ntail; of
&thorn;e pytt, onone a trumpe a&llbar; of fyre come oute of &thorn;e
pytt, and made suc&hbar; a noyce at &thorn;e cler&ktee; went at
a&llbar; &thorn;is werl&dtail; had bene at an en&dtail; <NOTE ID="P470.N1">MS. a nen&dtail;.</NOTE> .  And &thorn;a&ntail; he saw ascende oute of
&thorn;e pytt flawmes of fyre a&llbar; like burnsto&ntail;.  And emang
&thorn;aim he saw co&mtail; v&ptail; &thorn;is Lowis Latograuius,
&amp; he put furt&hbar; his han&dtail; vnto &thorn;e clerk &amp;
say&dtail;; "I a&mtail; her, &thorn;is wriche&dtail; Lowys, so&mtail;
tyme lorde of &thorn;e cete.  And now &thorn;ou seis wele myne astate.
Bod &amp; my childer wolde restore agay&ntail; suche possessions,
whilk whe&ntail; I liffi&dtail; I tuke fro suche kurkis, &thorn;ai
myght do me grete remedie, and &thorn;at &thorn;ou sa&llbar; te&llbar;
&thorn;aim be suche takens."  And &thorn;is done, he went into
&thorn;e pitt agay&ntail;.  And &thorn;e clerk was broght agay&ntail;
whik, neuer-&thorn;e-les he was pale &amp; passan&dtail; seke, and he
tel&dtail; &thorn;e fadurs sayingis &amp; &thorn;e tokyns vn-to his
childer.  And &thorn;ai tuke it to no fors, nor wolde nott restore
&thorn;e possessions agay&ntail;.  &amp; so it is to suppose &thorn;er
fadur saule abydis &thorn;urg&hbar; &thorn;er necligens in
perpetua&llbar; dampnacio&ntail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Seculi philosophi.  Infra de silencio.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Secretum debet celari.  Supra de celacione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Senex assuetus malis vix illa dimittit.  Supra de
Andrea.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sepulture non debent indifferenter in ecclesia
fieri.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Gregur tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a bissho&ptail;
&thorn;at grawnti&dtail; a place of beria&llbar; in &thorn;e
kur&ktee; vnto a riche ma&ntail; &thorn;at hight Valerius Patricius,
&thorn;at was a synner of his bodie.  And vppo&ntail; &thorn;e same
nyght Saynt Fausty&ntail;, in whase kur&ktee; &thorn;is was done,



<PB N="471">

apperi&dtail; vnto &thorn;e keper of &thorn;e <NOTE ID="P471.N1"><HI REND="i">After</HI> &thorn;e, keper, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE>
kurk &amp; sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "Go &amp; say vnto &thorn;e
bissho&ptail; &thorn;at he caste oute yone stynkan&dtail; fless&hbar;
oute of my kur&ktee;, or els he sa&llbar; dye with-in xxx<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> dayes."
And he had grete drede &thorn;eroff for to do itt, &amp; wolde not do
it.  Vppo&ntail; &thorn;e xxx<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> day he went to be&dtail; in wharte
&amp; hea&llbar;, &amp; o&ntail; &thorn;e mor&ntail; he was fo&ntail;
dea&dtail; in his bed sodanlie.  Also Valentinus &thorn;at wont in
Melay&ntail;, whe&ntail; he was beri&dtail; in &thorn;e kurk of Saynt
Sixtus, aboute mydnyght in &thorn;e same kurk was har&dtail; voyces
and cryes, as &thorn;er had bene me&ntail; <NOTE ID="P471.N2">MS. a me&ntail;.</NOTE> at
had bene draw&ntail; oute &thorn;er agay&ntail; &thorn;er wy&llbar;;
vnto &thorn;e whilk voycis &thorn;e kepers of &thorn;e kur&ktee;
ra&ntail;, and saw ij vglie <NOTE ID="P471.N3">Latin, duos deterrimos specie.</NOTE> &thorn;at
ban&dtail; &thorn;is Valentyne fete, and with a grete noyce &thorn;ai
drew hy&mtail; oute.  And o&ntail; &thorn;e mor&ntail; &thorn;ai soght
for hy&mtail; &amp; &thorn;ai fan&dtail; his bodie with-oute &thorn;e
kur&ktee;, caste&ntail; in a fowle dyke, and his fete bathe bo&ntail;
samen as &thorn;ai saw hy&mtail; drawe&ntail; oute of his grafe.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Sepeliuntur aliqui a Christo.  Supra de Martha et

Martino.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Sepultura in ecclesia&mtail; non impedit quin ibidem

sepulti puniantur.  Supra de locutione 
<NOTE ID="P471.N4"><HI REND="i">Reference from</HI> Latin MSS.</NOTE> , iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Sepeliri debet in sterquilinio religiosus proprietarius.

Supra de proprietario, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sepultura in ecclesiam quandoque parum
prodest.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Gregur tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was ane y&llbar;
ma&ntail; beri&dtail; in Saynt Laurence kurk at Rome.  And &thorn;er
was har&dtail; voyces comman&dtail;oute of his grafe, sayan&dtail;; "
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ardeo! ardeo!</FOREIGN> I bur&ntail;! I
bur&ntail;!"  And his wyfe, whe&ntail; sho har&dtail; te&llbar; of
&thorn;is, garte oppy&ntail; his grafe &amp; luki&dtail; what was
&thorn;erin; &amp; &thorn;ai fan&dtail; &thorn;e clothis at he was
wappi&dtail; in, bod his body was clene away.









<PB N="472">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sepeliri non debent vsurarij in claustris
religiosorum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede of ane archbyssho&ptail; <NOTE ID="P472.N1">Arund.  MS. archiepiscopus Bisuntinus.</NOTE> &thorn;at
hight Bysmytinus, at was a maister of dyvynitie, and he tellis how
o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; &thorn;er was ane vsurar beri&dtail; in
&thorn;e cloystur of ane abbay, he went oute of his grafe o&ntail;
&thorn;e nyght &amp; cryed &amp; may&dtail; grete noyce, &amp; threw
of &thorn;e thakk of &thorn;er dortur, &amp; fure fule with &thorn;e
monkis &amp; flaye&dtail; &thorn;aim &amp; di&dtail; meku&llbar;
skathe.  &amp; o&ntail; &thorn;e mor&ntail; his bodie was fo&ntail;
with-oute &thorn;e cetie, and it was broght agay&ntail; &amp; putt
into &thorn;e grafe.  Neuer-&thorn;e-les he di&dtail; oft sithis as he
did befo&rtail;.  So at &thorn;e laste, a holie ma&ntail;
coniuri&dtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; bad hy&mtail; te&llbar; hy&mtail; why
<NOTE ID="P472.N2">why, <HI REND="i">omitted and added above the line</HI>.</NOTE> &thorn;at he wulde not suffre hy&mtail; nor
&thorn;e monkis to hafe no reste.  And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail;
&amp; say&dtail;; "It is of me in despayr, ffor as with myne vsuris I
grevu&dtail; God bothe day &amp; nyght, right so I may hafe no reste
nowder day nor nyght.  Bod ye may be in gude reste and ye wol&dtail;
bere my bodie oute of your closter."  And so &thorn;ai di&dtail;, and
&thorn;ai war nevur after grevi&dtail; nor har&dtail; ma&rtail; of
hy&mtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sepeliri non debet vsurarius nisi sub
patibulo.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iacobus de Vetriaco tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was ane vsurar
&thorn;at wolde neuer restore his vsurie agay&ntail;, &thorn;uff
a&llbar; he war oft movi&dtail; &thorn;erto.  So hy&mtail;
happen&dtail; to fa&llbar; seke &amp; bow&ntail; to dye, and
calli&dtail; &thorn;e preste &amp; aski&dtail; his sacramentis; and
&thorn;e preste sai&dtail; he wulde gyff hy&mtail; no sacrament bod if
he restori&dtail; agay&ntail; his vsurie, and he wulde nott.  So
&thorn;e preste went away fro&mtail; hy&mtail; and his sekenes
incresi&dtail; on hy&mtail;, and he was bow&ntail; to dy.  &amp;
&thorn;e preste come, and &thorn;ai at warr aboute praye&dtail;
hy&mtail; to commend his sawle vnto almyghtie God, and he a[n]sswe[r]d
agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;, evy&ntail; whe&ntail; he was in







<PB N="473">

passyng; "I commend his saule vnto a&llbar; &thorn;e devuls in
he&llbar;."  And whe&ntail; he was dea&dtail;, his frendis
praye&dtail; &thorn;e preste at he mot be beri&dtail; in so&mtail;
noke or so&mtail; entre of &thorn;e kur&ktee;-gart&hbar;, becauce of
&thorn;e honestie; and &thorn;e preste denye&dtail; &thorn;aim &amp;
wolde nott.  And &thorn;is preste had ane ass &thorn;at did nothyng on
dayes bod cary&dtail; bukis &amp; vestementis fro &thorn;e prestis
howse into the kurk, and fro thens home agay&ntail;.  And sho cuthe go
no noder way bod vnto &thorn;e kurk &amp; fro &thorn;e kur&ktee;.  So
&thorn;is mans frendis praye&dtail; &thorn;e preste at his bodie mot
be lay&dtail; vppo&ntail; &thorn;e ass, and to what place
so&mtail;-evur at &thorn;e ass bare hy&mtail;, at &thorn;er he sulde
be berid; and &thorn;e preste grawnti&dtail;.  &amp; &thorn;ai made a
fu&llbar; barga&ntail;, trowyng at &thorn;e ass wol&dtail; owder bere
hy&mtail; vnto &thorn;e kur&ktee; or els vnto &thorn;e prestis
chawmer, becauce sho cuthe none oder way.  And we&ntail; his bodye was
lay&dtail; vppo&ntail; &thorn;is ass, sho nowder declynyd vnto
&thorn;e right hande nor &thorn;e lefte hand, bod bare hy&mtail;
evy&ntail; st[r]eght vnto &thorn;e galows, &amp; evy&ntail; vndernethe
&thorn;e galows sho shuke hy&mtail; dow&ntail;.  And &thorn;er he was
beri&dtail; <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">in sepultura patrum suorum</FOREIGN>.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Sequela.  Sequi plures non semper expedit.  Supra

de societate, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Sermo.  Sermonem audire impedit demon.  Supra

de auditu.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Sermoni possunt adaptari multa que dicuntur supra

de doctore, locucione, predicatore, et infra de

verbo.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Serpens.  Serpenti comparatur nequicia
aliquorum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Petrus Alphonsis <NOTE ID="P473.N1">MS. Petrus Alphensis.</NOTE> on a tyme as he went be a
wud-syde tellis how &thorn;at he fan&dtail; a serpent slay&ntail; with
hurdme&ntail;, &amp; bo&ntail; vnto a stokk; and he lowsi&dtail; hur
becauce sho was som-what on lyfe, &amp; lay&dtail; hur &thorn;er sho
mot fele warmenes of &thorn;e so&ntail;.  And so whe&ntail; sho was a
lity&llbar; warmy&dtail;, sho crope aboute hy&mtail;, and at &thorn;e
laste sho tange&dtail; hy&mtail; hugelie.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he
sai&dtail; vnto hur; "What dois



<PB N="474">

&thorn;ou? &thorn;ou dose me i&llbar; for gude, and whi duse &thorn;ou
so?"  And &thorn;e serpent ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
sai&dtail;; "I do not bod my kyn&dtail;."  And with &thorn;at sho
clappi&dtail; hur faste aboute his legg.  And he wol&dtail; hafe
ha&dtail; hur of &amp; sho wol&dtail; nott.  And so, be &thorn;er
bother assent, &thorn;ai calli&dtail; vnto &thorn;aim a fox to gyff a
iugemen&dtail; wheder sho sulde lowse of his legg or nay.  And
&thorn;ey tol&dtail; hy&mtail; a&llbar; &thorn;e matir how it
happen&dtail;.  Tha&ntail; &thorn;e fox say&dtail;; "In &thorn;is
cauce I ca&ntail; gyff no dome be heryng, bod if I se at myne ee how
it was with you bothe at your furste metyng."  So &thorn;is
serpen&dtail; lowsi&dtail;, &amp; onone sho was bo&ntail; vnto
&thorn;e stokk agay&ntail; as he fan&dtail; hur.  And &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;e fox gaff his iugement &amp; say&dtail;; "O &thorn;ou serpent!
&amp; &thorn;ou may now esskape, go &thorn;i wayes!  And &thorn;ou
ma&ntail;!" he say&dtail;, "I cownce&llbar; &thorn;e not labur no
mo&rtail; to lowse hur."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Seruicium.  Seruire Deo est vtile.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Libro de Dono Timoris' how som tyme &thorn;er was a
kyng &thorn;at had a baillay, &amp; he servi&dtail; hy&mtail; alway
trewlie.  So o&ntail; a tyme hy&mtail; happen&dtail; fa&llbar; seke,
and &thorn;e kyng come &amp; visit hy&mtail; &amp; offer&dtail;
hy&mtail; &thorn;at what &thorn;ing at he wol&dtail; aske, he sulde
hafe it.  And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "I wulde
beseke you at ye wulde delyver me of &thorn;is sekenes, for I a&mtail;
gretlie turment &thorn;er-with."  And &thorn;e kyng ansswer&dtail;
hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail; &thorn;at he wol&dtail; do it
with gude wi&llbar; and he myght, bod he say&dtail; &thorn;at he myght
nott.  Tha&ntail; &thorn;e seke ma&ntail; ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail;
&amp; say&dtail;; "Se&ntail; ye may not delyver me of my sekenes, here
I promytt to Hy&mtail; &thorn;at may delyver me, &thorn;at &amp; He
wi&llbar; delyver me &thorn;erof, ffrom hens furt&hbar; I sha&llbar;
seryff Hy&mtail; alone, &amp; nevur no ma&ntail;."  And onone he
cover&dtail; &amp; tuke hy&mtail; to &thorn;e serves of almyghti God,
&amp; wol&dtail; nevur seruff ma&ntail; after.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Seruilis timor inicium est boni.  Infra de timore

et voto.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Seueritas.  Seuerus iudex.  Supra de iudice, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>

<PB N="475">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Signum.  Signis evidentibus aliquando impedit Deus

malos vt non compleant quod ceperunt.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how Iulianus Apostata in dispite of criste&ntail;
me&ntail; garte &thorn;e Iewis repayre an&dtail; belde agay&ntail; ane
olde temple, &amp; gaff &thorn;aim grete gudis to &thorn;e bigyng
&thorn;er-of.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai had bygy&dtail; v&ptail; a
grete dele &thorn;eroff with lyme and stone, sodanly &thorn;er come a
grete wyn&dtail; &amp; blew a&llbar; dow&ntail;, and efter &thorn;at
&thorn;er come ane erde-quake &amp; shuke dow&ntail; &thorn;e
reuersyo&ntail;, &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;er come a fyre
evy&ntail; oute of &thorn;e gron&dtail;, &amp; not alonelie
burny&dtail; itt, bod also a&llbar; &thorn;aim &thorn;at come nere it.
And &thorn;a&ntail;, wit-in a day or ij after, &thorn;er apperi&dtail;
in &thorn;e ayre a syngne of &thorn;e cros.  And sodanlie a&llbar;
&thorn;e Iewis clothis wer fylli&dtail; with blak crossis.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Signa plura et diuersorum signorum narraciones

inuenies in libello de mirabilibus rebus et

eventibus, quem deo auxiliante intendo compilare.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Signum crucis.  Supra de cruce.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Silencium tenere est assu[esc]endum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' how abbot Agothe&ntail; bare in his
mouthe iij yere a stone vn[to] he was lerny&dtail; to be sty&llbar;
and sylent.  Also &thorn;er was a noder bruder &thorn;at whe&ntail; he
entred into religio&ntail; say&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; selfe; "Thow
&amp; ane ass be bothe as one; ffor as ane as is betin &amp; wy&llbar;
not speke, and suffers wrang and ansswers not, right so sa&llbar;
&thorn;ou bee; ffor &amp; &thorn;ou war putt fro &thorn;e burde,
&thorn;ou sulde not ansswer."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Silencium aliquando aliquis imponit sibi in
penam.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in &thorn;e 'Life of Secundus Philosophus,' how &thorn;at
o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; he was a chil&dtail; and went vnto &thorn;e
skule, and har&dtail; te&llbar; &thorn;at evur-ilk womma&ntail; was
incontynent, whe&ntail; he was perfite in

<PB N="476">

philosophye he went home in-to his aw&ntail; contre like as he had
bene a pylgre&mtail;, with a skryp&ptail; &amp; a staff.  And his hare
of his hea&dtail; &amp; his ber&dtail; war growe&ntail; long.  So he
was hosti&dtail; in his moder hows, and nowder sho nor none of
&thorn;e howshol&dtail; ken&dtail; hy&mtail;.  And he thoght he wolde
prufe if it wer trew &thorn;at was say&dtail; of womme&ntail;, and he
hight one of &thorn;e maydens x nobles to make hy&mtail; to lye be his
moder.  And sho grawnty&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; &amp; his moder bothe.
So at evy&ntail; he was broght in, and &thorn;ai went to bed samen.
And sho trowi&dtail; he sulde [hafe] <NOTE ID="P476.N1">MS. he.</NOTE> had at do
with hur, and whe&ntail; &thorn;ai war in be&dtail; he halsi&dtail;
hur in his armys as a chylde sulde do &thorn;e moder, &amp; lay
sty&llbar; &amp; his breste vnto hurs a&llbar; &thorn;e nyght &amp;
slepi&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; it was mor&ntail; he rase, and his moder
say&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "Wharto haste &thorn;ou &thorn;us
attempi&dtail; me?"  And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sayde;
"Nay, moder!  It is not wurthi to me to fyle &thorn;at vesse&llbar; at
I come oute off, ffor I a&mtail; Secundus, &thorn;i so&ntail;."  And
whe&ntail; sho har&dtail; &thorn;is, sho was so confusi&dtail; at sho
mot not suffre it, bod fe&llbar; in a deade swownyng &amp; spak neuer
wur&dtail; after.  So &thorn;is Secundus, whe&ntail; he saw sho was
dea&dtail;, he vnderstude &thorn;at his wurdis was cauce &thorn;eroff,
and he kepi&dtail; sylens &amp; wolde not speke.  So o&ntail; a tyme
after-war&dtail;, hy&mtail; happen&dtail; sodanlie to mete &thorn;e
emperour and he hailsi&dtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; he wol&dtail; not speke
agay&ntail;.  So &thorn;e emperour commawndi&dtail; becauce he
wol&dtail; not speke, at his hede sulde be smyte&ntail; of, and
delyuer&dtail; hy&mtail; vnto a ma&ntail;-wheller, and commandi&dtail;
hy&mtail; to labur hy&mtail; be &thorn;e way to luke if he cuthe gar
hy&mtail; speke.  And if he spak, he bad hy&mtail; smyte of his
hea&dtail;, &amp; if he wolde not speke, he ba&dtail; hy&mtail; latt
hy&mtail; goo.  And &thorn;is ma&ntail;-wheller sai&dtail; vnto
hy&mtail; as he went; "O, &thorn;ou Secundus!  Whi wi&llbar; &thorn;ou
dye?  Speke, and &thorn;ou mo&ntail; liff."  So he sett noght be his
lyfe, bod bade vppo&ntail; his dea&dtail; and lay&dtail; hy&mtail;
dow&ntail; &amp; putt furt&hbar; his nek&ktee;, redie to be
hedi&dtail;.  And &thorn;is done, &thorn;e manwheller broght hy&mtail;
agay&ntail; vnto &thorn;e emperour, and tolde hy&mtail; how &thorn;at,
vnto dye &thorn;erfo&rtail;, he wol&dtail; nevur speke wur&dtail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Silencium quandoque venditur.  Supra de aduocatis.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>



<PB N="477">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Silencium tenere debent religiosi.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Iero&mtail; tellis &amp; says; "I saw Saynt Theo&ntail;
sparri&dtail; in a ce&llbar;, solitarie, as it was say&dtail;, xxx<HI REND="sup">ti</HI>
yere, and evur he kepi&dtail; sylens."  And of hy&mtail; writis
Socrates &amp; says; "Theonas, &thorn;e fadur of iij m&lbar; monkys,
at was moste connyng in lettres of grew &amp; laty&ntail;, xxx<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> yeris
spa&ktee; nevur wurde, savyng in his prayers."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Silencium strictissimum tenere debent
religiosi.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede of Zenocrates &thorn;e philosophur, how o&ntail; a tyme as
he satt talkan&dtail; with oder folk, sodanlie he hel&dtail; his tong
&amp; wol&dtail; not ansswer &thorn;aim.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai
axki&dtail; hy&mtail; whi he wolde not speke <NOTE ID="P477.N1">MS. spele.</NOTE> ,
he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Som tyme me hase
forthoght &thorn;at I spa&ktee;, bod neuer &thorn;at I hel&dtail; my
tong."
</P>

<P>Also we rede in 'Vitis Patrum' how &thorn;at one alde mon&ktee;
kepi&dtail; a passan&dtail; strayte sylence.  And o&ntail; a tyme
whe&ntail; &thorn;er come vnto hy&mtail; a ma&ntail; of grete
auctoritie, &thorn;e brethir praye&dtail; hy&mtail; at he sulde putt
vnto hy&mtail; som gude thyng for edificacio&ntail; of his sawle.
[&amp; he ansswerd again &amp; said] <NOTE ID="P477.N2"><HI REND="i">The Latin version has the usual preface</HI>: qui ait.</NOTE> ,
"An&dtail; he be not amendi&dtail; be my silence, he may not be
amendi&dtail; be my wur&dtail;."
</P>

<P>Also Guillelmus tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was ane erle in
Normondie &thorn;at was passan&dtail; deuote vnto almi&yogh;tty
Go&dtail;.  And he vsi&dtail; oft sithis to vissit a kur&ktee; of
monkis.  So o&ntail; a tyme he come tymelie o&ntail; a nyght in a meke
habett, and I ca&ntail; not say be whatt crafte, bod he gatt into
&thorn;e kur&ktee;.  And &thorn;e sacrista&ntail;, trowyng at he had
bene a thefe, bett hy&mtail; &amp; putt hy&mtail; oute of &thorn;e
kur&ktee;.  And in &thorn;e mornyng, &thorn;e erle come into &thorn;e
chapitur howse emang &thorn;e monkis, &amp; commendi&dtail; &thorn;is
sacrista&ntail; becauce he was so diligent in his offes, &amp; at he
spari&dtail; hy&mtail; not whe&ntail; he come at inordinatt tyme.  And
fro thens furt&hbar; &thorn;is erle was so diligent in his offes &amp;
his prayers, at &thorn;er myght none grevans lett his silens.





<PB N="478">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Siluestri confessoris.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in his Legent how Constantyne &thorn;e emperour was made
lepre, and &thorn;urg&hbar; cownce&llbar; of a bissho&ptail; <NOTE ID="P478.N1">Latin, de consilio pontificis.</NOTE> &thorn;er was iij M&lbar; childer broght vnto Rome
to be slay&ntail;, at he mot be bathe&dtail; in &thorn;er war&mtail;
blude &amp; so be made hale.  And whe&ntail; he saw &thorn;e moders of
&thorn;ies childer, shewan&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;er brestis &amp;
pulland of &thorn;er hare, &amp; wepan&dtail; befo&rtail; hy&mtail;,
he made sorow &amp; say&dtail;; "How sulde I vse &thorn;is
wykki&dtail; bat&hbar;?  It is bettur to me to dye for &thorn;e heale
of &thorn;ies innocentis, &thorn;a&ntail; for to requovir my life for
&thorn;er deade."  And with &thorn;at he commandi&dtail; &thorn;e
childer agay&ntail; to be delyver&dtail; vnto &thorn;er moders, and
giff &thorn;aim grete giftis also.  And vppo&ntail; &thorn;at same
nyght, Saynt Petur apperi&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; and Saynt Paule, &amp;
sayd vnto hy&mtail;; "Becauce &thorn;ou vggi&dtail; to sla so
myc&hbar; innocent blude, ou&rtail; Lor&dtail; lesu Cryste sent vs to
giff &thorn;e cownce&llbar; how &thorn;ou sal be heli&dtail;.  Thow
sa&llbar; ca&llbar; Siluester &thorn;e bissho&ptail; <NOTE ID="P478.N2">Latin, episcopus.</NOTE> vnto the, &amp; here hy&mtail;, and &thorn;ou
sa&llbar; be curi&dtail;."  And he garte ca&llbar; hy&mtail;, &amp;
tolde hy&mtail; a&llbar; hys visio&ntail;.  And so Siluester
tol&dtail; hy&mtail; at &thorn;ase goddis at he wurshuppi&dtail; was
no goddis, bod &thorn;e servandis of goddis, as &thorn;e so&ntail;
&amp; &thorn;e mone, et cetera.  And he shewi&dtail; hy&mtail;
&thorn;er ymagis, at he mott verelie know what &thorn;ai wer.  And
&thorn;us he was enformy&dtail; in &thorn;e fayt&hbar; an&dtail;
cristen&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; he come oute of &thorn;e watir of
bapty&mtail;, he was clene of his lepre.  And a grete shynyng was our
hy&mtail;, to so meku&llbar; as he sai&dtail; he saw almighti
Go&dtail;; &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; he gaff meku&llbar; privalege vnto
&thorn;e kur&ktee;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Simia.  Simie peccator assimilatur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Libro de Dono Timoris,' how &thorn;e propurtie of
&thorn;e ape is to hafe ij whelpis; &amp; whe&ntail; &thorn;e hunter
commys &amp; pursewis hur, sho takis &thorn;at at sho luffis bettur in
hur armys, &amp; &thorn;e toder lepis vp o&ntail; hur bak&ktee;.  And
whe&ntail; &thorn;e hunter sewis hur sore, sho levis &thorn;at at is
in hur armys &amp; lattis it fa&llbar;, &amp; &thorn;e toder clevis
sti&llbar; by hur.





<PB N="479">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Simon Magus.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Leo &thorn;e pope tellis how o&ntail; a tyme as Symo&ntail;
stude befo&rtail; Nero, his sha&ptail; turnyd sodanlie, &amp; now he
semy&dtail; one olde ma&ntail; &amp; now a yong ma&ntail;.  And
herefor Nero trowi&dtail; &thorn;at he had bene &thorn;e so&ntail; of
Go&dtail;.  So o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;is Symo&ntail; say&dtail; vnto
Nero; "Becauce at &thorn;ou sha&llbar; verelie know at I a&mtail;
Goddis son, comman&dtail; my hea&dtail; to be smyty&ntail; of, &amp;
o&ntail; &thorn;e iij day I sa&llbar; rice fro deade vnto life."  And
so it was.  &amp; whe&ntail; &thorn;e turmetur trowi&dtail; &thorn;at
he had smyty&ntail; of his hea&dtail;, he strake of the head of a
weddur, &amp; hi&dtail; it &amp; hel&dtail; hy&mtail; away iij dayes
at he was not sene.  And &thorn;e weddur blude lay sty&llbar; in a
cake.  And o&ntail; &thorn;e iij day he present hy&mtail; vnto Nero,
&amp; bad hy&mtail; gar gedur vp his blude, for he &thorn;at was
hedi&dtail; was ressy&ntail; fro dea&dtail; vnto lyfe agay&ntail; as
he made his promys.  And whe&ntail; Nero saw hy&mtail; he had grete
mervayle, and trowi&dtail; at he had bene &thorn;e verray so&ntail; of
Go&dtail;.  So afterwar&dtail; o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; he was with
Nero in a chawmer, a fen&dtail; in his lyknes spakk with-oute vnto
&thorn;e peple.  Bod whe&ntail; Saynt Petur come, he vndi&dtail;
a&llbar; his crafte; and whe&ntail; he was flean&dtail; in &thorn;e
ayr, &thorn;urg&hbar; his prayer he made hy&mtail; to fa&llbar;, &amp;
bra&ktee; evure bone <NOTE ID="P479.N1">MS. evur ebone.</NOTE> of hy&mtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Simonia.  Simoniace nullus debet elegi.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; &thorn;ai sulde
chese a new abbott at &thorn;e abbay of Saynt Denys in Fraunce,
&thorn;e priour of &thorn;e same monasterie come vnto &thorn;e kyng of
France, &amp; gaff hy&mtail; l libras, &amp; prayed hy&mtail; to
vuchesafe favur his partie.  And &thorn;e kyng wol&dtail; beheste
hy&mtail; no thyng, bod tuke &thorn;e money &amp; made hy&mtail; in a
hope, &amp; betuke &thorn;is money vnto his chamberlay&ntail;.  So
&thorn;e selerer of &thorn;e place wyste not of &thorn;is, nor
&thorn;e thresurar nowder, and ather of &thorn;aim



<PB N="480">

come vnto &thorn;e kyng &amp; broght hy&mtail; a grete so&mtail; of
gol&dtail; &amp; praye&dtail; hy&mtail; favur &thorn;aim.  &amp; he
tuke &thorn;e mony evure dele <NOTE ID="P480.N1">MS. evur edele.</NOTE> .  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;e day come at &thorn;e abbott sulde be chosy&ntail; o&ntail;,
and &thorn;e kyng satt in &thorn;e chapytur-hows, and &thorn;ies iij
abade of &thorn;e kynges rewar&dtail;, &thorn;e kyng was war of a gude
innocent monke, syttan&dtail; in &thorn;e hyr&ntail; of &thorn;e
chapitre.  And he calli&dtail; hy&mtail; vnto hy&mtail; and made
hy&mtail; abbott.  And he excusi&dtail; hy&mtail; faste &amp; wolde
nott hafe bene, and alegi&dtail; many thyngis.  And emang o&thorn;er
&thorn;ingis he alegi&dtail; at &thorn;e abbay was gretelie
endetti&dtail;, &amp; he was bod a pure ma&ntail;.  And with &thorn;at
&thorn;e kyng smyli&dtail;, and ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp;
say&dtail;; "I sa&llbar; giff &thorn;e onone M &lbar; pon&dtail;, and
if &thorn;ou myster I sa&llbar; le&ntail; &thorn;e als muche, and
helpe &thorn;e &amp; forther &thorn;e in &thorn;at I ca&ntail;.  And
&thorn;erfo&rtail; take it on han&dtail; boldlie."  And so he
di&dtail;, and &thorn;e kyng gaff hy&mtail; &thorn;is gude at
&thorn;ai had broght hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;us &thorn;ies symonyers
war confusi&dtail;, &amp; belife &thorn;e abbay was wele rewli&dtail;
and clere oute of dett.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Simonia committitur sine pecunia.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how o&ntail; a tyme a holie ancres say&dtail; vnto
ane abbott of Ceustus ordur, whe&ntail; he spirri&dtail; hur whedur it
was expedient vnto hy&mtail; to be abbott or nay, and sho said nay, it
was not expedient unto hy&mtail; to abyde abbott, ffor he entri&dtail;
&thorn;erinto be symonye.  And he ansswerd hur agay&ntail; &amp;
say&dtail;; "What says &thorn;ou?  Says &thorn;ou at I have done
symonye?"  And sho ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
say&dtail;; "Whe&ntail; &thorn;e day of your eleccio&ntail; come,
&thorn;ou, desyran&dtail; &thorn;e abbotshu&ptail;, went not symeplie
as &thorn;ou was wunte to do, bod &thorn;ou sai&dtail; vnto &thorn;e
symeple monkis o&ntail; &thorn;is maner of wyse; 'It is not ou&rtail;
wurshu&ptail; to chese our abbott with-oute our abbay,' becauce
&thorn;ou knew &thorn;er was none in &thorn;e abbay aby&llbar; to be
abbot bod &thorn;ou.  And &thorn;us &thorn;ou begyli&dtail; &thorn;aim
&amp; was made abbott."  And whe&ntail; he har&dtail; &thorn;is, he
grawnti&dtail; it &amp; cuthe nott agay&ntail;-say it.  &amp;
&thorn;a&ntail; he gaff v&ptail; his abbotshu&ptail; &amp; become a
closter monke.



<PB N="481">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Simplicitas aliquando prodest.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a noble
castella&ntail;, and he vsi&dtail; oft sithes to take cate&llbar;
&amp; shepe of a certay&ntail; abbay of Ceustus ordur &thorn;at was
nere-han&dtail; hy&mtail;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e abbott &amp;
dyvers of &thorn;e monkis praye&dtail; hy&mtail; to lefe, he wolde
nott.  So o&ntail; a day he drafe away a grete drafe of &thorn;er
cate&llbar;, and &thorn;e abbott sent vnto hy&mtail; a monke &thorn;at
was bo&dtail; a symple ma&ntail;, and commaundi&dtail; hy&mtail;
&thorn;at what at evur he mot gett agay&ntail; of &thorn;is
cate&llbar;, he sulde with-owte&ntail; delay resayfe it.  So aboute
mete-tyme, &thorn;is monke come vnto &thorn;e caste&llbar;, and
di&dtail; his message.  &amp; &thorn;e knyght ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail;
&amp; say&dtail;; "Sur, ye sa&llbar; furste dyne, &amp;
&thorn;a&ntail; I sa&llbar; gyff you ane ansswer."  And as &thorn;e
monke sat at meate emang o&thorn;er me&ntail;, he was servi&dtail;
with fless&hbar; as o&thorn;er was, and &thorn;at largelie.  So he
vmthoght hy&mtail; of &thorn;e cate&llbar; of &thorn;er abbay, and he
ete of &thorn;is fless&hbar; a grete repaste; and &thorn;e knyght
&amp; his wyfe behelde hy&mtail; grathelie.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai
had dyny&dtail;, &thorn;is knyght calli&dtail; &thorn;e monke osyde,
&amp; axki&dtail; hy&mtail; whi he ete fless&hbar; whe&ntail; it was
rewle of his ordur &thorn;at monkis sulde [not] ete fless&hbar;?  And
&thorn;e monke fu&llbar; mekelie ansswerd hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
sai&dtail;; "Sur, myne obedyence cawsi&dtail; me to eat fless&hbar;,
ffor myne abbot commaundi&dtail; me &thorn;at of our cate&llbar; at
was tane away fro vs, I sulde resayfe agay&ntail; what at I mot gett.
And I knew wele at &thorn;e fless&hbar; at was sett befo&rtail; me was
of our cate&llbar;, and I trow &thorn;at I mo&ntail; nevur requover
mare.  And &thorn;erfo&rtail; in etyng, I resayvi&dtail; als
meku&llbar; as I myght."  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e knyght har&dtail;
&thorn;is, he was somwhat compuncte with &thorn;e monkis meke ansswer,
and he calli&dtail; his me&ntail; &amp; commaundi&dtail; at &thorn;e
monke sulde be restori&dtail; of als many cate&llbar; agay&ntail; as
evur he had tane fro &thorn;aim.  And also he beheste at fro thens
furt&hbar; he sulde not noy &thorn;aim, bott rather restore
&thorn;aim.  And &thorn;e cate&llbar; was delyver&dtail; vnto &thorn;e
mon&ktee;, and he went home with &thorn;ai&mtail; &amp; with his
mesage to-gedur, and telli&dtail; &thorn;e abbott &amp; &thorn;e
covent a&llbar; how he had done.  And &thorn;ai had grete merve&llbar;
here-off, &amp; thanki&dtail; God &amp; was fu&llbar; fay&ntail;.

<PB N="482">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Simplex aliquando deridetur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;at som tyme in Cola&ntail; &thorn;er
was a chano&ntail; at was so symple &amp; so vnconnyng &thorn;at he
cuthe nott te&llbar; no maner of nowmer, nor te&llbar; whilk was
o&dtail; whilk was evy&ntail; <NOTE ID="P482.N1">Harl. MS. vt nichil numerare sciret nisi in quantum res essent pares.</NOTE> , bod at he
wal&dtail; a&llbar; way cownt ij thynges to-gedur.  So o&ntail; a tyme
hy&mtail; happen&dtail; be made chano&ntail; of &thorn;e kechyng, and
he had &thorn;er many bakon-flikkis in &thorn;e balkis.  So o&ntail; a
tyme hy&mtail; happen&dtail; to te&llbar; &thorn;aim, and he cuthe no
noderways te&llbar;, &amp; he cuthe say none oder bod &thorn;us; "Lo,
&thorn;er a bake&ntail;-flyk&ktee; &amp; his felag&hbar;, and
&thorn;er a noder bako&ntail;-flikk &amp; his felow <NOTE ID="P482.N2">MS. flelow.</NOTE> ."  And so of a&llbar; &thorn;e toder.  So o&ntail;
a tyme one of hys meneya with-drew one of &thorn;ies
bako&ntail;-flykkis.  So o&ntail; [a] tyme afterwar&dtail;, &thorn;is
chano&ntail; come into &thorn;e kechy&ntail; agay&ntail;, and
telli&dtail; &thorn;ies bako&ntail;-flykkis &amp; fan&dtail; at
&thorn;ai war od, &amp; ane wanti&dtail;.  And he sayd vnto his menya
&thorn;er-of, and &thorn;ai prayed hy&mtail; be in pease &amp; go vnto
his chawmer and &thorn;ai sulde fyn&dtail; it wele agay&ntail; or
&thorn;at he come; and so he di&dtail;.  And whils he was away, his
meneya withdrew a noder bako&ntail;-flyk&ktee;, and so &thorn;er was
evy&ntail; behyn&dtail; as &thorn;er was befo&rtail;.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai calli&dtail; &thorn;er maister &amp; bad
hy&mtail; go luke if he had a&llbar; his bako&ntail;-flikkis, and he
come &amp; tel&dtail; &thorn;aim agay&ntail; as he was wunte to doo,
&amp; fand &thorn;ai wer evy&ntail;.  And so he trowe&dtail; at he had
gette&ntail; his flykkis agay&ntail;, &amp; in a grete myrthe he sayde
vnto his meneya; "O, ye felows!  I mot hafe haldy&ntail; my tong &amp;
loste my baky&ntail;-fly&ktee;."  And whe&ntail; his servandis wolde
eatt any gude meate, &thorn;ai wolde threpe vppo&ntail; hy&mtail; at
he was seke; and he wulde aske &thorn;aim whareby &thorn;ai wyste,
&amp; &thorn;ai wol&dtail; say, "Yis, Sur, for your haris er
passan&dtail; bolny&dtail;."  &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; he wol&dtail; trow
he was seke, &amp; lay hy&mtail; dow&ntail; o&ntail; his bed&dtail;.
And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai wol&dtail; ordan&dtail; gude metis and
gyff hy&mtail; owder little or noght &thorn;eroff, &amp; eate v&ptail;
&thorn;e toder &thorn;er selfe.

</P>
<P>
