</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sitire non habent aliqui ex complexione.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Solinus tellis how &thorn;er er so&mtail; &thorn;at er so grete of
bonys &thorn;at &thorn;ai neuer nowder er thrusti nor swetis; and he
sais he ca&ntail; consayve &thorn;at be many resons.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Sobrietas.  Sobrius debet esse iudex.  Supra de

abstinencia, vij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Societas malorum fugienda est.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Petrus Alphonsus <NOTE ID="P483.N1">MS. Alphunsus.</NOTE> tellis how o&ntail; a tyme
ij clerkis went samen befo&rtail; a place &thorn;er &thorn;a&rtail;
was many drynkers, and &thorn;ai calli&dtail; &thorn;aim in.  And
&thorn;e tone of &thorn;aim went into &thorn;aim, &amp; &thorn;e toder
wol&dtail; nott bod went o&ntail; hys wais; and it was fer with-in
nyght.  So &thorn;e wachis of &thorn;e tow&ntail; fande a&llbar;
&thorn;ies drynkers syttand samen, &amp; &thorn;e clerk with
&thorn;aim, &amp; becauce a ma&ntail; of &thorn;e tow&ntail; was
robbi&dtail; &thorn;at nyght, &thorn;ai tuke &thorn;aim a&llbar; &amp;
&thorn;e clerk with &thorn;aim, &amp; hange&dtail; &thorn;aim.  And
&thorn;e clerke at bade with &thorn;aim, or he was hange&dtail;,
say&dtail; o&ntail; &thorn;is maner of wyse; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Quisquis inique gentis consorcio fruitur, procul dubio
mortis immerite penas lucratur.</FOREIGN> What so&mtail; evur he be at
vsis i&llbar; company, na dowte of he sa&llbar; hafe ane i&llbar;
dea&dtail;."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXXII. 
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Socio fatuo vel malo non est adquiescendum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Libro de Dono Timoris' how o&ntail; a tyme ij brethur
went samen be &thorn;e way, and &thorn;e ton[e] was wyse &amp;
&thorn;e toder bod



<PB N="484">

a fule.  So &thorn;ai come vnto a gate-shaty&llbar; &thorn;er
&thorn;er was ij wa[yis], &thorn;at one a fayr way, &amp; &thorn;at
o&thorn;er a fowle way, and &thorn;e fule wolde not go be &thorn;e
fayre way <NOTE ID="P484.N1">Harl. MS. Voluit fatuus per viam delectabilem ire, sapiens autem dixit, "Et si illa via sit delectabilis, tamen ducit ad malum, alia, vero, licet sit aspera, tamen ad bonum hospitium ducit."</NOTE> .  And &thorn;e wise say&dtail; vnto
hy&mtail;; "&thorn;is way is bothe fayr &amp; gude, &amp; wul&dtail;
lede vs to a gude herbarie."  And &thorn;e toder say&dtail;; "Nay,
&thorn;is way, &thorn;uff a&llbar; it be fowle &amp; sharpe, yit it
w[ill] lede vs vnto a gude herberie; and &thorn;erfo&rtail; I
cownce&llbar; &thorn;e latt vs go here-bye."  So &thorn;is fule wolde
not trow bo&dtail; &thorn;at at he saw, &amp; wol&dtail; algatis go
&thorn;e fayr way, and &thorn;e wise wol&dtail; not lefe hy&mtail; bod
felu&dtail; hy&mtail;, &thorn;uf a&llbar; it wer agayns his wi&llbar;.
So as &thorn;ai w[ent] samen, thevis mett with &thorn;aim, and
&thorn;ai garte put &thorn;aim in priso&ntail;.  And afterwar&dtail;
&thorn;e kyng garte bryng befo&rtail; hy&mtail; a&llbar; &thorn;at wer
in priso&ntail;.  So &thorn;ies ij war broght befor &thorn;e kyng and
fe&llbar; at stryfe befo&rtail; hy&mtail;, ffor &thorn;e wyse made
playnt of &thorn;e fule, how &thorn;at he wolde not truste o&ntail;
hy&mtail; of &thorn;e way, and &thorn;e fule compleny&dtail; of
&thorn;e wyse becauce he folowi&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; wiste he was
bod a fule.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e kyng gaf a sentence &amp;
bat at &thorn;ai bothe sulde be hange&dtail;, &thorn;e fule becauce he
wol&dtail; not trow &thorn;e wyse, &amp; &thorn;e wise becauce he
folow&dtail; &thorn;e fule.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Socij aliquando mutuo se decipiunt.  Supra de

decepcione, iiij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Socius socium aliquando ad negandum deum inducit.

Supra de negacione.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Societatem plurium non expedit sequi.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Legenda Longabordica' of one Richar&dtail;, &thorn;at
was kyng of Freselan&dtail;, whe&ntail; he sulde be crysten&dtail; in
&thorn;e yere of ou&rtail; Lorde ccc, &amp; he had putt &thorn;e tone
fute in to &thorn;e funte <NOTE ID="P484.N2">MS. <HI REND="i">has another</HI> and <HI REND="i">here</HI>.</NOTE> , he helde &thorn;e
toder oute, &amp; say&dtail;; "Wha&rtail; er a&llbar; &thorn;e noble
me&ntail; of my ky&ntail;?  In he&llbar; or in Paradice?"  And one
telli&dtail; hy&mtail; at &thorn;ai wer in he&llbar;.  And whe&ntail;
he har&dtail; &thorn;at, he drew oute his fute of &thorn;e funt
agay&ntail; &





<PB N="485">

say&dtail;; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sanctius est plures quam pauciores
sequi.</FOREIGN> It is more halie to folow many &thorn;a&ntail; few."
And &thorn;us he was deseyvi&dtail; be a fen&dtail; &thorn;at
promysi&dtail; hy&mtail; to gyff hy&mtail; &thorn;at day thrid day ane
vnnumerable porcio&ntail; of gude.  And o&ntail; &thorn;e thrid day he
dyed sodanlie, &amp; was perpetuallie dampny&dtail; for evur.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Solitudo.  Solitudinem multi propter deum

appetunt.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' how on a tyme a solitarie went into
wyldernes, &amp; he was cle&dtail; a&llbar; in a ly&ntail; sak&ktee;
alone.  And whe&ntail; he had walki&dtail; &thorn;erin iij dayes, he
stude v&ptail; apo&ntail; a grete stone, and he was war vndernethe it
of a ma&ntail; fedan&dtail; hy&mtail; of grene herbis as it had bene a
beste.  And he went dow&ntail; privalie &amp; gatt hy&mtail; &amp;
hel&dtail; hy&mtail;, and &thorn;is olde ma&ntail; was naki&dtail;
&amp; myght not suffre &thorn;e odur of a ma&ntail;, and gatt fro
hy&mtail; &amp; ra&ntail; away als faste as he myght.  And &thorn;e
toder ran after hy&mtail; &amp; crye&dtail;; "Abyde, &amp; lat me
speke with &thorn;e!"  So he abade &amp; spak with hy&mtail; <NOTE ID="P485.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, and he abayde.</NOTE> , and whe&ntail; &thorn;ai come nere samen, &thorn;e
olde ma&ntail; bade &amp; aski&dtail; hy&mtail; whatt he wolde.  And
he say&dtail;; "Fadur, I pray &thorn;e, te&llbar; me a wur&dtail; at I
may be savi&dtail; bye!"  And he ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail;
&amp; say&dtail;; "Fle mans felowschup&ptail; &amp; be sti&llbar;,
&amp; &thorn;ou sa&llbar; be safe."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Solitudo quietem anime et consciencie facit.  Supra

de quiete, i.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Solitudinem eligere inspiratur a deo.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' of one Arsenius, &thorn;at was of moste
valow in &thorn;e emperours palas, and he besoght God in his prayers
to drys hy&mtail; into &thorn;e way of hele.  And a voyce come to
hy&mtail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Fle mans felowshu&ptail; &amp; &thorn;ou
sa&llbar; be safe."  And so he di&dtail;. et c&curl;.



<PB N="486">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Solitudinem relinquere suggerit
[diabolus].</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patru&mtail;' how &thorn;er was one &thorn;at
went into wyldernes, and he besoght God to sen&dtail; hy&mtail; a
place &thorn;er he wol&dtail; at he risti&dtail; and abade.  And so
&thorn;er come ane agle, &amp; he folu&dtail; hur, as sho had bene ane
aunge&llbar;, wha&rtail; &thorn;er was a pal&mtail;, &amp; a we&llbar;
at &thorn;e rute &thorn;eroff.  And whe&ntail; he ha&dtail; &thorn;er
many yeris liffi&dtail; in penance, &amp; had none oder mete bod of
&thorn;e frute of &thorn;e pal&mtail; &amp; dryn&ktee; of &thorn;e
we&llbar;, &thorn;e devu&llbar; ha&dtail; envy at hy&mtail;, &amp; he
come vnto hy&mtail; in lyknes of a messanger.  And whe&ntail; he
ha&dtail; beholde&ntail; hy&mtail; grathelie, he say&dtail; vnto
hy&mtail;; "Is not &thorn;is he &thorn;at I hafe soght?  Yis, forsuthe
it is he."  And so he come to hy&mtail; &amp; say&dtail;; "I hafe
soght &thorn;e many day, &amp; I cuthe not fyn&dtail; &thorn;e.  Go we
home, for &thorn;i fadur is dea&dtail; &amp; &thorn;e heritage is
happy&dtail; vnto &thorn;e; and &thorn;er wy&llbar; many folke feght
&thorn;erfo&rtail; bod if &thorn;ou co&mtail; tytter home, and if
&thorn;ou co&mtail; &thorn;ai wu&llbar; sease.  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;ou hase it, &thorn;ou may, and &thorn;ou wi&llbar;, deale it
for Goddis sake."  And he grawnti&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; &amp; come
home vnto his fadur howse, and fan&dtail; hy&mtail; o&ntail; lyfe.
And whe&ntail; he saw &thorn;at he was confusid in hy&mtail; selfe,
and abade &thorn;er in grete trubble and besynes.  And at &thorn;e
laste he dyed &amp; made a wrechi&dtail; en&dtail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Solitarius aliquando in peccatum labitur.  Supra de

presumpcione, j.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Solucio.  Solui debet debitum et promissum.  Supra

de promisso.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sortilegijs non est fides adhibenda.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Libro de Dono Timoris' how &thorn;at a womma&ntail;
&thorn;at vsyd sorcerie happend o&ntail; a tyme to fa&llbar; seke and
was bow&ntail; to dye.  And hur doghter cowncel&dtail; hur to be
schrevy&ntail; &amp; take hur sacramentis, and sho wolde not.  So hur
neghburs come in &amp; cowncel&dtail; hur &thorn;e same, and sho
ansswer&dtail; &thorn;aim agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;;

<PB N="487">
</P>

<P>"I mo&ntail; not dye &thorn;us sone."  And &thorn;ai sayd; "Yis, ye
er lyke to dye."  And sho say&dtail;; "Nay!  I a&mtail; certa&ntail;
at I mo&ntail; liff yit &thorn;is v yere."  And &thorn;ai axki&dtail;
hur how sho knew &thorn;at, and sho ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
sai&dtail; &thorn;at o&ntail; &thorn;e furste day of Maij &thorn;e
goke ansswer&dtail; hur &amp; say&dtail; v tymys, "Cukkow!"  And be
&thorn;at sho sayd sho wiste wele &thorn;at sho sulde liff v yere.
And &thorn;us onone after in &thorn;is belefe, with-owte&ntail; any
sacrament, sho dye&dtail;. et c&curl;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Sortilegium quandoque fit de sacramentis.  Supra

de sacramento, ij 
<NOTE ID="P487.N1">MS. j.</NOTE> .</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sortilegi puniuntur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was in Englond a womman
<NOTE ID="P487.N2">MS. womman&dtail;.</NOTE> &thorn;at vsi&dtail; sorcerie.  And o&ntail; a
day as sho was bow&ntail; to eatt, sho har&dtail; a craw cry beside
hur, and sodanlie &thorn;e knyfe &thorn;at was in hur hande fe&llbar;.
&amp; hereby sho demy&dtail; at hur dea&dtail; drew nere, &amp; so sho
fe&llbar; seke, bow&ntail; to dye.  And sho sent after a mon&ktee;
&amp; a no&ntail; &thorn;at was hur childer, and chargid &thorn;aim in
hur blissyng &thorn;at onone as sho war dea&dtail; &thorn;ai sulde sew
hur in a harte-sky&ntail;, &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; at &thorn;ai sulde
close hur in a tombe of stone, and at &thorn;ai sulde feste &thorn;e
coveryng &thorn;ero&ntail; stronglie bothe with lead &amp; strong
yr&ntail;, &amp; at &thorn;ai sulde close &thorn;is stane &amp; bynde
it aboute with iij strang chynys, and &thorn;a&ntail; at &thorn;ai
sulde do mes &amp; pray for hur aboute hur bodye.  And if sho lay so
sekurlie iij dayes, &thorn;a&ntail; sho chargi&dtail; &thorn;aim to
bery hur vpp[on] &thorn;e iiij day in &thorn;e ert&hbar;.  And so
a&llbar; &thorn;is was done, and ij furste nyghtis, as clerkis was
sayan&dtail; &thorn;er prayers aboute hur, ffendys brak &thorn;e yatis
of &thorn;e kur&ktee;, &amp; come in vnto hur &amp; brak ij of
&thorn;e chynys at was at ather en&dtail;; and &thorn;e myddy&llbar;
chyne abade sty&llbar; hale.  And vppo&ntail; &thorn;e iij nyght
aboute cokkraw, &thorn;er come in suche a throng of fendis, at
&thorn;ai at saw it semy&dtail; at &thorn;e temple turny&dtail;
vpsadow&ntail;.  So &thorn;er come a fen&dtail; at was maste
vgso&mtail; of a&llbar;, &amp; hyer &thorn;a&ntail; any of &thorn;e
toder was, and he come vnto &thorn;is tombe and calli&dtail; hur be
hur





<PB N="488">

name &amp; bad hur ryse.  And sho ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
sayde sho mot not for &thorn;e bondis at was bo&ntail; aboute &thorn;e
tombe.  And he bad lowse &thorn;aim, and onone at his commandment
&thorn;e chyne braste as it had bene hardis, &amp; &thorn;e coueryng
of &thorn;e tombe flow off.  And &thorn;er he tuke hur oppynlie
befo&rtail; a&llbar; me&ntail; &amp; bare hur oute of &thorn;e kurk.
And &thorn;er befo&rtail; &thorn;e yatis &thorn;er was ordan&dtail; a
blak hors, &amp; &thorn;at ane vglie, &amp; here-vppo&ntail; was sho
sett.  &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; onone sho &amp; a&llbar; &thorn;is
felowshu&ptail; vanysshid away.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Spectacula vana vitanda sunt.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Fulgencius tellis how &thorn;at Dyogenes, whe&ntail; he wex olde,
he was fellie vexi&dtail; with &thorn;e fevurs.  So o&ntail; a tyme he
sett hy&mtail; dow&ntail; at a tre-rute in &thorn;e so&ntail; to
comfurt&hbar; hy&mtail;, and whe&ntail; he was gretelie turment with
&thorn;e sekenes, &amp; saw other me&ntail; go vnto disportis &amp;
laykys, he sayd vnto hy&mtail; selfe; "O! how fonde at me&ntail; ar
now on dayes!  Lo! how &thorn;ai faste ry&ntail; to se wonders &amp;
me&ntail; feght, and lukis not after me &thorn;at stryvis with so
fe&llbar; a sekenes as I do."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXXX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sponsalia contrahuntur per anuli
tradicionem.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Guillelmus tellis how som tyme at Rome &thorn;er was a yong
ma&ntail; &thorn;at was new we&dtail;.  So o&ntail; a tyme as he was
playan&dtail; with his felows, he put furt&hbar; his han&dtail; vnto
&thorn;e ymage of Venus, &thorn;at <NOTE ID="P488.N1">MS. &thorn;as.</NOTE> was made of
bras, and delyver&dtail; hur his weddyng-ryng to kepe to &thorn;e play
war done.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e play was done he come &amp;
axki&dtail; his ryng agay&ntail;, &amp; he fan&dtail; it o&ntail;
&thorn;e ymage fynger &amp; &thorn;e fynger cruke&dtail; into &thorn;e
luff of hur hand.  And he wraysti&dtail; at hur fynger and he cuthe
nott gett of &thorn;e ryng nor yit breke hur fynger, so he lete it
alone.  And o&ntail; &thorn;e nyght after he come thedur with his
servan&dtail;, &amp; he fan&dtail; hur fynger streght &amp; &thorn;e
ryng taky&ntail; away.  And he turny&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
feny&dtail; as hy&mtail; ayli&dtail; nott, &amp; went to bed with his
wife; and as he lay in his bed with his wyfe, he fel&dtail; a blak
myrk thyng welter betwix hy&mtail; &amp; his wyfe, and he mot fele it
wele bod he myght noght se itt.  And be &thorn;is obstacle he was lett
fro halsyng



<PB N="489">

of his wyfe.  And he harde a voyce say vnto hy&mtail;; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mecum concube:</FOREIGN> hafe at do with me, for &thorn;is
day &thorn;ou wed me; ffor I a&mtail; Venus at &thorn;ou put &thorn;e
ryng o&ntail; &thorn;e fynger of, and &thorn;at sa&llbar; &thorn;ou
neuer hafe agay&ntail;."  And so it was a long tyme, and evur
whe&ntail; he wol&dtail; hafe ligge&ntail; with his wyfe, he bothe
feli&dtail; &thorn;is in his be&dtail; &amp; har&dtail; &thorn;e voyce
&thorn;eroff.  So o&ntail; a tyme he tuke his lefe at his wife &amp;
his howshol&dtail;, &amp; wol&dtail; walk fer oute of contrey.  So
hy&mtail; happyn&dtail; mete with a nygromansyer &thorn;at hight
Palumbus, and he tuke counce&llbar; at hy&mtail;.  &amp; he wrote
hy&mtail; a lettre and delyverd hy&mtail; it, and bad hy&mtail; bere
it befo&rtail; hy&mtail; in his hand vnto he co&mtail; att &thorn;e
nexte gateshaty&llbar;; and so he di&dtail;.  And agay&ntail;
evy&ntail; he come to a place &thorn;er iiij wayes met samen, &amp;
&thorn;er he saw co&mtail; rydan&dtail; &amp; o&ntail; fute a grete
pepy&llbar; bothe me&ntail; and womme&ntail;, so&mtail; merie and
so&mtail; hevye.  And emang o&thorn;er he saw a womma&ntail; gaylie
arayed like a commo&ntail; womma&ntail;, and hur clothis war so
thy&ntail; at he mot se a&llbar; &thorn;at evur sho ha&dtail;; &amp;
at &thorn;e laste come &thorn;e lor&dtail; of &thorn;is company &amp;
lukid angrelie of &thorn;is yong ma&ntail; &amp; axki&dtail; hy&mtail;
whatt he did &thorn;er.  And he, as it was taght hy&mtail;, wolde gyff
no wurde to ansswe&rtail;, bod put furt&hbar; his hand with &thorn;e
letter &thorn;erin.  And &thorn;is fen&dtail; knew &thorn;e seale of
&thorn;e lettyr &amp; durst not [scorn it] <NOTE ID="P489.N1">Harl. MS. Demon, notum sigillum non audens contempnere, legit scriptum.</NOTE> ,
bod tuke it &amp; red it, &amp; onone he sent a meneya vnto Venus
&amp; tuke &thorn;is ryng fro hur ayayns hur wi&llbar;.  And fro thens
forwar&dtail; &thorn;is yong ma&ntail; come home &amp; &thorn;is ryng
with hy&mtail;, &amp; neuer he was letti&dtail; to lyg with his wyfe
nor nevur har&dtail; uoyce after.

</P>
<P>
