<PB N="490">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXXXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Stephani Prothomartiris.  Stephanus infirmos
sanat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Austy&ntail; tellis how o&ntail; a tyme at Cesaria Capadocie
&thorn;er was a wurthi womma&ntail; &thorn;at had x sonnys.  So on a
day sho was gretelie vexi&dtail; ayayns &thorn;aim, and gaff
&thorn;aim a&llbar; hur malyso&ntail;.  And onone &thorn;e vengeange
of Go&dtail; folowi&dtail; after, for sodanlie &thorn;ai a&llbar; were
streke&ntail; with a palcie, &amp; &thorn;ai waxe&dtail; so pure at
&thorn;ai wavur&dtail; aboute here &amp; &thorn;er.  And evur whar
&thorn;ai went, ilk ma&ntail; behel&dtail; &thorn;aim and wondred
o&ntail; &thorn;aim.  And of &thorn;ies x, ij come vnto Yponeus <NOTE ID="P490.N1">Latin MS. Yponam venientes.</NOTE> , and &thorn;er befo&rtail; ane altar of Saynt
Stephan &thorn;ai war curi&dtail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Stephani corpus coniunctum est corpori Sancti

Laurencij.  Supra de Laurencio, j.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXXXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Studium.  Studere debent libenter
clerici.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Agellius.  Democritus, philosophus, whe&ntail; he was of a moste
happy &amp; riche fortu&ntail;, he went vnto Athenys &amp; lefte
a&llbar; to his frendis, for to by wysdo&mtail;.  And becauce in his
myn&dtail; he sulde desire none thyng at he saw, he garte putt oute
his ee&ntail; at he mott hafe his inward wittis mo&rtail;
whik. &thorn;uff a&llbar; Tertullianus<NOTE ID="P490.N2">MS. Tritullianus.</NOTE>
te&llbar; at he garte putte oute his ene becauce he mot not se no
womma&ntail; withoute&ntail; pere&llbar; of his chastitie, whilk
&thorn;at is not contrarie to our entent.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Studium circa celestia rapit hominem extra se.

Supra Augustini, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXXXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Studendum est amore celestium.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Gregorie tellis &amp; says; "Anthonye &thorn;at dwelte with
me in a monastarie many yeris, and euerilk day made his prayer





<PB N="491">

to God with gretand teris.  So o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; he bethoght
hy&mtail; of halie write, with a grete fervent desyre he soght not in
&thorn;aim wurdis of connyng, bod of compunccio&ntail; &amp; of
wepyng, &thorn;at his mynde be that mot be stirri&dtail; to
contemplacio&ntail; &amp; religio&ntail; of holie lyfe, and not for to
thynk of warldlie thyngys."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Stulticia.  Stulto socio non est adquiescendum.

Supra de societate,  ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Stulticie conueniunt que supra dicuntur de

infirmitate.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXXXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Suffragium.  Suffragia facta a bonis multum
valent.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Legen&dtail; Lombardica,' som tyme a knyght &thorn;at
was dea&dtail; apperi&dtail; vnto a nodir knyght &thorn;at was olife,
and sayd vnto hy&mtail;; "Fren&dtail;, deme none i&llbar; of no
ma&ntail;, and forgyff me if I hafe synny&dtail; oght agayns
&thorn;e."  And whe&ntail; he axke&dtail; hy&mtail; of his asstate, he
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "I a&mtail; turment with
dyvers paynys, bod I pray &thorn;e gar pray for me."  So he
axki&dtail; hy&mtail; if he wol&dtail; at suche a preste &amp; suche a
preste <NOTE ID="P491.N1">Harl. MS. an a tali et tali sacerdote, &amp;c.</NOTE> sulde pray for hy&mtail;.  He wol&dtail;
not ansswer agay&ntail;, in maner as he had refusi&dtail; &thorn;aim,
and he shuke his hea&dtail;.  So he axki&dtail; hy&mtail; if he wolde
at suche ane hermett praye&dtail; for hy&mtail;, and he sai&dtail;;
"Ya, walde God at he wolde pray for me."  And he promysi&dtail;
hy&mtail; at he sulde make hy&mtail; so to do.  And he tolde hy&mtail;
agay&ntail; &thorn;at he sulde liff to &thorn;at day ij yere &amp;
&thorn;a&ntail; he sulde dye; &amp; &thorn;us he dispayred away.  And
&thorn;e knyght amendi&dtail; his lyfe and at &thorn;e laste made a
gude ende.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXXXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Suffragia facta pro defunctis grata sunt
eis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cantor Parisiencis tellis how o&ntail; a tyme as ma&ntail; went
aboute &thorn;e kurk-gart&hbar; sayand alway his De Profundis for
a&llbar; criste&ntail; sawlis, so o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;is mans enmys
sewi&dtail; after hy&mtail; into &thorn;e same



<PB N="492">

kurkgart&hbar;, &amp; he fle&dtail; thedir.  And onone a&llbar;
&thorn;e dead me&ntail; rase, and ilkone of &thorn;aim a spade in his
han&dtail;, and manlelie &thorn;ai defendi&dtail; hy&mtail; and made
his enmys so ferde at &thorn;ai fled ichone.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Suffragium misse spiritualiter mortuis valet.  Supra

de sacerdote.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Suffragium orationis eciam dampnato profuit.

Supra de oratione.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXXXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Suffragia non prosunt dampnatis secundum

legacionem.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a preste &thorn;at
prayed speciallie with grete devocio&ntail; in his mes &amp; his other
prayers for a prince of Almany &thorn;at was dea&dtail;.  And
&thorn;er apperi&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; a certay&ntail; saynt &amp;
say&dtail;; "Whi laburs &thorn;ou so for a ma&ntail; &thorn;at is
dampne&dtail;?  It profettis hy&mtail; no thyng, for his saule is in
&thorn;e depe pitt of he&llbar;."  And &thorn;e preste ansswer&dtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Sur, he hase done me myky&llbar; gude."
And &thorn;e saynt bad hy&mtail; sease &amp; pray no mo&rtail; for
hy&mtail;, for he was deade a yere or he was beri&dtail;, and a wykkid
spirit instead of a sawle nurisshi&dtail; his body.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Suffragia cum elemosina valent.  Supra de

elemosina, x.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Suffragia obligatos pro alijs redemunt.  Supra de

obligacione.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Suffragia penam debitam minuunt.  Supra de

apostatis.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXXXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Superbia.  Superbus nec in vita nec in morte

parem vult habere.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Commestor tellis how whe&ntail; Alexander turny&dtail; agay&ntail;
into Babylo&ntail; &amp; his suster had poysond hy&mtail;, he mot not
speke, &amp; herefor he wrate his testament his aw&ntail; han&dtail;.
And he wol&dtail; not

<PB N="493">

bewitt hys kyngdo&mtail; hale vnto no a ma&ntail;, &thorn;at none of
&thorn;aim at come after hy&mtail; sulde be lyke hy&mtail; in power,
bod he made successurs of his kyngdo&mtail; xij yong me&ntail;
&thorn;at had bene in his felowshu&ptail; fro bar&ntail; little.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXXXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Superbus eciam per humilitatem gloriam appetit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius Publeus <NOTE ID="P493.N1">Arund. MS. Valerius Publi[c]us, consul romanus, plebem adeo dilexit, &amp;c.</NOTE> tellis how som tyme
&thorn;er was a cowncelour of Rome, and he luffi&dtail; the peple so
speciallie, vnto so meku&llbar; at he was calli&dtail; to surname
Plebicola.  And he dwelte in &thorn;e merket-stede, &amp; becauce his
howse was hyer &thorn;a&ntail; neghburs, he garte take &thorn;aim
downe &amp; make &thorn;ai&mtail; evy&ntail; with his neghburs <NOTE ID="P493.N2">Arundel MS. Idem edes suas in medio foro dirui fecit quia nimis excelse super ceteras apparebat, quantumcumque domi inferior tum gloria superior euasit.</NOTE> .


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXXXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Superbia aliquando oritur ex bonis
operibus.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Seuerus tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a saynt &thorn;at
had a grete vertue in castyng oute of ffendis, not alonelie whe&ntail;
he was present, nor in his aw&ntail; wur&dtail; alone, bod somtyme
whe&ntail; he was absent, and somtyme &thorn;urg&hbar; &thorn;e
he&mtail; of his hare, and somtyme be his lettres-sendyng.  &amp; he
wulde heale many folk &thorn;at war seke, and herefo&rtail;
&thorn;urg&hbar; a&llbar; &thorn;e wurl&dtail; &thorn;er come vnto
hy&mtail; meku&llbar; peple.  And as it was say&dtail;, he
absteny&dtail; hy&mtail; bothe fro meat &amp; drynk.
Neuer-&thorn;e-les at &thorn;e laste he cachi&dtail; a pride here-of
in his harte, to so meki&llbar; &thorn;at his vertue fayli&dtail; in
hy&mtail;, and whe&ntail; he saw &thorn;at, he repenti&dtail;
hy&mtail; &amp; besoght God at he mott be made lyke &thorn;aim at he
had cury&dtail;, &amp; at &thorn;e fen&dtail; myght hafe power
o&ntail; hy&mtail; v monethis.  And so it happen&dtail;, &amp; he was
bo&ntail;, &amp; he did many wondres at a&llbar; &thorn;e contrey spak
of hy&mtail;, how he was correcte with a fen&dtail; an&dtail;
bo&ntail; in bandys.  And in &thorn;e v monet&hbar; he was
delyvur&dtail;, not alonelie of &thorn;e fen&dtail;, bod of a&llbar;
o&thorn;er vanyties &thorn;at had behapped hy&mtail;.

</P>
