<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXLIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Te Deum devote cantantibus deuotus ympnus
est.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius [tellis] how &thorn;at in Essex <NOTE ID="P496.N1">Latin MSS. In Saxonia.</NOTE> ,
in a monasterye of nonnys, &thorn;er was a litle damyse&llbar;, and
o&ntail; a grete solempne nyght hur maistres lete hur co&mtail; with
hur to matyns.  So &thorn;e damyse&llbar; was bod a wayke thyng, and
hur maistres was fer&dtail; at sho sulde take colde, and sho
commaundi&dtail; hur befo&rtail; Te Deum to go vnto &thorn;e dortur to
hur bed agay&ntail;.  And at hur commandment sho went furt&hbar; of
&thorn;e where, &thorn;uff a&llbar; it war with i&llbar; wy&llbar;,
and abade withoute &thorn;e where &amp; thoght to here &thorn;e
residue of matyns.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;is song, Te Deum, was
bego&ntail;, sho saw hevy&ntail; oppy&ntail; &amp; a&llbar; &thorn;e
quere of &thorn;e nonnys lifte vp into hevy&ntail;.  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;ai come at &thorn;is place, " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Tibi omnes
angeli,</FOREIGN>" et c&curl;, sho saw a&llbar; &thorn;e ordurs of
angels, and evur-ilk ange&llbar; bow dow&ntail; his hea&dtail; &amp;
knele dow&ntail; o&ntail; his kne &amp; hol&dtail; vp &thorn;er handys
and wurshup God &amp; syng with &thorn;aim att sang, " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sanctus, Sanctus, Sanctus,</FOREIGN>" et c&curl;.  And
&thorn;e same di&dtail; &thorn;e apostels at " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Te
gloriosus,</FOREIGN>" and &thorn;e prophettis at " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Te prophetarum,</FOREIGN>" and &thorn;e martyrs at "
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Te martirum.</FOREIGN>" And afterwer&dtail;
confessurs and virgyns &amp; a&llbar; o&thorn;er di&dtail; &thorn;e
same.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai sang &thorn;e laste vers, " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">In te, Domine, speraui,</FOREIGN>" &thorn;e quere of
&thorn;e susters descendi&dtail; agay&ntail; dow&ntail; vnto &thorn;e
erth, and hevy&ntail; sparryd agay&ntail; after &thorn;aim <NOTE ID="P496.N2"><HI REND="i">A marginal note has</HI>, nota, de Te Deum.</NOTE> .


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXLIV. 
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Tempestas.  Tempestati aliquando admiscentur

demones.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how, in &thorn;e bisshoppryke of Treue&ntail;,
o&ntail; a tyme as a preste &thorn;at hyght Henry satt in &thorn;e
taver&ntail;, &thorn;er happend a stor&mtail; &amp; a tempeste in
&thorn;e ayre, &amp; &thorn;at a grete.  And he &amp; his clerk
ra&ntail; faste into &thorn;e kurk at <NOTE ID="P496.N3">&amp; <HI REND="i">erased, and</HI> at <HI REND="i">added above</HI>.</NOTE> rang
&thorn;e <NOTE ID="P496.N4">MS. <HI REND="i">repeats</HI>, &thorn;e.</NOTE> bellis, and whe&ntail; &thorn;ai come
at









<PB N="497">

&thorn;e kurk-dure, a dynt of &thorn;e thondre smate &thorn;aim bathe
dow&ntail;, so at &thorn;e clerk lay vnder-nethe &thorn;e preste,
&amp; he was nothyng hurte, and a&llbar; &thorn;e preste membrys war
a&llbar; to-swythy&ntail;, and a&llbar; &thorn;e tuder partie of his
bodie vntuchi&dtail;; and he was a ffornycatur.  And his clothis war
so revy&ntail; at neuer a pece of thayme was hale with a noder,
outtake &thorn;at parte o&ntail; his lefte arme &thorn;at his manyple
was wunte to hyng o&ntail;.  And he had o&ntail; a payr of new
buttows, and &thorn;ai wer al to-revy&ntail; as &thorn;ai had bene
revy&ntail; with fless-crokis, and &thorn;e solis war lyke as
&thorn;ai had bene sodde&ntail; in hate watir.  And &thorn;e clerk was
passand fer&dtail; &amp; had grete wonder hereof, and he saw fendis
feghtand in &thorn;e kurk and ij shrynys &thorn;at war behyn&dtail;
&thorn;e hie altar fe&llbar; dow&ntail; o&ntail; the altar &amp; brak.
&amp; &thorn;a&ntail; come &thorn;e saynttis at &thorn;e relykkis of
lay &thorn;erin, &amp; withstude stronglie &thorn;e fendis, and
&thorn;er was betwix &thorn;e saynttis &amp; &thorn;aim a grete
bate&llbar;.  So at &thorn;e laste &thorn;e fendis war
ouercomme&ntail;, &amp; becauce &thorn;ai mot not bere away with
&thorn;aim &thorn;e prestis bodie, &thorn;ai tuke a parte with
&thorn;aim of &thorn;e kurk-rufe.  Also &thorn;e clerk saw &thorn;e
preste bodie oft sithis bor&ntail; vp to &thorn;e steple top&ptail;
with strent&hbar; of fendis; bod thurg&hbar; helpe of &thorn;e
saynttis it was ay broght dow&ntail; agay&ntail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXLV. 
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Temptacio.  Temptaciones demonum sunt
diuerse.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' how Macharius &thorn;e abbott saw
o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;e devy&llbar; go in a mans lyknes.  And he had
o&ntail; a ly&ntail; garment a&llbar; to-revy&ntail; &amp; fu&llbar;
off holis, &amp; it hang fu&llbar; of lity&llbar; pottis.  And
&thorn;is abbot axked hy&mtail; whither he went, and he sai&dtail; he
went to giff his brethir a drynk.  So he axki&dtail; hy&mtail; wharto
he bare so many pottis, and he sai&dtail;; "I bere taste vnto our
brether, so &thorn;at if a pott please not to any of &thorn;aim I
sa&llbar; offer hy&mtail; a noder, or a thrid, &amp; so in ordur to
so&mtail; please hy&mtail;."  And whe&ntail; he come agay&ntail;,
&thorn;is abbot axki&dtail; hy&mtail; how he had done, and he ansswerd
&amp; said; "&THORN;er was none at wulde consente vnto me bod one."
So &thorn;is abbot rase &amp; went vnto his brethir, &amp; he fande
onone &thorn;is bruther at was tempi&dtail;, and with his
exhortacio&ntail; onone he converte hy&mtail; agay&ntail; vnto gude
lyfe.  So onone afterwar&dtail; &thorn;is

<PB N="498">

abbott mett &thorn;e devu&llbar; agay&ntail; &amp; axki&dtail;
hy&mtail; whither he went, and he sai&dtail; he went vnto his brethir.
And whe&ntail; he come agay&ntail; &thorn;is abbot axki&dtail;
hy&mtail; how his brethur di&dtail;.  And he say&dtail;, i&llbar;;
"for," he say&dtail;, "&thorn;ai er a&llbar; halie me&ntail;, &amp;
ane &thorn;at I had emang &thorn;aim, I hafe loste hy&mtail;, for he
is halier &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai a&llbar;, and &thorn;at duse me
meku&llbar; i&llbar;."  And whe&ntail; &thorn;is alde abbott harde
&thorn;is he hel&dtail; vp his handis and thanki&dtail; almightie God.

</P>
<P>
