<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXLVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Temptans caro debet domari.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' how som tyme &thorn;er was a yong
ma&ntail; in ane abbay, and be no contenence nor none other gude werk
he mot not distroy &thorn;e flaw&mtail; of his fless&hbar;.  So
o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; &thorn;is temptacio&ntail; was knowe&ntail;
emangis his brethur, his abbott garte kepe hy&mtail; strayte, and
commandi&dtail; a shar&ptail; angry monke at he sulde flite with
hy&mtail; &amp; bete hy&mtail;, and lat hy&mtail; compley&ntail;
hy&mtail; to whome he wolde.  So o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;e monkis
compleyny&dtail; vnto &thorn;e abbott &amp; sai&dtail; &thorn;is yong
monk had grete wrong.  He began to wepe and was destitute of a&llbar;
helpe; and &thorn;us he was done to a&llbar; a yere.  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;e yere was done, he was axki&dtail; if his i&llbar; thoghtis
wer gone, or if he feli&dtail; oght of &thorn;aim.  And he
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; vnto his abbott &amp; say&dtail;; "Fadur,
how may I thynk of fornycacio&ntail; whe&ntail; I may skantlie liff
for sorow &thorn;at I suffer?"

</P>
<P>
