<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXLIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Temptat virum mulier ultro se ingerens.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Historiis Barlaam' how &thorn;er was a kyng &thorn;at
hight Abennyr, and he had a so&ntail; &thorn;at hight Iosaphatt,
&thorn;at was christend.  And he, purposand to withdraw hy&mtail; fro
&thorn;e purpos of cristendo&mtail; &amp; chastite, he garte spar
hy&mtail; in a chamber be his one, and he garte bryng in to hy&mtail;
fayr yong womme&ntail; and clenlie arayed; and &thorn;ai sat by
hy&mtail; &amp; halsi&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; shewhi&dtail; hy&mtail;
fayr cowntenance



<PB N="501">

&amp; labur&dtail; hy&mtail; to luste &amp; lykyng of his fless&hbar;.
Nor he had no ma&ntail; &thorn;at he mott compley&ntail; hy&mtail; to
nor aske counce&llbar; &thorn;er-of att, nor eate with bod &thorn;ai,
and &thorn;ai war a&llbar; commo&ntail; vnto hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;e
devu&llbar; had grete power in temppyng of hy&mtail;, so &thorn;at he
fe&llbar; vnto luste and lykyng of his bodye.  Not-withstondyng he
vmthoght hy&mtail; of God &amp; bega&ntail; to wepe, &amp;
knokki&dtail; on his breste and besoght God to helpe hy&mtail;.  And
&thorn;us he chasi&dtail; away a&llbar; his i&llbar; thoghtis, and for
a&llbar; at &thorn;ies womme&ntail; cuthe do, his temptacio&ntail;
sesi&dtail; so &thorn;at he fe&llbar; not to sy&ntail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCL.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Temptacio carnis sensum aliquando
alienat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a wurthi womme&ntail;.
So o&ntail; a tyme as sho was be hur one in a caste&llbar; &thorn;at
sho dwelt in, sodanlie scho was inflammy&dtail; with &thorn;e fyre of
luff at sho mot not suffre it.  So sho met with &thorn;e portar &amp;
sho prayed hy&mtail; to co&mtail; vp with hur &amp; ly by hur.  And he
as a gude ma&ntail; ansswer&dtail; hur &amp; sai&dtail;; "Madame, what
is &thorn;at at ye say?  Wha&rtail; is your witt?  Behal&dtail;
Almyghti God &amp; thynk of your aw&ntail; wurshu&ptail;."  And sho
tuke no hede to his saying, bod whe&ntail; he had refusi&dtail; hur,
as God wol&dtail;, sho wente furt&hbar; of &thorn;e caste&llbar; vnto
a grete watir &thorn;at ra&ntail; vnder &thorn;e caste&llbar;, and
&thorn;er sho sett hur vp to &thorn;e shulders in &thorn;e calde
water, &amp; &thorn;er sho satt vnto a&llbar; &thorn;is luste
&thorn;at was in hur was slaki&dtail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; sho come
vp agay&ntail; &amp; thanki&dtail; &thorn;e porter of his
cownce&llbar;, and at he putt hur away fro&mtail; hy&mtail;, &amp;
say&dtail;; "And &thorn;ou had giffe&ntail; me m&lbar; marke of
gol&dtail; it culde nott hafe done me so meku&llbar; gude as &thorn;i
cownce&llbar; di&dtail;."  And with &thorn;at sho went in agay&ntail;
vnwemmy&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Temptacione carnis amota permittit deus aliquos
cadere in deteriorem <NOTE ID="P501.N1">MS. Temptacione carnis ammota permittit deus aliquando studere in deteriorem.</NOTE>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how &thorn;at in Fraunce &thorn;er was a religious
mayde&ntail; &thorn;at was made an anncras.  And be &thorn;e
temptacio&ntail; of &thorn;e devu&llbar; sho was gretelie tempyd with
luste of hur fless&hbar;, and sho prayed hertelie




<PB N="502">

vnto almighti God at sho mot be delyver&dtail; of &thorn;is
temptacio&ntail;.  So in hur prayers o&ntail; a tyme ane ange&llbar;
apperi&dtail; vnto hur and axki&dtail; hur if sho wolde be
delyver&dtail; fro &thorn;is temptacio&ntail;, &amp; sho sai&dtail;
ya, fu&llbar; fay&ntail;.  And he bad hur say with gude wi&llbar;
&thorn;is vers; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Confige timore tuo carnes meas,
et c&curl;,</FOREIGN>" &amp; sho sulde be delyver&dtail;.  And so sho
di&dtail;, and onone &thorn;e temptacio&ntail; left hur.  Bod onone
after sho fe&llbar; into a more perlious temptacio&ntail; of God &amp;
of &thorn;e christe&ntail; fayt&hbar;.  And sho praye&dtail; God
mo&rtail; specialli &thorn;a&ntail; sho did befo&rtail; at sho mot be
delyver&dtail; of &thorn;at temptacio&ntail;.  So o&ntail; a tyme
&thorn;e aunge&llbar; apperi&dtail; vnto hur agay&ntail; &amp;
sai&dtail;; "Suster, how is it with the?"  And sho ansswer&dtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; said; "Nevur wars."  Tha&ntail; &thorn;e ange&llbar;
askid hur if sho trowi&dtail; at sho mott lyff withoute
temptacio&ntail;.  "It is necessarie," he said, "vnto &thorn;e to hafe
&thorn;e tone of &thorn;ies temptacions, and &thorn;erfo&rtail; chese
&thorn;e whethur &thorn;ou wi&llbar; hafe."  And &thorn;a&ntail; sho
sai&dtail;; "I chese me vnto &thorn;e furste, ffor &thorn;uf a&llbar;
it be vnclene, yit it is kyndelie, and &thorn;e toder commys a&llbar;
of the devu&llbar;."  And &thorn;us &thorn;e spirut of blasfeme lefte
hur, and &thorn;e temptacio&ntail; of hur fless&hbar; turnyd
agay&ntail; vnto hur.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Temptacioni carnis conueniuntur multa que dicuntur

supra de luxuria.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Tempus necligere est valde periculosum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Libro de Dono Timoris' how o&ntail; a tyme a holie
ma&ntail;, as he was in his prayers, he har&dtail; a voyce crying
duelfullie in spiritt, &amp; makyng meku&llbar; sorow.  And whe&ntail;
he axkid what it was, it ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sayd it was
dampned and it made myku&llbar; sorow for losyng of tyme, ffor in
&thorn;at mene while, it sai&dtail;, it mot hafe done suche penance
for &thorn;e truspas at it had done at it mot hafe bene delyver&dtail;
fro pay&ntail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Temperancia bona auget elemosinam.  Supra de

elemosina.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Theodori, qui et Theodore.  Supra de paciencia, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Theodosij imperatoris.  Infra de vanitate, j.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>

<PB N="503">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLIII. 
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Testamentum vsurarij in morte factum
valet.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was ane vsurar, &amp; he
was a passan&dtail; riche ma&ntail;.  So hy&mtail; happen&dtail; to
fa&llbar; seke, bow&ntail; to dye.  So he sent after ane holie abbott,
&amp; confessi&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; forthoght his sy&ntail;, &amp;
made his testament in &thorn;is maner of wyse &amp; say&dtail;; "Sur,
and ye wi&llbar; ansswe&rtail; for my saule, I wi&llbar; giff vnto you
a&llbar; &thorn;at evur I hafe at do with, what at you plesis."  And
he graunti&dtail; &thorn;erto &amp; garte hafe a&llbar; his gudis vnto
his abbay, and also &thorn;e ma&ntail; &thorn;at was seke.  And
evy&ntail; as &thorn;ai broght hy&mtail; into &thorn;e abbay he
dye&dtail; and &thorn;is abbott restori&dtail; a&llbar; his vsuries
and gaff grete almos for hy&mtail;, and &thorn;e residue of his gudis
he turny&dtail; into &thorn;e vse of his abbay &amp; his brether.  So
as &thorn;e monkis war in &thorn;er prayers abowte &thorn;e bodie of
&thorn;is ma&ntail;, &thorn;ai war war stondan&dtail; o&ntail; his
lefte syde iiij vglie spyrittis, and whe&ntail; &thorn;ai saw
&thorn;aim &thorn;ai wer so fer&dtail; at &thorn;ai fled, a&llbar; bod
one olde holie monke.  And onone he was war o&ntail; &thorn;e <NOTE ID="P503.N1"><HI REND="i">After</HI> &thorn;e, left, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> right side of &thorn;is ma&ntail;, standan&dtail;,
iiij white aungels enence &thorn;e fendis.  And onone one of &thorn;e
fendis say&dtail;; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Dixit iniustus ut delinquat
in semetipso, non est timor Dei ante oculos eius. </FOREIGN> And
&thorn;is is fulfilli&dtail; in &thorn;is ma&ntail;."  Tha&ntail; a
noder sayd; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Quoniam dolose egit vt inveniatur
iniquitas eius ad odium.</FOREIGN>" And tha&ntail; &thorn;e iij
say&dtail;; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Verba [oris] eius iniquitas et
dolus, noluit intelligere vt bene ageret.</FOREIGN>" And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e iiij said; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iniquitatem
meditatus est in cubili suo, astitit [omni] uie non bone, maliciam
autem non odiuit.</FOREIGN>" And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai say&dtail;
a&llbar; to-gedur; "And God be rightwus &amp; His wurdis trew
&thorn;is ma&ntail; is owrs, for in a&llbar; &thorn;ies is he giltie."
And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e aungels ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
say&dtail;; "Now we sa&llbar; say &thorn;e residue of &thorn;e psalmys
at ye hafe bego&ntail;."  And &thorn;erfor &thorn;e furste ange&llbar;
say&dtail;; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Domine, in celo misericordia tua, et
veritas tua usque ad nubes.</FOREIGN>" Tha&ntail; &thorn;e secund
say&dtail;; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iustitia tua sicut montes Dei,
[iudicia tua] abyssus multa.</FOREIGN>" And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e
iij sai&dtail;; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Homines et iumenta saluabis,
Domine, quemadmodum multiplicasti misericordiam tuam, Deus.</FOREIGN>"
And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e iiij spak &amp; say&dtail;; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Filij autem hominum in tegmine alarum</FOREIGN>



<PB N="504">


<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">tuarum superabunt.</FOREIGN>" And &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;ai a&llbar; crye&dtail; samen &amp; say&dtail;; "&thorn;is
ma&ntail; is owrs, for he fle&dtail; vnto allmyghti Go&dtail; and
&thorn;edur sa&llbar; he go; ffor he trusti&dtail; to be vndernethe
&thorn;e coveryng of His wengis."  And &thorn;us &thorn;e fendis was
confusi&dtail;, and &thorn;us &thorn;e aungels had &thorn;is contryte
saule away with &thorn;aim.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Testamentum facientes frequenter parum legant pro

anima sua.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Libro de Dono Timoris' of ane vsurar, whe&ntail; he
sulde make his testament befo&rtail; &thorn;e preste &amp; many
o&thorn;er &thorn;at was bye, and he bewytt meku&llbar; vnto his
frendis and nothyng ordan&dtail; for his saule, &thorn;e preste spak
vnto hy&mtail; &amp; say&dtail; "Sur, thynk of your sawle."  And he
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Sur, ye say wele, ffor
trewlie I had nerehan&dtail; forgetty&ntail; itt bod now at ye thought
me o&ntail;."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Testatoris anima in purgatorio retinetur executoris

necligencia.  Supra de executore et in diuersis
alijs locis.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Testimonium.  Testes diligenter sunt examinandi.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius telles how a kyng of Fraunce, &thorn;at hight
Philip&ptail; <NOTE ID="P504.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">inserts</HI>, pat, <HI REND="i">here</HI>.</NOTE> , had a baillay at Paryss&hbar;,
&amp; he covett gretelie his neghbur vyneyar&dtail; to by, &amp; he
wolde not se&llbar; hy&mtail; it.  So his neghbur dyed, and &thorn;is
baillay vmthoght hy&mtail; of a fals wyle, and he hyri&dtail; ij
felows o&ntail; a nyght to go to &thorn;is mans grafe &amp; take
hy&mtail; vp.  And he &amp; &thorn;ai went o&ntail; a nyght vnto his
grafe &amp; tuke hy&mtail; oute of &thorn;e ert&hbar;, and putt in his
hand a bagg fu&llbar; of money, als muche as he ha&dtail;
profyr&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;erfo&rtail; whills he liffed, &amp;
made hy&mtail; to take of a seke with his aw&ntail; han&dtail; in
presens of &thorn;ies ij me&ntail;, notwithstondyng he was dea&dtail;,
and he praye&dtail; &thorn;aim bere witnes hereof, and gaff &thorn;aim
a gude rewar&dtail;.  So &thorn;ai layde hy&mtail; in agay&ntail;
&amp; fyllid &thorn;e grafe als wele as



<PB N="505">

it was before, and tuke &thorn;e money with &thorn;aim &amp; went
&thorn;er ways.  And o&ntail; &thorn;e mor&ntail; &thorn;is baillay
entred into &thorn;is vyne-yarde &amp; sai&dtail; it was his, and
&thorn;e wydow had meku&llbar; merve&llbar; here-of [&] sai&dtail;
nay, it was not soo.  And he sai&dtail; yis, he had boght it of hur
husban&dtail; in his lyfe &amp; paye&dtail; hy&mtail; in his
han&dtail; &thorn;erfo&rtail;, and &thorn;at he offre&dtail; hy&mtail;
for to prufe.  So &thorn;is wedow saw sho cuthe not prevale ayeyns
hy&mtail;, and went vnto &thorn;e kyng &amp; made playnt o&ntail;
hy&mtail;.  And &thorn;e kyng commaundi&dtail; &thorn;e cauce to be
examyn&dtail; be me&ntail; of law, bod &thorn;ai examyn&dtail; it not
sufficientlie, to so muche &thorn;e sentans went with &thorn;e baillay
ayayns &thorn;e wedow.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is wedow made more
sorow &thorn;a&ntail; she <NOTE ID="P505.N1">MS. he.</NOTE> di&dtail; afo&rtail;,
and sho come agay&ntail; vnto &thorn;e kyng and made a grete crying
&amp; a besekyng vnto hy&mtail; to helpe hur.  So &thorn;e kyng had
compassio&ntail; o&ntail; hur &amp; calli&dtail; &thorn;e wittnes
befo&rtail; hy&mtail; selfe, &amp; say&dtail; &thorn;at he wol&dtail;
examy&ntail; &thorn;aim.  So he calli&dtail; &thorn;at one oside into
a privay place and bad hy&mtail; say his pater noster, &thorn;at he
mott here it; and so he di&dtail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he garte spar
hy&mtail; in a chambre and calli&dtail; &thorn;e toder, &amp;
sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; sadlie in &thorn;is maner of wyse; "Thi
felow hase telled me a&llbar; &thorn;e trewt&hbar; of &thorn;e
vynegart&hbar; als trew as &thorn;e pater noster.  And trewlie, &amp;
&thorn;ou discor&dtail; fro hy&mtail;, &thorn;ou sa&llbar; be
punysshi&dtail; &thorn;erfo&rtail;, &thorn;at a&llbar; Fraunce
sa&llbar; witt."  So &thorn;is ma&ntail; was fer&dtail; &amp;
trowe&dtail; at &thorn;is felow had telli&dtail; hy&mtail; a&llbar; as
it was, and he fe&llbar; dow&ntail; o&ntail; his kneis befo&rtail;
&thorn;e kyng &amp; say&dtail;; "Lorde, hafe mercie o&ntail; me, for
we wer hyri&dtail; for a certay&ntail; money be &thorn;e baillay,
&amp; &thorn;us we di&dtail; &amp; &thorn;us," and telde hy&mtail;
evurilk-dele as &thorn;ai had done.  An&dtail; &thorn;e kyng was
gretelie grevi&dtail; at &thorn;is baillay &amp; putt hy&mtail; oute
of his offes, and restori&dtail; &thorn;e wedow of hur vyneyar&dtail;
agay&ntail;.  And he garte berie &thorn;e baillay a&llbar; whik for
disclanderyng of &thorn;is deade ma&ntail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Timere loco et tempore sapientis est.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Agellius <NOTE ID="P505.N2">MS. Agellus.</NOTE> tellis how, o&ntail; a tyme,
whe&ntail; a wurthi philosophur was sayland our a grete watyr with
many other, &amp; &thorn;e wawys wex grete aboute &thorn;e shu&ptail;,
&thorn;is philosophur wex pale-hewi&dtail; for ferde.  So onone as
a&llbar; me&ntail; wex sti&llbar;, &thorn;er was a lichurus riche
ma&ntail; in &thorn;e





<PB N="506">

shu&ptail;, &amp; he scorny&dtail; &thorn;is philosophur and blamyd
hy&mtail; for he was fer&dtail;, notwithstondyng he was ferde
hy&mtail; selfe.  And &thorn;is philosophur ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail;
agay&ntail;, &amp; sai&dtail; he was not fer&dtail; for his lichorus
bodie nor for his saule, bod for hy&mtail; selfe, &amp;
&thorn;erfo&rtail; no merve&llbar; if he wexi&dtail; pale.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Timeri semper debet iudicium vltimum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' how, o&ntail; a tyme, &thorn;er was a
monke &thorn;at axkid his abbott &amp; prayed hy&mtail; te&llbar;
hy&mtail; a wurde at he mot thynke o&ntail;.  And he bad hy&mtail; go
&amp; vmthynk hy&mtail; alway, "as a thefe duse in preso&ntail;
&thorn;at evur spirris whar &thorn;e iustis is and whe&ntail; &thorn;e
sessio&ntail; sa&llbar; be, and evur is in sorow &amp; mornyng for
fer&dtail; of hangyng; so sulde &thorn;ou &amp; evur-ilk ma&ntail;
thynk how &thorn;ou mo&ntail; co&mtail; befo&rtail; &thorn;e grete
iugement of Almyghtie God, and &thorn;er giff rekynyng of a&llbar;
&thorn;i dedis.  And if &thorn;ou thynk a&llbar;-way o&ntail;
&thorn;is maner of wyse, no dowte of &thorn;ou mo&ntail; be
savi&dtail;."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Timent eciam perfecti iudicium.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vitis Patrum' when abbot Agatho&ntail; was bow&ntail;
to dye, he lay iij dayes, &amp; his ee&ntail; oppy&ntail;, &amp;
stirri&dtail; nott and his brethur calli&dtail; nevur so faste
o&ntail; hy&mtail;.  So at &thorn;e laste he movi&dtail;, &amp;
&thorn;ai spak&ktee; vnto hy&mtail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "Abbay!
wha&rtail; erte &thorn;ou?"  And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
say&dtail;; "In &thorn;e covent of a&llbar; me&ntail;, and I mo&ntail;
to my iugement."  And &thorn;ai comfurthi&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp;
axki&dtail; hy&mtail; wharfo&rtail; he was fer&dtail;, and he
ansswer&dtail; agey&ntail; &amp; say&dtail; "With a&llbar; &thorn;e
strent&hbar; at I had I labur&dtail; to kepe &thorn;e commaundmentis
of God, and I a&mtail; bod a ma&ntail; and yit I wate nevur &thorn;uff
my werkis hafe plesi&dtail; God or nay, ffor &thorn;e iugement of
Almi&yogh;ty God is oderwas &thorn;a&ntail; is &thorn;e iugement of
ma&ntail;.  And &thorn;erfo&rtail; I hafe none o&thorn;er truste bod
at I mo&ntail; come to my iugement before &thorn;e hye seatt of
A&llbar;myghtie God."
</P>
<P>
<LIST><ITEM><FOREIGN>Timere debet peccator vbique quia deus vbique videt.

Supra de deo et abbate.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>

<PB N="507">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Timere debent viri boni purgatorium.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Libro de Dono Timoris' how o&ntail; a tyme as a
certay&ntail; meneya of religious me&ntail; spak samen of purgatorie
&amp; was passan&dtail; fer&dtail; &thorn;erfo&rtail;, &thorn;er was
emangis &thorn;aim a lay ma&ntail;, &amp; he say&dtail; "It is a grete
merve&llbar; of you, sen ye or so gude me&ntail; &amp; of so grete
penans, &thorn;at ye hafe so grete drede.  Sekurlie and secular
me&ntail; &thorn;at duse so meku&llbar; i&llbar; &amp; duse so little
penans &thorn;erfor knew it, &thorn;ai wulde fa&llbar; in a dispayr."
And &thorn;a&ntail; ane of &thorn;aim tolde hy&mtail; ane exsample of
a blyn&dtail; ma&ntail;, as is telli&dtail; befo&rtail; of &thorn;e
blyn&dtail; ma&ntail;.  Also we rede of a preste &thorn;at was
holde&ntail; a holie ma&ntail;, &thorn;at in his lyfe did grete
penance.  And vnto one &thorn;at axki&dtail; hy&mtail; whi he
di&dtail; so, he ansswer&dtail; &amp; sai&dtail; &thorn;us; "And a
&thorn;is tow&ntail; were fu&llbar; of fyre, me had levur be
&thorn;erin vnto &thorn;e day of dome &thorn;a&ntail; for to be in
purgatorie or in he&llbar; a day."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Timere casum in peccatum omnes debent.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Libro de Dono Timoris' how som tyme &thorn;er was a
gude ma&ntail; &thorn;at fe&llbar; to sy&ntail;, and a noder gude
ma&ntail; whe&ntail; he harde te&llbar; &thorn;eroff had grete sorow
&thorn;erfo&rtail; &amp; sayd vnto hy&mtail;; <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">"Ille heri et ego hodie."  Et supra de carne temptacione et
in pluribus alijs locis diuersis.</FOREIGN>

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Timore mundano debent aliqui amittere res

temporales.  Supra de contemptu mundi et de

diuicijs et infra de vsurario 
<NOTE ID="P507.N1">MS. vsura.</NOTE> .</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Timore humano timetur mors uel pena corporalis.

Supra de martirio, de morte, de penitencia et

hic de timore.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Timore servili faciunt aliqui aliqua de genere

bonorum.  Supra de contricione.

</FOREIGN>

<PB N="508">
</ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Timore speciali timent sancti ne opera sua deo

placeant.  Supra eodem, iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Titus.  Supra de prelato, vj, et de fame.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Thome Martiris Cantuariensis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in his 'Legent' how &thorn;er was in his dioces a preste
&thorn;at daylie sang mes of our Ladie, and he was accusi&dtail; vnto
&thorn;e archbissho&ptail;, Saynt Thomas, and he suspend hy&mtail; as
ane ydiott &amp; a man &thorn;at cuthe no gude.  So o&ntail; a tyme
whe&ntail; Saynt Thomas sulde sew his hayre, &amp; hid it vndernethe
his bed to wache ane howr &thorn;at he mot sew it in, our Ladie
apperi&dtail; vnto &thorn;is preste and bad hy&mtail; go vnto &thorn;e
archbissho&ptail;, "&thorn;at sho, for whase luff &thorn;ou <NOTE ID="P508.N1">MS. &thorn;us.</NOTE> was wunte say &thorn;i mes, hase sewi&dtail; his
hayre &thorn;at lyes in suche a place," &amp; tel&dtail; hy&mtail;
&thorn;er sho lefte itt," and say &thorn;at sho byddis hy&mtail;
relese &thorn;e suspensio&ntail; &thorn;at he hase putt ayenys the."
And he went &amp; tolde hy&mtail;, and whe&ntail; he harde it &amp;
fand it was as he say&dtail;, he <NOTE ID="P508.N2"><HI REND="i">After</HI> he, had, <HI REND="i">erased</HI>.</NOTE> relesi&dtail;
his suspensio&ntail; &amp; bad hy&mtail; say mes sty&llbar; of our
Ladie, &amp; bad him <NOTE ID="P508.N3">MS. his</NOTE> kepe it privay ewhils he
liffi&dtail; &amp; discure hy&mtail; noght.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Thomam Martirem honorant angeli.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in his 'Legen&dtail;' &thorn;at whe&ntail; he was
slay&ntail;, &amp; &thorn;e covent of Cantyrberie bega&ntail; for
hy&mtail; &thorn;e mes of Requiem, sodanlie a company of aungels was
&thorn;er, &amp; with a hy voyce abow&ntail; a&llbar; &thorn;e quere
&thorn;ai bega&ntail; to syng mes, &amp; sai&dtail;; " <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Letabitur iustus in Domino.</FOREIGN>" And onone as
&thorn;e monkis har&dtail; &thorn;aim, &thorn;ai felowi&dtail; and
sang as &thorn;ai di&dtail; &thorn;e mes furt&hbar;, as &thorn;ai
di&dtail;, of a martyr.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Thomam orans avis exaudita est.  Supra de ave, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Tonitruum.  Supra de tempestate.

</FOREIGN>
<PB N="509">
</ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Torneamentum vicit miles absens.  Supra de Maria.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Tribulacio.  Tribulatos deus multipliciter consolatur.

Supra de infirmitate, de consolacione et in alijs

pluribus locis.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
