et de accidia, j.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Turba est fugienda.  Supra de solitudine, j, ij et iij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vanitas semper est fugienda.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede ex 'Dictis Patrum' how som tyme &thorn;er was a monk at
Constantynople, &amp; dwelte &thorn;er in &thorn;e tyme of Theodoce
&thorn;e emperour in a liti&llbar; ce&llbar; with-oute &thorn;e cetie.
And &thorn;e emperour harde te&llbar; o&ntail; hy&mtail; &amp; went
vnto hy&mtail; be his one at speke with hy&mtail;; &amp; whe&ntail; he
come vnto hy&mtail; he knew not at it was &thorn;e emperour, &amp;
&thorn;is monke hasti&dtail; hy&mtail; &amp; put water in a
vesse&llbar;, &amp; tuke salte &amp; a morce&llbar; of brede &amp;
servi&dtail; hy&mtail; &thorn;er-off &amp; &thorn;ai ete to-gedur.
And &thorn;a&ntail; he say&dtail;; "I am Theodos &thorn;e emperour,
&amp; of devocio&ntail; I come hydur.  Ye er blissi&dtail; &thorn;at
er so sekur &amp; so fre of your necessities in &thorn;is werl&dtail;,
&amp; ye hafe a ristfu&llbar; &amp; a quiett lyffe forby &thorn;at I
hafe; ffor suthelie &amp; was blissidlie bor&ntail; in my real&mtail;,
and now I liff &thorn;erin &amp; I neuer eatt nor dryn&ktee;
with-oute&ntail; besynes."  And with &thorn;at he tuke his lefe att
hy&mtail; and went his ways.  So whe&ntail; he was gone, the same
nyght &thorn;is monke compasi&dtail; in his myn&dtail; &amp;
sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail; selfe; "Not alonlie many of &thorn;e peple,
bod also many of &thorn;e emperour pales, folowyng &thorn;e exsample
of &thorn;e emperour, wi&llbar; now co&mtail; for to se me &amp; do me
wurshu&ptail; as &thorn;e servan&dtail; of Go&dtail;.  And herof I
suppoce &thorn;ai wu&llbar; not sease.  And I am fer&dtail; leste
&thorn;e fen&dtail; vndergo me &amp; make me gladlie to ressayfe
&thorn;aim, &amp; at my harte take a comfu[r]t&hbar; be &thorn;er
lovyng &amp; be &thorn;er wurshu&ptail;, and be &thorn;at at I sulde
begy&ntail; to lose &thorn;e vertue of my mekenes."  And whe&ntail; he
had &thorn;us consydur&dtail; in hy&mtail; selfe, &thorn;e same night
he went into wyldernes in Egypte, and dwelte &thorn;er a&llbar; his
lyfe-tyme after with holie fadurs, oute of syght.

<PB N="510">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXIV. 
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vanitatem sancti per humilitatem fugiunt.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede also in 'Gestis Patrum' how o&ntail; a tyme a iustice of a
lande come for to se ane abbott, and whe&ntail; he har&dtail;
te&llbar; at he come <NOTE ID="P510.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">adds</HI>, and, <HI REND="i">here</HI>.</NOTE> , he garte clothe
hy&mtail; in sak-clothe and tuke in his hand brea&dtail; &amp; chese,
&amp; sett hy&mtail; in his ce&llbar;-dure.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e
iustis saw hy&mtail; he dispysi&dtail; hy&mtail; and say&dtail;; "Is
not &thorn;is &thorn;e ma&ntail; at we hafe har&dtail; so meku&llbar;
te&llbar; off?"  &amp; with &thorn;at he went his way &amp; wolde byde
no longer.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Vana gloria appetitur aliquando ex bonis operibus.

Supra de elemosina et de abstinencia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Vanitas punitur in purgatorio.  Supra de ave, i.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Vaspasianus.  Supra de prelato.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Vanitati possunt adaptari multa que dicuntur

supra de laude, gloria, et memoria.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Verbum.  Verbo non est semper adherendum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede how som tyme a ma&ntail; had ane ass, &amp; he rade hur,
&amp; a little so&ntail; that he had folowi&dtail; hy&mtail; on fute.
And &thorn;er was me&ntail; at mett &thorn;aim, emang &thorn;e whilk
so&mtail; sai&dtail;; "O, how fon&dtail; &thorn;is alde carle is,
&thorn;at rydis hy&mtail; selfe &amp; lattis hys so&ntail; ry&ntail;
in &thorn;e myre," &amp; whe&ntail; &thorn;ai war passi&dtail;
&thorn;ai lepi&dtail; o&ntail; bothe.  Tha&ntail; &thorn;ai mett a
noder meneyay, &amp; &thorn;ai say&dtail;, "Forsut&hbar;, &thorn;ies
er bo&dtail; fulis, for &thorn;ai wi&llbar; sla &thorn;is ass."  And
whe&ntail; &thorn;ai war passi&dtail;, he and his son light &amp; lete
&thorn;e ass go tome.  So &thorn;ai met a noder meneya, &amp;
&thorn;ai sayd; "&thorn;ies meneya er fonde, for &thorn;ai go bothe
o&ntail; &thorn;er fete, and &thorn;at one of &thorn;aim mot ryde."
&thorn;a&ntail; he sett his so&ntail; o&ntail; &amp; went o&ntail; his
fete hy&mtail; [self].  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ai mett a noder
meneya &thorn;at say&dtail;; "Loo!  Yone fonde alde carle, he gois
o&ntail; his fete hy&mtail; selfe &amp; lattys his so&ntail; ryde,
&thorn;at mott bettyr go &thorn;a&ntail; he may."  And &thorn;a&ntail;



<PB N="511">

he &amp; his so&ntail; tuke vp &thorn;is ass &amp; bare hur.  &amp;
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;er mett &thorn;aim a noder meneya and &thorn;ai
sai&dtail;: "Lo, &thorn;ies fulies!  How &thorn;ai bere &thorn;is ass
&thorn;at sulde bere &thorn;aim!"  Tha&ntail; he sett dow&ntail;
&thorn;e ass &amp; say&dtail; vnto his so&ntail;; "Loo!, so&ntail;
here may &thorn;ou se how &thorn;at evur we doo, alway me&ntail;
wi&llbar; fawte vs &amp; speke of vs.  And &thorn;erfo&rtail; it is
not gretelie to charge of wurdis-spekyng and a ma&ntail; do wele."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Verba aliquando inducunt ad credendum quod

non est.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iacobus de Vetriaco tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a pure
ma&ntail; &thorn;at bare vnto &thorn;e markett att se&llbar; a lambe.
So &thorn;er was in &thorn;e markett a iaper &thorn;at saw he was bod
ane innocent, &amp; he sai&dtail; vnto his felows; "Doo as I sa&llbar;
te&llbar; you, &amp; we sa&llbar; hafe &thorn;is lambe fro&mtail; yone
felow."  And he made &thorn;aim stan&dtail; in dyvers placis in sonder
in &thorn;e same way, ilkone after o&thorn;er.  And as &thorn;is
ma&ntail; went by &thorn;aim &thorn;e furst say&dtail; vnto &thorn;is
ma&ntail;; "Ma&ntail;, wi&llbar; &thorn;ou se&llbar; &thorn;at hunde?"
And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Skor&ntail; me
nott, for it is no hunde, it is a lambe."  So he come vnto &thorn;e
secun&dtail;, &amp; he axki&dtail; hy&mtail; hif he wol&dtail;
se&llbar; hy&mtail; &thorn;at hund for a peny.  And he was wrothe
&thorn;er-with, &amp; sai&dtail;; "Ye doo bod skor&ntail; me."  So he
come vnto the thri&dtail;, and he sai&dtail; in &thorn;e same wise.
So &thorn;is ma&ntail; had grete merve&llbar; hereoff &amp; waxed
shamefu&llbar;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he come to &thorn;e iiij &amp;
&thorn;e v, &amp; &thorn;ai spirri&dtail; hy&mtail; in &thorn;e same
wyse.  So &thorn;is felow bega&ntail; to vmbethynk hy&mtail; what
&thorn;is sulde mene, at so many me&ntail; sulde spyr hy&mtail; of
&thorn;is lambe if it war a dogg, &amp; a&llbar; acordi&dtail; in one
&thorn;at it sulde be a dogg &amp; no lambe.  So at &thorn;e laste he
agrei&dtail; vnto &thorn;er oppynyons &amp; say&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;
selfe; "God knowis &thorn;at I trowi&dtail; it had bene a lambe, bod
becauce it is a dogg I wi&llbar; bere it no ferther."  And with
&thorn;at he keste it fro&mtail; hy&mtail; &amp; sai&dtail; he wulde
bere it no langer.  And whe&ntail; he had caste&ntail; it fro&mtail;
hy&mtail; he went his way, and &thorn;is iaper &amp; his felows tuke
v&ptail; &thorn;is lambe &amp; ete itt.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Verba ociosa non sunt credenda.  Supra de ocio, ij.</FOREIGN>

<PB N="512">
</ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Verum semper dicere non semper expedit.  Supra

de adulacione, j.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Veritas non est celanda in necessitate.  Supra de

testimonio.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Veritati possunt adaptari multa que dicuntur

supra de falsitate et mendacio.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vestes preciose contempnende sunt a
sanctis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Vita Iohannis Elemosinarij' how o&ntail; a tyme
&thorn;er was a riche ma&ntail; &thorn;at saw hy&mtail;, &amp; he was
bothe a bisshop&ptail; &amp; a patriarke, at he was bod in a pure
clothyng &amp; a vile, of xxxvj &dtail; price he boght a garment and
gaff it vnto &thorn;is patriarke.  And &thorn;is Ioh&ntail;, seyng
&thorn;e devocio&ntail; of &thorn;is ma&ntail;, tuke it.  Bod a&llbar;
&thorn;at nyght he lay wakan&dtail; &amp; sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;
selfe; "Who sa&llbar; say &thorn;at meke Ioh&ntail; is cle&dtail; with
a garment of xxxvj &dtail; price, and &thorn;e brethur of Cryst er
slay&ntail; for calde? &thorn;ou meke Ioh&ntail;!" he sai&dtail;, "It
sa&llbar; not cover &thorn;e a noder nyght, ffor it is rightwus at
&thorn;e brethur of our Lor&dtail; be cled &thorn;erwith mo&rtail;
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ou, vnhappy creatur!"  And o&ntail; &thorn;e
mor&ntail; he sent it into &thorn;e tow&ntail; for to se&llbar;, and
he &thorn;at gaff hy&mtail; it boght it, and offer&dtail; it vnto
hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; praye&dtail; hy&mtail; were itt.  And he
tuke it &amp; evur selli&dtail; it, &amp; &thorn;e price ay &thorn;at
he tuke &thorn;erfo&rtail; he gaff it wnto pure folk.  And evur
&thorn;is ma&ntail; boght it agay&ntail; &amp; gaff hy&mtail; itt.  So
at &thorn;e laste &thorn;is holie ma&ntail; thanky&dtail; hy&mtail;
&amp; sayde; "We sa&llbar; se who sa&llbar; defayle, I or &thorn;ou."
And &thorn;is ma&ntail; was evur ryche enog&hbar; als lang as he
barkan&dtail; with &thorn;is holie ma&ntail;, &amp; evur &thorn;is
holie ma&ntail; gaf &thorn;e price &thorn;at he sent hy&mtail;
&thorn;erfo&rtail; vnto pure men.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Vestes preciose eleuant hominem in superbiam.

Supra de augurio.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Via melior est tenenda.  Supra de socio, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Victoriam semper debent appetere pugnantes.

Supra de bello, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>

<PB N="513">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vigilare debent in orationibus religiosi.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in &thorn;e 'Lyfe of Saynt Arsenius <NOTE ID="P513.N1">MS. Arseme.</NOTE>
,' &thorn;at whe&ntail; he saw &thorn;e so&ntail; ryse he wolde
tur&ntail; his bak &thorn;ero&ntail;, &amp; lifte vp handis &amp; his
harte vnto hevy&ntail; to Almyghty God, &amp; say his prayers.  &amp;
so he wolde sytt a&llbar; day to &thorn;e so&ntail; shane o&ntail; his
face agay&ntail;, and &thorn;a&ntail; he wulde tur&ntail; hy&mtail;
&amp; sitt in his prayers a&llbar; nyght.  And agayns mor&ntail;,
whe&ntail; he wexi&dtail; werie &amp; his natur wolde ruste, he wolde
say vnto slepe; "Co&mtail;, servan&dtail;, &amp; serif me."  and
evy&ntail; sittan&dtail; he walde spar his ee&ntail; &amp; slepe a
while, and onone he wulde wake agay&ntail; &amp; go vnto his prayers.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Vigiliam quandoque inducit temptacio demonis per

sompni subtraccionem.  Supra de abstinencia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Vindicta.  Vindicant se aliqui crudeliter 
<NOTE ID="P513.N2"><HI REND="i">The tale from Valerius to follow this heading is missing in the</HI> English MS.</NOTE> .</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vindicans se ante mortem celeriter moritur 
<NOTE ID="P513.N3"><HI REND="i">Heading supplied from</HI> Harl. MS. <HI REND="i">with</HI> celeriter <HI REND="i">for</HI> celerabilius.</NOTE> .</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in &thorn;e 'Storie of Alexander,' how &thorn;at
whe&ntail; Pausanias had wowndi&dtail; Phili&ptail;, &thorn;at was
Alexander fadur, &thorn;at hy&mtail; burde nedis dye, Alexander gatt
&thorn;is Pawsanias &amp; broght hy&mtail; vnto Phili&ptail;; and he
put a swer&dtail; in his fadur right hand and helpy&dtail; hy&mtail;
with his han&dtail; &amp; slew hy&mtail;.  And whe&ntail; he
dye&dtail; &thorn;is Philip&ptail; say&dtail;; "Now &thorn;e end of my
lyfe, nor my dea&dtail;, nor none o&thorn;er thyng may hevy me ewhuls
I hafe slay&ntail; hy&mtail; &thorn;at hase slay&ntail; me.  And,
Alexander, I hafe myn&dtail; of ow&rtail; go&dtail;, how he sai&dtail;
vnto &thorn;i moder at sho sulde bere &thorn;e so&ntail; of
vengeange."  And with &thorn;at he leny&dtail; hy&mtail; dow&ntail;
and swelte.









<PB N="514">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vindicant se aliqui subtiliter.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Petrus Alphonsis <NOTE ID="P514.N1">MS. Alphensis, for Alphonsus.</NOTE> tellis how so&mtail; tyme
&thorn;er was a kyng &thorn;at had a wardrop[er] &thorn;at was
maister-shaper of his clothyng; and he had many servandis vnder-nethe
hy&mtail; of &thorn;e whilk ane was calli&dtail; Nediu.  And &thorn;ai
sewi&dtail; &amp; war at bur&dtail; in a mans howse <NOTE ID="P514.N2">Arund. MS. in domo eunuchi regis.</NOTE> &thorn;at hight Eunuchus.  So o&ntail; a day
&thorn;ai went to dyner, &amp; &thorn;is Nediu was not &thorn;er,
&amp; &thorn;ai ete hony &amp; drank wyne, &amp; had many o&thorn;er
gude metis sent vnto &thorn;aim fro &thorn;e kyng.  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;ai war att dyner &amp; ete, &thorn;is Eunuchus axki&dtail;
&thorn;aim whi &thorn;ai abade not Nediu, and &thorn;er maister
ansswer&dtail; &amp; sai&dtail; at he wulde ete no hony and he war
&thorn;er.  So at &thorn;e laste &thorn;is Nediu come &amp; fan&dtail;
&thorn;aim at dyner, &amp; say&dtail;; "Whi bade ye noght for me?"
And Eunuchus tolde hy&mtail; how &thorn;at his maister say&dtail; he
wolde eate no hony, &amp; he hel&dtail; his tong &amp; say&dtail;
noght.  Notwithstondyng he bega&ntail; to vmthynk hy&mtail; how he mot
be vengi&dtail;.  So o&ntail; a tyme he sayde vnto &thorn;is Eunuchus,
"Bewar, ye &amp; your howshol&dtail;, of my maister at he do you no
har&mtail;, for som tyme he wi&llbar; wax fon&dtail; &amp; is evyn
bray&ntail;-wude."  And &thorn;is Eunuchus ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail;
&amp; sai&dtail;; "And I knew &thorn;e how&rtail; whe&ntail; it
happen&dtail; hy&mtail; I sulde byn&dtail; hy&mtail;."  And &thorn;is
Nediu say&dtail;; "Whe&ntail; &thorn;ou seis hy&mtail; luke
hedurwar&dtail; &amp; &thorn;edurwar&dtail; &amp; opo&ntail; &thorn;e
erde, &amp; rap abowte hy&mtail; with his handis and ryse oute of his
seate &amp; remow his stule, &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ou sa&llbar;
vnderstan&dtail; &thorn;at he is wude."  So within a while after
&thorn;is Nediu o&ntail; a tyme hi&dtail; his maister sheris, and he
myssyd &thorn;aim &amp; bega&ntail; to caste &thorn;e stra
hedurwar&dtail; &amp; &thorn;edurwar&dtail; &amp; luke aboute
hy&mtail; &amp; rap o&ntail; &thorn;e bur&dtail; with his nefe, &amp;
ryse &amp; remofe &thorn;e stule at he satt o&ntail;.  And whe&ntail;
Eunuchus saw &thorn;is, he calli&dtail; faste o&ntail; his servandis
&amp; onone &thorn;ai tuke hy&mtail; &amp; ban&dtail; hy&mtail; faste.
And evur he crye&dtail;; "Whi do ye so?  What hafe I done?"  And evur
&thorn;ai ban&dtail; hy&mtail; strayter, and bete hy&mtail; to he was
nerehan&dtail; dea&dtail;.  So at &thorn;e laste he come vnto
hy&mtail; selfe & <NOTE ID="P514.N3">&amp; <HI REND="i">omitted and added above the line.</HI></NOTE> &thorn;ai lowsi&dtail;
hy&mtail;, and he axki&dtail; &thorn;aim whi &thorn;ai di&dtail; so.
And Eunuchus tolde hy&mtail; how &thorn;at Nediu say&dtail; at he was
wude.  And &thorn;a&ntail; his maister say&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;;









<PB N="515">

"Whe&ntail; saw &thorn;ou me be wude?"  And Nediu ansswer&dtail;
hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "&thorn;ou was wude, maister,
whe&ntail; &thorn;ou sai&dtail; at &thorn;ou saw me nevur eat honye."
And whe&ntail; &thorn;ai &thorn;at was abowte hy&mtail; harde
&thorn;is, &thorn;ai demy&dtail; at he had rightwuslie vengi&dtail;
hy&mtail;, &amp; so he satt with his aw&ntail; skathe.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Vindicant se aliquando creature 
<NOTE ID="P515.N1">ir-<HI REND="i">omitted and added above the line</HI>.</NOTE>  irracionales.  Supra

de bufone.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vindicare se nolunt sancti.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in &thorn;e 'Legend of Saynt Macharie,' how o&ntail; a
tyme as he cut hys han&dtail; with his knyfe, &amp; it bled a grete
dele becauce he brak &thorn;e knyfe, &amp; whe&ntail; he had done he
reprovi&dtail; hy&mtail; selfe becauce he di&dtail; wrong <NOTE ID="P515.N2">Harl. MS. Dum sanctus Macharius pulicem se pungentem manu occidisset et multum sanguinis ex illo emanasset, reprehendens se ipsum quod propriam vindicasset iniuriam, &amp;c.  Arund.  MS. Dum sanctus Macharius calicem, &amp;c.</NOTE> , &amp; went naki&dtail; into wyldernes &amp; was
&thorn;er vj monethis.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he come home a&llbar;
tobitty&ntail; and skratty&dtail; with thornys and breers.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXXII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vindicat se deus aliquando per mortuos.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in &thorn;e 'Historie of Saynt Basy&llbar;,' o&ntail; a
tyme whe&ntail; Iulianus Apostata wente to procede agay&ntail;
&thorn;e Persas, he bosti&dtail; Basi&llbar; &thorn;at <NOTE ID="P515.N3">Latin MSS. quod in reditu Cesariam Capadocie destrueret.</NOTE> as he come agaynwar&dtail; to Capado[ce] he sulde
destroy a&llbar; Cesarie.  And o&ntail; &thorn;e nyght folowyng,
&thorn;is Basi&llbar; saw in &thorn;e kurk of our Ladie a multitude of
angels, and in myddest of &thorn;aim a womma&ntail; standan&dtail;,
and sai&dtail; vnto &thorn;aim abowte hur; "Ca&llbar; vnto me
Mercurius &thorn;at sa&llbar; sla Iulianus Apostata, &thorn;at
blasfemys bothe me and my So&ntail;."  And &thorn;is Mercurius was a
certay&ntail; knyght &thorn;at &thorn;is same Iulianus had slay&ntail;
for &thorn;e fayt&hbar; of Cryste, and was beri&dtail; in &thorn;e
same kurk.  And onone &thorn;is Mercurius was redie in his armur, and
sho sent hy&mtail; into &thorn;e bate&llbar;.  And onone &thorn;is
Basy&llbar;










<PB N="516">

went to &thorn;er he was gravy&ntail; &amp; opyn&dtail; his grafe,
&amp; he fan&dtail; nowder his bodie nor his armur &thorn;at was
beri&dtail; with hy&mtail;, &amp; &thorn;a&ntail; he axki&dtail;
&thorn;e keper of &thorn;e kur&ktee; who bare away &thorn;is armur,
and he sware grete athis at it was &thorn;er &thorn;at same nyght.  So
&thorn;is Basilius went thens ty&llbar; o&ntail; &thorn;e mor&ntail;,
and &thorn;a&ntail; he come agay&ntail; &amp; fand bothe his bodie and
his armur, and his spere bludye to &thorn;e myddyste.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;er come ane &amp; say&dtail;; "Whe&ntail;
Iulianus Apostata was araye&dtail; in &thorn;e bate&llbar;, &thorn;er
come ane vnknowy&ntail; knyght army&dtail; &amp; a spere in his
han&dtail;, apo&ntail; a hors, and he smate &thorn;e hors with
&thorn;e spurris and with a bolde spyritt he rade at &thorn;is
Iulya&ntail;, &amp; manlelie with his spere he smate hy&mtail;
thrug&hbar;; and whe&ntail; he had done, sodanlie he vanyssi&dtail;
away."  And as we rede in 'Historia Tripartita,' &thorn;is
Iulia&ntail;, whe&ntail; he was hurte, he fylli&dtail; his hand with
his aw&ntail; blude, and keste it into &thorn;e ayre &amp; say&dtail;;
" <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vicisti, Galilee, vicisti!</FOREIGN>" And in
&thorn;is wrichi&dtail; voyce he swelte, and a&llbar; his childur
lefte hy&mtail; &thorn;er vnberi&dtail;; &amp; &thorn;e Persis come
&amp; flew hy&mtail; and of his sky&ntail; &thorn;ai made a
fute-sky&ntail; <NOTE ID="P516.N1">Harl. MS. subtercintorium?</NOTE> to &thorn;e kyng of Persis <NOTE ID="P516.N2">MS. Kyng of Pars.  Lat. MSS. regi Persarum.</NOTE> .

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Vindicat eciam deus bonos in hac vita.  Supra de

obediencia, vij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Vir.  Viro ultro 
<NOTE ID="P516.N3">So Lat. MSS.  English MS. <HI REND="i">has</HI>, multus.</NOTE>  se ingerit mulier.  Supra de

temptacione, v 
<NOTE ID="P516.N4"><HI REND="i">The</HI> MS. <HI REND="i">gives a wrong reference, here corrected by the</HI> Lat. MSS.</NOTE> .</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Virum suum decipit vxor.  Supra de muliere, ix.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Virginitas eciam cum detrimento corporis aliquando

seruatur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Iero&mtail; tellis how at a ffeste xxx<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> archars come &amp;
slew a ma&ntail; &thorn;at hight Phidones, &amp; whe&ntail; &thorn;ai
ha&dtail; done, &thorn;ai garte bryng his doghters &thorn;at war
maydens afor&ntail; &thorn;aim at &thorn;ai mot naky&ntail;
&thorn;aim, &amp; defowle &thorn;aim &thorn;er o&ntail; &thorn;e
payment wha&rtail; &thorn;er fadur was slone.












<PB N="517">

And &thorn;ai feny&dtail; &thorn;aim sorowfu&llbar;, &amp; band
&thorn;aim samen &amp; fe&llbar; a&llbar; samen into a pytt &amp;
drowny&dtail; &thorn;aim, becauce with &thorn;er dea&dtail; at
&thorn;ai mot kepe &thorn;er virginite.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Virginitatem in filia amissam pater aliquando

crudeliter punit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis how Virgillius slew his aw&ntail; doghter in
&thorn;e markett, to &thorn;e entent &thorn;at hy&mtail; had lere be
calli&dtail; &thorn;e slaer of a virgy&ntail; &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e
fadur of a strompett.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Virgines iuuat deus virginitatem suam
custodire.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Iero&mtail; tellis how o&ntail; a tyme whe&ntail; a
virgy&ntail; wolde not sacryfice &thorn;e ydolfis as &thorn;e paynom
commauns di&dtail; hur, &thorn;ai led hur vnto &thorn;e
borde&llbar;-howse, and &thorn;er come thedur a yong ma&ntail; to hafe
defowli&dtail; hur.  And sodanlie &thorn;er come a lyo&ntail;
rynnan&dtail; &thorn;urg&hbar; &thorn;e cetie vnto &thorn;e
borde&llbar;, &amp; tuke &thorn;is yong ma&ntail; &amp; hel&dtail;
hy&mtail; and luki&dtail; o&ntail; &thorn;e virgy&ntail; &amp;
di&dtail; hy&mtail; no skathe, bod luki&dtail; what sho wolde
comman&dtail; hy&mtail; to do.  And he prayed &thorn;e virgy&ntail; to
comman&dtail; &thorn;e lio&ntail; to lat hy&mtail; goo, and sho did
gude for i&llbar; and commawndi&dtail; &thorn;e lyo&ntail; to lat
hy&mtail; go.  And &thorn;us he was delyver&dtail;, and &thorn;ai
&thorn;at saw had grete mervayle &thorn;eroff.  And &thorn;e
lyo&ntail; went&curl; his ways &amp; &thorn;ai lete hur go.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Virtus animi eciam in mulieribus inuenitur.  Supra

de muliere, iij et xv.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Virtus viri.  Supra de muliere 
<NOTE ID="P517.N1">So Harl. MS.  Eng. MS. de viro.</NOTE> , ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Virtuti possunt adaptari multa superposita in diuersis

locis.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Visio sive visus.  Videt deus omnia et ubique.  Supra

de deo et abbate, iij 
<NOTE ID="P517.N2">MS. ij.</NOTE> .</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>



<PB N="518">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXXVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Videre mulieres vel malos viros non multum

expedit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis how Democritus put oute his aw&ntail; ee&ntail; at
he sulde not se gude to be i&llbar;, and Tertulianus <NOTE ID="P518.N1">MS. Terculianus.</NOTE> tellis &thorn;at he made hy&mtail; selfe
blyn&dtail;, for he mot not se womme&ntail; withowte&ntail;
concupiscens.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Visus est cohibendus.  Supra de oculo, j, et de

aspectu.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Videre malos non est dilectabile.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Cronicles' how o&ntail; a tyme as Iulianus Apostata
made his sacrafice at Co[n]stantynople vnto &thorn;e ymage of
Fortu&ntail;, his modir, the bissho&ptail; of Calcidony, &thorn;at was
blyn&dtail; for age, come vnto hy&mtail; &amp; calli&dtail; hy&mtail;
wrichi&dtail; Apostata.  And he ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail;,
&amp; say&dtail;; "Thi Galile may not luff &thorn;e."  And he
ansswe[r]&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "Therefor God tuke
fro&mtail; me my syght at I sulde not se the at is withowte&ntail;
petie."  And Iulianus ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; nothyng agay&ntail;,
bod went his ways home als faste as he myght.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Visiones multas ostendit deus diuersis personis.

Supra in pluribus locis.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXXVIII. 
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Visitacio personarum religiosarum aliquando
profuit.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iacobus de Vetriaco tellis how o&ntail; a tyme &thorn;e chawntur
of Camatensis <NOTE ID="P518.N2">Arund. MS. Cameracensis = Cambray.</NOTE> as he was in trave&llbar;, went
oute of his way to visett dame Marie of Ogniez <NOTE ID="P518.N3">MS. Ognnez.</NOTE>
.  And ane of his felows sai&dtail; vnto hy&mtail;; "For God, what
seke ye &thorn;er?  Wi&llbar; ye go kepp butterfleis as barnys duse?"
And he feyny&dtail; &amp; went o&ntail;.  And as &thorn;ai
walki&dtail; to-gedur







<PB N="519">

his felow waxi&dtail; werie in tarying for hy&mtail;, and went vnto
hy&mtail; &amp; commawndi&dtail; hy&mtail; to haste hy&mtail;.  And
whe&ntail; he behel&dtail; &thorn;is holie maydy&ntail;, sodanlie he
was changi&dtail; in his witt, and fe&llbar; vnto suche a wepyng
&thorn;at a grete while he mot not abstene hy&mtail; nor go furt&hbar;
of hur presens.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e chawntur purseyvi&dtail;
&thorn;is &amp; was meri, &amp; say&dtail;; "Go we!  Whar-to sulde we
stand here at kepp buttyrfleis?"  And he after grete sobbyng &amp;
teris vnnethis mot be had away, and say&dtail;; "I pray &thorn;e
forgyff me, for I wate nevur what I sayde.  Bod now in &thorn;is holie
womma&ntail; I hafe purseyvi&dtail; be experyens &thorn;e vertue of
God Almyghtie."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Visitacionem corporalem amicorum non multum

sancti approbant.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede of &thorn;e abbott Pastor, &thorn;at many yere dwelte in
wyldernes with his brether, &amp; he wolde neuer se his moder.  So
o&ntail; a tyme sho come into &thorn;e kur&ktee;, &amp; wolde hafe
sene hy&mtail; &amp; spoky&ntail; with hy&mtail;; and he was war
o&ntail; hur he gatt hy&mtail; into his ce&llbar; &amp; clappy&dtail;
to &thorn;e dure faste.  And sho come &amp; stude att &thorn;e dure
&amp; wepu&dtail;, &amp; crye&dtail; vppo&ntail; hy&mtail; &amp;
prayed hy&mtail; comfurt&hbar; &amp; speke with hur, &amp; say&dtail;
sho wal&dtail; fay&ntail; se hy&mtail;.  And he went vnto &thorn;e
dure &amp; say&dtail; vnto hur; "Whar-to standis &thorn;ou
cryan&dtail; &thorn;er, &thorn;ou olde wyfe?"  And whe&ntail; sho
harde hy&mtail; speke, sho crye&dtail; faster &thorn;a&ntail; sho did
befo&rtail;, &amp; say&dtail;; "So&ntail;, I wol&dtail; se you, whi
wi&llbar; ye not lat me se you?  A&mtail; I not your moder &thorn;at
gaff you at suke of my breste?  And now I a&mtail; olde &amp;
white-hari&dtail;."  And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp;
say&dtail;; "In &thorn;is werl&dtail; &thorn;ou may not se vs, bod
&thorn;ou sa&llbar; se vs in a noder werl&dtail;."  And sho sai&dtail;
agay&ntail;; "So&ntail;, &amp; I se you here, I sa&llbar; also se you
&thorn;er."  And &thorn;a&ntail; he say&dtail;; "Bod if &thorn;ou lyff
in gude lyfe as we do here, &thorn;ou may happe&ntail; not see vs
&thorn;er."  And whe&ntail; he ha&dtail; so say&dtail; sho went hur
way, &amp; was merie and say&dtail;; "And I may se you &thorn;er, I
rak neuer if I se you nevur here."

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Visitat deus per tribulaciones.  Supra de infirmitate,

iij, et in pluribus locis.

</FOREIGN>
<PB N="520">
</ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Visitat deus per consolaciones.  Supra de

consolacione et in pluribus locis.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Visitatores conuentuum aliquando false informantur.

Supra de inuidia.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Vnccio extrema non debet pretermitti ante mortem.

Supra de furto.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXXX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Voluntas propria deserenda est a religiosis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Dictis Patrum' how o&ntail; a tyme ane olde monke
say&dtail;; "Tha&ntail; I do my selfe meku&llbar; tribulacio&ntail;,
whe&ntail; I doo myne aw&ntail; wy&llbar;."


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXXXI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Voluntas pro facto reputatur quando non adest

facultas.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a monke of Saynt
Barnardis, and he lefte his habett &amp; went into &thorn;e
werl&dtail;, and &thorn;er he become a preste of a kur&ktee;; &amp;
he had a lemma&ntail; dwellan&dtail; with hy&mtail;, &amp; he gatt hur
childer bothe sonnys &amp; doghters.  So lang tyme after Saynt
Barnar&dtail; happi&dtail; to be hosti&dtail; in &thorn;is apostata
howse, and he knew Saynt Barnar&dtail;, bod he know not hy&mtail;.
And in &thorn;e mornyng whe&ntail; Saynt Barnar&dtail; was bow&ntail;
to ga, he mot not speke with hy&mtail; for he was gane vnto &thorn;e
kurk, and he sayd vnto ane of his sonnys; "Go &amp; bere my message
vnto &thorn;i fadur, &amp; say I thank hy&mtail; his gude herberie."
And &thorn;is childe was dombe bor&ntail; &amp; spak neuer wurde.  And
he ra&ntail; vnto his fadur &amp; tolde hy&mtail; a&llbar; how
&thorn;e abbott sent hy&mtail; wur&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; he
har&dtail; his childe speke, for ioy he wepu&dtail;, and he garte
hy&mtail; say his message ouer onys or twyce.  And he axki&dtail;
hy&mtail; what &thorn;e abbot did vnto hy&mtail;, &amp; he sai&dtail;
he dyd no thyng vnto hy&mtail;, bod at he spak vnto hy&mtail; and bod
hy&mtail; go say &thorn;ies wurdies vnto his fadur.  So &thorn;is
preste was compuncte with so evydent a meracle, and hastelie he come
vnto &thorn;is holie ma&ntail;.  And with grete wepyng he fe&llbar; to
hys ffete &amp; say&dtail;; "A! holie fadur! Som tyme I was suche a
mon&ktee; of yours, and

<PB N="521">

I beseke your fadurhede to licent me to co&mtail; hame agay&ntail;
vnto myne abbay with you."  And he ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail;
agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "Byde me here, an&dtail; I sa&llbar;
co&mtail; agay&ntail; by &thorn;e &amp; take &thorn;e home with me."
And he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "Sur, I a&mtail;
afer&dtail; in &thorn;e menewhile &thorn;at I sa&llbar; dye."  And he
ansswer&dtail; hy&mtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "And &thorn;ou
dye in suche a contricio&ntail; &amp; a purpas, doute not &thorn;ou
sa&llbar; be a monke befo&rtail; A&llbar;myghti Go&dtail;."  And with
&thorn;at he went his ways.  &amp; whe&ntail; he come agay&ntail; he
fan&dtail; hy&mtail; new dea&dtail; &amp; beri&dtail;, and whe&ntail;
he har&dtail; te&llbar; &thorn;erof he garte oppy&ntail; his grafe.
And &thorn;ai &thorn;at wer aboute axki&dtail; hy&mtail; what he
wol&dtail; doo, &amp; he sai&dtail; he wul&dtail; se how he lay in his
grafe, a clerk or a mon&ktee;; &amp; &thorn;ai sai&dtail; at
&thorn;ai beri&dtail; hy&mtail; in clerkis clothis.  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;e er&dtail; was taky&ntail; of hy&mtail;, &thorn;ai fan&dtail;
hy&mtail; not cle&dtail; as a clerk, bod rather a monke, &amp; in a
monkis abbett.  And &thorn;us he was magnyfie&dtail; of a&llbar;
me&ntail;, becauce his gude wi&llbar; torny&dtail; hy&mtail; as to
your gude dede <NOTE ID="P521.N1">Arund. MS. et magnificatus est ab omnibus deus, qui voluntatem pro facto reputat.</NOTE> .


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXXXII. 
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Votum vouent aliqui racione alicuius periculi, et

liberati a periculo soluere non curant.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Libro de Dono Timoris' how som tyme &thorn;er was a
ma&ntail; &thorn;at had bothe a cow and a calfe vnto &thorn;e mownte
of Saynte Michae&llbar;, betwix &thorn;e bowndis of Bretay&ntail; and
Normondie, at he mot esskape &thorn;e flowyng of &thorn;e see
&thorn;at vmwhile occupie&dtail; &thorn;at way.  And &thorn;e flude
come o&ntail; hy&mtail; and he crie&dtail; of Saynt Micha&llbar; &amp;
say&dtail;; "O &thorn;ou blissi&dtail; Michae&llbar;, delyver me &amp;
I sa&llbar; gyff &thorn;e &thorn;is calve."  And whe&ntail; he was
delyveri&dtail; he say&dtail;; "Saynt Miche&llbar; was bod a fule
&thorn;at trowe&dtail; at I wolde hafe gyffy&ntail; hy&mtail; my
calfe."  So afterwar&dtail; hy&mtail; happen&dtail; to be take&ntail;
with &thorn;e same flude.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he crye&dtail; of Saynt
Michae&llbar; &amp; praye&dtail; hy&mtail; delyver hy&mtail; &amp; he
sulde gyff hy&mtail; bothe &thorn;e cow &amp; &thorn;e calfe.  So he
was delyver&dtail; &amp; say&dtail; as he did befo&rtail;.  So
&thorn;e iij tyme he went thedur at feche home &thorn;is cow &amp;
&thorn;is calfe, &amp; sodanlie as he come hamwer&dtail;, &thorn;e
se-flude vmlappi&dtail; bothe hy&mtail; &amp; &thorn;e cow &amp;
&thorn;e calfe, &amp; drowny&dtail; &thorn;aim a&llbar; thre, and
&thorn;at onone.





<PB N="522">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXXXIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Votum de ingressu religionis eciam ab infirmitate

corporali sanat.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was a knyght &thorn;at
hight Lodowycus, &amp; he ffe&llbar; seke bow&ntail; to dye, &amp;
with lefe of his wyfe he made a vow &thorn;at he sulde be a monk of
Ceustus ordur &amp; he mott covir of his seknes.  And &thorn;at done,
onone withoute&ntail; swete or blude or hostyng, or any o&thorn;er
&thorn;ing, at a&llbar; me&ntail; marvel&dtail; off, agayns &thorn;e
kynd of his infirmyte he beca&ntail; to covir &amp; was hale
furt&hbar;with.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXXXIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vouere et non reddere dampnabile est.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Petrus Damianus tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a riche
har&dtail; ma&ntail;, and o&ntail; a tyme he made a vow &thorn;at
an&dtail; he liffi&dtail; x yere langer he sulde make hy&mtail; a
religious ma&ntail; in &thorn;e monasterie of Saynt Vincent.  So
whe&ntail; &thorn;e tear&mtail; was fulfilli&dtail; &thorn;e abbott
axki&dtail; hy&mtail;, &amp; he bega&ntail; to fey&ntail; &amp; wolde
nott.  And in &thorn;e menewhile he fe&llbar; in sekenes and he delte
meku&llbar; to pure folk &amp; was shrevy&ntail;, and semyd as he wer
wele disposi&dtail;, so he dye&dtail;.  So o&ntail; &thorn;e nexte
night after &thorn;e abbott &thorn;og[ht] &thorn;at he saw <NOTE ID="P522.N1">MS. <HI REND="i">either</HI>, say, <HI REND="i">corrected to</HI> saw, <HI REND="i">or vice versa.</HI></NOTE> in a grete play&ntail; medow ane emperour with
a&llbar; his companye, and hy&mtail; thoght he saw certay&ntail;
kepers com lede &thorn;is ma&ntail; a grete pace.  And &thorn;is
abbo[t] crye&dtail; o&ntail; hy&mtail; &amp; bad; "Abyde, bruther,
&amp; speke with me!  Bruther," he say&dtail;, "What aylis &thorn;e?
Whe&thorn;er erte &thorn;ou in pay&ntail; or in ioy?"  And he with a
hevie chere ansswer[d] hy&mtail; &amp; sai&dtail;; "Whar-to axkis
&thorn;ou me of ioy, &thorn;at is turment with so many paynes?"  And
&thorn;a&ntail; he axki&dtail; hy&mtail; what Saynt Vincent di&dtail;
vnto hy&mtail;, and he ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;;
"He made me long to trayste in hy&mtail;, bod now I a&mtail; werie and
hase loste my hope, and as I promytt hy&mtail; &amp; kepi&dtail; it
not, now I a&mtail; servi&dtail; o&ntail; &thorn;e same wyse."



<PB N="523">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXXXV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vsurarij pena aliquando visibiliter
demonstratur.</FOREIGN></HEAD> 

<P> Cesarius tellis how som tyme in &thorn;e cete of Metence &thorn;er
was ane vsurer &thorn;at die&dtail;, &amp; he was passan&dtail;
covatus.  And whe&ntail; he drew nere his dea&dtail;, he praye&dtail;
his wife to lay a bag fu&llbar; of syluer by hy&mtail; whe&ntail; he
was dead in his grafe; and so sho di&dtail;.  So afterwar&dtail;
&thorn;aim happen&dtail; oppen <NOTE ID="P523.N1">MS. oppen&dtail;.</NOTE> &thorn;at same
grafe agay&ntail;, &amp; &thorn;ai fan&dtail; &thorn;erin ij tadis,
ane in &thorn;e bag mouthe and a noder on his brest&curl;; &amp;
&thorn;at one of &thorn;aim drew oute penys of &thorn;e bag with his
mouthe &amp; &thorn;e toder tuke &thorn;aim at hy&mtail; &amp; putt
&thorn;aim into his harte, right as he had say&dtail;; "With mony we
sa&llbar; fy&llbar; &thorn;ine vnsaciable harte."  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;ai saw &thorn;is, &thorn;ai wer so fer&dtail; at &thorn;ai fled
away &amp; fillid &thorn;e grafe agay&ntail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXXXVI. 
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vsurarijs aliquando apparent demones in
morte.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was ane vsurar at was
bow&ntail; to [dye] <NOTE ID="P523.N2">Latin MSS. vsuraria moritura.</NOTE> , and hy&mtail; thoght at
he saw a&llbar; &thorn;e felde; fu&llbar; of crawis &amp; crakis.  And
he bega&ntail; for to cry faste &amp; say&dtail;; "Allas!  alas!  Se,
now &thorn;ai co&mtail; vnto me, ffor now &thorn;ai er at &thorn;e
dure.  And now &thorn;ai er in &thorn;e howse, and now &thorn;ai [er]
o&ntail; my breste, and now &thorn;ai draw my saule oute of my bodie."
And in &thorn;is crying he dye&dtail;.  And &thorn;e same nyght, at
many folke bothe har&dtail; &amp; saw, &thorn;ai <NOTE ID="P523.N3">Latin MSS. demones . . . cor tollentes usque ad tectum, &amp;c.</NOTE> lifte his bodie v&ptail; into &thorn;e howse-rufe,
&amp; lete it fa&llbar; oftsithis &amp; breke a&llbar; to gobettis;
and a&llbar; &thorn;e lyght in &thorn;e howse was putt oute, and
me&ntail; &amp; womme&ntail; fle&dtail;.  &amp; o&ntail; &thorn;e
mor&ntail; &thorn;ai fan&dtail; his bodie &thorn;er a&llbar;
to-reve&ntail; &amp; rente, and &thorn;ai tuke it &amp; bery&dtail;
itt in &thorn;e felde emang bestis.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Vsurarij depositum non est seruandum.  Supra de

deposito, j.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>




<PB N="524">

</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXXXVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vsurarius debet prius restituere et postea

elemosinas facere.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how som tyme at Pariss&hbar; &thorn;er was a grete
vsurar, so he fe&llbar; vnto compunccio&ntail; and he come &amp;
aski&dtail; counce&llbar; at ane &thorn;at hight Maurice, &thorn;at
was bisshop &thorn;er, how he mot be savy&dtail;.  And &thorn;is
bissho&ptail; had a kur&ktee; of ou&rtail; Ladie in byggyng, and he
cowncel&dtail; hy&mtail; to giff his money holie &thorn;ervnto.  And
he suspecte hy&mtail; somwhat in his cownce&llbar;-gyffyng, and went
vnto Maister Petur at was chawntur &thorn;er, and he bad hy&mtail; go
gar cry oppynlie &thorn;at he was redie to restore vnto a&llbar;
me&ntail; &thorn;at at he had had wronguslie of &thorn;aim; and so it
was done.  And &thorn;is done he come agay&ntail; vnto &thorn;e
chawntur, and tuke witnes at his consciens &amp; sai&dtail; &thorn;at
he had restori&dtail; agay&ntail; a&llbar; &thorn;at he had wronguslie
getty&ntail; vnto a&llbar; &thorn;at come vnto hy&mtail;, &amp;
&thorn;is he had somwhat lefte.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he sai&dtail;
hy&mtail; burde do almos-dede, &amp; after &thorn;at go in his sarke
&amp; his breke &thorn;urg&hbar; &thorn;e cetie naki&dtail;, and so he
di&dtail;.  And ane folowy&dtail; hy&mtail; with a wande,
cryan&dtail;, "Behol&dtail;, &thorn;is is &thorn;at ma&ntail;
&thorn;at princes wurshuppi&dtail; for his money!"  And
&thorn;urg&hbar; &thorn;is penance-doyng he his sawle was savi&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXXXVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vsurariorum elemosine non placent deo.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Cesarius tellis how som tyme in Colay&ntail; &thorn;er was ane
vsurarie, and he fe&llbar; vnto compunccio&ntail; &amp; shrafe
hy&mtail; vnto a preste.  And he say&dtail; he wolde gyff all his
gudis for Goddis sake, and &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e preste bad
hy&mtail; cut shyvis of brea&dtail; &amp; fy&llbar; a kyste
&thorn;erwith and lokk it.  And so he di&dtail;.  And o&ntail;
&thorn;e toder day, whe&ntail; he sulde co&mtail; &amp; se it &amp;
opyn&dtail; &thorn;e kyste, he fand &thorn;er als many tadis as he put
in shyvis of brea&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; he tolde &thorn;e preste
&thorn;erof, he say&dtail;; "Loo, now, how &thorn;ine almos at
&thorn;ou makis of &thorn;ine vsurie plesis vnto God!"  And he was
fer&dtail; &amp; axki&dtail; what he sulde do.  And he sai&dtail;,
"And &thorn;ou wi&llbar; be savi&dtail;, lyg a&llbar; &thorn;is nyght
naky&dtail;

<PB N="525">

emang yone vermy&ntail;."  Lo! how grete contricio&ntail; he had!  For
&thorn;uff a&llbar; he di&dtail; it with a grete vgsomnes, he
lay&dtail; hy&mtail; nakid emang &thorn;is vermy&ntail;.  And &thorn;e
preste lokki&dtail; &thorn;e kyste and went his ways, and o&ntail;
&thorn;e toder day whe&ntail; he oppynd itt, he fand nothyng &thorn;er
bod &thorn;is mans banys.  And he tuke &thorn;aim &amp; beri&dtail;
&thorn;aim in a porche of Saynt Geryo&ntail;.  And as it is
say&dtail;, &thorn;ai er of so grete vertue &thorn;at vnto &thorn;is
day no tade may abyde whykk within &thorn;e bowndis of &thorn;at
kur&ktee;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Vsurarij condentis testamentum omnia debent

reportari in manus executorum, et inde debent

fieri restituciones.  Supra de testamento.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCLXXXIX.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vsurarius et si a peccato non abstinet, saltem
debet habere <NOTE ID="P525.N1">MS. habet.</NOTE> intencionem
restituendi.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iacobus de Vetriaco tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was a
riche ma&ntail;, and &thorn;uf a&llbar; he had meku&llbar; gude,
nevur-&thorn;e-les to gett more gude he lete his money to hyre.  Bod
&thorn;e increce &thorn;erof he durste nott tur&ntail; into his
aw&ntail; vse, bod lay&dtail; it oparte at he mott restore it
agay&ntail; at his dea&dtail;-day, and so he di&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXC.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vsurarij eciam post mortem ab vsuris non cessant.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iacobus de Vetriaco tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was ane vsurar
&amp; he wolde nothyng restore whe&ntail; he dye&dtail;, bod, for
honor of &thorn;e werl&dtail;, he garte deale large almos, and he
bewytt in his testament a grete sow&mtail; of money and &thorn;at he
chargi&dtail; his sons &amp; his frendis at it sulde be lent in vsurie
iij yere after his decese, and at &thorn;ai sulde gyff for his sawle
a&llbar; &thorn;at multiplie&dtail; &thorn;erof.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXCI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vsurarius inuite moritur.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iacobus de Vetriaco tellis how so&mtail; tyme &thorn;er was ane
vsurar &thorn;at lay in passions of dea&dtail;, and he bega&ntail; to
be passyng [hevie] &


<PB N="526">

sorowfu&llbar;, &amp; prayed his sawle t[o] abyde in &thorn;e body
&amp; he sulde purvay &thorn;erfo&rtail;, and he promytt it gol&dtail;
&amp; syluer &amp; a&llbar; &thorn;e delytis of &thorn;is werl&dtail;,
&amp; els he wol&dtail; not gyff &thorn;er-fo&rtail; &thorn;e valour
of a sh[red] clowte <NOTE ID="P526.N1">Harl. MS. non vnam pictam.</NOTE> .  So at &thorn;e laste he
saw his sawle wolde not abyde in his bodie bod at hy&mtail; burde
nedelyngis dye, he wex passand wrot&hbar; &amp; say&dtail; vnto his
saule; "&THORN;ou sawle!  I sulde hafe ordan&dtail; &thorn;e a gude
herbarie, bod se&ntail; &thorn;ou erte so fond at &thorn;ou wi&llbar;
not abyde, I beteche &thorn;e vnto a&llbar; &thorn;e devuls in
he&llbar;."  And &thorn;us he dye&dtail; and was beri&dtail; in
he&llbar;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXCII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vsurarij nomen est confusibile.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iacobus de Vetriaco tellis how som tyme &thorn;er was [a] prechur
&thorn;at in his sermon&dtail; tol&dtail; of &thorn;e myschevus crafte
of vsurie, and whe&ntail; he had done his sermon&dtail;, he bad at
a&llbar; me&ntail; sul&dtail; rise to his absolucio&ntail; in ordur as
he calli&dtail; &thorn;aim be &thorn;er offes.  And furste he bad
smythis ryse, and so &thorn;ai did &amp; he asoyled [&thorn;aim], and
&thorn;ai went &thorn;er ways.  Tha&ntail; he bad ryse baxsters, and
so dyd &thorn;ai, and &thorn;us he calli&dtail; vp ilk crafte after
other.  &amp; at &thorn;e laste he bad ryse vsuraris, and &thorn;uff
a&llbar; &thorn;er was ma in &thorn;e kurk &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;er
was of any o&thorn;er crafte, yit &thorn;er wolde none ryse, bod for
shame &thorn;ai hid &thorn;aim.  And o&thorn;er folke lug&hbar;e &amp;
skorny&dtail; &thorn;aim, &amp; a&llbar; &thorn;ies vsuraries rase and
went oute confusi&dtail;.


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXCIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vsurarij a bonis non debent sepeliri.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Iacobus de Vetriaco tellis, whe&ntail; neghburs wolde hafe
lifti&dtail; vp &thorn;e bodie of ane vsurar &thorn;at was dea&dtail;,
&amp; bor&ntail; hy&mtail; vnto his grafe, &thorn;ai mot not mufe it
be no maner of wyse.  And &thorn;ai had grete merve&llbar;
&thorn;eroff.  So emang &thorn;aim &thorn;er was one olde wyse
ma&ntail;, &amp; he say&dtail; "Surs, ye know wele at &thorn;e custom
in &thorn;is cetie is &thorn;is, &thorn;at whe&ntail; any maner of
ma&ntail; dyes, &thorn;ase me&ntail; &thorn;at er of &thorn;e same
crafte er wunte to bere hy&mtail; vnto his grafe, as prestis duse
prestis, &amp; so of o&thorn;er."  So privalie &thorn;ai calli&dtail;
iiij at &thorn;ai knew wele was vsurars, and onone &thorn;ai
lifti&dtail; hy&mtail; vp &amp; had hy&mtail; away, for &thorn;e
devu&llbar;



<PB N="527">

wolde not lett his servandis to bere away his servant wha&rtail; he lett
gude me[n] to do itt.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Vsurarij sepultura est sub patibulo.  Supra de

sepultura.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Vsurarij aliquando moriuntur dum sunt in maiori

festo et securitate.  Supra de demone, x 
<NOTE ID="P527.N1"><HI REND="i">A wrong reference apparently.</HI></NOTE> , et

alijs locis diuersis.</FOREIGN></ITEM>
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Vsurarius restituens saluatur.  Supra de testamento.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXCIV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vsurarij restituere amittunt aliquando timore

paupertatis.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in 'Libro de Dono Timoris' how som tyme a preste
movi&dtail; ane vsurar whe&ntail; he was seke to dispose hy&mtail; for
&thorn;e heale of his sawle, and he tolde hy&mtail; at iij
&thorn;inges was necessarie vnto hy&mtail;, &thorn;at is to say,
fullie to be shrevy&ntail;, &amp; to sorow for his synnys, and to make
restitucio&ntail; at his power.  And he granti&dtail; with gude
wy&llbar; to do &thorn;e ij furste, bod he say&dtail;; "How sulde I do
&thorn;e thri&dtail;, for &thorn;a&ntail; sulde I lefe nothyng to me
nor my chylder."  And &thorn;e preste sayde bod if he did &thorn;us,
he mot not be savi&dtail;.  And he axki&dtail; if wise me&ntail; &amp;
scriptur sayde so, and he sai&dtail; ya, for suthe.  And he
ansswer&dtail; agay&ntail; &amp; say&dtail;; "I wi&llbar; nevur prufe
whethur &thorn;ai sai&dtail; suthe or nay, for I wi&llbar; make no
restitucio&ntail;."  And &thorn;us he dye&dtail;, more dredan&dtail;
pouertie in &thorn;is warlde &thorn;a&ntail; evurlastand pay&ntail; in
&thorn;e toder werl&dtail;.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Vulpes oracioni obedit.  Supra de oracione, ij.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXCV.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vxor sine licencia viri sui exennia dare non debet.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> We rede in &thorn;e 'Legend of Saynt Edmund, Bissho&ptail; of
Canturberie,' how &thorn;er was a wyfe &thorn;at luffi&dtail;
hy&mtail; wele and wolde he ha&dtail;



<PB N="528">

had at do with hur, &amp; oft sythis sho broght hy&mtail; presentis to
make hy&mtail; lightlier to enclyne to hur entent.  So he knew wele
enog&hbar; hur entent, and axki&dtail; hur if sho broght hy&mtail;
&thorn;ies presentis be consent of hur husban&dtail; or nay.  And sho
sayd, nay, hur husband sulde nott wit what sho did vnto hy&mtail;, nor
yit what he did vnto hur.  And he ansswerd agay&ntail; &amp;
say&dtail;; "I wi&llbar; not take &thorn;i giftis with-oute consent of
&thorn;i husban&dtail;."  And &thorn;us &thorn;e womma&ntail; with
grete shame bare hur presentis agay&ntail;, and he was clere and
fullie ri&dtail; o&ntail; hur.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Vxor de facili non debet haberi suspecta a viro suo.

Supra de suspicione.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXCVI.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vxor modica occasione est zelotipa.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Saynt Iero&mtail; tellis of ane &thorn;at hight Gorgias, &amp;
&thorn;uf a&llbar; at he war chastie, neuer-&thorn;e-les he had a fayr
maydy&ntail;, and here-fo&rtail; his wyfe was passand hevy &amp;
sa&dtail;.  So his neghburs in &thorn;e contrey, ij of &thorn;aim,
fe&llbar; wrat&hbar;, and &thorn;is Gorgias sent &thorn;aim a fayr
buke &thorn;at he had compyli&dtail; of concorde, &amp; say&dtail; "He
commaundis you to concordans &thorn;at kepis [not] iij at
concor&dtail; in a howse, &thorn;at is to say, him selfe, his wyfe,
and his maydyn <NOTE ID="P528.N1">Harl. MS. "Iste uobis precepit de concordia, qui se, uxorem, ancillam, tres in vna domo, concordare non potuit."</NOTE> ."  So his wyfe had a grete
envye at his mayde&ntail; fayrenes, &amp; here-for sho wol&dtail; not
sease, &thorn;uf a&llbar; hur husban&dtail; war not wurthie, daylie
for to chyde hy&mtail;, becauce sho mystryste hy&mtail;, for &thorn;e
mayde&ntail; was fayrer &thorn;a&ntail; sho.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Vxor rixosa pacienter debet tolerari 
<NOTE ID="P528.N2">MS. tollerari.</NOTE> .  Supra de paciencia.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXCVII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vxor a viro debet corripi si ornet se racione
alterius viri.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Valerius tellis how a noble ma&ntail; of Rome &thorn;at was
suspecte <NOTE ID="P528.N3">Harl. MS. Romanus suspicius uxorem suam dimisit.</NOTE> of his wyfe, and here-fo&rtail; he
say&dtail; he wolde lefe hur, ffor &thorn;e law,









<PB N="529">

he say&dtail;, was so &thorn;at a womma&ntail; sulde not make hur
fress&hbar; &amp; gay with hur husban&dtail; gude, to gyff hy&mtail;
&thorn;at seis hur occasio&ntail; to make hur husban&dtail;
cukwolde. &amp; here-fo&rtail; he wolde not lat hur be gayl[ie]
cle&dtail;, to &thorn;e entent at sho sulde not be suspecte nor broght
in blame.

</P>
<P>
<LIST LANG="LAT">
<ITEM><FOREIGN>Vxor casta multum est amabilis.  Supra de castitate.</FOREIGN></ITEM></LIST>


</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> DCCXCVIII.
<LB>
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vxore&mtail; non expedit ducere.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P> Ieronimus <NOTE ID="P529.N1">Harl. MS. Ieronimus.  Fertur Auriolus Theofrasti 'Libro de Nupcijs.'</NOTE> tellis in 'Libro de Nupcijs' of
ane Aureolus Theophrasti, &amp; in &thorn;is buke he axkis if a wise
ma&ntail; sulde wed a wyfe, and he says &thorn;uf sho war nevur so
fayre, nor so wele taght, nor had nevur so honest fadur nor moder, yit
nevur-&thorn;e-les, he says, a wyse ma&ntail; sulde not wed hur, for
&thorn;is Aurelious sais it is not possible to a ma&ntail; to please
bothe his wife &amp; his childer; ffor womme&ntail;, he says,
bur&dtail; hafe gol&dtail; &amp; syluer &amp; gay clothyng, &amp; a
servan&dtail; and mayny o&thorn;er thyngis, &amp; yit a&llbar;
&thorn;e nyght sho wi&llbar; lyg chaterran&dtail; &amp; say <NOTE ID="P529.N2">Arund. MS. "Illa ornatior procedit in publicum et honoratur ab omnibus, ego autem in conuentu feminarum despicior."  Aitque; "Cur aspiciebas vicinam?" &amp;c.</NOTE> &thorn;at &thorn;er <NOTE ID="P529.N3">&thorn;er <HI REND="i">omitted and added above the line.</HI></NOTE> is oder
&amp; &thorn;at hase bettur curchus &amp; er fressher araye&dtail;
&thorn;a&ntail; sho is, and if sho be wele araye&dtail; hur lykis
. . . . to co&mtail; emang no pepu&llbar; and sho wi&llbar; say, "Lo!
I a&mtail; &thorn;e baddeste in a&llbar; &thorn;is tow&ntail;!" Also
sho wi&llbar; say vnto hur husbon&dtail;; "Whi behel&dtail; &thorn;ou
&thorn;i neghbur wyfe, &amp; whi spak &thorn;ou with &thorn;i neghbur
mayde&ntail;?"  And whe&ntail; he commys fro &thorn;e markett sho
wi&llbar; say; "What hase &thorn;ou boght?  I may not hafe a
fren&dtail; nor a felow for &thorn;e, nor luf of a noder ma&ntail; bod
if I be suspecte."  And &thorn;erfo&rtail; &thorn;er sulde no
ma&ntail; make chesyng of his wyfe long befo&rtail;, bod take
suc&hbar; one as hy&mtail; happen&dtail; whedur sho be fayre or fowle,
or prowde or angry, &amp; &thorn;erfo&rtail; &thorn;ai sulde not be
provi&dtail; or &thorn;ai war we&dtail;.  A hors or ane ass, ane ox or
a cow or a servan&dtail; a&llbar; &thorn;ies sulde be provi&dtail; or
&thorn;ai wer boght or hyri&dtail;, bod a womma&ntail; sulde not a
ma&ntail; se or he wed hur, &thorn;at he war not displesi&dtail; after
&thorn;ai war we&dtail;.  And if &thorn;ou giff hur









<PB N="530">

a&llbar; &thorn;i gude to kepe, yit sho wy&llbar; trow at &thorn;ou
kepis so&mtail; &thorn;i selfe, and &thorn;us sho wi&llbar; suspecte
&thorn;e &amp; hafe &thorn;e in hatere&dtail;, &amp; happelie
afterwar&dtail; poyso&ntail; the.  And if &thorn;ou bryng me&ntail; of
craft in-to &thorn;i hows, as tailliours or o&thorn;er, it is
pere&llbar; for hur vnclennes.  So [if] &thorn;ou forbyd hur it
wi&llbar; cauce hur do truspas.  Therefo&rtail; what profettis a
diligente kepyng of a wyfe whe&ntail; ane vnchaste wyfe may not be
kepy&dtail;, ffor &thorn;e keper of chastite is nede <NOTE ID="P530.N1">Infida enim custos castitatis est necessitas.</NOTE> , and &thorn;at sho &thorn;at is not lustie to
sy&ntail;, sho may be calli&dtail; chastie.  And if sho be fayr,
o&thorn;er me&ntail; wi&llbar; luf hur, and if sho be fowle sho
wi&llbar; be prowde, at cauce me&ntail; make meku&llbar; o&ntail; hur,
and it is fu&llbar; har&dtail; to kepe &thorn;at wele &thorn;at many
me&ntail; luffis, and it is fu&llbar; hevy to hafe &thorn;at no
ma&ntail; wy&llbar; cheris nor hafe in welde.  Nevur-&thorn;e-les a
fowle wyfe may bettir be kepy&dtail; &thorn;a&ntail; a fayr wyfe may,
for &thorn;er is no thyng bod so&mtail; peple wi&llbar; giff &thorn;er
vew and &thorn;er fantasye &thorn;er-vnto.

</P>
<P>
